window.EXP={"PW-0001":"Statement 1 is incorrect : The concept of stupa originates from pre-Buddhist burial mounds in India which were used for funerary purposes such as burial mounds called 'Megalithic cairns'. Buddhism adopted and transformed these existing structures into significant religious monuments. While the architectural form of the Stupa was adapted and refined by Buddhists, its origins are not exclusively Buddhist. Statement 2 is correct : Stupas were primarily built to serve as repositories of sacred relics. These relics could include the ashes or bodily remains of the Buddha, his disciples, or other revered figures. Example: the Dhamek Stupa at Sarnath (Uttar Pradesh) is believed to mark the spot where the Buddha delivered his first sermon. The relics were placed in a small chamber called the 'harmika' at the center of the stupa, making it a focal point for veneration and pilgrimage. Statement 3 is correct : Stupas serve both votive and commemorative functions often constructed as acts of reverence and offerings to the Buddha or other enlightened figures. They are built to honor important even","PW-0002":"The Prime Minister inaugurated and laid the foundation stone of multiple projects in Somnath Temple complex in August 2021. The Somnath temple, also called Deo Patan, is located in Prabhas Patan, Veraval in Gujarat, India. Statement 1 is correct: Somnath Temple, is believed to be the first among the twelve Jyotirlinga shrines of Shiva. Apart from Somnath, other famous jyotirlingas are Mallikarjuna (Andhra Pradesh), Mahakaleshwar, Omkareshwar (Madhya Pradesh), Bhimashankar (Maharashtra), Baidyanath (Jharkhand), Kashi Vishwanath (Uttar Pradesh) etc. Statement 2 is correct: Al-Biruni, an Arab traveler, gave a highly favorable description of Somanth temple in Kitab Al- Hind (Book of India). It is believed to have inspired Mahmud of Ghazni's expedition in 1024 AD. Statement 3 is incorrect: The contemporary Somnath temple’s reconstruction was started under the orders of the first Home Minister of India, Vallabhbhai Patel. The then President of India, Dr. Rajendra Prasad, did the Pran-Pratistha at the existing temple in 1951. 4","PW-0003":"Mughal and Nawabi architecture is marked by the use of red sandstone, white marble, and intricate brickwork. This choice reflects cultural influences seen in monuments like the Buland Darwaza, Jama Masjid, Bara Imambara, Rumi Darwaza, and the Taj Mahal. Statement 1 is incorrect: The Buland Darwaza (Gate of Magnificence) and Khankah (Sufi monastery) at Fatehpur Sikri was built by Emperor Akbar to commemorate his victory over Gujarat. It is made of red sandstone, with some white marble used for decorative inlays. White marble is not the primary material. Statement 2 is incorrect: Bada Imambara, located in Lucknow was built by Asaf-ud-daula in 1784. It was built to give employment and revenue to the public This structure has been made by interlocking bricks without the use of mortar in its construction. Rumi Darwaza is also located in Lucknow, built by Nawab of Awadh Asaf-ud-daula. It is built using lakhauri bricks, coated with lime. It does not use red sandstone or marble. Stucco ornamentation ( gajkari) was used to decorate the monuments, giving it a deep relief effect even on flat wa","PW-0004":"Statement 1 is incorrect: Ajanta Caves were built in two phases: Satavahana period (2nd century BCE) and later in the Vakataka period (5th-6th century CE). They are primarily associated with Buddhist art and culture. They are famous for murals, sculptures, and rock-cut chaityas (prayer halls) and viharas (monasteries). Mahabalipuram (Mamallapuram) was built in the 7th-8th century CE during the reign of Narasimhavarman I (630-668 CE) of Pallava dynasty. Statement 2 is incorrect: Ajanta caves are mostly dedicated to Buddhist denominations while Mahabalipuram is known for rock-cut monolithic temples, cave temples, and the Shore Temple (structural temple built with granite blocks) mostly dedicated to Shaivaite and Vaishnavite traditions. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 136 Statement 3 is correct: Both Mahabalipuram and Ajanta are one of the finest examples of rock-cut monuments. The Ajanta Caves are a series of rock-cut caves carved into a horseshoe- shaped cliff housing chaityas and viharas with intricate carvings and paintings. The monuments at Mahabalipuram include rock-cut temples and bas-relie","PW-0005":"Pair 1 is correctly matched: The Ajanta Caves (Maharashtra) are famous for their rock-cut Buddhist architecture including sculptures and paintings from the 2nd century BCE to the 6th century CE. The Mahaparinirvana of Buddha (his final passing away) is depicted in Cave 26 where a huge reclining Buddha (over 23 feet long) is shown lying on his right side, with his disciples mourning below and celestial beings above. They were built under the patronage of Satavahana and Vakataka rulers. Pair 2 is incorrectly matched: The Varaha Avatar sculpture is not located at Mount Abu. It is found at Udayagiri Caves near Vidisha, Madhya Pradesh. The Udayagiri Caves are famous for their early Gupta period rock-cut sculptures, including the iconic Varaha panel depicting Vishnu rescuing Goddess Earth (Bhudevi) from the ocean. Mount Abu (Rajasthan) is primarily known for its Dilwara Temples (11th-13th century CE) of Jain architecture. Pair 3 is correctly matched: The Arjuna’s Penance or Descent of the Ganges is a massive open-air rock relief located at Mamallapuram (Mahabalipuram) in Tamil Nadu. It dep","PW-0006":"","PW-0007":"Indian rock-cut architecture includes Badami caves (6th century AD), Barabar caves for the Ajivikas (3rd century BC), and Ellora caves (5th–10th centuries AD), showcasing diverse religious traditions like Hinduism, Buddhism, and Jainism, with remarkable architectural complexity. Statement 1 is incorrect: Badami caves were constructed by the Chalukya dynasty, in their capital Badami, which was earlier known as Vatapinagar. Barabar caves are the oldest surviving rock-cut caves in India. Statement 2 is incorrect: The Barabar Caves were patronized by Emperor Ashoka and his successors. These are located in Jehanabad district, Bihar. Statement 3 is correct: Ellora caves are a complex of Hindu (Caves 13-29), Buddhist (Caves 1-12) and Jain (Caves 30-34) monuments. These were built during the Rashtrakuta dynasty. It was designated as a World heritage site by UNESCO. 2. TEMPLE ARCHITECTURE 10","PW-0008":"Statement 1 is correct: The Chausath Yogini temple is in Morena district in Madhya Pradesh. According to an inscription dated 1323 AD, this temple was built by Kachachapaghata king Devapala (1055-1075). Statement 2 is incorrect: The temple with a circular design pattern is situated on top of a small hill. It is not the only circular temple in India. Other examples are Kameshwar Temple, Kashmir and Vishnu Temple at Topra (Haryana) etc. Statement 3 is incorrect: Originally 64 yoginis were placed in 64 subsidiary shrines around the central shrine of Maha Shakti. Today Shiva linga have taken their place in shrines. The central shrine also holds a Shivalinga. Statement 4 is correct: This temple’s circular design has given rise to the popular idea that our old Indian parliament’s design designed by architects Edwin Lutyens and Herbert Baker was taken from here. Fig.: Chausath Yogini Temple 11","PW-0009":"Vijayanagara art and architecture, flourishing from the 14th to 16th centuries, blends Dravidian styles with Islamic and Persian influences. Notable for grand temples like Virupaksha and the Hampi ruins, it features large gopurams, intricate carvings, and expansive courtyards, reflecting both devotion and royal splendor. Option (d) is correct: Kalyan Mandapa (or Kalyana Mandapam) is an architectural feature commonly seen in South Indian temples, especially during the Vijayanagara period (14th–17th century). These mandapas were used for ceremonial purposes, such as the symbolic marriage of deities. The Virupaksha Temple and Hazara Rama Temple in Hampi are prime examples of Vijayanagara architecture which feature Kalyana Mandapams with intricately carved pillars and large open spaces. The Kalyan Mandapa serves as a ceremonial hall within the temple complex, specifically built for conducting marriage rituals of deities, symbolizing the divine wedding of the presiding deity. The mandapas are often elaborately decorated with sculptures, intricate carvings, and motifs depicting deities, my","PW-0010":"Sun temples in India, dedicated to the Sun God Surya, are renowned for their architectural grandeur and symbolic representation of cosmic order. Famous Sun temples in India are Konark Sun Temple (Odisha), Dakshinaarka Temple at Gaya (Bihar), Bhramanya Dev Temple at Unao (Madhya Pradesh), Sun Temple at Modhera (Gujarat). Option 1 is correct: Arasavalli located in the Srikakulam district of Andhra Pradesh is famous for the Suryanarayana Temple is dedicated to the Sun God (Surya). This temple is one of the few ancient Sun temples in India and is believed to have been built in the 7th century CE by the Kalinga king Devendra Varma. The temple is designed in such a way that the sun's rays fall directly on the feet of the Sun God's idol twice a year, during the months of March and September. Option 2 is incorrect: Amarkantak is a pilgrimage town in Madhya Pradesh which marks the origin of the Narmada River. Here Lord Shiva is worshiped as Narmadeswar Amarkantak. Option 3 is incorrect: Omkareshwar located in Madhya Pradesh is one of the 12 Jyotirlingas and is famous for the Omkareshwar Templ","PW-0011":" The rock-cut elephant situated in Dhauli was constructed during the reign of Ashoka, who ruled from 272 to 231 BC (3rd Century AD) .  Varaha Image at Udayagiri Hill was built in the 5th century AD by Chandragupta II (Vikramaditya) to commemorate the victory over the foreign Shaka.  The rock-cut monuments in Mahabalipuram were constructed during the 7th and 8th centuries AD mainly by the Pallava king Narasimha.  On the other hand, the Lingaraj Temple was built in the 11th century AD, under the reign of the Eastern Ganga dynasty. The temple is a major Shaivite temple, a prime example of Kalinga architecture and is one of the largest temples in Odisha UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 138 14","PW-0012":"Indian temple architecture is diverse, with distinct regional styles such as the Nagara (northern), Dravida (southern), and Vesara (a blend of both). The Panchayatan style is a sub-school of Nagara architecture, specifically prevalent in North India. Option (c) is correct:  Panchayatan is a temple architecture style where the main shrine (garbhagriha) is surrounded by four subsidiary shrines, forming a quincunx (four smaller shrines at the corners and one main shrine in the center).  The term comes from the Sanskrit words Pancha (five) and ayatana (containing).  The Dashavatara Vishnu Temple in Deogarh, Uttar Pradesh, built in the early 6th century AD, follows this style, with the main shrine on a rectangular plinth and four subsidiary shrines at the corners, totaling five shrines. Other temples that follow the Panchayatan style are Kandariya Mahadeva Temple (Khajuraho, MP), built during the Chandela period and the Lakshmana Temple (Khajuraho, MP). 15","PW-0013":"Temple architecture in India follows three main styles: Nagara (Northern), Dravida (Southern), and Vesara (Mixed). Nagara Style (North Indian Temple Architecture) is found in Northern, Central, and Western India. Its key features are :  Shikhara (Tower) which is curvilinear in shape, rising progressively higher.  Multiple Shikharas each smaller than the main one.  Garbhagriha (Sanctum Sanctorum) which houses the deity.  Mandapa (Pillared Hall) usually present in front of the sanctum.  Amalaka (Ribbed Disc), a large stone disc placed on top of the shikhara. Notable examples are : Kandariya Mahadeva Temple (Khajuraho, Madhya Pradesh), Sun Temple (Konark, Odisha),Lingaraj Temple (Bhubaneswar, Odisha),etc. Dravida Style (South Indian Temple Architecture) is seen across Tamil Nadu, Karnataka, Andhra Pradesh, Telangana. Its key features:  Vimana (Tower) are pyramid-like structure over the sanctum.  Gopurams (Gateway Towers) are large, ornate entrance towers.  Sculptures & Mandapas are extensive carvings and pillared halls.  Temple Tanks are found in major temples for ritualistic p","PW-0014":"Rajput regional paintings, flourishing in Rajasthan from the 16th to 19th centuries, are known for their vibrant colors, detailed depictions of court life, and themes from Hindu mythology. Styles like Mewar, Marwar, and Bundi showcase ornate portraits, landscapes, and historical events with a distinctive blend of Persian and Indian artistic traditions. Option (d) is correct: Bani Thani paintings are a distinctive style of Indian miniature art that originated in the 18th century in the Rajput kingdom of Kishangarh, Rajasthan. Bani Thani painted by artist Nihal Chand is often referred to as the \"Mona Lisa of India\" and depicts a courtesan who was the muse and beloved of Raja Sawant Singh. The painting is characterized by its graceful curves, large eyes, and delicate features. 17","PW-0015":"","PW-0016":"","PW-0017":"Pair 1 is correctly matched : Tabo Monastery situated in the Spiti Valley of Himachal Pradesh, India is a historically and culturally significant Buddhist monastery. It was founded in 996 CE and is one of the oldest continuously functioning Buddhist monasteries in India and is renowned for its exquisite murals, sculptures, and architecture reflecting a blend of Tibetan and Indian artistic influences. Pair 2 is incorrectly matched : Lhotsava Lhakhang is located in Nako village which is part of Kinnaur district of Himachal Pradesh. Pair 3 is correctly matched : Alchi Temple Complex located in the village of Alchi in Ladakh, India and was built in the 12th century is another important Buddhist site. It is particularly famous for its unique and well-preserved wall paintings which showcase a fusion of Indian and Kashmiri artistic styles. 20","PW-0018":" The Ajanta Caves located in Aurangabad, Maharashtra dates back to the 2nd century BCE to the 6th century CE. The Caves were patronized by the Satavahanas during the early phase (2nd century BCE) and later by the Vakatakas, especially under King Harisena (5th–6th century CE). They are globally renowned for their exquisite mural paintings which depict Jataka tales, scenes from Buddha’s life and courtly settings. These paintings were created using the tempera technique (dry plaster method) showcasing remarkable artistry and intricate detailing. Some of the most famous artworks include Bodhisattva Padmapani, Bodhisattva Vajrapani and the Dying Princess.  The Lepakshi Temple is located in Andhra Pradesh. It was built in the 16th century under the Vijayanagara Empire by the brothers Viranna and Virupanna. The Veerabhadra Temple at Lepakshi is particularly renowned for its mural paintings which adorn its ceilings and walls. These paintings depict Hindu deities, royal processions and mythological themes which showcases the distinct Vijayanagara style characterized by bright colors and int","PW-0019":"","PW-0020":"Carnatic music is a classical music tradition of South India, characterized by its intricate ragas (melodies) and talas (rhythms), with a strong emphasis on vocal performance and improvisation. Prominent early singers include Muthuswami Dikshitar, Syama Sastri, and Tyagaraja, who significantly contributed to its development through their compositions and performances. Statement 1 is incorrect: Tyagaraja is known for his devotional songs (Kritis) to Lord Rama and not Lord Krishna. Statement 2 is correct: He innovated the technique of structural variations of musical lines and created new Ragas. Statement 3 is incorrect: Annamacharya belonged to the 15th century whereas Tyagaraja belonged to the 18th century and so they are non-contemporary. Statement 4 is correct: Annamacharya is renowned for his keertanas (devotional songs), most of which are dedicated to Lord Venkateshwara, the deity of the Tirumala Venkateswara Temple in Tirupati. 23","PW-0021":"Dhrupad is derived from ‘Dhruva’ (fixed star) and ‘Pada’ (song), is an ancient form of classical music that emerged from early vocal traditions. It is performed with tanpura and pakhawaj, its lyrics in Braj Bhasha often reflect devotion and heroism, expressing emotions like veera and sringar. Key gharanas include Dagarvani, Bishnupur, Darbhanga, and Mallik. Statement 1 is incorrect: Dhrupad traces its roots back to the ancient text Sama Veda. Its modern form evolved during the 15th and 16th centuries particularly in the courts of the Rajput kingdoms and the Mughal emperors. The Rajput kings such as Raja Man Singh Tomar of Gwalior were great patrons of Dhrupad. Dhrupad flourished under the patronage of emperors like Akbar, who admired musicians like Tansen. Statement 2 is correct: Dhrupad is deeply rooted in spirituality and devotion. It often incorporates themes from Hindu scriptures, such as the Bhagavad Gita and the Puranas, and is traditionally performed in temples and royal courts. The lyrics of Dhrupad compositions (called prabandhas) are usually in praise of deities like Vishnu","PW-0022":"Sankirtana is a Meitei cultural performance art which includes a wide range of artistic expressions carried out to commemorate special religious occasions and different phases in the lives of the Vaishnava people of the Manipur plains. Sankirtana rituals are centered around temples and domestic spaces, where dancers and singers narrate stories of Lord Krishna’s life and actions through dance and song. In 2013, UNESCO added Manipur’s distinctive cultural legacy to its Representative List of Intangible Cultural Heritage of Humanity. Statement 1 is correct: Manipuri Sankirtana is a vibrant combination of song and dance. It is a form of devotional performance that involves singing, drumming, and dancing, often performed in a circular formation. The performers sing hymns and devotional songs, accompanied by rhythmic movements and drumming. Statement 2 is incorrect: While cymbals (kartal) are an essential part of Manipuri Sankirtana but they are not the only instruments used. The primary instrument in Sankirtana is the Pung, a traditional Manipuri drum. Other instruments such as the harmon","PW-0023":"Sattriya is a classical dance form from Assam which was developed in the 15th–16th century by Srimanta Sankardev as part of the Vaishnavite movement. The dance follows a codified sequence, beginning with Ramdani (pure dance), followed by Gayan Bayan (percussive music and dance), and includes Krishna Nritya and Gopi Nritya, depicting Krishna’s tales. It is accompanied by Borgeet (devotional songs) composed by Sankardev and Madhavdev and often features Ankia Naat (one-act plays). Statement 1 is correct: Sattriya was traditionally performed in sattras (Vaishnavite monasteries) and combined dance, music, and drama. Sattriya dance tradition is governed by strictly laid down principles in respect of hasta mudras, footwork, aharyas, music etc. Statement 2 is correct: The Sattriya dance form was introduced in the 15th century A.D by the great Vaishnava saint and reformer of Assam, Mahapurusha Sankaradeva as a powerful medium for the propagation of the Vaishnava faith. Statement 3 is incorrect: It is based on the songs composed by Sankaradeva and Madhvadeva not Tulsidas, Kabir and Mirabai. 26","PW-0024":"India’s rich cultural heritage boasts a variety of folk dance forms, each reflecting regional traditions. Garba from Gujarat is performed during Navratri with rhythmic clapping and circular movements. Mohiniattam, though a classical dance from Kerala, often incorporated folk elements. Yakshagana from Karnataka combines dance, music, and theatrical storytelling. Other notable folk dances include Bhangra from Punjab, Kathakali from Kerala, Lavani from Maharashtra, and Kuchipudi from Andhra Pradesh. These dances, often performed during festivals, celebrate local folklore, deities, and seasonal transitions, blending music, drama, and vibrant costumes. Pair 1 is correctly matched: Garba is a famous dance form of Gujarat, performed to honor the Hindu Deity, Goddess Durga. It is a sacred practice in Gujarat to perform this joyful folk dance on practically all important occasions. Pair 2 is incorrectly matched: Mohiniattam is a classical dance form from Kerala, characterized by its graceful, soft, and feminine style. It is classified under the Lasya category, which emphasizes elegance and ge","PW-0025":"Statement 1 is correct : Kuchipudi dance form originates from Andhra Pradesh and is known for its dramatic elements. Dancers often incorporate spoken dialogues (Vachika Abhinaya) as part of the performance, especially in dance-dramas like Bhama Kalapam. The traditional Sutradhara (narrator) or lead performer in Kuchipudi often delivers dialogues. Bharatanatyam originates from Tamil Nadu and is primarily a silent dance form where expressions are conveyed through gestures (Mudras), facial expressions (Abhinaya), and body movements. Spoken dialogues are not part of traditional Bharatanatyam performances. Statement 2 is incorrect : Dancing on a brass plate (Tarangam) is a signature feature of Kuchipudi, not Bharatanatyam. In Kuchipudi the dancer balances on the edges of a brass plate while moving gracefully and often with a pot of water on the head (symbolizing control and balance). Bharatanatyam focuses more on structured footwork, linear movements and geometric postures. 6. MARTIAL ARTS IN INDIA 29","PW-0026":"Kalaripayattu is an ancient martial art form which originated in Kerala, a state in the southern part of India. Its name derives from the Malayalam words \"Kalari,\" meaning training ground or battlefield and \"Payattu,\" meaning practice or fight. This martial art is renowned for its comprehensive training regimen which includes strikes, kicks, grappling, weaponry, healing methods, and meditation. Practitioners begin their training with an oil massage to enhance body agility and suppleness. The art also emphasizes knowledge of \"Marmas\" or vital points by integrating traditional healing practices into its system. 7. CULTURE IN INDIA 30","PW-0027":" Shantiniketan located in West Bengal is the home of Rabindranath Tagore’s Visva-Bharati University. It was inscribed on the UNESCO World Heritage List in September 2023 for its cultural and educational significance. Santiniketan which means ‘abode of peace’ started taking shape in 1901, and it was this place Tagore later put up the foundations of Visva Bharati University.  Sacred Ensembles of the Hoysalas: The Sacred Ensembles of the Hoysalas locatĊd in Karnataka, include the Hoysala temples at Belur, Halebid, and Somnathapura. These temples were inscribed on the UNESCO World Heritage List in September 2023 for their exceptional architecture and artistry. The shrines are characterized by hyper- real sculptures and stone carvings that cover the entire architectural surface, a circumambulatory platform, a large- scale sculptural gallery, a multi-tiered frieze, and sculptures of the Sala legend. Other sites:  Rani-ki-Vav located in Gujarat is an 11th-century stepwell known for its intricate architecture and sculptures. These stepwells are a distinctive form of subterranean water res","PW-0028":"Pair 1 is incorrectly matched: Besnagar (located in Madhya Pradesh) is not known for being a Shaivite Cave Shrine. It is known for Garuda Pillar dedicated to lord Vasudeva by Heliodorus,an envoy of an Indo-Greek ruler Antialkidas in the court of Bhagabhadra. Heliodorus followed Vaishnava Sect. Pair 2 is correctly matched: Bhaja (located in Maharashtra) is renowned for its Buddhist cave complex dating back to the 2nd century BCE. The 22 cave complex is part of the early phase of Buddhist rock-cut architecture and include a chaitya (prayer hall) and viharas (monastic cells). Pair 3 is correctly matched: Sittanavasal (located in Tamil Nadu) is famous for its Jain cave complex which dates back to the 2nd century BCE. The site includes a rock-cut cave temple with beautiful frescoes depicting Jain themes such as the Samavasarana (divine preaching hall). Art and Culture 143 32","PW-0029":"","PW-0030":"India’s tribal languages reflect its rich cultural diversity, with hundreds of languages spoken by indigenous communities. These languages belong to various linguistic families, including Indo-Aryan and Dravidian. There are also other smaller language families, such as Austroasiatic (Ex-Munda languages) and Tibeto- Burman (Ex-Bodo). Examples of Tribal Languages include Halbi (Madhya Pradesh, Maharashtra), Ho (Jharkhand, Odisha), Kui (Odisha), Gondi (Central India), Korku (Madhya Pradesh), Kurukh (Odisha, Jharkhand), and Bhili (Rajasthan, Gujarat). Option (d) is correct:  Halbi is spoken in Chhattisgarh, Madhya Pradesh, Odisha, and Maharashtra. It is an Indo-Aryan language influenced by Marathi and Odia. It is used by the Halba tribe and is recognized as a lingua franca among tribal communities in Bastar region.  Ho is spoken in Jharkhand, Odisha, West Bengal, and Chhattisgarh. It belongs to the Munda language family which a branch of the Austroasiatic languages. The Ho tribe is an ethnic Munda community which primarily speaks this language. It has its own script called Warang Citi ","PW-0031":"Pair 1 is correctly matched: Bhilsa is the medieval name of the modern day Vidisha city of Madhya Pradesh. Vidisha was also known as Besnagar in ancient times. King Ashoka of the Mauryan dynasty served as the Governor of Vidisha during his father’s regime. It is known for its archaeological sites including the Udayagiri Caves and the Heliodorus Pillar. Pair 2 is incorrectly matched: Dwarasamudra was the capital of the Hoysala kingdom in the 11th century. Today it is known as Halebidu - a town located in Hassan district in Karnataka and is known for exquisite Hoysala architecture, including the Hoysaleswara Temple. Pair 3 is correctly matched: Girinagar also known as Girnar or Revatak Parvat is a group of mountains in the Junagadh district of Gujarat. Temples situated on Mount Girnar are sacred to both Digambar and Swetambars branches of Jainism. Pair 4 is incorrectly matched: Thanesar (Thaneshwar) is an old Hindu pilgrimage town of Haryana that was famous as Sthanesvara in ancient times. Thaneshwar was ruled by the great King Harsha of the Vardhan dynasty. 36","PW-0032":"Pair 1 is correct: Chapchar Kut is a spring festival of Mizo people in Mizoram. It is celebrated in March after they complete their jhum cultivation (Jungle clearing). UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 144 Pair 2 is correct: The Khongjom Parba is a traditional ballad form from Manipur. It commemorates the bravery of Manipuri warriors, particularly the Battle of Khongjom fought during the Anglo-Manipur War of 1891. The ballad is performed with a combination of singing and storytelling with the accompaniment of instruments like the dholak (a type of drum). Pair 3 is incorrect: Thang-Ta is an ancient Manipuri Martial Art dance developed from the war environment of Manipur by the Meitei community. Thang-Ta was also known as Huyen Lallong which means ‘The art of sword and the spear’. 37","PW-0033":"India’s cultural landscape is marked by a wide array of religious traditions that include the Chaliha Sahib Festival (Sindhis), Nanda Raj Jaat Yatra (Garhwalis), Wari-Warkari (Maharashtrians), Baisakhi (Punjabis), Bohag Bihu (Assamese), and Onam (Keralites) Pair 1 is correctly matched: The Chaliha Sahib Festival is a significant religious festival celebrated by the Sindhi community. It is dedicated to Jhulelal the patron saint of the Sindhis and involves 40 days of fasting, prayers, and rituals. Pair 2 is incorrectly matched: The Nanda Raj Jaat Yatra is a major pilgrimage in Uttarakhand associated with Garhwali and Kumaono community, not Gond community. It is a traditional yatra (pilgrimage) that takes place every 12 years, and involves a journey to the Nanda Devi peak. Pair 3 is incorrectly matched: The Wari-Warkari tradition is associated with the Warkari sect of Maharashtra, not the Santhal community. The Warkari sect is a devotional movement centered around the worship of Lord Vitthal (a form of Lord Krishna) and involves an annual pilgrimage to the Pandharpur temple. 38","PW-0034":"","PW-0035":"The designations ‘Mahattara’ and ‘Pattakila’ were used for village officers in medieval India.  Mahattara was used to denote the village headman. They played a crucial role in local governance, overseeing agricultural activities, resolving disputes, and ensuring the welfare of the villagers.  Pattakila is generally identified with the modern term 'Patel' and was believed to be the king's representative in the village. Their responsibilities included collecting taxes, maintaining law and order, and implementing the directives of the central administration at the village level. 40","PW-0036":"Every monsoon the Gond and Korku tribes of Betul and Harda districts of Madhya Pradesh celebrate a month- long festival known as Hari Jiroti. This festival is dedicated to promoting greenery and environmental conservation. During Hari Jiroti community members engage in the plantation of saplings, especially those of fruit-bearing trees such as mango, guava, and jamun. This practice not only enhances the local ecosystem but also ensures a sustainable source of food and income for future generations. 41","PW-0037":"The Indian national calendar based on the Saka calendar was officially adopted on 22nd March 1957. This calendar is utilized alongside the Gregorian calendar for official purposes such as the Gazette of India, news broadcasts by All India Radio, and government communications. The Saka calendar commences with the month of Chaitra.  In a common year (365 days): 1st Chaitra corresponds to 22nd March in the Gregorian calendar.  In a leap year (366 days): 1st Chaitra corresponds to 21st March. Art and Culture 145 42","PW-0038":"The Bhakti movement was a devotional reform movement in medieval India, emphasizing love and devotion to a personal god over ritualistic practices. It spread across regions, with prominent saints like Kabir, who challenged religious orthodoxy; Ramanuja, who advocated for Vishnu worship; and Meerabai, a passionate devotee of Krishna. Statement 1 is incorrect: Bijak is a collection of Kabir’s teachings(not Saint Dadu Dayal), a 15th-century mystic poet and saint who challenged ritualistic practices in Hinduism and Islam. His writings influenced the Bhakti movement and are included in the Guru Granth Sahib. He was a disciple of Ramananda. Statement 2 is incorrect: Vallabhacharya’s philosophy came to be known as Pushti Marga. He founded the philosophy of Shuddhadvaita which believed in the absolute union. He was the first to advocate for Krishna Bhakti using the Maha Bhagavata Purana as a foundation. 43","PW-0039":"The Manganiyars are a traditional Muslim community of musicians from the Thar desert region of Rajasthan, India. Known for their rich musical heritage, they specialize in folk and devotional music, often performing for royalty, festivals, and religious occasions. Their repertoire includes Sufi songs, bhajans, and wedding songs, which are deeply rooted in the region’s cultural and spiritual life. The Manganiyars use traditional instruments such as the dholak, khartal, and sarangi, passing down their art through generations. Their performances are recognized for their emotional depth and storytelling, making them an integral part of Rajasthan’s musical tradition. 44","PW-0040":"According to the Linguistic Experts Committee, the following benchmarks must be met for a language to be considered “classical”:  High antiquity of (its) is early texts/recorded history over a period of 1500- 2000 years.  A body of ancient literature/texts, which is considered a heritage by generations of speakers.  Knowledge texts, especially prose texts in addition to poetry, epigraphical and inscriptional evidence.  The Classical Languages and literature could be distinct from its current form or could be discontinuous with later forms of its offshoots. Both Kannada and Telugu have been declared as ‘Classical Language/Languages’ by the Government. Gujarati has not been declared as a classical language by the government of India. The classical languages in our country are Tamil (2004), Sanskrit (2005), Kannada (2008), Telugu (2008), Malayalam (2013), Odia (2014), Marathi, Pali, Prakrit, Assamese and Bengali (announcement made in 2024). 45","PW-0041":"The national motto of India \"Satyameva Jayate\" inscribed below the national emblem is derived from the Mundaka Upanishad. This ancient Sanskrit scripture is one of the principal Upanishads embedded within the Atharva Veda. The phrase \"Satyameva Jayate\" translates to \"Truth alone triumphs.\" The adoption of ‘Satyameva Jayate’ as the national motto reflects India's commitment to truth and righteousness, values deeply embedded in its ancient scriptures. The phrase was popularized during India's independence movement and was chosen to symbolize the nation's moral and ethical foundation. 47","PW-0042":"The Bhakti movement was a devotional reform movement in India that emphasized personal devotion to a chosen deity, transcending ritualism and caste distinctions. It gained momentum through saints like Kabir, Ramanuja, Mirabai, Tulsidas, Alvars, and Nayanars, who spread the message of love and surrender to God. Option (b) is correct: Guru Nanak was preaching during the time when the Lodi dynasty fell and Babur took over. He emphasized the oneness of God, equality of all people, selfless service, and devotion to truth, transcending religious divisions. While Dadu Dayal was born after the fall of the Lodi dynasty and was active during the latter part of the 16th century, so he was not preaching when Babur took over. Tyagaraja, on the other hand, lived in the 18th-19th century, much later than the fall of the Lodi dynasty. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 146 48","PW-0043":"The Indian schools of orthodox philosophy (Āstika) include Nyaya, Vaisheshika, Sankhya, Yoga, Mimamsa, and Vedanta, all of which accept the authority of the Vedas. These schools emphasize reasoning, metaphysical principles, and the pursuit of liberation through knowledge, ethics, and meditation. Statement 1 is incorrect: While Samkhya accepts rebirth (or samsara) and acknowledges that the soul’s entanglement with Prakriti results in repeated cycles of reincarnation, it does not emphasize karma in the same way as the systems that directly teach the law of cause and effect leading to future rebirths. Samkhya philosophy is dualistic and not monistic because it has two entities, Purush (spirit) and Prakriti (nature). Statement 2 is correct: Samkhya emphasizes the attainment of knowledge of the self by means of concentration and meditation. It believes that after you have ‘died’ in this life you will go through a process of rebirth where depending on your actions in your former life your status will be decided. Liberation (moksha) occurs when the Purusha realizes its distinct nature from ","PW-0044":"Madhyama-vyayoga is one of the thirteen plays attributed to Bhasa. It is a one-act play (Prakarana) that revolves around a family reunion and is based on an episode from the Mahabharata. The play is notable for its dramatic structure, emotional depth, and adherence to classical Sanskrit theatrical conventions. The story unfolds with themes of valor, familial bonds, and moral dilemmas, culminating in a reunion that highlights Bhāsa's skill in dramatizing epic tales.  Kavyalankara is a work on poetics and literary criticism attributed to Bhamaha, a 7th-century Sanskrit scholar. It is one of the earliest texts on Sanskrit poetics and discusses figures of speech (alankaras) and the nature of poetry.  Natyashastra is a foundational text on Indian performing arts, including drama, dance, and music attributed to Bharata Muni. It is often referred to as the \"fifth Veda\" and provides detailed guidelines for theatrical performance, stagecraft, and aesthetics.  The Mahabhashya is a commentary on Panini’s Ashtadhyayi, the foundational text of Sanskrit grammar. It is attributed to Patanjali an","PW-0045":"Sanghabhuti was an Indian Buddhist monk from Kashmir who traveled to China towards the end of the 4th century AD. Sanghabhuti is primarily associated with the Sarvastivada Vinaya, a text that outlines the monastic rules and discipline for Buddhist monks and nuns. He traveled to China and collaborated with Chinese scholars to translate and comment on this text, which was crucial for the establishment of Buddhist monastic practices in China. 51","PW-0046":"Pair 1 is incorrectly matched: Devichandragupta is a Sanskrit play attributed to Vishakhadatta, not Bilhana. The play is based on the historical events surrounding the Gupta king Chandragupta II and his queen Dhruvadevi. Vishakhadatta also authored Mudrarakshasa. Bilhana was an 11th-century Kashmiri poet known for his works like Vikramankadevacharita (a biography of the Chalukya king Vikramaditya VI) and Chaurapanchasika (a collection of love poems). Pair 2 is correctly matched: Hammira-Mahakavya is a Sanskrit epic poem written by Nayachandra Suri, a Jain scholar. The text narrates the life and exploits of Hammira, a 13th-century Chauhan king of Ranthambor and his resistance against the Delhi Sultanate. Pair 3 is incorrectly matched: Milinda-panha (Questions of King Milinda) is a Buddhist text that records a dialogue between the Indo-Greek king Menander I (Milinda) and the Buddhist monk Nagasena. The text is attributed to Nagasena, not Nagarjuna. Nagarjuna was a 2nd-century CE philosopher and founder of the Madhyamaka school of Mahayana Buddhism and is known for works like Mulamadhya","PW-0047":"Mrichchhakatika (The Little Clay Cart), authored by Shudraka, is a classic Sanskrit drama. It narrates the love story between Charudatta, a virtuous but impoverished Brahmin merchant, and Vasantasena, a wealthy courtesan. This work, set against the backdrop of urban life in ancient India, explores themes of love, morality, social hierarchy, and political intrigue. Unlike epics or courtly literature, Mrichchhakatika focuses on the lives of ordinary people, providing valuable insights into the socio- economic conditions of the time. Other Sanskrit plays ascribed to Shudraka are Vinavasavadatta, Bhana (short one-act monologue) and Padmaprabhritaka. 53","PW-0048":"Mudrarakshasa by Vishakhadatta is a political drama revolving around the strategic acumen of Chanakya (Kautilya) in securing Chandragupta Maurya’s rise to power. The play narrates the clever maneuvering by Chanakya to win over Rakshasa, a loyal minister of the Nanda dynasty, to Chandragupta’s side. It provides valuable insights into Mauryan administrative policies and the importance of realpolitik during this era. 54","PW-0049":"Sangam literature refers to the ancient Tamil literary corpus, composed between 300 BCE and 300 CE, which includes poems celebrating heroism, love, and ethics. Notable works include the Tolkappiyam, the earliest Tamil grammar text, and the Ettuthokai and Pattupattu, which offer insights into the socio- political and cultural life of Tamil kingdoms. A is true: The Padinen Kilukanakku is a collection of 18 post- Sangam Tamil literary works, divided into Aham (love) and Puram (war) genres. These works are considered a continuation of the Sangam literature in terms of themes, style, and language. They reflect the same poetic traditions and cultural values as the Sangam compositions. R is true: The Padinen Kilukanakku is classified as post- Sangam literature because it was composed after the Sangam period proper. While the Sangam works are the earliest Tamil literary compositions, the Padinen Kilukanakku texts were written later during the post-Sangam period (circa 300–600 CE). R is the correct explanation of A: The Padinen Kilkanakku texts though composed in the Post-Sangam period but ca","PW-0050":"The Dharma Chakra Pravartana Sutta records the Buddha’s first sermon at Sarnath, where he expounded the Four Noble Truths and the Eightfold Path. This path provides a practical guide to overcoming dukkha (suffering) and achieving Nirvana. The Eightfold Path consists of: Right View; Right Intention; Right Speech; Right Action; Right Livelihood; Right Effort; Right Mindfulness and Right Concentration. It advocates a balanced approach, avoiding extremes of asceticism and indulgence, laying the foundation for Buddhist ethics and practice. This sermon marks the beginning of the Sangha (monastic community). 56","PW-0051":"Pair 1 is correctly matched: Mrichchakatikam (The Little Clay Cart) is an ancient Sanskrit play by Shudraka, blending romance, social commentary, and drama, and is known for its vivid portrayal of love, class struggles, and moral dilemmas. Pair 2 is incorrectly matched: Buddhacharita was written by Ashvaghosha, not Vasuvandhu. The work, composed in the 2nd century CE, narrates the life and teachings of Sakyamuni (Gautama Buddha), including his birth, renunciation, enlightenment, and his efforts to spread the Dharma. Pair 3 is correctly matched: Mudrarakshasa is a classical Sanskrit play by Vishakhadatta, depicting the political intrigue and cunning diplomacy of Chanakya as he helps Chandragupta Maurya rise to power, showcasing themes of statecraft and strategy. Pair 4 is correctly matched: Harshacharita (The Deeds of Harsha) is a biographical work on Emperor Harsha (7th century CE), written by Banabhatta. He was the court poet of Harshavardhana and is considered one of the earliest Indian biographers. 57","PW-0052":"A is matched with 3 : Varahamihira authored Brihat- Samhita, a significant text in ancient Indian astronomy and astrology, reflecting the scientific knowledge of the Gupta period. He also wrote Panchasiddhantika. B is matched with 4 : Vishakhadatta is the author of two major historical Sanskrit dramas:  Devi-Chandraguptam play which describes the love story of King Chandragupta II (Vikramaditya) and Queen Dhruvadevi.  Mudrarakshasa is about Chandragupta Maurya’s rise with the help of Chanakya. C is matched with 2 : Sudraka is known for Mrichchhakatikam (The Little Clay Cart), a Sanskrit play that tells the story of the romance between Charudatta, a noble but impoverished merchant, and Vasantika, a courtesan. The central themes include love, sacrifice, and the struggles of social classes, with an emphasis on the tensions between the upper and lower classes. D is matched with 5 : Bilhana authored Vikramankadeva- Charita, an epic poem which celebrates the achievements and virtues of King Vikramaditya VI, who ruled the Western Chalukya dynasty (also known as the Kalyani Chalukyas) from","PW-0053":"The Kharosthi script was an ancient script used in northwest India. It was used mainly in the Gandhara region and is associated with the Buddhist texts and inscriptions of that area. It was derived from the Aramaic script and written from right to left, distinguishing it from most other Indian scripts like Brahmi, which were written from left to right. Nandnagari and Sharada scripts both evolved from Brahmi and were written from left to right. 59","PW-0054":"The dialogue between Nachiketa and Yama is one of the most famous philosophical exchanges found in the Kathopanishad, a part of Yajurveda. In their dialogue, Nachiketa asks profound questions about the nature of death, immortality, and the soul’s journey, which leads to deep philosophical teachings on the eternal nature of the self (Atman) and the ultimate truth (Brahman). 60","PW-0055":"The Milindapanho (Questions of King Milinda) is an important Buddhist text that records a philosophical dialogue between Indo-Greek King Menander I (Milinda) and the Buddhist monk Nagasena. This text explores profound Buddhist concepts like impermanence (Anicca), non-self (Anatta), and the doctrine of karma through logical discourse and metaphors. The Milindapanho is considered an important work in the Theravada tradition. 61","PW-0056":"Arthashastra, attributed to Kautilya, contains provisions related to social and economic aspects, including marriage and divorce. According to Arthashastra, a wife deserted by her husband had the legal right to seek divorce and remarry. If a man abandoned his wife without valid reason then she could remarry after waiting for a certain period. It also mentions conditions under which a woman could remarry if her husband was missing, dead, or had become a renunciate (ascetic). 9. BUDDHISM AND JAINISM 62","PW-0057":" Shakyamuni epithet is widely used in Buddhist texts such as the Lalitavistara Sutra and Mahayana scriptures for Gautama Buddha \"Shakyamuni\" means \"Sage of the Shakya Clan.\" Gautama Buddha was born as Prince Siddhartha in the Shakya clan which ruled the region of Kapilavastu (modern Nepal-India border).  Tathagata means \"The One Who Has Thus Gone (Tatha- gata) or Thus Come (Tatha-agata),\" referring to Buddha's enlightened state and transcendence over worldly existence. It is one of the most common epithets used by Gautama Buddha himself in Pali Canon texts like the Digha Nikaya and Majjhima Nikaya.  \"Nayaputta\" is not an epithet of Gautama Buddha; rather, it refers to Mahavira, the 24th Tirthankara of Jainism 63","PW-0058":"Dhanyakataka (also spelled Dharanikota or Dharanikonda) was an ancient city located in the present- day Andhra Pradesh region of India. It flourished as a major Buddhist center, particularly under the Mahasanghika school of Buddhism. The city is closely associated with the Amaravati Stupa, one of the most significant Buddhist monuments in India. It was a hub of Buddhist learning and practice during the Satavahana period (2nd century BCE to 2nd century CE) and continued to be important under the Ikshvaku dynasty (3rd–4th century CE). Excavations have revealed Buddhist relic caskets, stupas, and monasteries, confirming its association with Buddhism. Art and Culture 149 64","PW-0059":" Parishishta Parvan also called the Sthaviravali Charita. It was written by Hemachandra (12th century CE). It is a Jain historical text that provides biographies of Jain monks and rulers who supported Jainism. It contains details about Chandragupta Maurya's conversion to Jainism under the guidance of Bhadrabahu.  Trishashtilakshana Mahapurana is a Jain Purana written by Hemachandra in the 12th century CE. It details the lives of 63 great Jain figures (Shalaka Purushas), including the 24 Tirthankaras, 12 Chakravartins, 9 Vasudevas, 9 Balabhadras, and 9 Prati-Vasudevas.  Nettipakarana (The Guidebook) is an ancient Pali Buddhist text. It is part of the Khuddaka Nikaya of the Pali Canon and serves as a guide for interpreting Buddhist teachings.  Avadanasataka(Century of Noble Deeds) is a Buddhist text written in Sanskrit. It is a collection of Buddhist legends and moral stories, emphasizing karmic consequences and rebirth. 66","PW-0060":" Āryadeva was a Mahayana Buddhist monk, a disciple of Nagarjuna and a Madhyamaka philosopher. His key work \"Catuḥśataka\" (Four Hundred Verses) elaborates on Madhyamaka philosophy. His writings are important sources of Madhyamaka in both East Asian Buddhism and Tibetan Buddhism.  Dignaga, a Buddhist logician and author of the Pramāṇasamuccaya (Compendium of the Means of Valid Knowledge) laid the foundations of Buddhist logic.  Nathamuni (9th–10th century CE) was a Vaishnavite scholar and theologian. He is credited with compiling the Nalayira Divya Prabandham, a collection of hymns by Tamil Alvars, which became a foundational text in Sri Vaishnavism. He was also the guru of Yamunacharya and predecessor of Ramanuja in the Vishishtadvaita tradition. 67","PW-0061":"Paramitas are qualities to be perfected in order to attain a state of self enlightened Universal Buddha (a samma sambuddha) a term prevalent in Eastern and Northern Buddhist traditions. Paramitas These are qualities to be perfected in order to transcend into a self enlightened Universal Buddha . Here, The Fourth Noble Truth outlines the Eightfold Path, which is a practical guideline for attaining the cessation of suffering (nirvana), while the Ten Paramitas focus more on the qualities required of a Bodhisattva, both paths lead toward enlightenment. Following are the Ten Paramitas: Generosity, Morality, Patience, Energy, Meditation, Wisdom, Skillful means, Resolution, Power, Knowledge. 68","PW-0062":"Statement 1 is incorrect: The Sthaviravadins were an early Buddhist sect that later became associated with Theravada Buddhism, not Mahayana. Statement 2 is correct: Mahasanghika was further subdivided into several sects including Lokottarvadin, Kavya Variks, Kaukkitikas in coming years. Lokottarvadin was based on the philosophy of Lokottar Buddha or Supernatural Buddha. Statement 3 is correct: The deification of Buddha by Mahasanghika fostered Mahayana Buddhism. They attributed divinity to Buddha and worship of Buddha in Statue form started which is still prevalent in modern days. 69","PW-0063":"In ancient Indian Non-Vedic religious traditions like Buddhism and Jainism, distinct roles and terminologies were used to describe various types of spiritual practitioners and followers such as Parivrajaka, Shramana and Upasaka. Pair 1 is correctly matched: The Sanskrit word Parivrajaka means renunciant & wanderer in English. Ajita Keshkambalin, Makhkhali Goshala, Gauthama Buddha, and Vardhamana Mahavira are a few well-known examples for Parivrajaka. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 150 Pair 2 is incorrectly matched: Brahmins were privileged as intermediaries between God and its followers, making them socially dominant groups of the society. There have been many movements that tried to distance themselves from this practice and belief. Shramanas were one such group.  Famous among them were Buddhists, Jains, lokayats, and Ajivikas. The Shramanas included a variety of ascetics, monks and lay followers of various sects.  They renounced worldly life to search for the truth about life and the universe. The main feature of Shramana was their equal treatment. They lived as an equal member of the orde","PW-0064":"Buddhism has several sects, with the main ones being Theravada, which follows the earliest teachings of the Buddha, and Mahayana, which emphasizes the Bodhisattva path and compassion for all beings. Additionally, Vajrayana (or Tibetan Buddhism) incorporates esoteric practices and is a significant branch of Mahayana. All three statements are features of Mahayana Buddhism. The Mahayana sect of Buddhism emerged during the Fourth Buddhist Council held in Kashmir during the reign of Kanishka. The deification of Buddha and worship of images of Buddha and Bodhisattvas was a distinctive feature of this sect. A Bodhisattvas is someone who has compassion within himself or herself and who can make another person smile or help someone suffer less. 71","PW-0065":"Sthanakvasi is a branch of Svetambara Jainism that was started in 1653 AD by a merchant named Lavaji. It holds that the path to soul purification and achieving Nirvana/Moksha does not include idol worship. Option (b) is correct: The Sthanakvasi sect is a reformist sect within Jainism. It emerged in the 15th century CE as a reaction against the perceived ritualism and temple-centric practices of the Murtipujaka (idol- worshipping) Jains.mThe Sthanakvasis emphasize asceticism, non-violence (ahimsa), and meditation. They reject the worship of idols and instead focus on spiritual practices and the study of Jain scriptures.mThe sect derives its name from the term \"Sthanak\", meaning a place of worship, which is typically a simple hall rather than an ornate temple. 72","PW-0066":"A Bodhisattva in Buddhism is an enlightened being who, out of compassion, chooses to remain in the cycle of birth and death (samsara) to help all sentient beings attain liberation. The Bodhisattva path emphasizes the cultivation of perfections (paramitas) like generosity, wisdom, and patience to achieve Buddhahood. According to Buddhist tradition, Maitreya is a Bodhisattva who will appear on earth in future, attain enlightenment and teach pure dharma. He will be the future Buddha.  Avalokiteshvara (The Lord Who Looks Down), also called Padmapani (The Lotus-Bearer) and Lokesvara in Sanskrit ( The Lord of the World) is believed to hear the cries of suffering beings and assist in their liberation, offering help and comfort. The Bodhisattva is often depicted with multiple arms, symbolizing the ability to reach out and help countless beings simultaneously. 73","PW-0067":"Statement 1 is incorrect: Sautrantika and Sammitiya were the sects of Buddhism. Statement 2 is correct: Sarvastivadin considers everything empirical to be impermanent, they maintain that the dharma factors are eternally existing realities. Sarvastivadin:  Believes in the eternal existence of dharma factors  Affirms the presence of past, present, and future  Criticized by Sautrantikas for violating the Buddhist idea of impermanence. Sautrantika:  Descended from the Sarvastivadins  Relies on sutras rather than Abhidharma commentaries  Adheres to extreme momentariness, believing only the current moment exists  Criticizes Sarvastivadin’s belief in the existence of past, present, and future phenomena Sammitiya and other sub-schools:  Branches off from Vatsiputriya, a parent school  Well-known in Gujarat and Sindh during the Maitraka dynasty  Split into two sub-schools: Avantakas and Kurukulas 74","PW-0068":"","PW-0069":" Kosala was one of the 16 Mahajanapadas (Great Kingdoms) during Buddha’s time. Buddha was born in Lumbini which was under the rule of the Kosala kingdom at that time. His father, King Suddhodana was the leader of the Shakya clan which a vassal state under Kosala. King Prasenajit (Pasenadi) of Kosala was a major contemporary of Buddha and a patron of Buddhism.  Magadha was the most powerful Mahajanapada during Buddha’s lifetime. Buddha attained enlightenment in Bodh Gaya, which was in Magadha. King Bimbisara of Magadha was one of Buddha’s earliest royal patrons and donated the Venuvana monastery in Rajgir. 76","PW-0070":"Monasteries in Buddhism serve as centers of spiritual practice, meditation, and learning, preserving Buddhist teachings and traditions. They also foster community life and support the monastic community in pursuing enlightenment. Pair 1 is correctly matched: Tabo Monastery is located in Spiti Valley, Himachal Pradesh known for its ancient murals and manuscripts. Pair 2 is incorrectly matched: Lhotsava Lhakhang temple is in Nako village in the Kinnaur region of Himachal Pradesh. Zanskar Valley is in the Kargil district of Ladakh. It has been identified as one of the hundred most endangered heritage sites by the World Monuments Fund. Pair 3 is correctly matched: Alchi temple complex is situated in Alchi village of Leh district, Ladakh. It was associated with Guru Rinchen Zangpo around the 10th century. 77","PW-0071":"In Buddhist architecture, a chaitya is a prayer hall or sanctuary, typically containing a stupa (a mound-like structure that houses relics of the Buddha). Chaityas were places of worship, where Buddhist communities gathered for prayers, rituals, and meditation. These structures often have a barrel-vaulted roof and a central nave leading to the stupa at the far end. A vihara is a monastic dwelling or residence for monks. It usually consists of a series of cells or rooms surrounding a central courtyard, where monks lived, meditated, and studied. Viharas were intended for residential purposes, as opposed to chaityas, which were for communal worship. They can be found in Ajanta Caves, Karle Caves, etc. 78","PW-0072":"Buddhist philosophy emphasizes the Four Noble Truths, which teach that suffering (dukkha) arises from craving (tanha) and that the cessation of suffering is possible through the Eightfold Path. In Buddhism, Nirvana is the ultimate goal of the spiritual path, and it refers to the cessation of suffering (dukkha) and the end of the cycle of birth, death, and rebirth (samsara). It is achieved by extinguishing the “flame of desire”. It is often described as the extinction of three fires- greed(raga), aversion(dwesha) and ignorance(moksha). When these flames are extinguished, the cycle of rebirth is skipped. Achieving Nirvana is the goal of the Buddhist path, attained through ethical conduct, meditation, and wisdom. 79","PW-0073":" In Jainism, penance (tapas) is a key practice to purify the soul and annihilate karma. Through austerities, self- discipline, and spiritual practices, Jains believe one can reduce and eventually destroy karmic influences. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 152  Jainism teaches that all living beings, as well as non-living objects, possess a form of soul (jiva). This worldview leads to Jains’ strong commitment to ahimsa (non-violence), as every soul, whether human, animal, plant or even minute organisms, is considered sacred.  Karma is considered the bane of the soul and must be ended to achieve liberation. Karma is viewed as a powerful force that binds the soul (jiva) to the cycle of birth, death, and rebirth (samsara). The ultimate goal is to achieve liberation (moksha) by ending the influence of karma through right belief, right knowledge, and right conduct. 80","PW-0074":"Statement 1 is Incorrect: The Middle Path (Madhyamaka Marga) was a core teaching of Gautama Buddha. He rejected extreme asceticism as well as indulgence in sensual pleasures. Jainism of Mahavira advocated extreme asceticism, including rigorous penance, fasting, and self-mortification. Statement 2 is Correct: Both Buddhism and Jainism did not accept the Vedas as supreme authority. They rejected the idea that Brahmins had a monopoly on religious knowledge. Buddha and Mahavira promoted rationalism, self-experience, and ethical conduct over scriptural authority. Statement 3 is Correct: Both religions rejected the efficacy of Vedic rituals and sacrifices and instead emphasized the importance of moral conduct, meditation, and self-discipline. They believed that liberation (nirvana in Buddhism, moksha in Jainism) could not be achieved through rituals but only through personal effort and spiritual practice. 81","PW-0075":"Mudras in Buddhist iconography are symbolic hand gestures that convey specific spiritual meanings. For example, the Dharmachakra Mudra represents the teaching of the Dharma, while the Bhumisparsha Mudra symbolizes the Buddha’s moment of enlightenment. Option (b) is correct: The”Bhumisparsha Mudra” hand gesture shown in Lord Buddha’s image symbolizes his calling of the Earth to witness his purity and chastity despite the temptations of Mara. It means ‘touching the earth’ in Sanskrit. This mudra, formed with all five fingers of the right hand extended to touch the ground, symbolizes the Buddha’s enlightenment under the bodhi tree, when he summoned the earth goddess, Vasundhara, to bear witness to his attainment of enlightenment. 82","PW-0076":"Jain’s philosophy holds that the world is created and maintained by Universal laws. Jainism does not support belief in the creator god. According to Jain doctrine, the universe and its constituents (soul, matter, space, time and motion) have always existed. Jainism believes in the theory of Karma. Both the idea of reincarnation and the universal soul are accepted in Jainism. To break free from the circle of karma and reach salvation, Jainism teaches that one must lead a life of extreme austerity and penance. Jainism theory of Anekantavada stresses that there are many different facets to the ultimate truth and reality, or the “theory of plurality.” 83","PW-0077":"Jainism is based on two main philosophical principles: Anekantavada and Syadvada.Additionally, Jainism emphasizes karma, the moral law of cause and effect, and the goal of achieving liberation (moksha) through non-violence (ahimsa) and self- discipline. Option (b) is correct: Anekantavada is a fundamental doctrine of Jainism, meaning “the theory of manifold perspectives.” It advocates that reality is multifaceted and cannot be fully understood from a single viewpoint, which aligns with Jain teachings of tolerance and non-absolutism. This philosophical approach is unique to Jainism and is not part of the core concepts in Buddhism, Sikhism, or Vaishnavism. Jain Syadvada, the theory of conditional predication suggests that statements about reality are context-dependent. 84","PW-0078":"The statue of Gomateshwara, also known as Bahubali, at ShravanaBelagola in Karnataka represents Bahubali, the son of the first Tirthankara Rishabhanatha, not the last Tirthankara Mahavira. This monolithic statue, approximately 57 feet tall was commissioned by the Ganga dynasty minister and commander Chavundaraya. 86","PW-0079":"Pavarana is a significant Buddhist ceremony observed at the end of Vassa, the three-month rainy season retreat for monks. During this retreat monks stay in a fixed monastery and refrain from extensive travel to avoid harming small creatures that emerge during the rains. On the full moon day of Ashvin (September–October) the Pavarana ceremony is held which marks the conclusion of Vassa. It serves as a day of confession when monks publicly acknowledge any offenses or mistakes they may have committed during their stay. It allows fellow monks to offer constructive criticism, fostering discipline and humility within the Sangha. It is an essential aspect of Vinaya (monastic discipline) which reinforces ethical behavior. 87","PW-0080":"The Buddhist Councils were pivotal in preserving and organizing the Buddha’s teachings. The First Council (483 BCE), held under King Ajatasatru, aimed to preserve the Buddha’s teachings, with Mahakassapa presiding. The Second Council (383 BCE) under King Kalasoka led to the split into Early Theravada and Early Mahayana. The Third Council (250 BCE), presided by Mogaliputta Tissa under Emperor Ashoka, focused on purifying Buddhism and compiling the Abhidhamma Pitaka. The Fourth Council (1st century AD) under King Kanishka in Kashmir formalized the division into Mahayana and Hinayana sects. Option (d) is correct: The Fourth Buddhist Council was convened during the reign of Emperor Kanishka of the Kushan dynasty around the 1st century CE in Kundalvana (modern-day Kashmir). The council was presided over by the scholar-monk Vasumitra, with Ashvaghosha serving as his deputy. This council had a significant influence on the development and spread of Mahayana Buddhism. 88","PW-0081":"Assertion (A) is correct: Jainism emphasized ahimsa (non-violence) as its core principle. It not only prohibited violence against humans and animals but also extended non- violence to plants, insects, and microorganisms. Reason (R) is correct: Agriculturalists could not easily adopt Jainism because farming inherently involves plowing land, which kills many insects and small organisms. Jainism was largely adopted by traders, merchants, and urban elites rather than peasants and farmers. Both A and R are true, and R is the correct explanation of A. Reason (R) explains that agricultural practices, which harm insects and pests, conflict with Jainism’s principle of non-violence (Ahimsa). This makes it difficult for agriculturalists to fully embrace Jainism. 89","PW-0082":"Padmapani is a title often used for Avalokiteshvara. He is one of the most revered Bodhisattvas in Mahayana Buddhism, symbolizing compassion and mercy. His name means “The Lord Who Looks Down (upon the world with compassion).” Avalokitesvara is believed to postpone his own enlightenment to help all sentient beings achieve liberation. He is especially worshiped in Tibet, China, Japan, and Southeast Asia. The Dalai Lama is considered an incarnation of Avalokitesvara in Tibetan Buddhism. Mahayana Buddhism and represent key Bodhisattvas who embody different aspects of Buddhist ideals and qualities.  Vajrapani: Vajrapani is a prominent Bodhisattva in Mahayana Buddhism, often depicted holding a vajra (thunderbolt), symbolizing power and the ability to ward off evil.  Manjusri: Manjusri is a Bodhisattva associated with wisdom in Mahayana Buddhism. He is often depicted holding a sword to cut through ignorance and a scripture in his left hand, symbolizing the wisdom of the Buddha.  Maitreya: Maitreya is the future Buddha in Buddhist tradition, believed to appear in the future to teach pure","PW-0083":"Buddhism and Jainism, both originating in ancient India around the 6th century BCE, share several common principles. Both religions advocate personal spiritual development through ethical conduct and meditation, offering alternative paths to liberation and enlightenment. Statement (1) is incorrect: Only Buddhism avoids extremes, not Jainism. Buddhism follows the Middle Path (Madhyamaka), avoiding both extreme penance and indulgence. Jainism, especially in Digambara tradition, follows extreme asceticism, advocating severe penance as a path to liberation. Statements (2), (3) and (4) are correct:  Both Buddhism and Jainism rejected the Vedas as the ultimate authority. They criticized the Brahmanical rituals, caste system, and the monopoly of Vedic priests. Both religions focused on direct realization, self-discipline, and ethical conduct over Vedic rituals.  Buddha and Mahavira both opposed elaborate rituals and sacrifices performed by Brahmins. Buddhism emphasized meditation, moral conduct, and wisdom over rituals.  Ahimsa (non-violence) is a fundamental principle in both Buddhism a","PW-0084":"Therigatha often translated as Verses of the Elder Nuns is a Buddhist text. It is part of the Sutta Pitaka, containing verses attributed to early Buddhist nuns. It documents the spiritual experiences and enlightenment of female disciples of the Buddha. Option (b), (c) and (d) are incorrect:  Acarangasutra is one of the oldest Jain scriptures belonging to the Shvetambara Jain canon. It discusses the ethical conduct, discipline, and lifestyle of Jain monks, especially emphasizing Ahimsa (non-violence). It is attributed to the direct disciples of Mahavira.  Sutrakritanga is a Jain scripture from the Shvetambara canon. It contains theological discussions and criticizes rival religious philosophies, including Vedic traditions and Ajivikas.  Brihatkalpasutra is a later Jain text which is part of the Shvetambara tradition. It deals with monastic discipline, rules for Jain monks and spiritual practices. 10. SCIENCE AND TECHNOLOGY DURING ANCIENT PERIOD 92","PW-0085":"The Baudhayan Sulva Sutras contain one of the earliest known statements of the Pythagorean theorem, relating to the lengths of the sides of a right-angled triangle. This ancient Indian text provided a geometric construction method for determining the length of the hypotenuse based on the other sides of the right- angled triangle. It predates the work of Pythagoras. The theorem is significant in the history of Indian mathematics and geometry. 93","PW-0086":"A is matched with 2 : Vishakh-adatta is best known as a playwright and author of the Sanskrit drama Mudrarakshasa (The Signet Ring). The play is a historical drama set in the time of Chandragupta Maurya and his advisor Chanakya (Kautilya). B is matched with 3 : Varahamihira was a renowned astronomer and mathematician of ancient India. He is best known for his works Brihat Samhita and Pancha Siddhantika which deal with astronomy, astrology, and mathematics. C is matched with 1 : Charaka is considered one of the principal contributors to Ayurveda. He is traditionally regarded as the author of the Charaka Samhita, a foundational text of Ayurveda. D is matched with 4 : Brahmagupta was a prominent mathematician and astronomer of ancient India. He is best known for his work Brahmasphutasiddhanta which covers topics in algebra, arithmetic, and astronomy. 94","PW-0087":"The Gupta Era (320 AD-550 AD) is considered to be the golden era of India in terms of art, literature, astronomy, medical science, etc. Sushruta is known as an ancient Indian physician and is often regarded as the “father of surgery.” He authored the Sushruta Samhita, which provides detailed information on surgical techniques and medicinal practices. Although he lived slightly before the Gupta period, his work was highly influential and widely studied during the Gupta period. Hence the most appropriate answer is Susrutha. Art and Culture 155 Sudraka was an ancient Indian playwright, best known for the Sanskrit drama Mrichchhakatika (The Little Clay Cart).Shaunaka was an ancient sage and scholar, traditionally credited with compiling the Brihaddevata. Saumilla is sometimes referenced in ancient Indian literature,but specific historical details are scarce. 11. SCULPTURE 95","PW-0088":"","PW-0089":"The Nataraja bronze sculptures, of the Chola period (9th–13th century CE), are celebrated masterpieces of Indian art, symbolizing the cosmic dance of Lord Shiva. These icons, crafted using the lost-wax (cire perdue) casting technique, exemplify the technical and artistic sophistication of the era. An outstanding example is the Nataraja statue from Chidambaram, where Shiva is depicted in dynamic motion. Spiritual symbolism in these sculptures underscore the Chola dynasty’s devotion to Shaivism. The iconic Chola Bronze sculptures of Nataraja, the cosmic dance form of Shiva, depict the deity with four hands. Each hand represents different symbolic gestures (mudras): one holds a drum, another a flame, the third makes the ‘abhaya mudra’ (a sign of fearlessness), and the fourth points to the raised foot, symbolizing liberation. 12. MISCELLANEOUS 97","PW-0090":"Pair 1 is correctly matched: Puthukkuli shawls are a traditional craft of the Toda tribe in the Nilgiri Hills of Tamil Nadu. The shawls are adorned with intricate Toda embroidery, locally called \"Pugur,\" meaning flower. This craft has been granted Geographical Indication (GI) status and is a significant cultural heritage of Tamil Nadu. Pair 2 is incorrectly matched: Sujni embroidery originates from Bihar, not Maharashtra. It is a traditional form of embroidery from the Bhusura village in Bihar, often used to create quilts and other textile products. It has also received a GI tag. Pair 3 is incorrectly matched: Uppada Jamdani saris are woven in Uppada, East Godavari district of Andhra Pradesh, not Karnataka. These saris are known for their fine silk and intricate weaving patterns and have been granted a GI tag. 98","PW-0091":"Mimamsa system of philosophy is one of the 6 schools of orthodox Indian philosophy. It was started by Jaimini. In the Mimamsa system of philosophy, liberation (moksha) is primarily achieved through the performance of proper rituals (karma), which align with the Vedic prescriptions. Mimamsa emphasizes that correct action, particularly ritualistic duties (such as yajnas), leads to purification of the self and ultimately liberation. By doing so, an individual can attain liberation from the cycle of birth and death (samsara) and achieve the highest good, which is initially seen as heavenly bliss and later as freedom from bodily bondage. While Jnana (knowledge) and Yoga are central to other philosophies like Vedanta and Sankhya, Mimamsa focuses on Karma as the means to attain liberation. 99","PW-0092":"Anuvrata is a concept in Jainism that refers to the small vows or lesser vows prescribed for lay followers (householders) as opposed to the Mahavratas (great vows) followed by monks and nuns. The Anuvratas are a set of ethical guidelines that help laypeople lead a morally upright life while still engaging in worldly activities. They include:  Ahimsa (non-violence)  Satya (truthfulness)  Asteya (non-stealing)  Brahmacharya (chastity)  Aparigraha (non-possessiveness) These vows are less strict than the Mahavratas and are tailored to the practical realities of household life. v v v","PW-0093":"Stars and constellations have been used for navigation by identifying specific patterns in the night sky. For example, the North Star (Polaris) in the Ursa Minor constellation indicates true north in the Northern Hemisphere. Option (c) is correct: Walking in the direction while keeping the polestar to his left would lead him towards EAST of his current position and he can reach his village. 5","PW-0094":"The Earth’s magnetic field plays a crucial role in pro- tecting life on Earth from harmful electrically charged particles, such as those from the solar wind and cosmic rays. These par- ticles typically form a protective shield known as the magneto- sphere. The charged particles are trapped in this field and funneled towards the Earth’s magnetic poles, where they cre- ate phenomena like the auroras (Northern and Southern Lights). 1. SOLAR SYSTEM AND EVOLUTION OF EARTH 1","PW-0095":"On June 21st, the Northern Hemisphere experiences the Summer Solstice. During this time, the Northern Hemi- sphere is tilted towards the Sun. The Sun’s rays directly hit the Tropic of Cancer, causing very hot weather. This results in the longest day and the shortest night of the year in the North- ern Hemisphere. The North Pole also has continuous daylight for about six months. Meanwhile, in the Southern Hemisphere, it is winter, with longer nights and shorter days. 2","PW-0096":"On 21st June, In the Arctic Circle (66.5°N) region , the Sun does not set, remaining above the horizon for 24 hours, cre- ating continuous daylight (known as the Midnight Sun). Mean- while, the Southern Hemisphere experiences winter, with the Antarctic Circle (66.5°S) in darkness. 3","PW-0097":"The variations in the length of daytime and nighttime throughout the year are primarily caused by the Earth’s revo- lution around the Sun on a tilted axis. The Earth’s axis is tilt- ed at an angle of approximately 23.5° relative to its orbital plane around the Sun. This tilt causes different parts of the Earth to receive varying amounts of sunlight during different times of the year, leading to the changing lengths of days and nights.  During the Winter Solstice (around 21st December), the Southern Hemisphere is tilted towards the Sun, causing the Northern Hemisphere to experience the shortest day and the longest night.  The Equinoxes (around 21st March and 22nd September) occur when the Earth’s axis is not tilted towards or away from the Sun, resulting in approximately equal day and night lengths. 7 Geography UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 340 6","PW-0098":"Statement 1 is correct : About 97.5% of Earth’s water is saltwater found in oceans. The remaining 2.5% is freshwater. Most of it is locked in glaciers, ice caps, or deep underground. Only about 0.3% of total freshwater is readily available in rivers, lakes, and accessible groundwater for hu- man use. Since 0.3% of 2.5% is less than 1% of total water, this confirms that freshwater available for use is indeed less than 1%. Statement 2 is incorrect : Around 68.7% of all freshwater is stored in ice caps and glaciers, primarily in the Antarctic and Greenland ice sheets. The remaining freshwater is found in groundwater, rivers, and lakes. The volume of water in rivers and lakes combined is only about 0.3% of the total freshwater available. 7","PW-0099":"As of 2009, Jupiter had the highest number of known moons (63 at that time). Jupiter’s large number of moons is at- tributed to its massive size and strong gravitational pull, which allows it to capture a variety of objects into its orbit. However in future years Saturn has since been found to have more moons than Jupiter.  As of October 2023, Jupiter has 95 confirmed moons, making it the planet with the second-largest number of moons in the solar system. Some of Jupiter’s most famous moons include Ganymede (the largest moon in the solar system), Europa, Io, and Callisto.  Saturn has 146 confirmed moons which makes it the planet with the largest number of moons in the solar system. Some of Saturn’s notable moons include Titan (the second- largest moon in the solar system and the only moon with a dense atmosphere), Enceladus, and Rhea. 8","PW-0100":"Order of Planets in the Solar System (from the Sun) is Mercury> Venus > Earth > Mars > Jupiter > Saturn > Uranus > Neptune. Mars is the 4th planet from the Sun and Uranus is the 7th planet from the Sun. Therefore the planets that lie between Mars (4th) and Uranus (7th) are Jupiter (5th) and Saturn (6th). 9","PW-0101":"The average distance from the Earth to the Sun is approximately 150 million kilometers or 150 × 106 km. This distance can vary slightly due to the elliptical shape of Earth’s orbit, but the average distance remains close to 150 million kilo- meters. 1 AU is approximately 149.6 million kilometers, which is roughly 150 × 106 km. 10","PW-0102":"Assertion (A) is False: Mars takes a longer time than Earth to orbit the Sun. The time taken by a planet to or- bit around the Sun is called its orbital period or year. Mars has an orbital period of about 687 Earth days which means it takes 687 days to complete one revolution around the Sun. Earth takes 365.25 days (about 365 days) to complete one revolu- tion around the Sun. Reason (R) is True: Mars does have a smaller diameter than Earth. The diameter of Earth is 12,742 km . The diameter of Mars is 6,779 km (almost half of Earth). The time taken by a planet to orbit the Sun depends on its distance from the Sun, not its diameter. Since Mars is farther from the Sun than Earth thus it has a longer orbital period. 11","PW-0103":"","PW-0104":"","PW-0105":"","PW-0106":"Statement 1 is correct : Asteroids orbit the Sun in an elliptical path, similar to planets. They are rocky remnants from the early formation of the Solar System about 4.6 billion years ago. Their composition includes metals, silicates, and carbon-rich materials. Statement 2 is correct : Most asteroids are much smaller, typically less than 1 km in diameter. There are millions of as- teroids in the Solar System, ranging in size from tiny pebbles to massive bodies. Statement 3 is incorrect : Most asteroids are located between the orbits of Mars and Jupiter, not Jupiter and Saturn. This re- gion is called the Main Asteroid Belt, which contains the majori- ty of known asteroids. Some asteroids such as Trojan asteroids, share orbits with Jupiter but are not found in the region between Jupiter and Saturn. 17","PW-0107":"","PW-0108":"The Sun, positioned at the center of the Solar System, is the closest star to Earth, with a distance of roughly 93 million miles (approximately 8 light-minutes). Its proximity makes it crucial for life on Earth. Option (d) is incorrect : Sirius, also known as the Dog Star, is one of the brightest stars visible from Earth. However, it is located approximately 8.6 light-years away, making it significantly far- ther than the Sun. 19","PW-0109":"The presence of ice caps and frozen water is the most critical condition for the potential existence of life on Mars. Wa- ter is fundamental for life as we know it. The presence of frozen water (ice caps) on Mars suggests the possibility of liquid water under certain conditions, making it the most crucial factor for life. Recent discoveries of underground water reservoirs beneath the Martian surface further highlight its importance. Mars, the fourth planet from the Sun, is often called the “Red Planet” due to its iron-rich, reddish surface. It has a thin atmo- sphere primarily composed of carbon dioxide, with traces of ni- trogen and argon. Mars has polar ice caps, large volcanoes like Olympus Mons, and a canyon system known as Valles Marineris. The planet experiences seasons, dust storms, and temperature fluctuations. Scientific interest in Mars stems from evidence of ancient rivers, lakes, and possible subsurface water, making it a key target in the search for past or present life. 20","PW-0110":"The “Diamond Ring” phenomenon is a striking opti- cal effect observed during a total solar eclipse. It occurs when a small sliver of the Sun’s light is visible around the edge of the Moon, creating the appearance of a brilliant diamond resting on a luminous ring. This effect is typically seen moments just before the eclipse reaches totality or immediately after it ends. 2. CLIMATOLOGY 21","PW-0111":"Statement 1 is incorrect : Low, thick clouds, not the high clouds primarily reflect solar radiation and cool the sur- face of the Earth. Statement 2 is incorrect : High, thin clouds, not the low clouds primarily transmit incoming solar radiation. At the same time, they trap some of the outgoing infrared radiation emitted by the Earth and radiate it back downward, thereby warming the surface of the Earth. 27","PW-0112":"Statement 1 is correct : In the tropical zone, trade winds blow from the east towards the west. These winds push warm surface water towards the western parts of the oceans (e.g., the western Pacific Ocean and the western Atlantic Ocean). As a result, the water in the western parts of tropical oceans is warmer than in the eastern parts. The eastern sections of the oceans tend to have upwelling, where colder, nutrient-rich waters from deeper layers rise to the surface. Statement 2 is correct : In the temperate zone, the westerlies (winds blowing from the west towards the east) push the surface water eastward, causing the western parts of oceans (like the western coast of continents) to be colder. The water in the eastern sections of oceans tends to be warmer due to the Ekman transport, which moves warm water towards the eastern coasts. For example, in the North Atlantic Ocean, the Gulf Stream carries warm water from the tropics to the eastern coasts of North America and Europe, keeping the eastern sections warmer than the western parts. 28","PW-0113":"","PW-0114":"The Jet Stream is a geostrophic wind that generally blows from west to east across the upper layers of the tropo- sphere at an altitude of 20,000 to 50,000 feet. Air masses with different temperatures collide to form jet streams. Thus, the lo- cation of the Jet Stream’s formation is normally characterized by surface temperatures. Statement 1 is incorrect: Jet streams exist in both the North- ern and Southern Hemispheres. They typically form near the boundaries of major air masses and are driven by temperature differences and the Earth’s rotation. The Polar Jet Stream and Subtropical Jet Stream are present in both hemispheres. Statement 2 is correct: Not all cyclones form an eye. The eye is a distinct feature of well-developed, intense tropical cyclones. In contrast, temperate cyclones do not have an eye because there is no central area where winds and rainfall are calm or inactive. Statement 3 is incorrect: The eye of a tropical cyclone is the calm center with the lowest surface pressure and the warmest air above it. At about 12 km high, the air in the eye can be 10°C or more warmer ","PW-0115":"Dew formation occurs when the Earth’s surface cools down sufficiently at night, causing moisture in the air to con- dense into water droplets on cool surfaces. On clear nights, the Earth’s surface loses heat rapidly through a process called radia- tive cooling. This cooling lowers the temperature of surfaces like grass or leaves, leading to the formation of dew as the air reaches its dew point. Option (b) is correct : On cloudy nights, the situation changes. Clouds act like a blanket, reflecting back the infrared radiation (heat) emitted by the Earth’s surface. This process is known as the greenhouse effect at a smaller scale. Because the heat is trapped, the Earth’s surface doesn’t cool enough for dew to form. 31","PW-0116":"","PW-0117":"Option (c) is correct : Monsoon Climate is characterized by Seasonal reversal of winds, where the wind direction changes with the seasons. It is found primarily in India, South-east Africa, Northern Australia, the Guinea Coast of West Africa and the Pa- cific Coast of Columbia. Summer monsoon (from June to September) : Winds blow from the southwest, bringing moisture from the Indian Ocean, leading to heavy rainfall. Winter monsoon (from October to February) : Winds blow from the northeast, bringing dry, cool air from the landmass. 35","PW-0118":"Tropical rainforests, also called equatorial forests, are found near the equator between the Tropics of Cancer and Capricorn. These forests thrive in areas with high tempera- tures and consistent rainfall, which support the rich and di- verse vegetation. Statement 1 is correct : This is a defining characteristic of trop- ical rainforests, also called equatorial forests. The trees are generally tall (often reaching 30–45 meters), and their crowns form a continuous canopy, which allows very little sunlight to reach the forest floor. The canopy helps in conserving moisture and maintaining the unique ecosystem. Statement 2 is correct : Tropical rainforests are known for their high biodiversity, with a large number of species coex- isting in close proximity. The climatic conditions (constant warmth and moisture) lead to intense ecological dynamics that promote coevolution, making these forests the most biodi- verse terrestrial ecosystems on Earth. Statement 3 is correct : Epiphytes, such as mosses, ferns, and orchids, are common in equatorial forests. These plants grow on other plants (us","PW-0119":"The annual range of temperature refers to the difference between the highest and lowest temperatures over the course of a year. This range is typically higher in the interior of continents compared to coastal areas due to specific climatic factors. Statement 1 is correct : Land heats and cools more rapidly than water due to its lower specific heat capacity. This leads to great- er temperature extremes in continental interiors. In contrast, coastal areas experience moderate temperatures year-round be- cause water’s higher specific heat allows it to absorb and release heat more slowly, stabilizing the climate. Statement 2 is incorrect : Altitude affects local temperature (higher altitudes are cooler), but it does not significantly influ- ence the annual temperature range between coastal and inte- rior regions. The question is about horizontal (coastal vs. interi- or) differences, not vertical (altitude) differences. Geography 347 Statement 3 is incorrect : While winds affect the local tempera- ture, strong winds do not have a direct relationship with the annual temperature range. Wind ","PW-0120":"Thunder is caused by lightning. When a lightning bolt travels through the air, it heats the air to an extremely high tem- perature (up to 30,000 Kelvin). This sudden heating causes the air to expand explosively, creating a shockwave that we hear as thunder. It is not caused by the meeting of clouds, the separation of clouds, or the upward movement of air and water particles. Statement 1 is incorrect : Thunder is not caused by the meet- ing of clouds. Cumulonimbus clouds are indeed responsible for thunderstorms, but thunder itself results from the rapid heating and expansion of air due to lightning, not the merging of clouds. Statement 2 is incorrect : Lightning occurs due to electrical dis- charge within or between clouds and the ground. Thunder re- sults from the sudden expansion of air due to the intense heat of lightning, not from nimbus cloud separation. Statement 3 is incorrect : While violent air and water particle movements occur within cumulonimbus clouds during a thun- derstorm, they do not directly produce thunder. The updrafts and downdrafts determine storm intensity but a","PW-0121":"In the troposphere (near earth surface), temperature usually decreases as altitude rises. This is called the lapse rate. On average, the temperature drops by 1°C for every 165 meters of height. This equals about 6.5°C for every kilometer. Statement 1 is correct : The Earth’s surface absorbs solar radi- ation and then re-radiates it as heat. The air in contact with the surface warms up and transfers heat to the layers above through conduction, convection, and radiation. Since the primary heat source is the Earth’s surface, higher altitudes receive less heat, leading to a drop in temperature. Statement 2 is incorrect : Moisture content (water vapor) which accounts for around 1% of air varies greatly in the tropo- sphere, decreases significantly with altitude, as most water vapor is found near the Earth’s surface. The upper atmosphere is drier, not more moist. Statement 3 is correct : As altitude increases, air pressure and density decrease. Less dense air holds less heat, contributing to a decrease in temperature with height. 40","PW-0122":"The Tropical Savannah climate is characterized by a definite dry and wet season. This climate type is found in regions like parts of Africa, South America, and Australia. The distinguishing feature is the seasonal variation between a wet season (characterized by heavy rainfall) and a dry season (with very little or no rainfall). 41","PW-0123":"Statement 1 is correct : The primary reason the west- erlies in the Southern Hemisphere are stronger and more per- sistent than in the Northern Hemisphere is because the South- ern Hemisphere has significantly less landmass (about 20% land and 80% water), whereas the Northern Hemisphere has 40% land and 60% water. The vast oceans in the Southern Hemi- sphere allow westerly winds to move with minimal obstruc- tion, making them stronger and more persistent. In contrast, larger landmasses in the Northern Hemisphere create friction and disrupt wind flow. Statement 2 is incorrect : The Coriolis force acts equally in both hemispheres at the same latitude as it depends on the Earth’s ro- tation and the latitude. It does not make the westerlies stronger in one hemisphere over the other. The main reason for the differ- ence is the land-sea distribution. The Coriolis force is stronger near the poles and weaker at the equator, but it does not explain the difference in strength of the westerlies between the two hemispheres. 42","PW-0124":"Statement 1 is correct : The African and Eurasian desert belt (Sahara, Arabian, Thar, Gobi) lies in the sub-tropical high-pres- sure zone (20°–30° latitudes). In this region, descending dry air from the Hadley Cell suppresses cloud formation and rainfall, creating arid conditions. This becomes the main reason for the formation of these deserts. Statement 2 is incorrect : Warm ocean currents increase evaporation followed by humidity, leading to higher rainfall in coastal areas rather than desert formation. Deserts are main- ly found near cold ocean currents (e.g., the Atacama Desert near the Peru Current, the Namib Desert near the Benguela Current), which cool the air and reduce its moisture-holding capacity, causing dry conditions. Moreover, many deserts in this belt are landlocked, far from direct oceanic influence. 43","PW-0125":"Statement 1 is correct: The lower stratosphere is most- ly free from clouds and water vapor, as most weather phenomena occur in the troposphere below. This impacts the clear air condi- tions, making it ideal for jet aircraft to fly smoothly. Statement 2 is correct: The stratosphere is a stable layer with no vertical air movements like convection currents. In con- trast, the troposphere experiences turbulence due to rising and falling air masses. The absence of vertical winds in the lower stratosphere ensures a steady flight for jet aircraft. Stratosphere: It is the second layer of Earth’s atmosphere, ex- tending from about 12 km to 50 km above the surface. It con- tains the ozone layer, which absorbs harmful UV radiation. Unlike the troposphere, temperature increases with altitude due to ozone absorption. The air is dry and stable, with almost no clouds or weather disturbances, making it suitable for jet air- craft and weather balloons. 44","PW-0126":"Mangroves function as a safety hedge due to their ex- tensive root systems. These roots act as a natural barrier, pro- tecting coastlines from erosion and the impact of strong waves during storms, cyclones, and tsunamis. The dense network of roots helps to dissipate the energy of waves, reducing their im- pact on the shoreline. Mangroves: Mangroves are salt-tolerant trees and shrubs found in coastal intertidal zones, primarily in tropical and sub- tropical regions. They thrive in saline, waterlogged, and oxy- gen-poor soils, with specialized stilt roots (for stability) and pneumatophores (for breathing in low-oxygen conditions). They act as natural coastal barriers, protecting shorelines from erosion, storm surges, and tsunamis and also support rich biodiversity, providing habitat for fish, crabs, birds, and other marine life. Major mangrove forests in India in- clude Sundarbans, Mahanadi Delta, Godavari-Krishna Del- ta, and Pichavaram. SUPER HINT Logically ask: What physical feature of mangroves could protect people from violent water and wind? Only Option D aligns with this, Strong","PW-0127":"Tropical rainforests, also known as Evergreen for- ests, thrive in regions receiving substantial rainfall, typically exceeding 150–200 cm annually. These forests maintain tem- peratures within the range of 15–30°C throughout the year, conditions that match the given data. They are found in India’s Western Ghats and Northeast, boasting diverse flora (rosewood, mahogany, rubber) and fauna (elephants, monkeys, sloths). This combination of factors creates a complex and thriving ecosystem. 46","PW-0128":"El Niño is a climate pattern characterized by unusu- ally warm ocean temperatures in the eastern equatorial Pacific Ocean. El Niño Modoki is a distinct phase of El Niño with a dif- ferent spatial pattern of warming in the Pacific Ocean. Statement 1 is incorrect : Because it reverses the typical loca- tions of El Niño and El Niño Modoki. Normal El Niño occurs in the Eastern Pacific Ocean, where sea surface temperatures be- come unusually warm, typically around the equator off the coast of South America. El Niño Modoki, on the other hand, forms in the Central Pacific Ocean, with warming concentrated between the dateline and the central Pacific, distinct from the usual loca- tion of normal El Niño. Statement 2 is correct : During normal El Niño events, the atmospheric changes (increased wind shear and cooler waters in the Atlantic) tend to suppress hurricane formation in the At- lantic Ocean, leading to fewer hurricanes. In contrast, El Niño Modoki causes different atmospheric conditions that have been linked to a greater frequency and intensity of hurricanes in the Atlantic Ocean. The ","PW-0129":"","PW-0130":"Albedo is the measure of a surface’s reflectivity, with higher albedo indicating greater reflection of sunlight, influenc- ing Earth’s temperature and climate. Statement 1 is correct : Albedo refers to the reflectivity of a surface, or the fraction of light that a surface reflects. A higher albedo means more reflection of light, which causes an object to appear brighter when viewed with reflected light. This is why snowy surfaces (with high albedo) appear brighter than forests or oceans (with low albedo). Statement 2 is incorrect : Mercury actually has a much lower albedo than Earth. Mercury’s rocky and heavily cratered surface reflects only about 12 to 14% of sunlight, meaning it absorbs the vast majority of incoming sunlight and appears relatively dark. On the other hand, Earth has a higher albedo due to its cloud cover, oceans, and ice caps, which reflect a significant por- tion of sunlight back into space. Earth’s average albedo is around 0.30 to 0.35. The albedo scale ranges from 0 to 1, where 0 means a surface absorbs all incoming sunlight (no reflection) and 1 means a surface ","PW-0131":"Assertion (A) is false: Wind patterns in the Northern Hemisphere move clockwise around high-pressure systems and counterclockwise around low-pressure systems. In the Southern Hemisphere, the pattern is opposite: counter- clockwise around high-pressure systems and clockwise around low-pressure systems. The statement in the Assertion (A) is incorrect because it gener- alizes wind patterns without distinguishing between high-pres- sure and low-pressure systems. Reason (R) is true: The Coriolis effect, caused by the Earth's ro- tation, deflects winds to the right in the Northern Hemisphere and to the left in the Southern Hemisphere. This influences the direction of wind patterns, making R correct. Conclusion: Since A is false but R is true, the correct answer is (d): 52","PW-0132":"Insolation, or the solar radiation received by the Earth, plays a crucial role in driving atmospheric circulation by heat- ing the surface unevenly. This creates temperature and pressure differences, which, in turn, influence atmospheric thickness and convection patterns. Assertion (A) is true : Thickness of the atmosphere is maxi- mum over the Equator. The Equator experiences greater atmo- spheric thickness due to intense heating, causing air to expand and rise to higher altitudes, increasing the vertical extent of the atmosphere. Reason (R) is true : The Equator receives high levels of inso- lation year-round due to its position, with the Sun being direct- ly overhead during the equinoxes and nearly overhead at other times, contributing to sustained heating. This results in strong convection currents that lift air to higher altitudes, contributing to the greater atmospheric thickness. Reason(R) explains Assertion(A) : Because the strong insola- tion and convection over the Equator lead to the expansion and lifting of air, directly causing the atmosphere to be thicker in this region","PW-0133":"Assertion (A) is true : The amount of atmospheric moisture varies with latitude because temperature differenc- es across latitudes influence evaporation and condensation. Near the Equator, high temperatures increase evaporation rates, allowing the atmosphere to hold more water vapor, re- sulting in higher moisture content. In polar regions, lower temperatures reduce evaporation, leading to minimal moisture in the air. Reason (R) is true : The capacity of air to hold moisture is di- rectly related to its temperature. Warmer air has a greater ca- pacity to retain water vapor, while colder air can hold much less moisture. Since temperature is latitude-dependent, atmo- spheric moisture content is indirectly influenced by latitude. Reason (R) explains Assertion (A) : Because temperature, which is dependent on latitude, determines the air’s ability to hold water vapor. This explains the variation in atmospheric moisture content across latitudes, with tropical regions being more humid and polar regions drier. 54","PW-0134":"Primary productivity refers to the rate at which plants and other photosynthetic organisms produce organic com- pounds from carbon dioxide and sunlight, forming the base of the food chain in an ecosystem. Assertion (A) is false : While temperate forest soils are gen- erally richer in nutrients due to slower decomposition rates and seasonal leaf litter, tropical rainforest soils are nutrient-poor. The rapid decomposition in tropical rainforests causes nutrients to be quickly absorbed by the dense vegetation, leaving the soil itself infertile. Once the forest is cleared, the exposed soil is rap- idly depleted due to erosion and leaching from heavy rains, mak- ing sustained agriculture difficult without chemical inputs. Reason (R) is true : The primary productivity (the rate at which plants convert sunlight into energy through photosyn- thesis) of tropical rainforests is indeed very high compared to temperate forests. This is due to consistent warm tempera- tures, high rainfall, and abundant sunlight year-round, which promote continuous plant growth. However , this high productiv- ity i","PW-0135":"Assertion (A) is true : Areas located within 5° to 8° latitude on either side of the Equator, often influenced by the In- tertropical Convergence Zone (ITCZ), experience year-round rainfall due to persistent solar heating and moisture-laden air masses. The ITCZ is a region where the northeast and southeast trade winds converge, causing warm, humid air to rise continuously. This rising air cools and condenses, leading to frequent cloud formation and precipitation. The consistent high temperatures in these regions enhance evaporation, while the abundant mois- ture ensures that convectional rainfall occurs almost daily, par- ticularly in the afternoons when the ground has heated the most. Reason (R) is true : Convectional rainfall is characteristic of equatorial regions. High temperatures during the day cause the surface air to heat up and rise (convection), cooling as it as- cends, leading to afternoon rainfall. This process is driven by the intense solar heating and high humidity near the Equator. Reason(R) explains Assertion(A) : Because the continuous rainfall near the Equator is a ","PW-0136":"","PW-0137":"Statement 1 is incorrect : Equatorial regions general- ly experience two main seasons: a wet season (due to intense convectional rainfall) and a dry season (caused by a temporary shift in wind patterns). These regions do not have four distinct seasons like temperate zones. Statement 2 is incorrect : In a Mediterranean climate, sum- mers are dry due to the dominance of subtropical high-pressure systems, while winters are wet due to cyclonic activity. This cli- mate is commonly found in areas like Southern California, parts of Australia, and the Mediterranean basin itself. Statement 3 is correct : In China-type climate rainfall occurs throughout the year. This climate is known as the humid sub- tropical climate and is typical of regions like southern China, Taiwan, and parts of southeastern United States. Statement 4 is correct : Tropical highlands show vertical zonation of climates, where altitude impacts temperature and vegetation. Example: In the Andes, conditions transition from tropical climates at lower elevations to temperate and alpine climates at higher altitudes. As the altit","PW-0138":"Albedo is the measure of a surface’s reflectivity, with higher albedo indicating greater reflection of sunlight. Option (b) is correct : The correct sequence in decreasing order of albedo values is Tundra → Taiga → Tropical Deciduous → Tropical Evergreen  Tundra (Highest Albedo) : Snow and ice dominate the Tundra landscape, leading to the highest reflectivity (albedo). Snow reflects up to 80–90% of sunlight.  Taiga (Second Highest Albedo) : Taiga, or boreal forests, have a lower albedo than tundra but still reflect sunlight during snowy winters. Dense coniferous forests, combined with snow, lead to moderate albedo values.  Tropical Deciduous Forest – Moderate Albedo : These forests shed leaves seasonally, and during the dry season, the exposed ground and sparse canopy increase albedo slightly. Albedo ranges from 15% to 20%.  Tropical Evergreen Forest – Low Albedo : Dense, evergreen canopies absorb most sunlight due to year- round leaf cover. Albedo is very low, around 10% to 15%. 60","PW-0139":"Assertion (A) is true : The 60°–65° latitudes in both hemispheres are dominated by the subpolar low-pressure belt, where the cold polar easterlies meet the warm wester- lies, creating a zone of convergence. This leads to rising air and low-pressure conditions. Reason (R) is false : While oceans generally have a more stable pressure pattern due to their thermal inertia, low-pressure sys- tems in the subpolar regions are not restricted to oceans and can also occur over land, especially in areas influenced by west- erlies and cyclonic activity. 61","PW-0140":"A tropical cyclone is a powerful, rotating storm system characterized by strong winds, heavy rain, and low pressure, typ- ically forming over warm ocean waters in tropical regions. Assertion (A) is true : In a tropical cyclone, surface winds spi- ral inwards toward the low-pressure center due to the Cori- olis effect. The rotation direction depends on the hemisphere (counterclockwise in the Northern Hemisphere, clockwise in the Southern Hemisphere). Reason (R) is true : Air descends in the center of the cyclone, creating the eye of the storm, which is typically calm and free of rain. This descent is due to subsidence in the center of the low-pressure system. Reason (R) is NOT the correct explanation of Assertion (A): The inward spiraling of surface winds is caused by the pressure gradient force pulling air toward the low-pressure center and the Coriolis effect, not by the descending air in the cyclone’s center. 62","PW-0141":"Thundercloud development, specifically cumulonim- bus clouds, is influenced by various climatic and geographical factors. Statement 1 is correct : Condensation is the process by which water vapor in the atmosphere cools and turns into liquid water droplets. For condensation to occur, the air must be saturated, and cooling must take place. This forms clouds, and in the case of thunderstorms, the towering cumulonimbus clouds. These clouds result from intense condensation when warm, moist air rises and cools. Statement 2 is correct : High temperatures near the Earth’s surface heat the air, causing it to become lighter and rise (con- vection). Humidity refers to the amount of water vapor in the air. When the air is warm and moist, it carries more energy, which is essential for unstable atmospheric conditions. These con- ditions fuel the upward movement of air masses, leading to the formation of thunderclouds. Statement 3 is correct : Orography refers to the influence of mountains and terrain on weather patterns. When air is forced to rise over mountains (called orographic lift- ing), it ","PW-0142":"","PW-0143":"","PW-0144":"","PW-0145":"","PW-0146":"Option (c) is correct : The correct sequence of the dif- ferent layers of the atmosphere from the surface of the Earth upwards is : Troposphere → Stratosphere → Mesosphere → Ionosphere  Troposphere: This is the lowest layer of the atmosphere, extending from the Earth’s surface up to about 8-15 km. It contains most of the Earth’s weather systems and clouds.  Stratosphere: Above the troposphere, this layer extends from around 15 km to 50 km. It contains the ozone layer, which absorbs and scatters ultraviolet solar radiation.  Mesosphere: Above the stratosphere, the mesosphere stretches from 50 km to 85 km. It is the layer where meteors burn up upon entry into the Earth’s atmosphere.  Ionosphere: This is not a distinct layer like the others but rather a region of the atmosphere (spanning from about 60 km to 1,000 km) where ionization of gases occurs. The ionosphere overlaps with the thermosphere and exosphere. 69","PW-0147":"The climate data provided, with moderate tempera- tures and distinct seasonal rainfall patterns, is more in line with the China-type climate found in parts of Eastern Asia. The temperature gradually increases from 3.9°C in January to 27.8°C in July and then decreases towards December. This shows warm summers and cool winters, which is characteris- tic of the China-type climate, where summers are typically hot and humid and winters are cold and dry. 70","PW-0148":"","PW-0149":"","PW-0150":"The Ionosphere ranges from approximately 60 ki- lometers (37 miles) to 1,000 kilometers (620 miles) above the Earth. It is characterized by the presence of ions and free elec- trons. These electrically charged particles are created by solar radiation (primarily ultraviolet and X-rays) that ionizes the at- mospheric gases. The ionosphere plays a crucial role in radio wave propagation. It contains several layers (D, E, F1, and F2), each with varying densities of ions and electrons. These layers can reflect radio waves, allowing them to travel far beyond the horizon. The ability of the ionosphere to reflect radio waves de- pends on the frequency of the radio waves and the state of the ionosphere (which varies with time of day and solar activity). 73","PW-0151":"Ocean Mean Temperature (OMT) represents the ther- mal energy in the upper layer of the ocean. It is measured up to the 26°C isotherm, which represents the depth where water temperature is consistently 26°C. OMT is a more reliable indi- cator than Sea Surface Temperature (SST) for predicting the Indian monsoon rainfall, as it reflects the ocean’s thermal energy more comprehensively. Statement 1 is incorrect : OMT is measured up to the 26°C iso- therm. In the southwestern Indian Ocean during January–March, the depth of the 26°C isotherm is approximately 59 meters, not 129 meters. Statement 2 is correct : OMT, especially during the Janu- ary-March period (pre-monsoon season) has been found to be a useful indicator for forecasting the Indian Summer Monsoon rainfall. Warmer OMT in this period can suggest a stronger monsoon and potentially higher rainfall, while cooler OMT may indicate a weaker monsoon. This is because the ocean’s temperature influences the amount of moisture available for the monsoon winds. Studies by the Indian Institute of Tropical Mete- orology (IITM) and other scienti","PW-0152":"Statement 1 is correct : Coral reefs predominantly thrive in warm, shallow waters, typically between the Trop- ics of Cancer and Capricorn (30°N to 30°S latitude). These tropical regions provide the ideal conditions—such as appropri- ate temperature, light, and salinity—for coral growth. The warm water temperatures are essential for the symbiotic relationship between coral polyps and the algae (zooxanthellae) that live within their tissues. Statement 2 is correct : The Great Barrier Reef in Australia, along with coral reef systems in Indonesia and the Philippines (part of the Coral Triangle), collectively account for more than one-third of the world’s coral reefs. These regions are globally renowned for their extensive and diverse coral systems. Statement 3 is correct : Coral reefs are among the most bio- diverse ecosystems on Earth, hosting over 25,000 described species from 32 of the 33 known animal phyla, which is more than the number of animal phyla found in tropical rainforests. 77","PW-0153":"Statement 1 is incorrect : The Indian Ocean Di- pole(IOD) is defined by the difference in sea surface tempera- tures (SSTs) between the western and eastern parts of the Indian Ocean, not the Pacific Ocean. Specifically, it involves the SST gradient between the western equatorial Indian Ocean (50°E-70°E and 10°S-10°N) and the southeastern equatorial In- dian Ocean (90°E-110°E and 10°S-0°N). Statement 2 is correct : A positive IOD (warmer SST in the western Indian Ocean) can help mitigate the adverse effects of El Niño on the Indian monsoon by enhancing monsoonal rainfall. Conversely, a negative IOD (warmer SST in the eastern Indian Ocean) can exacerbate El Niño’s drought-like conditions over India. SUPER HINT For S1, It’s called the Indian Ocean Dipole, so logically, it should involve two regions within the Indian Ocean, not the Pacific. So mentioning the Eastern Pacific is a red flag and likely false. For S2, phrase \"can influence\" is way too general to be called false. Atmospheric phenomenons are complex and related Hence likely true. 78","PW-0154":"","PW-0155":"Tides are the periodic rise and fall of sea levels, driven by various forces acting upon Earth’s water bodies. These forces include:  The Sun’s gravitational pull plays a secondary role in creating tides, as it is much farther away from Earth compared to the Moon. However, its gravitational influence still contributes significantly to spring tides (higher-than-normal tides) when the Sun, Moon, and Earth are aligned (new moon and full moon phases).  The Moon’s gravitational force is the primary driver of tides. Due to its proximity to Earth, the Moon exerts a stronger pull on Earth’s oceans, causing the bulge of water that forms high tides. The gravitational pull of the Moon is nearly 2.5 times more effective than that of the Sun in causing tides due to its closer proximity.  The Earth-Moon system rotates around a common center of mass, creating a centrifugal force that acts opposite to the Moon’s gravitational pull. This force also contributes to the formation of tides on the side of Earth opposite the Moon, leading to high tides there. It helps explain the formation of high tides","PW-0156":"Option (c) is correct : Regions where warm and cold ocean currents meet are highly productive fishing grounds due to:  Plankton Growth: Cold currents bring nutrient-rich deep water, while warm currents stabilize conditions, fostering plankton blooms, the base of the marine food chain.  Fish Abundance: These regions attract fish feeding on plankton, creating rich fishing zones like Newfoundland (Labrador Current meets Gulf Stream), North Sea (Gulf Stream meets Arctic currents), and seas near Japan (Kuroshio meets Oyashio). 81","PW-0157":"The Earth’s rotation affects ocean currents through the Coriolis effect, which causes moving fluids like air and water to be deflected to the right in the Northern Hemisphere and to the left in the Southern Hemisphere. This deflection influences the direction of ocean currents. Option 2 is correct : Wind patterns which are driven by differences in air pressure, are primary drivers of surface ocean currents. The friction between the wind and the ocean surface pushes water, creating currents. Option 3 is correct : Differences in water density, which are caused by variations in salinity and temperature, influence vertical ocean currents. Cold water is denser and tends to sink, while warm water is lighter and tends to rise. This process contributes to the thermohaline circulation. Option 4 is incorrect : The revolution of the Earth does not directly influence ocean currents. While the revolution of Earth impacts seasons and sunlight distribution, it is not a direct cause of ocean current movement. Geography 359 82","PW-0158":"Statement 1 is correct : Ocean acidification reduces the ability of calcareous phytoplankton (such as coccolithophores) to form their calcium carbonate shells. As the ocean becomes more acidic, the process of calcification is impaired, adversely affecting their growth and survival. Statement 2 is correct : Coral reefs rely on the ability of coral polyps to produce calcium carbonate skeletons. As ocean acidity increases, it becomes more difficult for corals to build and main- tain their skeletons, making them more vulnerable. This not only threatens corals themselves but also the ecosystems that depend on them. Statement 3 is correct : The larvae of some marine organisms, particularly those with phytoplanktonic larvae, rely on calci- um carbonate for protection and growth. As the ocean becomes more acidic, these organisms may face difficulties in developing their shells, which could disrupt marine food webs. Statement 4 is incorrect : While phytoplankton contribute to the release of dimethyl sulfide (DMS), which is linked to cloud formation, ocean acidification does not have a direct ","PW-0159":"Statement 1 is incorrect : La Niña is characterized by unusually cold ocean temperatures in the Equatorial Pacific (not the Indian Ocean). In contrast, El Niño is associated with unusually warm ocean temperatures in the Equatorial Pacific Ocean. Statement 2 is incorrect : El Niño events are associated with a weakening of the Indian monsoon leading to reduced rainfall and drought conditions in India. This occurs because the warm- ing of the central and eastern Pacific Ocean alters atmospheric circulation patterns, which can suppress the monsoon rains over the Indian subcontinent. La Niña events typically have the op- posite effect, strengthening the Indian monsoon and often resulting in above-average rainfall. The cooling of the central and eastern Pacific Ocean during La Niña enhances the monsoon circulation, leading to increased precipitation over India. 84","PW-0160":"The annual range of temperature is the difference between the highest and lowest temperatures recorded in a particular place or region over the course of a year. Statement 1 is incorrect : The annual range of temperature (the difference between the highest and lowest average monthly temperatures) is generally smaller in the Pacific Ocean com- pared to the Atlantic Ocean. This is primarily due to the Pacif- ic’s larger size and greater thermal inertia. The vastness of the Pacific allows for more heat absorption and distribution, mod- erating temperature extremes. Atlantic’s relatively smaller size and its greater contact with Arctic waters leads to more pronounced seasonal temperature variations. Also the Atlantic Ocean is narrower and more enclosed, allowing for greater temperature variability. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 360 Statement 2 is correct : The Northern Hemisphere has a greater annual range of temperature than the Southern Hemisphere. This is primarily due to the larger landmasses in the Northern Hemisphere, which heat up and cool down more quickly compared to the predominantly oc","PW-0161":"Statement 1 is correct : The Horse Latitudes are sub- tropical regions located at approximately 30° to 35° North and South latitudes. These are high-pressure zones characterized by calm winds and minimal precipitation. The name “Horse Lati- tudes” is believed to have originated from the historical practice of sailors throwing horses overboard to conserve water when ships were stranded in these calm regions. Statement 2 is incorrect : The Horse Latitudes are high-pres- sure belts, not low-pressure belts. These regions are associat- ed with the subtropical high-pressure zones, where air from the equator descends, creating stable and dry conditions. The high-pressure conditions result from the descending air of the Hadley cells, which suppresses cloud formation and leads to arid climates. Many of the world’s major deserts, such as the Sahara and the Australian Outback, are situated under the Horse lati- tudes. Low-pressure belts, on the other hand, are found near the equator (Intertropical Convergence Zone) and at higher latitudes (subpolar lows). 86","PW-0162":"The Diamantina Trench is a deep-sea trench located in the southeastern Indian Ocean, off the coast of Western Australia. It is part of the Diamantina Fracture Zone, a complex series of deep troughs and ridges. The trench was formed due to seafloor spreading and tectonic activity in the Indian Ocean basin. It is not associated with a subduction zone, unlike many other deep-sea trenches such as the Mariana Trench in the Pacific Ocean. 87","PW-0163":"Statement 1 is incorrect : While some ocean currents are slow-moving others like the Gulf Stream, can move swift- ly, reaching speeds of up to 5.6 miles per hour (9 kilometers per hour). Additionally, ocean currents are not limited to surface movements as there are also deep-water currents driv- en by differences in water density. Statement 2 is correct : Ocean currents play a significant role in maintaining the Earth’s heat balance by transporting warm wa- ter from the equator to the poles and cold water from the poles to the equator. This helps regulate global temperatures. Statement 3 is correct : Prevailing winds, such as the trade winds and westerlies, are a primary force driving ocean cur- rents. These winds create friction on the ocean’s surface, causing water to move. Statement 4 is correct : The configuration of the ocean, such as the shape of ocean basins, land masses, and coastlines, signifi- cantly influences the direction, speed, and path of ocean cur- rents. For example, the Gulf Stream is influenced by the shape of the North American coastline, and the Antarctic Circum","PW-0164":"Assertion (A) is true : Neap tides occur when the gravitational forces of the Moon and the Sun are perpendicular to each other (i.e., during the first and third quarters of the lunar cycle). Since the Sun’s gravitational force partially cancels out the Moon’s gravitational effect, the difference between high tide and low tide is minimal. As a result, the high tide is lower than normal, and the low tide is higher than normal. Reason (R) is false : Neap tides occur during the first and third quarter phases of the Moon, not during the new moon. Spring tides, on the other hand, occur during the full moon and new moon when the Sun, Earth, and Moon are aligned, causing a high- er-than-normal tidal range. 89","PW-0165":"","PW-0166":"","PW-0167":"Assertion (A) is true: Mangroves are specialised for- est ecosystems found in the tropical and subtropical regions of the world especially along coastlines where saltwater and freshwater meet. They are specially adapted to thrive in saline, waterlogged soils where few other plants can survive. Reason (R) is true: Mangroves play a critical role in stabiliz- ing shorelines by trapping sediments with their dense root sys- tems, reducing erosion, and protecting coastal areas from storm surges and sea-level rise. They act as natural barriers, mitigating the impact of waves and tides, and preventing seawater from en- croaching further inland. Reason (R) correctly explains Assertion (A) : Assertion (A) describes mangroves as specialized ecosystems in tropical and subtropical coastal regions and Reason (R) explains why these ecosystems are specialized i.e. their ability to stabilize shorelines and protect against sea encroachment. 4. GEOMORPHOLOGY 93","PW-0168":"A volcano is an opening or rupture in the Earth’s crust through which molten rock (magma), gases, and ash es- cape from beneath the surface. When magma reaches the surface, it is called lava. Volcanic eruptions can shape mountains and is- lands, affecting both the environment and climate. Example : Mount Etna(Italy), Kilauea (USA) The materials that reach the Earth’s surface in volcanoes in- clude :  lava flows  pyroclastic debris  volcanic bombs  ash and dust  gases such as nitrogen compounds  sulphur compounds  minor amounts of chlorine, hydrogen and argon etc. SUPER HINT You can try, The \"NOT\" approach for all statements, this tests the improbability of negating a statement—if denying its impact seems highly unlikely, the statement is plausibly true. For example: Can I deny Pyroclastic flow, or gases or ash are not products of Volcanoes? Likely No!, Hence all are likely true. 95","PW-0169":"Statement 1 is correct : There are two types of body waves- P and S waves. The P-waves and S-waves are also known as primary waves and secondary waves, respectively. The P-waves move faster and are the first to arrive at the surface. Therefore, in a seismograph, P waves are recorded earlier than S waves. The S-waves arrive at the surface with some time lag. Statement 2 is correct : In P-waves, the media particle vibrates parallel to the direction of the wave. Thus it causes the to-and-fro motion. Further, in the S-waves media particles vibrate perpen- dicular (up and down at right angles) to the direction of wave propagation i.e. in the right angle. P-waves S-waves Arrival Times Surface Waves Amplitude 96","PW-0170":"Black cotton soil, also known as regur soil, is highly valued in India because of its excellent moisture-retaining prop- erties and suitability for cotton cultivation. Black cotton soil is primarily formed from the weathering of basaltic rocks, which are a type of fissure volcanic rock. These basaltic rocks were originally erupted during the Cretaceous period as part of the Deccan Traps in the northwest Deccan plateau. The weathering process of these volcanic rocks releases minerals that, combined with climatic factors, result in the formation of the distinctive black soil. The high clay content of black cotton soil enables it to retain moisture efficiently. Its properties make it particularly suitable for cotton cultivation, hence the alternative name “black cotton soil.” 97","PW-0171":"Statement 1 is correct: Continental drift is the gradu- al movement of Earth’s continents due to tectonic plate activity. It causes geographical isolation, leading to divergent evolution and speciation. Species adapt to new environments, creating dis- tinct biogeographical patterns like the unique primates in Aus- tralia and South America. This process has shaped evolutionary changes over time. Statement 2 is correct: Periodic advances and retreats of ice sheets, impacting climate and sea levels. It creates environmen- tal pressures, pushing species to adapt. Glacial cycles result in population bottlenecks, migration, or extinction and influences evolutionary paths. The Pleistocene glaciations played a crucial role in shaping the distribution and diversity of many species ob- served today 98","PW-0172":"Soil erosion is the process by which soil is displaced and transported from one location to another by natural forces such as wind or water. It is a natural process that occurs over time, but human activities such as deforestation, overgraz- ing, and construction can accelerate the process, leading to sig- nificant environmental damage. Statement 1 is incorrect: Terrace cultivation is a *method to * prevent soil erosion, not a factor associated with it. Terraces are leveled platforms built into hillsides to slow down the flow of water and reduce soil loss. So, this option is incorrect. Geography 363 Statement 2 is correct : Deforestation is one of the major rea- sons for soil erosion. It includes cutting and felling of trees, re- moval of forest litter. Browsing and trampling by livestock, forest fires, also leads to deforestation, etc. Vegetation plays a critical role in anchoring soil, reducing the impact of rainfall, and pro- tecting against wind erosion. When forests are cleared, the soil becomes exposed and vulnerable to erosion. Statement 3 is incorrect: While a tropical climat","PW-0173":"Statement 1 is correct : The distinctive red colour is one of the key characteristics of laterite soils. It appears red due to the high concentration of iron oxides. In tropical climates, heavy rainfall causes intense leaching, washing away silica and other bases while leaving behind iron and aluminum oxides, which give the soil its distinctive red color. Statement 2 incorrect : Laterite soils are poor in nitrogen, phosphorus, and potash (potassium). The intense leaching caused by heavy rainfall in tropical regions washes away these soluble nutrients. Statement 3 is incorrect : Laterite soils are primarily found in the humid tropical regions of India, such as the Western Ghats, parts of Eastern Ghats, and some northeastern states. Rajasthan and Uttar Pradesh (UP) have a drier climate which is not suitable for the formation of laterite soils. Statement 4 is correct : The agro-climatic conditions of lat- erite soils support the cultivation of crops such as tapioca, ca- shew nuts, groundnut, coffee, and rubber. These crops are well-adapted to the moisture-retaining and nutrient-poor nat","PW-0174":"Statement 1 is incorrect: The Gondwana beds are pri- marily famous for containing coal reserves, with nearly 98% of India’s coal reserves found in them. They are not significant for natural gas reserves. Natural gas in India is more common- ly associated with other formations such as sedimentary basins such as the Cambay Basin or the Krishna-Godavari Basin. Statement 2 is correct: Kodarma in Jharkhand is a well-known region for mica production, which has been an important min- eral in India’s mineral resources. Mica is found abundantly here and Kodarma is often referred to as the “mica capital” of India. Statement 3 is incorrect: The Dharwar system of rocks is not known for petroleum production. The Dharwar rocks are partic- ularly valuable for metallic minerals like high-grade iron ore, manganese, and copper. Petroleum is not found in the Dhar- war rock system but in other formations like the Cambay Basin or the Rajasthan Basin. 101","PW-0175":"Factors of The Dynamic Changes of the Earth:  Electromagnetic radiation from the sun, particularly in the form of solar energy, drives atmospheric and surface processes such as weathering, erosion, and the water cycle. These processes contribute to the continuous reshaping of Earth’s surface.  Geothermal energy originates from Earth’s internal heat, which fuels volcanic activity and drives plate tectonics. These internal processes lead to the formation of new landforms, mountain building, and seafloor spreading, all of which dynamically alter Earth’s surface.  Gravity influences the movement of water, sediments, and tectonic plates. It plays a crucial role in processes like mass wasting (landslides), river flow, and glacial movement which contributes to the dynamic changes on Earth’s surface.  The movement of tectonic plates leads to continental drift, mountain formation, earthquakes, and volcanic activity.  Rotation of the Earth causes the Coriolis effect, which deflects moving air and water, influencing weather patterns, ocean currents, and thus affecting erosion and depositio","PW-0176":"Below the mantle, the core is divided into two main parts: the outer core and the inner core.  Outer Core: This layer is in a liquid state and is primarily composed of iron mixed with nickel and small amounts of other elements. The movement of this liquid iron alloy is responsible for generating Earth’s magnetic field. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 364  Inner Core: At the center of the Earth lies the inner core, a solid sphere predominantly made up of iron. Its high density and the immense pressure it is subjected to keep it in a solid state despite the high temperatures. 103","PW-0177":"Statement 1 is incorrect : The Earth’s magnetic axis is tilted at approximately 11 degrees relative to its geographic axis (the axis around which the Earth rotates). The 23.5-degree tilt refers to the Earth’s rotational axis relative to its orbit around the Sun, which is responsible for the seasons, not the magnetic field. Statement 2 is correct : The North Magnetic Pole is currently located in the Arctic region of Northern Canada, specifically on Ellesmere Island. The magnetic poles are not fixed and move over time due to changes in the Earth’s magnetic field. Statement 3 is correct : The magnetic equator is an imaginary line where the Earth’s magnetic field is entirely horizontal (no dip angle). The magnetic equator passes near Thumba in South India. The Thumba Equatorial Rocket Launching Station was established in this location due to its proximity to the magnetic equator. 104","PW-0178":"Statement 1 is correct: The total land area of the Earth is approximately 1475 lakh square kilometers or 147.5 million square kilometers. The Earth’s surface area is about 510 million square kilometers, with land covering roughly 29% of it. Statement 2 is incorrect: About 71% of the Earth’s surface is covered by water and 29% is land. This gives a land-to-water ratio of approximately 1:2.4 and not 1:4 as mentioned in the question. Statement 3 is correct: The Pacific Ocean is the largest and deepest ocean, covering an area of about 168 million square ki- lometers. It contains the maximum percentage of Earth’s water, contributing significantly to the planet’s hydrosphere. 105","PW-0179":"The correct order of continents in terms of their percentage of Earth’s land area is: Asia > Africa > North America > South America > Antarctica > Europe > Australia. The sequence that accurately reflects the decreasing order of land area is:  Africa: Second largest continent, covering 20.3% of Earth’s land area.  North America: Third largest continent, covering 16.3% of Earth’s land area.  South America: Fourth largest continent, covering 12.0% of Earth’s land area.  Europe: Sixth largest continent, covering 6.8% of Earth’s land area. 106","PW-0180":"","PW-0181":"","PW-0182":"","PW-0183":"Soil erosion is a natural process involving the detach- ment, transportation, and deposition of soil particles, pri- marily due to water or wind. The stages of water-induced soil erosion occur in the following sequence : Splash Erosion → Sheet Erosion → Rill Erosion → Gully Erosion Fig: Stages of Water Induced Soil Erosion 1. Splash Erosion : This is the initial stage of erosion where raindrops hit bare soil surfaces, dislodging soil particles. It creates a loose layer of soil vulnerable to further erosion by runoff. 2. Sheet Erosion : A thin, uniform layer of soil is removed over a large area by surface runoff. In this stage, a thin, uniform lay- er of soil is washed away over a large area by surface runoff, without noticeable channels. Often goes unnoticed but con- tributes significantly to soil loss. 3. Rill Erosion : When runoff becomes concentrated, it forms small channels or rills in the soil. Rills disrupt agricultural fields and increase erosion intensity. 4. Gully Erosion : As rills expand and deepen, they turn into gul- lies, creating large channels that severely degrade th","PW-0184":"Thermal power is the largest source of electricity in India, accounting for around 70% of the country’s total power generation. It primarily relies on coal, gas, and oil as fuel sources, with coal-based plants being the dominant contributors. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 366 Statement 1 is incorrect : Water is essential in thermal power plants for cooling high temperatures and generating steam to power turbines. In India, river water is primarily used for this purpose, but some plants, like Mundra Thermal Power Station in Gujarat, use seawater. Statement 2 is incorrect : More than a third of India’s freshwa- ter-based plants are in areas with high or extreme water stress. On average, they run at 15-25 % lower capacity than those in less water-stressed regions because of limited water availability. Ex-Suratgarh Thermal Power Plant (Rajasthan) Statement 3 is incorrect : Many coal-based power plants in In- dia are privately owned and operated. For example, the Mundra Thermal Power Plant in Gujarat is owned by Adani Power and is one of the largest private-sector coal-based power plants in the co","PW-0185":"Statement 1 is incorrect : The East-West Corridor is a part of India’s National Highways Development Project (NHDP) which is designed to improve connectivity between the eastern and western regions of the country. It connects Silchar in Assam to Porbandar in Gujarat, passing through states like West Ben- gal, Bihar, Uttar Pradesh, Madhya Pradesh, and Rajasthan. The Golden Quadrilateral forms a quadrilateral connecting Delhi, Mumbai, Chennai, and Kolkata. The East-West Corridor is not under the Golden Quadrilateral Project. Statement 2 is incorrect : The India–Myanmar–Thailand Tri- lateral Highway is an initiative to enhance connectivity between the three countries. The highway connects Moreh in Manipur, India, to Mae Sot in Thailand, passing through Myanmar. The route includes key locations such as Tamu and Mandalay in Myanmar. Chiang Mai located further north in Thailand is not on this route. Statement 3 is incorrect : The Bangladesh-China-India-Myan- mar (BCIM) Economic Corridor is a proposed initiative aimed at enhancing economic integration and connectivity among the four countri","PW-0186":"Option (c) is correct : The Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC) is the world’s largest producer of cobalt, ac- counting for approximately 70-75% of global production. Cobalt is a critical metal used in lithium-ion batteries for electric vehi- cles (EVs) and electronic devices. The DRC’s vast mineral-rich de- posits in the Katanga region which makes it the dominant player in the global cobalt supply chain  Argentina is known for its vast mineral resources like lithium, silver, copper, and gold. It is part of the “Lithium Triangle” (along with Chile and Bolivia) which makes it one of the world’s largest producers of lithium. It is a significant producer of silver, particularly from the Patagonia region. It has significant copper and gold mining operations in regions like San Juan and Mendoza.  Botswana is globally known for its diamonds, copper, nickel, and coal. It is one of the world’s top diamond producers, with mines in Jwaneng and Orapa mines. It has significant copper and nickel reserves in the Selebi- Phikwe region.  Kazakhstan is rich in uranium, coal, chromium, and zinc.","PW-0187":"","PW-0188":"Pair 1 is correctly matched : Kamarajar Port is the 12th major port of India and the first in the country to oper- ate as a public company. In 1999 it was declared a major port under the Indian Ports Act,1908. It was incorporated as Ennore Port Limited under the Companies Act, 1956 in October 1999. Kamarajar Port is the only corporatized major port in India, op- erating as a company. Today, the landlord port model, where the port authority leases the facilities to private operators, is the dominant approach in larger and medium-sized ports. Pair 2 is correctly matched : Mundra Port is situated along the northern coast of the Gulf of Kutch near Mundra in Gujarat. It is the largest privately owned port of India. It is owned and operated by Adani Ports and Special Economic Zone Limited (APSEZ) and handles a significant portion of India’s cargo. Pair 3 is incorrectly matched : Jawaharlal Nehru Port (Nhava Sheva) is the largest container port in India. Visakhapatnam Port ranks as India’s third largest state-owned port in terms of cargo volume handled and holds the distinction of being the","PW-0189":"Statement 1 is correct: India has more arable area than China. According to the World Bank India has approxi- mately 156 million hectares of arable land, while China has about 119 million hectares. Statement 2 is incorrect: China has a higher proportion of its arable land under irrigation than India. As per reports from the Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO) about 50% of Chi- na’s arable land is irrigated while India has approximately 35% of its arable land under irrigation. Statement 3 is incorrect: According to FAO (2021) China’s ce- real yield is about 6,300 kg/ha while India’s is around 3,200 kg/ha. This shows that China’s agricultural productivity is significantly higher than India’s. 118","PW-0190":"Option (c) is correct : The Tea Board under the Min- istry of Commerce and Industry, along with the Indian Tea As- sociation, lists Assam, West Bengal, Tamil Nadu, Himachal Pradesh, Tripura, Kerala, and Karnataka as tea-producing States.  Kerala : Known for its tea plantations, particularly in Wayanad and the Western Ghats.  Himachal Pradesh: Known for tea cultivation, especially in Kangra region.  Tripura : Also a tea-producing State, with significant tea cultivation.  Andhra Pradesh: Not a tea-producing State compared to the others listed. However, some claim Araku Valley as a minor tea production centre in the state.  India tea production during 2023-24 was 1382.03 Million Kgs increased by 7.06 Million Kgs over 2022-23 Tea plants require specific climatic and soil conditions for growth. These include :  Climate : Tropical and subtropical climates with warm, moist conditions and no frost throughout the year.  Rainfall : Around 1500 mm annually.  Temperature : Cooler temperatures, generally below 15-30 C, are ideal for tea cultivation.  Soil : Well-drained, fertile soil tha","PW-0191":"Statement 1 and 2 are correct : In India, monazite serves as the primary source of rare earth elements and thori- um. Rare earth metals comprise a group of 17 elements known for their lustrous, silvery-white appearance and soft, heavy me- tallic properties. China dominates global rare earth production, contributing around 60-70 % of the total output. These elements play a critical role in the production of electron- ics, magnets, and batteries. Monazite, abundant in India’s coastal sands, is rich in rare earth elements and thorium, a radioactive material. Thorium is crucial for India’s three stage nuclear en- ergy program. Statement 3 is incorrect : Monazite is not found in the entire Indian coastal sands. While it is found along most of the south- ern Indian coast, particularly in Kerala, Tamil Nadu, and Orissa, it does not occur throughout the entire coastline. Statement 4 is correct : As per Atomic Energy (Radiation Pro- tection) Rules 2004, Indian Rare Earths Limited (IREL), a whol- ly owned Public Sector Undertaking of the Government of India (GOI) under Department of Atomic Ene","PW-0192":"","PW-0193":"","PW-0194":"Statement 1 is correct : According to Section 3(e) of the Mines and Minerals (Development and Regulation) Act, 1957 (MMDR Act), ‘minor minerals’ include building stones, gravel, ordinary clay, ordinary sand, and other minerals that the Central Government may declare as minor minerals. Statement 2 is incorrect : State Governments have the power to grant mining leases for minor minerals under Section 15 of the MMDR Act. The Central Government does not have the power to frame rules related to the grant of minor minerals. The power to frame rules for minor minerals lies with the State Govern- ments under Section 15(1A) of the MMDR Act. Statement 3 is correct : Section 23C of the MMDR Act em- powers State Governments to make rules for preventing illegal mining, transportation, and storage of minerals, including minor minerals. 125","PW-0195":"Statement 1 is correct : The area under rice cultivation in India, in 2019-20 was 43.7 million hectares while in 2023- 24, it became 47.6 million hectares and is highest amongst all. Statement 2 is incorrect : The annual area under Jowar rang- es between 4 and 5 million hectares while the oilseed area is 27.1 million hectares (2019-20) i.e area under the cultivation of Jowar is less than that of oilseeds. Statement 3 is correct : The area under sugarcane cultivation is 4.6 million hectares (2019-20), 4.9 million hectares (2020-21), 5.2 million hectares (2021-22). The area under cotton cultivation is 13.5 million hectares (2019-20), 13.3 million hectares (2020- 21), and 12.4 million hectares (2021-22). Hence the area under cotton cultivation is more than sugar cultivation. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 370 Statement 4 is incorrect : With respect to the year in which the question is asked The area under sugarcane cultivation does not seem to be steadily decreasing. The area under sugarcane culti- vation is 4.99 million hectares (2013-14), 5.066 million hectares (2014-15), 4.953 million hectares","PW-0196":"Statement 1 is incorrect : According to the Mines and Minerals (Development and Regulation) Amendment Act, 2015 (MMDR Amendment Act), state governments have the power to auction non-coal mines. The central government sets the guidelines for the auction process, but the actual auction of non-coal mines is conducted by the state governments. Statement 2 is incorrect : Andhra Pradesh and Jharkhand do have gold mines.  Andhra Pradesh: Gold is found in Ramagiri in the Anantapur district.  Jharkhand: Both alluvial and native gold are present, with alluvial gold found in the sands of the Subarnarekha River and Sona Nadi, and native gold found near Lowa in the Singhbhum district.  Largest gold ore deposits in India are found in Bihar (based on recent discovery but not certified yet by GSI) , Rajasthan , and Karnataka with Andhra Pradesh and Jharkhand having smaller reserves. Statement 3 is correct : Rajasthan has significant iron ore de- posits. Iron ore deposits, primarily hematite and magnetite, are found in Rajasthan, specifically in districts like Jaipur, Udaipur, Jhunjhunu, Sikar, Bh","PW-0197":"Shale gas is a type of natural gas that is trapped within shale formations, which are fine-grained sedimentary rocks. Un- like conventional natural gas, which is found in porous reservoirs like sandstone, shale gas is tightly bound within the rock and re- quires advanced extraction techniques to release it. Option (d) is correct: The Ministry of Petroleum and Natu- ral Gas (MOPNG) has identified six basins as potentially shale gas bearing. These are: Cambay, Assam-Arakan, Gondwana, Krishna-Godavari Basin, Cauvery Basin and the Indo Gan- getic plain. 128","PW-0198":"","PW-0199":"Option 1 is correct: The Integrated Watershed Devel- opment Programme (IWDP) emphasizes soil conservation measures to prevent erosion and runoff. By implementing techniques such as terracing, contour plowing, and afforestation, the programme aims to maintain soil health and fertility, thereby enhancing agricultural productivity. Option 2 is incorrect: The IWDP does not encompass river interlinking projects. Its focuses is on watershed management at the micro-level which aims to conserve soil and water within specific catchment areas. River interlinking is a separate initia- tive under India’s National Perspective Plan which seeks to transfer water from surplus to deficit regions through large-scale infrastructure projects. Option 3 is correct: The IWDP emphasizes rainwater har- vesting and groundwater recharge through the construction of check dams, percolation tanks, and farm ponds. These struc- tures help capture rainwater, allowing it to percolate into the ground and recharge aquifers. This is particularly important in rainfed and arid regions where groundwater levels are critical","PW-0200":"Pair 1 is incorrectly matched : Kinnaur is primarily known for its apple orchards, not for Areca nut production. The region’s agriculture is most famous for apples, along with other fruits like apricots and peaches. Areca nut is mostly produced in states like Karnataka, Kerala, and Assam, which have the ideal climatic conditions for this crop. Pair 2 is incorrectly matched : Mewat is not particularly famous for mango production. The region is known for agriculture and allied agro-based activities, but mango cultivation is not a pri- mary feature of Mewat. The major mango-growing states in In- dia include Andhra Pradesh, Uttar Pradesh, Karnataka, Bihar, and West Bengal. Pair 3 is incorrectly matched : Coromandel Coast is primarily known for the production of crops like rice, pulses, sugarcane, cotton, and peanuts. It is not known for soybean production. The major states producing soybeans in India are Maharashtra and Madhya Pradesh, which together contribute 89% of the to- tal production of soybeans in the country. 132","PW-0201":"Option 1 is incorrect : Bhadrachalam is not famous for the production of traditional sarees or fabric. Instead, it is known primarily for its temples, especially the Sri Rama Temple, and its religious significance. Option 2 is correct : Chanderi, located in Madhya Pradesh, is renowned for the production of Chanderi sarees. These sarees are famous for their fine, lightweight fabric, often woven from UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 372 silk and cotton, and embellished with intricate zari work. Chan- deri sarees are a hallmark of Indian textile heritage and are con- sidered luxurious due to their delicate craftsmanship. Option 3 is correct : Kancheepuram, in Tamil Nadu, is inter- nationally famous for its Kanjeevaram sarees. These sarees are made of mulberry silk, renowned for their rich texture and fes- tive quality, often highlighted by the use of gold or silver zari (thread made of precious metals). They are considered one of the finest and most durable traditional sarees in India. Option 4 is incorrect : Karnal is not known for the production of traditional sarees or fabric. It is primarily re","PW-0202":"Indian coal is predominantly of the bituminous to sub-bituminous variety, which accounts for over 80% of the non-coking coal reserves in India. Bituminous coal is widely used in India, particularly in power plants, but the high ash con- tent requires effective ash handling and disposal systems. Option 1 is correct : Indian coal is characterized by a high ash content, which refers to the non-combustible residue left after burning coal. This is a significant characteristic of coal in India, making it less efficient and more environmentally damaging when burned. Option 2 is correct : Indian coal has a low sulphur content, which makes it relatively cleaner than coals from other regions that have higher sulfur levels. This reduces the emissions of harmful sulfur dioxide when the coal is burned. Option 3 is incorrect : Indian coal typically has a high ash fusion temperature (about 1,500°C). The ash fusion temperature re- fers to the temperature at which the ash in coal begins to soften and fuse, and Indian coal is known for its high ash fusion tem- perature, making it more resistant to fus","PW-0203":"Cotton, Groundnut and Rice are Kharif Crops in India while wheat is a Rabi Crop. About Kharif Crops :  Kharif crops are sown during June-July and harvested during September-October period. Rice, maize, jowar, bajra, moong, tur, urad, jute, cotton, soybean, groundnut, etc. are the type of kharif crops.  Rice : Temperature-22-32 degree celsius, Rainfall-1500-300 cm,Soil-Deep clay and loamy soil.  Cotton : Temperature 21-30 degree celsius,Rainfall 50-100 cm,Soil-well drained light sandy loams,yellow and black soils.  Groundnut: Temperature-30-35 degree celsius, Rainfall-40-125 cm,Well drained sandy loam soil About Rabi Crops:  Rabi crop is sown during October-December month and harvested in April-June. Wheat, barley, peas, gram, mustard etc are types of Rabi crops.  Wheat : Temperature 10-15 degree celsius, Rainfall 50-100 cm, Soil-well drained fertile loamy soil. 135","PW-0204":"Water is an indispensable resource for various indus- trial processes. In India, different industries use water in varying amounts, but the thermal power sector stands out as the high- est consumer due to its extensive cooling and steam generation requirements. While engineering, paper and pulp, and textiles industries do require water for various operations such as man- ufacturing, cleaning, and processing, their water consumption is comparatively much lower than that of thermal power plants. 136","PW-0205":"","PW-0206":"The crops which are predominantly rainfed in India are Groundnut, Sesamum and Pearl millets.  Groundnut is a drought-tolerant crop that requires moderate rainfall for its growth and development. Rainfall for cultivation - 500 to 600 mm per annum, distributed rainfall pattern throughout the growing season. Groundnut can withstand a dry spell of 15-20 days during its vegetative stage, but it requires adequate moisture during the flowering and pod formation stages.  Sesamum requires temperature is 25°C to 30°C, can tolerate up to 40°C, sensitive to frost required rainfall is 500-600 mm , its drought-tolerant, excessive rainfall during flowering can cause lower yields . It requires well-drained Soil type, rich in organic matter, pH range of 5.5 to 8.0. Geography 373  Pearl millet is a hardy crop that can grow in semi-arid regions. The ideal rainfall for pearl millet cultivation is between 400 to 600 mm per annum, with a well-distributed rainfall pattern throughout the growing season. Pearl millet can tolerate drought conditions and requires moisture during the early growth stages, esp","PW-0207":"Tamil Nadu is a leading producer of mill-made cotton yarn in India due to the availability of a rich pool of skilled labor, which is crucial for operating the state’s large textile industry. The state has a long tradition of textile manufacturing, support- ed by well-developed infrastructure and favorable government policies. Statement 1 is incorrect : Black cotton soil is often considered ideal for cultivating cotton because of its moisture-retaining properties. However, this soil type is not predominant in Tam- il Nadu. Instead, black cotton soil is commonly found in states like Maharashtra, Gujarat, and Madhya Pradesh. The cotton used in Tamil Nadu’s mills is primarily sourced from these cot- ton-growing regions, rather than being grown locally on black cotton soil. Statement 2 is correct : Tamil Nadu has a long-established tradition in textile manufacturing. The state is renowned for its skilled and semi-skilled workers who efficiently manage complex mill operations, machinery, and quality control. This expertise is one of the major reasons behind its leading position in the cott","PW-0208":"Statement 1 is incorrect : The Infant Mortality Rate (IMR) accounts for the deaths of infants within the first year of life, not just within a month after birth. The mortality during the neonatal period (first 28 days) is a subset of infant mortality. Statement 2 is incorrect : Infant Mortality Rate is defined as the number of infant deaths (under 1 year of age) per 1,000 live births in a given year, not per 100 live births. Indicator Definition India(NFHS‐5/ Recent Esti- mates) Infant Mortal- ity Rate (IMR) Number of deaths of in- fants (aged <1 year) per 1,000 live births ~28 per 1,000 live births Maternal Mortali- ty Ratio (MMR) Number of maternal deaths (due to pregnancy/ childbirth complications) per 100,000 live births ~97 per 100,000 live births (esti- mate from recent surveys) Total Fer- tility Rate (TFR) Average number of chil- dren a woman is expected to have over her reproduc- tive lifetime ~2.0 children per woman Crude Birth Rate Number of live births per 1,000 total population per year ~19.5 per 1,000 population per year (contextual estimate) Crude Death Rate Number of d","PW-0209":"Population density is measured as the number of people living per square kilometer. Below is a table summarizing key de- mographic data from the three censuses : UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 374 Census Year Population Density (persons/sq km) Annual Exponential Growth Rate (%) 1951 117 1.25 2001 324 1.93 2011 382 ~1.64 Statement 1 is incorrect : In 1951, the density was about 117 persons/sq km. By 2001, it had risen to 324 persons/sq km. Although this is a substantial increase, calculating the multipli- cation factor shows: = » 324 Factor 2.77 117 This means the density increased by roughly 2.77 times—which is less than three times. For additional context, the 2011 census reported a further increase to 382 persons/sq km, confirming a continuing but moderate increase. Statement 2 is incorrect : The annual growth rate (exponential) of India’s population has not doubled during this period. The growth rate was highest during the 1971 Census but gradually declined thereafter, indicating no doubling of the growth rate be- tween 1951 and 2001. The annual exponential growth rate is the average rate a","PW-0210":"Median age refers to the age at which half the popu- lation is younger and half is older. It reflects the demographic profile of a country, with higher median ages indicating older populations. With respect to year in which question has been asked :  India : India, being a developing nation with a younger population and a higher birth rate, has the lowest median age among these countries.  China : China’s population control policies (like the one- child policy) and the country’s demographic transition have resulted in a population that is older than India’s but younger than that of the USA and the UK.  USA : The USA has a relatively older population compared to India and China due to factors such as higher life expectancy and a stable birth rate. Therefore, the median age is higher than those of India and China but lower than the UK’s.  UK : The UK, being an industrialized and developed nation with an aging population, has the highest median age among the four countries. The population has a stable growth rate and a higher proportion of elderly individuals, making the median age ","PW-0211":"India’s National Population Policy, 2000, sets a long- term objective to achieve a stable population by the year 2045. This goal aligns with sustainable economic growth, social development, and environmental protection. The policy em- phasizes addressing unmet needs for contraception, healthcare infrastructure, and personnel, aiming to bring the Total Fertility Rate (TFR) to replacement levels by 2010. The medium-term objective is to achieve a TFR of 2.1 by 2010, and the long-term objective is to stabilize the population by 2045. 145","PW-0212":"In 2008, the percentage of persons above 65 years of age in India’s population was approximately in the range of 5-6%. According to the World Bank, approximately 7.07% of India’s population was aged 65 and above in 2023. This means that approximately 7.07% of India’s total population is currently aged 65 and above. Geography 375 146","PW-0213":"According to the Census of India 2001, the percentage of rural population in various states was as follows :  Himachal Pradesh: 90.2%  Bihar: 89.5%  Orissa (now Odisha): 85.0%  Uttar Pradesh: 79.2% Therefore, among the given options, Himachal Pradesh had the highest percentage of rural population to its total population in 2001. As per 2011 Census, percentage of rural population to the to- tal population in these states is Himachal Pradesh: Approx- imately 89.97%, Bihar: Approximately 88.72%, Odisha: Ap- proximately 83.32% & Uttar Pradesh: Approximately 77.73% 147","PW-0214":"According to the Census of India 2001, the populations of the given regions were as follows :  Sikkim: 540,851  Mizoram: 888,573  Puducherry (formerly Pondicherry): 974,345  Chandigarh: 900,635 Therefore, among the options provided, Sikkim had the smallest population as per the 2001 Census. According to the Census of India 2011, the populations of the specified regions are Sikkim: 610,577, Mizoram: 1,097,206, Puducherry (formerly Pondicherry): 1,247,953 & Chandi- garh: 1,055,450 148","PW-0215":"","PW-0216":"Statement 1 is incorrect : Chikmagalur, located in Kar- nataka, is renowned for its coffee production rather than sug- ar. The region’s elevation, rainfall, and temperature create ideal conditions for cultivating some of the finest coffee beans in the world. Today, Chikmagalur is one of India’s highest coffee-pro- ducing areas, with its culture and lifestyle deeply intertwined with coffee cultivation. Statement 2 is incorrect : Mandya, also situated in Karnataka, is primarily known for its sugarcane cultivation and sugar production, not coffee. The district is home to several sugar factories and numerous jaggery-making units, underscoring its prominence in sugar production. 150","PW-0217":"The term “million-plus cities” refers to urban agglomerations with a population exceeding one million. Based on the Census of India data below, the populations of the selected cities in 2001 and 2011 are as follows : UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 376 City Population in 2001 Population in 2011 Ludhiana 1,398,467 1,618,879 Kochi Urban Agglomeration 1,355,406 2,117,990 Surat 2,433,835 4,467,797 Nagpur 2,052,066 2,405,421 Hence, cities—Ludhiana, Surat, Kochi and Nagpur—were clas- sified as million-plus cities in India based on the 2001 census data. 151","PW-0218":"Population density is defined as the number of persons per square kilometer. It is calculated by dividing the total popula- tion of a state by its total area. The Census of India is conducted every ten years, providing comprehensive data on population distribution and density. The following table presents the pop- ulation density (persons per square kilometer) of Himachal Pradesh, Meghalaya, Arunachal Pradesh, and Sikkim as per the Census data of 2001 and 2011 : Option (c) is correct : State 2011 Census Density 2001 Census Density Himachal Pradesh 123 109 Meghalaya 132 103 Arunachal Pradesh 17 13 Sikkim 86 76 As per the Census of India 2001, Arunachal Pradesh has the lowest population density among the states of India, primarily due to its large geographical area and relatively low population, coupled with its hilly terrain and low urbanization. 152","PW-0219":"In 2007, Foodgrains output touched 230.67 million tonnes (MT) mark, comprising record output of wheat (78.4 MT), rice (96.43 MT) and pulses (15.11 MT). Coarse cereals production was an all-time-high of 40.73 MT, along with oilseeds at 28.82 MT. Thus the sequence in option (d) is correct. As per Final Estimates, the estimated production of major crops during 2023-24:  Rice (1378.25 Lakh tonnes) >Wheat (1132.92 Lakh tonnes) >Nutri / Coarse Cereals (569.36 Lakh tonnes)) > Pulses (242.46 Lakh tonnes) 153","PW-0220":"Statement 1 is incorrect : India was the first country to launch a National Programme for Family Planning in 1952. The Mission Parivar Vikas, one of the key flagship Family Plan- ning Programmes of Government of India was launched in 2016 for increasing access to contraceptives and family planning services. Statement 2 and 3 are correct :  The National Population Policy of India 2000 , aimed to achieve a replacement level of fertility (2.1 children per woman) by 2010, with a target population of about 111 crores.  The Total Fertility Rate (TFR) represents the average number of children a woman is expected to have during her reproductive years, based on current fertility rates. Kerala was the First State in India to achieve replacement level fertility. The Global Burden of Diseases (GBD) 2021 study notes that India’s TFR was 1.9 in 2021, below the replacement level of 2.1. Geography 377 155","PW-0221":"In 2001 Uttar Pradesh had the highest Population while Maharashtra ranked the second. In 2011 the same trend continued with Uttar Pradesh having the highest population (199,812,341) while Maharashtra followed(11,23,74,333) it at second.  The Census, conducted under the Census Act of 1948, is a decennial exercise managed by the Office of the Registrar General and Census Commissioner, Ministry of Home Affairs. It is a Union subject under Article 246 of the Indian Constitution, listed as item 69 in the Seventh Schedule.  In the census 2011 the population wise ranks in decreasing order are : Uttar Pradesh > Maharashtra> Bihar> West Bengal> Andhra Pradesh> Madhya Pradesh> Tamil Nadu.  While ranking from last in increasing order: Sikkim< Mizoram< Arunachal Pradesh< Goa < Nagaland.  Among the UTs Lakshadweep is the least populous while Delhi is the most Populous. 157","PW-0222":"Kharif crops are typically grown during the monsoon season (June to September) in India, and they require plenty of water. These crops are usually harvested after the monsoon season, around September to October.  Cotton is a Kharif crop grown during the monsoon season.  Groundnut and Maize are also Kharif crops grown during the monsoon season.Although it can also be grown in the Rabi season in some areas, it is primarily a Kharif crop in India.  Mustard is typically grown in the Rabi season (winter).  Thus, Cotton, Groundnut, and Maize are Kharif crops, while Mustard is a Rabi crop. 158","PW-0223":"Assertion (A) is true : The eastern coastal states (West Ben- gal, Odisha, Andhra Pradesh, Tamil Nadu) are among the largest rice-producing regions in India. The western coastal region (Maharashtra, Goa, Karnataka, Kerala) produces comparatively less rice due to limited lowland areas suitable for large-scale paddy cultivation. Reason (R) is false : The western coast (Konkan, Malabar) re- ceives higher rainfall than the eastern coast due to the south- west monsoon and orographic effect of the Western Ghats. The eastern coast receives sufficient rainfall, mainly from the south- west monsoon (except Tamil Nadu, which depends on the northeast monsoon). Additionally, major rivers like the Ganga, Godavari, Krishna, and Kaveri provide irrigation, supporting rice cultivation. Although the eastern coast produces more rice, the main reason is not higher rainfall but the presence of large river deltas, extensive irrigation, and favorable soil conditions. The western coast, despite higher rainfall, has limited flat land for large-scale rice cultivation, as it is narrow and hilly due to the Weste","PW-0224":"Statement 1 is correct : The Indian subcontinent is indeed the original home of the cotton plant. The Neolithic Site of Mehr- garh near Bolan Pass in Balochistan region of Pakistan has the oldest evidence of cotton. Many Harappan sites provide evidence of cotton cultivation. Statement 2 is correct : The first commercial cotton hybrid was Hybrid-4 (H-4) , developed by Indian scientist Chandrakant T. Patel in 1970. This hybrid was created by crossing the Gujarat-67 variety with the American variety . These hybrids offer advantages like higher yields, improved resistance to pests and diseases, and better adaptability to diverse climatic conditions. 160","PW-0225":"The Genetic Engineering Appraisal Committee (GEAC) is the regulatory body responsible for granting environ- mental release of genetically modified (GM) crops like Bt Cotton in India, while the final approval for commercial cultivation is de- cided by the central government.  It functions under the Ministry of Environment, Forest and Climate Change (MoEFCC). It was established under the 1989 Rules, which were framed under the Environment Protection Act, 1986.  It oversees the safety assessment of GM crops before their commercial release. Final approvals for cultivation are based on GEAC’s recommendations, but the central government makes the final decision after considering inputs from other stakeholders like the Indian Council of Agricultural Research (ICAR) and the Ministry of Agriculture.” 161","PW-0226":"Statement 1 is incorrect : India was the second- largest producer of fruits after Brazil in 2003-04. According to the Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO) of the United Nations, this trend continued, and in 2019, India remained the world’s second-largest producer of both fruits and vegetables. Statement 2 is incorrect : Ranked by volume, Zimbabwe, Chi- na, India (3rd), and Malawi were major exporters of tobacco in 2002. However by 2021-22, India was the second largest to- bacco producer behind China and India was the 2nd largest exporter of tobacco behind Brazil. To regulate tobacco production, and exports of tobacco, Tobacco Board was formed in 1976. It is based in Andhra Pradesh. The Cigarettes and Other Tobacco Products Act ad- opted by Parliament in 2003 bans tobacco advertising and smoking in public places. India has signed and ratified the global Framework Convention on Tobacco Control (FCTC) treaty adopted by the World Health Assembly in 2003. 162","PW-0227":"Amongst the given, In 2003 as well as the in the lat- est ranking Japan had the highest life expectancy in the world. The highest average life expectancy countries according to statis- ta are- Monaco > Republic of Korea (South Korea) > China (Hongkong) > Spain > Malta > Israel. In India, life expectan- cy at birth (years) has improved from 63 years in 2000 to 67.3 years in 2021. Comparison of option countries : Country Life Expectancy (Approx.) Canada ~83.9 years Germany ~81.5 years Japan ~85.2 years Norway ~83.3 years 163","PW-0228":"Statement 1 is correct: Ethnic Albanians are the larg- est minority in Macedonia. In 2007, rising tensions over Koso- vo’s final status appeared to spark outbreaks of violence. Ethnic Albanian extremists were seeking to break away from Macedonia to join Kosovo. Likewise, Macedonians are a minority in Albania. Greeks are the largest minority of Albania. Statement 2 is incorrect : Serbs are the largest minority group in Kosovo while the Ethnic Albanian makes up the major- ity. The conflict in Kosovo was largely driven by ethnic Albanian demands for independence from Serbia. 164","PW-0229":"Below is a table summarizing approximate population figures for the four countries in question for the years 2003 and 2024 : Country Population (2003) Population (2024) Indonesia ~222 million ~275 million Pakistan ~158 million ~240 million Japan ~127 million ~123 million Sudan ~39 million ~45 million 165","PW-0230":"Based on the data from the Census of India 2001 and 2011, the population densities (persons per square kilometer) for the specified states are as follows : Geography 379 State Population Density (2001) Population Density (2011) West Bengal 903 1,029 Kerala 819 860 Uttar Pradesh 698 829 Madhya Pradesh 196 236 166","PW-0231":"Below is a table summarizing approximate population figures for the four countries for the years 2002 and 2024: Country Population (2002) Population (2024) Indonesia ~214 million ~283 million Brazil ~176 million ~212 million Russia ~145 million ~144 million Japan ~127 million ~123 million Option (c) is correct: Based on the table above, the correct de- scending order (largest to smallest) for the population of the countries is: Indonesia (2)>Brazil (1)> Russia (4)> Japan (3) 167","PW-0232":"","PW-0233":"","PW-0234":"A is correctly matched with 3: 1901-1921 period is often re- ferred to as the “Stagnant Phase” in India’s demographic history. Both birth and death rates were high, leading to minimal popu- lation growth. The decade from 1911 to 1921 even witnessed a slight decline in population, primarily due to epidemics, famines, and the influenza pandemic of 1918-19. B is correctly matched with 1: 1921-1951 is known as the “Steady Growth Phase”. This period saw a decline in death rates due to improvements in healthcare, sanitation, and transporta- tion. However, birth rates remained high, resulting in a gradual increase in population. The population grew from approximately 251 million in 1921 to 361 million in 1951 C is correctly matched with 2: 1951-1981 is termed as the “Rapid High Growth Phase”. This era experienced a significant surge in population. While death rates continued to decline, birth rates remained relatively high, leading to a sharp increase in pop- ulation numbers. The population nearly doubled during these three decades, rising from about 361 million in 1951 to 683 mil- lion in ","PW-0235":"Statement 1 is incorrect : Indian Railways is the fourth largest railway system in the world. The United States, China, and Russia have larger railway networks in terms of total track length. Statement 2 is correct : National Highways in India make up only about 2% of the total road network but are designed to handle long-distance, high-speed travel. They carry approxi- mately 45% of the country’s total road traffic and transport demand. Statement 3 is incorrect : Kerala has a well-developed and dense road network but states like Goa and Tripura actually have higher road densities. Therefore, Kerala does not hold the record for the highest surface road density among Indian states. Statement 4 is correct : Earlier, National Highway 7 (NH 7) was the longest highway in India. Following the renumbering of National Highways, NH 7 was merged into NH 44, which is now the longest National Highway in the country stretching from Srinagar (Jammu and Kashmir) to Kanyakumari (Tam- il Nadu) 172","PW-0236":"The exceptionally high population densities in both the Nile Valley and the island of Java are primarily attributable to the practice of intensive agriculture. The fertile soil, favorable climate, and availability of water have made these regions ideal for farming, which has historically supported large populations. Industrialization and urbanization are secondary factors, while topographic limitations have influenced but not caused the high population density. Region Key Natural Factor Primary Agricultural Practice Resulting Popu- lation Density Nile Valley Nutrient-rich silt from annual Nile floods Intensive cultivation of wheat, rice, cotton Sustained high density in a nar- row fertile strip Java Fertile volca- nic soil Intensive rice cultivation Among the high- est population densities globally 173","PW-0237":"The Census of India is a decennial exercise conduct- ed by the Office of the Registrar General and Census Com- missioner, India, to collect demographic, social, and eco- nomic data about the population. Below are tables summarizing key census data for the states in- volved, for the years 1991, 2001, and 2011. Geography 381 Table 1. Population Density (persons per sq km) State 1991 Cen- sus 2001 Cen- sus 2011 Census West Bengal 767 903 1,029 Uttar Pradesh ~600 698 829 Table 2. Adult Literacy Rate (% of people aged 15 and above) State 1991 Census 2001 Census 2011 Census Bihar 38.48% 903 ~47% ~58.44% Table 3. Sex Ratio (number of females per 1,000 males) State 1991 Census 2001 Census 2011 Census Kerala 1,036 ~1,040 ~1,045 Himachal Pradesh ~976 ~980 ~990 Option (d) is correct : Bihar had the lowest literacy rate in India in the 1991 Census at around 38.48%. 175","PW-0238":"Assertion (A) is True: The Ganga Plain,a part of the Indo-Gangetic Plain supports one of the highest population densities in India. This is primarily due to its fertile alluvial soil, which makes the land highly productive for agriculture. The region benefits from abundant water resources, a favorable cli- mate, and flat terrain, all of which have historically encouraged dense human settlements. Reason (R) is True: The Ganga is the most harnessed river in India, with its waters extensively used for irrigation, drinking, in- dustrial purposes, and hydroelectric projects. This extensive har- nessing has been pivotal for the region’s agricultural productivity and development. R is not the correct explanation of A : The reason alone does not directly explain the high population density in the Ganga Plain. Population density is influenced by a variety of factors, in- cluding geographical, historical, economic, and cultural factors. The availability of fertile land for agriculture, historical settle- ment patterns, economic opportunities, and cultural factors play significant roles in dete","PW-0239":"Assertion (A) is True : Australia is one of the world’s largest exporters of beef and has a significant cattle industry focused on meat production. The country’s vast grazing lands and favorable climate make it ideal for raising cattle for beef. Ac- cording to the Australian Bureau of Agricultural and Resource Economics and Sciences (ABARES), beef production is a major agricultural activity, and Australia exports a significant portion of its beef to international markets. In contrast, dairy farming, while still important, is smaller in scale compared to the beef industry. Reason (R) is True : It is true that meat, particularly beef and lamb, forms a significant part of the Australian diet. This dietary habit reflects the cultural preferences in Australia, where a ma- jority of the population consumes meat. Reason (R) is not the correct explanation of Assertion(A) : The reason provided does not directly explain why cattle rearing in Australia is predominantly for meat production. The primary factors influencing this include:  Geographical and Climatic Conditions: Australia’s expansiv","PW-0240":"Assertion (A) is False: The natural sex ratio at birth worldwide, including in India, favors male births. Typically, about 105 male births occur for every 100 female births. In India, this ratio is similar or sometimes even more skewed toward males, due to both biological factors and socio-cultural practices. For instance, data from the 2011 Census of India show an overall sex ratio of about 940 females per 1,000 males, indicating that more male children are born than female children. Reason (R) is True: Biologically, male infants are known to be more vulnerable to certain health complications, including in- fections and genetic disorders. Consequently, male children tend to have a slightly higher mortality rate in infancy compared to female children. This phenomenon is observed in many popula- tions worldwide, including India. 178","PW-0241":"A is correctly matched with 2 : Gujarat is the largest producer of cotton in India, followed by Maharashtra. It has fa- vorable black soil and climate conditions for cotton cultivation. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 382 B is correctly matched with 1 : Madhya Pradesh is the leading producer of gram (chickpea) in India, accounting for a signifi- cant share of the total production. C is correctly matched with 4 : Kerala is known as the “Spice Garden of India” and is a major producer of black pepper. The state’s humid tropical climate is ideal for growing various spices, including black pepper. D is correctly matched with 3 : West Bengal is a major pro- ducer of pineapple, particularly in regions like Darjeeling and Jalpaiguri. 179","PW-0242":"","PW-0243":"","PW-0244":"A is correctly matched with 2 : Jamnagar, located in Gujarat, is historically known for its textile industry, including woollen and silk textiles. The city is known for its production of Bandhani (tie-dye) fabrics and other woollen textiles. B is correctly matched with 5 : Hospet, in Karnataka, is part of the Bellary-Hospet region, which is rich in iron ore deposits. It is a major center for iron and steel production, with industries like Jindal Steel and Vijayanagar Steel Plant operating in the re- gion. C is correctly matched with 1 : Korba, in Chhattisgarh, is known as the “Power Capital of India” and is a major center for aluminium production. The Bharat Aluminium Company (BAL- CO) operates a major plant in Korba, contributing significantly to the aluminium industry. D is correctly matched with 3 : Haldia, in West Bengal is an industrial city with a major fertilizer plant. The Haldia Pet- rochemicals Limited (HPL) and other chemical industries are prominent here. 183","PW-0245":"A is correctly matched with 2 : Alibag is renowned for its beautiful beaches(Alibag Beach and Kihim Beach) and coastal scenery, making it a popular holiday destination. Its proximity to Mumbai has led to its development as a resort town, attracting tourists seeking leisure and relaxation. B is correctly matched with 1 : Balapur, located near the coast, has a community primarily engaged in fishing activities. The town’s economy is significantly supported by its fishing industry, supplying seafood to nearby regions. C is correctly matched with 4 : Nhava Sheva, also known as Jawaharlal Nehru Port (JNPT), is India’s largest container port located near Mumbai. D is correctly matched with 3 : Ratnagiri is known for its pet- rochemical industries, including oil refineries and other relat- ed facilities. 184","PW-0246":"Surface road density is calculated as the total length of surface roads (in km) divided by the area of the state (in 100 km² units). States with higher road density have better road con- nectivity and infrastructure. The correct descending order by state number is: Tamil Nadu (4) > Punjab (3) > Maharashtra (2) > Haryana (1)  Tamil Nadu (State 4): 158.78 km per 100 km2  Punjab (State 3): 127.78 km per 100 km2  Maharashtra (State 2): 117.61 km per 100 km2  Haryana (State 1): 63.70 km per 100 km2 185","PW-0247":"","PW-0248":"","PW-0249":"","PW-0250":"A is correctly matched with 2:The Karanpura coal- fields are located in Jharkhand, known for their vast coal re- serves. B is correctly matched with 3: The Hutti Gold Mines in Karna- taka are one of the few active gold mining areas in India.The Hutti region has a long history of gold mining and remains significant in India’s gold production. C is correctly matched with 4: Nellore district in Andhra Pradesh is famous for its high-quality mica deposits. D is matched with 1: The Bhandara district in Maharashtra is a significant producer of manganese, used in steel production and other industries. 190","PW-0251":"The sex ratio in a population is defined as the number of females per 1,000 males. As per 1991 census sex ratio declined slightly from 934 to 927 between 1981-1991 , indicating a de- cline in the proportion of females relative to males. When we examine the census data for India over recent decades, we observe that the sex ratio does not follow a single steady trend; rather, it shows variations from one census to another. As per the table, These fluctuations indicate that the sex ratio in India is neither steadily declining, stable, nor uniformly increasing; it is fluctu- ating over time. Various factors contribute to these changes, in- cluding differences in birth rates, mortality rates, socio-economic conditions, and cultural practices.  1991 to 2001: The ratio increased again to 933, suggesting a modest recovery.  2001 to 2011: The ratio further improved to 943, which is a significant increase compared to 1991. 191","PW-0252":"","PW-0253":"","PW-0254":"A is correctly matched with 2 : Barley is a hardy crop that grows well in a cool climate and can tolerate poor soil fer- tility. It is commonly cultivated in temperate regions. It is rown in temperate regions like Rajasthan, Uttar Pradesh, and Madhya Pradesh in India. B is correctly matched with 4 : Rice is typically cultivated in areas with abundant rainfall and warm temperatures. It thrives in alluvial soils that are rich in nutrients, which is why the ideal condition is described as a hot and moist climate with rich soil. Major rice-producing states in India include West Bengal, Punjab, Uttar Pradesh, and Andhra Pradesh. Geography 385 C is correctly matched with 1 : Millets are drought-resistant crops that grow in areas with a hot and dry climate and can tolerate poor, sandy soils. They are commonly cultivated in arid and semi-arid regions. 2023 was declared the International Year of Millets by the UN to promote their cultivation. D is correctly matched with 3 : Tea requires a warm and moist climate, well-drained soil, and grows best in high-altitude ar- eas. Hill slopes in region","PW-0255":"The descending order by production quantity is: Groundnut (3) > Soyabean (4) > Mustard (2) > Sesamum (1)  Groundnut is the largest produced oilseed in India. It is cultivated primarily in Gujarat, Andhra Pradesh, and Tamil Nadu, often in semi-arid regions.  Soybean is the second largest oilseed crop, grown predominantly in Madhya Pradesh, Maharashtra, and Rajasthan.  Mustard ranks third in oilseed production and is grown widely in the north-western plains, particularly in Rajasthan, Haryana, and Uttar Pradesh.  Sesamum (or sesame) has a lower production compared to the others. It is cultivated in small quantities across Gujarat, Uttar Pradesh, and West Bengal.  India ranks among the top five producers of oilseeds globally.  Groundnut accounts for about 35% of total oilseed production.  The National Mission on Edible Oils (NMEO) aims to boost domestic production and reduce import dependence. 195","PW-0256":"Manganese, Nickel, Lead-zinc, and Asbestos are important mineral resources in India, each predominantly mined in specific states due to favorable geological conditions. A is correctly matched with 1: Manganese ore is a crucial raw material for the steel industry and is extensively mined in Madhya Pradesh. Regions like the Balaghat district in Madhya Pradesh are well known for their significant deposits. B is correctly matched with 2: Nickel is primarily mined in Orissa (Odisha), where substantial reserves exist, particularly in areas such as the Sukinda Valley. Orissa is recognized for its notable nickel deposits. C is correctly matched with 3: Lead and zinc ores are largely found in Rajasthan. The Zawar mines in are one of the most prominent sources of lead and zinc in India. Rajasthan is re- nowned for its lead-zinc mining. Lead and Zinc are used in bat- teries, galvanization, and alloys. D is correctly matched with 4 : Asbestos is mined in Andhra Pradesh, particularly in regions like Cuddapah and Kurnool. Andhra Pradesh has well-established asbestos mining opera- tions. They are u","PW-0257":"Cotton Production in India is concentrated in regions with warm temperatures (21–30°C), a semi-arid climate, and soil conditions favorable to cotton cultivation (such as the black, moisture-retaining regur soil). It is produced in North-west and Western India in states like Gujarat, Maharashtra, and Pun- jab.  Gujarat: Recognized as the largest cotton producer in India, owing to its conducive climate and extensive cultivation practices.  Maharashtra: Known for significant rain-fed cotton farming on regur soil, which supports high yields.  Rajasthan: Especially in its irrigated parts, Rajasthan contributes a substantial share to the country’s cotton production 197","PW-0258":"","PW-0259":"India has diverse agro-climatic zones, enabling different re- gions to specialize in certain crops based on soil type, rainfall, and climate. Pair 1 is incorrectly matched : Tapioca (cassava) is widely grown in Kerala, particularly in hilly and rain-fed areas, but it is not considered a major or economically significant crop of the state compared to others. Pair 2 is correctly matched : Maharashtra is a leading produc- er of cotton in India, particularly in Vidarbha and Marathwada regions, owing to its black soil. Maharashtra is followed by Guja- rat and Telangana in cotton production. Pair 3 is correctly matched : West Bengal is the largest pro- ducer of jute in India, contributing around 75% of the nation’s total yield. The benefits from the alluvial soils of the Ganga-Brah- maputra delta and experienced agricultural workforce. Known for its durability and versatility, jute plays a crucial role in various industries, including textiles and packaging. Pair 4 is correctly matched : Gujarat leads in groundnut pro- duction, especially in Saurashtra and Kutch regions, due to suitable sa","PW-0260":"Drip irrigation is a highly efficient water-saving irri- gation technique where water is directly supplied to the plant roots through a network of pipes, valves, and emitters. Statement 1 is correct : Drip irrigation delivers water only to plant roots, preventing water wastage in surrounding soil areas. Since weeds grow in moist conditions, less water in non-target areas leads to reduced weed growth. Statement 2 is incorrect : Drip irrigation does not reduce soil salinity. Instead it may lead to salt accumulation near the root zone over time due to limited leaching of salts from the soil. Flood irrigation is more effective in reducing soil salinity as it washes away excess salts. Statement 3 is correct : Since drip irrigation supplies water at a slow and controlled rate there is minimal surface runoff, preventing soil erosion. Unlike traditional irrigation methods like flood or sprinkler irrigation, which cause water runoff and soil displacement, drip irrigation keeps soil structure intact. SUPER HINT For S1, \"Drip\" means water only near plants and not for weeds hence less likely wee","PW-0261":"","PW-0262":"The nitrogen cycle is a crucial process that maintains the soil fertility necessary for plant growth. Statement 1 is correct : Animals excrete urea through urine containing nitrogen. When this urea is deposited onto the soil, soil microorganisms break it down through a process called mineralization, converting it into ammonium (NH4 +), which can readily absorbed by plants. Statement 2 is incorrect : While the burning of coal releases ni- trogen oxides (NOx) into the atmosphere, it does not directly add nitrogen to the soil. Instead, the pollutants can contribute to air pollution and acid rain, which may eventually affect soil quality but not in a beneficial way for nitrogen enrichment of soil. Geography 387 Statement 3 is correct : The death and decomposition of veg- etation naturally adds nitrogen to the soil. When plants die, their organic matter decomposes due to microbial activity. During de- composition, nitrogen is released in the form of ammonium and nitrates, which then enrich the soil. This recycling of nutrients is a natural and critical component of the nitrogen cycle. SUP","PW-0263":"","PW-0264":"Statement 1 is correct : Coffee plant requires a hot and humid climate of tropical areas whereas tea can be cultivated in both tropical and subtropical areas.  Coffee thrives in a hot and humid tropical climate, requiring temperatures between 15°C and 28°C with well-distributed rainfall. Traditional coffee producing regions include the southern states of Karnataka (largest producer), Kerala, and Tamil Nadu. Non-traditional regions consist of Andhra Pradesh and Odisha, located in the Eastern Ghats of India.  Tea can grow in both tropical and subtropical with temperaturerange 20-30°C requiring high humidity and well-distributed rainfall (100-200 cm) areas. For example, it is cultivated in Assam (tropical) and Darjeeling (subtropical) regions. Assam is the largest producer of tea in the country. Statement 2 is incorrect : Coffee is propagated by seeds but tea is not propagated by stem cuttings only.  Coffee is primarily propagated by seeds, but vegetative propagation methods like cuttings and grafting are also used.  Tea is propagated both by seeds and vegetative methods, including ","PW-0265":"Soil conservation techniques aim to prevent soil erosion, im- prove soil fertility, and maintain ecological balance. Option 1 is correct : Rotating crops helps maintain soil fertili- ty by alternating nutrient-exhausting crops with nitrogen-fixing ones, reducing soil degradation and pest infestations. Legumes are rotated with cereals to fix nitrogen in the soil in states like Punjab and Haryana. Option 2 is correct : Sand fences are barriers made of wood or other materials to trap sand and stabilize soil in areas prone to wind erosion, such as coastal or desert regions. It is practised in arid regions like Rajasthan, where wind erosion is a problem. Option 3 is correct : Terracing involves creating step-like structures on slopes, which slows down water runoff, prevents soil erosion, and conserves moisture, making it highly effective in hilly areas. Option 4 is correct : Wind breaks are rows of trees or shrubs planted to reduce wind speed and protect soil from erosion, especially in open fields. It is commonly used in hilly regions like the Himalayas and Western Ghats. UPSC GS Paper-I","PW-0266":"The National Development Council (NDC) in 2007 ad- opted a resolution to launch a Food Security Mission compris- ing rice, wheat and pulses to increase the annual production of rice by 10 million tonnes, wheat by 8 million tonnes and pulses by 2 million tonnes by the end of the Eleventh Plan (2011-12). Accordingly, a Centrally Sponsored Scheme, ‘National Food Se- curity Mission’ (NFSM), was launched in October 2007. Initially, NFSM (2007-08) focused on rice, wheat, and pulses only. The objectives of NFSM are :  Increase production of specific crops through area expansion and productivity enhancement.  Ensure sustainability by focusing on improved technologies and efficient resource use.  Enhance farm profitability and rural livelihoods. 206","PW-0267":"Statement 1 is correct : Paddy fields are typically flooded, creating anaerobic (oxygen-deprived) conditions. Soil saturation in wetland rice fields restricts oxygen transport, creat- ing anaerobic conditions due to submergence. This environment supports the activity of methanogenic bacteria, which produce methane (CH4), a potent greenhouse gas. Rice cultivation is a significant source of methane emissions globally. Statement 2 is correct : Nitrogen-based fertilizers, which en- hance crop yield, stimulate soil microbes to convert nitrogen into nitrous oxide (N2O), another potent greenhouse gas. Mi- crobial processes like nitrification and denitrification in the soil release nitrous oxide, especially in poorly drained, water- logged soils. Nitrous oxide has a global warming potential 265 times greater than CO2 over 100 years. 207","PW-0268":"","PW-0269":"Assertion (A) is false: It is incorrect to assert that there are no tea plantations in any African country. Several Afri- can countries, such as Kenya, Uganda, Tanzania, Malawi, and Rwanda, are major tea producers. Kenya is the third-largest tea producer globally after China and India. Malawi was the first African country to grow tea (in the 19th century) and re- mains a key exporter. Reason (R) is true: Tea plants do need fertile soil with high humus. Tea plants thrive in fertile, well-drained soils with high humus content, which improves water retention and nutrient availability. 209","PW-0270":"Dalbergia species is a genus of trees and shrubs known for their high-quality timber, especially varieties used in furni- ture and musical instruments. Dalbergia includes species such as Dalbergia sissoo (Indian Rosewood) and Dalbergia latifo- lia (East Indian Rosewood), which are primarily used for rose- wood timber. These trees are valued for their durability, aes- thetic grain patterns, and strength, making them popular for crafting luxury furniture and decorative items. Dalbergia species are not associated with crops like cashew, coffee, or tea. Indian Rosewood is an upright, deciduous tree that grows up to 25 meters tall with a trunk diameter of 2-3 meters. It has leathery leaves that can reach 15 cm in length. The tree produc- es whitish-pink flowers and has an oval-shaped crown. Its fruit is brown, pod-like, dry, and hard. The sapwood ranges from white to pale brown, while the heartwood varies from golden to dark brown. Dalbergia nigra and Dalbergia latifolia are among the other recognized species of Indian Rosewood. Geography 389 210","PW-0271":"","PW-0272":"Assertion (A) is true: Bt cotton is a genetically mod- ified (GM) crop that has been engineered to produce a protein toxic to certain insect pests, particularly bollworms. The gene responsible for this trait is derived from the soil bacterium Ba- cillus thuringiensis (Bt). When the Bt gene is inserted into the cotton plant, the plant produces the Bt toxin, which kills specific insect pests when they feed on the plant. Reason (R) is true: The Bt gene is derived from the bacteri- um Bacillus thuringiensis. This bacterium naturally produces a protein (Cry protein) that is toxic to certain insects. Scientists isolated the gene responsible for producing this protein and in- serted it into the cotton plant’s genome to create insect-resistant transgenic cotton. Reason (R) correctly explains Assertion (A) : The insertion of the Bt gene from Bacillus thuringiensis into cotton plants en- ables these transgenic plants to produce the Bt toxin internally. The Bt gene encodes a protein that is toxic to certain insects but harmless to humans and other non-target organisms. When the gene is inserted","PW-0273":"","PW-0274":"","PW-0275":"","PW-0276":"Option 1 is incorrect : Jackfruit(Artocarpus hetero- phyllus) is an evergreen tree native to tropical regions of Asia. It retains its foliage throughout the year unlike deciduous trees, which shed their leaves during certain seasons. The tree thrives in hot and humid climates and is known for edible fruit that grows directly from the trunk. Jackfruit trees are common in India, Bangladesh, and Southeast Asia Option 2 is correct : Mahua (Madhuca indica) is a deciduous tree found in the dry forests of Central India including parts of Madhya Pradesh, Jharkhand, and Chhattisgarh. This tree sheds its leaves during the dry season to conserve water. Mahua is cul- turally significant in tribal communities and its flowers are used to make a traditional alcoholic drink. The tree’s flowers are also edible and have medicinal properties. Option 3 is correct : Teak (Tectona grandis) is one of the most valuable hardwoods in the world. It is a deciduous tree that sheds its leaves in the dry season between February and March. It is known for its durability, resistance to weathering, and ability to wit","PW-0277":"Option 4 is correct : The Rann of Kutch in Gujarat is an extensive marshland formed due to repeated falls in sea level. This region was a shallow part of the Arabian Sea. Over time tectonic activity and sea level changes caused the area to be- come landlocked and created a vast salt marsh. During monsoons it gets flooded and in the dry season it turns into a salty desert. Option 1,2 and 3 are incorrect :  Bhitarkanika Mangroves is located in Odisha. These mangroves are coastal wetlands characterized by tidal waters and mangrove forests and not by repeated falls in sea level.  Marakkanam Salt Pans is situated in Tamil Nadu. These are man-made salt pans used for salt production and not natural marshlands formed by sea level changes.  Naupada Swamp is a freshwater wetland, not a salt marsh formed by sea level fluctuations. It is located in Andhra Pradesh. 218","PW-0278":"Option (c) is correct : Gandikota canyon is situated on the Pennar River in Andhra Pradesh and is known as the Grand Canyon of India. Gandikota is a small village in the Kadapa dis- trict of Andhra Pradesh. Gorges are formed when rivers erode through gigantic rock formations over a long period of time. A gorge is any valley formed by a source of water flowing between tall slabs of steep rocks. The swift flowing waters of River Pen- nar cut through the granite rocks near the village of Gandiko- ta, naturally eroding the rock and forming a deep valley. 219","PW-0279":"Pair 1 is incorrectly matched: Namcha Barwa is not situated in Garhwal Himalayas. It is part of Eastern Himalayas marking the easternmost section of the Himalayas. The peak lies inside the Great Bend of the Yarlung Tsangpo River, where the river takes a significant turn before entering India as the Brah- maputra. Pair 2 is correctly matched: The part of the Himalayas lying between Satluj and Kali rivers is known as Kumaon Himalayas. Nanda Devi is part of the Kumaon Himalayas located in the Chamoli district of Uttarakhand. The peak is flanked by the Rishi- ganga valley to the west and the Goriganga valley to the east. The surrounding Nanda Devi National Park was recognized for its unique biodiversity and was declared a UNESCO World Heri- tage Site. Pair 3 is incorrectly matched: Nokrek Peak stands as the high- est point in Meghalaya’s Garo Hills, situated in northeastern In- dia. It belongs to the Shillong Plateau and is geographically sep- arate from the Sikkim Himalaya which is located further north in Sikkim. It is recognized for its diverse flora and fauna and the Nokrek region ha","PW-0280":"Pair 1 is incorrectly matched: The Ghataprabha Res- ervoir is built on the Ghataprabha River, a tributary of the Krishna River, located in the Belagavi district of Karnataka(not Telengana). It provides irrigation to the drought-prone regions of north Karnataka. The Gokak Falls is located on this river. Pair 2 is correctly matched: The Gandhi Sagar Dam is con- structed on the Chambal River is situated in the Mandsaur and Neemuch districts of Madhya Pradesh. It is one of the five ma- jor dams of the Chambal Valley Project and plays a vital role in irrigation and hydroelectricity. Pair 3 is incorrectly matched: The Indira Sagar Dam is the larg- est dam in India, in terms of volume of water stored in the reser- voir. It is located in Madhya Pradesh, not Andhra Pradesh. It is built on the Narmada River and is one of the largest reservoirs in India. Pair 4 is incorrectly matched: The Maithon Dam is built on the Barakar River, a tributary of the Damodar River. It is situated in Dhanbad district of Jharkhand. It is a key component of the Damodar Valley Corporation (DVC) project, controlling ","PW-0281":"","PW-0282":"Option 1 is incorrect: The Brahmani River does not originate in the Eastern Ghats. The Brahmani River is formed by the confluence of the South Koel and Sankh rivers in Jharkhand. The South Koel originates near Nagri in Jharkhand, while the Sankh River originates in the Chotanagpur Plateau. Af- ter the confluence, it flows through the Eastern Ghats in Sundar- garh, Deogarh, Dhenkanal, and Jajpur districts. Option 2 is correct: The Nagavali River originates in the East- ern Ghats near Lakhbahal in the Kalahandi district of Odisha. It flows through Odisha and Andhra Pradesh before draining into the Bay of Bengal. Option 3 is incorrect: The Subarnarekha River originates near Nagri in the Chotanagpur Plateau of Jharkhand. It flows through Jharkhand, West Bengal, and Odisha before emptying into the Bay of Bengal. The Chotanagpur Plateau is part of the Deccan Plateau, not the Eastern Ghats. Option 4 is correct: The Vamsadhara River rises in the Durga- kangar Hills of the Eastern Ghats in the Kalahandi district of Odisha. It flows through Odisha and Andhra Pradesh before draining into the Ba","PW-0283":"Option 1 is correct : Nagarhole National Park is located in the Kodagu and Mysore districts of Karnataka. The Nagarahole River flows through the park which joins the Kabini River which also is a boundary between Nagarahole and Bandipur National Park. Option 2 is incorrect : Papikonda National Park is located in the East Godavari and West Godavari districts of Andhra Pradesh. It lies in the Godavari River Basin, not the Cauvery Basin. Option 3 is correct : Sathyamangalam Tiger Reserve (STR) is located at the confluence region of Western and Eastern Ghats, in the Erode district of the state of Tamil Nadu. In the northern part of Erode district, the Palar river flows and drains into the Cauvery river. The Bhavani River, a major tributary of the Cauvery, flows through this region. Option 4 is correct : Kabini river, a tributary of the Cauvery river flows through the Wayanad Wildlife Sanctuary. SUPER HINT For S2, \"Konda\" phrase In Papikonda is more associated with Andhra and Telangana state areas which are far away from Cauvery basin, hence likely false, eliminating options A and D. 225","PW-0284":"Aliyar, Isapur and Kangsabati are geographically dis- persed across different states, but they share the common char- acteristic of being sites of significant water reservoirs. These reservoirs are crucial for irrigation, drinking water supply, and sometimes hydroelectric power generation in their respective regions. 226","PW-0285":"Kodaikanal Lake, also known as Kodai Lake is a man- made lake (artificial) located in the Kodaikanal city in Dindigul district in Tamil Nadu, India. The lake was built in 1863, in the middle of Kodaikanal town. Sir Vere Henry Levinge, the then Col- lector of Madurai, had a key role in its construction. The lake is star-shaped, centrally located in the town of Kodaikanal and is surrounded by lush green hills of the northwestern Palani Hills range. It is fed by several small streams from the Palani Hills. Option (b), (c) and (d) are incorrect:  Kolleru Lake is a large, natural, shallow freshwater lake located in the northeastern part of Andhra Pradesh, between the Krishna and Godavari deltas. It is designated as a Ramsar Wetland Site due to its ecological importance. It is a natural lake formed by the accumulation of river waters and is a major habitat for migratory birds.  Nainital lake is a natural lake and was formed due to tectonic movements. It is a natural, kidney-shaped, tectonic lake formed due to geological movements. It is part of the Kumaon Lake Region and is a popular tou","PW-0286":"Statement 1 is correct: Barren Island is India’s only active volcano and is located in the Andaman Sea, within the Andaman and Nicobar Islands. It belongs to the volcanic arc of the Sunda Trench and is part of the Andaman Subduction Zone which makes it seismically active. Statement 2 is incorrect: Barren Island is located about 140 km northeast of Port Blair (the capital of the Andaman and Nicobar Islands), not Great Nicobar. Great Nicobar is located far south of the Andaman Islands, whereas Barren Island is in the northern Andaman Sea. Statement 3 is incorrect: The Barren Island volcano has erupted multiple times after 1991. Significant eruptions were recorded in 1994–1995, 2005, 2009, and most recently in 2017–2018. Thus, it has not remained inactive since 1991. SUPER HINT When S1 says its active volcano and S3 says its inactive since approx 27 years, that means both statements clearly contradicts. Its a active volcano is a well known fact as being the \"only\" active one in India, thus S3 is more likely false, giving option A as correct. 228","PW-0287":"Statement 1 is incorrect : The Teesta River originates from the Tso Lhamo Lake in North Sikkim, near the Khangse Glacier. The Brahmaputra River originates from the Angsi Gla- cier in Tibet. Thus, their sources are not the same. The Teesta River flows through Sikkim and West Bengal before entering Bangladesh. Statement 2 is correct : River Rangeet originates from the Hi- malayas in West Sikkim and is the largest tributary of Teesta River. It joins the Teesta at Melli near the border of Sikkim and West Bengal. Statement 3 is incorrect : Teesta River does not flow directly into the Bay of Bengal. It joins the Brahmaputra River (called Jamuna in Bangladesh) before flowing into the Bay of Bengal. The Teesta meets the Jamuna near Fulchhari in Bangladesh and then the combined flow reaches the Bay of Bengal. 229","PW-0288":"","PW-0289":"Teak(Tectona grandis) is a dominant tree species of Tropical moist deciduous forest. Tropical moist deciduous forests are found in the states of Jharkhand, Chhattisgarh, West Odisha, and on the eastern slopes of the Western Ghats. Also known as Monsoon Forests, annual rainfall in these forests is in the range of 100 to 200 cm Characteristics of Tropical Moist Deciduous Forests  Rainfall: 1000–2000 mm annually  Temperature: 24–32°C  Seasonality: Distinct wet and dry seasons, leading to partial shedding of leaves during dry months  Soil: Deep, fertile, well-drained alluvial and lateritic soils  Main Trees are Teak (Tectona grandis), Sal (Shorea robusta), Sandalwood, Rosewood, Indian Laurel, Mahua, etc. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 394 231","PW-0290":"The Godavari is India’s second longest and third-biggest river, after the Ganga. Through a vast network of tributaries, the river eventually drains into the Bay of Bengal. The Godavari is the greatest river in peninsular India in terms of length, catchment area, and flow, and has been nicknamed the Dakshina Ganga, or “Southern Ganga.” It originates from Trimbakeshwar in Maharashtra. Options 2 and 3 are correct :  Indravati River is one of the most significant tributaries of the Godavari, originating from the Dandakaranya Plateau in Kalahandi district, Odisha. It flows westward through Chhattisgarh and Maharashtra before joining the Godavari near Bhadrachalam, Telangana. It plays a crucial role in the region’s hydrology by supporting the Indravati Hydroelectric Project, one of India’s largest hydroelectric power projects.  Pranahita River is another major tributary of the Godavari formed by the confluence of the Wardha and Wainganga rivers in Maharashtra. It flows southward through Maharashtra and Telangana and eventually merges into the Godavari. Pranahita is considered one of the ","PW-0291":"","PW-0292":"The Andaman & Nicobar Islands uniquely house a com- bination of mangrove, evergreen, and deciduous forests, making them one of India’s most ecologically diverse regions. The Andaman and Nicobar Islands have a tropical rainforest canopy. The Middle Andamans harbours mostly moist decidu- ous forests. North Andamans is characterised by the wet ever- green type, with plenty of woody climbers. The coastal regions of Andaman and Nicobar Islands have mangrove forests.  Mangroves are salt-tolerant trees thriving along tropical coastlines, providing crucial habitats for marine life. In India, they are found in West Bengal, Gujarat, Andaman & Nicobar Islands, Andhra Pradesh, and Tamil Nadu. These forests withstand saline conditions and frequent submersion.  Evergreen forests which retain their leaves year-round. They are highly biodiverse and occur in the Western Ghats, Andaman & Nicobar Islands, and Northeast India. Semi-evergreen forests exist in transitional zones, while dry evergreen forests are located in the Shivalik Hills and coastal Andhra Pradesh. Geography 395  Deciduous forests, ","PW-0293":"The Himalayan ecosystem exhibits distinct vegetation zones based on altitude and climate. Statement 1 is correct: Oak trees dominate the temperate broadleaf forests of the Himalayas. They are typically found between 1,500–3,000 meters. Common species include Quercus leucotrichophora (Banj Oak) in the western Himalayas (Uttara- khand, Himachal Pradesh) and Quercus semecarpifolia (Kharsu Oak) at higher elevations. Oak forests play a key role in soil con- servation and water retention, making them ecologically vital. Statement 2 is correct: Coniferous trees like Rhododendron, pine, deodar, silver fir, spruce and cedar, are found in the temper- ate forests (1500 and 3000 metres). Some key species include Rhododendron arboreum (Buransh), found in Uttarakhand and Sikkim, and Rhododendron hodgsonii, which thrives in Arunachal Pradesh and Meghalaya. The vibrant flowers con- tribute to pollination cycles and biodiversity. Statement 3 is incorrect: Sandalwood does not naturally grow in the Himalayas. It is native to tropical dry deciduous for- ests. It is primarily found in Karnataka, Tamil Na","PW-0294":"Statement 1 is incorrect : The Changpa are a semi-no- madic ethnic group. They are mainly found in the Changtan plateau that stretches across the cold desert of Ladakh and parts of Jammu and Kashmir. They are also known as Champa. A smaller number resides in the western regions of the Tibet Autonomous Region in China. They share linguistic and cultur- al affinities with Tibetans. Statement 2 is correct : The Changpa community is known for rearing Changra goats, which produce the fine wool known as Pashmina. They are raised for ultra-fine cashmere wool, also known as pashmina once woven. Statement 3 is correct : The Changpa community is recognized as a Scheduled Tribe (ST) in the Union Territory of Ladakh. This classification provides them with certain constitutional safe- guards and benefits. 237","PW-0295":"Coral reefs are underwater ecosystems formed by colo- nies of tiny animals called coral polyps. These animals secrete a hard, calcium carbonate exoskeleton that provides a founda- tion for the growth of other corals and a diverse array of marine organisms. Coral reefs are found in tropical and subtropical waters around the world, particularly in the Pacific Ocean, the Indian Ocean, and the Caribbean Sea. Fig: Map showing distribution of Coral Reefs in India Options 1 is correct: Andaman and Nicobar Islands archipel- ago is home to some of India’s most diverse and well-developed coral reefs which supports a rich variety of marine life. Options 2 is correct: Gulf of Kachchh is situated along Gujarat’s western coast. This region features fringing reefs around its is- lands. Though less developed due to environmental factors, these reefs contribute significantly to marine biodiversity. Options 3 is correct: Gulf of Mannar is ocated between south- eastern India and Sri Lanka. The Gulf of Mannar hosts extensive fringing reefs around 21 islands. It is part of the Gulf of Mannar Marine Natio","PW-0296":"Pair 1 is correctly matched : Tamang , Limbu, Bhut- ia, Khas, Lepchas are important tribal communities of Sikkim. Pair 2 is incorrectly matched : Karbi is a tribal community from Karbi Anglong of Assam, not Himachal Pradesh. Other import- ant tribes from the state include Bodo, Kachari, Miri, Mishimi, Rabha. Pair 3 is correctly matched : The Dongaria Kondh is a par- ticularly vulnerable tribal group found in the Niyamgiri Hills of Odisha. They are known for their unique cultural practices and traditional agriculture. Pair 4 is incorrectly matched: The Bonda tribe is one of the oldest and most primitive tribes in India, residing in the hilly re- gions of the Malkangiri district in southwestern Odisha, not in Tamil Nadu.  Some of the main tribes from Tamil Nadu are Malayali, Toda, Kurumbas, Paniyan, Irular, Kattunayakan, Kanikkar, Palliyan, Kadar, etc. Toda, Kota, Kurumbas, Kattunayakan, Paniyan and Irular have been designated as ‘Primitive Tribes’.  The People of Sikkim consist of three ethnic groups, that is, Lepcha, Bhutia and Nepali. Of these, the Lepchas and Bhutias communities ","PW-0297":"The Narmada River is unique among India’s major peninsular rivers due to its westward flow into the Arabian Sea, contrasting with the predominantly eastward flow of other large rivers in the region. Statement 1 is correct : The Narmada River flows through a linear rift valley which is a geological depression created by the subsidence of the Earth’s crust. It is flanked by the Vindhya Range to the north and the Satpura Range to the south. This rift valley naturally channels the river westward, distinguishing it from most other peninsular rivers that flow eastward. Statement 2 is incorrect : Though the Narmada does flow be- tween the Vindhya and Satpura ranges but it not the cause of its westward flow. The ranges themselves are remnants of older folded mountains. Statement 3 is incorrect : While most rivers in the Indian pen- insula flow eastward towards the Bay of Bengal. This is due to the region’s natural slope to the west from Central India. But the Narmada River’s westward course is dictated by its unique geological setting within a rift valley. 240","PW-0298":"National Parks in India are biodiversity hotspots, often intertwined with rivers that sustain their ecosystems. Pair 1 is incorrectly matched: Corbett National Park, located in Uttarakhand, is traversed by the Ramganga River, not the Ganga. The Ramganga is a significant tributary within the park, supporting its rich biodiversity. Pair 2 is incorrectly matched: The Kaziranga National Park is circumscribed by the Brahmaputra River, which forms the northern and eastern boundaries, and the Mora Diphlu, which forms the southern boundary. The Manas River flows through the Manas National Park. Pair 3 is incorrectly matched: Silent Valley National Park is located in Kerala. It is drained by the Kunthipuzha River, a tributary of the Bharathapuzha River. The Kaveri River flows through Karnataka and Tamil Nadu, not Kerala. 241","PW-0299":"The Himalayas are the youngest fold mountains in the world. They exhibit dynamic geological features shaped by tec- tonic activity. These features provide evidence of their youthful and evolving nature, making them a fascinating subject for geol- ogists and travelers alike. All the given features—deep gorges, U-turn river courses, parallel mountain ranges, and steep gradients causing landslides—are evidence of the Himalayas being young fold mountains. These characteristics result from ongoing tectonic uplift, erosion, and the mountains’ relatively re- cent formation (around 50 million years ago). 242","PW-0300":"Monsoon refers to a seasonal change in wind patterns that results in a shift in precipitation patterns over a region. Mon- soons occur primarily in tropical and subtropical regions and are characterized by a wet season and a dry season. Statement 1 is correct: The monsoon duration decreases from southern India (June-September) to northern India (July-August) due to the gradual weakening of monsoon winds as they move inland. Due to its proximity to the sea, India’s south- ern region has earlier and longer rainy seasons than its northern region. Statement 2 is correct: The northern plains experience a rainfall gradient, with higher rainfall in the east (Assam, West Ben- gal) and decreasing towards the west (Punjab, Rajasthan) due to the weakening of monsoon winds. During the southwest monsoon, Kolkata receives 119 cm, Patna 105 cm, Allahabad 76 cm, and Delhi 56 cm. 243","PW-0301":"Arunachal Pradesh has the following mentioned char- acteristics:  Northern Rajasthan lies approximately between 26°N to 27°N latitude. Arunachal Pradesh (27°N–29°N) closely aligns with this latitude range. Assam (24°N–28°N), Himachal Pradesh (30°N–33°N), and Uttarakhand (29°N–31°N) are either too far north or south.  As per the India State of Forest Report (ISFR) 2021, Arunachal Pradesh has 82.4% forest cover. While Assam has 35.83%, Himachal Pradesh 27.72%, and Uttarakhand 45.44%.  Arunachal Pradesh has over 12% of its forest area designated as Protected Areas, including Namdapha National Park, Pakke Wildlife Sanctuary, and Mouling National Park. 244","PW-0302":"Under the text of the Ramsar Convention wetlands are defined as: “areas of marsh, fen, peatland or water, whether natural or artificial, permanent or temporary, with water that is static or flowing, fresh, brackish or salt, including areas of marine water the depth of which at low tide does not exceed six metres”. Wetlands in India are vital ecosystems supporting biodiversity, water regulation, and livelihoods. They are classified into coastal and inland wetlands, each with unique ecological and geograph- ical significance. Statement 1 is correct : Gujarat has the largest area under wetlands in India. It is primarily due to the extensive Rann of Kutch, a seasonal salt marsh, and coastal wetlands like the Gulf of Kutch. According to the National Wetland Inventory and Assess- ment by the Space Applications Centre (ISRO), Gujarat accounts for ~22.7% of India’s total wetland area. Statement 2 is incorrect : Inland wetlands (like lakes, rivers, and marshes) cover a larger area than coastal wetlands (like mangroves, estuaries, and lagoons). As per the National Wetland Atlas, inland wetland","PW-0303":"Arunachal Pradesh, often referred to as the “Orchid Paradise of India,”. It boasts over 600 orchid species, account- ing for approximately 40% of the country’s orchid diversity. The state’s sub-alpine and sub-tropical climates provide ideal conditions for orchid cultivation which makes it highly suit- able for developing an export-oriented industry with minimal production costs. Orchids belong to the family Orchidaceae and are perennial herbs. Nearly 24000 species of orchids spreads over 140 gen- era are reported from India, besides Hybrids produced regu- larly. Orchids, which grow on trees, are known as epiphytes. Those that grow on the ground are referred to as terrestrial. Those that grow on rocks are known as lithophytes, while some relatively little known ones grow on decaying matter or rotting logs are known as saprophytes. 246","PW-0304":"Brahmaputra makes a “U” turn in its course to flow into India due to the Syntaxial bending of geologically young Himalayas. The Himalayan mountains’ gently arching ranges on their west- ern and eastern extremities are abruptly bent southward in deep knee bends known as syntaxial bends. The massive mountains seem to bend around a pivotal point on both the ends. The west- ernmost point is located where the Hindu Kush joins the Kara- koram south of the Pamir. Arunachal Pradesh’s eastern border features a similarly abrupt, almost hairpin curve when the moun- tain’s strike abruptly shifts from an easterly to a southerly ten- dency. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 398 247","PW-0305":"The above characteristics clearly define Gujarat.  The northern region of Gujarat comprises the Kutch and Banaskantha districts, which are characterized by arid and semi-arid conditions due to low annual rainfall (less than 500 mm). The Thar Desert extends into parts of Gujarat, contributing to the dry climate.  Gujarat is the largest producer of cotton in India (~30% of national production). The central districts, such as Ahmedabad, Surendranagar, Rajkot, and Bhavnagar, have ideal black soil (Regur soil) that supports cotton cultivation.  Gujarat is highly commercialized in agriculture, focusing on cotton, groundnut, tobacco, and castor rather than food crops. The Saurashtra and Kutch regions specialize in cash crops due to their soil type and climatic conditions. 248","PW-0306":"Statement 1 is correct: National Parks are established under the Wildlife (Protection) Act, 1972. The State Govern- ment issues a notification specifying the precise limits of the area designated as a National Park. Any alteration of these boundaries requires a resolution passed by the State Legislature.These areas receive strict protection, and activities like hunting, poaching, and deforestation are strictly prohibited. India’s first National Park ​Jim Corbett National Park was established under this Act. Statement 2 is incorrect: Biosphere Reserves aim to conserve entire ecosystems rather than focusing on specific species. They are designated to promote the conservation of biodiversity, foster sustainable development, and support research and edu- cation. These reserves include core, buffer, and transition zones to balance conservation with sustainable use. Statement 3 is correct: Wildlife Sanctuaries in India allow certain human activities, such as grazing or resource collec- tion, under regulated conditions. The Chief Wildlife Warden may grant permissions for such activities, en","PW-0307":"","PW-0308":"Pair 1 is incorrectly matched: Jharkhand is not the primary source of copper in India. The Singhbhum district of Jharkhand has some copper reserves but Madhya Pradesh (Malanjkhand) and Rajasthan (Khetri) are the largest producers, contribut- ing ~90% of India’s copper. Pair 2 is correctly matched: Odisha (formerly Orissa) is the largest producer of nickel in India, with major deposits in the Sukinda Valley. Pair 3 is incorrectly matched: Kerala is not a significant source of tungsten in India. The distribution of tungsten re- sources in India is as follows: Geography 399  Karnataka: Approximately 41%  Rajasthan: Around 27%  Andhra Pradesh: About 17%  Maharashtra: Approximately 11% 251","PW-0309":"Pair 1 is correctly matched: Bhitarkanika National Park in Odisha is a vital estuarine ecosystem and a key habitat for saltwater crocodiles, the world’s largest living reptiles. It hosts mangrove forests, estuarine habitats, and numerous bird species. Pair 2 is correctly matched: Desert National Park in Rajasthan is one of the last remaining strongholds of the Great Indian Bus- tard. It is critically endangered and among the heaviest flying birds. The park consists of sand dunes, grasslands, and rocky landscapes, providing an ideal habitat for this rare bird. Pair 3 is incorrectly matched: Eravikulam National Park in Kerala is renowned for the Nilgiri Tahr, an endangered moun- tain goat, not the Hoolock Gibbon. Hoolock Gibbons are native to Northeast India, primarily in Arunachal Pradesh and Assam. 252","PW-0310":"Tropical Moist Deciduous Forests cover the largest area in India, found across Central India, the Western Ghats, the Eastern Ghats, and the Himalayan foothills. They thrive in 1,000- 2,000 mm annual rainfall zones and experience a distinct dry sea- son, leading to leaf shedding. Dominant tree species are Sal (Sho- rea robusta) in the north and Teak (Tectona grandis) in the south. It covers about 37% of India’s total forest area. 253","PW-0311":"Option (d) is correct: Himachal Pradesh is a mountainous state located in the western Himalayas, and several significant rivers flow through it. These rivers originate in the Himalayas and are vital for irrigation, hydroelectric projects, and other wa- ter needs in northern India.  Beas River originates from Beas Kund near Rohtang Pass in Himachal Pradesh. It flows entirely within Himachal Pradesh before entering Punjab.  Chenab River originates near Baralacha Pass in the Lahaul-Spiti region of Himachal Pradesh. After originating in Himachal, it flows into Jammu & Kashmir and later into Pakistan.  Ravi River originates near Bara Banghal in the Kangra district of Himachal Pradesh. It flows through Chamba district and then into Jammu & Kashmir before crossing into Pakistan.  Sutlej River originates from Mansarovar Lake near Mount Kailash in Tibet. It enters Himachal Pradesh through the Shipki La Pass and flows through Kinnaur before entering Punjab. The Bhakra Nangal Dam is built on this river.  Yamuna River originates near Yamunotri Glacier in Uttarakhand.The river forms the east","PW-0312":"","PW-0313":"","PW-0314":"","PW-0315":"Amarkantak, a significant geographical landmark in India, serves as the source for two major rivers that exhibit con- trasting hydrological patterns.  The Narmada River originates from the Amarkantak Plateau in Madhya Pradesh. It flows westward for 1,312 km, forming a natural divide between North and South India before emptying into the Arabian Sea via the Gulf of Khambhat. Its basin is elongated, with hilly upper reaches and fertile lower plains ideal for cultivation.  The Son River is a major southern tributary of the Ganga, also originates near Amarkantak in Chhattisgarh. It initially flows north-northwest through Madhya Pradesh before turning eastward, cutting through the Kaimur Range and running parallel to the Kaimur Hills. It then flows through Uttar Pradesh, Jharkhand, and Bihar, eventually joining the Ganga near Patna. Fig: Map showing routes of Narmada and Son after originating near Amarkantak Option (b), (c) and (d) are incorrect:  Badrinath (Uttarakhand) is associated with the origin of the Alaknanda River, which later joins the Ganga system, but it does not give rise ","PW-0316":"Statement 1 is incorrect : India possesses significant reserves of thorium, particularly in the southern parts of the country. Major Thorium Deposit states are : Andhra Pradesh ,Tamil Nadu ,Odis- ha , Kerala ,Gujarat, West Bengal and Jharkhand. Statement 2 is incorrect : Kerala’s monazite sands, particularly along the coastal regions of Kollam and Palakkad, are among the richest for thorium in the world. These sands contain ap- proximately 1.9 million tonnes of monazite, with high concen- trations of thorium (up to 10%) and rare earth elements (55–60%). UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 402  Thorium is a naturally occurring, radioactive metal more abundant than uranium in the Earth’s crust. Extracted primarily from monazite sands, it is considered a potential nuclear fuel due to its ability to breed fissile uranium-233. Thorium has applications in nuclear reactors, high- temperature ceramics, and scientific instruments but requires further development for widespread use.  Monazite is primarily used for extracting thorium and rare earth metals, essential for nuclear energy and advanced technolog","PW-0317":"Statement 1 is incorrect : While Kerala is renowned for its numerous west-flowing rivers that drain directly into the Arabian Sea, it is important to note that the state also possesses a few significant east-flowing rivers. The Kabini, Bhavani, and Pambar rivers, for instance, contribute to the eastward flow of water, ultimately merging with the larger Kaveri River system. These rivers flow eastward into neighboring states and ultimate- ly merge with the Kaveri River. Kabini flows into Karnataka, while Bhavani and Pambar enter Tamil Nadu. They play a sig- nificant role in inter-state water systems and biodiversity. Statement 2 is incorrect : Madhya Pradesh, a state character- ized by diverse geographical features, is home to a network of rivers flowing westward. The Narmada, Tapi, and Mahi rivers are prominent examples of this westward drainage pattern, ulti- mately finding their way to the Arabian Sea.  Kabini River : Originates in the Wayanad district of Kerala from the confluence of the Panamaram and Mananthavady rivers. It flows eastward for approximately 240 km before joining t","PW-0318":"Biodiversity hotspots are regions with exceptional levels of plant and animal endemism that are under significant threat. Options 1 and 2 are correct : Among the given regions, the Eastern Himalayas, encompassing parts of Nepal, Bhutan, In- dia, and China, and the Eastern Mediterranean Region qualify as biodiversity hotspots. These regions harbour a remarkable di- versity of life, including numerous species found nowhere else on Earth. However, threats like deforestation, habitat loss, and climate change pose significant risks to this precious ecosystem.  The Eastern Himalayas region supports iconic species like the Bengal tiger, Asian elephant, red panda, and greater one-horned rhinoceros. The Eastern Himalayas’ rich biodiversity arises from its unique geography at the intersection of three biogeographical realms: Indo-Malayan, Palaearctic, and Sino-Japanese.  The Eastern Mediterranean is part of the larger Mediterranean Basin biodiversity hotspot, one of the richest and most threatened regions globally. The region also supports diverse wildlife, including migratory birds, reptile","PW-0319":"Sambhar Lake, situated in Rajasthan, India, holds the distinction of being the nation’s largest inland saline wetland. This expansive lake, located southwest of Jaipur, plays a crucial role in the region’s ecology. Historically renowned for salt production, Sambhar Lake pro- vides a vital habitat for a diverse array of flora and fauna, particu- larly migratory birds such as flamingos and pelicans. However, the lake faces environmental challenges including pollution, wa- ter scarcity, and human encroachment. Despite these challenges, Sambhar Lake remains an ecologically significant and culturally important landmark in Rajasthan. 266","PW-0320":"India’s port system comprises two distinct categories: major ports and non-major (minor) ports. As of 2024, the nation has 13 major ports and 217 non-major ports, forming a crucial network for maritime trade. Major ports, strategically administered by the Ministry of Ports, Shipping and Waterways under the Government of India, play a pivotal role in the coun- try’s maritime trade. In contrast, non-major ports come under the jurisdiction of the respective State Maritime Boards, with some also operating under the public-private partnership (PPP) model. Among the given options, Dahej is classified as a non-major port in India. In contrast, Kochi (Cochin), Paradip, and New Mangalore are all designated as major ports. India has 13 major ports and over 200 minor ports spread across its 7,500 km coastline. Major Ports are managed by the Central Government and handle significant cargo traffic. Minor Ports are managed by State Governments and include private ports. Western Coast 1. Deendayal Port (Kandla) - Gujarat 2. Mumbai Port - Maharashtra 3. Jawaharlal Nehru Port Trust (JNPT) - Maharasht","PW-0321":"","PW-0322":"Located in the Kishtwar district of Jammu and Kashmir, India, the Dul Hasti Hydroelectric Power Plant, a 390 MW project, was constructed by the National Hydroelectric Power Corpo- ration (NHPC). This power plant utilizes the run-of-the-river principle, harnessing the flow of the Chenab River to generate electricity. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 404 269","PW-0323":"Statement 1 is correct : Tropical deserts indeed form along the western margins of continents within the trade wind belt due to several factors. Trade winds, blowing from east to west, lose moisture on eastern coasts and arrive dry on the western side. These regions lie under subtropical high-pressure belts (15°–30° latitude), where descending air suppresses cloud formation and rainfall. Additionally, cold ocean currents, such as the Hum- boldt Current, cool the air, reducing its moisture-holding capac- ity and creating stable, dry conditions. In some cases, mountains block moist winds, causing a rain shadow effect. Together, these factors create arid environments like the Sahara, Atacama, and Namib deserts. Statement 2 is incorrect : In India, the Eastern Himalayas expe- rience significantly higher rainfall compared to the Western Hi- malayas. This precipitation is primarily attributed to the South- west monsoon, rather than the Northeast monsoon. The Bay of Bengal branch of the monsoon carries moisture-laden winds that are funneled toward the Eastern Himalayas. When these winds enc","PW-0324":"","PW-0325":"With reference to the year in which this has been asked , Andaman and Nicobar Islands have the maximum number of National Parks among the given states/UTs :  Andaman and Nicobar Islands : 9 National Parks  Assam : 7 National Parks  Arunachal Pradesh : 2 National Parks  Meghalaya : 2 National Parks Currently, Madhya Pradesh has the maximum number (12) of National Parks. 272","PW-0326":"","PW-0327":"Reserves of diamond-bearing Kimberlite rocks have been discovered in Raipur district, Chhattisgarh in the recent past. Kimberlite is an igneous rock that often contains diamonds, and its presence indicates the possibility of diamond deposits. These discoveries are part of the Mainpur Kimberlite Field, which has been extensively explored by the Geological Survey of India (GSI). India’s diamond history is rich and varied. Andhra Pradesh, especially the Krishna River basin, was once a major diamond source, home to the famed Golconda mines that yielded iconic gems like the Koh-i-Noor. Although large-scale mining has ceased, potential reserves remain. MadhyaPradesh, dubbed India’s ‘diamond state’, currently hosts the country’s sole active industrial-scale diamond mine, Majhgawan, near Panna. This region has a centuries-old diamond mining tradition, primarily producing industrial-grade stones. 274","PW-0328":"The Servarayan Hills, also known as the anglicised ‘Shevaroy Hills’, are a prominent mountain range in Tamil Nadu. Located near the city of Salem, these hills form a signif- icant part of the southern section of the Eastern Ghats. The name ‘Servarayan’ is derived from a local deity worshipped in the region, reflecting the cultural significance of these mountains. Spanning 400 sq. km, they feature lush forests, coffee planta- tions, and diverse flora and fauna. The hills are home to Yer- caud, a popular hill station, and the Shevaroy Temple, situ- ated at the highest peak (1,620 m). The region is known for its panoramic views, trekking trails, and unique biodiversity, includ- ing endemic species like Neelakurinji and shield-tail snakes. The hills also host bauxite deposits and fruit orchards. 275","PW-0329":"Statement 1 is incorrect : The Red Panda is naturally found in the Eastern Himalayas and not in the Western Himala- yas. The red panda, a small arboreal mammal, is native to the temperate forests of the Eastern Himalayas, spanning from Ne- pal, Bhutan, and India to southwestern China. Its distribution in- cludes parts of southern Tibet, Sikkim, Assam, Bhutan, northern Myanmar, and the Hengduan and Gongshan Mountains of south- western China. The species thrives in temperate forests with dense bamboo undergrowth at elevations of 2,000–4,300 meters. Fig: Red Panda Statement 2 is correct : The slow loris, a primate, inhabits South and Southeast Asia. Its range extends from Northeast In- dia across Indochina, eastward to Southeast Asia, and south- ward to Java, encompassing Borneo, Sumatra, and numerous smaller islands. While both species share a portion of their geographical range in Northeast India, their overall distributions differ significantly, with the red panda primarily confined to the Himalayas and the slow loris widespread across Southeast Asia. Fig: Slow Loris 276","PW-0330":"Statement 1 is incorrect : As per the 2006 data, Petr- onet LNG Ltd. was setting up another LNG terminal at Kochi, Kerala (not Mangalore). Statement 2 is correct : The Head Office of the Dredging Cor- poration of India is at Visakhapatnam. DCI is a crucial organi- zation for maintaining and developing India’s waterways. They are responsible for dredging harbors, ports, and shipping chan- nels, ensuring safe and efficient navigation for vessels. Statement 3 is correct : The Narwapahar Mine is operated by the Uranium Corporation of India Limited. UCIL is the prima- ry company responsible for uranium mining and processing in India, and the Narwapahar Mine in Jharkhand is one of their key operations. It’s an important source of uranium ore, which is essential for India’s nuclear power program. 277","PW-0331":"Statement 1 is incorrect : Electricity-related appeals are handled through a structured system. While each state has a State Electricity Regulatory Commission (SERC) to oversee its electricity sector, including tariffs, licensing, and consumer com- plaints, appeals against SERC orders don’t go to a state-level body. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 406 Instead, they are directed to the Appellate Tribunal for Elec- tricity (APTEL), a national-level tribunal. The APTEL also hears appeals against orders from the Central Electricity Regu- latory Commission (CERC) and adjudicating officers. While the idea of having accessible avenues for appeals related to electrici- ty matters is important, the Appellate Tribunal for Electricity (APTEL) is actually a national-level body, not one established by each individual state government. Statement 2 is correct : The Accelerated Power Development and Reforms Programme (APDRP), later revamped and renamed as the Restructured Accelerated Power Development and Reforms Programme (R-APDRP) and now subsumed under the Integrated Power Development Scheme (IPDS), did in-","PW-0332":"Assertion (A) is true : Andhra Pradesh and West Bengal exhibit contrasting agricultural land use patterns. Andhra Pradesh has a net sown area of approximately 40%, while West Bengal utilizes about 60% of its land for cultivation. This differ- ence in land utilization makes the initial assertion about their respective net sown areas correct. Reason (R) is false : Most of Andhra Pradesh has red sandy soils, black cotton soils, and alluvial soils, not predominantly laterite soils. Laterite soils are found in parts of the Eastern Ghats and some upland areas, but they do not dominate the state’s agricultural landscape. Laterite soil is a highly weathered, red to yellow soil rich in iron and aluminum oxides, formed in hot, humid tropical regions due to intense leaching. It is poor in fertility, acidic, and best suited for crops like tea, coffee, cashew, and rubber with proper soil management. Laterite soil in India is found in Kerala, Karnataka, Maharashtra, Goa, Odisha, Andhra Pradesh, Tamil Nadu, Jharkhand, West Bengal etc. 279","PW-0333":"The arrangement of these hill ranges in India, from north to south, follows a specific order. Beginning in the north are the Nallamalai Hills, located primarily in Andhra Pradesh. Moving southward, the Javadi Hills, situated in Tamil Nadu, come next. Further south lies the prominent Nilgiri Hills, also in Tamil Nadu, known for their biodiversity and hill stations. Finally, the southernmost range in this sequence is the Anamalai Hills, straddling the border of Kerala and Tamil Nadu, and home to the highest peak in the Western Ghats, Anamudi. Therefore, the cor- rect north-to-south sequence is Nallamalai Hills, followed by the Javadi Hills, then the Nilgiri Hills, and finally the Anamalai Hills. Geography 407  The Nallamalai Hills, a part of the Eastern Ghats, extend across Andhra Pradesh and Telangana, stretching from the Krishna River to the Pennar River. These hills are home to the Nagarjunasagar-Srisailam Tiger Reserve, India’s largest tiger reserve, which plays a crucial role in wildlife conservation.  The Javadi Hills, a north-south hill range in Tamil Nadu, are a continuation ","PW-0334":"Biosphere Reserves are areas of terrestrial and coast- al ecosystems promoting solutions to reconcile the conservation of biodiversity with its sustainable use. They are designated by UNESCO under its Man and Biosphere (MAB) Programme. Currently , India has 18 Biosphere Reserves, designated to con- serve biodiversity, ecosystems, and traditional lifestyles. Option (b) is correct : Agasthyamalai, Nilgiri, and Panchmarhi are all recognized Biosphere Reserves in India. The Nallamalai Hills, while a significant geographical feature, are not currently designated as a Biosphere Reserve.  Agasthyamala Biosphere Reserve is located in the southern Western Ghats, Agasthyamala Biosphere Reserve spans 3,500 sq. km across Kerala and Tamil Nadu. Recognized by UNESCO in 2016, it harbors tropical forests, 2,254 plant species (405 endemic), and rare fauna like the Nilgiri Tahr and Asian Elephant. It includes Neyyar, Peppara, and Shendurney Wildlife Sanctuaries and Kalakad Mundanthurai Tiger Reserve.  Nilgiri Biosphere Reserve is India’s first biosphere reserve (1986), Nilgiri spans 5,520 sq. km acr","PW-0335":"Kochi receives the highest rainfall (~3000 mm) due to the Southwest Monsoon and its proximity to the Western Ghats, making it one of the wettest cities in India. Kolkata fol- lows with around 1600 mm of rainfall, heavily influenced by the Bay of Bengal branch of the monsoon, with most rain occurring between June and September. Patna, with approximately 1200 mm of annual rainfall, experiences moderate monsoon rains, though lesser than Kolkata. Delhi, receiving around 800 mm of rainfall, has a semi-arid climate, with monsoon rains but signifi- cantly lower precipitation than the other cities. Thus, the correct sequence in decreasing order of rainfall is Kochi–Kolkata–Patna–Delhi. 284","PW-0336":"Statement 1 is incorrect : Silent Valley National Park is part of the Nilgiri Biosphere Reserve and is located in Ker- ala’s Western Ghats. It is not situated in the Nallamalai range. The park is known for its untouched tropical rainforest, rich bio- diversity, and ecological importance. It is home to rare species like the lion-tailed macaque, Nilgiri langur, and Malabar gi- ant squirrel. The park also has 960 plant species and 170 bird species. In the 1970s, the “Save Silent Valley” movement helped protect it. This movement stopped a hydroelectric project that threatened the park’s ecosystem. Silent Valley was declared a na- tional park in 1984. Statement 2 is correct : The Pathrakkadavu Hydro Electric Project was proposed near the Silent Valley National Park. This proposal sparked significant environmental concerns and debate due to the potential impact on the park’s fragile ecosystem. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 408 Statement 3 is correct : The Kunthi River, originating from the Anginda peak in the Silent Valley National Park, Kerala, is a tributary of the Bharathapuzha River. Known for ","PW-0337":"Option 1 is correct : Champaner-Pavagadh Archaeolog- ical Park is located in Gujarat. This UNESCO World Heritage Site features a blend of Hindu and Islamic architecture, including temples, mosques, and water installations. It is renowned for the Kalika Mata Temple and its 16th-century pre-Mughal city remains. Option 2 is correct : Chhatrapati Shivaji Terminus, Mumbai is a UNESCO World Heritage Site since 2004, this Victorian Gothic Revival railway station blends British and Indian architec- tural styles. Built in 1887, it is a bustling hub and an iconic sym- bol of Mumbai’s heritage. Option 3 is correct : Mamallapuram (Mahabalipuram) is situ- ated in Tamil Nadu. This UNESCO site showcases 7th-8th centu- ry Pallava dynasty rock-cut temples, monolithic structures, and bas-relief sculptures like Arjuna’s Penance. The Shore Temple is its most prominent landmark. Option 4 is correct : Sun Temple (Konark Temple) was built in the 13th century in Odisha. The Konark Sun Temple is designed as Surya’s chariot with intricately carved wheels and horses. This UNESCO site is a masterpiece of Kaling","PW-0338":"Statement 1 is correct : Damodar Valley Corporation (DVC) was established in 1948, making it India’s first multipurpose river valley project after independence. Operating in West Ben- gal and Jharkhand, it focuses on flood control, irrigation, hydro- power generation, and industrial water supply. DVC manages four major dams (Tilaiya, Konar, Maithon, Panchet) and the Durgapur Barrage. It supports agriculture, industrial develop- ment, and electricity distribution across eight states. Inspired by the Tennessee Valley Authority (USA), DVC plays a crucial role in regional development and environmental management. Statement 2 is correct : The DVC’s infrastructure includes both thermal and gas power stations, in addition to hydroelectric power plants. The DVC has a significant number of coal-based thermal power stations. Some of the major ones include :  Mejia Thermal Power Station (West Bengal)  Bokaro Thermal Power Station (Jharkhand)  Chandrapura Thermal Power Station (Jharkhand)  Durgapur Steel Thermal Power Station (West Bengal) Maithon Gas Turbine Station is a gas-based thermal p","PW-0339":"Statement 1 is incorrect : Andhra Pradesh does not have the longest coastline in India. Gujarat has the longest coast- line among Indian states, stretching approximately 1214 km. Andhra Pradesh ranks second among states with a coastline of around 972 km. Geography 409 When considering both states and Union Territories, Gujarat has the longest coastline among the states, followed by Andhra Pradesh, Tamil Nadu (~1,076 km), and Maharashtra (~720 km). However, the Union Territory of Andaman and Nicobar Islands has the longest coastline overall, spanning about 1,962 km. Statement 2 is incorrect : As of 2004, Maharashtra had the highest number of airports in India, not Gujarat. It included major airports like Mumbai (Chhatrapati Shivaji International Airport), Pune, Nagpur, and others, along with several smaller domestic airports. Even today Gujarat does not have the highest number of airports in India. While Gujarat has a good number of airports, Uttar Pradesh, has the most. The number of airports can also fluc- tuate with new airports being built. Currently, Uttar Pradesh has the highest","PW-0340":"","PW-0341":"","PW-0342":"Assertion (A) is false : Mangalore, being a coastal city on the western coast of India, receives significantly more rain- fall than Bangalore. Coastal areas in this region are directly im- pacted by the southwest monsoon. Reason (R) is true : Bangalore does receive rainfall from both the southwest and northeast monsoons. However, the amount of rainfall from the northeast monsoon is relatively small, and the rainfall from the southwest monsoon is also less compared to coastal areas like Mangalore. While the reason is true, it does not explain why Bangalore would have more rainfall than Mangalore; in fact, the opposite is the case. Thus, Assertion (A) is false but Reason (R) is true. 293","PW-0343":"","PW-0344":"Option (b) is correct : The descending order of the lengths of the rivers is as follows : Godavari River : The total length is 1,465 km. It is the sec- ond-longest river in India after the Ganges and flows eastward from its origin in Trimbakeshwar, Maharashtra, to the Bay of Bengal. Narmada River : The total length is 1,312 km. It originates from the Amarkantak Plateau in Madhya Pradesh and flows west- ward into the Arabian Sea through the Gulf of Khambhat. Mahanadi River : The total length is approximately 851 km. It originates from the highlands of Chhattisgarh and flows east- ward into the Bay of Bengal. Tapi (Tapti) River : The total length is about 724 km. It origi- nates from the Satpura ranges in Madhya Pradesh and flows westward into the Arabian Sea. Therefore, the correct sequence of rivers in the descending order of their length is Godavari – Narmada – Mahanadi – Tapi. IMPORTANT INDIAN RIVERS (Lengths in KM) Name Length(Kms) Mouth Ganga 2.525 Bay of Bengal (BoB) Godavari 1.465 BoB Krishna 1.400 BoB Narmada 1.313 Arabian Sea Yamuna 1.211 BoB Indus 1.114 (3180) Arabian Sea Br","PW-0345":"Nanda Devi is the second-highest mountain in India and is lo- cated in the Kumaon Himalayas in the state of Uttarakhand. It is part of the Greater Himalayas and is renowned for its chal- lenging climbing routes and stunning natural beauty. Geography 411 Indus River Punjab Himalaya Kumaon Himalay Satluj River Kali River Teesta River Dihang River Kailash Range Ladakh Zaskar Karakoram Nepal Himalay Assam Himalay 296","PW-0346":"","PW-0347":"Area of the states in the options given are :  Gujarat : 196,024 square kilometers  Karnataka : 191,791 square kilometers  Andhra Pradesh : 160,205 square kilometers  Tamil Nadu : 130,058 square kilometers Therefore Tamil Nadu is the smallest among the four states. India covers an area of 3.287 million square kilometers (2.4% of the world’s land surface area), making it the sev- enth-largest country in the world by land area. As of now, In- dia is divided into 28 States and 8 Union Territories. Sequence of states in India area wise in descending order : Ra- jasthan > Madhya Pradesh > Maharashtra > Uttar Pradesh > Gujarat > Karnataka > Andhra Pradesh > Odisha > Chhat- tisgarh > Tamil Nadu > Telangana > Bihar > West Bengal > Arunachal Pradesh > Jharkhand > Assam > Himachal Pradesh > Uttarakhand > Punjab > Haryana > Kerala > Meghalaya > Ma- nipur > Nagaland > Tripura > Mizoram > Sikkim > Goa. The largest UT is Jammu and Kashmir while the smallest is the Lakshadweep. 299","PW-0348":"In India, The Tropic of Cancer (23.5° N) passes through 8 Indian states : Gujarat, Rajasthan, Madhya Pradesh, Chhat- tisgarh, Jharkhand, West Bengal, Tripura and Mizoram. Location of the given cities in comparison to the Tropic of Cancer is the following : Delhi: 28.7041° N Jodhpur: 26.2389° N Tropic of Cancer: 23.5° N Kolkata: 22.5726° N Nagpur: 21.1458° N Thus, Kolkata is nearest to the Tropic of Cancer. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 412 Other cities near to the Tropic of Cancer :  Udaipur (Rajasthan): 24.5854° N.  Agartala (Tripura): 23.8315° N.  Aizawl (Mizoram): 23.7271° N.  Ranchi (Jharkhand): 23.3441° N.  Bhopal (Madhya Pradesh): 23.2599° N.  Gandhinagar (Gujarat): 23.2156° N.  Jabalpur (Madhya Pradesh): 23.1815° N.  Kolkata (West Bengal): 22.5726° N. The latitude of the Tropic of Cancer is the imaginary circle at approximately 23.5° N. It marks the northernmost point where the Sun appears directly overhead at noon. This occurs during the June solstice (around June 21), when the Northern Hemisphere is tilted toward the Sun. The Tropic of Cancer passes through 17 countries, incl","PW-0349":"","PW-0350":"The climatic data provided matches the conditions of Chennai, which has a tropical wet and dry climate. Chennai experiences an average annual temperature of around 26°C, with a moderate annual temperature range of about 9°C due to its coastal location. The average annual rainfall of 120-140 cm is typical of Chennai, primarily influenced by the Northeast Monsoon. Other loca- tions do not fit this profile: Allahabad and Kolkata have larger temperature ranges due to their continental climates, while Cherrapunji receives significantly higher rainfall, averaging over 450 cm annually. Hence, the station is most likely Chennai.  Moderation Effect of coasts : The presence of a sea reduces the annual range of temperature due to the high specific heat capacity of water, which absorbs and releases heat more slowly than land. This moderating effect prevents extreme temperature variations, leading to smaller differences between summer and winter temperatures in coastal areas.  Continentality : It refers to the influence of a location’s distance from the sea on its climate. Inland areas experien","PW-0351":"It is a migratory species that travels thousands of miles from South America and other regions to nest on the beaches of Orissa. The Olive Ridley turtles are known for their mass nesting events, called ‘arribadas’, where thousands of turtles come ashore to lay eggs. In India, the state of Orissa ( now Odisha ) is particularly famous for being a nesting ground for these turtles. The Olive Ridley turtle is listed as Vulnerable by the IUCN Red List due to threats like habitat destruction, pollution, fishing nets, and climate change. 303","PW-0352":"","PW-0353":"The Mekong-Ganga Cooperation (MGC) is a regional initiative aimed at enhancing cultural, economic, and tourism ties among member countries. It was launched in 2000 and includes six countries: India, Thailand, Myanmar, Cambodia, Laos, and Vietnam. The project focuses on areas such as tourism, educa- tion, culture, and transportation, rather than irrigation, hydro- electric power, or defense. 307","PW-0354":"Assertion (A) is true : Anticyclonic conditions are character- ized by high atmospheric pressure and sinking air, which leads to clear skies and low temperatures. These conditions are com- mon in winter, especially in northern India after a cyclonic rain from western disturbances. Reason (R) is true : Winter rainfall in northern India, such as the Western Disturbances, is the result of cyclonic (low-pressure) conditions. However, this rain also creates conditions of anti- cyclonic activity. R correctly explains A : Cyclonic activities beyond the Indian border bring rain to India in winter. This creates a high Pressure area with light winds radiating outwards. This wind creates anti- cyclonic activity in northern India. Thus, Reason (R) is the correct explanation of Assertion (A). UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 414  Anticyclone Formation : Anticyclones are centers of high pressure. They are surrounded by closed isobars having decreasing pressure outward. The circulation is from central high pressure towards the periphery in such a way that air blows outwards in a clockwise direction in the Nor","PW-0355":"Statement 1 is correct : As of 2001, India’s total in- stalled power generation capacity was approximately 95,000 MW, according to reports from the Central Electricity Author- ity (CEA). This included contributions from thermal, hydroelec- tric, nuclear, and renewable energy sources. As of June 2023-24, the installed capacity has risen to around 146,190 MW. Statement 2 is incorrect : As of 2001 and even today, nuclear power contributes only around 1-3% (not 15%) of the total electricity generation. The installed nuclear capacity is approx- imately 7,480 MW, which is a minor fraction of the total energy mix. India’s nuclear expansion has been slow due to regulatory challenges, safety concerns, and the high cost of nuclear plants. Statement 3 is incorrect : Hydroelectricity accounted for about 25-30% of India’s electricity generation in 2001, not 40%. While hydroelectricity was once a dominant source of power in India, its share has been gradually declining as thermal and renew- able energy sources expanded. Currently, hydroelectricity ac- counts for only about 10-15% of India’s total ","PW-0356":"The Aravalli Range, one of the world’s oldest mountain systems, is estimated to be around 670 million years old based on geological studies and radiometric dating techniques. Some re- searchers even suggest its origins could date back further, making it as old as 2-4 billion years, but its prominent development and erosion cycles place its approximate age at 670 million years. The Aravalli Range, formed during the Proterozoic Era through tectonic collisions that created the Aravalli-Delhi Fold Belt, has been eroded over millions of years into its pres- ent low-lying form. Stretching approximately 700 km across Rajasthan, Haryana, Delhi, and Gujarat, the range is geolog- ically rich, with metamorphic and igneous rocks containing valuable minerals like lead, zinc, marble, and mica. Ecologically, it serves as a biodiversity hotspot and acts as a natural barrier against the spread of the Thar Desert. Cul- turally, the Aravallis house ancient forts, temples, and land- marks such as Mount Abu and the Dilwara Temples, mak- ing them historically and environmentally significant. 310","PW-0357":"The first sunrise of the new millennium (1 January 2000) in India was observed at the 92°30’ E meridian in Arunachal Pradesh, the country’s easternmost region. Located near the Myanmar border, this was the first point in India to receive sun- light as the millennium began. While countries like New Zealand saw it earlier due to their proximity to the International Date Line, within India, 92°30’ E, the nation’s easternmost meridian amongst the given options, marked the dawn of the new era, highlighting its significance as the first place in the country to witness sunrise. 312","PW-0358":"Statement 1 is correct : Tides play a significant role in both navigation and fishing activities. Tides help ships navigate shallow waters by increasing water depth during high tide. They also influence fishing, as certain fish species move with tidal cur- rents, making them easier to catch. Statement 2 is correct : High tides increase the water level in harbors, which is essential for larger ships to enter or leave safe- ly. Without the rise in water levels brought about by tides, large ships might find it difficult to dock or leave the harbor, as they need sufficient water depth to avoid grounding. Statement 3 is correct : The ebb and flow of tidal waters help to flush out silt, sand, and other debris from the harbor area. This natural process reduces the risk of siltation, ensuring that ports and harbors remain navigable by preventing the accumulation of sediments that could otherwise block ships. Statement 4 is correct : Both Kandla Port (in Gujarat) and Diamond Harbour (near Kolkata) are tidal ports, meaning they are influenced by tidal movements. The activities at these ports d","PW-0359":"Assertion (A) is true : The frequency of floods in the north Indian plains has indeed risen in recent decades. This can be attributed to a combination of factors:  Climate Change: With global warming, the frequency and intensity of rainfall events have increased. In many parts of India, especially in the north, monsoon rains have become more unpredictable, leading to sudden heavy downpours that overwhelm the drainage systems and flood the plains.  Urbanization and Poor Drainage Systems: As more urban areas are developed, the natural landscape changes. Cities with poor drainage systems cannot handle heavy rainfall, leading to waterlogging and flooding.  Deforestation: Deforestation, particularly in the catchment areas of rivers, reduces the land’s ability to absorb rainfall. The lack of tree cover and vegetation increases surface runoff, which can rapidly flow into rivers and cause them to overflow.  River Management Issues: Rivers like the Ganges and Brahmaputra are heavily managed with embankments, dams, and other infrastructure. However, many of these structures have not been p","PW-0360":"The Indian elephant is the largest population of the Asian elephant species, and India is home to about 60-70% of the total population of Asian elephants. The passage refers to the distribution of the population in north-west India (Dehradun, Bijnor), western Ghats (Karnataka, Kerala, Tamil Nadu), central India (Southern Bihar, Orissa), and the eastern parts (Assam, North Bengal), all of which are areas where elephants are found in the wild. Elephants predominantly inhabit moist deciduous forests, dry thorn forests, and grasslands, which align with the habitats described. Distinctive Features :  They have smaller ears compared to their African counterparts.  Their trunks are highly sensitive and versatile, used for feeding, drinking, bathing, and social interactions.  Adult males typically weigh up to 5,000 kg and stand about 2.5 to 3 meters tall at the shoulder.  Males have large tusks, although not all elephants have visible tusks (especially females). 315","PW-0361":"India’s National Forest Policy (1988) recommends that at least 33% of the total geographical area of the country should be under forest cover to maintain proper ecological balance. Forests play a crucial role in maintaining the environment by preventing soil erosion, conserving water, supporting biodiversity, and reg- ulating the climate. Currently, India’s forest cover is around 24% of its total geo- graphical area, according to the Forest Survey of India (FSI) report. While the target of 33% forest cover is still not fully achieved, ongoing afforestation and conservation programs aim to increase the forest cover to meet this goal. 316","PW-0362":"","PW-0363":"","PW-0364":"A is matched with 3 : The Deccan Traps are one of the largest volcanic provinces in the world, formed due to massive volcanic eruptions during the late Cretaceous and early Eocene periods (about 66 million years ago). These lava flows cover a vast part of western and central India. B is matched with 1 : The Western Ghats, that include Sahyadri Hills, are part of the Late Cenozoic formations, meaning they formed relatively recently in geological history. These mountains are the result of faulting and uplift processes. C is matched with 2 : The Aravalli Range is one of the oldest mountain ranges in the world, dating back to the Pre-Cambri- an era . It is heavily eroded and was once part of a much larger mountain system. D is matched with 5 : The river valleys of the Narmada and Tapi belong to the Pleistocene era (about 2.5 million to 11,700 years ago). They have alluvial deposits from recent geological periods due to sedimentation from river action. 323","PW-0365":"The 18°C January isotherm is used as the dividing line between the tropical and subtropical zones in India. This isotherm runs roughly along the Tropic of Cancer (23.5°N latitude) and helps distinguish the warmer tropical climate of southern India from the relatively cooler subtropical climate of northern India. Areas south of the 18°C isotherm (cover- ing most of Peninsular India) experience tropical climate with higher temperatures, minimal winter, and a distinct mon- soon pattern. Areas north of the 18°C isotherm (including northern states like Punjab, Haryana, and parts of Uttar Pradesh) fall under the subtropical zone, experiencing cooler winters and greater temperature variations between seasons. 324","PW-0366":"The Alamatti Dam is constructed on the Krishna Riv- er in Karnataka. It is a part of the Upper Krishna Irrigation Project and is located in Bagalkot district. The dam plays a cru- cial role in irrigation, hydroelectric power generation, and water management in Karnataka. It is one of the largest reservoirs in South India and helps regulate the flow of the Krishna River. 325","PW-0367":"The Farakka Barrage was constructed across the Gan- ga River in West Bengal with the aim of diverting water to the Hooghly River to ensure that the Kolkata Port remains naviga- ble. The Farakka Feeder Canal is responsible for carrying the diverted water into the Hooghly River. Canal Capacity : The canal has a designed carrying capacity of 40,000 cusecs, which is the amount of water it can carry per second. This is an important feature of the Farakka Barrage, as it ensures the flow of sufficient water into the Hooghly River to prevent silting and to support the navigation in Kolkata’s port. 326","PW-0368":"","PW-0369":"","PW-0370":"The term ‘De-notified Tribes’ (DNTs) refers to com- munities that were previously classified as ‘Criminal Tribes’ under the Criminal Tribes Act (CTA) of 1871 during British rule in India. The British labeled certain nomadic and semi-no- madic tribes as ‘criminal’ by birth based on their traditional livelihoods, often involving hunting, trading, or performing arts. After India’s independence, the Criminal Tribes Act was re- pealed in 1952, and these communities were ‘de-notified’, meaning they were no longer considered criminal by default. However, despite this legal change, many Denotified Tribes (DNTs) and Nomadic Tribes (NTs) continue to face social stig- ma, discrimination, and lack of formal recognition. 330","PW-0371":" Kishenganga : This river flows through the Kashmir Valley, which is located in the northernmost region of India. Therefore, it should be placed first.  Ganga : The Ganga originates in the Himalayas, in Uttarakhand, flowing through the northern plains. It is the second river in the north-south direction.  Wainganga: The Wainganga originates in the Satpura Range of Madhya Pradesh and flows through the central region of India. So it comes next.  Penganga: The Penganga flows through Maharashtra and Telangana, which places it in the southernmost position of these rivers. 8. LOCATION/MAP BASED : INDIAN GEOGRAPHY 331","PW-0372":"The Ganga River originates from the Gangotri Gla- cier in the Himalayas and flows into the Bay of Bengal. It drains about one-fourth of India’s land area and supports hundreds of millions of people. The river generally flows from northwest to southeast. The Yamuna River passes through the Delhi region and follows a southeastward path, roughly parallel to the Ganges. It eventu- ally joins the Ganges near Prayagraj (Allahabad). Option (b) is correct : The main left-bank tributaries of the Ganga are (from west to east)- in the order of joining : 1. Ramganga 2. Gomati 3. Ghaghara 4. Gandak 5. Kosi The major Right bank tributaries are Yamuna, Son, Punpun, Damodar, and Ajay. Among these, Yamuna is the largest and most significant. The Ganges River is formed at Devprayag in Uttarakhand, where the Alaknanda and Bhagirathi rivers meet. Among them, Bhagirathi is considered the main source of the Ganges due to its mythological significance, while Alaknanda is hydrological- ly larger. Other important tributaries in the upper course in- clude the Mandakini, Dhauliganga, and Pindar rivers. 332","PW-0373":"Statement 1 is incorrect: The Amarkantak Hills are located at the confluence of the Vindhya and Satpura Rang- es, not the Sahyadri Range. It is a plateau region in Madhya Pradesh where the Vindhya and Satpura Ranges meet, along with the Maikal Hills. The Sahyadri Range is another name for the Western Ghats which are located along the western coast of India located further south. Statement 2 is incorrect: Biligirirangan Hills belong to the Eastern Ghats mountain range rather than the Satpura Range. The BR Hills serve as an ecological bridge between the Western and Eastern Ghats, providing a corridor for wildlife movement. Statement 3 is incorrect: The Seshachalam Hills are part of the Eastern Ghats located in Andhra Pradesh, and are not related to the Western Ghats. The Seshachalam Hills are known for the Sri Venkateswara National Park and the Tirumala Temple. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 420 333","PW-0374":"Statement 1 is correct : Jhelum River passes through Wular Lake and the lake controls its flow and water discharge . It is one of the largest freshwater lakes of Asia and is located in Bandipora district in Jammu and Kashmir. Statement 2 is incorrect : The Kolleru Lake is fed directly by water from the seasonal Budameru and Tammileru streams and not the Krishna River. It is indirectly connected to the Krishna and Godavari systems by drains and channels. Kolleru Bird Sanctuary serves as a habitat for migratory birds. Statement 3 is incorrect: Kanwar Jheel/Kabar Taal is a fresh- water residual oxbow lake formed due to the meandering of Burhi Gandak River, a tributary of Ganga(not Gandak Riv- er). It is located in Begusarai, Bihar. The lake is a significant bio- diversity hotspot, particularly for migratory birds, and has been designated as a Ramsar site. 334","PW-0375":"The Siachen Glacier lies to the north of the Nubra Val- ley, which is situated in the northern part of the Ladakh region of India. It is located in the Karakoram Range in the northernmost part of the Indian subcontinent. It is positioned in the region claimed by both India and Pakistan and is the longest glacier in the world outside the polar regions, spanning approximately 76 kilometers (47 miles).The Nubra Valley, located at the confluence of the Shyok and Nubra Rivers, is a key geographical feature in the vicinity of the Siachen Glacier. It is also the world’s highest battlefield. 335","PW-0376":"Pair 1 is correctly matched: Pandharpur is a famous pilgrimage town in Maharashtra and is located on the banks of the Chandrabhaga River. It is renowned for the Vitthal Temple which is dedicated to Lord Vitthal (a form of Lord Vishnu). It is one of the most visited pilgrimage sites in Maharashtra. During the annual Ashadhi Ekadashi festival, thousands of devotees take a holy dip in the Chandrabhaga River. Pair 2 is correctly matched: Tiruchirappalli is an Indian city of Tamil Nadu on the banks of the Cauvery River. The city is his- torically and culturally significant with landmarks such as the Sri Ranganathaswamy Temple and Rock Fort Temple. Pair 3 is incorrectly matched: Hampi was the capital of the Vijayanagara kingdom and is located on the bank of the Tung- abhadra River in present state of Karnataka. The Malaprabha River is a separate river that originates in the Western Ghats and flows through the Belagavi district of Karnataka. It is a tributary of the Krishna River. 336","PW-0377":"Bengaluru located at 77.5946° E is approximately 0.378 degrees east of Delhi is closest to Delhi. Longitude of In- dian Cities:  The longitude of Delhi is 77.216721°E  The longitude of Bangalore is 77.59450 E.  The longitude of Nagpur is 79.0888° E.  The longitude of Pune is 73.8474” E. 337","PW-0378":"","PW-0379":"Pair 1 is incorrectly matched : Bodhgaya is located in the Magadh region of Bihar not Baghelkhand (which is in Madhya Pradesh and parts of Uttar Pradesh). It is one of the ho- liest Buddhist sites in the world. It is where Gautama Buddha attained enlightenment under the Bodhi tree around 5th-6th century BCE. The Mahabodhi Temple, a UNESCO World Heri- tage Site, is a major pilgrimage center for Buddhists. The Great Buddha Statue, monasteries built by Buddhist communities worldwide, and the annual Kalachakra festival add to its spiri- tual significance. Pair 2 is correctly matched : Khajuraho is in Madhya Pradesh, part of the Bundelkhand region, which spans Uttar Pradesh and Madhya Pradesh. It is famous for its Hindu and Jain tem- ples, built between the 10th-12th centuries by the Chandela dynasty. The temples are known for their intricate carvings and erotic sculptures which symbolizes Kama (desire) as one of the four goals of life (Purusharthas) in Hindu philosophy. Important temples include Kandariya Mahadev, Lakshmana, Vishwanath, and Parshvanath Jain Temple. Pair 3 is incorrectly ","PW-0380":"The Brahmaputra River, a major transboundary riv- er in South Asia, is fed by numerous tributaries that enhance its volume and sustain the diverse ecosystems along its course. the Dibang, Kameng, and Lohit rivers are important tributaries of Brahmaputra River. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 422 Option (d) is correct :  The Dibang River also known as the Sikang, originates in the Mishmi Hills of Arunachal Pradesh, India. It traverses through the rugged terrains of Arunachal Pradesh, carving out deep gorges and valleys. The Dibang merges with the Lohit River near the town of Sadiya in Assam. Together they join the main channel of the Brahmaputra River.  The Kameng River originates from a glacial lake beneath the Gori Chen mountain in the Tawang district of Arunachal Pradesh. The river flows through the Bhalukpong circle of West Kameng district in Arunachal Pradesh and then through the Sonitpur district of Assam. It joins the Brahmaputra River near the town of Tezpur in Assam.  The Lohit River originate in the Zayü County of the Tibet Autonomous Region, China. Upon entering India in Arunachal ","PW-0381":"Pair 1 is correctly matched: Srisailam is a famous pil- grimage site located in the Nallamala Hills of Andhra Pradesh. It is home to the Mallikarjuna Jyotirlinga Temple, one of the 12 Jyotirlingas of Lord Shiva. They are a significant range in south- ern India, located along the border of Andhra Pradesh and Tel- angana. The Srisailam Sanctuary is also located in this region which is known for its rich biodiversity and the Srisailam Dam on the Krishna River. Geography 423 Pair 2 is incorrectly matched : Omkareshwar is situated on the Mandhata hills in Madhya Pradesh (ancient name: Shivpuri). The name “Omkareshwar” comes from the way the River Narmada flows here as it circles the Mandhata hill in the shape of a “Om.” Omkareshwar is one of Shiva’s 12 cherished Jyotirlinga shrines. Pair 3 is incorrectly matched: Pushkar is known for the Push- kar Lake and the Brahma Temple. It is located in the Aravalli Range in Rajasthan, not the Mahadeo Hills. Pushkar is a major pilgrimage site associated with the worship of Lord Brahma. The Mahadeo Hills which are part of the Satpura Range are located","PW-0382":"India has a vast network of national highways, with a total length of 1,46,195 kilometers as per Annual Report 2024- 25 of Ministry of Road Transport and Highways. Pair 1 is incorrectly matched: : NH4 (National Highway 4) was one of the major national highways in India before the renumbering of highways in 2010. After renumbering, NH4 was largely replaced by NH48. It connected Mumbai to Chennai via Pune, Bengaluru, and other cities. It did not connect Chennai and Hyderabad. Pair 2 is incorrectly matched: : NH6 (National Highway 6) did not connect Mumbai and Kolkata directly. After renumbering, it was largely replaced by NH53 and NH16. Historically it con- nected Surat (Gujarat) to Kolkata, passing through states like Maharashtra, Chhattisgarh, and Odisha. Pair 3 is incorrectly matched: : The old NH 15 ran from Pathan- kot in Punjab to Samakhiali in Gujarat, passing through cit- ies like Bikaner and Jaisalmer in Rajasthan. It did not connect Ahmedabad and Jodhpur. 344","PW-0383":"Option 1 is incorrect : The Barak River originates in the Manipur Hills near the border of Nagaland at an altitude of about 3,015 meters. It primarily flows through Manipur, Mizoram, Nagaland, and Assam before entering Bangladesh. Option 2 is correct : The Lohit River originates in the Zayü County of Tibet and enters India through Arunachal Pradesh. It flows through the Mishmi Hills before joining the Brahmapu- tra River. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 424 Option 3 is correct : The Subansiri River, often referred to as the “Gold River”, originates in the Tibetan Himalayas and en- ters India via the Miri Hills in Arunachal Pradesh. It eventually merges with the Brahmaputra River. 347","PW-0384":"Pair 1 is incorrectly matched: The Cardamom Hills are part of the Western Ghats, spanning Kerala and Tamil Nadu. It is named after the cardamom spice that is abundantly cultivated here. These hills are famous for their spice planta- tions, including pepper and coffee. It is home to Periyar Wild- life Sanctuary, known for its rich biodiversity and tiger reserve. The Coromandel Coast is along the Bay of Bengal on the east- ern coast of India Pair 2 is incorrectly matched: The Kaimur Hills are an exten- sion of the Vindhya Range and spread across Madhya Pradesh, Bihar, Jharkhand, and Uttar Pradesh. These hills are known for prehistoric rock paintings and ancient caves, making them an important archaeological site. The region contains several waterfalls and plateaus and plays a crucial role in rainwater retention for local rivers. The Konkan Coast lies along the Ara- bian Sea, covering Maharashtra, Goa, and Karnataka, while the Kaimur Hills are located deep inland Pair 3 is correctly matched : The Mahadeo Hills are part of the Satpura Range in Madhya Pradesh. These hills are known for th","PW-0385":"Pair 1 is correctly matched: Nokrek Biosphere Re- serve is located in the Garo Hills district of Meghalaya. The biosphere reserve’s name comes from Nokrek Hill, the highest peak of the Garo Hills. It was designated a UNESCO biosphere reserve in 2009 and is home to the red panda and a rich va- riety of flora and fauna. The reserve is also a significant part of the Western Meghalaya Elephant Landscape and contains the Nokrek National Park. Pair 2 is incorrectly matched: The Loktak Lake is a freshwater lake in Manipur and is the largest freshwater lake in Northeast India. It is not located in the Barail Range, which is a mountain range in Assam and Nagaland. It is well-known for the phumdis that float above it. Keibul Lamjao National Park, the only floating national park in the world is located in this lake. Pair 3 is incorrectly matched: : Namdapha National Park is sit- uated in the Changlang district of Arunachal Pradesh. It is part of the Patkai Range, not the Dafla Hills. The Noa Dihing River runs east to west through the national park. The Dafla Hills are located on the Arunachal P","PW-0386":"The river originating in Jharkhand referred to here is the Brahmani River. It originates as the Koel River in Jharkhand and is later called the Brahmani in Odisha. River originating in Odishas is the Baitarani River which originates in the Ke- onjhar district of Odisha. The Brahmani and Baitarani rivers merge at a place called Dhamra, near the Bay of Bengal forming a large delta before flowing into the sea. Bhitarkanika National Park is located in the estuarine re- gion formed by the merging of the Brahmani and Baitarani rivers. It is located in the Kendrapara district of Odisha. It is a unique ecosystem of mangroves, wetlands, and tidal rivers. It is one of India’s most important wildlife sanctuaries and a Ramsar site (a wetland of international importance). It is home to saltwater crocodiles, Olive Ridley sea turtles, and a vari- ety of bird species. 350","PW-0387":"The Omkareshwar Project, a multi-purpose dam project, is located in the Khandwa district of Madhya Pradesh, India. This project utilizes the Narmada River, a ma- jor river system in central India, to achieve several key objectives such as:  A primary function is the generation of hydroelectric power, with a station capacity of 520 MW, contributing substantially to the regional energy supply.  The project is intended to provide irrigation to extensive agricultural lands, thereby increasing agricultural productivity and supporting local economies.  The Omkareshwar Project also plays a role in supplying water for domestic and industrial use, ensuring access to this vital resource. The dam itself is situated on the Narmada River, proximate to the town of Omkareshwar, a significant Hindu pilgrimage site. The town’s religious importance derives from the presence of the Omkareshwar Temple, dedicated to Lord Shiva. Geography 425 351","PW-0388":"India’s extensive coastline, stretching approximately 7,516 kilometers, is shared by nine diverse states, each contrib- uting unique characteristics to the nation’s maritime heritage.  Starting from the west: Gujarat boasts the longest coastline in India which dotted with numerous ports and playing a crucial role in maritime trade. Maharashtra’s coastline is home to the bustling metropolis of Mumbai, a major commercial and entertainment hub. Goa is renowned for its beautiful beaches and vibrant tourism industry. Karnataka’s coastline is significant for its port cities and coastal cuisine. Kerala is famed for its backwaters, lush greenery, and historical spice trade connections.  On the eastern coast: Tamil Nadu possesses a long coastline with important ports and cultural significance, including the historic city of Chennai. Andhra Pradesh which is located north of Tamil Nadu has a substantial coastline crucial for fishing and maritime activities. Odisha, known for its rich cultural heritage, also has a significant coastline vulnerable to cyclones. West Bengal features a coastline t","PW-0389":"","PW-0390":"Statement 1 is correct: The saltwater crocodile (Crocodylus porosus) is India’s largest reptile and is found in the mangroves and coastal waters of:  Andaman & Nicobar Islands (notably in North & Middle Andaman)  Bhitarkanika National Park, Odisha  Sundarbans, West Bengal  Mahanadi & Godavari estuaries They are apex predators inhabiting coastal areas, estuaries, riv- ers, and mangrove swamps. The Andaman and Nicobar Islands provide suitable habitats for these crocodiles. Bhitarkanika holds the record for the world’s largest saltwater crocodile, mea- suring 7.1 meters (23 feet) UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 426 Statement 2 is incorrect : Shrews are small mammals found in various parts of India, including the Western Ghats but they are not exclusive to the Malabar region. Tapirs are not found in India. They are native to Central and South America, as well as Southeast Asia (Malayan tapir). 355","PW-0391":"","PW-0392":" Chhattisgarh has significant deposits of bauxite, particularly in the Maikal Hills and the Surguja district. The mineral is found in is associated with lateritic formations. These bauxite deposits contribute to India’s aluminum industry.  Dolomite is a sedimentary rock composed primarily of calcium magnesium carbonate, is another mineral resource found in Chhattisgarh. It is found in the Bastar and Durg districts of Chhattisgarh. Dolomite is used in the steel industry, cement manufacturing, and as a source of magnesium. Dolomite is used in a range of industrial applications, including cement manufacturing, steelmaking, and as a fluxing agent.  Chhattisgarh is endowed with substantial deposits of iron ore, a crucial raw material for the steel industry. The state’s iron ore reserves are known for their quality and contribute significantly to India’s steel production capacity. Major deposits are found in the Bailadila range in the Dantewada district which is known for its high-grade hematite iron ore..  Chhattisgarh is one of the few states in India where tin ore is found in commer","PW-0393":"The Tehri Hydropower Complex is located on the Bhagirathi river. This complex features a towering earth and rock-fill dam, one of the world’s tallest. The project has also spurred regional development in Garhwal including a new town and improved infrastructure. Bhagirathi River is considered the primary source stream of the Ganges. It emerges from the Gan- gotri Glacier in Uttarakhand 358","PW-0394":"Pair 1 is incorrectly matched : Kapildhara Falls is l situated on the Narmada River located in the state of Madhya Pradesh, India. It is named after sage Kapila who is believed to have meditated here. Pair 2 is correctly matched : Jog Falls on Sharavathi River is located in Shivamogga district, Karnataka.. This impressive waterfall is formed by the Sharavathi River plunging down a deep gorge. It is also called “Gerusoppa Falls” or “Jogada Gundi”. Pair 3 is correctly matched: Shivasamudram Falls is another well-known waterfall in Karnataka, is correctly associated with the Cauvery River. This waterfall is not only a natural spectacle but also a source of hydroelectric power. 359","PW-0395":"Pair 1 is correctly matched: The Daman Ganga Ir- rigation Project is located in Gujarat. This project utilizes the waters of the Damanganga River which flows through both Gu- jarat and Maharashtra, to provide irrigation to agricultural lands in the region. This project is crucial for irrigation, drinking water, and industrial water supply in Gujarat and Dadra & Nagar Haveli. Pair 2 is correctly matched: The Girna Irrigation Project is situated in Maharashtra. This project harnesses the waters of the Girna River, a tributary of the Tapi River.The key compo- nent of the project is the Girna Dam, an earthfill dam constructed across the Girna River . The primary purpose of the Girna Irriga- tion Project is to provide irrigation to agricultural lands in the Nashik and Jalgaon districts of Maharashtra. The project helps to stabilize and increase agricultural production in this region. Pair 3 is correctly matched: Pamba River originates in the Western Ghats and flows through Pathanamthitta district, Ker- ala before emptying into the Vembanad Lake. The Pamba Irrigation Project was built for ","PW-0396":"The Tapovan and Vishnugarh hydroelectric projects are lo- cated in Chamoli district of Uttarakhand. These projects utilize the waters of the Dhauliganga River. The Tapovan-Vishnugarh project is a run-of-river scheme, meaning it harnesses the natural flow of the river without creating a large storage reservoir. Developed by NTPC Limited, a major power generation com- pany in India, the Tapovan-Vishnugarh project has a planned installed capacity of 520 MW. This capacity represents a sub- stantial contribution to the power generation capabilities of Ut- tarakhand and the nation. Run-of-river projects like this gen- erally have a smaller environmental footprint compared to large dam projects with vast reservoirs. 361","PW-0397":"The Bhoodan Movement (Land Gift Movement) was initiated by Acharya Vinoba Bhave in 1951. The move- ment began in Pochampalli, a village in the Nalgonda district of present-day Telangana (then part of Hyderabad State). The movement was inspired when landless farmers in Pochampalli requested land and local landlord Vedire Ramachandra Reddy donated 100 acres of land. This event sparked a nationwide movement, where landowners voluntarily donated land to landless peasants. Acharya Vinoba Bhave was a prominent Indian social re- former and spiritual leader, who played a pivotal role in the country’s post-independence era. He was deeply influenced by Mahatma Gandhi’s philosophy of non-violence and social justice and dedicated his life to working for the upliftment of the mar- ginalized and the establishment of a more equitable society. He is particularly renowned for initiating the Bhoodan Movement was a unique land reform initiative that aimed to redistribute land from wealthy landowners to landless peasants through vol- untary donations. 362","PW-0398":"The Stilwell Road, also known as the Ledo Road, was constructed during World War II. It was a crucial supply route for the Allied forces, connecting Ledo in Assam, India to Kunming in Yunnan province of China, via northern Myanmar. It was built to transport supplies to China after the Burma Road was cut off by the Japanese. Ledo was a railhead, a natural and logical starting point for the arduous overland route. The route traversed the formidable Patkai Range, with peaks reaching over 9,000 feet, and dense, often impenetrable jungles. The construction was primarily undertaken by American engineers and laborers with support from local workers. General Joseph Warren Stilwell, the namesake of the road. The Stilwell Road remains a powerful symbol of wartime cooperation and a re- minder of the complex geopolitical dynamics of the era. 363","PW-0399":"Option (d) is correct: Assertion (A) is false : Kali River (Kalinadi) flows westward, not eastward. It originates from Diggi village in Karnataka’s Western Ghats and drains into the Arabian Sea near Karwar, Karnataka. The river’s course is influenced by the Western Ghats, which cause many rivers in peninsular India to flow westward. Kali River is an important source of hydroelectric power, with several dams like Supa Dam built on it. Reason (R) is true: The Deccan Plateau is a vast elevated landform in peninsular India. It has a gradual eastward slope which makes most rivers in peninsular India (like the Goda- vari, Krishna, and Kaveri) flow eastward towards the Bay of Ben- gal. The Western Ghats form a natural barrier that causes some rivers, like the Kali, Sharavathi, and Netravati, to flow westward into the Arabian Sea. 364","PW-0400":"National Highway 53, formerly known as NH 6, is a major east-west artery in India’s National Highway network. It originates in Hazira, Gujarat, on the western coast and ter- minates in Kolkata, West Bengal, on the eastern coast. This extensive route traverses a significant swathe of central India, connecting diverse regions and facilitating the movement of peo- ple and goods across the country. The highway runs through six states: Gujarat, Maharashtra, Chhattisgarh, Odisha, Jharkhand, and West Bengal. This broad coverage underscores its importance as a vital link between different parts of the na- tion. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 428 365","PW-0401":"Statement 1 is incorrect : ​Balaghat (Madhya Pradesh) is not known for diamond mines. It is famous for its copper deposits and manganese reserves. The largest copper mines in India, operated by Hindustan Copper Limited (HCL), are located here. Balaghat is famous for its manganese deposits. Statement 2 is incorrect : ​Majhgawan (Panna, Madhya Pradesh) is not known for manganese. It is famous for its di- amond mines. It is operated by National Mineral Development Corporation (NMDC). 366","PW-0402":"The Damodar River originates in the Chota Nagpur Plateau. It flows eastward through Jharkhand and West Ben- gal before joining the Hooghly River, a distributary of the Ganges. It is known as the “Sorrow of Bengal” due to its frequent flooding in the past. The Damodar River basin is heavily indus- trialized and densely populated, making it a crucial river for the region, though it also faces significant environmental challenges. Option (b) is incorrect : Mahanadi originates in the highlands of the Sihawa district in the state of Chhattisgarh. It flows generally eastward through Chhattisgarh and Odisha before emptying into the Bay of Bengal. The Hirakud Dam is India’s longest earthen dam which is built on this river. Option (c) is correct: The Narmada River’s source is in the Amarkantak hills in the Anuppur district of Madhya Pradesh. Amarkantak is a significant pilgrimage site and a biodi- versity hotspot. The Narmada flows westward through Madhya Pradesh, Gujarat, and Maharashtra before emptying into the Arabian Sea. Option (d) is incorrect : The Tapi River originates in the Mul- tai","PW-0403":"The approximate location coordinates for each city:  Hyderabad: 17.4065° N, 78.4772° E  Bhopal: 23.2599° N, 77.4126° E  Lucknow: 26.8467° N, 80.9462° E  Bengaluru (Bangalore): 12.9716° N, 77.5946° E As Lucknow has the highest longitude value, making it the most eastwardly located city among the four. 368","PW-0404":"","PW-0405":"A is correctly matched with 2: BALCO’s primary op- erations are centered in Korba, Chhattisgarh. BALCO operates a large aluminum smelter and alumina refinery in Korba. The availability of coal in the region is a key factor in BALCO’s opera- tions, as it provides the energy needed for aluminum production. B is correctly matched with 4: HINDALCO (Hindalco Indus- tries Limited) ahas a significant presence in Renukoot, Ut- tar Pradesh. Renukoot is known for its aluminum industry, and HINDALCO’s operations are a major employer in the area. HIN- DALCO’s Renukoot facility includes an aluminum smelter and a captive power plant. C is correctly matched with 1: Indian Aluminium Company (INDAL) had operations in Hirakud, Odisha. Hirakud is known for the Hirakud Dam, a major dam on the Mahanadi River. The availability of hydroelectric power from the dam was a key factor in the establishment of INDAL’s aluminum smelter in Hirakud. D is correctly matched with 3: NALCO (National Aluminium Company) has operations in Koraput, Odisha. Koraput is rich in bauxite deposits, the primary raw material for al","PW-0406":"","PW-0407":"Guru Shikhar, literally translated as the ‘peak of the guru’’ stands as the highest point of the Aravalli Range in the state of Rajasthan, India. Guru Shikhar,at 1,722 meters is the highest peak in Rajasthan. It is a sacred site with a temple ded- icated to the Dattatreya Temple believed to be an incarnation of the Hindu Trinity (Brahma, Vishnu, and Shiva). It houses the Mount Abu Infrared Observatory (MIRO), one of India’s most important astronomical observatories which is managed by the Physical Research Laboratory (PRL), Ahmedabad. 372","PW-0408":"India’s rivers have profoundly shaped its cities, influenc- ing their growth, culture, and identity. A is correctly matched with 4: Betul is located in the south- ern part of Madhya Pradesh near the Tapti River. The Tapti originates from the Satpura range in Multai (Betul district), Madhya Pradesh. It is one of the few rivers in peninsular India that follows a westward course. B is correctly matched with 1: Jagdalpur in the Bastar dis- trict of Chhattisgarh lies on the Indravati River. The Indravati River originates in Odisha and is a tributary of the Godavari River. It flows through Chhattisgarh, carving deep gorges and support- ing the famous Chitrakote Waterfalls, often referred to as the “Ni- agara of India.” The river is crucial for the region’s biodiversity, especially for wildlife in the Indravati National Park. C is correctly matched with 2: Jabalpur is situated on the banks of the Narmada River. The Narmada is one of India’s most sacred rivers and is often called the “Lifeline of Madhya Pradesh.” It originates from Amarkantak in Madhya Pradesh and flows westward into the Ara","PW-0409":"India with its diverse topography and varied climatic conditions is home to a plethora of valleys, each possessing its unique charm and ecological significance. A is correctly matched with 3: Markha Valley is located in the Ladakh region of Jammu & Kashmir (now a Union Territory). It is one of the most famous trekking routes in Hemis National Park and is surrounded by the Zanskar and Ladakh ranges. The valley is known for its stunning landscapes, Buddhist monaster- ies, and remote villages, offering breathtaking views of the Kang Yatse Peak. B is correctly matched with 4: Dzukou Valley is a pristine and picturesque valley located on the border of Nagaland and Mani- pur. It is often called the “Valley of Flowers of the Northeast” due to its seasonal blooms of rare Dzukou lilies and other vibrant flowers. C is correctly matched with 2: Sangla Valley is located in the Kinnaur district of Himachal Pradesh. It is famous for its lush green landscapes, apple orchards, and the Baspa River that flows through it. It is surrounded by the Greater Himalayas of- fering stunning views of snow-cappe","PW-0410":"As of 2025, India has 573 wildlife sanctuaries, covering a total area of 123,762.56 km2, which constitutes 3.76% of the country’s land area. They were created under the Wildlife (Pro- tection) Act of 1972. Wildlife sanctuaries are an integral part of India’s conservation strategy. A is correctly matched with 4 : Chandra Prabha Wildlife Sanctuary is located in the Chandauli district of Uttar Pradesh, about 70 km from Varanasi. It was established in 1957 and cov- ers around 78 sq km and is home to species like leopards, nilgai, and wild boars. The sanctuary is famous for its scenic waterfalls like Raja and Devdari Falls. B is correctly matched with 2: The Karera Wildlife Sanctuary is located in the Shivpuri district of Madhya Pradesh. This sanctu- ary is known for its avian diversity and provides a vital habitat for various bird species. It is home to blackbucks and over 245 species of migratory birds, including pintails and spoonbills. C is correctly matched with 5: Jaisamand Wildlife Sanctuary, located in Udaipur, Rajasthan is known for its diverse flora and fauna, including leopards","PW-0411":" The Shyok River is a tributary of the Indus River. It originates from the Rimo Glacier, part of the Karakoram Range in Ladakh, India. The river flows through the Shyok Valley and passes through northern Ladakh and Gilgit-Baltistan (POK) before merging with the Indus River near Skardu. It is the northernmost river in the given list.  The Zaskar River is a tributary of the Indus River.It originates from the Zaskar Range in Ladakh and flows southeast before joining the Indus near Leh. The famous Chadar Trek takes place on its frozen waters during winters. It is located south of the Shyok River.  The Spiti River originates from the Kunzum Range in Himachal Pradesh. It flows through the cold desert valley of Spiti. It eventually merges with the Sutlej River at Khab, near the India-Tibet border. It is south of both Shyok and Zaskar Rivers.  The Sutlej River is the largest tributary of the Indus River. It originates from Rakshastal Lake near Mount Kailash in Tibet and enters India through Shipki La Pass in Himachal Pradesh. It then flows through Punjab before entering Pakistan. It is t","PW-0412":"Statement 1 is incorrect : The headquarters of the North Western Railway (NWR) is located in Jaipur, not Jodh- pur. The NWR is one of the 18 zones of Indian Railways and cov- ers parts of Rajasthan, Gujarat, and Punjab. Statement 2 is incorrect : The Indrail Pass is a travel-as-you- please ticket offered by Indian Railways to foreign tourists, not specifically for freedom fighters or sportspersons. It allows unlimited travel on the Indian Railways network for a specified period. Statement 3 is correct : The Fairy Queen, a steam locomotive built in 1855 is recognized by Guinness as the world’s oldest steam engine still in regular (though limited) operation. It oper- ates as a luxury tourist train between Delhi and Alwar, offering a journey that includes visits to heritage sites and wildlife desti- nations like the Sariska Tiger Reserve. 378","PW-0413":"A is correctly matched with 1 : Kothagudem,a city in Telanga- na (earlier part of Andhra Pradesh), India, is the administra- tive center of the Bhadradri Kothagudem district. The city is a crucial hub for coal reserves and houses the Singareni Collier- ies Company and thermal power station. B is correctly with Raichur Thermal Power Station (RTPS) is a coal-based power plant located in Shaktinagar, Raichur dis- trict, Karnataka. The power station is operated by Karnataka Power Corporation Limited (KPCL) and significantly contributes to Karnataka’s electricity supply. Raichur boasts the historic Raichur Fort. Its economy is primarily agricultural, earning it the nickname “Rice Bowl of Karnataka”. C is correctly with Mettur town in Tamil Nadu’s Salem dis- trict, is renowned for the massive Mettur Dam. The Mettur Thermal Power Station is a major coal-fired power plant. With a total installed capacity of 1,440 MW across multiple units com- missioned since 1987, it plays a vital role in meeting Tamil Na- du’s energy needs. D is correctly with Wanakbori in Gujarat is primarily known for its","PW-0414":"India’s diverse handicrafts, expressions of rich cultural heritage, thrive in specialized centers across the country. These centers preserve traditions, empower artisans, and produce globally rec- ognized artistic treasures. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 432 A is correctly matched with 4: Mon is a district in Nagaland and is home to the Konyak Naga tribe. It is known for their rich hand- icraft traditions such as wood carvings, traditional headgear, beadwork, and handwoven textiles. The Konyak warriors now cre- ate beautiful handicrafts that represent their tribal heritage. B is correctly matched with 2 : Nalbari district of Assam is well known for its bamboo and cane handicrafts, including mats, baskets, and decorative items. It is also famous for the tra- ditional Assamese handloom industry, particularly the produc- tion of Mekhela Chador (Assamese women’s attire). C is correctly matched with 1 : Naisghat located in Arunachal Pradesh is known for its tribal handicrafts such as woodwork, cane and bamboo products, and handmade textiles. Arunachal Pradesh has a strong tradition of weaving, wit","PW-0415":"A is correctly matched with 3 : The Thal Heavy Water Plant, located in the Raigad district of Maharashtra, is a crucial facil- ity for the production of heavy water. Heavy water (deuterium oxide) is essential in nuclear reactors as a moderator and cool- ant. The Thal plant uses a process involving ammonia-hydrogen exchange to enrich deuterium from natural water. It’s a vital com- ponent of India’s nuclear program. B is correctly matched with 1 : The Manuguru Heavy Water Plant is situated in the Bhadradri Kothagudem district of Telan- gana (it was formerly in Andhra Pradesh before the state bifurca- tion). It houses a Heavy Water Plant (HWP) that plays a crucial role in supplying heavy water for pressurized heavy-water reactors (PHWRs) in India. C is correctly matched with 2 : The Kakrapar Atomic Power Station (KAPS) is located near Kakrapar village in the Surat dis- trict of Gujarat. It houses two units of pressurized heavy water reactors (PHWRs). These reactors use heavy water as a modera- tor and coolant and natural uranium as fuel. KAPS is an import- ant source of nuclear power in","PW-0416":"The State of Uttar Pradesh shares its boundaries with eight Indian states and the National Capital Territory of Delhi. These adjacent states include Rajasthan, Haryana, Himachal Pradesh, Uttarakhand, Bihar, Madhya Pradesh, Jharkhand, and Chhattisgarh. Uttar Pradesh shares an inter- national border with the nation of Nepal.  Punjab situated in the northwest shares its boundaries with Jammu and Kashmir (Union Territory), Himachal Pradesh, Haryana and Rajasthan.  Chhattisgarh located in central India is surrounded by Madhya Pradesh, Maharashtra, Telangana, Andhra Pradesh, Odisha, and Jharkhand.  Jharkhand in the east,shares borders with Bihar, Uttar Pradesh, Chhattisgarh, Odisha, and West Bengal.  Rajasthan in the west, is bordered by Punjab, Haryana, Uttar Pradesh, Madhya Pradesh and Gujarat. 382","PW-0417":"A is correctly matched with 1 : Giridih located in Jharkhand is one of India’s earliest coal mining sites. It is known for superior-quality metallurgical coal used in steel pro- duction. Giridih is part of the Jharia and Bokaro coal belt, which is among the richest in the country. B is correctly matched with 3 : Alwar in Rajasthan is known for copper reserves, particularly in the Khetri Copper Belt. The Khetri Copper Complex (KCC) is operated by Hindustan Copper Limited (HCL), extracts copper ore from this region. Rajasthan accounts for a significant portion of India’s copper production. C is correctly matched with 4 : Dharwar in Karnataka is known for its rich manganese deposits. Manganese is crucial for steel manufacturing and is found in as- sociation with iron ore in Karnataka. Karnataka, along with Odi- sha and Madhya Pradesh, contributes majorly to India’s manga- nese production. D is correctly matched with 2 : Jayamkondam town in Tamil Nadu is known for its lignite reserves. Lignite is a type of coal that is lower in carbon content than bituminous coal. It is used as a fuel fo","PW-0418":"A is correctly matched with 3 : Gopinath Beach is located near the town of Bhavnagar in Gujarat. It is known for its rocky shores and breathtaking views of the Arabian Sea. The beach is named after the Gopinath Mahadev Temple located nearby. B is correctly matched with 1: Lawson’s Bay Beach is situat- ed in Visakhapatnam, Andhra Pradesh. This scenic and serene beach is an extension of Ramakrishna Beach and is popular for swimming and sunbathing. It is a clean and less crowded des- tination compared to other beaches in Vizag. C is correctly matched with 5: Devbagh Beach is located near Karwar in Karnataka. It’s known for its pristine sands, clear wa- ters, and the serene environment. The area surrounding Devbagh is also known for its natural beauty, including the backwaters and the nearby islands. D is correctly matched with 4: Sinquerim Beach is a popular beach in Goa located near the historic Aguada Fort. It is well known for water sports like jet skiing, windsurfing, and ba- nana boat rides. The beach is a favorite among tourists for its golden sands and stunning sunsets. 385","PW-0419":"A is correctly matched with 4 : Similipal Biosphere Reserve is located in the Mayurbhanj district of Odisha. Similipal Bio- sphere Reserve is renowned for its diverse ecosystems, encom- passing dense forests, grasslands, and wetlands. The reserve is a significant habitat for the Bengal tiger and the Asian elephant. The Similipal biosphere reserve is an important part of the Ma- yurbhanj Elephant Reserve which also includes the Kuldiha Wildlife Sanctuary and Hadgarh Wildlife Sanctuary. B is correctly matched with 3 : Dehang-Debang Biosphere Reserve is situated in the eastern Himalayan region of Arunachal Pradesh. The Brahmaputra River, known as the Siang and Dihang in Arunachal Pradesh, flows through the reserve. Dehang-Debang is a crucial habitat for several endan- gered species such as Mishmi Takin and the Red Panda. C is correctly matched with 5 : Nokrek Biosphere Reserve is in the West Garo Hills of Meghalaya. It is home to the rare and endangered species of the Red Panda. The reserve is also famous for being the origin of Meghalaya’s important rivers including the Simsang River. ","PW-0420":" Mahadev Hills is located in Madhya Pradesh. They are known for their scenic beauty, forested slopes, valleys, and waterfalls. It is composed of sandstone and sedimentary rocks and support diverse flora and fauna. These hills also hold cultural significance as sacred sites integrated into local traditions.  Satpura Range lies south of the Mahadeo Hills, spanning Madhya Pradesh, Maharashtra, and Chhattisgarh. Named after the Sanskrit word for “seven mountains,” it consists of rolling hills, plateaus, and peaks made of metamorphic and sedimentary rocks. It is home to national parks like Kanha and Satpura.  Western Ghats (Sahyadri Parvat) runs along India’s western coast through Maharashtra, Goa, Karnataka, Kerala, and Tamil Nadu. They are composed mainly of basalt rock from ancient volcanic activity. They give rise to rivers like Godavari, Krishna, and Kaveri. The Western Ghats regulate monsoon patterns by intercepting Arabian Sea winds and hold cultural value with ancient temples and sacred sites. Thus, the correct sequence from north to south is: Mahadeo Hills -> Satpura Range -> ","PW-0421":"Sambhar Lake is India’s largest inland saltwater lake, located in Rajasthan. It is spread across Jaipur, Nagaur, and Ajmer districts. The lake covers an area of about 230 square kilo- meters during peak monsoon and is known for its historical and economic significance due to salt production. Option (b) is correct: Sambhar Lake is located approximately 80 km southwest of Jaipur, making it the nearest major city. Jai- pur, the capital of Rajasthan,is well connected to Sambhar Lake via NH 8 and NH 48. The lake is also a popular weekend getaway from Jaipur for bird watchers and photographers. It is home to migratory birds like flamingos, pelicans, and storks. 388","PW-0422":"A is correctly matched with 1 : Kanger Ghati National is lo- cated in the Bastar district of Chhattisgarh. It is known for its biodiversity and limestone caves, such as the famous Kotumsar Cave. The park is home to species like the Bastar hill myna, ti- gers, leopards, and various reptiles. It is also known for its scenic beauty and waterfalls, such as the Tirathgarh Falls. B is correctly matched with 4 : Nagerhole National Park is located in Kodagu and Mysore districts of Karnataka. It is part of the Nilgiri Biosphere Reserve and is famous for Bengal Tigers, Indian Elephants, and leopards. C is correctly matched with 3 : Kugti Wildlife Sanctuary is located in the Chamba district of Himachal Pradesh. It is one of the largest wildlife sanctuaries in the state. It is known for its alpine and sub-alpine vegetation and is home to species like the Himalayan brown bear, musk deer, and snow leopard.The sanctu- ary is also a popular trekking destination. The sanctuary features alpine meadows, coniferous forests of deodar and fir, and vibrant rhododendron shrubs. D is correctly matched with 2","PW-0423":"The Onge, a Particularly Vulnerable Tribal Group (PVTG) inhabit Little Andaman Island of Andaman and Nicobar Islands. They are one of the oldest tribes of India, believed to have migrated from Africa around 60,000 years ago.The Onges are hunter-gatherers and rely on forest produce and fishing for survival. Their population is critically low, with fewer than 150 members as per the latest census. Option (b), (c) and (d) are incorrect :  Dadra and Nagar Haveli is home to tribes like the Warli, Kokna, and Dhodia but not the Onge tribe. The tribes here are primarily engaged in agriculture and forest-based occupations.  Daman and Diu, in contrast, has a smaller tribal presence and is better known for its Portuguese colonial heritage blended with Gujarati culture. Tribal communities are less culturally prominent here compared to Dadra and Nagar Haveli or Lakshadweep.  Lakshadweep’s population is predominantly Muslim with traditional social groups like the Koyas (landowners), Melacheris (laborers), and Aminidivi (boat builders). Their rich maritime culture revolves around seafaring and fi","PW-0424":" The Subarnarekha River originates in Jharkhand’s Chota Nagpur Plateau. It flows through West Bengal and Odisha before emptying into the Bay of Bengal. Also known as the “Golden Line” due to historical traces of gold in its sands. It is one of the smallest east-flowing rivers.  The Mahanadi originates from Sihawa Hills in Chhattisgarh and flows through Odisha before meeting the Bay of Bengal. The Hirakud Dam, one of the longest dams in the world, is built on this river.  The Godavari River, called “Dakshina Ganga” from Trimbak Plateau in Maharashtra and flows through Telangana, Andhra Pradesh, and Odisha before emptying into the Bay of Bengal. It is the longest river of Peninsular India.  The Krishna River originates from Mahabaleshwar (Maharashtra) and flows through Karnataka, Telangana, and Andhra Pradesh before reaching the Bay of Bengal. It is the second-longest river in Peninsular India after the Godavari.  The Pennar River originates from Nandi Hills in Karnataka and flows through Andhra Pradesh and Tamil Nadu before joining the Bay of Bengal.  The Cauvery River originate","PW-0425":"The shaded area on the given map represents India’s tropical wet and dry climate zone (also called the tropical savanna climate), where the mean temperature for July falls within this range. This climate is primarily found in: Madhya Pradesh (central and southern parts),Maharashtra (Vidarbha region),Karnataka (northern districts), Andhra Pradesh (Ray- alaseema region) and Tamil Nadu (interior regions) Climate and Vegetation Characteristics:  In July, during the monsoon season, temperatures range between 27.5°C – 30.0°C, offering relief from the extreme summer heat. In Summers (March–May) temperatures soar above 40°C in several areas while Winters (December– February) are mild, with temperatures rarely dropping below 18°C.  This region experiences distinct wet and dry seasons. Monsoon Season (June–September) receives heavy rainfall, ranging from 750 mm to 1,500 mm annually. Dry Season (October–May): Very little rainfall, leading to water scarcity and drought-prone conditions in some areas.  The region has savanna-like landscapes, with grasslands and scattered trees (e.g., teak, sal","PW-0426":"A is correctly matched with 2 : Mahe Port is located on the Malabar Coast of Kerala, Mahe is a small enclave with- in the state. Its minor port primarily serving local fishing and coastal traffic. Mahe was a French settlement from the 18th cen- tury and became part of India in 1954. It is named after French Governor Mahé de La Bourdonnais. B is correctly matched with 1 : Karaikal is the second-larg- est district of Puducherry UT and is located within Tamil Nadu along the Coromandel Coast. It is a deep-water commercial port that plays a crucial role in cargo shipments, petroleum imports, and exports. It has been developed as a privately operated, all-weather port, capable of handling large ships. C is correctly matched with 3 : The Pondicherry port is situ- ated in the capital of the Union Territory of Puducherry. It has historically served as a major French trade center and is strate- gically located along the Bay of Bengal. The port was an import- ant hub for spices, textiles, and maritime commerce during French rule. Today, the Pondicherry port is being revived for commercial opera","PW-0427":"A is correctly matched with 5 : Veraval is a major fishing and shipbuilding port on the west coast of India, situat- ed in the Gir Somnath district of Gujarat. It is well known for its large seafood industry, particularly fish exports, and serves as an important hub for marine trade in the Arabian Sea. It was a major shipbuilding center during the reign of the Maharajas of Junagadh, producing wooden ships that sailed across the Indian Ocean. It also serves as a gateway to the Somnath Temple, one of the holiest pilgrimage sites for Hindus. B is correctly matched with 2: Karwar is a natural deep-wa- ter port located in the Uttara Kannada district of Karnataka. It is strategically significant as it houses the INS Kadamba naval base, which is part of the Indian Navy’s Project Seabird. It is well known for trade in iron ore, granite, and other minerals. The picturesque coastline, lush green surroundings, and calm waters make Karwar an emerging center for coastal tourism and seafood industries. C is correctly matched with 4: Tuticorin, also known as Thoothukudi Port, is one of India’s larg","PW-0428":"In the given map, copper deposits discovered by the Atomic Minerals Division of Department Atomic Energy, are at Hassan in Karnataka and marked as ‘4’. Karnataka possesses other mineral wealth as well, including asbestos (found in Chik- kamagaluru, Hassan, Mandya, Mysuru, and Shivamogga districts), barytes and pyrite (Chitradurga district), calcite (Belagavi, Vi- jayapura, and Mysuru districts), and copper (Chikkamagaluru, Chitradurga, Kalaburagi, Hassan, Uttara Kannada, Raichur, and Shivamogga districts). 396","PW-0429":"The Tehri Dam is located in the Tehri Garhwal dis- trict of Uttarakhand. It is the tallest dam in India and one of the highest in the world. It is built on the Bhagirathi River near its confluence with the Bhilangna River. The dam plays a crucial role in hydroelectric power generation, irrigation, and municipal wa- ter supply. Its construction began in 1978 and was completed in 2006 and is managed by THDC India Limited. The dam generates approximately 1,000 MW of renewable energy, significantly con- tributing to India’s power infrastructure. Tehri Lake has emerged as a popular destination for adventure tourism, offering various water sports and recreational activities. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 438 397","PW-0430":"The Kudankulam Nuclear Power Plant (KNPP) is situated in Kudankulam, within the Tirunelveli district of Tamil Nadu, India. It is located approximately 20 km northeast of Kanyaku- mari and about 100 km from Thoothukudi (Tuticorin). In the provided figure, this site is clearly labeled as B. It is developed by the Nuclear Power Corporation of India (NPCIL) in collaboration with Russia. The plant initially features two 1,000 MW VVER-1000 pressurized water reactors (PWRs). These reactors were supplied by Russia’s Atomstroyexport and represent India’s first adoption of imported PWR technology. The reactors are based on the advanced third-generation AES- 92 model, which prioritizes safety and efficiency. Under a 2008 agreement between India and Russia plans are underway to con- struct four more units, further expanding the plant’s capacity. 398","PW-0431":"With reference to the map of Jammu and Kashmir the relative locations of above mentioned points: ‘A’ is Baramulla, ‘B’ is Srinagar, ‘C’ is Anantnag and ‘D’ is Kar- gil. A represents Baramulla: Baramulla, located on the banks of the Jhelum River. It is the largest district in the Kashmir Valley in terms of both population and area. It is bordered by districts like Srinagar, Kupwara, Budgam, and Bandipore, as well as the Line of Control and Neelum District in Pakistan-occupied Kashmir. B represents Srinagar: Srinagar, the summer capital of Jam- mu and Kashmir is located at the center of the Kashmir Valley along the Jhelum River (locally called Vyath). It is famous for its gardens, lakes, houseboats, Kashmiri handicrafts, and dried fruits. C represents Anantnag: Anantnag is located in southern Je- hlum Valley. It is known for its numerous streams like Lidder (originating from Sheshnag Lake), Sandran, Brengi, and Ar- path. These streams irrigate large areas of the district. Its prox- imity to the Pir Panjal Range gives it a temperate summer cli- mate compared to other districts in the va","PW-0432":"Indian Standard Time (IST) is calculated based on the 82.5°E longitude, which passes through Mirzapur, Uttar Pradesh. IST is 5 hours 30 minutes ahead of Greenwich Mean Time (GMT+5:30). Since the Earth rotates 360° in 24 hours, it covers 15° of longitude per hour which means that for every de- gree of longitude, there is a 4-minute difference in local time. Shillong is located at 92°E longitude, which is 9.5° east of the IST reference meridian. By multiplying this difference with 4 minutes per degree, we get a time difference of 9.5 × 4 = 38 min- utes. Since local time increases towards the east, Shillong will be 38 minutes ahead of IST. Therefore, if it is 10:00 AM IST then the local time in Shillong will be 10:38 AM. 400","PW-0433":"The Krishna-Godavari basin is a large sedimentary basin on the east coast of India, formed by the Krishna and Go- davari rivers. It extends into the Bay of Bengal and is known for its significant hydrocarbon reserves, including both oil and natural gas. The Ravva offshore block, a prolific oil and gas producing area, is located within this basin. The basin’s geo- logical history and structure have created favorable conditions for the accumulation of hydrocarbons, making it a crucial region for India’s energy sector. Geography 439 401","PW-0434":"In 1997, the sal forests of Madhya Pradesh, a state in central India, experienced a severe outbreak of the sal bor- er beetle (Hoplocerambyx spinicornis). This insect infestation posed a significant threat to the health and survival of the sal trees, which are a dominant species in the region’s forests. The epidemic rapidly spread across vast tracts of sal forests, caus- ing widespread damage and mortality among the trees. The sal borer beetle’s larvae burrow into the bark and heartwood of sal trees, disrupting the flow of nutrients and water within the tree. This infestation weakens the trees, making them susceptible to other diseases and ultimately leading to their death. The 1997 epidemic resulted in the loss of a substantial portion of the sal forest cover in Madhya Pradesh, with significant ecological and economic consequences. 402","PW-0435":"The Krishna-Godavari (KG) Basin is located along India’s eastern coast spanning 50,000 square kilometers. It covers parts of Andhra Pradesh and extends into the Bay of Bengal. It is a peri-cratonic passive margin basin, formed by sediment deposition from the Krishna and Godavari rivers over millions of years which created formations rich in hydrocarbons. The KG Basin holds significant oil and gas reserves, with deposits found in diverse geological layers extending from Permo-Triassic sandstones (onshore) to Pleistocene complexes (offshore). ONGC has been a key player in its exploration, alongside private firms like Reliance Industries. Major discoveries include the Ravva oil field (offshore) and Kaikalur, Vadali, and Mori (onshore). The KG-D6 block which is operated by Reliance contains some of India’s largest natural gas reserves. 403","PW-0436":"1 represents Palanpur: Palanpur Railway Junction, located in Banaskantha district, Gujarat, is a key station on the Delhi-Ahmedabad broad gauge line under the Western Railway zone. It connects Palanpur to major cities in Rajasthan, Gujarat, and beyond, handling significant passenger and freight traffic, contributing to regional connectivity and economic activity. 2 represents Mahesana: Mahesana Railway Junction, situat- ed in northern Gujarat, is another important station under the Western Railway zone. It links Mahesana district to major cities within Gujarat and other states through express, passenger, and local trains. The station supports regional economic develop- ment by facilitating the movement of people and goods. 3 represents Ahmedabad: Ahmedabad Railway Station (Kalu- pur) is one of Western India’s busiest stations. A major junction under the Western Railway zone, it connects Ahmedabad to all major Indian cities. Hosting prestigious trains like the Shatabdi and Duronto Express, it features modern infrastructure and ame- nities, playing a pivotal role in Gujarat’s connectiv","PW-0437":"4 represents Uttar Pradesh: UP is ocated in the fertile In- do-Gangetic plain which has abundant groundwater resources due to favorable geology and extensive aquifers. Of approximate- ly 14.23 million hectares of net irrigated area around 84% is reliant on groundwater through wells and tubewells. 3 represents Maharashtra: Groundwater availability is limited due to varied topography, basaltic rock formations, and uneven rainfall distribution. Around 2.87 million hectares (28.75 lakh hectares) of agricultural land is irrigated using groundwater ac- counting for 71% of the total irrigated area. 2 represents West Bengal: West Bengal is situated in the Gan- ges delta and enjoys significant groundwater availability due to abundant rainfall and river systems. Groundwater irrigation is significant but utilizes only 42% of its potential, with a focus on smallholder farmers. 1 represents Assam: Groundwater availability is high, par- ticularly in the Brahmaputra valley, but its potential remains underutilized. Groundwater irrigation covers approximately 74,000 hectares. Despite high potential i","PW-0438":"3 represents Mizoram: ​Mizoram has a significant population of Scheduled Tribes (ST), accounting for over 94.4% of its total population, according to the 2011 Census. The predominant tribes include the Lushai (Mizo), Hmar, Paite and many oth- er smaller groups which contributes to the state’s rich cultural diversity. These tribes predominantly practice agriculture, weav- ing, and crafts as part of their livelihood. The Mizo language is widely spoken across the state and is an important part of their cultural identity. 1 represents Arunachal Pradesh: Arunachal Pradesh, located in the northeastern part of India has a significant tribal popula- tion, with over 60 tribes. These indigenous groups like the Apa- tani, Monpa, and Nyishi form around 68.8% of the state’s total population as per 2011 Census. The majority of the state’s popu- lation is classified as Scheduled Tribes (STs), making it one of the highest in India in terms of ST percentage. 2 represents Manipur: Manipur has a significant Scheduled Tribe (ST) population, constituting around 40.9% of the state’s total population accor","PW-0439":"A represents Brajbhasha Region: Brajbhasha is predominant- ly spoken in the western districts of Uttar Pradesh, India, in- cluding Mathura, Agra, Aligarh, Etah, Hathras, Bulandshahr, and Badaun. It is characterized by its melodic and gentle tone. Brajbhasha boasts of a rich literary tradition, with renowned po- ets like Surdas, Raskhan, Bihari Lal, and Keshavdas having composed their works in this language. Its influence on Hindi lit- erature is profound particularly in the realm of Krishna Bhakti Kavya (devotional poetry dedicated to Lord Krishna). B represents Awadhi Region: Awadhi is primarily spoken in the central regions of Uttar Pradesh, encompassing districts like Ayodhya, Lucknow, Rae Bareli, Sultanpur, Pratapgarh, Jaunpur, and Faizabad. A distinguishing feature of Awadhi is the prominence of the ‘a’ sound. The epic Ramcharitmanas, a cornerstone of Hindi literature, was composed by Tulsidas in Awadhi. The language’s influence on Hindi literature is substan- tial especially within the Ram Bhakti Kavya tradition (devo- tional poetry dedicated to Lord Rama). C represents Bhojpur","PW-0440":"A represents The Rift Valley of the Narmada : The Narma- da River flows through a prominent rift valley in central India formed by tectonic forces that caused the Earth’s crust to stretch and created a graben. This geological depression is bounded by the Vindhya and Satpura mountain ranges. The valley is char- acterized by steep slopes and a flat valley floor, which makes it unique in terms of topography. B represents The Chhattisgarh Plain : The Chhattisgarh Plain, often referred to as the “rice bowl of Central India,” is located primarily in the state of Chhattisgarh. The region is drained by the Mahanadi River and its tributaries, which contribute to its fertile alluvial soil, ideal for agriculture. The plain is known for its rice cultivation, as well as crops like pulses, oilseeds, and sugar- cane. The plain holds significant mineral deposits, including coal, iron ore, bauxite, and manganese. C represents The Chota Nagpur Plateau : The Chota Nagpur Plateau spans across Jharkhand, West Bengal, and Odisha marked by its uneven topography, featuring a mix of hills, valleys, and river","PW-0441":"1 refers to Kosi River : The Kosi River originates at the conflu- ence of Sun Kosi, Arun Kosi, and Tamur Kosi in Nepal (with its source in Tibet). It is known as the “Sorrow of Bihar” due to its devastating floods caused by heavy silt deposition. It flows through northern Bihar, passing important cities like Saharsa, Supaul, and Purnea, before joining the Ganges near Kursela. 4 refers to Gomati River : The Gomati River originates from Gomat Taal (Fulhaar Jheel) near Pilibhit in Uttar Pradesh. It flows through key cities such as Lucknow, Sultanpur, and Jaun- pur, eventually joining the Ganges at Kaithi in Ghazipur district. 3 refers to Ghaghara River : The Ghaghara River originates from the Tibetan Plateau near Lake Manasarovar. It passes through significant cities like Ayodhya and Gorakhpur before merging with the Ganges near Chhapra in Bihar. 2 refers to the Gandak River : The Gandak River arises from the Dhaulagiri range in Nepal and flows through northern Bi- har, passing cities like Bettiah and Muzaffarpur. It meets the Ganges near Hajipur and has an average discharge of 1,680 m³","PW-0442":" A refers to Gujarat where groundnut is a major crop and currently the largest producer of it.  B refers to western part of Maharashtra which is known for sugarcane cultivation . Maharashtra is ranked second in sugarcane production after Uttar Pradesh.  C refers to the This may not be true anymore, since almost 68% Ragi is grown in Karnataka  D refers to Andhra Pradesh and tobacco is cultivated in this area. Currently Andhra Pradesh is the largest producer of tobacco.  Groundnut : Groundnut is primarily cultivated in Gujarat, Andhra Pradesh, Tamil Nadu, Karnataka, Maharashtra, and Rajasthan. It thrives best in well-drained sandy loam soil and a warm climate. India is the second-largest producer of groundnuts globally after China, contributing significantly to oilseed production.  Ragi (Finger Millet) : Ragi is mainly grown in Karnataka, Tamil Nadu, Andhra Pradesh, Odisha, and Maharashtra. It grows well in red loamy soil and requires a semi-arid climate. Karnataka is the largest producer of ragi in India, making it a staple crop for the region. At the global level, India is the ","PW-0443":"","PW-0444":"Pair 1 is incorrectly matched : Idukki is not a ther- mal power station; it is a hydroelectric project in Kerala. The Idukki Dam, built on the Periyar River, is one of the largest hy- droelectric projects in India. Pair 2 is correctly matched : Sabarigiri Hydro-electric Proj- ect is a hydropower project in Kerala, located on the Pamba Riv- er. It is one of the major hydropower projects in the state. Pair 3 is correctly matched : Ghatprabha Project is an irriga- tion project in Karnataka. The Ghatprabha River, a tributary of the Krishna River, is dammed to provide water for irrigation. Pair 4 is correctly matched : Ramganga Multipurpose Proj- ect is located in Uttarakhand, constructed on the Ramganga Riv- er. It serves multiple purposes, including irrigation, hydroelectric power generation, and flood control. 412","PW-0445":"The dotted (broken) line on the map represents the Durand Line, which marks the boundary between Afghanistan and Pakistan. This border was established in 1893 by Sir Hen- ry Mortimer Durand, a British civil servant, and Abdur Rah- man Khan, the Emir of Afghanistan. The Durand Line serves as the international border between Afghanistan and Pakistan, although it remains a subject of dispute.  McMohan Line : The boundary between India and China (Arunachal Pradesh region), drawn during the Simla Convention (1914). China disputes this line, but India recognizes it as the official border.  Line of Demarcation by the Boundary Commission (1947) : Drawn by Sir Cyril Radcliffe during the partition of British India. It demarcates India and Pakistan (Punjab and Bengal regions). This line led to massive displacement and violence during Partition.  Route of the Younghusband Expedition : A British military expedition to Tibet in 1903-1904, led by Francis Younghusband. The route passed through Sikkim and entered Lhasa, Tibet, aiming to secure British influence in the region. 413","PW-0446":"The river described above that thrice forks into two streams and reunites is the Cauvery River. It flows through the states of Karnataka and Tamil Nadu. The Cauvery River is known for splitting into multiple streams and forming islands :  Srirangapatna (Karnataka): The river splits and encircles the island town, famous for the Ranganathaswamy Temple.  Shivanasamudra (Karnataka): The river divides into two branches, forming the Shivanasamudra Falls (Gaganachukki and Barachukki).  Srirangam (Tamil Nadu): The river bifurcates and surrounds Srirangam Island, home to the renowned Ranganathaswamy Temple, the largest functioning Hindu temple complex. These phenomena occur due to the unique geography and mean- ders of the Cauvery River.  Tungabhadra River: A major tributary of the Krishna River, formed by the Tunga and Bhadra Rivers. It flows through Karnataka and Andhra Pradesh, famous for Hampi, a UNESCO World Heritage Site.  Krishna River: One of the longest rivers in India, originating from Mahabaleshwar (Maharashtra) and flowing through Karnataka, Telangana, and Andhra Pradesh into","PW-0447":"The place referred to in the quotation is Tranquebar (Tharangam- badi), located on the Tamil Nadu coast. It was a Danish colony from 1620 to 1845, when it was sold to the British. Tranquebar is known for its rich colonial heritage, including the Danish Fort (Fort Dansborg), built by the Danish East India Company, which stands as a reminder of Denmark’s presence in India. The New Jerusalem Church, constructed by Danish missionaries, adds to the town’s historical charm. The quaint streets and peaceful beachfront, often deserted, give the town a serene and timeless appeal. No other Indi- an coast shares a similar Danish colonial history, making the Tamil Nadu coast (Tranquebar) the correct answer. 9. LOCATION/MAP BASED : WORLD GEOGRAPHY 415","PW-0448":"The longest border between any two countries in the world is between Canada and the United States, which spans approximately 8,891 kilometers (5,525 miles). The border is divided into two: the border shared with Canada by the continen- tal United States and the border that the state of Alaska shares with northern Canada. Eight Canadian provinces and thirteen American states run along the shared boundary.  The US- CANADA border is not only the longest border but also the longest undefended border in the world. Despite its length, there are no military fortifications along the entire stretch.  The border between India and Bangladesh is the longest border India shares with any of its neighbors. 416","PW-0449":"The Red Sea is a narrow body of water. It stretches about 1,200 miles (1,930 km) southeast from Suez, Egypt. The sea ends at the Bab el-Mandeb Strait, which connects to the Gulf of Aden. From there, it leads into the Arabian Sea. Statement 1 is correct : The Red Sea is located in a region characterized by arid and semi-arid climates, with very little rainfall throughout the year. The surrounding regions, such as parts of Egypt, Saudi Arabia, and Sudan, experience low annual precipitation. The average annual rainfall along the Red Sea coast is less than 100 mm(annually) in most areas, with some regions experi- encing no rainfall at all. For example, the city of Jeddah, Saudi Arabia, on the Red Sea coast, has an annual rainfall of only about 80 mm. Statement 2 is correct : The Red Sea is almost unique in that it does not receive significant inflows from any large rivers. While there are some small streams and wadis (seasonal rivers such as Wadi Fatimah) that flow into the Red Sea, they do not signifi- cantly contribute to the volume of water in the sea. The Red Sea’s water balance is m","PW-0450":"Cote d’Ivoire (Ivory Coast) and Ghana are the two largest cocoa producers in the world, contributing over 60% of the global cocoa supply. Cote d’Ivoire alone produces about 40%, making it the top producer, while Ghana, the second-larg- est producer, is known for its high-quality cocoa beans. Cocoa from these countries is a key ingredient in the global choc- olate industry, supplying major manufacturers like Nestlé, Mars, and Hershey. Their dominance in cocoa production is due to a tropical climate with hot, humid conditions, fertile soil ideal for cocoa cultivation, and a labor-intensive farming system support- ed by extensive smallholder networks. 418","PW-0451":"The North Sea is a shallow, northeastern arm of the At- lantic Ocean located between the British Isles and the mainland of northwestern Europe and covering an area of 220,000 square miles (570,000 square km). Option (b) is correct : The sea is bordered by:  The island of Great Britain to the southwest and west,  The Orkney and Shetland islands to the northwest,  Norway to the northeast,  Denmark to the east,  Germany and the Netherlands to the southeast  Belgium and France to the south. Geography 445 419","PW-0452":"Ukraine is a country located in eastern Europe. Its capi- tal is Kyiv which is located on the Dnieper River in north-central Ukraine. Ukraine shares its borders with seven countries:  Poland to the west  Slovakia to the west  Hungary to the west  Romania to the southwest  Moldova to the southwest  Russia to the east and northeast  Belarus to the north Among given countries Ukraine shares borders with Hungary and Romania only. The other countries- Bulgaria, Czech Re- public, Latvia, and Lithuania do not share a land border with Ukraine. 420","PW-0453":"","PW-0454":"Pair 1 is correctly matched : The Bandarpunch Glacier is the source of the Yamuna River. It is located in the Garhwal region of Uttarakhand. It is one of the major rivers in northern India. Pair 2 is correctly matched : The Bara Shigri Glacier is one of the largest glaciers in Himachal Pradesh. The meltwater from this glacier forms the Chandra River which combines with the Bhaga River to create the Chenab River. Pair 3 is incorrectly matched : The Milam Glacier located in the Kumaon region of Uttarakhand is the source of the Gori Ganga River, not the Mandakini River. The Mandakini River originates from the Chorabari Glacier near Kedarnath. Pair 4 is correctly matched : The Siachen Glacier, one of the longest glaciers in the world, is located in the Karakoram range in Ladakh. It is a major source of the Nubra River, which is a tributary of the Shyok River. The Nubra Valley, known for its cold desert landscape, lies along the Nubra River, making the gla- cier a crucial hydrological feature of the region. Pair 5 is incorrectly matched : Zemu Glacier is the primary source of the Teesta R","PW-0455":"Pair 1 is correctly matched : The Adriatic Sea is a body of water separating the Italian Peninsula from the Balkan peninsula. The countries with coasts on the Adriatic sea are Albania, Bosnia and Herzegovina, Croatia, Italy, Montenegro and Slovenia. Pair 2 is incorrectly matched : Black Sea is not bordered by Croatia. Black Sea is a large inland sea situated at the southeast- ern extremity of Europe. It is bordered by Ukraine to the north, Russia to the northeast, Georgia to the east, Turkey to the south, and Bulgaria and Romania to the west. Pair 3 is correctly matched : Caspian Sea is the world’s larg- est inland body of water, variously classed as the world’s larg- est lake or a full-fledged sea. It is an endorheic basin (a basin without outflows) located between Europe and Asia. It is bound- ed by Kazakhstan in the northeast, Russia in the northwest, Azerbaijan in the west, Iran in the south and Turkmenistan in the southeast. Pair 4 is correctly matched : The Mediterranean Sea is an in- tercontinental sea that stretches from the Atlantic Ocean on the west to Asia in the east and ","PW-0456":"","PW-0457":"Option (c) is correct: The correct sequence of cities in South-East Asia as one proceeds from south to north would be Jakarta>Singapore>Bangkok>Hanoi.  Jakarta is the capital of Indonesia and is located on the island of Java approximately at 6.2° S (south of the equator). It is the southernmost city among the four listed.  Singapore is a city-state located at the southern tip of the Malay Peninsula at approximately 1.3° N (just north of the equator). It is north of Jakarta.  Bangkok is the capital of Thailand and is located in the central part of the country at approximately 13.8° N. It is north of Singapore and Jakarta.  Hanoi is the capital of Vietnam and is located in the northern part of the country. At approximately 21.0° N. It is the northernmost city among the four listed. 427","PW-0458":"","PW-0459":"The Mediterranean Sea is a significant body of water almost entirely enclosed by land, serves as a natural border for numerous countries across three continents: Europe, Asia, and Africa. Option (c) is correct: The countries bordering the Mediterra- nean Sea are Albania, Algeria, Bosnia and Herzegovina, Croatia, Cyprus, Egypt, France, Greece, Israel, Italy, Lebanon, Libya, Mal- ta, Monaco, Montenegro, Morocco, Slovenia, Spain, Syria, Tuni- sia, and Turkey.  Jordan has a coastline along the Red Sea at its southwestern tip (the Gulf of Aqaba) but does not have a coastline along the Mediterranean Sea.  Iraq shares borders with Turkey to the north, Iran to the east, Kuwait to the southeast, Saudi Arabia to the south, Jordan to the southwest, and Syria to the west. Iraq has a minimal coastline along the Persian Gulf but lacks any coastline on the Mediterranean Sea. 430","PW-0460":"Option (b) is correct : Traveling by road from Kohima in Nagaland to Kottayam in Kerala involves traversing multi- ple Indian states. To determine the minimum number of states one would pass through, including the origin and destination, let’s analyze the shortest route:  Nagaland: Starting point at Kohima.  Assam: Proceed westward into Assam.  West Bengal: Continue through Assam into West Bengal.  Odisha: Travel southward from West Bengal into Odisha.  Andhra Pradesh: Proceed further south into Andhra Pradesh.  Tamil Nadu: From Andhra Pradesh, enter Tamil Nadu.  Kerala: Finally, arrive at Kottayam in Kerala. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 450 This route covers seven states in total. Alternatively, after Andhra Pradesh, one could enter Karnataka before reaching Ker- ala, still totaling seven states. 431","PW-0461":"","PW-0462":"Option 1 is correct : Aleppo is a major city in northern Syria. It is one of the oldest continuously inhabited cities in the world. It has been a focal point in the Syrian Civil War, experienc- ing significant destruction and humanitarian crises. Option 2 is incorrect: Kirkuk is a city in northern Iraq and not Yemen. It is known for its ethnic diversity and significant oil re- serves. The city has been a point of contention due to its strategic importance and the presence of various ethnic groups such as Kurds, Arabs, and Turkmen. Option 3 is incorrect: Mosul is a city in northern Iraq, not Pal- estine. It has been a significant cultural and economic center in Iraq. It was occupied by ISIS from 2014 to 2017, leading to exten- sive damage and loss of life. Option 4 is correct: Mazar-i-Sharif is a city in northern Af- ghanistan. It known for its cultural significance and the Shrine of Hazrat Ali 434","PW-0463":"Statement 1 is incorrect: The broadening (not Deepening) of the Malacca straits between Malaysia and Indonesia will reduce the navigation time and distance. The Malacca Strait is situated between Malaysia and Indonesia and is one of the main shipping lanes. The narrow waterway creates a chokepoint between the Indian Ocean and the Pacific Ocean. Statement 2 is correct: Opening a new canal across the Kra isthmus between the Gulf of Siam and the Andaman Sea can reduce the navigation time and distance. Kra isthmus is the narrowest part of the Malay Peninsula. It is bordered to the west by the Andaman Sea and to the east by the Gulf of Thailand. 435","PW-0464":"","PW-0465":"The Tropic of Capricorn is situated at approximately 23°27′ south of the Equator. It marks the southernmost latitude where the Sun can be directly overhead during the December solstice. This significant line traverses ten countries across three continents: South America, Africa, and Australia.  South America: Brazil, Paraguay, Argentina and Chile.  Africa: Namibia, Botswana, South Africa,Mozambique and Madagascar.  Australia 437","PW-0466":"Cape Canaveral, also called Cape Kennedy, is a major spaceport on Florida’s east coast. It serves as the primary launch site for U.S. space missions. It was established in 1949 as a mis- sile testing site, Cape Canaveral has played a crucial role in space exploration, evolving into a key launch site. Being positioned on a barrier island along Florida’s east coast, its coastal setting offers ideal conditions for launching spacecraft into orbit.  While Virginia has NASA’s Wallops Flight Facility, it is not used for space shuttle launches. North Carolina and South Carolina also lack any major spaceport like Cape Canaveral. 440","PW-0467":"","PW-0468":"","PW-0469":"","PW-0470":"Statement 1 is correct : Ajman is one of the seven emirates and the smallest in terms of area. The United Arab Emirates (UAE) is a federation of seven emirates, established on 2nd De- cember 1971. Initially, six emirates—Abu Dhabi, Dubai, Shar- jah, Ajman, Umm Al-Quwain, and Fujairah—formed the union, while Ras al-Khaimah joined later in 1972. Statement 2 is correct : Initially, Ras al-Khaimah chose not to join the UAE in 1971, but later became part of the federation on 10th February 1972. 446","PW-0471":"","PW-0472":"Copacabana Beach is in Rio de Janeiro, Brazil, a city renowned for landmarks such as Christ the Redeemer, Sugarloaf Mountain, and its famous beach. With its lively Carnival festival, samba music, and beautiful beaches, Rio is a key cultural and tourist hub in South America. 448","PW-0473":"Addis Ababa (Ethiopia) does not have the same clock time as the other three cities at any given instant. Addis Ababa (Ethiopia) follows East Africa Time (EAT), which is GMT+3, meaning it is always ahead by 3 hours compared to the other three cities. 449","PW-0474":"","PW-0475":"The Amazon River is the longest river among the giv- en options. The Amazon River flows through South America, mainly in Brazil, Peru, and Colombia. It has the largest discharge vol- ume of any river in the world. Some sources debate whether the Amazon or the Nile is the longest river, but in this set of options, Amazon is the longest. Comparison of the approximate lengths of the given rivers :  Amazon River : 6,992 km (4,345 miles)(approximately)  Amur River : 4,444 km (2,763 miles)  Congo River : 4,700 km (2,922 miles)  Lena River : 4,400 km (2,736 miles) The Nile is traditionally considered the longest, the Amazon has the largest discharge of water in the world, making it the largest river by volume. 451","PW-0476":"The largest coral reef in the world is the Great Barri- er Reef, which is located off the coast of Australia. The Great Barrier Reef is the world’s largest coral reef sys- tem, stretching over 2,300 km (1,400 miles) along the north- east coast of Australia in the Coral Sea. It consists of over 2,900 individual reefs and 900 islands. It is visible from space and is one of the Seven Natural Wonders of the World. It is a UNESCO World Heritage Site and a crucial ecosystem, home to diverse marine life. 452","PW-0477":"Options 1 and 2 are correct : The Bermuda Triangle extends between Southern Florida, Puerto Rico, and Bermuda, form- ing a triangular region in the Atlantic Ocean. The Bermuda Triangle, also known as the Devil’s Triangle, is a loosely de- fined region where several ships and aircraft are said to have mysteriously disappeared. Option 3 is incorrect : Hawaiian Islands are located in the Pa- cific Ocean, far from the Bermuda Triangle, and are not part of it. 453","PW-0478":"Option (b) is correct : The historical Macedonian terri- tory refers to the region of Macedonia, which was part of ancient Greece and later divided into several modern-day countries. The territorial disputes, especially over the use of the name Macedo- nia, have been a source of tension primarily between Greece and Bulgaria.  Greece claims the cultural and historical heritage of ancient Macedonia and has been particularly sensitive to the use of the name Macedonia, especially when used by the neighboring North Macedonia.  Bulgaria has also made historical claims to parts of this region due to the presence of Bulgarian-speaking populations in the area historically known as Eastern Macedonia.  This dispute over the Macedonian region and its historical claims has been a point of contention for many years, especially surrounding issues of identity, heritage, and territorial integrity. 454","PW-0479":"Option (c) is correct : The Huangpu River is the main river that runs through Shanghai, China. It divides the city into two parts:  Puxi (west of the river) – The older, historic part of Shanghai.  Pudong (east of the river) – A modern financial district with skyscrapers like the Shanghai Tower. The river is 113 km long and plays a vital role in trade and transportation. It is also famous for the Bund, a waterfront area showcasing Shanghai’s colonial-era architecture. 455","PW-0480":"","PW-0481":"Statement 1 is correct : The length of a terrestrial mile is lesser than that of a nautical mile. A terrestrial (statute) mile measures 1,609 meters (1.609 km), whereas a nautical mile is 1,852 meters (1.852 km), making the statement correct. Statement 2 is incorrect : The Harmattan is a dry, dusty trade wind that originates from the Sahara Desert and blows toward the West African coast, affecting countries like Nigeria, Ghana, and Senegal, rather than the East African coast as stated. Statement 3 is incorrect : Greece and Albania are not located on the Iberian Peninsula. The Iberian Peninsula comprises Spain, Portugal, Andorra, and a small portion of France. In contrast, Greece and Albania are part of the Balkan Peninsula. 457","PW-0482":"","PW-0483":"","PW-0484":"The Balearic Islands are an archipelago located in the western Mediterranean Sea, near the eastern coast of Spain. They are a popular tourist destination known for their scenic landscapes, beaches, and cultural heritage. They are an auton- omous community of Spain and consist of four main islands. Geography 457 461","PW-0485":"Option (b) is correct : Lithuania is a Baltic country in Northern Europe. It shares land borders with Latvia to the north, Belarus to the east and south, Poland to the south, and Russia (Kaliningrad) to the west. Ukraine does not share a border with Lithuania. Belarus lies between them. 464","PW-0486":"Peshawar, the capital of Khyber Pakhtunkhwa prov- ince, is the northernmost among these cities. Moving south- ward, Islamabad, the capital of Pakistan, comes next. Further south lies Gujranwala, a major industrial city in Punjab prov- ince. Finally, Multan, known for its Sufi shrines, is located in southern Punjab, making it the southernmost in the given op- tions. Therefore, the correct north-to-south order is Peshawar → Islamabad → Gujranwala → Multan. 465","PW-0487":"Statement 1 is incorrect : Great Britain consists of En- gland, Scotland, and Wales. It does not include Northern Ire- land. The United Kingdom (UK) comprises Great Britain and Northern Ireland. Statement 2 is correct : England covers approximately 53% of the total area of the UK (130,279 km2 out of 242,495 km2), making the statement accurate. 467","PW-0488":"The Itaipu Dam, located on the Parana River at the bor- der of Foz do Iguaçu (Brazil) and Ciudad del Este (Paraguay), is one of the largest hydroelectric plants in the world. Completed in 1984, it is managed by Itaipu Binacional, equally owned by Brazil and Paraguay. The dam generates over 14,000 MW of electricity, supplying nearly 90% of Paraguay’s energy needs and about 15% of Brazil’s consumption. It remains a sym- bol of successful binational cooperation and a major contributor to renewable energy production globally. 468","PW-0489":"Malaysia is not part of the Mekong River basin. The river does not flow through Malaysia at any point. Malaysia’s ma- jor rivers include the Rajang River and Kinabatangan River. The Mekong River is one of the longest rivers in Asia (about 4,350 km long). It originates in China’s Tibetan Plateau and flows through six countries: China, Myanmar, Laos, Thailand, Cambodia, and Vietnam before emptying into the South China Sea. 469","PW-0490":"","PW-0491":"A is matched with 1 : The Black Sea is an inland sea in south- eastern Europe. It is bordered by six countries: Bulgaria, Roma- nia, Ukraine, Russia, Georgia, and Turkey. Bulgaria’s eastern coastline lies along the western edge of the Black Sea, providing it with significant maritime access. This strategic position has historically facilitated trade and cultural exchanges between Bul- garia and other Black Sea nations. B is matched with 3 : The Red Sea is a seawater inlet of the In- dian Ocean. It is situated between northeastern Africa and the Arabian Peninsula. It is bordered by several countries, includ- ing Egypt to the northwest, Sudan to the southwest, and Eritrea to the southeast. Djibouti and Saudi Arabia lie to the east, while Yemen is situated to the southeast. The Red Sea is also connected to the Mediterranean Sea through the Suez Canal and to the Ara- bian Sea via the Bab el-Mandeb Strait. C is matched with 2 : The Yellow Sea is a marginal sea of the Western Pacific Ocean. It lies between mainland China and the Korean Peninsula. D is matched with 4 : The Caspian Sea is re","PW-0492":"","PW-0493":"","PW-0494":"Israel shares its borders with four neighboring coun- tries : Lebanon to the north, Syria to the northeast, Jordan to the east, and Egypt to the southwest. These borders have evolved significantly since Israel’s estab- lishment in 1948, influenced by various geopolitical events and agreements. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 460  Lebanon : The border with Lebanon is defined by the Blue Line, established by the United Nations in 2000 to confirm Israel’s withdrawal from southern Lebanon. This line closely approximates the Green Line set under the 1949 armistice agreement between Lebanon and Israel. The area east of the Hasbani River is considered part of Syria and included in the Golan Heights.  Syria : The border with Syria includes the Golan Heights, a strategically significant region that Israel captured during the 1967 Six-Day War.  Jordan : The border with Jordan was established following the 1994 peace treaty between the two nations. This agreement marked the first peace treaty between Israel and an Arab country, leading to the normalization of diplomatic and economic relations.  Egypt ","PW-0495":"","PW-0496":"","PW-0497":"Option (d) is correct : A is matched with 3 : Located in the western Indian Ocean, Seychelles is an archipelago of 115 islands known for its stun- ning beaches, coral reefs, and unique biodiversity. It is home to the rare coco de mer and two UNESCO World Heritage Sites. B is matched with 1 : The Chagos Archipelago, in the central Indian Ocean, consists of 55 coral islands. Known for its pristine marine ecosystem, it includes Diego Garcia, a significant mili- tary base. Historically, it was used for coconut plantations. C is matched with 4 : Mauritius, part of the Mascarene Is- lands, lies east of Madagascar. It is renowned for its volcanic landscapes, coral reefs, and rich biodiversity. The island is a major tourist destination with a peaceful multicultural society. D is matched with 2 : Socotra, a Yemeni island in the Ara- bian Sea, is famous for its alien-like biodiversity and endemic species. Recognized as a UNESCO World Heritage Site, it fea- tures unique landscapes like limestone plateaus and granite mountains. 478","PW-0498":"If an observer sees the stars rising perpendicular to the horizon, they are positioned at the equator. At the Earth’s equator, stars appear to rise straight up from the eastern horizon, move directly overhead, and set in the west. This occurs because the Earth’s rotational axis is perpendicular to the observer’s horizon at this location. The celestial equator, which is an imaginary extension of Earth’s equator into space, perfectly aligns with the observer’s horizon. As a result, stars follow a vertical trajectory as they rise and set. In contrast, at other latitudes, such as the Tropic of Cancer, the North Pole, or the South Pole, stars rise and set at different an- gles due to the observer’s varying position on the globe and the tilt of the Earth. 479","PW-0499":"","PW-0500":"Dadra and Nagar Haveli, a union territory in western India, comprises two distinct parts: Nagar Haveli, bordered by Maharashtra and Gujarat, and Dadra, surrounded by Gujarat. Its predominantly tribal population includes the Dhodia, Kokna, and Varli tribes, with Gujarati, Hindi, Marathi, and tribal dialects widely spoken. The terrain varies from the hilly Sahyadri Moun- tains to plains traversed by the Daman Ganga River. 481","PW-0501":"A is correctly matched with 3 : Bishkek, the capital and largest city of Kyrgyzstan, is situated in the foothills of the Tian Shan mountains. It’s a relatively young city compared to others in Central Asia, having its origins in a 19th-century Rus- sian fort. B is correctly matched with 1 : Ashgabat, the capital of Turk- menistan, is located in the Karakum Desert. It’s a city that has undergone significant transformation in recent decades, with large-scale construction projects and the development of numer- ous white marble buildings, giving it a distinctive appearance. Ashgabat is known for its modern architecture, grand boule- vards, and numerous monuments. C is correctly matched with 2 : Tashkent, the capital of Uz- bekistan, is the largest city in Central Asia. It’s a city with a long and rich history, having been an important trading center on the Silk Road. Tashkent has experienced significant changes over time, including periods of Russian and Soviet rule. The city is now a major industrial, cultural, and educational center in Uzbekistan. Tashkent boasts a mix of architectural","PW-0502":"Yugoslavia : The Federal Republic of Yugoslavia, as it existed circa 2000, was a federation comprising Serbia and Montenegro. Geographically, it occupied the easternmost por- tion of the area in question, bordering the other listed entities. It is important to note that this federation was in the process of dissolution during this period i.e 2000. Bosnia : Bosnia and Herzegovina, often referred to simply as Bosnia, is located west of the former Yugoslavia. It is a country situated in Southeastern Europe, occupying a significant portion of the Balkan Peninsula. Its geography is characterized by moun- tainous terrain and diverse cultural influences. Croatia : The Republic of Croatia is situated further west than Bosnia and Herzegovina. Bordering the Adriatic Sea, it is also located in Southeastern Europe. Croatia is known for its exten- sive coastline, numerous islands, and historic cities, reflecting its complex history. Geography 463 Slovenia : The Republic of Slovenia is the westernmost of the four entities listed. Located in Central Europe, it is known for its mountainous landscape","PW-0503":"Lake Victoria is the largest lake in Africa and the larg- est tropical lake in the world. It is shared by three countries: Tanzania, Uganda, and Kenya. The lake’s boundaries serve as international borders, most notably between Tanzania and Uganda. Its significance extends beyond political boundaries, as it plays a crucial role in the regional ecosystem and serves as a vital resource for the surrounding populations. 485","PW-0504":"Maracaibo is a major city in northwestern Venezuela, situated on the western side of Lake Maracaibo, connected to the Gulf of Venezuela and the Caribbean Sea. Its strategic location and the discovery of vast oil reserves in the Maraca- ibo Basin have led to its development as a crucial port for the petroleum industry. Maracaibo serves as a primary hub for the export of crude oil and refined petroleum products, con- tributing significantly to Venezuela’s economy.  Caracas is the capital city of Venezuela, located in the northern part of the country. While Caracas is an important economic and political center, its primary function is not that of an oil port. The city is situated inland and, while it has access to the coast, it is not a major point of export for crude oil. Caracas functions as the center of government and administration, as well as a hub for various industries and services.  Maracay is a city in north-central Venezuela, located inland, southwest of Caracas. It is primarily known as an industrial and agricultural center. Maracay does not have a significant role as an o","PW-0505":"Assertion (A) is true : Chile holds a prominent posi- tion in the global copper market, consistently ranking among the top producers worldwide. Its copper mining industry is a significant contributor to the nation’s economy and plays a cru- cial role in supplying copper to meet global demand. This sus- tained high level of production underscores Chile’s importance in the international copper trade. Reason (R) is true : Chile possesses exceptionally large de- posits of porphyry copper, a type of ore deposit that is a pri- mary source of copper globally. These deposits are characterized by their large size and relatively low-grade ore, but their sheer scale makes them economically viable for large-scale mining operations. The abundance of porphyry copper deposits in Chile is the fundamental reason for its substantial copper production and its leading role in the world market. The geological endowment of this resource directly explains Chile’s capacity to produce such significant quantities of copper. Thus, both A and R are true and R is the correct explanation of A. 487","PW-0506":"A is correctly matched with 1 : Darwin, the capital of Australia’s Northern Territory, is a city situated on the Timor Sea. Its geographical location in the far north of the con- tinent gives it a tropical climate characterized by distinct wet and dry seasons. B is correctly matched with 2 : Kuala Lumpur, the capital of Malaysia, is a bustling metropolis located on the west coast of the Malay Peninsula. The city experiences a tropical climate with consistently high rainfall throughout the year. C is correctly matched with 4 : Lagos, the largest city in Ni- geria, is a sprawling urban center situated on the coast of the Gulf of Guinea in the southwestern part of the country. The city’s climate is tropical, marked by distinct wet and dry seasons. As the economic powerhouse of Nigeria, Lagos boasts a substan- tial industrial sector, with significant activity in the petroleum industry and various manufacturing enterprises. D is correctly matched with 3 : Nairobi, the capital of Kenya, is located in the southern part of the country, situated on a high plateau. This elevated position moder","PW-0507":"1 is matched with Andes Mountains : The Andes Mountains, a powerful mountain range stretching along the western edge of South America, are geologically young and tec- tonically active. They were formed by the subduction of the Naz- ca Plate beneath the South American Plate. The range is known for its towering peaks, including Aconcagua, the highest moun- tain in the Americas. 2 is matched with Brazilian Shield : The Brazilian Shield is a large geological region covering much of eastern and central Bra- zil. Made up of ancient Precambrian rocks, this stable area has been shaped by millions of years of erosion, resulting in rolling hills, plateaus, and escarpments. Rich in minerals like iron ore, gold, manganese, and diamonds, the Brazilian Shield has played a key role in the development of Brazil’s mining industry. 3 is matched with Guyana Highlands : The Guyana Highlands, a plateau and mountain range in northern South America, stretch across Guyana, Venezuela, Brazil, Suriname, and French Guiana. Known for its ancient crystalline rocks and unique table-top mountains called tepuis, th","PW-0508":"Option (b) is correct : Indian Standard Time (I.S.T.) is based on the meridian 82°30’ E, which is the reference for I.S.T. If it is noon (12:00 PM) at I.S.T., and people at another place are having 6:00 AM morning tea, that means the time difference be- tween the two places is 6 hours. To calculate the longitude difference :  A time difference of 1 hour corresponds to a 15° difference in longitude.  Therefore, a 6-hour difference corresponds to a 90° difference in longitude (6 × 15°). Since the other place is 6 hours behind I.S.T., it must be 90° to the west of the I.S.T. meridian.  I.S.T. The meridian is at 82°30’ E, so moving 90° to the west brings us to 7°30’ W. Thus, the place is at a longitude of 7°30’ W. 493","PW-0509":" Indian Standard Time (IST) is UTC +5:30 hours, based on the longitude 82°30’ E.  The International Date Line (IDL) is at approximately 180° longitude.  The difference in longitude between the IDL (180°) and the IST meridian (82°30’ E) is 97°30’ (180° – 82°30’). Time difference calculation :  15° of longitude corresponds to 1 hour of time difference.  97°30’ corresponds to 6 hours and 30 minutes (97.5° ÷ 15° = 6.5 hours). Normal Earth Rotation (West to East) :  When it is 12:00 noon at the IDL, it would be 05:30 AM (IST) (because IST is ahead of IDL by 6 hours 30 minutes). Reversed Rotation (East to West) : If the Earth rotates in the opposite direction, the time difference reverses. Instead of being ahead, IST will lag behind the IDL by 6 hours and 30 minutes.  When it is 12:00 noon at the IDL, it will be 6:30 PM (18:30 IST). 494","PW-0510":"The coastal regions of California(1), particularly cen- tral and southern California, have a textbook Mediterranean climate. Hot dry summers, mild wet winters, and the character- istic chaparral vegetation are all hallmarks of this climate type. Therefore, California is the most accurate representation of a region with a Mediterranean climate. A Mediterranean climate is characterized by :  Hot, Dry Summers: Temperatures are warm to hot, with little to no rainfall.  Mild, Wet Winters: Winters are cool to mild, with moderate to heavy rainfall.  Seasonal Rainfall Pattern: Most of the annual rainfall occurs in the winter months.  Clear Skies and Sunshine: Summers are typically sunny with low humidity.  Vegetation: Common plants include olive trees, grapevines, shrubs, and evergreen trees, adapted to dry summers. This climate is found in regions like the Mediterranean Ba- sin, California, central Chile, southwestern Australia, and parts of South Africa. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 466 495","PW-0511":"","PW-0512":"","PW-0513":"","PW-0514":"“A” matches with “Iraq” : The Republic of Iraq is typ- ically situated to the east of Syria and south of Turkey. It shares borders with Iran to the east, Saudi Arabia and Kuwait to the south, Jordan to the west, and Syria to the northwest. Iraq is characterized by the fertile plains of the Tigris and Euphrates river valleys, which have been the cradle of civilization for mil- lennia. The country also includes desert regions and mountain- ous areas in the north. “B” is matched with “Syria”: The Syrian Arab Republic is lo- cated in the northwestern part of the Middle East. It borders Turkey to the north, Lebanon and Israel to the west, Jordan to the south, and Iraq to the east. Syria’s geography includes coastal plains along the Mediterranean Sea, mountainous regions in the west, and desert areas in the east. “C” is matched with “Saudi Arabia”: The Kingdom of Saudi Ara- bia occupies the majority of the Arabian Peninsula. It is the largest country in the Middle East and shares borders with sev- eral nations, including Jordan, Iraq, and Kuwait to the north, Yemen and Oman to the south, a","PW-0515":"Option (d) is correct : The location marked “D” is Jaffna. Jaffna, located on the northernmost peninsula of Sri Lanka, is a re- gion of significant geographic and cultural importance. The Jaffna Peninsula, connected to the rest of the island by a narrow isth- mus, juts out into the Palk Strait, separating Sri Lanka from India. 10. MISCELLANEOUS 500","PW-0516":"","PW-0517":"Mahogany is a tropical hardwood tree native to the Americas. Known for its reddish-brown timber, which is dura- ble, beautiful, and easy to work with, mahogany is highly valued in furniture making, cabinetry, and boatbuilding. However, it is not naturally found in the Himalayan region. The climatic and environmental conditions of the Himalayas are unsuitable for its growth, so any presence of mahogany there would be the result of human introduction rather than natural occurrence. 502","PW-0518":"Option (b) is correct : As of 2008, the four Indian bio- sphere reserves recognized under UNESCO’s World Network of Biosphere Reserves (WNBR) were : 1. Nilgiri Biosphere Reserve (2000) 2. Gulf of Mannar Biosphere Reserve (2001) 3. Sundarbans Biosphere Reserve (2001) 4","PW-0519":"Statement 1 is correct : The Visakhapatnam Steel Plant (RINL), also known as Vizag Steel, is a prominent integrated steel producer located in Visakhapatnam, Andhra Pradesh, India. By the year 2007, RINL had been granted “Mini Ratna” status by the Indian government. This designation recognizes the compa- ny’s strong performance and gives it greater autonomy in finan- cial and operational decision-making. Statement 2 is correct : In 2006, The Indian Iron and Steel Company (IISCO), formerly an independent entity, was success- fully merged with the Steel Authority of India Limited (SAIL). SAIL, a major public sector steel producer in India, undertook this merger to consolidate its operations, enhance efficiency, and streamline its production processes. The merger of IISCO with SAIL has integrated the resources and expertise of both organiza- tions, creating a larger and more robust entity within the Indian steel sector. 504","PW-0520":"Statement 1 is correct : National Thermal Power Cor- poration (NTPC) has diversified into the hydropower sector as part of its efforts to expand into more environmentally friendly energy sources. It has undertaken projects like the Koldam Hy- dro Electric Power Project in Himachal Pradesh and other hydropower projects in Uttarakhand and West Bengal. Addi- tionally, NTPC has acquired stakes in hydro-focused companies like THDC India and NEEPCO, further expanding its hydropower portfolio. Statement 2 is correct : Power Grid Corporation of India (PG- CIL) has diversified into the telecom sector through its subsidi- ary, Power Grid Teleservices Limited, under the brand name PowerTel. It uses its extensive transmission network for laying optical fiber cables and offers telecom services, including leasing bandwidth to telecom operators. 506","PW-0521":"Anthracite is a hard, brittle coal characterized by its high carbon content, typically ranging from 86% to 98%. It is considered the most metamorphosed type of coal, meaning it has undergone the most intense heat and pressure during its formation. This high carbon content makes anthracite the clean- est-burning type of coal, producing very little smoke or volatile matter. It is often referred to as “hard coal” and burns with a short, blue flame. Due to its cleaner-burning properties, an- thracite is a preferred fuel source where minimizing air pol- lution is a priority. However, its relative scarcity and higher cost compared to other coal types limit its widespread use. 508","PW-0522":"Otto Schmidt, a Soviet geophysicist and astronomer, proposed a theory for the origin of the Earth and other planets in the solar system based on a cloud of gas and dust particles. His hypothesis, known as the “dust cloud hypothesis”, sug- gested that the Sun, while already formed, captured or interact- ed with a surrounding cloud of interstellar material. This cloud, composed of gas, dust, and ice particles, began to rotate and flat- ten under the influence of the Sun’s gravity. Within this rotating disk, particles collided and clumped together, gradually forming larger and larger bodies. v v v","PW-0523":"Alfalfa, chickpea, and clover are nitrogen-fixing plants. They belong to the leguminous family and form symbi- otic associations with Rhizobium bacteria in their root nodules, aiding in nitrogen fixation and enriching soil fertility. Amaranth, purslane (Kulfa), and spinach, are non-legumi- nous plants and lack the ability to fix nitrogen as they do not form symbiotic relationships with nitrogen-fixing bacteria or develop root nodules. This natural ability of legumes like al- falfa, chickpea, and clover to fix nitrogen is extensively utilized in crop rotation practices to replenish soil nutrients and enhance agricultural productivity. 2","PW-0524":"Lichens and Mosses do not need soil to grow and sur- vive.  Lichens are generally found on rock, tree bark, soil (but can survive without soil as well), houses, tombstones, cars, old farm equipment, etc. Thus, lichen can be found surviving on surfaces without soil.  Mosses are non-vascular plants. They do not need soil to survive.  They have a rhizoid multi-cell anchoring structure that is used to climb and grip over rocky surfaces. Moss thrives in moist and shady areas. Ferns and Mushrooms generally need soil to grow.  Ferns are vascular plants and typically require soil for anchorage and to absorb water and nutrients. While they can grow in places like cracks in rocks, they usually still need some form of substrate (soil or organic material) to thrive.  A mushroom is the fleshy, spore-bearing fruiting body of a fungus. They typically require organic matter to decompose as a source of nutrients. Mushrooms are unlikely to grow on a surface without soil unless there is some decaying organic material available. SUPER HINT Observed Logic means using your real-life observations, eve","PW-0525":"Primary Producers are organisms like plants and algae that produce their own food through photosynthesis or chemo- synthesis. They form the base of the food chain in marine eco- systems. Cyanobacteria and Diatoms are primary producers.  Cyanobacteria (also known as blue-green algae) are photosynthetic bacteria that play a significant role in marine ecosystems by converting sunlight into energy and producing oxygen. They are particularly important in nutrient-poor (oligotrophic) oceanic regions.  Diatoms are a type of phytoplankton that perform photosynthesis. They are among the most important primary producers in the oceans which contribute significantly to global carbon fixation. They are a key food source for zooplankton and other marine organisms. Copepods and Foraminifera are consumers.  Copepods are small crustaceans that are not primary producers. They are zooplankton that feed on phytoplankton (primary producers) and other small organisms. They play a crucial role in marine food webs as a link between primary producers and higher trophic levels.  Foraminifera are not prima","PW-0526":"Detritivores also known as detritivores, detritophag- es, detritus feeders, or detritus eaters are heterotrophs that obtain nutrients by consuming detritus (decomposing plant and animal parts as well as feces). By doing so, all these detritivores contribute to decomposition and the nutrient cycles. Option (c) is correct: Earthworms, Millipedes and Woodlice are Detritivores. Detritivores are an important aspect of many ecosystems. They can live on any type of soil with an organic component, including marine ecosystems, where they are termed interchangeably with bottom feeders. Typical detritivorous animals include earth- worm, millipedes, springtails, woodlice, dung flies, slugs, many terrestrial worms, sea stars, sea cucumbers, fiddler crabs, and some sedentary polychaetes such as worms of the family Terebellidae. 5","PW-0527":"The phosphorus cycle is unique for not have a signifi- cant atmospheric component. Phosphorus is primarily released into the cycle through the weathering of rocks containing phos- phate minerals (e.g., apatite). Weathering releases phosphate ions (PO₄³⁻) into soil and water, making it available for uptake by plants and other organisms. Phosphorus is one of the most im- portant nutrients in biological systems since it is a fundamental ingredient of nucleic acids, phospholipids, and several phosphor- ylated compounds. 6","PW-0528":"All of the given species can establish a symbiotic re- lationship with other organisms. Symbiotic Relationship:  A relationship between two (or more) species that may or may not be advantageous to one or both is referred to as symbiotic.  Symbiosis typically occurs between different species. Interactions within the same species (intraspecific) are usually not categorized as symbiosis but may involve other forms of cooperation. For eg., Coral has a symbiotic relationship (each gives something to the other and gets something back in return) with ‘zooxanthellae’ microscopic algae which live on coral. Option 1 is correct: The relationship between cnidarians and dinoflagellate algae is termed “symbiotic” because both the an- imal host and the algae are benefiting from the association. It is a mutualistic interaction. Option 2 is correct: Two common mutualistic relationships in- volving fungi are mycorrhiza (fungi and plant roots) and lichen (fungi and either cyanobacteria or green algae). Option 3 is correct: Protozoa mostly represent a close mutual- istic association between a protozoa","PW-0529":"Reservoir Volume (Million Cubic km) Percentage of the Total Oceans 1,370 97.25 Ice caps and Glaciers 29 2.05 Groundwater 9.5 0.68 Lakes 0.125 0.01 Soil Moisture 0.065 0.005 Atmosphere 0.013 0.001 Streams and Rivers 0.0017 0.0001 Biosphere 0.0006 0.00004 Water makes up about 71% of the Earth’s surface, while the oth- er 29% consists of continents and islands. Oceans and Seas make up 97% of the Earth’s water and only about 2.5% is in the form of freshwater. 71 % of earth surface constitutes water & only 29 % constitutes a land area of earth. 97 % of water area constitutes Oceans & Seas & 2.5 % as freshwater. Statement 1 is incorrect: Fresh Water distribution is as given below: Ice Caps and Glaciers > Groundwater >Lakes Ice & Snow > Soil Moisture > Atmosphere > Rivers and Streams. Statement 2 is correct: While about 69% of earth’s freshwa- ter is in ice caps and glacier, groundwater has about 30% of earth’s freshwater. Kakes, Rivers and swamps etc make up the remaining 1%. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 472 While 75 % of freshwater is in glaciers & ice caps, only 7 % of freshwater is groundwater.","PW-0530":"Both warm and mid-latitude deserts have a predomi- nance of xerophytic or drought-resistant plants. This compris- es cacti, thorny bushes, wiry grasses with extensive roots, and scattered dwarf acacias. Option (d) is correct: In order to gather moisture and search for ground water, the majority of desert shrubs have lengthy roots that are widely distributed. These plants typically have a few (or no leaves) tiny, needle-shaped, waxy, leathery leaves or hairy foliage to reduce water loss through transpiration. 9","PW-0531":"MSTrIPES stands for Monitoring system for Tigers – Intensive Protection and Ecological Status.M-STrIPES was launched in 2010 by NTCA and WII across Indian tiger reserves. It is a software-based monitoring system, designed to assist wild- life protection. The system consists of two components:  Field based methods for ecological monitoring, law enforcement, recording wildlife offences, and patrolling.  A specialised GIS application for reporting, analysis, and data storage. Forest guards are required to use a GPS to track their movements as part of MSTrIPES, in addition to entering their observations on site-specific data sheets. 10","PW-0532":"An ecosystem can be defined as a functional unit of nature, where living organisms (producers, consumers, and de- composers) interact among themselves and also with the sur- rounding physical environment. Ecosystems can be of any size and usually encompasses a diverse range of species. E.g. Aquatic Ecosystem. In the ecosystem, biotic and abiotic components are linked together through nutrient cycles and energy flows. Ev- erything that lives in an ecosystem is dependent on the other species and elements that are also part of that ecological com- munity. A damaged or extinct component of an ecosystem has an effect on the entire system. 11","PW-0533":"Decomposers are organisms that primarily feed on dead organisms or the waste from living organisms. Some organ- isms perform a similar function as decomposers, and are some- times called detritivores. The difference lies in the way decomposers and detritivores break down organic material. Detritivores must digest organic material within their bodies in order to break it down and gain nutrients from it. Decomposers do not need to digest organic ma- terial internally in order to break it down. Fungi and Bacteria are examples of decomposers. Scavengers are the one among the first to arrive at a dead organism’s remains. It includes jack- als, wolves, raccoons, and opossums. 12","PW-0534":"","PW-0535":"Productivity is the rate of biomass production. It is measured in mass per unit volume per unit time. The quantity of biomass or organic matter created by plants during photosyn- thesis per unit area during a certain time is referred to as pri- mary production. Gross primary productivity of an ecosystem is the rate of production of organic matter during photosynthesis. A considerable amount of GPP is utilized by plants in respiration. Option (c) is correct: The correct sequence of ecosystems in decreasing order of productivity is Mangroves > Grasslands > Lakes > Oceans  Mangroves have the highest productivity due to abundant nutrients, tidal action, and high photosynthetic rates making them crucial breeding grounds for marine life (NPP: ~2000 gC/m²/year).  Grasslands follow, as they receive ample sunlight but have moderate water availability, supporting rapid grass growth (NPP: ~600–1500 gC/m²/year).  Lakes are less productive than grasslands because nutrient availability varies with depth and type (eutrophic lakes are more productive than oligotrophic ones) (NPP: ~300–1000 gC/m²/","PW-0536":"Food Chain is the successive transfer of nutrients and energy from one creature to another. A food chain shows a straightforward relationship and only one component of the food or energy flow. E.g. Grasses → Grasshopper → Frog → Snake → Hawk/Eagle. Statement 1 is correct: A food chain is a linear flow of energy and nutrients from one organism to another. Primary producers → primary consumers → secondary con- sumers → tertiary consumers. Statements 2 and 3 are incorrect:  Food chains are not limited to a single species or population. They involve multiple species across different trophic levels (e.g., producers, primary consumers, secondary consumers). A food chain represents interactions between different species, not within a single population.  A food chain does not illustrate the numbers of organisms eaten by others. It shows the sequence of energy transfer and feeding relationships. The number of organisms at each trophic level is better represented by a food web or ecological pyramid (e.g., pyramid of numbers, pyramid of biomass). 15","PW-0537":"","PW-0538":"About 71% of the earth’s surface is covered with water. Out of the total water present on the planet earth, the majority is in the form of seas and oceans (more than 97%) and is termed as saline water. While the remaining water is termed as freshwater. Option (c) is correct: The decreasing order of proportion of freshwater in different forms: Snow caps, icebergs and glaciers → groundwater → soil moistures → freshwater lakes → atmo- sphere → rivers. Groundwater makes the largest portion of freshwater after freshwater that exists as ice caps and glaciers. 17","PW-0539":"Millennium Ecosystem Assessment (MA) was initi- ated in 2001 by the United Nations. The objective of the MA was to evaluate how changing ecosystems might affect human well-being as well as the scientific foundation for any necessary action to improve the systems’ conservation and sustainable us- age, as well as their contribution to human well-being. ​Ecosystem services to the society are in the form of: UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 474 1. Provisioning services: food, raw materials, genetic resources, water, etc 2. Regulating services: carbon sequestration and climate regulation 3. Cultural services: tourism and religion 4. Supporting services: that are necessary for the production of all other ecosystem services such as nutrient recycling,crop pollination and soil formation, etc. 18","PW-0540":"Phytoplanktons are the primary producers in the ma- rine food chain and hence they are called the ‘grass of the sea’. They contribute more than half of the oxygen in the environment and help in reducing global warming by absorbing human-in- duced carbon dioxide. They are important bioindicators regulat- ing life in oceAns: Statements 1 is correct: If phytoplankton are destroyed then less CO₂ will be absorbed thereby increasing atmospheric carbon and contributing to global warming. Phytoplankton are responsi- ble for carbon fixation through photosynthesis. They absorb CO₂ from the atmosphere and convert it into organic matter. When phytoplankton die, some of this carbon sinks to the ocean floor, sequestering it for long periods. Statements 2 is correct: Phytoplankton are the primary produc- ers in marine ecosystems forming the base of the food web. They are consumed by zooplankton which in turn are eaten by larger organisms like fish, marine mammals, and seabirds. The destruc- tion of phytoplankton would disrupt the entire marine food chain and can lead to the collapse of fisheries an","PW-0541":"Upwelling is a process in which deep, cold water of the ocean rises toward the surface. Winds blowing across the ocean surface push water away. Water then rises up from beneath the surface to replace the water that was pushed away. This process is known as “upwelling.” Statement 1 is incorrect: Decomposer microorganisms pri- marily reside in the deep ocean and play a role in breaking down organic matter. Upwelling does not bring decomposers to the surface. Most decomposition occurs at depth and decomposer microbes are not significantly transported to the surface by up- welling. Statement 2 is correct: Upwelling regions bring nutrients like nitrogen, phosphorus, and iron from deep waters to the sur- face. These nutrients enhance phytoplankton growth which supports higher trophic levels such as fish and marine mammals. Major upwelling zones include the coasts of Peru, California, and West Africa. These regions contribute to high fishery productivity (Ex: Peru- vian anchovy fishery). Statement 3 is incorrect: Bottom-dwelling (benthic) organ- isms such as crustaceans and mollusks are not","PW-0542":"Tropical rainforests and tropical deciduous forests dif- fer in their nutrient cycles, soil composition, and regenera- tion capacity. When a tropical rainforest is removed, it does not regenerate quickly because of the nutrient-poor soil. In trop- ical rainforests, the warm and humid conditions promote rapid decomposition of organic matter by bacteria and fungi. But due to the high density of plant life the nutrients released are im- mediately absorbed by plants leaving the soil infertile. In contrast the tropical deciduous forests have richer soils be- cause the leaf litter decomposes and replenishes soil nutrients more effectively. Options (b), (c) and (d) are incorrect:  Propagules (seeds, spores, or other reproductive structures) of rainforest trees generally have high viability. However, the regeneration of rainforests is hindered more by soil nutrient deficiencies than by the viability of propagules.  Many rainforest species are fast-growing especially pioneer species that colonize disturbed areas. However, the lack of nutrients in the soil limits their growth and the overall","PW-0543":"This increasing concentration of a toxic substance as it moves up the food chain is known as biomagnification. Pred- ators at the highest trophic levels like hawks suffer the most severe effects, including reproductive issues, weakened immune systems, and neurological damage due to the high pesticide load. When a chlorinated hydrocarbon pesticide like DDT enters the food chain, it accumulates in fatty tissues through bioaccumu- lation. As predators consume contaminated prey, the pesticide concentration increases, peaking in top predators due to biomag- nification. Thus in the above food chain—Food crop → Rat → Snake → Hawk—the hawk experiences the highest pesticide concen- tration. 22","PW-0544":"Keystone species play a crucial role in maintaining eco- system structure and function, having a disproportionate impact relative to their abundance. Like the keystone in an arch, they support the stability of the entire system. These species influence population sizes, modify the environment, and affect species di- versity and community composition. Removing a keystone spe- cies can disrupt the ecosystem, leading to biodiversity loss and instability. Some of the Keystone Species are: Sea Otters(kelp forest ecosystem). Wolves and other top predators(Grassland ecosystem), Elephants(Savannah), Beavers and Starfish. Options (b), (c) and (d) are incorrect:  Allopatric species are species that evolve separately due to geographic isolation, Eg. African and Indian elephants.  Sympatric species are species that evolve separately within the same geographic area.  Threatened species are species at risk of becoming endangered in the near future due to factors like habitat loss, climate change, and human activities. 23","PW-0545":"National forest policy 1988 was introduced with the principal aim of ensuring environmental stability and maintaining ecologi- cal balance including atmospheric equilibrium which are vital for sustenance of all life forms, human, animal and plant. Key objectives of National Forest Policy 1988 are:  Increasing substantially the forest/tree cover in the country through massive afforestation, reforestation and social forestry programmes  Encouraging efficient utilisation of forest produce and maximising substitution of wood.  Checking soil erosion and denudation in the catchment areas of rivers, lakes, reservoirs.  However, the National Forest Policy of 1988 does not promote the wide use of insecticides and pesticides. Instead, it emphasizes the importance of maintaining a balanced ecosystem and preserving biodiversity within forests. 2. BIODIVERSITY 24","PW-0546":"","PW-0547":"Marsupials are a group of mammals commonly referred to as pouched mammals, such as kangaroos and wallabies. These animals are characterized by giving birth to underde- veloped young, which then continue their development in the mother's pouch (marsupium). They give live birth, but they do not have long gestation times like placental mammals. The pouch provides protection and access to nourishment during this critical growth stage. Statement-I is correct: Marsupials can be observed in regions spanning Australia, Papua New Guinea, and South America. They are not naturally found in India. Examples of marsupials include kangaroos, wallabies, wombats, opossums, bandicoots, and koalas. Statement-II is incorrect: These creatures predominantly in- habit arid and semi-arid areas, and they are not restricted solely to montane grasslands. Marsupials are highly adapt- able and thrive in a variety of habitats, including forests, deserts, grasslands. Additionally, they coexist with predators like dingoes, eagles, and foxes in their natural environments. SUPER HINT \"ONLY' is strong phrase. Also, ag","PW-0548":"Option 1 is incorrect: Lion-tailed Macaque, also re- ferred to as the wanderoo, inhabits the upper canopy of tropical evergreen rainforests and monsoon forests across various ele- vations. This species is endemic to the Western Ghats. They are diurnal which means it is active during the day and not nocturnal. IUCN Red List: Endangered Option 2 is correct: Malabar Civet is endemic to the Western Ghats of India. It is listed as Critically Endangered on the IUCN Red List. The Malabar civet is considered nocturnal and so elu- sive that little is known about its biology and ecology apart from habitat use. IUCN Red List: Critically Endangered Option 3 is incorrect: The Sambar, a large deer native to the Indian subcontinent and Southeast Asia, is crepuscular, active during twilight (morning and evening), and occasionally after sunset. Males are mostly solitary while females form small herds of up to 16 individuals. IUCN Red List: Vulnerable 27","PW-0549":"The waggle dance is a unique form of communication performed by honey bees (Apis mellifera) to convey information about the direction and distance of food sources, water, or poten- tial nesting sites to other members of their hive. Worker honey- bees, all of which are females, constitute the only bees typically observed flying outside the hive by the general populace. Bees perform two distinct types of dances: The Round Dance and the Tail-wagging or Waggle Dance. The waggle dance of honeybees has long been recognized as a behaviour that communicates in- formation about resource location from a foraging worker to her nest mates. 28","PW-0550":"Microorganisms are classified into three primary groups on the basis of their preferred range of temperature:  Psychrophiles (cold-loving microbes)  Mesophiles (moderate - temperature - loving microbes)  Thermophiles (heat-loving microbes). Statement 1 is correct: Hyperthermophiles such as Pyrobolus and Pyrodictium can grow at temperatures exceeding 100°C es- pecially in high-pressure environments like deep-sea hydrother- mal vents. Statement 2 is correct: Psychrophiles such as Colwellia psy- chrerythraea and Pseudomonas syringae can grow at tempera- tures as low as -10°C and remain metabolically active even at -20°C in environments like Arctic permafrost, deep-sea polar waters, and glacial ice. These microbes produce cryoprotectants such as antifreeze proteins to prevent ice crystal formation in- side their cells. Statement 3 is correct: Acidophiles such as Ferroplasma acidar- manus and Acidithiobacillus ferrooxidans thrive in environments with pH as low as 0.5, such as acidic hot springs, acid mine drain- ages, and volcanic sulfur pools. These microbes have evolved mechanisms to","PW-0551":"Orangutans are highly intelligent great apes known for their tool-using abilities. They have been observed breaking off small branches and using them as tools to scrape insects from holes in trees or logs. This behavior demonstrates their advanced cognitive skills, problem-solving abilities, and adaptability in for- aging. None of the other listed animals. Environment and Ecology 477 30","PW-0552":"Statement 1 is correct: In India, Biodiversity Man- agement Committees (BMCs) are established at the local level under the Biological Diversity Act, 2002. The National Biodi- versity Authority (NBA) and State Biodiversity Boards (SBBs) work with BMCs to regulate access to biological resources and traditional knowledge, ensuring compliance with the Nagoya Protocol. Statement 2 is correct: Biological Diversity Act, 2002 em- powers BMCs to determine Access and Benefit Sharing (ABS) mechanisms for biological resources found within their jurisdic- tion. They can levy collection fees on any person or entity ac- cessing biological resources for commercial use. 31","PW-0553":"Lemongrass is a tall herb that is widely distributed in tropical and subtropical regions of Asia, Africa, and Australia. Lemongrass is most frequently produced in China and India. The lemongrass herb is well known for its effectiveness at warding off mosquitoes and works as a mosquito repellent. It contains the chemical citronella, which aids in disguising the smells that mosquitoes use to target victims. A 2011 study found that the strong odour of lemongrass oil effectively killed or fully repelled more than 90% of the mosquitoes from a particular range of species. 32","PW-0554":"Savanna Biome is a particular kind of grassland biome made up of vast expanses of open grassland with few trees. Tropical and Semi-tropical savannas are two kinds of sa- vannas. All continents excluding Antarctica have grasslands. The largest savannas are found close to the equator in Africa. Option (c) is correct:  Frequent wildfires both natural (lightning-induced) and human-induced prevent the establishment of dense forests. Fires destroy young tree saplings before they can mature into large trees, thus maintaining grasslands. Savanna fires are a key ecological process that helps maintain the balance between grasslands and scattered trees.  Large herbivores like elephants, zebras, and antelopes feed on young tree shoots, preventing forests from expanding. Grazing by animals ensures that tree cover remains sparse which allows grasses to dominate. Studies on African and Indian savannas have shown that herbivory is a critical limiting factor for tree growth.  The limited and unpredictable rainfall pattern allows grasses to outcompete trees for available water. Savannas experience ","PW-0555":"Transfer of pollen grains (shed from the anther) to the stigma of a pistil is termed pollination. Flowering plants have evolved an amazing array of adaptations to achieve pollination. Depending on the source of pollen, pollination is divided into three types, i. e. Autogamy, Geitonogamy and Xenogamy. Statement 1 is correct: Butterflies are important pollinators for many flowering plants. Plant species particularly those that produce brightly colored, scented flowers with deep nectar tubes are adapted to butterfly pollination. A drastic fall in butterfly populations would result in reduced pollination, affecting plant reproduction and possibly leading to a decline in the popula- tion of such plant species. Statement 2 is incorrect: There is no direct link between butterfly populations and fungal infections in cultivated plants. Fungal infections are influenced by factors like humidity, temperature, plant health, and soil conditions rather than by the presence or absence of butterflies. Statement 3 is correct: Butterflies form a crucial part of the food chain, serving as prey for birds","PW-0556":"The Western Ghats Ecology Expert Panel (WGEEP), also known as Gadgil Committee was chaired by Prof. Madhav Gadgil. It was established by the Ministry of Environment & For- ests in 2010 and submitted its report in 2011. The panel was con- stituted to primarily demarcate ecologically sensitive areas in the Western Ghats and recommended measures for the management of these ecologically sensitive areas. The Kasturirangan com- mittee was constituted to examine the WGEEP report in 2012. The key recommendations were:  Declaring the entire Western Ghats as an Ecologically Sensitive Area (ESA).  Dividing the region into three zones (Ecologically Sensitive Zones 1, 2, and 3), with strict regulations on mining, industries, and land-use changes.  Implementing bottom-up democratic decision-making by involving local communities in conservation efforts.  Banning large-scale developmental projects in sensitive zones. 35","PW-0557":"Statement 1 is correct: The National Biodiversity Authority(NBA) plays a crucial role in preventing biopiracy which is the unauthorized use of biological resources or tradi- tional knowledge without fair compensation or consent. The NBA ensures that access to India's biological resources (in- cluding agricultural crops, medicinal plants, and traditional knowledge) is regulated. This helps protect India's indige- nous and traditional genetic resources from exploitation by foreign entities or corporations. Statement 2 is incorrect: NBA does not directly supervise sci- entific research on genetic modification (GM) of crops. The regu- lation of Genetically Modified (GM) crops falls under the Genetic Engineering Appraisal Committee (GEAC) which functions un- der the Ministry of Environment, Forest and Climate Change. Statement 3 is correct: The NBA’s approval is mandatory be- fore filing any Intellectual Property Rights (IPR) application for patents related to biological resources originating in In- dia. This prevents foreign companies from claiming patents on Indian plants, seeds, and tr","PW-0558":"The IUCN Red List of “threatened species” is the world’s most comprehensive inventory of the global conserva- tion status of plant and animal species, which is a grouping of three categories: Critically Endangered, Endangered, and Vulner- able. Statement 1 is incorrect: The Red Data Books primary purpose is not to catalog endemic species in biodiversity hotspots. Its focus is on the conservation status of species, par- ticularly those that are threatened (vulnerable, endangered, or critically endangered). Statement 2 is correct: The purpose of the Red Data Books is to provide a detailed list of threatened species, including plants and animals. These species are categorized based on their risk of extinction, using criteria such as population size, rate of decline, and geographic range. Statement 3 is incorrect: The Red Data Books do not focus on listing protected sites or conservation areas. Information about protected sites (such as national parks, wildlife sanctu- aries, or biosphere reserves) is typically found in other publi- cations or databases, such as the World Database on Pro","PW-0559":"Ex Situ Conservation In Situ Conservation  Ex situ conservation is the preservation of biodiversity away from their natural habitats. Here, zoological or botanical parks are places where animals and plants are raised or grown.  In situ conservation refers to the preservation of plants and animals in their natural environments. Environment and Ecology 479  Another method of ex situ conservation is the reintroduction of an animal or plant into its former environment. For instance,  This includes the establishment of: 1. National parks and sanctuaries 2. Biosphere reserves  the extinct Gangetic Gharial has been brought back into the rivers of Uttar Pradesh, Madhya Pradesh, and Rajasthan. 3. Nature reserves 4. Reserved and protected forests 5. Preservation plots 6. Reserved forests  Important locations for ex situ conservation include seed banks, botanical, horticultural, and recreational gardens. 38","PW-0560":"Biodiversity Hotspot are regions with high species richness and a high degree of endemism. In 1988, the British bi- ologist Norman Myers coined the term “biodiversity hotspot” as a biogeographic region characterized both by exceptional lev- els of plant endemism and by serious levels of habitat loss and provided certain qualifications for a hotspot. Options 1, 3 and 5 are correct: In 1989, Conservation Inter- national (CI) adopted Myers’ hotspots as its institutional mod- el. Western Ghats-Sri Lanka and Indo-Burma Region meets the Myers’ criterion to qualify as Biodiversity Hotspot:  Species richness and endemism is one of the major criteria which must contain at least 1,500 species of vascular plants (> 0.5% of the world’s total) as endemics.  ‘Degree of Threat’ is also a major criteria for the recognition of biological hotspots. It has to have lost at least 70% of its original habitat. (It must have 30% or less of its original natural vegetation). In other words, it must be threatened. Options 2, 4 and 6 are incorrect: Vegetation density, ethno-bo- tanical importance and adaptati","PW-0561":"The diversity of plants and animals varies widely over the world. The tropics are home to more species than temperate or polar regions. Statement 1 is correct: Species diversity decreases as we move away from the equator towards the pole. This is due to several reasons:  Lower latitudes experience warmer temperatures and more stable climates, which support a greater variety of life forms.  The equatorial regions receive more consistent and intense sunlight throughout the year, leading to higher primary productivity (photosynthesis) and thus more diverse ecosystems.  Tropical regions, such as rainforests, have complex habitats with multiple layers (canopy, understory, forest floor) which support a wide range of species.  Tropical regions have remained relatively stable over geological time, allowing species to diversify over millions of years. Statement 2 is correct: Elevational diversity gradient (EDG) is an ecological pattern where biodiversity changes with eleva- tion. The EDG states that species richness tends to increase as elevation increases, up to a certain point, creating","PW-0562":"Biodiversity provides a number of natural services for human beings which are listed in the table below: Ecosystem Services  Protection of water resources  Soil formation and protection  Nutrient storage and recycling  Pollution breakdown and absorption  Contribution to climate stability  Maintenance of ecosystems  Recovery from unpredictable events Biological Services  Food  Medicinal resources and pharmaceutical drugs  Wood products  Ornamental plants  Pollination of crops  Breeding stocks  Diversity in genes, species and ecosystems Social Ser- vices  Research, education and monitoring  Recreation and tourism  Cultural values UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 480 41","PW-0563":"Being a confluence of different biogeographical zones Himalayan Range is very rich in species diversity. ​The Himalayas act as a natural transition zone between several major bio- geographical regions, leading to high species diversity and endemism. ​There are ten biogeographic zones in India: 1. Trans-Himalayan zone. 2. Himalayan zone 3. Desert zone. 4. Semi Arid zone. 5. Western ghat zone. 6. Deccan plateau zone. 7. Gangetic plain zone. 8. North east zone. 9. Coastal zone 10. Islands 42","PW-0564":"Biodiversity hotspot concept is promoted by Conser- vation international. Each biodiversity hot spot represents a re- markable universe of extraordinary floral and faunal endemic-ity struggling to survive in rapidly shrinking ecosystems. To qualify as a hotspot, a region must meet two strict criteria:  Species endemism: It must contain at least 1,500 species of vascular plants (> 0.5% of the world’s total) as endemics, and  Degree of threat: It has to have lost at least 70% of its original habitat. Statements 1 and 2 are incorrect:  Biodiversity hotspots aren’t limited to tropical regions; examples include the Mediterranean Basin and California Floristic Province.  While India is home to significant biodiversity but it has only three recognized hotspots. These hotspots are the Eastern Himalayas, Western Ghats and Andaman and Nicobar Islands. The Western Himalayas are not considered as a separate biodiversity hotspot. 43","PW-0565":"Statement 1 is correct: The salt-water crocodile, the largest living reptile, is found in coastal regions of the Andaman and Nicobar Islands. These islands provide a suitable habitat for the species, including mangrove swamps and estuarine areas, which are ideal for the crocodile’s nesting and hunting. Statement 2 is correct: The shrew is a small mammal found in the forested areas of the Western Ghats, including the Malabar region. The most common is Malabar Shrew. The tapir, specifi- cally the Malayan tapir, is found in the rainforests of the Western Ghats. Tapirs are herbivorous mammals that are adapted to the dense forests and are native to parts of South and Southeast Asia, including the Western Ghats. 44","PW-0566":"The International Union for Conservation of Nature (IUCN) is a global organization that assesses the conservation status of species. IUCN maintains a Red List to categorize species based on their risk of extinction. Endangered species are those at high risk, requiring urgent conservation efforts to prevent ex- tinction and protect biodiversity. Some of the common species which are under ‘Endangered’ category of the Red Book, are list- ed as under: 1. Indian Elephant 2. Bengal Tiger 3. Asiatic Lion 4. Indian Rhino 5. Ganges Dolphin 6. Crocodile The Gharial (Gavialis gangeticus), a species of crocodile found in India, is critically endangered, with fewer than 250 individuals remaining in the wild. The Mugger Crocodile (Crocodylus pal- ustris) is classified as Vulnerable. Habitat loss, poaching, and declining prey populations have contributed to their endan- gered status. The Asian Elephant (Elephas maximus) is listed as Endan- gered by the International Union for Conservation of Nature (IUCN). Habitat loss, human-wildlife conflict, and poaching are significant threats to their survival","PW-0567":"Methane (CH4) and nitrous oxide (N2O) are the two most important GHGs after carbon dioxide (CO2). The most rap- id increase in CH4 emission was found in natural wetlands and rice fields due to increased rice cultivation area and climate warming. N2O emission increased substantially in all the biome types and the largest increase occurred in upland crops due to increasing air temperature and nitrogen fertilizer use. Rice pad- dies are considered one of the most important sources of CH4 and N2O emissions, which have attracted considerable attention due to their contribution to global warming. Environment and Ecology 481 46","PW-0568":"The System of Rice Intensification involves cultivat- ing rice with as much organic manure as possible, starting with young seedlings planted singly at wider spacing in a square pattern; and with intermittent irrigation that keeps the soil moist but not inundated, and frequent inter cultivation with weeder that actively aerates the soil. SRI is not a standardised, fixed technological method. It is rather a set of ideas, a methodology for comprehensively managing and conserving resources by changing the way that land, seeds, wa- ter, nutrients, and human labour are used to increase productivi- ty from a small but well-tended number of seeds. Advantages of SRI Disadvantages of SRI  Higher yields – Both grain and straw  Higher labour costs in the initial years  Reduced duration  Difficulties in acquiring the necessary skills  Reduced seed requirement  Not suitable when no irrigation source available  Lesser chemical inputs  Less water requirement  Reduced electricity consumption  Less chaffy grain  rain weight increased without change in grain size  Higher head rice recovery","PW-0569":"Permaculture is a totally integrated design system that’s modelled on nature. Statement 1 is correct: Permaculture farming promotes multi-cropping and integrated farming systems. While chemical farming is more suitable for monoculture cropping due to the use of crop-specific inputs like irrigation, chemical fertiliser and har- vesting methods. Statement 2 is correct: Conventional farming usually alters the natural environment, increases soil salinity, and eliminates biodiversity. Such problems are not seen in permaculture farm- ing as it relies on organic fertilizers. Statement 3 is incorrect: Chemical farming is based on the intense use of inputs like chemical fertilizers and irrigation that make the soil less fertile over time, thus restricting its practice in semi-arid regions. Thus, conventional farming is not suitable for semi-arid regions. Permaculture involves well-designed sys- tems that don’t produce waste and permaculture tries to imitate well-designed systems. Thus, it can work in arid climates as well. Statement 4 is correct: Mulching is an important component of Permacul","PW-0570":"Climate-Smart Agriculture (CSA) is a strategy to assist those in charge of managing agricultural systems in efficiently adapting to climate change. The CSA approach pursues the triple objectives of:  Sustainably increasing productivity and incomes  Adapting to climate change  Reducing greenhouse gas emissions where possible Statement 1 is correct: The Climate-Smart Village project in India is a CGIAR Research Program on Climate Change, Agri- culture and Food Security (CCAFS). Statement 2 is correct: Climate Change, Agriculture and Food Security (CCFAS) is carried out under CGIAR (formerly the Consultative Group for International Agricultural Research). Statement 3 is correct: ICRISAT is a CGIAR Research Center. It is a non-profit, non-political public international research or- ganization that conducts agricultural research for development in Asia and sub-Saharan Africa with a wide array of partners throughout the world. 49","PW-0571":"Fertigation is a technique for applying fertilizer where the drip irrigation system incorporates the fertilizer into the irrigation water. In this technology, irrigation is used to evenly disperse fertiliser solutions. Fertigation is practised extensively in commercial agriculture and horticulture. Fertigation is used to supplement nutrients that are already present or to make up for nutrient shortages found during plant tissue analysis. Statement 1 is correct: Drip irrigation also avoids water spill- age on the field which could have promoted weed growth or in- creased soil alkalinity due to water logging. Statement 2 is incorrect: Rock phosphate is not water-solu- ble and thus not suitable for fertigation. Only water-soluble fer- tilizers are effectively used in fertigation systems. Statement 3 is correct: Accurate placement of nutrient, where the water goes the nutrient goes as well. Thus, increased nutrient absorption by plants. Statement 4 is correct: Fertigation mixes fertilizers into irri- gation water so that plants receive small, measured amounts of nutrients regularly, whic","PW-0572":"The practice of sowing seed without tillage or prepara- tion of soil is called Zero-tillage or No-till farming. In some cases it may reduce labour, fuel, irrigation and machinery costs. Anoth- er possible benefit is that because of the higher water content, instead of leaving a field fallow it can make economic sense to plant another crop instead. No-till farming decreases the amount of soil erosion tillage causes in certain soils, especially in sandy and dry soils on sloping terrain. Statement 1 is correct: Zero tillage is the process where the crop seed will be sown through drillers without prior land prepa- ration and disturbing the soil where previous crop stubbles are present. Statement 2 is correct: Direct Seeded Rice (DSR) is a viable option to reduce the unproductive water flows, with increasing shortage of water, dry-DSR with minimum or zero tillage further enhances the benefits of this technology by saving labour. Statement 3 is correct: Carbon sequestration is the process of capturing and storing atmospheric carbon dioxide to mitigate cli- mate change. No-tillage farming h","PW-0573":"Sustainable Agriculture is farming in such a way to protect the environment, aid and expand natural resources and to make the best use of nonrenewable resources. Options 1, 2 and 3 are correct:  Mixed cropping or diverse cropping: When two or more crops are cultivated concurrently on a field, it is known as mixed cropping or diversified cropping. In the unlikely event that one crop fails, the other crops will mitigate the risk of a complete crop failure.  Legume intensification: A category of plants known as leguminous plants (legume) contain edible roots or knobs that help nitrogen-rich soil grow vegetables or other meals. A leguminous crop is typically cultivated alongside the primary crop. Legumes contribute to increased soil fertility by fixing nitrogen from the atmosphere.  Crop Rotation: It entails the methodical planting of various crops in a specific order over the course of several years in the same growing space. It contributes to the preservation of soil nutrients, the reduction of soil erosion, and the prevention of pests and disease in plants.  Tensiometer: A tensiom","PW-0574":"Biochar is a high-carbon, fine-grained residue that is currently produced through modern pyrolysis processes (direct thermal decomposition of biomass in the absence of oxygen and preventing combustion). The extremely porous nature of biochar is found to be effective at retaining both water and water-solu- ble nutrients. When applied to soil, biochar can improve water retention, increase soil fertility, and enhance microbial activi- ty, leading to better crop yields. Environment and Ecology 483 Statement 1 is correct: The use of biochar in vertical farming, part of the growing medium, can increase output significantly. As biochar migrates vertically through the soil profile, therefore can be used as a part of the growing medium in vertical farming. Statement 2 is correct: Its presence on the earth can improve water quality, increase soil fertility, raise agricultural pro- ductivity, and reduce pressure on old-growth forests. Using biochar in the soil promotes the growth of nitrogen-fixing mi- croorganisms. Statement 3 is correct: Biochar is hygroscopic. Thus it is a de- sirable soil m","PW-0575":"In India, pesticides must be registered with the Minis- try of Agriculture & Farmers Welfare’s Directorate of Plant Pro- tection, Quarantine & Storage before they can be used. A 2015 report by the Anupam Verma Committee recommended banning 27 pesticides, including some commonly used chemicals men- tioned above:  Carcinogenic: Oxyfluorfen, Pendimethalin (causes Thyroid follicular cell adenoma)  Endocrine disruptor: Dicofol, Carbofuran, Oxyfluorfen  Eco-toxic: Carbofuran, Monocrotophos, Carbofuran, Oxyfluorfen. Pesticides restricted for use in the India: Aluminium Phos- phide, Captafol, Cypermethrin, Dazomet, Dichloro Diphe- nyl Trichloro ethane (DDT), Fenitrothion, Methyl Bromide, Monocrotophos, Trifluralin. 54","PW-0576":"Statement 1 is incorrect: Soil water holding capacity is the amount of water that a given soil can hold for crop use. Soil texture and organic matter are the key components that deter- mine soil water holding capacity. Organic matter influences the physical conditions of a soil in several ways. Statement 2 is incorrect: Sulphur is one of three nutrients that are cycled between the soil, plant matter and the atmosphere. The sulphur cycle describes the movement of sulphur through the atmosphere, mineral and organic forms, and through living things. Statement 3 is correct: Salinization is a major problem associat- ed with irrigation, because deposits of salts build up in the soil and can reach levels that are harmful to crops. SUPER HINT S1 and S2 contain extreme phrases like \"Drastically reduces\" and \"any role\", hence more probable to be false, instead, S3 contains \"some\" hence plausible to be true. “Some” = possibility logic, not absolute. If even one species of organism does something, the statement is likely correct. 56","PW-0577":"Conservation Agriculture (CA) is a farming system that promotes minimum soil disturbance (i.e. no tillage), main- tenance of a permanent soil cover, and diversification of plant species. It enhances biodiversity and natural biological pro- cesses above and below the ground surface, which contribute to increased water and nutrient use efficiency and to improved and sustained crop production. According to FAO’s website there are three principles of Conser- vation of Agriculture: 1. Minimum mechanical soil disturbance: It refers to low dis- turbance no-tillage and direct seeding. The disturbed area must be less than 15 cm wide or less than 25% of the cropped area (whichever is lower). 2. Permanent soil organic cover: Three categories are distin- guished: 30-60%, >60-90% and >90% ground cover, measured immediately after the direct seeding operation. An area with less than 30% cover is not considered as CA. 3. Species diversification: Rotation/association should involve at least 3 different crop species. The rotation of crops is not only necessary to offer a diverse “diet” to the soil mic","PW-0578":"Efficient water use in agriculture refers to practices and techniques that aim to maximize the productivity of crops while minimizing water consumption. It involves employing methods such as capturing and storing water and drip irrigation to deliver water directly to the plant roots, reducing losses due to evapora- tion or runoff. Statements 1 and 3 are correct: Conservation Tillage includes no-till farming or zero tillage which is a way of growing crops or pasture from year to year without disturbing the soil through tillage. Zero tillage helps in soil moisture conservation. Crop res- idues act as mulches and reduce evaporation losses and protect the soil from direct impact of raindrops, thus controlling crusting and sealing processes. Statement 2 is incorrect: Though, Gypsum helps in dissolution of the salt clay pan found in soils that hinder the percolation of water and helps in water conservation. 58","PW-0579":"With excessive use of nitrogenous fertilizers in agricul- ture, the necessity for nitrogen-fixing bacteria decreases as soil nitrogen levels increase. The soil becomes more acidic and ni- trate leaches into the groundwater when nitrogenous fertilisers are used excessively or inappropriately. Fertilizers in agriculture increase inputs of nutrients to soils affecting their pH value. Statement 1 is incorrect: Nitrogen-fixing microorganisms, such as Rhizobium (in leguminous plants), Azotobacter, and Cyano- bacteria (blue-green algae) fix atmospheric nitrogen into the soil. But excessive nitrogen fertilizers reduce biological nitrogen fix- ation because plants get sufficient nitrogen from fertilizers and do not depend on these microbes. Thus instead of increasing, nitrogen-fixing bacteria decrease in population due to re- duced plant-microbe symbiosis. Statement 2 and 3 are correct: The conversion of Nitrogen from one form to the other involves the generation or consump- tion of acidity and the uptake of urea, ammonium or nitrate by plants will also affect the acidity of the soil. Due to ","PW-0580":"Micro-irrigation is the slow distribution of water to the soil using surface drip and micro-sprinkler systems in the form of discrete or continuous drips, tiny streams, or miniature spray. Benefits of micro irrigation systems: Helps in water-saving and checking further depletion, Increased irrigation efficiency, Higher yields, Less water loss, Energy efficient, Lower consump- tion of fertilizers, Weed and disease reduction, Cost savings, Pre- cision farming. Statement 1 is correct: An efficient drip irrigation system re- duces the consumption of fertiliser through fertigation. Statement 2 is incorrect: Dryland farming is defined as the pro- duction of crops without irrigation in regions that receive rainfall of less than 500mm annually. Crop selection, Microcatchments and Runoff farming are some other methods of irrigation in dry- land farming. Statement 3 is correct: Micro-irrigation helps in water-saving and checking further groundwater depletion. 60","PW-0581":"Terrestrial Carbon sequestration is the process through which carbon dioxide from the atmosphere is absorbed by trees and plants through photosynthesis and stored as carbon in soil and biomass. Option 3 is correct: Zero Tillage is the process where the crop seed will be sown through drillers without prior land prepara- tion and distributed in the soil where previous crop stubbles are present. Zero tillage not only reduces the cost of cultivation it also reduces the soil erosion, crop duration, irrigation require- ment and weed effect which is better than tillage. Zero tillage is environmentally safe because it helps in reducing greenhouse effect through carbon sequestration. Options 1 and 2 are incorrect:  Contour bundling involves the construction of banks along the contours. Terracing and contour bunding divide the hill slope into numerous small slopes, check the flow of water, promote absorption of water by soil and save soil from erosion. Retaining walls of terraces control the flow of water and help in reducing soil erosion.  Relay Cropping is the process of growing one crop, ","PW-0582":"Per- and polyfluoroalkyl substances (PFAS) are a large, complex group of synthetic chemicals that have been used in con- sumer products around the world since about the 1950s. Statement 1 is correct: People are most likely exposed to these chemicals by consuming PFAS-contaminated water or food, us- ing products made with PFAS, or breathing air containing PFAS. Although PFOS use has been phased out, it can still be found in drinking water, groundwater, soil, and air. Statement 2 is correct: PFAS molecules have a chain of linked carbon and fluorine atoms. Because the carbon-fluorine bond is one of the strongest, these chemicals do not degrade easily in the environment, leading to long-term contamination. Statement 3 is correct: PFAS can accumulate in the bodies of animals, including humans, through persistent exposure. They tend to concentrate in organs like the liver and kidneys and bio- accumulate up the food chain 62","PW-0583":"Hydrofluorocarbons (HFCs) are a climate “Super- Pol- lutant” - Greenhouse gases with hundreds to thousands of times the heat-trapping power of carbon dioxide (CO2). HFCs are syn- thetic gases used in air conditioning systems, aerosol propel- lants, foam- blowing agents, solvents, and flame retardants. These gases were first developed as alternatives to ozone- de- pleting chemicals, but after their rollout, it was learned that their release to the atmosphere during manufacturing processes and leakage during use, servicing, and retirement/replacement of equipment poses a grave threat to our climate. Lubricants are typically based on oils and synthetic esters, not HFCs. 64","PW-0584":"The updated (2021) WHO Global Air Quality Guidelines (AQGs) provide recommendations on air quality guideline levels as well as interim targets for six key air pollutants. The guidelines focus on so-called classical pollutants, particulate matter (PM₂.₅ and PM₁₀), ozone (O₃), nitrogen dioxide (NO₂), sulfur dioxide (SO₂) and carbon monoxide (CO). Statement 1 is correct: The 24-hour ceiling mean of PM 2.5 used to be 25 micrograms but has now dropped to 15. Statement 2 is incorrect: Ozone at ground level is formed by the reaction with sunlight (photochemical reaction) of pollutants such as nitrogen oxides (NOx) from vehicle and industry emis- sions and volatile organic compounds (VOCs) emitted by vehi- cles, solvents and industry. As a result, the highest levels of ozone pollution occur during periods of sunny weather and not during inclement weather. Statement 3 is incorrect: Particles with a diameter of 10 μm (PM10) can reach the lungs but cannot enter the bloodstream. However, particles with a diameter of 2.5 μm or less can pene- trate deeper into the lungs, reaching the alveoli, ente","PW-0585":"Normal rain has a pH of about 5.6 when pH falls below this; it is called Acid rain (pH 4.2 to 4.4). Acid rain results when Sulfur Dioxide (SO2) & Nitrogen Oxides (NOX) react with water, oxygen & other chemicals to form Sulfuric & Nitric acids. Nitrous oxide and Sulphur dioxide cause Acid rain. The acid rain harms microorganisms in the soil; inhibits the activity of nitro- gen fixation bacteria; soil acidification; ocean acidification; af- fects the growth of plants; food chain; kills aquatic animals; cor- rosion of metals & weathering of stone buildings & statues. Environment and Ecology 487 NOx + SO2 + Moisture + other chemicals → Acid Rain (HNO3 + H2SO4) 68","PW-0586":"Copper Smelting is a process of applying heat to ore in order to extract a base metal. Smelting uses heat and a chem- ical reducing agent to decompose the ore, driving off other ele- ments as gases or slag and leaving the metal base behind. It is the method of extracting pure elemental copper (Cu) from copper concentrate (CuFeS2). Statement 1 is incorrect: Copper smelting generally does not release lethal quantities of carbon monoxide (CO) into the envi- ronment. Statement 2 and 3 are correct: Some smelting processes can also produce large quantities of solid waste, known as slag. This slag may leach heavy metals (arsenic, cadmium, lead or mer- cury depending on the composition of the ore) into groundwater reservoirs. Smelting processes are known to emit high quantities of air pollutants such as hydrogen fluoride, sulphur dioxide, oxides of nitrogen, offensive and noxious smoke fumes, vapours, gases, and other toxins. SUPER HINT For S1, ''Lethal quantities\" is an extreme phrase, what is lethal quantity? How to define it? It's all vague and hence more probable to be false, giving corr","PW-0587":"Statement 1 is correct: Furnace oil or fuel oil is a dark viscous residual product of crude-oil distillation. It is used as a fuel in different types of combustion equipment. Statement 2 is correct: Marine engines and slow speed engines use Furnace oil for power generation, they are used for drying tea leaves. Thermic fluid heaters and hot air generators also use Furnace oil. Statement 3 is correct: The emissions of oxides of sulphur are a direct result of the sulphur content of the fuel oil.  Furnace oil is a dark, viscous residual fuel obtained by blending mainly heavier components from crude distillation units. Compared to other petroleum products, it has a relatively low flash point and high viscosity.  Its major advantages are:  High energy content, making it an efficient fuel choice for heating purposes  Often cost-competitive compared to other heating options  Readily available in many regions, ensuring a consistent supply  Furnace/fuel oil combustion can produce emissions, including sulfur dioxide (SO2), nitrogen oxides (NOx), and particulate matter 70","PW-0588":"Magnetite particles are a highly magnetic mineral form of iron and are known to be present in air pollution. Expo- sure to airborne particulate matter (PM) is associated with pul- monary, cardiovascular and neurological problems. Option 1 is correct: Vehicle brake systems are the major source of airborne magnetite at the roadside. Option 2 is correct: Petrol and diesel-engine exhaust are also a source of airborne magnetite. Option 4 is correct: Other sources of Magnetite pollution in- clude Power plants. Options 3 and 5 are incorrect: Household microwave stoves and telephone lines not are established as sources of airborne magnetite particles. Other sources of Magnetite pollution include microwave Stoves within homes, As per WHO, Telephone lines produce low frequency, low energy electromagnetic fields which are the potential source of magne- tite particles. SUPER HINT For S5, Had telephone lines been a real source of neuro- degenerative magnetite particles, the effects would have surfaced in public health long ago — given our lifelong proximity. Since no such pattern is observed, the","PW-0589":"The Common Carbon Metric’ is a protocol developed by United Nations Environment Program’s Sustainable Build- ings & Climate Initiative (UNEP-SBCI) for measuring energy use & reporting GHG emissions from Building Operations. Its purpose is to support greenhouse gas (GHG) emission’s reduc- tions through accurate measurement of energy efficiency improvements in building operations. 72","PW-0590":"Blue Carbon is the carbon captured by the world’s ocean and coastal ecosystems. There are three types of coast- al ecosystems — mangroves, seagrasses and tidal marshes; these store half the “blue” carbon buried beneath the ocean floor. These areas absorb and store carbon at a much faster rate than other areas, such as forests, and can continue to do so for millions of years. The carbon found in coastal soil is often thousands of years old. 73","PW-0591":"","PW-0592":"","PW-0593":"Social Cost of Carbon is best described as the measure of monetary value of long-term damage done by a tonne of CO2 emissions in a given year. The social cost of carbon (SCC) is used to estimate in dollars all economic damage that would result from emitting one ton of carbon dioxide into the atmosphere. India’s country-level social cost of carbon emission was estimat- ed to be the highest at $86 per tonne of CO2. It means the Indian economy will lose $86 by emitting each additional tonne of CO2. India is followed by the US ($48) and Saudi Arabia ($47). 76","PW-0594":"Statement 1 is correct: Coal ash contains contaminants like mercury, cadmium and arsenic. Without proper manage- ment, these contaminants can pollute waterways, groundwater, drinking water, and the air. Statement 2 is correct: Burning of fossil fuels (which contain sulphur and nitrogenous matter) such as coal and oil in power stations and furnaces or petrol and diesel in motor engines pro- duce sulphur dioxide and nitrogen oxides, which also leads to ‘acid rain’. Statement 3 is correct: Indian Coal has comparatively higher ash content than imported coal due to the drift theory of the for- mation of coal deposits in India. Coal seams formed due to drift theory contain higher ash as compared to the in-situ theory of formation. 77","PW-0595":"Waste-to-Energy (WTE) technologies consist of any waste treatment process that creates energy in the form of electricity or heat from several types of waste: from the semi-sol- id (e.g. thickened sludge from effluent treatment plants) to liq- uid (e.g. domestic sewage) waste. Landfill gas recovery, Gasifi- cation, Pyrolisis, Thermal Depolymerisation are examples of Waste-to-Energy (WTE) technologies. Option (d) is correct: Pyrolysis is a process of chemical de- composition of organic matter brought about by heat. In this process, the organic material is heated in the absence of air until the molecules thermally break down to become a gas compris- ing smaller molecules (known collectively as syngas). Gasifi- cation can also take place as a result of partial combustion of organic matter in the presence of a restricted quantity of oxygen or air. The gas, so produced, is known as producer gas. The gases produced by pyrolysis mainly comprise carbon monoxide (25%), hydrogen and hydrocarbons (15%), and carbon dioxide and nitrogen (60%). It is used commercially as a waste to energy system th","PW-0596":"","PW-0597":"Methane hydrate is an ice-like substance formed when CH4 and water combine at low temperature (up to 250C) and moderate pressure (greater than 3-5 MPa, which corresponds to combined water and sediment depths of 300 to 500 m). Statement 1 is correct: Owing to the melting of ice, global warm- ing might trigger the release of methane gas from these deposits hence having a significant impact on climate change. Statement 2 is correct: Sediment and sedimentary rock units below Arctic permafrost have the temperature and pressure con- ditions suitable for the formation and stability of methane hy- drate. Statement 3 is correct: Methane is relatively short-lived in the atmosphere; a molecule of methane is oxidised to water and car- bon dioxide within a decade or so, mainly by reaction with other trace gases. 80","PW-0598":"Burning stubble (parali) is the process of removing crop residue from the field in order to prepare it for the next crop. Open stubble burning releases a lot of harmful pollutants into the air, including smoke, particles, greenhouse gases (CO2, N2O, O3 CH4), air pollutants (CO, NH3, NOx, SO2, NMHC), and volatile organic compounds. These pollutants are dangerous to human health. Husk burning reduces the fertility of the soil by destroying its nutrients. When stubble burns, heat is produced that permeates the soil, causing the loss of moisture and benefi- cial microbes. SUPER HINT You can try, The \"NOT\" approach for all statements, this tests the improbability of negating a statement—if de- nying its impact seems highly unlikely, the statement is plausibly true. For Example: CO or O3 are NOT released in crop burning? Absurd, unlikely. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 490 81","PW-0599":"Sand mining is the extraction of sand, mainly through an open pit (or sandpit) but sometimes mined from beaches and inland dunes or dredged from ocean and river beds. Statement 1 is incorrect: Sand mining typically does not direct- ly affect the salinity of the river. Salinity is more influenced by factors like the influx of seawater in coastal areas, evaporation rates, and the presence of saline minerals in the riverbed. Statement 2 is correct: The amount of suspended particles in the water at the excavation site and downstream increases due to increased riverbed and bank erosion. This process stirs up the sediments and increases the chance of contamination of groundwater. Statement 3 is correct: Heavy sand mining causes removal of sand and gravels from the riverbed. Due to this the groundwa- ter table drops leaving the drinking water wells on the embank- ments of these rivers dry. Alteration of rivers, damage to river biodiversity, altered sediment budget lead to poor water quality, worsen water scarcity threat to coastal communities, damage to public and private property. 82","PW-0600":"BOD measures the amount of dissolved oxygen re- quired by microorganisms to break down organic material in water over a specific time. BOD is the amount of dissolved oxygen needed by bacteria in decomposing the organic wastes present in water. It is measured in milligrammes per litre of water of ox- ygen. The higher value of BOD indicates low (Dissolved Oxygen) DO content of water. BOD is not a reliable method for assessing water pollution because it only includes biodegradable elements.  Standard Method 5210B is the most widely used method for determining Biological Oxygen Demand (BOD). It measures the difference in dissolved oxygen (DO) over a five-day incubation period at 20°C.  The initial DO is recorded, and after incubation, the final DO is measured. The BOD value is then calculated based on oxygen depletion.  Higher BOD indicates poor water quality due to higher oxygen demand, while lower BOD suggests purer water with less oxygen consumption. DO levels are lower in summer as warm water holds less oxygen. 83","PW-0601":"Bioremediation is a branch of biotechnology that em- ploys the use of living organisms in the removal of contaminants, pollutants, and toxins from soil, water, and other environments. These organisms can include microbes and bacteria. As a result, compared to other cleanup techniques, bioremediation causes less disruption to the neighbourhood communities. Statement 1 is correct: Bioremediation uses naturally occurring organisms to break down hazardous substances into less toxic or non-toxic substances. Statement 2 is incorrect: Not all contaminants are easily treated by bioremediation using microorganisms. For eg. Heavy metals such as cadmium and lead are not readily absorbed or captured by microorganisms. Statement 3 is correct: The use of genetic engineering to cre- ate organisms specifically designed for bioremediation has great potential. For e.g. Alcanivorax, a bacteria with oil-eating abili- ties, can be used to create species that are much more capable of cleaning oil spills. Types of Bioremediation:  Aerobic Bioremediation: Requires oxygen for microbial reactions, where bact","PW-0602":"Biofuels are hydrocarbon fuel that is created in a short amount of time—days, weeks, or even months—from organic matter (living or once-living material). Biofuels may be solid, liquid or gaseous in nature:  Solid: Wood, dried plant material, and manure  Liquid: Bioethanol and Biodiesel  Gaseous: Biogas Statement 1 is incorrect: Algaculture (farming algae) can be initiated on land unsuitable for agriculture or saline water or wastewater. Statements 2 and 3 are correct: Producing algae for biofuels (excluding simple seaweed production) requires significant capi- tal investments, which may be a significant barrier in developing countries that have a weak investment climate. Also during the setup stage, the production of algae- based biofuels will necessi- tate expertise in advanced technology. SUPER HINT For S1, \"seas ONLY\" is an extreme absolute phrase and hence unlikely to be true. Thus eliminate options A and D. In contrast, S 2 and S3 are too general and practical to be false, hence more likely to be true. 85","PW-0603":"Green India Mission is one of the eight missions launched under the National Action Plan on Climate Change (NAPCC) with the aim to maintain, restore, and improve India’s dwindling forest cover and combating climate change through a combination of adaptation and mitigation strategies. Statement 1 and 2 are incorrect: Green accounting is an ap- proach that incorporates environmental costs into financial assessments. The primary goal of green accounting is to help businesses balance economic objectives with environmental con- siderations. It is not part of the Green India Mission. Facing seri- ous challenges like overproduction of crops like rice and wheat, soil degradation, and food price volatility, the country would need the Second green revolution to focus on the interconnect- edness of agriculture, water, and energy to make farming more climate-resilient and environmentally sustainable. Both the statements are irrelevant to the Green India Mission. Statement 3 is correct: The mission intends to increase forest/ tree cover; improve/enhance ecosystem services and increase the forest-","PW-0604":"There are six AQI categories, namely Good + Satisfac- tory, Moderately polluted, Poor, Very Poor, and Severe. Each of these categories is decided based on ambient concentration values of air pollutants and their likely health impacts (known as health breakpoints). AQ sub-index and health breakpoints are evolved for eight pollutants, namely:  Ground-level Ozone or O3  Particulate Matter (PM10 and PM 2.5)  Carbon Monoxide or CO  Sulphur Dioxide or SO2 and  Nitrogen Dioxide or NO2  Ammonia (NH3)  Lead (Pb) 87","PW-0605":"India is second largest crude steel producer in the world. The steel industry is highly resource and energy-inten- sive, as well as significantly polluting. For instance, India’s cur- rent average emission intensity is 2.55 tonnes of CO2 per tonne of crude steel, while the global average is around 1.95 tonnes. Emissions from the steel sector have decreased by 15% from 2005 to 2022, and the government aims for an additional 10% reduction by 2030. The major environmental impacts of integrated steel mills are from coking and iron-making. Coke production is one of the major pollution sources from steel production. Air emissions such as coke oven gas, naphthalene, ammonium compounds, crude light oil, sulfur and coke dust are released from coke ov- ens. Steel production has a number of impacts on the environment, including air emissions (CO2, CO SOx, NOx, PM2.5), wastewater contaminants, hazardous wastes, and solid wastes. 88","PW-0606":"Nanoparticles are used in the manufacture of scratch proof eyeglasses, crack-resistant paints, anti-graffiti coatings for walls, transparent sunscreens, stain-repellent fabrics, and self-cleaning windows, and ceramic coatings for solar cells. Ad- ditionally, stronger, lighter, cleaner, and more intelligent surfaces and systems can be created with nanoparticles. Statement 1 is correct: A matter particle with dimension rang- ing from 1 to 100 nanometers is referred to as nanoparticle. Nanoparticles can accumulate in the environment and con- taminate water and soil. Statement 2 is correct: Nanoparticles can also enter the food chain and cross cell membranes. Statement 3 is correct: Nanoparticles can trigger free radicals and may damage cells in organs like the liver, heart, or blood. Health Implications Of Nanoparticles:  Nanoparticles enhance drug delivery and target-specific treatment. However, some nanoparticles may reduce a drug’s efficacy or introduce toxicity risks to non-target orgAns:  Nanoparticles can accumulate in the liver and spleen, potentially altering liver function an","PW-0607":"Brominated Flame Retardants (BFRs) are mixtures of man-made chemicals that are added to a wide variety of prod- ucts, including for industrial use, to make them less flammable. They are used commonly in plastics, textiles and electrical/elec- tronic equipment. Statements 1 is correct: Brominated Flame Retardants (BFRs)don’t degrade easily in fact they are highly resistant to degradation in the environment. Statements 2 is correct: Some brominated flame retardants were identified as persistent, bioaccumulative, and toxic to both humans and the environment and were suspected of caus- ing neurobehavioral effects and endocrine disruption. 90","PW-0608":"Water Pollution is the contamination of water bodies, usually as a result of human activities. Heavy metal water pol- lution is the contamination of water with toxic heavy metals, such as lead, mercury, cadmium, arsenic, and chromium etc. Heavy metals can enter the water through natural processes and human activities. Options 1, 3 and 5 are correct: Arsenic, Fluoride, Iron, Ura- nium, Nitrate, are some major groundwater pollutants in India. Option 2 is incorrect: Sorbitol is a sugar alcohol found in fruits and plants with diuretic, laxative and cathartic properties. It is not related with drinking water pollution. Option 4 is incorrect: Formaldehyde is used to preserve fish longer. The use of this chemical is banned in fresh foods by the Food Safety and Standards Authority of India. The International Agency for Research on Cancer (IARC) of WHO classifies formal- dehyde as “carcinogenic to humans”. Formaldehyde is not estab- lished as a drinking water pollutant. Water Quality Criteria according to CPCB  Drinking Water Source without conventional treatment but after disinfection  Tot","PW-0609":"E-waste is any electrical or electronic equipment that’s been discarded. Recently, India’s first e-waste clinic was inaugu- rated in Bhopal. Environment and Ecology 493 E-waste Sources Constituents PCBs, glass panels, and Computer monitors Lead Resistors & Semiconductors Cadmium Relays and switches, &PCBs Mercury Galvanised steel plates & decorator or hardener Chromium Cabling, Computer & housing Plastics & PVC Electronic equipments & circuit boards Brominated flame-retardants Front panels of CRTs Barium, Phospho- rus & Heavy metals Copper wires, PCB tracks Copper Nickel Cadmium batteries Nickel Lithium-ion battery Lithium Motherboards Beryllium Options 1, 2, 3, 5 and 6 are correct: All elements in these op- tions are the harmful constituents that are released into the envi- ronment due to improper disposal of e-waste. Option 4 is incorrect: Heptachlor is a pesticide classified under Persistent Organic Pollutants (POPs) per the Stockholm Conven- tion. It is unrelated to e-waste. Option 7 is incorrect: Plutonium, while used in some industri- al and military applications, is a radioact","PW-0610":"Normal rain has a pH of about 5.6 when pH falls below this; it is called Acid rain (pH 4.2 to 4.4). Acid rain results when Sulphur Dioxide (SO2) & Nitrogen Oxides (NOX) react with water, oxygen & other chemicals to form Sulfuric & Nitric acids. NOx + SO2 + Moisture + other chemicals → Acid Rain (HNO3 + H2SO4) Acid rain harms microorganisms in the soil; inhibits the activity of nitrogen fixation bacteria; soil acidification; ocean acidifica- tion; affects the growth of plants; food chain; kills aquatic ani- mals; corrosion of metals and weathering of stone buildings & statues. 93","PW-0611":"Photochemical smog, often referred to as “Los An- geles smog,” is most commonly found in urban areas with high numbers of automobiles. It does not require smoke or fog to form. This type of smog is formed from the nitrogen oxides and hydrocarbon (peroxyacetyl nitrate, a hazardous pollutant) vapors released by vehicles and other sources, which then un- dergo photochemical reactions in the lower atmosphere in the presence of sunlight. 94","PW-0612":"Aflatoxins are produced by certain species of fungi (moulds), specifically Aspergillus flavus and Aspergillus para- siticus, which often grow on stored grains and oilseeds under conditions of high humidity and temperature. Exposure to aflatoxins can lead to serious health issues, including liver cancer, especially in children. Beyond health risks, aflatox- ins cause significant economic losses, with an estimated 25% of global food crops affected annually. 95","PW-0613":"A rapid rise in the population of algae in an aquatic system is known as an algal bloom, marine bloom, or water bloom. Algal blooms can appear in both marine and freshwater habitats. “Harmful algal blooms (HAB)” are blooms that can af- fect wildlife or the environment. Harmful Algal Bloom can lead to fish die-offs, cities cutting off water to residents, or states having to close fisheries. Statement 1 is correct: Estuaries receive nutrient-rich water from rivers which can include agricultural runoff, sewage, and industrial effluents. These nutrients, particularly nitrogen and phosphorus promote the growth of algae causing algal blooms. Statement 2 is correct: Heavy rainfall during the monsoon season can cause significant runoff from agricultural fields, urban areas, and other land surfaces. This runoff can carry fertilizers, pesticides, and other nutrients into the sea, pro- viding the necessary conditions for algal blooms Statement 3 is correct: Water that rises to the surface as a re- sult of upwelling is typically colder and is rich in nutrients, which again leads to algal blooms.","PW-0614":"The Kyoto Protocol is an international treaty that com- mits industrialized nations to reducing greenhouse gas emissions in order to mitigate climate change and was adopted at COP 3 (the third Conference of the Parties) in 1997 in Kyoto, Japan. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 494 Statement 1 is correct: The Kyoto Protocol officially came into force on February 16, 2005. Statement 2 is incorrect: The Kyoto Protocol primarily focus- es on reducing greenhouse gas emissions to combat climate change, not on the depletion of the ozone layer. The ozone layer issue is addressed by the Montreal Protocol, which focuses on phasing out substances that deplete the ozone layer. Statement 3 is correct: Methane (CH₄) is a more potent green- house gas than carbon dioxide (CO₂) in the short term. Although CO₂ persists longer in the atmosphere, methane has a much high- er global warming potential over a 20-year period—about 84 times more potent than CO₂. 5. CLIMATE CHANGE 97","PW-0615":"Statement 1 is correct: The Climate Group is an inter- national non-profit organization that works to accelerate climate action by building and running large networks of businesses, governments, and other organizations. It focuses on initiatives like RE100 (renewable energy), EP100 (energy productivity), and EV100 (electric vehicles). Statement 2 is incorrect: The EP100 initiative is led by the Cli- mate Group in partnership with the Alliance to Save Energy, not the International Energy Agency (IEA). Statement 3 is correct: EP100 is a global initiative that encour- ages companies to commit to doubling their energy productivity (output per unit of energy consumed). This helps drive innova- tion, increase competitiveness, and reduce greenhouse gas emis- sions. Statement 4 is correct: Several Indian companies, such as Ma- hindra & Mahindra, Godrej and Dalmia Cement, are members of EP100 and have committed to improving their energy produc- tivity. Statement 5 is incorrect: EP100 is a global initiative that brings together companies committed to improving energy productivi- ty. The Under2","PW-0616":"","PW-0617":"There is a renewed interest in two dominant methods of geoengineering such as stratospheric sulphate aerosol in- crease and cirrus cloud thinning aims to reduce global warming effects. Geoengineering, often known as climate intervention, is the de- liberate and extensive modification of the Earth’s climatic system with the intention of reducing global warming.  The stratosphere can be injected with sulphate aerosol particles to block some of the sun’s rays and possibly cool the planet. Sulphur droplets are good at scattering the sun’s light back out into space and it does not heat the stratosphere as much as other aerosols. 102","PW-0618":"As per the Indian Nitrogen Assessment report, 2017, the share of agriculture in total GHG emissions has gradually de- clined from 28% in 1994 to 14% in 2016. Agricultural emissions in India are primarily from the livestock sector (54.6%) and the use of nitrogenous fertilizers (19%). Rice cultivation in anaerobic conditions accounts for a major portion of agricultural emissions (17.5%). Statement 1 is correct: Agricultural soils release nitrogen ox- ides into the environment  Fertilizers (especially nitrogen-based like urea) lead to the emission of nitrous oxide (N₂O), a greenhouse gas.  Microbial processes such as nitrification and denitrification release NO, NO₂, and N₂O. Statement 2 is correct: Cattle release ammonia into the envi- ronment  Cattle excrete urea in urine, which breaks down into ammonia (NH₃) through microbial action.  Livestock farming is a major contributor to ammonia emissions. Statement 3 is correct: Poultry industry releases reactive nitro- gen compounds into the environment  Poultry litter (manure, bedding material, and feed waste) contains nitrogen compoun","PW-0619":"Hydrogen-enriched CNG (H-CNG) is a blended gas. It is produced by mixing hydrogen with CNG. HCNG reduces emis- sions of CO up to 70% and engines can be calibrated to release lower amounts of NO. enables up to 5 % savings in fuel. It can be the first step towards the future Hydrogen economy. It gives better performance due to higher Octane rating of H2. Statement 1 is incorrect: HCNG doesn’t eliminate but reduces emissions of CO up to 70%. Statement 2 is correct: It can be used in place of gasoline, die- sel fuel and propane (C3H8) / LPG and its combustion produces fewer undesirable gases. Statement 3 is correct: The blending of hydrogen with CNG pro- vides a blended gas termed as HCNG. Also, the ideal Hydrogen concentration is close to 20 %. It can prove to be the ideal fuel for heavy-duty vehicles and applications with high loads. Statement 4 is incorrect: The current cost of Hydrogen is more than the cost of Natural Gas. So, HCNG’s cost is more than CNG. SUPER HINT When S2 says \"Reduces\", then, isn't S1's \"Elimination of CO\" an extreme phrase, hence S1 is more probable to be false,","PW-0620":"Carbon Sequestration is a process to capture and store CO2 to curb global warming. It is captured from the air, industries or power stations and stored permanently underground. Terres- trial Carbon Sequestration is the process through which CO2 from the atmosphere is absorbed by trees and plants through photosynthesis and stored as carbon in soils and biomass (tree trunks, branches, foliage, and roots). In Geologic Carbon Se- questration CO2 can be stored in oil reservoirs, gas reservoirs, unmineable coal seams, saline formations and shale formations with high organic content. Statement 1 is correct: Uneconomic coal seams can be used to store CO2 because the CO2 molecules attach to the surface of coal. Statement 2 is correct: CO2 is sometimes injected into declining oil fields to increase oil recovery. Statement 3 is correct: Other potential sites are gas reservoirs, saline formations and shale formations with high organic content. 105","PW-0621":"Intended Nationally Determined Contributions (IN- DCs) are planned reductions in greenhouse gas emissions out- lined by countries under the United Nations Framework Conven- tion on Climate Change (UNFCCC). NDCs are at the heart of the Paris Agreement and embody efforts by each country to reduce national emissions and adapt to the impacts of climate change. The UNFCCC, in its Nationally Determined Contributions (NDC) Synthesis Report, has called for more ambitious climate action plans by the countries in order to achieve the Paris Agreement target of containing global temperature rise to 2°C by the end of the century (ideally it is 1.5°C). 106","PW-0622":"GHG Protocol is developing standards, tools and online training that helps countries to measure and manage greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions from private and public sector operations, value chains and mitigation actions. The GHG Protocol arose when the World Resources Institute (WRI) and World Business Council for Sustainable Development (WBCSD) recognized the need for an international standard for corporate GHG accounting and reporting in the late 1990s. 107","PW-0623":"Statement 1 is correct: If the global temperature in- creases beyond 3 °C above the pre-industrial level, the terrestrial biosphere will tend towards being a net carbon source. Taiga and temperate forests act as an important carbon sink that would turn into a carbon source. Statement 2 is correct: As temperatures rise, mass coral bleach- ing events occur. If the temperature keeps on rising, widespread coral mortality will occur. Statement 3 and 4 are incorrect: The temperate regions can still survive if the temperature increases. The temperate zones are where the widest seasonal changes occur. The vegetation can survive there. The weather should be warm and moist during the early stage of the growth of cereals. Therefore, the cultivation of cereals would still be possible if the temperature rises. 108","PW-0624":"Bagasse and Molasses: Introduction Uses Bagasse is the remnant left after extracting the juice of the sugarcane or sorghum is known as bagasse. It is a dry pulpy fibrous material. It is used for the generation of heat en- ergy and electricity. Ethanol produced from it is also used as a popular fuel in some countries. It substitutes wood to produce pulp, paper, and board. As a cattle feed when mixed with molasses and enzymes and then fermenting. Molasses is the thick syrup that results from the refining of sugar- cane or sugar beets into sugar. It contains a good amount of Vitamin B6 and minerals like cal- cium, manganese, iron and magnesium.  Sweetening and flavouring foods.  In the production of fine commercial brown sugar.  In baking and cooking.  Producing ethanol and is the prime ingredient in the distillation of few alcoholic beverages.  As a cattle feed. Statements 1 and 3 are correct: Bagasse can be used for the generation of heat energy and electricity. Molasses can be used for the production of ethanol and it is also used as the ingredient in the distillation of a few a","PW-0625":"Greenhouse Effect is a naturally occurring phenomenon that warms and covers the lower atmosphere of the planet, keep- ing it at a temperature where life may survive. The earth’s cooling and warming are balanced by them. Without this, the current 15 degrees Celsius average temperature of the earth’s surface would be -19 degrees Celsius. Human-induced greenhouse gas emissions upset the natural balance & lead to increased warmth. Option (d) is correct: Carbon dioxide absorbs the infrared (IR) radiation emitted by the Earth’s surface. When sunlight reaches the Earth it warms the surface, which then re-emits this energy as infrared radiation. CO₂ molecules absorb this IR radi- ation, trapping heat in the atmosphere and causing the tempera- ture to rise.The increasing amount of carbon dioxide in the air is slowly raising the temperature of the atmosphere because it ab- sorbs the infrared part of the solar radiation. It absorbs energy with a wavelength of 15 μm (micrometres). 111","PW-0626":"For slowing down global warming, carbon sequestra- tion involves the capture and storage of CO2. It is captured from the air, industries or power stations and stored permanently underground. This promotes Long-term reserve of CO2 or forms of carbon to control temperatures. Carbon sequestration aids in lowering the amount of GHGs (due to combustion of fossil fuels) present in the air. Statement 2 is correct: The photosynthesis by phytoplankton in the oceans is natural carbon sequestration and it is responsible for much of CO2 being moved from lower atmosphere to oceans: Statements 1 is incorrect: CO₂ is a heavy gas that primarily ac- cumulates in the troposphere and lower stratosphere but does not escape into the outer stratosphere or space. The primary removal mechanisms of CO₂ involve absorption by oceans, pho- tosynthesis by plants, and geological sequestration rather than atmospheric escape. Statements 3 is incorrect: Polar ice caps and glaciers are not a major active carbon sink. Ice trapping does not remove a signif- icant amount of CO₂ from the atmosphere on short time scales. ","PW-0627":"Emissions of all the above-mentioned gases i.e. Carbon dioxide, Oxides of Nitrogen and Oxides of Sulphur take place from coal combustion at thermal power plants. Gas Sources Carbon dioxide (CO2) Burning of fossil fuels, deforestation Oxides of Sulphur Burning fossil fuels, Smelting ores, Volcanic eruptions, Vehicles, etc Nitrogen oxides (N2O) Burning of fossil fuels, fertilizers; burning of wood and crop residue. Carbon Monoxide (CO) Iron ore smelting, burning of fossil fuels, burning e-waste. 113","PW-0628":"Antarctic Ozone Hole was discovered by British Ant- arctic Survey scientists Farman, Gardiner and Shanklin in 1985. The formation of the ozone hole in the Antarctic has been an annual occurrence (in the months of September, October and November, due to a set of special meteorological and chemical conditions that arise at the South Pole, such as the presence of strong polar front, polar stratospheric clouds and increasing inflow of human-made chemicals like CFCs, etc. 114","PW-0629":"Statements 1 is correct: India lacks sufficient alter- native technologies, such as those for renewable energy and waste management, which are essential for mitigating global warming. This gap hampers the country’s ability to address cli- mate change effectively. Statements 2 is correct: As a developing country, India faces challenges in investing significant funds into research and de- velopment due to its economic constraints. Statement 3 is incorrect: It is not accurate to claim that devel- oped countries have primarily set up polluting industries in India. Developed countries have shifted some industries to developing nations due to lower environmental regulations and labor costs (a process known as carbon leakage) but this is not a dominant factor in India's overall emissions. India has strict environmental regulations such as Extended Producer Responsibility (EPR) and Corporate Social Responsibility (CSR) norms. 116","PW-0630":"The Earth’s atmosphere contains gases and particles that contribute to the greenhouse effect, trapping heat and leading to global warming. These gases absorb and re-emit infra- red radiation, while particles like soot can alter solar radiation balance and reduce the reflectivity of surfaces like ice and snow, further influencing climate change. Option (d) is correct:  Soot directly contributes to warming by absorbing sunlight and reducing the reflectivity of snow and ice.  Sulphur hexafluoride is a potent greenhouse gas with a high global warming potential.  Water vapour is the most significant greenhouse gas and amplifies the warming effect through feedback mechanisms.  Other gases that contribute to the greenhouse effect and cause global warming are Carbon Dioxide, Methane, Nitrous Oxide, Ozone and Chlorofluorocarbons (CFCs). 117","PW-0631":"The United Nations Framework Convention on Cli- mate Change (UNFCCC) was drawn up at the UN Conference on Environment and Development, Rio de Janeiro, 1992. This conference, also known as the Earth Summit, set the foundation for global cooperation on climate change and sustainable devel- opment. 118","PW-0632":"A carbon credit represents the reduction or removal of 1 metric ton of CO₂ or its equivalent from the atmosphere. It allows for compensating carbon emissions by funding projects that either reduce emissions, like renewable energy or energy efficiency, or remove CO₂ through methods like reforestation or carbon capture. The concept of carbon credits was formalized under the Kyoto Protocol (1997), introducing mechanisms like Emission Trad- ing, where countries could sell excess credits, and the Clean De- velopment Mechanism (CDM), allowing investments in emis- sion-reduction projects in developing countries for credits. 119","PW-0633":"","PW-0634":"The Clean Development Mechanism (CDM) under the UNFCCC enables developing countries to receive funds from developed nations for adopting technologies that reduce green- house gas emissions. It allows developed countries to invest in emission-reduction projects in developing countries. In return, these developed countries earn carbon credits while promoting sustainable development. Statement 1 is correct. CDM is indeed one of the Kyoto Proto- col mechanisms designed to help reduce greenhouse gas emis- sions by allowing developed countries to invest in emission-re- duction projects in developing countries. Statement 2 is incorrect. CDM projects are implemented in de- veloping countries, not in Annex I countries (which are mostly developed nations). The idea is that developed countries (Annex I) can earn carbon credits by funding emission-reducing projects in developing countries (non-Annex I). 6. ENVIRONMENTAL LAWS, CONVENTIONS AND POLICIES 121","PW-0635":"Emissions that lead to high concentrations of SO2 gen- erally also lead to the formation of other SOx. The largest sources of SO2 emissions are from fossil fuel combustion at power plants and other industrial facilities. EPA’s national ambient air quali- ty standards for SO2 are designed to protect against exposure to the entire group of sulfur oxides (SOx). SO2 is the component of greatest concern and is used as the indicator for the larger group of gaseous sulfur oxides (SOx). Other gaseous SOx (such as SO3) are found in the atmosphere at concentrations much lower than SO2. 123","PW-0636":"Statement 1 is correct: Critical Wildlife Habitats (CWH) are de- fined under the Scheduled Tribes and Other Traditional Forest Dwellers (Recognition of Forest Rights) Act, 2006.. These are ar- eas within wildlife sanctuaries and national parks that are criti- cal for the survival of wildlife species and where human activities may be restricted. Statement 2 is correct: The Baiga tribe in Madhya Pradesh was one of the first communities in India to be granted Habitat Rights under the Forest Rights Act, 2006. This recognition ensures their right to live in and sustainably use forest resources in their tra- ditional habitats. Statement 3 is incorrect: The declaration of Habitat Rights is the responsibility of the Ministry of Tribal Affairs and state-level authorities under the framework of the Forest Rights Act, 2006. SUPER HINT For S3, aligns with Function-person/organisation/min- istry match trap as its easy to manipulate to make it false. Isn't it should be Tribal affairs ministry?? Environment and Ecology 501 125","PW-0637":"Central Ground Water Authority has been constitut- ed under Section 3 (3) of the Environment (Protection) Act, 1986 to regulate and control development and management of groundwater resources in the country. Central Ground Water Authority takes care of regulation and control, management and development of groundwater in the country and issues necessary regulatory directions for the purpose. Environment (Protection) Act, 1986 was enacted in the after- math of Bhopal Gas Tragedy (1984) for protecting, improving environment & reducing pollution. The Act authorises the cen- tral government to control & reduce pollution from all sources. It also provides procedures for setting standards of emission or discharge of environmental pollutants. Organization Affiliated Ministry/De- partment Key Responsibilities Central Ground Wa- ter Board (CGWB) Ministry of Jal Shakti, Department of Water Resources, River Devel- opment & Ganga Rejuve- nation Management, exploration, monitoring, assessment, augmentation, and regulation of groundwater resources in India. National Water De- velopment Agency (NWDA","PW-0638":"Statement 1 is correct: As per Section 39 of Wild Life (Protection) Act, 1972, every Wild Animal shall be the property of the State Government, and, where such animal is hunted in a sanctuary or National Park declared by the Central Government, such animal or any animal article, trophy, uncured trophy or meat [derived from such animal, or any vehicle, vessel, weapon, trap or tool used in such hunting] shall be the property of the Central Government. Statement 2 is correct: The law governing the subject of wild- life, the Wildlife (Protection) Act, 1972, provides for equal pro- tection for wild animals irrespective of where they are found. It does not discriminate between wild animals found in protected areas and outside. Statement 3 is incorrect: Mere apprehension or fear that a wild animal could endanger human life is not a ground for capture or killing. As per Wildlife (Protection) Act, 1972, only if the wild an- imal becomes a danger to human life or is deceased or disabled beyond recovery can it be allowed to be captured or killed by the competent authority, (Chief Wildlife Warde","PW-0639":"The Wildlife Protection Act, 1972 has six schedules. Schedule VI mandates, ‘no person is allowed to cultivate a speci- fied plant mentioned in schedule 6, except with a licence granted by the Chief WildLife Warden’. The plants mentioned in the sixth schedule includes:  Beddomes Cycad  Blue Vanda  Kuth  Ladies slipper orchids  Pitcher plant  Red Vanda The Wildlife (Protection) Amendment Act, 2022 has re- duced the total number of schedules to four by –  Reducing the number of schedules for specially protected animals to two (one for greater protection level),  The Amendment has removed the schedule for vermin species, and  The Amendment has inserted a new schedule for specimens listed in the Appendices under Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species of Wild Fauna and Flora (CITES).  Appendix I of CITES includes the world’s most endangered plants and animals. 128","PW-0640":"Steel Slag, a by-product of steel making, is produced during the separation of the molten steel from impurities in steel-making furnaces. The slag occurs as a molten liquid melt and is a complex solution of silicates and oxides that solidi- fies upon cooling. Statement 1 is correct: Steel slag is widely used as a base course material in road construction, providing a strong and durable foundation beneath asphalt roads, tracks, and paved surfaces. Its high strength, resistance to deformation, and excellent drainage properties enhance pavement longevity. Statement 2 is correct: Steel slag can be used in the agricultural sector due to its ability to correct soil acidity. In fact, developed countries like Japan, the USA have taken the lead in making fer- tilisers using steel-making slag. Statement 3 is correct: Additionally, it is utilized in the pro- duction of Portland slag cement (PSC), where it is blended with ordinary Portland cement to improve durability and resistance to chemical attacks. This not only enhances cement quality but also promotes sustainable construction by recycling","PW-0641":"Option 1 is correct: Copper slag is a by-product ob- tained during smelting and refining of copper. The use of copper slag in cement and concrete provides potential environmental as well as economic benefits. Option 2 is correct: Cold mix asphalt is produced by mixing unheated mineral aggregate with either emulsified bitumen or foamed bitumen. It is suitable for light to medium trafficked roads when used in base and surface courses. Option 3 is correct: The Government has allowed the use of coir based geotextiles for construction of rural roads under the Pradhan Mantri Gram Sadak Yojana in 2020. Options 4 and 5 are incorrect: Hot Mix Asphalt (HMA) is a com- bination of approximately 95% stone, sand, or gravel bound to- gether by asphalt cement, a product of crude oil. The wide use of hot mix technology leads to environmental pollution as these plants emit a huge amount of greenhouse gases. Portland cement is a major CO2 emitter. 130","PW-0642":"Statement 1 is incorrect: The Indian Forest Act, 1927, was amended in 2017 to exclude bamboo grown on non-forest land from the definition of \"tree,\" thereby allowing its free cul- tivation and transportation. However, this amendment does not grant forest dwellers the right to fell bamboo grown on forest ar- eas. Bamboo in forest areas is still regulated under forest laws. Statement 2 is correct: The Forest Rights Act (FRA) of 2006 rec- ognizes bamboo as a minor forest produce (MFP). Statement 3 is correct: The FRA, 2006, grants forest dwellers the right to own, collect, use, and dispose of minor forest pro- duce (MFP). This includes bamboo, tendu leaves, honey, and oth- er non-timber forest products. The National Bamboo Mission (NBM) in India, initiated by the Ministry of Agriculture and Farmers Welfare, seeks to enhance the bamboo sector's growth. It aims to expand bamboo plan- tations, improve post-harvest management, promote product development, and rejuvenate the industry, supporting nurser- ies, cultivation, and processing units. 131","PW-0643":"Laws to manage e-waste have been in place in India since 2011 under The e-Waste (Management and Handling) Rules, 2011, which was amended in 2016 as E-waste (Management) Rules, 2016. It recognises producers’ liability for recycling and reducing e-waste in the country. Extended Producer Responsibility (EPR) is a policy approach under which producers are given a significant responsibility – financial and/or physical – for the treatment or disposal of post-consumer products. The Central Pollution Control Board (CPCB) has been given the Extended Producer Responsibility (EPR) authorisation under the new e-waste rules. 132","PW-0644":"Compensatory Afforestation Fund Act (Campa Act), 2016 is aimed at providing an appropriate institutional mecha- nism to utilize afforestation funds. The Act sets up the Central and State Compensatory Afforestation Fund Management & Planning Authorities (CAMPA). Statement 1 is correct: As per the Act, the Compensatory Affor- estation Fund Management and Planning Authority (CAMPA) is set up at both central and state levels for expeditious and trans- parent utilisation of funds released for forest land diverted for non-forest purposes. The National Fund receives 10% & State Fund gets 90% of funds collected. Environment and Ecology 503 Statement 2 is incorrect: The Compensatory Afforestation Fund Act, 2016 does not mandate people’s participation in com- pensatory afforestation programmes. While community involve- ment is encouraged in forest conservation efforts, the Act does not legally require it. 133","PW-0645":"​Environment (Protection) Act, 1986 is aimed at pro- tecting, improving the environment & reducing pollution. The Act, empowers the Government of India for coordination of action by the state, planning and execution of nationwide pro- grammes. The Act authorises the central government to control & reduce pollution from all sources. Statement 1 is incorrect: The provisions in the Environment (Protection) Act, 1986 does not explicitly mention detailed pro- visions for public participation. However, it does enable certain mechanisms that indirectly promote public involvement. Statement 2 is correct: Section 3(2)(v) of the Act states that the central government can prescribe standards for the quality of the environment and emissions or discharges of pollutants from various sources. The Act also allows the government to regulate industrial and commercial activities that may harm the environ- ment. 134","PW-0646":"The NGT provides environ- mental justice and Central Pollution Control Board (CPCB)  NGT was established by National Green Tribunal Act, 2010, with jurisdiction over all civil disputes addressing important environmental issues.  Central Pollution Control Board (CPCB) was established under the Water (Prevention and Control of Pollution) Act of 1974 as a statutory body.  National Green Tribunal Act, 2010 was enacted for effective and expeditious disposal (within 6 months of appeal) of environmental cases and to help reduce burden of litigation in the higher courts.  It is also entrusted with the powers & functions under the Air (prevention and control of pollution) Act, 1981.  It provides for Enforcement of legal environmental rights, relief & compensation for damages caused.  It works under the Ministry of Environment, Forest & Climate Change (MoEF&CC).  The tribunal’s decision is enforceable as a civil court judgement and is governed by natural justice principles. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 504 Statement 1 is incorrect: Both the NGT and CPCB were estab- lished by some Acts, namely, ","PW-0647":"Global Alliance for Climate-Smart Agriculture (GACSA) is an inclusive, voluntary and action-oriented multi-stakeholder platform on Climate-Smart Agriculture (CSA). The vision is to improve food security, nutrition and resil- ience in the face of climate change. GACSA aims to catalyze and help create transformational partnerships to encourage actions that reflect an integrated approach to the three pillars of CSA. Statement 1 is incorrect: The concept of Climate-Smart Ag- riculture (CSA) was originally developed by FAO and officially presented at the Hague Conference on Agriculture, Food Se- curity and Climate Change in 2010, through the paper “Cli- mate-Smart Agriculture: Policies, Practices and Financing for Food Security, Adaptation and Mitigation”. The Global Alliance for Climate-Smart Agriculture (GACSA) was launched during the UN Climate Summit of 2014, in New York(not at the Paris Climate Summit in 2015). Statement 2 is correct: Its membership does not impose any binding obligations on its participants, allowing for flexible engagement in promoting climate-smart agricultural pr","PW-0648":"The proposal to translocate some of the lions from their natural habitat in Gujarat was aimed at establishing a second population of Asiatic lions in Kuno Palpur Wildlife Sanctuary in Madhya Pradesh. This initiative is part of the Asiatic Lion Rein- troduction Project, which seeks to ensure the genetic stability and conservation of the species. The last wild population of the Asiatic lion is found in the region of Gir Forest National Park, in the state of Gujarat. 138","PW-0649":"Schedule I of the Wildlife (Protection) Act, 1972 cov- ers endangered species that need rigorous protection. The spe- cies are granted protection from poaching, killing, trading etc. Wildlife (Protection) Act, 1972 was passed in order to safe- guard various plant and animal species. Some of the animals granted protection under the Schedule I include, Black Buck, Ti- ger, Clouded Leopard, Snow Leopard, Swamp Deer, Himalayan Bear, Asiatic Cheetah, Kashmiri Stag, Fishing Cat, Lion-tailed Macaque, Musk Deer, Rhinoceros, Brow Antlered Deer, Chinkara (Indian Gazelle), Capped Langur, Golden Langur, Hoolock Gibbon etc. Species declared protected under Schedule I are prohibited to be hunted throughout India, except under threat to human life or in case of a disease that is beyond recovery. Thus tortoise species declared under Schedule I enjoys the same level of protec- tion as iconic species like the tiger and elephant. Note: Updated schedules have been added in the vermin ques- tion of 2024. 139","PW-0650":"Under the Wildlife (Protection) Act, 1972, certain species are granted varying levels of protection through clas- sification into different schedules. Species listed in Schedule I receive the highest level of protection, prohibiting hunting ex- cept under specific circumstances such as threat to human life, if the animal is disabled or diseased beyond recovery or for scien- tific research.  The Gharial (Gavialis gangeticus), a critically endangered crocodilian, is listed under Schedule I, providing it with stringent protection measures.  The Indian Wild Ass (Equus hemionus khur), found primarily in the Rann of Kutch, is also listed under Schedule I, ensuring its protection.  The Wild Buffalo (Bubalus arnee), native to parts of central India, is included in Schedule I, reflecting its endangered status and the need for strict conservation efforts. Note: Updated schedules have been added in the vermin ques- tion of 2024.\" Environment and Ecology 505 140","PW-0651":"Paris Summit COP21-2015 is a legally binding Inter- national Treaty on Climate Change. It was adopted by 195 Parties at COP 21 in Paris, on 12 December 2015 & entered into force on 4 November 2016. It requires all parties to put forward their Na- tionally Determined Contributions (NDCs) which are voluntary in nature. Statement 2 is correct: Paris Summit COP21 aims to limit glob- al warming due emission of green house gas emissions to below 2 degree Celsius, preferably to 1.5 degrees Celsius, compared to pre-industrial levels. It requires all parties to put forward their Nationally Determined Contributions (NDCs) which are volun- tary in nature. Statements 1 and 3 are incorrect: The Treaty was only “agreed” by 195 Parties in Paris at the conference. The agreement will en- ter into force only after 55 countries that account for at least 55% of global emissions have deposited their instruments of ratifica- tion. Developed countries will work to define a clear roadmap on ratcheting up climate finance to USD 100 billion (not USD 1000 billion) by 2020. SUPER HINT For S1, \"All members of UN","PW-0652":"The Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs) are a set of 17 global objectives established by the United Nations in 2015 as part of the 2030 Agenda for Sustainable Develop- ment. These goals address various global challenges, including poverty, inequality, climate change, environmental degradation, peace, and justice, with a target to achieve them by 2030. The SDGs replaced the Millennium Development Goals (MDGs) in 2015, which started a global effort in 2000 to tackle the indignity of poverty. Statement 1 is incorrect: The Club of Rome, established in 1968, is known for its 1972 report titled “The Limits to Growth,” which discussed the potential consequences of un- checked economic and population growth. While this report highlighted the need for sustainable practices, it did not pro- pose the SDGs. The Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs) were born at the United Nations Conference on Sustainable Devel- opment in Rio de Janeiro in 2012. The SDGs were formulated through a United Nations-led process, culminating in their adoption in 2015. Statement 2 is correct: In 2015, the United Nation","PW-0653":"United Nations Convention to Combat Desertifi- cation (UNCCD) was established in 1994. It is the sole legally binding international agreement linking environment and de- velopment to sustainable land management. There are 197 Par- ties to the Convention, including 196 country Parties and the European Union. The Convention, based on the principles of par- ticipation, partnership and decentralization, is a multilateral commitment to mitigate the impact of land degradation. Its flag- ship publication includes Global Land Outlook. Statement 1 is correct: Its 197 Parties aim, through inno- vative national schemes and global partnerships, to imple- ment the Convention and achieve the Sustainable Develop- ment Goals. The end goal is to protect the land from overuse and drought, so it can continue to provide food, water and energy. Statement 2 is incorrect: The Convention addresses specifically the arid, semi-arid and dry sub-humid areas, known as the dry- lands, where some of the most vulnerable ecosystems and peo- ple can be found. It is not particularly focussed towards South Asia and Nor","PW-0654":"Pairs 1 is incorrectly matched: Annex-I countries re- fer to developed countries listed under the Kyoto Protocol with binding commitments to reduce emissions. The Cart- agena Protocol deals with biosafety and regulates the trans- boundary movement of living modified organisms (LMOs), not emissions reduction. Pairs 2 is incorrectly matched: Certified Emissions Reduc- tions (CERs) are issued for emission reductions under the Kyoto Protocol, not the Nagoya Protocol. The Nagoya Proto- col focuses on access to genetic resources and fair sharing of benefits, not emission reductions. Pair 3 is correctly matched: The Clean Development Mech- anism (CDM) under the UNFCCC enables developing countries to receive funds from developed nations for adopting technolo- gies that reduce greenhouse gas emissions. The CDM is the main source of income for the UNFCCC Adaptation Fund, which was established to finance adaptation projects and programmes in developing country Parties to the Kyoto Protocol that are partic- ularly vulnerable to the adverse effects of climate change.  Cartagena Protocol on Biosa","PW-0655":"The Economics of Ecosystems and Biodiversity (TEEB) was launched by Germany and the European Commis- sion in 2007. It is a global effort to raise awareness of the eco- nomic advantages of biodiversity. TEEB’s objective is to raise at- tention to the rising costs associated with biodiversity loss and ecosystem degradation and to bring together experts in science, economics, and policy to facilitate actionable solutions. Statement 1 is incorrect: It is an international initiative, launched by Germany and the European Commission. The sec- ond phase of the TEEB study is hosted by the United Nations Environment Programme (UNEP) with support from a number of other organizations. Statement 2 is correct: It is an international initiative to draw attention to the global economic benefits of biodiver- sity. Its principal objective is to mainstream the values of biodi- versity and ecosystem services into decision-making at all levels. Statement 3 is correct: Its objective is to highlight the growing cost of biodiversity loss and ecosystem degradation. It follows a structured approach to valuati","PW-0656":"Reducing Emissions from Deforestation and Forest Degradation (REDD+) is a mechanism developed by Parties to the UNFCCC. In order to provide incentives for developing countries to cut emissions from forested lands and invest in low-carbon paths, it sets a financial value for the carbon con- tained in forests. For activities based on results, the developing countries will be compensated. The UN-REDD Programme has identified the following three topics for supporting national REDD+ governance structures:  Country-led multi-stakeholder governance assessments that contribute to the development and implementation of national REDD+ strategies (for tackling forest degradation and biodiversity loss) and nationally owned monitoring frameworks  Social standards, including poverty and gender.  Land and/or carbon tenure and the role of REDD+ within national land use strategies The REDD+ goes beyond simply deforestation and forest degra- dation by including the role of conservation, sustainable manage- ment of forests and enhancement of forest carbon stocks. 146","PW-0657":"Agenda 21 is a comprehensive action plan for sus- tainable development, adopted at the United Nations Confer- ence on Environment and Development (UNCED), commonly known as the Earth Summit, held in Rio de Janeiro, Brazil, in 1992. The number “21” refers to an agenda for the 21st cen- tury. It’s objective is to achieve Global sustainable development. Statement 1 is correct: Agenda 21 serves as a comprehensive plan of action for sustainbility to be taken globally, nationally, and locally by organizations of the United Nations System, governments, and major groups in every area where humans im- pact the environment. Statement 2 is incorrect: Agenda 21 is a product of the Earth Summit (UN Conference on Environment and Development) held in Rio de Janeiro, Brazil, in 1992. The World Summit on Sustainable Development (WSSD), held in Johannesburg in 2002, reaffirmed the commitment to Agenda 21 and aimed to assess progress and implement further actions 147","PW-0658":"As a protocol to the Vienna Convention (first inter- national agreement to protect the ozone layer,) Montreal Pro- tocol deals with the substances that deplete the Ozone Layer (ozone-depleting substance-ODS). The Montreal Protocol phases down the consumption and production of the different ODS in a step-wise manner, with different timetables for devel- oped and developing countries (referred to as “Article 5 coun- tries”). The Montreal Protocol is an international treaty de- signed to protect the ozone layer by phasing out the production and consumption of numerous substances responsible for ozone depletion. Finalized in 1987, it has been hailed as one of the most successful environmental agreements, achieving universal ratifi- cation and significantly reducing the presence of ozone-deplet- ing substances (ODS) in the atmosphere. 148","PW-0659":"Rio+20 is the short name for the United Nations Con- ference on Sustainable Development which took place in Rio de Janeiro, Brazil in June 2012 i.e. twenty years after the land- mark 1992 Earth Summit in Rio. At the Rio+20 Conference, world leaders, along with thousands of participants from the private sector, NGOs and other groups, came together to shape how we can reduce poverty, advance social equity and ensure en- vironmental protection on an ever more crowded planet. In Rio, Member States agreed to initiate a process to create a set of Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs) that would build on the Millennium Development Goals and align with the post- 2015 development agenda. The conference also endorsed pio- neering guidelines for green economy policies. Additionally, governments decided to establish an intergovernmental pro- cess under the General Assembly to explore strategies for fi- nancing sustainable development. 149","PW-0660":"The Genetic Engineering Appraisal Committee was constituted under the Environment (Protection) Act, 1986. The Genetic Engineering Appraisal Committee (GEAC) functions under the Ministry of Environment, Forest and Climate Change (MoEF&CC). It is responsible for the appraisal of activities in- volving large-scale use of hazardous microorganisms and recombinants in research and industrial production from the environmental angle. The committee is also responsible for the appraisal of proposals relating to the release of genetically engineered (GE) organisms and products into the environment including experimental field trials. The committee oversees the use, import, and export of ge- netically modified organisms and crops, ensuring they comply with environmental safety standards. 150","PW-0661":"The Sustainable Sugar Initiative (SSI) was launched jointly by International Crops Research Institute for the Semi-Ar- id Tropics (ICRISAT) and World Wide Fund for Nature (WWF). SSI aims at cultivating sugarcane mainly by changing the way the inputs and methods are used, such as less use of seeds ,less use of water, optimum utilization of fertilizers and land, aims at reducing the input cost. Statement 1 is correct: The Sustainable Sugarcane Initiative (SSI) is an innovative set of agronomic practices that involves using less seeds, raising seeds in a nursery, and following new planting methods. Statements 2 and 4 are correct: SSI provides ample scope for intercropping and the drip irrigation method as it incorporates wider seed spacing and better water and nutrient management to increase the cane yields significantly. Statement 3 is incorrect: Application of both inorganic and organic fertilizers such as Nitrogen, Phosphorus, and Potas- sium (NPK) fertilizers are part of Sustainable Sugar Initia- tive (SSI). UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 508 151","PW-0662":"Option 1 is correct: The International Treaty on Plant Genet- ic Resources for Food and Agriculture, also known as the Seed Treaty, was adopted during the 31st session of the United Na- tions Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO) in 2001. India is a signatory to this treaty, which directly impacts biodiversity, as seeds are crucial for the conservation of plant genetic resources. Option 2 is correct: United Nations Convention to Combat Desertification (UNCCD) was established in 1994. It is the sole legally binding international agreement linking environment and development to sustainable land management. Habitat loss to meet our demand for food, raw materials or buildings is the lead- ing cause of species extinction. Conserving, restoring, and sus- tainably managing habitats and ecosystems is recognized as the most effective way to protect biodiversity. One powerful example is the Great Green Wall. The Wall is an African-led initiative to restore biodiversity. Option 3 is correct: World Heritage Convention (1972) of UNESCO is concerned with the protection of the World Cultur- al an","PW-0663":"Statement 1 is incorrect: Earth Hour is a global move- ment for environmental conservation, started by the World Wide Fund for Nature (WWF) in 2007. Statement 2 is correct: It is an annual event that takes place on the last Saturday of March. Millions of people in over 180 coun- tries and territories participate in it by turning off their lights for 1 hour. Statement 3 is correct: It showcases the urgent need to take ac- tion on the pressing issue of climate change. Further, it promotes awareness about environmental issues on a public platform. 153","PW-0664":"The 'Montreux Record' is a register of wetlands listed under the Ramsar Convention that have experienced, are experi- encing, or are expected to experience changes in their ecological character. These changes may be due to factors like technological development, pollution, or other human influences. The Ramsar Convention, established in 1971 in Ramsar, Iran, is an international agreement aimed at the \"conservation and sus- tainable use of wetlands.\" It is not a regulatory framework, but rather the only global treaty specifically focused on the preser- vation of wetlands. According to the Ramsar Convention, wetlands include all areas of marsh, fen, peatland, and water, whether natural or man-made, permanent or temporary, and with freshwater, brackish, or salt- water, whether flowing or static. This definition also includes ma- rine areas with a depth of less than six meters at low tide. World Wetlands Day is celebrated on February 2nd each year. 154","PW-0665":"Wetlands International is a global organisation that works to sustain and restore wetlands and their resources for people and biodiversity. It is an independent, not-for-profit, global organization, supported by governments and NGO mem- bers from around the world. Statement 1 is incorrect: Wetlands International is not an inter- governmental organization. Instead, it is an independent NGO that works in partnership with governments, international organizations, and local communities. While Wetlands Inter- national collaborates closely with the Ramsar Convention, it is not formed by the signatories. The Ramsar Convention rec- ognizes Wetlands International as one of its International Orga- nization Partners (IOPs), along with other bodies like WWF and BirdLife International. Statement 2 is correct: Wetlands International conducts field projects that generate data on wetland management and conser- vation. These insights inform policies, guide sustainable practic- es, and raise awareness. Their work spans research, community projects, and advocacy with governments, corporations, and in- ","PW-0666":"Wetlands connect land and water, offering crucial ser- vices for rivers. They absorb water during wet seasons, aiding flood protection and groundwater recharge, while filtering nutri- ents and sediments. Wetlands also support diverse ecosystems, serving as spawning grounds for fish and nesting sites for migra- tory birds. Pair 1 is correctly matched: Harike Wetland is the largest wetland in northern India on the border of Tarn Taran Sahib district and Ferozepur district of Punjab. The wetland and the lake were formed by constructing the headworks across the Sut- lej River in 1953, located downstream of the confluence of the Beas and Sutlej rivers just south of Harike village. Pair 2 is incorrectly matched: The Keoladeo National Park or Keoladeo Ghana National Park is formerly known as the Bharatpur Bird Sanctuary is in the Bharatpur District of Ra- jasthan. It is situated at the confluence of the Gambhira and the Banganga rivers. Pair 3 is incorrectly matched: Kolleru lake is the largest fresh- water lake in Andhra Pradesh, India. It is located between Krish- na and Godavari deltas. ","PW-0667":"National Green Tribunal (NGT) Act, 2010 aims at ef- ficient & quick resolution of environmental disputes (within 6 months of appeal) in order to lessen the burden of litigation in the higher courts. The Act established National-Green Tribunal with jurisdiction over all civil cases involving substantial ques- tions relating to the environment. Tribunal is guided by prin- ciples of natural justice & its order is executable as a decree of a civil court. Although the NGT’s orders are final, they may be contested in the SC within 90 days. Statement 1 is correct: The NGT Act is grounded in the fun- damental right to a clean and healthy environment, which is integral to the Right to Life under Article 21. Landmark judg- ments, such as Subhash Kumar v. State of Bihar (1991) and M.C. Mehta cases, have expanded the interpretation of Article 21 to include environmental protection. Statements 2 and 3 are incorrect: Provisions mentioned in statements 2 and 3 have no bearing upon National-Green Tri- bunal:  Article 275(1) of the Constitution of India guarantees grants-in-aid from the Consolidated","PW-0668":"The Indian Forest Act, 1927 This Act provides the legal framework for the management and protection of forests in In- dia. By regulating the use of forest resources, it directly contributes to the conservation of biodiversity within forest ecosystems. In order to increase accountability for forest pro- tection, this act lays out the steps that must be taken when designating a region as a Reserved Forest, Protected Forest, or Village Forest. Import and Ex- port (Control) Act, 1947 This Act regulates the import and export of goods, including wildlife and plant species. By controlling trade, it helps prevent the exploitation and illegal trafficking of endan- gered species, thereby contributing to biodi- versity conservation. Mining and Mineral Development (Regulation) Act 1957 Mining activities, whether occurring within or near Protected Areas, cause a range of en- vironmental consequences that can be severe and irreversible. Thus mining is restricted in reserved areas. Customs Act, 1962 Import and export of GMOs or exotic species are strictly regulated whereas certain medic- inal plant","PW-0669":"Central Ground Water Board monitors groundwater levels throughout the country on a regional scale, four times in a year during the months of March/April/May, August, Novem- ber and January. For monitoring of ground water level, CGWB has a dedicated network of about over 30000 monitoring sta- tions called “National Hydrograph Network Stations (NHNS)”, which comprises open dug wells and purpose built bore/tube wells for water level monitoring called piezometers. Statement 1 is incorrect: 256 of our approximately 700 districts have groundwater levels which are “critical” or “over-exploit- ed” as per the latest data from the Central Ground Water Board (2017). As per the report ‘National Compilation on Dynamic Groundwater Resources of India, 2017 out of the total 6881 as- sessment units (Blocks/Mandals/ Talukas) in the country, 1186 units in various States (17%) have been categorized as ‘Over-Ex- ploited’, 313 units (5%) are ‘Critical’. This adds to 22%. Statement 2 is correct: The Central Ground Water Authority (CGWA), established under Section 3(3) of the Environment (Protection) Act, 1","PW-0670":"Partnership for Action on Green Economy (PAGE) is a direct response to the Rio+20 Declaration, The Future We Want i.e. The United Nations Conference on Sustainable De- velopment 2012, Rio de Janeiro. PAGE serves as a framework to coordinate UN efforts in the green economy and to help na- tions meet and track the upcoming Sustainable Development Goals. The partnership aims to place sustainability at the core of economic policies and practices, thereby advancing the 2030 Agenda for Sustainable Development. It supports countries in re- shaping their economic policies around sustainability to foster growth, create jobs, reduce poverty and inequality, and strength- en ecological foundations. 161","PW-0671":"The UNFCCC Secretariat introduced the “Climate Neu- tral Now” initiative in 2015 to promote voluntary action towards climate neutrality. In 2016, during the UN Climate Change Conference in Marrakech (COP22), the UNFCCC Secretari- at combined its “Climate Neutral Now” initiative with the “Momentum for Change” initiative, creating a new pillar fo- cused on climate neutrality. The initiative aims to achieve a cli- mate-neutral world by 2050, as outlined in the Paris Agreement. It provides a platform for recognizing and showcasing successful climate actions by non-Party stakeholders, including businesses, investors, cities, regions, and civil society. 162","PW-0672":"Global Climate Change Alliance (GCCA) operates through the existing national and international channels for po- litical cooperation and dialogue. It became the main project of the Global Climate Change Alliance Plus (GCCA+) in 2015 with strategic focus on promoting the 2015 Paris Agreement on Cli- mate Change, the 2030 Agenda for Sustainable Development, and its Sustainable Development Goals. Statement 1 is correct: The Global Climate Change Alliance (GCCA) is an initiative of the European Union. Statement 2 is correct: It was launched to enhance dialogue and cooperation on climate change, this initiative focuses on support- ing developing countries, particularly Least Developed Countries (LDCs) and Small Island Developing States (SIDS), which are most vulnerable to its effects. It provides technical and financial assistance to help these nations integrate climate change into their development strategies and budgets. Statement 3 is incorrect: The World Resources Institute (WRI) is a global research organization focused on the intersection of environment, economic opportunity, and hum","PW-0673":"Climate and Clean Air Coalition (CCAC) is a volun- tary alliance of governments, intergovernmental organisations, corporations, academic institutions, and organisations from civil society dedicated to enhancing air quality and defending the en- vironment by taking steps to reduce short-lived climate pollut- ants. Statement 1 is incorrect: The United Nations Environment Programme (UNEP), the governments of Bangladesh, Canada, Ghana, Mexico, Sweden, and the United States joined forces in 2012 to launch initiatives to handle short-lived climate pollut- ants as an urgent and collective concern. CCAC is not an initia- tive of G20 countries. Statement 2 is correct: CCAC works to reduce Short-Lived Cli- mate Pollutants which includes black carbon, methane, tropo- spheric ozone, and hydro-fluorocarbons. By addressing these pollutants, the coalition aims to achieve near-term climate bene- fits, improve air quality, and promote public health. 164","PW-0674":"TRAFFIC’s mission aligns with the long-term goals of the Kunming-Montreal Global Biodiversity Framework, envision- ing a world in harmony with nature. By 2050, it aims to ensure that biodiversity is valued, conserved, restored, and sustainably used, safeguarding ecosystem services, supporting a healthy planet, and providing essential benefits for all. Statement 1 is incorrect: TRAFFIC is an independent non-gov- ernmental organization and operates as a strategic alliance between the World Wide Fund for Nature (WWF) and the International Union for Conservation of Nature (IUCN). It is not a bureau under UNEP. TRAFFIC was established in 1976 as a specialist group of the Species Survival Commission of the IUCN. It later evolved into a strategic alliance between WWF and IUCN, focusing on monitoring wildlife trade to support conservation efforts. Statement 2 is correct: TRAFFIC works to monitor the wildlife trade in the context of both biodiversity conservation and sus- tainable development. It operates globally, with a network of offices and projects around the world, working to monitor an","PW-0675":"The Globally Important Agricultural Heritage Sys- tems (GIAHS) initiative, led by the Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO), aims to identify and safeguard traditional agricultural systems worldwide. These systems are recognized for their unique landscapes, rich biodiversity, and the traditional knowledge of local communities. Three sites recognised as GI- AHS in India:  Kuttanad Below Sea Level Farming System of Kerala.  Koraput Traditional Agriculture of Odisha.  Pampore Saffron Heritage of Kashmir. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 512 Statement 1 is incorrect: The GIAHS initiative supports the sustainability and viability of traditional agricultural sys- tem. However its primary goal is not to introduce modern technology or farming methods to enhance productivity. In- stead, it focuses on preserving and promoting traditional practic- es that have proven sustainable over time. Statement 2 is correct: The main objective of the GIAHS ini- tiative is to recognize and protect traditional agricultural practices, along with their associated landscapes, biodiver- sity, and the cultural knowledge","PW-0676":"BirdLife International is a global partnership of con- servation organizations dedicated to the protection of birds, their habitats, and global biodiversity. Established in 1922 as the International Council for Bird Preservation, it has evolved into a worldwide network operating in over 100 countries. Statement 1 is correct: BirdLife International functions as a global alliance of non-governmental organizations focused on bird conservation. Each partner represents a specific coun- try or territory, working collaboratively to achieve shared con- servation goals. Statement 2 is incorrect: The term “biodiversity hotspots” was introduced by British ecologist Norman Myers in 1988 to identify regions with significant levels of biodiversity under threat from human activities. This concept was later adopted and promoted by organizations such as Conservation International. It did not originate from BirdLife International. Statement 3 is correct: BirdLife International is responsible for identifying and documenting Important Bird and Biodi- versity Areas (IBAs). These sites are recognized for ","PW-0677":"Statement 1 is incorrect: IUCN is an NGO, founded in October 1948 as the International Union for the Protection of Nature (or IUPN) following an international conference in Fon- tainebleau, France. Later the name was changed to International Union for Conservation of Nature and Natural Resources (IUCN). CITES is an international agreement between governments, aiming to ensure that international trade in specimens of wild animals and plants does not threaten their survival. The CITES Secretariat is administered by UNEP and is located at Geneva, Switzerland. Statement 2 is correct: IUCN supports scientific research, manages field projects globally and brings governments, non-government organisations, United Nations agencies, compa- nies and local communities together to develop and implement policy. Statement 3 is correct: CITES is legally binding on its Par- ties but it does not replace national legislation. It provides a framework that each Party must implement through its own do- mestic laws to ensure the Convention’s provisions are enforced at the national level. 168","PW-0678":"As the world’s largest climate fund, GCF accelerates transformative climate action in developing countries through a country-owned partnership approach and use of flexible financ- ing solutions and climate investment expertise. Statement 1 is correct: Green Climate Fund aims to make an ambitious contribution to attaining the mitigation and adap- tation goals of the international community to counter climate change. The Fund allocates its resources to low-emission and climate-resilient projects and programmes in developing countries. Statement 2 is incorrect: The GCF was established in 2010 by 194 countries party to the United Nations Framework Con- vention on Climate Change (UNFCCC) as an operating entity of the Convention’s financial mechanism. It is not founded un- der the United Nations Environment Programme (UNEP), the Or- ganisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD), the Asian Development Bank (ADB), or the World Bank. Environment and Ecology 513 169","PW-0679":"Statement 1 is incorrect: Animal Welfare Board of In- dia was established in 1962 under Section 4 of the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals Act, 1960. It serves as a statutory advisory body on animal welfare laws and promotes animal welfare in the country. Statement 2 is correct: The National Tiger Conservation Au- thority (NTCA) is a statutory body. It was constituted under the Wildlife (Protection) Act, 1972, as amended in 2006. It aims to strengthen tiger conservation initiatives by providing a statutory basis for the protection of tiger reserves and ensuring accountability in the management of these reserves. Statement 3 is correct: The National Ganga River Basin Au- thority (NGRBA) was established in 2009 under the Environ- ment (Protection) Act, 1986. It is chaired by the Prime Minis- ter and includes Union Ministers and Chief Ministers of states through which the Ganga flows. It is in charge of overseeing the restoration of the River Ganga Basin, including Ganga and its trib- utaries, and the prevention of pollution. 170","PW-0680":"BNHS is one of the biggest non-governmental groups working on biodiversity and conservation. It was established in 1883. It has its headquarters in Mumbai’s Hornbill House. BNHS funds numerous research projects, and it also puts out the Bombay Natural History Society Journal. The Great Hornbill serves as the BNHS’s emblem. Statement 1 is incorrect: BNHS is an independent non-gov- ernmental organization (NGO) and is not an autonomous body under the Ministry of Environment and Forests. While it collaborates with various governmental agencies, it operates independently. Statement 2 is correct: BNHS’s mission focuses on the con- servation of nature, primarily biological diversity, through action based on research, education, and public awareness. It has been instrumental in various conservation initiatives, in- cluding the protection of endangered species and habitats across India. Its research has significantly contributed to policy formu- lation and implementation in the field of wildlife conservation. Statement 3 is correct: By organizing nature trails, camps, and workshops, BNHS prov","PW-0681":"Statement 1 is incorrect: The State Government will establish a Community Reserve management committee, which will be in charge of conserving, maintaining, and overseeing the community reserve in accordance with Section 36 D of the Wild- life Protection Act (WLPA). The committee will choose a chair- man who will serve as the community reserve's Honorary Wild Life Warden. Statement 2 is correct: Community Reserves are designated to protect wildlife and biodiversity. Under the Wildlife Protection Act, 1972 hunting is strictly prohibited in all protected areas in- cluding Community Reserves. Section 9 of the Act prohibits hunting of wild animals listed in Schedules I, II, III, and IV. Statement 3 is correct: In a Community Reserve, the collection of non-timber forest produce by the local communities is subject to the specific rules and regulations governing the Community Reserve. It may be regulated or restricted to ensure sustainable use and conservation of resources. Statement 4 is incorrect: After a forest has been made into a community reserve, people cannot use it for agricultural ","PW-0682":"Statement 1 is incorrect: The Government of India is not obligated to protect and conserve all the wetlands within its territory. It is only obligated to conserve the wetlands that are recognised under the Ramsar convention as Ramsar sites. Statement 2 is incorrect: The Wetlands (Conservation and Management) Rules, 2010, notified by the Ministry of Environ- ment and Forest, aim to conserve and manage wetlands in India UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 514 and prevent their degradation. However, they were not based on the Ramsar Convention's recommendations. Its objectives are wetland conservation, protection, and management to prevent further degradation of wetlands in India. Statement 3 is correct: As per Wetlands (Conservation and Management) Rules, 2010 a wetland includes natural or artificial areas of marsh, fen, peatland, or water, with static or flowing wa- ter, fresh, brackish, or salt, and marine areas with a depth at low tide not exceeding six meters. It also covers inland waters such as lakes, reservoirs, tanks, backwaters, lagoons, creeks, estuar- ies, and man made wetlands, along with","PW-0683":"Miyawaki method is a method of urban afforestation by turning backyards into mini-forests. It includes planting trees as close as possible in the same area which not only saves space, but the planted saplings also support each other in growth and block sunlight from reaching the ground, thereby preventing the growth of weeds. Thus the saplings become maintenance-free (self-sustainable) after the first three years. It helps to create a forest in just 20 to 30 years while through conventional methods it takes anywhere between 200 to 300 years. In the Miyawaki Process:  The native trees of the region are identified and divided into four layers — shrub, sub-tree, tree, and canopy.  The quality of soil is analysed and biomass which would help enhance the perforation capacity, water retention capacity, and nutrients in it, is mixed with it. The ground is covered with a thick layer of mulch.  A mound is built with the soil and the seeds are planted at a very high density — three to five sapling per square meter. 174","PW-0684":"Wetlands Location and Significance Hokera Wet- land  Jammu and Kashmir.  A perennial natural wetland that is part of the Jhelum basin. Renuka Wet- land  Himachal Pradesh  A naturally occurring wetland that receives freshwater springs and underground karst formations from the lower Himalayas and the Giri river. Rudrasagar lake  Melaghar, Tripura  A lowland sedimentation reservoir in the northeastern highlands that receives water from three enduring streams that empty into the River Gomti. Sasthamkotta lake  Kollam district, Kerala  Being Kerala's largest freshwater lake, it has long been a popular destination for travellers. 175","PW-0685":"Desert National Park is one of the biggest nation- al parks in the country. The environment of the Thar Desert is well-illustrated by the Desert National Park. The main landform is made up of permanent dunes, jagged boulders, and compact salt lake bottoms. Statement 1 is correct: Desert National Park, one of India's largest, showcases the Thar Desert's unique environment, fea- turing permanent dunes, jagged boulders, and salt lake bottoms. Located in Rajasthan, it spans the districts of Jaisalmer and Barmer. Environment and Ecology 515 Statement 2 is incorrect: Human activities are not allowed in National Park yet many villagers live inside Desert Nation- al park. There are several villages inside and outside the Desert National Park. The primary occupation of the villagers inside the Desert National Park is animal husbandry like goat, sheep, cattle, camel, donkey and followed by agriculture. Statement 3 is correct: The Thar desert harbours a wide array of flora and faunal species. Desert National Park is one of the pri- mary habitats of the Great Indian Bustard, a critically endan- ","PW-0686":"Nagarjunsagar-Srisailam is the largest tiger re- serve in India having a Core/ Critical Tiger Habitat of 2595.72 SqKm. The tiger reserve spans states of Telangana and Andhra Pradesh. The reserve is home to the multifunctional reservoirs Srisailam and Nagarjunasagar. This reserve’s basin is bisected by the Krishna River. In addition to the Bengal Tiger, which serves as the area’s top predator, other species are also present here, including the leop- ard, rusty-spotted cat, pangolin, mugger crocodiles, Indian rock python, and countless different types of birds. A variety of wood- lands, from southern mixed deciduous tropical forest to southern thorn forest multiple types of hurbs and bamboo thickets also grow in this area. 178","PW-0687":"Kanha National Park is located in Madhya Pradesh’s Mandla and Balaghat districts. It officially introduced a mas- cot, “Bhoorsingh the Barasingha”. Kanha National Park (Mandla and Balaghat districts, Madhya Pradesh) is home to the Hard Ground Barasingha, also known as the Swamp Deer(Rucervus duvaucelii). They are exclusively graminivorous, meaning their diet consists solely of grasses. It is the state animal of Madhya Pradesh and is only found in the Kanha Tiger Reserve. Tiger, Leopard, Dhole, Bear, Gaur, and Indi- an Python are some of the other species discovered. Evergreen Sal forests are the most famous feature (Shorea Robusta) of Kanha National Park’s flora. The Indian Swamp Deer (Rucervus duvaucelii), also known as Barasingha, is a large herbivorous mammal primarily found in India, with some populations in Nepal and Bangladesh. It is known for its distinctive long, branched antlers and yellow- ish-brown coat. The species is graminivorous, thriving on grass- es in wetlands, marshes, and floodplains. The Hard Ground Barasingha, a subspecies, is notably found in Kanha National Par","PW-0688":"Option 1 is correct: To safeguard the critically endan- gered Musk Deer and its environment, the Askot Musk Deer Sanctuary was established. The refuge is sometimes referred to as “Green Paradise on Earth.” It is situated in Askot, a tiny village in the Pithoragarh district of Uttarakhand. Snow leopard, Hima- layan black bear, Himalayan tahr, blue sheep, musk deer, loong, monal, kalij pheasant, and cheer pheasant are some examples of the local fauna. Option 2 is correct: Gangotri National Park is located in Uttar- kashi, Uttrakhand, in the Bhagirathi River’s upper watershed. Gangotri Glacier is situated inside the park. The park is com- pletely surrounded by temperate coniferous forests. The typical vegetation includes chirpine, deodar, fir, spruce, oak, and rhodo- dendron. The park is home to a number of rare and endangered animals, including the snow leopard, musk deer, Himalayan monal, Himalayan snowcock, and blue sheep (also known as bharal). Options 3 and 4 are incorrect: Kishanpur Wildlife Sanctuary is home to Tigers, Leopards, Pythons, Barking Deer, Ghariyal, Wild Boar and Swam","PW-0689":"National Parks are designated protected areas aimed at preserving the natural environment, ecosystems, and wildlife. India’s first national park, i.e Jim Corbett National Park was established in 1936. As of 2023 India has 106 national parks, covering a total area of 44,402.95 km². Valley of Flowers National Park was established in 1982. Lo- cated in Chamoli, in the state of Uttarakhand, it is renowned for its meadows of indigenous alpine flowers and the variety of veg- etation. The park is entirely inside the temperate alpine region. It is located close to Joshimath in the Garhwal area, tucked in the upper reaches of the Bhyundar Ganga river’s Pushpawati river valley. The Asiatic black bear, snow leopard, musk deer, brown bear, red fox, and blue sheep are among the rare and endangered species that call this area home. Himalayan monal pheasants and other high-altitude birds can also be seen in the park. The Valley of Flowers is one of the most unique ecosystems in the world. It lies within the Nanda Devi Biosphere Reserve and is part of a biodiversity hotspot in the Indian Himalayas. ","PW-0690":"Agasthyamala Biosphere Reserve was established in 2001. It is located near the southernmost tip of the Western Ghats. It includes the following wildlife sanctuaries: Kalakkad Mundanthurai Tiger Reserve, Shendurney Wildlife Sanctu- ary, Peppara Wildlife Sanctuary, and Neyyar Wildlife Sanctu- ary. It comprises the tropical wet evergreen forests of India, the moist deciduous forests of the South Western Ghats, the montane rain forests of the South Western Ghats, and the Shola forests. The Kanikaran tribe, one of the oldest extant ancient tribes in the world, is also found in Agasthyamalai. In 2016, it was added to the World Network of Biosphere Reserves of UNESCO. 182","PW-0691":"Pakke Tiger Reserve is also known as “Pakhui Tiger Re- serve”. It is situated in the East Kameng district of Arunachal Pradesh, India. It is one of the key protected areas in the Eastern Himalayas and is renowned for its rich biodiversity. The reserve lies within the Eastern Himalayan biodiversity hotspot, an area known for its diverse flora and fauna. Pakhui is home to a significant population of Royal Bengal tigers, along with Asian elephants, clouded leopards, Hoolock gibbons, and a variety of bird species, including the endangered Great Indian hornbill. For its Hornbill Nest Adoption Program, this Tiger Reserve re- ceived the 2016 India Biodiversity Award in the category of “Con- servation of vulnerable species.” 183","PW-0692":"Sathyamangalam Tiger Reserve (STR) is situated where the Western and Eastern Ghats converge. This region is home to a sizable tiger population and is adjacent to other land- scapes dedicated to protecting tigers, including BRT, Bandipur, Mudumalai, and Nagarahole. The Nilgiri-Eastern Ghats Elephant Reserve includes this area as well. Due to its peculiar location, the tiger reserve offers a distinctive ecological landscape contain- ing a wide variety and complex mix of vegetation and animals. The connectivity provided by Sathyamangalam also plays a cru- cial role in reducing human-wildlife conflict, preserving ecosys- tems, and supporting conservation initiatives. 184","PW-0693":"Keibul Lamjao National Park in the Bishnupur district of the Indian state of Manipur is the only floating park in ex- istence and is a crucial component of Loktak Lake, which lies in North East India. Locally known as “Phumdi,” the national park is distinguished by floating decaying plant matter. It was estab- lished in 1966 as a wildlife sanctuary to protect the Eld’s deer’s natural habitat, which is in risk of extinction (Cervus eldi eldi). It was declared a national park in 1977. The park is unique in that it is “too shallow to be a lake, too deep to be marsh.” The park offers a diverse array of aquatic, wetland, and terrestrial ecosystems and is mostly made up of damp, semi-evergreen forests. Fauna found in the park in- clude the brow-antlered deer (Cervus eldi eldi), which is its emblematic species, as well as the Asian Golden Cat, Marbled Cat, Malayan Bear, Hog Deer, Himalayan Black Bear, and others. 185","PW-0694":"The Namdapha National Park is located at the inter- national border between India and Myanmar (Burma) in Changlang District, Arunachal Pradesh in northeast India. It is known for its unique climate that ranges from tropical to subtropical, temperate, and arctic due to its vast altitude variation. Spanning from 200 meters to 4,500 meters above sea level, the park encompasses a wide range of ecosystems. The lower altitudes experience tropical and subtropical climates with rich biodiversity, including dense forests and diverse wildlife. As you move higher, the climate shifts to temperate, and eventually, at the highest elevations, it reaches an arctic-like climate, hosting snow-covered peaks. This diversity in climate allows the park to support an incredible variety of flora and fauna, including spe- cies like the snow leopard, clouded leopard, and tiger. Environment and Ecology 517 186","PW-0695":"Eco-Sensitive Zones are defined “as areas/zones with identified environmental resources having incomparable values which require special attention for their conservation” because of its landscape, wildlife, biodiversity, historical and natural val- ues. Statement 1 is incorrect: The National Wildlife Action Plan (2002-2016) of the Ministry of Environment, Forest and Climate Change (MoEFCC) stipulates that state governments should declare land falling within 10 km of the boundaries of national parks and wildlife sanctuaries as eco-fragile zones or Eco-Sensi- tive Zones (ESZs) under the Environmental (Protection) Act, 1986 and not Wildlife (Protection) Act, 1972. Statement 2 is incorrect: The basic aim is to regulate certain activities around National Parks and Wildlife Sanctuaries so as to minimise the negative impacts of such activities on the fragile ecosystem encompassing the protected area. In Eco-Sensitive Zones (ESZs), prohibited activities include com- mercial mining, polluting industries, and large hydropower projects. Regulated activities involve tree felling, hotel construc-","PW-0696":"","PW-0697":"Project Tiger was initiated in 1973 under the Wild- life Protection Act, 1972, with the National Tiger Conservation Authority (NTCA) overseeing the implementation. The project was launched with the primary goal to protect the Bengal tiger, enhance their population, and safeguard their habitats through the establishment of Tiger Reserves. The project has been highly successful, expanding to include a range of conservation efforts. A Tiger Reserve is a protected area legally designated for the con- servation of striped big cats. It can also be classified as a national park or wildlife sanctuary. For example, Sariska Tiger Reserve is also a national park because it was initially established as a na- tional park before being dedicated to tiger conservation. 189","PW-0698":"According to the Ministry of Environment, Forest and Climate Change , a national park is defined as an area, whether within a sanctuary or not, that can be designated by the state government due to its ecological, faunal, floral, geomorphologi- cal, or zoological significance. The purpose of this designation is to protect, propagate, or develop the wildlife and its environ- ment. In National Parks, local people are generally not allowed to collect and use the biomass or any resources for subsistence purposes. The primary objective of National Parks is the protec- tion of biodiversity and preservation of ecosystems. These parks are strictly protected under the Wildlife Protection Act, 1972, and human activities, including the collection of resources like firewood, grazing, and hunting, are prohibited unless specifi- cally allowed for research or management purposes. 190","PW-0699":"Pair 1 is correctly matched: Bhitarkanika National Park is well-known for its population of Saltwater Croco- diles (Crocodylus porosus), which are the largest living reptiles in the world. The park is located in the Kendrapara district of Odisha and is home to a significant number of these crocodiles. It also has rich biodiversity, including mangroves and various bird species. Pair 2 is correctly matched: Desert National Park is well- known for being a habitat of the critically endangered Great Indian Bustard, a large bird species. The National Park is located in Jaisalmer and Barmer district of Rajasthan. Pair 3 is incorrectly matched: Eravikulam National Park in Kerala is known for its population of Nilgiri Tahr, not the Hoolock Gibbon. The Hoolock Gibbon (Hoolock hoolock) is found in parts of Northeast India and in the forests of Assam, Meghalaya, and Arunachal Pradesh, not in Kerala. 191","PW-0700":"Many animals are predators, parasites or parasitoids, using other animals as food. They use a great diversity of hunting strategies and behaviours to capture or feed on their prey. Inver- tebrate predators, parasites and parasitoids play an important role in keeping many animal populations under control.  Parasitoid is an insect whose larvae feed and develop within or on the bodies of other arthropods. Each parasitoid larva develops on a single individual and eventually kills that host. Most parasitoids are wasps, but some flies and a small number of beetles (carabid beetles), moths, lacewings, and even one caddisfly species have evolved to be parasitoids. Parasitoids alone number about 68,000 named species, and most have yet to be named and described.  Predator: They are organisms that capture and eat another (the prey). This act is called predation. The predatory invertebrates include scorpions, centipedes, predatory mites, predatory snails and slugs, nematodes and planarian worms.  Detritivores: Termites are detritivores that eat dead and decaying organic matter like logs of wo","PW-0701":"The banyan fig tree Ficus microcarpa is famous for its aerial roots, which sprout from branches and eventually reach the soil. Aerial roots are roots above the ground that are found in diverse plant species like mangroves, banyan figs and orchids. The tree also has a unique relationship with a wasp that has co- evolved with it and is the only insect that can pollinate it. Figs are known to sustain at least 1,200 bird and mammal species. Fig trees were among the earliest domesticated crops and appear as sacred symbols in Hinduism, Buddhism and other spiritual tra- ditions. 195","PW-0702":"Butterflies: Hybrid Heliconius butterflies are poison- ous in nature. In nature, these butterflies are rare. Heliconius melpomene and Heliconius cydno are both highly poisonous, having evolved to produce their own cyanide, and predators have learned exactly what both of these toxic insects look like. Fish: “Venomous” fish are those that can inject their toxic venom into victims, whereas “poisonous” fish are those that cause toxic symptoms only if they are eaten. For example: Lionfish, red-bel- lied piranha etc. Frogs: Frogs are amphibians which can survive both on land and water. Some of them can be poisonous also. Poison dart frogs are small, brightly colored amphibians that live on tropical rainforest floors across Central and South America. Poison dart frogs are named for the toxins they secrete from their skin, which have tra- ditionally been used to tips of hunters' weapons. For example, the Embera and Noanama Indigenous people in western Colombia have used the skin of golden poison frogs (Phyllobates terribilis) to tip blowgun darts for hundreds of years. 196","PW-0703":"Pair 1 is incorrectly matched: The Indri is endemic to the island country of Madagascar, specifically inhabiting the east- ern rainforests. The unique geographical features and climate of Madagascar have facilitated the evolution of numerous species found nowhere else on Earth, including the Indri. Pair 2 is incorrectly matched: Elk is the largest and most ad- vanced subspecies of red deer, found in North America and in the high mountains of Central Asia. It is a member of the deer family. Recent genetic studies suggest that the “red deer” may have three species:  European red deer.  Tibetan–West Chinese red deer.  Elk. Pair 3 is incorrectly matched: Bonobos and chimpanzees look very similar and both share 98.7% of their DNA with humans— making the two species our closest living relatives. Bonobos are usually a bit smaller, leaner, and darker than chimpanzees. They are found only in the Democratic Republic of Congo. Their dis- continuous range extends from the Lualaba River in the east to the Kasai/Sankuru Rivers in the south and as far as the Congo River in the west and around La","PW-0704":"Statement 1 is correct: Both males and females of the lions are polygamous and breed throughout the year, but females are usually restricted to one or two adult males of their pride. In captivity, lions often breed every year, but in the wild, they usu- ally breed no more than once in two years. Females are receptive to mating for three or four days within a widely variable repro- ductive cycle. Statement 2 is correct: There are four big cats that can roar: lion, tiger, leopard and jaguar - all of which belong to the genus Panthera. In these species, the epihyal bone, part of the voice box, is replaced by a ligament. This can be stretched, creating a larger sound-producing passage and thus a wider range of pitch. The bones of the cheetah's voice box form a fixed structure, with di- vided vocal cords that vibrate with both in and out breaths. This structure is the same for all the 'small' cats. While this design en- ables these cats to purr continuously, it limits the range of other sounds and prevents them from being able to roar. Statement 3 is incorrect: Leopards are known for thei","PW-0705":"The Invasive Species Specialist Group (ISSG) is a glob- al network of scientific and policy experts on invasive species, organised under the auspices of the Species Survival Commis- sion (SSC) of the International Union for Conservation of Nature (IUCN). The ISSG fosters and enables the worldwide exchange of knowledge and information concerning invasive species. It also ensures the linkage between knowledge, practice, and policy to ensure that decisions are based on well-informed insights. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 520 199","PW-0706":"Statement 1 is correct: Mushrooms possess antibacte- rial properties, enhance the immune system, and aid in lowering cholesterol levels. Moreover, they serve as significant reservoirs of bioactive compounds. Consequently, certain mushroom ex- tracts are utilised to support human health and are available in the form of dietary supplements. Statement 2 is correct: Psychoactive properties refer to sub- stances that influence brain function, resulting in alterations in mood, awareness, cognition, emotions, or behaviour. Psilocybin is a hallucinogenic compound found in specific mushrooms com- monly known as magic mushrooms. Statement 3 is correct: In recent times, there has been a grow- ing discovery of insecticidal compounds within mushrooms. Statement 4 is correct: Bioluminescence refers to the genera- tion and release of light by living organisms. Panellus stipticus stands out as one of the most luminous bioluminescent mush- rooms found on our planet. The newly discovered species, desig- nated as Roridomyces phyllostachydis found in Meghalaya, now joins the ranks of the 97 recognised t","PW-0707":"Statement 1 is incorrect: Indian squirrels, such as the Indian Palm Squirrel, do not burrow in the ground to build nests. Instead, they construct nests in trees, crevices, or other elevat- ed areas using materials like leaves and twigs. Burrow-making is more characteristic of rodents like rats or ground squirrels, which are not typical Indian squirrels. Statement 2 is correct: Nuts serve as the primary food source for these creatures year-round, especially during the winter months when they are preparing for hibernation. They store nuts by burying them underground, enabling retrieval during the win- ter season. Statement 3 is correct: Squirrels are omnivores. Their diet primarily consists of nuts and fruits, although they will also con- sume seeds, insects, small mammals, reptiles, eggs, and occasion- ally even bird chicks. 201","PW-0708":"Statement 1 is correct: Guchhi mushroom is a species of fungus in the family Morchellaceae of the Ascomycota. They are prized for their unique, honeycomb-like appearance. Statement 2 is correct: It is grown in the foothills of Himala- yas mostly in the temperate forests of Himachal Pradesh, Ut- taranchal, and Jammu and Kashmir. Statement 3 is incorrect: These mushrooms cannot be culti- vated commercially due to their specific growth conditions. Found in conifer forests of temperate regions, they grow only in high mountain areas after the snow melts and are harvested wild by local communities. 202","PW-0709":"Golden Mahseer is also known as the tiger of Indian rivers. It is a species of the genus Tor. The Golden Mahseer, the longest-living freshwater fish, is native to mountain and sub-mountain regions found in the Himalayan Rivers (Indus, Ganga and Brahmaputra). The Pong Dam reservoir supports an ample population of the golden Mahseer. IUCN Conservation Status: Endangered. The Indian Nightjar (Caprimulgus asiaticus), Spoonbill (Platalea leucorodia), and White Ibis (Threskiornis aethiopicus) are all bird species found in India. 203","PW-0710":"Option 1 is correct: Hedgehogs are small mammals with short limbs and a body low to the ground. Their most dis- tinctive characteristic is the thousands of stiff, sharp spines - harder and sharper than those of a porcupine - that cover the animal’s back and sides, like a pincushion filled with needles. If attacked they will curl into a prickly and unappetizing ball that deters most predators. Option 2 is incorrect: Marmot are any of 14 species of giant ground squirrels found primarily in North America and Eur- asia. Marmots are well suited for life in cold environments and have small fur-covered ears, short, stocky legs, and strong claws for digging. Marmots do not roll up and protect their vulnerable parts. They often use their sharp teeth and powerful jaws to defend themselves. Option 3 is correct: Pangolin, also called scaly anteaters be- cause of their preferred diet. They are the most trafficked mam- mal in the world. If touched or grabbed it will roll up completely into a ball, while the sharp scales on the tail can be used to lash out. Environment and Ecology 521 204","PW-0711":"","PW-0712":"Statement 1 is incorrect: Oil palm trees are native to West Africa but were brought to South-East Asia over 100 years ago as an ornamental tree crop. Southeast Asia, particularly In- donesia and Malaysia, is the largest producer of palm oil. Statement 2 is correct: Non-food applications of Palm oil are Cosmetics, toiletries, soaps and detergents. Oleochemical industry, as a base material for laundry detergents, household cleaners and cosmetics. Statement 3 is correct: Palm oil can be used to produce bio- diesel, which can be used in compression ignition engines, i.e., diesel engines without any modifications. SUPER HINT S2 and S3 mentions \"Some\" and \"Can be used\" which are not absolute requirement, it is possible hence likely true. Thus eliminate options A and C. 206","PW-0713":"Leguminous plants have small pockets or nodules in their roots that host a specific type of bacteria known as nitro- gen-fixing bacteria. Statements 1 and 2 are incorrect: Moringa is a rapidly grow- ing, drought-tolerant tree native to the Indian subcontinent. It is found naturally in the sub-Himalayan regions of Northern India and is now cultivated globally in tropical and subtropical climates. Unlike leguminous plants, Moringa is not a legume and is deciduous, shedding its leaves seasonally. On the other hand, tamarind, a leguminous tree known for its edible fruit, is native to tropical Africa, not South Asia. Statements 3 and 4 are correct: In India most of the Tamarind is collected as Minor Forest Produce with Minimum Support Price. Tamarind is also actively exported from India. Statement 5 is correct: Biodiesel is derived from the tamarind seed through the transesterification process as potential alter- native feedstock for the diesel engine. Seeds of Moringa too can be used for biodiesel production. 207","PW-0714":"Asian Elephants come in three sub-species i.e. Indi- an, Sumatran, and Sri Lankan. The majority of the continent’s remaining elephants belong to the Indian subspecies, which has the largest range. Statement 1 is correct: The leader of a group is the oldest fe- male. She guides the herd in their search for food and water sources. These matriarchal units can occasionally divide into smaller, temporary groups. Statement 2 is correct: The gestation period lasts for 22 months, yielding a single baby. Statement 3 is incorrect: Although sexually mature in their ear- ly teens, elephants generally only start to mate at about 20 years and stop bearing calves at about 50. Statement 4 is incorrect: Recent census showed Kerala as hav- ing 5,706 elephants, while Karnataka has 6049 elephants. 208","PW-0715":"The Ceylon frogmouth (Batrachostomus monilig- er), Coppersmith barbet (Megalaima haemacephala), Gray- chinned minivet (Pericrocotus solaris), and White-throated redstart (Myioborus albogularis) are all species of birds found in India. These birds are known for their unique characteristics and are an important part of India’s rich avifauna. The Ceylon frogmouth is a nocturnal bird, while the Coppersmith barbet is known for its distinctive call that sounds like a coppersmith at work. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 522 209","PW-0716":"Statement 1 is correct: The Asiatic lion (Panthera leo persica) is a subspecies of lion that is naturally found only in India. The Gir Forest is a protected area that provides a habitat for these majestic animals, and conservation efforts are in place to protect and manage the Asiatic lion population. Statement 2 is incorrect: Double-humped camels (Camelus bactrianus) are naturally found in the Central Asian region, particularly in countries like Mongolia, China, and parts of Afghanistan. In India, they are found in the Ladakh region, but their native habitat is not India alone. Statement 3 is incorrect: The one-horned rhinoceros (Rhi- noceros unicornis) is found in India, particularly in Assam and other northeastern states and it is also found in parts of Nepal and Bhutan. 210","PW-0717":"Statement 1 is correct: Many species of turtles are herbi- vores, especially those that live in freshwater or on land. For instance, the green sea turtle (Chelonia mydas) is primarily herbivorous, feeding on seagrass and algae. Similarly, the Aldab- ra giant tortoise is also herbivorous, feeding mainly on grasses and leaves. Statement 2 is correct: Several species of fish are herbivores, consuming algae, aquatic plants, or detritus. Examples include parrotfish, which graze on algae, and certain species of sur- geonfish, which feed on marine plants. Statement 3 is correct: Some marine mammals are herbi- vores, notably the manatee and dugong, which feed on sea- grasses. These mammals are specialized to thrive on a plant- based diet. Statement 4 is correct: Boa Constrictors and Green Anacon- das are examples of viviparous snakes, meaning they give birth to live young with no eggs involved at any stage of development. SUPER HINT “Some” = possibility logic, not absolute. If even one spe- cies of organism does something, the statement is likely correct. UPSC uses “some” to lower the burden","PW-0718":"Pair 1 is correctly matched: Blue Finned Mahseer is found in the Mula-Mutha River close to the Indian city of Pune, a part of the Krishna River basin. It is a freshwater fish. It is also known as Deccan Mahseer or Tor Khudree. Pair 2 is incorrectly matched: Irrawaddy Dolphin’s habitat ex- tends from the Bay of Bengal to New Guinea and the Philippines. It is found in three rivers namely the Irrawaddy (Myanmar), the Mahakam (Indonesian Borneo) and the Mekong but not in Chambal river. The highest single lagoon population of dolphins is considered to be found in Chilika Lake. Pair 3 is correctly matched: Rusty Spotted Cat has been ob- served in eastern Gujarat’s Gir National Park, in Maharashtra’s Tadoba-Andhari Tiger Reserve and along India’s Eastern Ghats. 212","PW-0719":"Prosopis juliflora, or mesquite, is a leguminous flow- ering plant native to South America. It has become invasive in regions like India, Africa, and the Middle East, where it competes with native species for water and nutrients, threatening local bio- diversity. 213","PW-0720":"","PW-0721":"‘Red Sanders’ are known for their rich hue and ther- apeutic properties. They are in high demand across Asia, par- ticularly in China and Japan for use in cosmetics and medicinal products as well as for making furniture, woodcraft and musical instruments. The main threats that Red Sanders face are illic- it felling for smuggling, forest fires, cattle grazing and other anthropogenic threats. Statement 1 is correct: Red Sanders is an endemic tree species native to the Eastern Ghats, specifically found in the forests of Andhra Pradesh. It thrives in rocky, degraded, and fallow lands with red soil and a hot, dry climate. Statement 2 is incorrect: It occurs in the forest formation which is classified as “Southern Tropical Dry Deciduous Forests”. The tree is listed as Endangered on the IUCN Red List, due to over-exploitation of its timber and habitat loss. Efforts are being made to protect the tree’s habitats and to promote sustain- able harvesting practices. 216","PW-0722":"India is home to nine hornbill species, about one-fifth of the 50+ species worldwide. While mainly frugivores, some also consume small mammals, reptiles, and birds. The Great Indian Hornbill primarily inhabits tropical evergreen forests and is found mostly in the Western Ghats and Nilgiris. It relies on large trees with cavities for nesting and roosting. 217","PW-0723":"Statement 1 is correct: Dugongs, or \"sea cows,\" are ma- rine mammals that graze on seagrasses in shallow coastal waters of the Indian and western Pacific Oceans. As the only herbivorous mammal living exclusively in the sea, including in India, dugongs are crucial for maintaining healthy seagrass ecosystems, which support marine biodiversity. Statement 2 is incorrect: The dugong is not found along the entire coast of India. It is mainly found in the Gulf of Mannar and Palk Bay (Tamil Nadu and Kerala) and in the waters of An- daman and Nicobar Islands. The species has a restricted dis- tribution and is not widespread along India's entire coastline.. Statement 3 is correct: The dugong is listed under Schedule I of the Wildlife (Protection) Act, 1972, which provides it with the highest level of protection in India. As a protected species, hunt- ing, poaching, or harm to the dugong is illegal. 218","PW-0724":"The Gangetic Dolphin (Platanista gangeticus) is India's National Aquatic Animal. It is native to the Ganges-Brahmapu- tra-Meghna and Karnaphuli-Sangu river systems, which span Ne- pal, India, and Bangladesh. Endemic to the Indian subcontinent, the Gangetic dolphin be- longs to the Platanistidae family and is one of only four freshwa- ter dolphin species globally. Recognized by its triangular dorsal fin and long, slender beak, this stocky, gray or brown dolphin can grow up to 2.5 meters. Adapted to murky freshwater environ- ments, it uses echolocation to navigate and is locally known as ‘susu.’ 219","PW-0725":"Azadirachta indica, commonly known as the Indian neem tree, is a tropical evergreen belonging to the Meliaceae family, native to the Indian subcontinent, renowned for its me- dicinal and ecological significance. Neem is typically grown in tropical and subtropical regions. Statement 1 is correct: Neem oil and neem barks are used as an insect repellent and can be used for controlling the spread of some insects and mites. Statement 2 is incorrect: While neem seeds contain oil, which has potential as biofuel ,the manufacturing of hospital deter- gents is not a common or widespread use of neem seeds. The primary application of neem oil in hospital settings is in disin- fectants or antiseptic creams, not detergents specifically. Statement 3 is correct: Neem oil has multiple applications in the pharmaceutical industry. Neem is considered a weed and based on its antimicrobial resistance and other antifungal properties, they are also used in pharmaceutical and cosmetic industries. 220","PW-0726":"Gangetic dolphins live in the Ganges-Brahmapu- tra-Meghna and Karnaphuli-Sangu river systems of Nepal, In- dia, and Bangladesh. The Ganges river dolphin can only live in freshwater. They are essentially blind. They are also called ‘susu’. Statement 1 is correct: Dams and barrages disrupt the nat- ural flow of rivers, reducing the availability of suitable hab- itats for the dolphins. They also fragment populations and prevent dolphins from migrating to areas with adequate food resources. These structures can obstruct the dolphins’ access to breeding and feeding grounds. Statement 2 is incorrect: While crocodiles may compete with dolphins for food yet an increase in the population of croc- odiles in rivers is not considered a threat to Gangetic dol- phins. Statement 3 is correct: Dolphins die as a result of accidental- ly being caught in fishing nets, also known as bycatch. Statement 4 is correct: The use of pesticides and fertilizers in agricultural practices leads to water pollution, which can degrade the dolphins’ habitat by reducing water quality and food availability (as it affect","PW-0727":"Option 2 is correct: Common mynas are native to South Asia, with their breeding range extending from Afghani- stan through India and Sri Lanka to Bangladesh. They have been introduced to many tropical regions worldwide, except South America. While generally resident in India, occasional east-west movements occur. The Common Myna is an omnivorous, oppor- tunistic feeder, often foraging on insects disturbed by grazing cat- tle. It thrives in urban environments and is known for its strong territorial instincts, often found in open woodlands. Option 1 is incorrect: Painted storks forage in flocks in shallow waters along rivers or lakes. A wading bird that lives in the wet- lands of tropical Asia. They feed on fish, frogs, and insects in shal- low water. It has distinctive pink tertial feathers Option 3 is incorrect: The habitat of Black-necked Crane is in the high altitude wetlands and grasslands of the Tibetan plateau, Sichuan (China), and eastern Ladakh (India). They are not oppor- tunistic feeders. 222","PW-0728":"Option 1 is correct: The Gharial is critically endan- gered. Once found across the Indian subcontinent, its population has drastically declined due to habitat loss, reduction in prey species, entanglement in fishing nets, and water pollution. It is now confined to a few river systems, especially in the Chambal River. The Gharial is listed as critically endangered by the IUCN Red List. Option 2 is correct: The Leatherback turtle is the largest spe- cies of sea turtle and is listed as vulnerable by the IUCN. The species faces numerous threats, including accidental capture in fishing nets, habitat destruction (especially nesting sites), and il- legal hunting. It is found along India’s coasts, particularly in the Andaman and Nicobar Islands and parts of the Tamil Nadu coast. However many subpopulations (such as in the Pacific and Southwest Atlantic) are Critically Endangered. Option 3 is correct: The Swamp deer (also called the Baras- ingha) is endangered. It is found in wetland areas in parts of In- dia, such as Uttarakhand and Madhya Pradesh. Habitat destruc- tion, hunting, and the dra","PW-0729":"Option 1 is correct: Star Tortoise (Geochelone ele- gans) is naturally found in India. It is a species of tortoise that inhabits the dry forests and scrublands of India, particularly in Rajasthan, Gujarat, Madhya Pradesh, and parts of Tamil Nadu. Environment and Ecology 525 It is easily recognizable due to the star-like patterns on its shell. The species is endangered due to habitat loss and illegal trade. There is a huge international demand for these animals as exotic pets which threatens their survival. Option 2 is correct: Monitor lizards are found in India and are widespread across the country. Several species, including the Indian monitor lizard (Varanus bengalensis), can be found in forests, grasslands, and even near human settlements. These liz- ards are known for their size, strength, and scavenging habits. Option 3 is correct: Pygmy Hog (Porcula salvania) is natural- ly found in India, specifically in the grasslands of Assam. It is a critically endangered species and is the smallest wild pig in the world. The Pygmy hog’s population has been reduced due to hab- itat destruct","PW-0730":"Mammals are warm-blooded animals with hair and ver- tebrates, or backbones. Unlike other classes of animals, female mammals produce milk to nourish their young. Almost all mam- mals give birth to live young (except for the platypus and echid- na, which lay eggs). Statements 1 is correct: Dugong belongs to the order Sirenia and is a marine mammal found in warm coastal waters. The Du- gong (Dugong dugon) is the sea cow found in Indian waters. They are herbivorous and are known for their gentle nature. They give birth to live young and nurse them with milk, char- acteristic of mammals. They are found in over 30 countries and in India are seen in the Gulf of Mannar, Gulf of Kutch, Palk Bay, and the Andaman and Nicobar Islands. Statement 2 is incorrect: The Sea Horse is not a mammal but a fish, part of the genus Hippocampus. Despite its name, the sea horse is a small marine creature, known for its unique horse-like head and upright swimming posture. It is an ectother- mic species (cold-blooded) and lays eggs, unlike mammals which give birth to live young Statements 3 is correct: Sea Lion ","PW-0731":"Bio-fertilizers are living or biologically active products or microbial inoculants of bacteria, algae and fungi (separate- ly or in combination) which are able to enrich the soil with ni- trogen, phosphorus, organic matter etc. Statement 1 is incorrect: Agaricus refers to a genus of fun- gi, commonly known for species like Agaricus bisporus, the common button mushroom. While it is used in culinary and medicinal contexts, it is not used as a biofertilizer. They are not involved in nitrogen fixation or other activities that promote soil fertility, which are characteristic of biofertilizers. Statement 2 is correct: Nostoc is a genus of cyanobacte- ria (blue-green algae) that can fix atmospheric nitrogen. It is often used as a biofertilizer because of its ability to enhance soil fertility by converting atmospheric nitrogen into a form that plants can utilize. Nostoc is commonly found in rice paddies and is used to improve nitrogen content in the soil, especially in or- ganic farming. Statement 3 is incorrect: Spirogyra is a genus of green algae that primarily plays a role in freshwater e","PW-0732":"Lion-tailed macaques (Macaca silenus) are endemic to India, found only in the Western Ghats. They inhabit evergreen and semi-evergreen rainforests, typically at elevations up to 1,500 meters, and are often associated with broadleaf trees. This species is of conservation importance due to its primitive traits. Despite having a relatively wide range, their habitat is small and highly fragmented. The Lion-tailed Macaque has a distinctive ap- pearance with a dark coat, silver-white mane, long tail, and pink face. It resides in monsoon forests and disturbed habitats across Karnataka, Kerala, and Tamil Nadu, but is absent in Andhra Pradesh. 227","PW-0733":"The drastic decline in the vulture population in India is primarily attributed to the use of a veterinary drug called di- clofenac. This drug was commonly administered to cattle to treat inflammation and pain. However, when vultures fed on the car- casses of cattle that had been treated with diclofenac, they suf- fered from kidney failure and fatal toxicity, leading to a sharp decline in their population. 228","PW-0734":"When a pollen grain moves from the anther (male part) of a flower to the stigma (female part), pollination happens and it is the first step in a process that produces seeds, fruits, and the next generation of plants. Vectors that move pollen within the flower and from flower to flower are called pollinators. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 526 Option (d) is correct : Pollination is the transfer of pollen grains from the stamens (the flower parts that produce them) to the ovule-bearing organs or to the ovules (seed precursors) themselves. There are two cate- gories of pollinators, i.e. invertebrate pollinators which includes bees, moths, flies, wasps, beetles and butterflies and verte- brate pollinators which has monkeys, rodents, lemurs, tree squirrels, bats and birds.  The fruit bats (also known as megabats) and nectar- feeding bats are particularly involved in pollination. Bats are vital for the pollination of various species, including certain species of cacti, bananas, and agave plants, which rely on them for reproduction.  Bees are some of the most efficient and well-known pollinators. B","PW-0735":"Seabuckthorn (soil binding, rich in vitamins) is a shrub which produces an orange-yellow coloured edible berry. It can be found in India above treeline in the Himalayan region, usually in arid places like the cold deserts of Ladakh and Spiti. Seabuckthorn grows naturally in Lahaul, Spiti, and some regions of Kinnaur in Himachal Pradesh. Statements 1 and 3 are correct: Seabuckthorn is a soil-bind- ing plant which prevents soil-erosion, it also has commercial value, as it is used in making juices, jams, nutritional capsules etc. Statement 2 is incorrect: While sea buckthorn has various uses, including medicinal and nutritional, it is not primarily known for being a biodiesel source. While some studies have explored its potential as a biofuel, it is not widely regarded as a primary source of biodiesel. Statement 4 is incorrect: Sea buckthorn does not have signif- icant commercial value for its timber. The plant is primarily valued for its fruits, oils, and medicinal properties, not for timber production. 230","PW-0736":"The International Union for Conservation of Nature (IUCN) Red List of Threatened Species, also known as the IUCN Red List or Red Data Book, founded in 1964, is an inventory of the global conservation status and extinction risk of biological species. Great Indian Bustard, Musk Deer, Red Panda and Asiatic Wild Ass (Currently Vulnerable, but as the question is from 2012, we will consider it as Endangered) all are Endangered Species. Im- portant species and their Conservation status are: Species Particulars Great Indi- an Bustard  State bird of Rajasthan  Flagship grassland species, representing the health of the grassland ecology.  States: Rajasthan and Gujarat. Small populations occur in Maharashtra, Karnataka and Andhra Pradesh.  Conservation Status: Critically Endangered Musk Deer  Habitat: J&K, Uttarakhand. Himachal Pradesh, Sikkim and Arunachal Pradesh.  Conservation Status: Endangered Red Panda  Red panda is endemic to the temperate forests of the Himalayas.  Habitat: Sikkim and Assam, northern Arunachal Pradesh.  Threats: habitat loss and fragmentation, poaching, and inb","PW-0737":"The Chiru, or Tibetan Antelope, is adapted to the cold, high-altitude regions of the Tibetan Plateau, steppes, and semi-desert areas. These regions are characterized by cold temperatures and sparse vegetation. Chiru is well-suited to sur- vive in these challenging environments. It is primarily poached for its fine wool, known as Shahtoosh rather than for musk. Environment and Ecology 527 Oryx is a type of antelope that is adapted to hot, arid, and desert regions, such as the Thar Desert in western India and regions in Africa. These antelopes are well-suited to ex- treme heat and dryness due to their ability to survive with very little water, and they often thrive in desert environments. It is poached for its horns and meat. 232","PW-0738":"Option 1 is correct: Black-necked crane is a state bird of Ladakh. It is found in northeastern Ladakh and some parts of Himalayan foothills in India. It is endemic to the Tibet- an Plateau and migrates to India during the winter months. It is listed as vulnerable and is considered an important species for conservation. Option 2 is incorrect: The Cheetah was historically found in India but was declared extinct in India in the 1950s due to hunting and habitat loss. However, the species is now being re- introduced in India, especially in Kuno National Park, Mad- hya Pradesh. Option 3 is correct: In India, most of these species are found in the eastern Himalayas and the north-east, at the confluence of two biogeographically significant regions, the Himalayan and the Indo-Malayan regions. These arboreal mammals are adapted to glide between trees in search of food. Option 4 is correct: The Snow Leopard is found in high-alti- tude regions of Himachal Pradesh, Ladakh, and parts of Ut- tarakhand and Sikkim. It is classified as vulnerable and is an apex predator in cold mountain ecosystems. 23","PW-0739":"Option 1 is correct: Rising temperatures are affecting biodiversity. Global warming induced climate change is causing changing rainfall patterns, extreme weather events, and ocean acidification. These are putting pressure on species already threatened by other human activities. Option 2 is correct: Mammals and birds that require large ter- ritories as well as animals with migratory habitat are adversely affected by fragmentation of Habitat. This results in population decline. Option 3 is correct: Invasive alien species are animals, plants, fungi and microorganisms entered and established in the envi- ronment from outside of their natural habitat. They reproduce rapidly, out-compete native species for food, water and space, and are one of the main causes of global biodiversity loss. Option 4 is incorrect: Promotion of vegetarianism is not a cause for the loss or threat of biodiversity. 234","PW-0740":"The Indian wild ass also known as the Ghudkhur, is na- tive to the Rann of Kutch in Gujarat, India. This region is char- acterized by sandy and saline desert conditions, which are the natural habitat of the Indian wild ass. The species has no natu- ral predators in this area, but its survival is threatened due to habitat destruction, human encroachment, and competition for resources. It is listed under Schedule I of the Wildlife Protection Act of 1972. Listed as Near Threatened in the IUCN’s Red List of Threatened Species. 10. MISCELLANEOUS 235","PW-0741":"Sustainable aviation fuel (SAF), hydrogen and electric all have a role to play in the decarbonization of aviation. SAF is vitally important as it can address decarbonization of fuel over its lifecycle, and this is now available to be used in all turbine engines including in mid and long-range aircraft. Therefore, un- derstanding the feedstock landscape as well as the technology pathways is integral to maximising the production and supply of SAF. The production of SAF starts with one of five main families of raw materials:  Corn grain  Oil seeds  Algae  Other fats, oils, and greases  Agricultural residues  Forestry residues  Wood mill waste  Municipal solid waste streams  Wet wastes (manures, wastewater treatment sludge)  Dedicated energy crops. SUPER HINT You can try, The \"NOT\" approach for all statements, this tests the improbability of negating a statement—if de- nying its impact seems highly unlikely, the statement is plausibly true. For Example: Agri reside or mill waste or sludge are NOT used in fuel manufacturing? unlikely. 236","PW-0742":"Distributed energy resources, or DERs, are small-scale energy systems that power a nearby location. DERs can be con- nected to electric grids or isolated, with energy flowing only to specific sites or functions. DERs include both energy generation technologies and energy storage systems. When energy generation occurs through distributed energy re- sources, it is referred to as distributed generation. Examples of distributed energy resources that can be installed include:  Roof top solar photovoltaic units  Wind generating units  Battery storage  Batteries in electric vehicles used to export power back to the grid  Combined heat and power units, or tri-generation units that also utilise waste heat to provide cooling  Biomass generators, which are fuelled with waste gas or industrial and agricultural by-products.  Open and closed cycle gas turbines  Reciprocating engines (diesel, oil)  Hydro and mini-hydro schemes  Fuel cells. 237","PW-0743":"The UNOPS Sustainable Investments in Infrastructure and Innovation (S3i) initiative was introduced in 2015 as a pi- lot project to investigate inventive approaches to financing sus- tainable infrastructure endeavours in developing nations. The initiative sought to capitalise on UNOPS’ proficiency and track record in providing infrastructure solutions that align with the requirements and ambitions of individuals and communities. The S3i initiative provides initial funding for significant projects in affordable housing, renewable energy, and health infrastruc- ture. It does not emphasise investments in mass rapid transport infrastructure. 239","PW-0744":"The R2 Code of Practices (R2 Standard) is a set of guide- lines designed to promote environmentally responsible practices in the electronics recycling industry. It provides a framework for recyclers to ensure that electronic waste (e-waste) is managed in a way that protects human health, safety, and the environment. The R2 Standard covers areas such as:  Safe handling and disposal of hazardous materials.  Data security and destruction.  Worker health and safety.  Environmental responsibility. 240","PW-0745":"The Himalayan nettle has gained attention as a sustain- able source of textile fibre. The fibres extracted from the stems of this plant are strong, durable, and eco-friendly, making them suitable for producing textiles. This has significant potential for promoting sustainable livelihoods in rural and mountainous re- gions, especially in the Himalayas.  Himalayan nettle (Girardinia diversifolia) is not known for its use as an anti-malarial drug. Anti-malarial drugs are derived from plants like Artemisia annua (source of artemisinin) or Cinchona officinalis (source of quinine).  Himalayan nettle is not recognized as a source of biodiesel. Biodiesel is usually derived from oil-rich plants like Jatropha, Pongamia, or algae.  While Himalayan nettle is a fibrous plant but it is not widely used as a source of pulp for the paper industry. The paper industry primarily relies on wood pulp from trees like Eucalyptus, Bamboo, or agricultural residues like wheat straw and bagasse. Environment and Ecology 529 241","PW-0746":"Statement 1 is correct: The Forest Carbon Partnership Facility (FCPF) is a global partnership that includes governments, businesses, civil society organizations, and indigenous peoples. It was established to support efforts to reduce emissions from de- forestation and forest degradation (REDD+). Statement 2 is incorrect: The FCPF does not provide financial aid to universities, individual scientists, or institutions for scien- tific forestry research. Instead, it focuses on providing financial and technical assistance to countries for REDD+ readiness and implementation. The FCPF supports REDD+ efforts through two separate but complementary funds- The FCPF Readiness Fund and The FCPF Carbon Fund. Statement 3 is correct: The FCPF assists countries in their REDD+ efforts by providing financial and technical assistance. This includes helping countries prepare for REDD+ implementa- tion, develop national strategies, and build capacity for monitor- ing, reporting, and verification (MRV) of forest carbon emissions. 242","PW-0747":"The BioCarbon Fund Initiative for Sustainable Forest Landscapes (ISFL) is managed by the World Bank. This initiative aims to reduce greenhouse gas emissions from deforestation and forest degradation in developing countries, promoting sustain- able land-use practices. It seeks to promote reduced greenhouse gas emissions from the land sector, from deforestation and forest degradation in developing countries (REDD+), and from sustain- able agriculture, as well as smarter land-use planning, policies and practices. 243","PW-0748":"In the Greendex 2009 report, India was ranked top in the world . The Greendex is a measure of consumer environ- mental behaviors, which was created by the National Geo- graphic Society in collaboration with the international poll- ing firm GlobeScan. The score reflects how environmentally responsible the population of a country is based on their consumer behavior, such as their attitudes and actions to- wards sustainability, including energy usage, waste manage- ment, and preferences for eco-friendly products. India’s top rank in Greendex 2009 highlighted the eco-friendly practices and sustainable consumption behaviors prevalent among Indian consumers compared to other nations. 244","PW-0749":"The World Summit on Sustainable Development (WSSD), also known as Rio+10, was held in Johannesburg, South Africa, in 2002. This summit marked the 10th anniversa- ry of the Earth Summit held in Rio de Janeiro, in 1992. The WSSD focused on sustainable development issues, including poverty alleviation, environmental conservation, and the promo- tion of sustainable practices worldwide. In 1992, the Earth Summit (United Nations Conference on Envi- ronment and Development) was held in Rio de Janeiro, Brazil. It resulted in key outcomes such as the Rio Declaration, Agen- da 21, and the establishment of the Convention on Biological Diversity and the UN Framework Convention on Climate Change (UNFCCC). 245","PW-0750":"Economic activities are actions undertaken by individuals, businesses, or governments to produce, distribute, exchange, or consume goods and services with the aim of earning income or generating value. These activities form the backbone of an economy and are classified based on their nature and purpose. Economic activities are generally classified into four sectors based on their nature and role in the economy :  Primary activities involve the direct extraction of natural resources and are labor-intensive, relying on environmental conditions. Examples include agriculture, fishing, forestry, mining, and oil drilling.  Secondary activities focus on processing raw materials into finished or semi-finished goods through industrial production. This sector includes manufacturing industries such as steel production, textile weaving, car manufacturing, and construction.  Tertiary activities provide services rather than goods and support both the primary and secondary sectors. Key examples include banking, healthcare, education, retail, transportation, and IT services.  Quaternary activiti","PW-0751":"Physical capital refers to tangible, man-made assets that businesses purchase or invest in to produce goods or services. It is part of one of the three factors of production, alongside land (natural resources) and labor (human resources). Physical capital includes assets like machines, vehicles, computers, and buildings. It is categorized into two types:  Fixed capital consists of long-term physical investments used repeatedly in production over multiple accounting periods. These assets, such as buildings and machinery, are not consumed during production but have a long-term value that may depreciate over time. Examples include a farmer’s plough, a computer etc.  Working capital refers to liquid assets like cash, inventory, or materials that can be quickly converted into currency. It is utilized during the production process to create the final product. Yarn used by a weaver, petrol etc are examples. Pair 1 is incorrectly matched : A farmer’s plough is a long-term asset used repeatedly over many years in the production process. It is classified as fixed capital, not working capital","PW-0752":"","PW-0753":"Statement 1 is incorrect : According to World Bank data, India’s nominal GDP grew significantly between 2000 and 2010. In 2000, India’s nominal GDP was around $468.4 billion, and by 2010, it had crossed $1.7 trillion, reflecting an increase of approximately 2.5 to 3 times. While this reflects robust and steady economic expansion, it falls short of the fourfold increase claimed in the statement. Over the last decade from 2014 to 2024, India’s Gross Domestic Product (GDP) witnessed substantial growth, rising from around $2 trillion in 2014 to approximately $3.7 trillion in 2023, re- flecting an increase of $1.7 trillion during this period. Statement 2 is correct : In the early 1990s, the public sector contributed significantly to India’s GDP, accounting for around Indian Economy 239 25-30% of the total GDP. By 2010, following economic liberal- ization and reforms that encouraged private sector growth, the public sector’s share had declined to around 20-22%. Between 2014 and 2024, the public sector’s share in India’s GDP declined from around 20-22% to approximately 15-17% (RBI, Economic","PW-0754":"As of 2007, the services sector was the largest contrib- utor to India’s GDP, followed by industry, and finally agricul- ture. This trend marks India’s transition from an agrarian econ- omy to a service-led economy, driven by growth in IT, finance, trade, and tourism. The industrial sector expanded steadily, but at a slower pace, while agriculture’s share declined due to lower productivity and workforce migration to other sectors. As per the Economic Survey 2006-07, the services sector ac- counted for approximately 55% of India’s GDP, with industry contributing around 27% and agriculture just 18%. As of the 2023-24 fiscal year, India’s Gross Value Added (GVA) at current prices is estimated at ₹267.62 lakh crore. The ser- vices sector contributes 54.72% to this total, amounting to ₹146.44 lakh crore. The industry sector contributes 27.62%, equating to ₹73.93 lakh crore, while the agriculture and allied sectors account for 17.66%, totaling ₹47.28 lakh crore. 7","PW-0755":"As per Reserve Bank of India (RBI) data for 2000- 01, In 2001, Maharashtra had the highest Per Capita Net State Domestic Product (NSDP) amongst above options , driven by its strong industrial base, financial services hub in Mumbai, and a well-developed infrastructure. Gujarat followed Maharashtra, leveraging its thriving trade, petrochemical industries, and rapid industrialization. Tam- il Nadu ranked third with a diversified economy, including textiles, automobiles, and IT industries. Karnataka ranked fourth as its IT sector was still in the early stages of development compared to its current dominance. Note: Today, According to the Press Information Bureau (PIB) of India, the per capita NSDP at current prices (2021-22) for these states were as follows :  Karnataka : 2,65,623 Rs.  Gujarat: 2,50,100 Rs.  Tamil Nadu : 2,41,131 Rs.  Maharashtra: 2,15,233 Rs. Based on this data, the descending order of these states with ref- erence to their level of Per Capita Net State Domestic Product is: Karnataka > Gujarat> Tamil Nadu >Maharashtra 8. Assertion (A): India’s software exports incre","PW-0756":"Assertion (A) is true : India’s software exports ex- peri-enced an average growth rate of approximately 50% CAGR in the late 1990s, primarily fueled by the global demand for IT services from developed markets like the U.S. and Europe. The Y2K issue and the growth of outsourcing significantly contribut- ed to this surge. Reason (R) is true : Indian software companies such as TCS, In- fosys, and Wipro were globally competitive due to their cost-ef- fectiveness and adherence to international quality standards, including CMM Level 5 certifications. This helped establish In- dia’s reputation as a trusted IT outsourcing destination. As per NASSCOM reports and Mathur (2006), India’s IT sector leveraged its skilled workforce, competitive pricing, and quality assurance to gain a dominant share in the global IT services mar- ket. Thus, Reason (R) provides the correct explanation for Asser- tion (A). 9","PW-0757":"","PW-0758":"In a report “Changing Structure of Rural Economy of India: Implications for Employment and Growth 2017,” pub- lished by NITI Aayog, following observations were made : Statement 1 is incorrect : Both rural and urban regions have seen an improvement in worker productivity as well as the abso- lute level of income per worker. For rural areas, it was Rs. 37273 in 2004 -05 and Rs. 101755 in 2011 -12, while for urban areas it was Rs. 120419 in 2004 -05 and Rs. 282515 in 2011 -12. Indian Economy 241 Statement 2 is incorrect : As per the 2011 Census, 68.8% of India’s population and 72.4% of the workforce resided in rural areas. However, the steady transition to urbanisation over the years has led to a decline in the rural share of the workforce, from 77.8% in 1993 -94 to 70.9% in 2011 -12. Statement 3 is correct : About two-thirds of rural income is now generated in non -agricultural activities. Non-farm economy has increased in rural areas. The share of agriculture in the rural economy has decreased from 57% in 1993 -94 to 39% in 2011 -12. Statement 4 is correct : After 2004 -05, the rural ","PW-0759":"Statement 1 is correct : From the Second Five Year Plan(1956-61), there was determined thrust towards substi- tution of basic and capital goods industries. This plan fo- cused on Rapid Industrialization with an emphasis on capital goods and heavy industries. It was based on the PC Mahalano- bis Model. Statement 2 is correct : The Fourth Plan (1969-74) provided a necessary corrective to the earlier trend which helped partic- ularly the stronger sections in agriculture as well as in industry to enable them rapidly to enlarge and diversify the production base. It has adopted the objective of correcting the earlier trend of increased concentration of wealth and economic power and eliminating disparities in income between different regions. Thus, it targeted Growth with Stability, progressive achievement of self-reliance and income distribution. Statement 3 is incorrect : The Fifth plan (1974-78) aimed at removal of poverty and attaining self-reliance. The financial sector became an integral part of the plan in the Ninth five -year plan(1997-2002). Note : Details on Five Year Plans are gi","PW-0760":"Statement 1 is incorrect : India’s agriculture sector has shown a gradual decline in contribution to the Indian economy post-reform. India’s traditional occupation, agriculture, currently makes up only 15% of the GDP, down from 29% in 1991. Statement 2 is correct : India is seen as a successful exporter of IT software, auto parts, textiles, and engineering goods in the reform period. Thus, the share of India’s exports in world trade increased after its liberalisation of economic policies in 1991. India’s share in world exports was around 0.5% in 1990 and in- creased to approximately 1.85% by 2023 (PwC report). Statement 3 is correct : The Foreign investments including FDI and FII have increased from about US $ 100 million in 1990-91 to US $ 467 billion in 2012-13. Statement 4 is correct : The opening up of the economy has led to rapid increase in foreign exchange reserves. In 1991, India had only $5.8 billion in forex reserves, which were insufficient to cover imports for even three weeks. As of 2012-13, forex re- serves had grown to over $292 billion (RBI data).The trend has continu","PW-0761":"","PW-0762":"The Eighth Five-Year Plan (1992–1997) marked a shift in India’s industrialization strategy by emphasizing infra- structure development and liberalization policies over tra- ditional heavy industries. This change stemmed from the eco- nomic reforms of 1991, which aimed to boost private sector participation, attract foreign investment, and focus on services and technology-driven industries. This shift had significant implications, including the moderniza- tion of infrastructure, which improved connectivity and effi- ciency, and the expansion of the private sector, which became a key driver of economic growth and employment opportunities. 19","PW-0763":"As per Article 281 of the Indian Constitution, the Pres- ident of India is respo-nsible for causing the recommendations of the Finance Commission to be laid before both Houses of Par- liament, along with an explanatory memorandum on the action taken on its recommendations. Indian Economy 243 Options (b), (c), and (d) are incorrect :  The Speaker of Lok Sabha oversees parliamentary proceedings but does not deal with Finance Commission recommendations.  The Prime Minister and Union Finance Minister play roles in policy and implementation but do not have the constitutional responsibility mentioned under Article 281. 20","PW-0764":"Strengthening of capital markets was not a core fo- cus of the Eleventh Five-Year Plan (2007–2012). The plan em- phasized inclusive growth, focusing on poverty reduction, employment generation, gender equality, education, and health. 21","PW-0765":"The India-based Neutrino Observatory (INO) was designated as a mega science project in the 11th Five-Year Plan to promote research in high-energy physics. Option (d) is correct : Neutrinos are subatomic particles that play a key role in understanding the fundamental forces of na- ture. Despite their elusive nature and weak interactions, they are essential to various processes in the universe, such as stellar re- actions and cosmic phenomena.  Neutrinos are chargeless elementary particles that travel near the speed of light, making them difficult to detect.  Neutrinos are produced in nuclear reactions, such as beta decay, which occurs in stars, nuclear reactors, and radioactive decay processes. In beta decay, a neutron decays into a proton, emitting a beta particle (electron) and a neutrino.  Neutrinos have negligible but non-zero mass, confirmed through experiments in neutrino oscillation in particle physics.  Neutrinos are incredibly abundant in the universe. It is estimated that trillions of neutrinos pass through the human body every second, and they are virtually undetectable","PW-0766":"The Emergency (1975–1977) was declared during the Fifth Five-Year Plan (1974–1979). It was a politically turbulent period marked by restrictions on civil liberties. In 1977, general elections were held, resulting in the defeat of the Congress party and the formation of the Janata Party government, ending In- dira Gandhi’s rule. 23","PW-0767":"Statement 1 is correct : The Second Five-Year Plan (1956–61) focused on establishing heavy industries such as steel plants, machinery, and chemical plants. It was based on the Mahalanobis model, which aimed at rapid industrialization. Statement 2 is correct : The Third Five-Year Plan (1961–66) emphasized import substitution, a strategy to reduce depen- dence on foreign goods by promoting domestic industries. This policy was key to building India’s self-reliant industrial base. 24","PW-0768":"The National Development Council (NDC), compris- ing the Prime Minister, Union Ministers, Chief Ministers of states, and members of the Planning Commission, had the final authority to approve India’s Five-Year Plans. This ensured that national and state priorities were aligned. 25","PW-0769":"Economic liberalization in India began with substan- tial changes in the industrial licensing policy under the New Economic Policy of 1991. The reforms aimed to reduce state control by delicensing industries, promoting competition, and encouraging private sector participation. This marked a depar- ture from the License-Permit Raj of earlier decades. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 244 26","PW-0770":"The Economic Survey of India is published annually by the Ministry of Finance, Government of India. It is usually released just before the Union Budget and provides a compre- hensive overview of the country’s economic performance in the previous year and outlook for the future. The Economic Survey is prepared by the Department of Eco- nomic Affairs under the Ministry of Finance and includes analy- ses of various economic sectors, fiscal policies, and key challeng- es the country faces. 27","PW-0771":"The Seventh Five-Year Plan (1985–1990) focused on economic productivity, self-sufficiency, and modernization. It aimed at improving living standards and emphasizing agricul- ture, energy, and infrastructure. The plan also initiated measures toward economic liberalization, setting the stage for future re- forms. 28","PW-0772":"The Eighth Five-Year Plan (1992–1997) emphasized infrastructure growth alongside economic liberalization and privatization introduced in 1991. The plan aimed to develop sectors like power, transportation, and telecommunications to drive industrial and economic growth. 30","PW-0773":" Stabilization refers to short-term macroeco-nomic policies aimed at reducing inflation, fiscal deficit, and balance of payments crises. It involves quick adjustments to restore financial stability. To stabilize the economy in 1991, India immediately raised interest rates to control inflation and stabilize foreign reserves.  Structural adjustment refers to long-term reforms focused on improving the efficiency of the economy through trade liberalization, privatization, and regulatory reforms. These are gradual and multi-step processes. Ex- After the 1991 stabilization measures, India undertook long-term structural reforms such as liberalizing trade and privatizing state- owned enterprises. 31","PW-0774":"Full convertibility would mean the rupee exchange rate would be left to market factors without any regulatory inter- vention. There would be no limit on inflow or outflow of capital for various purposes including investments, remittances, or asset purchases/sales. Full convertibility of the Indian rupee is primarily aimed at promoting exports by making trade transactions easier and eliminating restrictions on currency exchange. This helps Indian exporters compete in global markets by allowing free movement of capital. Indian Economy 245 3. AGRICULTURE 32","PW-0775":"Statement 1 is correct: The Digital India Land Re- cords Modernization Programme (formerly the National Land Record Modernization Programme) was revamped into a Central Sector Scheme from April 1, 2016, with full funding (100 %) provided by the Central Government for its implementation. Statement 2 is correct : A major objective of DILRMP is the dig- itization of cadastral maps to improve land record transpar- ency. Cadastral maps show land boundaries and ownership details at a detailed level and are crucial for modern land ad- ministration. Statement 3 is correct : To address linguistic barriers, the gov- ernment, with technical support from C-DAC Pune, has initiated the transliteration of land records into any of the 22 languag- es listed in Schedule VIII of the Constitution. As of February 2025, 17 States and Union Territories have adopted translitera- tion tools for their land records under the Digital India Land Re- cords Modernisation Programme (DILRMP).  The Digital India Land Record Modernization Programme (DILRMP) was earlier known as the National Land Record Modernization ","PW-0776":"The ‘Small Farmer Large Field’ (SFLF) concept is an innovative agricultural model designed to address the challeng- es faced by small and marginal farmers. In this approach numer- ous smallholder farmers in a specific region come together to form groups and collectively manage and synchronize their farming activities. By pooling their resources and coordinating operations—from seed selection to harvesting—they effectively transform their fragmented individual plots into a unified larger field. Key Features of the SFLF Model:  Collective Decision-Making: Farmers jointly select crop varieties and plan the cultivation process, ensuring uniformity and efficiency across the consolidated land.  Synchronized Agricultural Operations: Activ-ities such as planting, irrigation, pest management, and harvesting are carried out in a coordinated manner, optimizing resource use and reducing operational costs.  Enhanced Bargaining Power: By operating as a collective, farmers gain better leverage when negotiating with suppliers for inputs like seeds and fertilizers, and when marketing their produce","PW-0777":"Statement 1 is correct : The Indian government in- cludes niger seeds in its Minimum Support Price (MSP) pro- gram for Kharif crops. The MSP for niger seeds was set at ₹7,734 per quintal for the 2023-24 season reflecting an increase from previous years. Statement 2 is correct : Niger is primarily cultivated as a Kharif crop in India. It is sown during the monsoon season (June-Ju- ly) and harvested in the post-monsoon period (September-Oc- tober). It is grown mainly in states like Odisha, Maharashtra, Chhattisgarh, and Madhya Pradesh. Statement 3 is correct : Niger seed oil is traditionally used by various tribal communities in India for cooking purposes. The oil which is extracted from niger seeds is valued for its nutri- tional properties and forms an integral part of the diet in several tribal regions. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 246 35","PW-0778":"Factors/Policies affecting the Price of Rice in recent past are :  Minimum Support Price : MSP is a type of market intervention that the government uses to protect farmers against a sudden drop in farm prices. Rice is included in MSP and thus the government announces MSP for rice, ensuring farmers receive a minimum price for their produce. A high MSP leads to increased procurement costs and can push up market prices.  Government Trading : The government imports or exports rice through agencies like the Food Corporation of India (FCI). Restrictions or encouragement in exports/imports can affect domestic rice prices.  Government’s Stockpiling : The government maintains buffer stocks under the Public Distribution System (PDS) and food security programs. Large stockpiling can reduce market supply, influencing prices.  Consumer Subsidies : The government provides subsidized rice through schemes like the National Food Security Act (NFSA) and PDS. While subsidies help consumers, they can distort market demand and affect pricing trends. 36","PW-0779":"Statement 1 is incorrect : The Union Government provides subsidies on fertilizers to ensure their affordability for farmers and to maintain agricultural self-sufficiency. As a result, fertilizer prices in India are regulated by the government. For ex- ample , the retail price of urea is directly controlled, while non- urea fertilizers fall under the Nutrient-Based Subsidy (NBS) scheme, where prices have some market influence but still re- ceive government support. Statement 2 is correct : Ammonia (NH₃) is a key raw material for making urea. It is produced by reacting natural gas (CH₄) with steam to extract hydrogen, which then combines with nitro- gen from the air to form ammonia in the Haber-Bosch process. Statement 3 is correct : Sulphur is a key ingredient in the pro- duction of phosphoric acid, which is used to make phosphatic fertilizers (e.g., DAP - Di-Ammonium Phosphate). It is ob- tained as a by-product from oil refineries and natural gas pro- cessing plants. 37","PW-0780":"Public Investment is the investment by the State (Cen- tral, state and local governments or through publicly owned com- panies) to build the nation’s capital stock by devoting resources to the basic physical infrastructure (such as roads, bridges, rail lines, airports, and water distribution), research and develop- ment, etc. that leads to increased output and/or living standards. The following can be considered as Public Investment in Agri- culture : Option 2 is correct : Computerization of Primary Agricultur- al Credit Societies will enhance productivity in the agricultur- al sector, as there will be easy and timely access of credit. This improves efficiency, transparency, and accessibility of credit for farmers, contributing to agricultural development. Option 3 is correct : Investing in the development of social capital for farmers fosters a network of support and knowl- edge-sharing, which can significantly enhance the adoption of new agricultural technologies and practices. Option 6 is correct : Setting up cold storage facilities by the governments will enhance productivity in ","PW-0781":"Announced in the 1998–1999 budget, the Kisan Cred- it Card Scheme aims to provide farmers with the institutional credit they need to meet their financial needs at various phases of farming. It is implemented by all public sector banks, regional rural banks, and cooperative banks across the nation. Options 1, 3 and 4 are correct : Under the Kisan Credit Card scheme, short-term credit support is given to farmers for the fol- lowing purposes :  The Kisan Credit Card (KCC) scheme provides credit for working capital requirements, including maintaining and repairing farm assets like equipment, machinery, and other resources.  KCC also provides credit for the consumption requirements of the farmer’s family, such as food, fuel, and other basic household needs.  Post Harvest Expenses : The scheme provides support for expenses related to post-harvest activities, such as packaging, storage, and transportation.  Other than these the Kisan Credit Cards are issued to the farmers so that they may use them to purchase agriculture inputs such as seeds, fertilizers, pesticides etc. and draw cash f","PW-0782":"The MSP is recommended by the Commission for Agri- cultural Costs and Prices and is announced by the Cabinet Com- mittee on Economic Affairs. The main objectives of establishing the MSP are :  To protect farmers from distress sales  To procure food grains for the public distribution system (PDS). Statement 1 is incorrect : While the government does ensure procurement at MSP for certain crops, the procurement is not unlimited. There are limits to the amount that can be procured at MSP, and these limits are determined by the government’s pro- curement policies and the capacity of procurement agencies like the Food Corporation of India (FCI). The government may also limit procurement based on market conditions, storage capacity, and other factors. Statement 2 is incorrect : MSP is the minimum price at which the government purchases crops, but it does not ensure that the market price will never surpass the MSP. Market prices can ex- ceed the MSP due to factors like demand, supply, and overall mar- ket conditions. While MSP affects market prices, it is not the only factor determining th","PW-0783":"The Economic Cost of food grains to the FCI includes the Minimum Support Price and bonus (if any) paid to the farmers plus the procurement incidentals and distribution cost. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 248  Procurement incidentals are expenses incurred during procurement till the food grains reach the first point of godown.  Distribution costs are now included in economic costs, whilst buffer carrying costs are now included in buffer subsidies. Food Corporation of India (FCI) is a statutory body that falls under the Ministry of Consumer Affairs’ Department of Food and Public Distribution. In 1965, the Food Corporations Act of 1964 created the FCI. It was founded in the midst of a severe grain crisis, particularly in wheat. In order to suggest re- munerative pricing to farmers, the Commission on Agricultural Costs and Prices (CACP) was established in 1965. 41","PW-0784":"","PW-0785":"","PW-0786":"","PW-0787":"","PW-0788":"Drip irrigation is a type of micro-irrigation system that applies small amounts of water and fertilizer uniformly across a specific area. Examples of drip irrigation methods include sur- face drip irrigation, subsurface drip irrigation (SDI), drip tape, and micro-sprinklers. Option 1 is correct : Drip irrigation delivers water directly to the plant’s root zone, reducing water availability for weeds, which helps in minimizing weed growth. Option 2 is incorrect : Some of the disadvantages of Drip Irriga- tion are sensitivity to clogging, problem of moisture distribution, salinity hazards and high cost compared to furrow. Option 3 is correct : Drip irrigation generally doesn’t contribute to significant erosion since water is delivered at low pressures and in controlled amounts, unlike surface irrigation where water flow can lead to erosion. 48","PW-0789":"The Fair and Remunerative Price (FRP) is the price set by the government that mills are legally required to pay farm- ers for the sugarcane they purchase. It is mandated under the Sugarcane Control Order, 1966 published under the Essential Commodities Act (ECA), 1955. The FRP is announced by the Cabinet Committee on Economic Affairs (CCEA), and it serves as a benchmark price for sugar mills to pay farmers. The Cabinet Committee on Economic Affairs (CCEA) announces the decision following the Commission on Ag- ricultural Costs and Prices’ (CACP) recommendation. 49","PW-0790":"","PW-0791":"Statement 1 is incorrect: The Accelerated Irrig-ation Benefits Programme was launched in 1996-97. Its goal was to provide Central Loan Assistance (CLA) to the states, rather than directly to poor farmers. The programme aimed to help states complete their major irrigation projects that were in the advanced stages of development. Its primary objective was to speed up the completion of ongoing irrigation projects. Statement 2 is correct: The Command Area Development (CAD) programme was launched in 1974-75. Its aim was to close the gap between the irrigation potential and the actual use of major and medium irrigation schemes. The ultimate goal of the programme is to deliver irrigation water to the fields. The plan involves creating field channels, land contouring, and a rotational water supply. These measures are designed to improve water use efficiency in agriculture. In 2004, the programme was re- structured into the Command Area Development and Water Management Program. 51","PW-0792":"This is because the replacement of wooden ploughs (a less durable, less efficient tool) with steel ploughs (which are more durable, efficient, and require less labor for maintenance and use) leads to increased productivity per unit of capital, i.e., the plough itself. This represents a shift towards more capital-in- tensive technology. This is capital-augmenting rather than labor-augmenting progress because the improvement is in the capital itself (the plough), making it more productive, rather than increasing the labor force or improving labor productivity directly.  Labour Augmenting is technology that increases skills and productivity of the existing labour force (example - teaching people how to use the computer).  Capital Augmenting technology enhances the productivity of existing capital goods. In this case, replacement of wood by steel, increases the productivity of plough. 52","PW-0793":"The main aim of the Seed Village Concept is to involve farmers in the production of quality seeds through training, ensuring that these seeds are accessible to others at the right time and at affordable prices. This approach empowers farm- ers to contribute to seed production, meeting local demand and ensuring that both they and neighboring farmers have access to high-quality seeds. Option (b) is correct : A village is referred to as a ‘seed village’ if a trained group of farmers produces seeds for a variety of crops and provides for the requirements of themselves, their fellow vil- lagers, and villagers in nearby villages at an affordable price. Thus this option best captures the main objective of the Seed Village Concept, which focuses on training farmers to produce high-quality seeds for local use, ensuring accessibility and af- fordability. 53. In the context of food and nutritional security of India, enhancing the ‘Seed Replacement Rates’ of various crops helps in achieving the food production targets of the future. But what is/are the constraint/ constraints in its wider/greate","PW-0794":"Statement 1 is incorrect : India has a National Seed Policy, which was formulated in 2002. The policy aims to provide farmers with access to high-quality seeds, promote private sector participation, and ensure seed availability for food security. The policy provides a framework for seed develop- ment, production, quality control, distribution, and market- ing. The policy also encourages research and development in seed technology and promotes the participation of both the pub- lic and private sectors in the seed industry. Statement 2 is incorrect : The private sector plays a signifi- cant role in the supply of quality seeds especially for high-val- ue crops like vegetables and horticultural crops. Companies like Mahyco, Syngenta, and Namdhari Seeds are actively involved in the production and distribution of quality seeds. Statement 3 is correct : A significant demand-supply gap persists for quality seeds particularly in low-value, high-vol- ume crops like cereals and pulses despite efforts from both pub- lic and private sectors. This gap is attributed to factors such as the high cost","PW-0795":"Statement 1 is correct : The Sugarcane price in India is determined by statutory provisions of the Sugarcane (Con- tro) Order, 1966 issued under the Essential Commodities Act (ECA), 1955. Until 2009, the Union Government fixed the Statu- tory Minimum Price (SMP) for sugarcane under the Sugarcane (Control) Order, 1966. However, from the 2009-10 sugar season onwards, the SMP was replaced by the Fair and Remunerative Price (FRP), which continues to be fixed by the Union Govern- ment based on recommendations of the Commission for Agricul- tural Costs and Prices (CACP). FRP is the minimum price that is determined by the government of India on the recommendation of CACP. Statement 2 is correct : Both sugar and sugarcane are classified as essential commodities under the Essential Commodities Act, 1955, which allows the government to regulate their pro- duction, supply, and distribution to ensure availability and con- trol prices. In addition to the Fair and Remunerative Price (FRP) set by the central government for sugarcane, some Indian states also announce their own State Advised Price (S","PW-0796":"Statement 1 is incorrect : The Commission for Ag- ricultural Costs and Prices (CACP) is responsible for recom- mending the Minimum Support Prices (MSP) for 23 crops (not 32), which include cereals, pulses, oilseeds, and other crops. These crops include 7 cereals, 5 pulses, 7 oilseeds, and 4 com- mercial crops. Statement 2 is incorrect : The National Food Security Mission (NFSM) was launched in 2007-08 by the Ministry of Agricul- ture and Farmers’ Welfare, not by the Ministry of Consumer Affairs, Food, and Public Distribution. The National Food Security Mission (NFSM) aims to increase the production of rice, wheat, and pulses through area expan- sion, productivity improvement, and restoring soil fertility. It also focuses on creating jobs and boosting the farm economy. From 2014-15, coarse cereals were included in the mission. Key inter- ventions include demonstrations of improved farming practices, seed distribution, farm machinery, efficient water use, plant pro- tection, soil management, and farmer training. 56","PW-0797":"Pair 1 is correct : According to the “Press Note on Advance Estimates of National Income, 2008-09” released by the Ministry of Statistics and Programme Implementation (MoSPI), the per capita income at current prices during 2008-09 was estimated to be ₹38,084. Therefore, the figure of ₹37,000 is approximately correct. Pair 2 is incorrect : As per the “Agricultural Statistics at a Glance 2008” published by the Ministry of Agriculture & Farm- ers Welfare, Government of India, the production of rice during the 2006-07 crop year was approximately 93.35 million tons. Thus, the figure of 180 million tons is significantly higher than the actual production during that period. Pair 3 is correct : As per the “Agricultural Statistics at a Glance 2008” published by the Ministry of Agriculture & Farmers Wel- fare, wheat production during the 2006-07 crop year was around 75.80 million tons. Therefore, the figure of 75 million tons is ap- proximately correct. 57","PW-0798":"Assertion (A) is false : India does export natural rubber, although in limited quantities. While India is primarily a net importer of natural rubber to meet domestic demand, it also exports small amounts, especially of certain grades like RSS (Ribbed Smoked Sheets). UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 252 Reason(R) is True : In the early years of 2000s, India was a ma- jor producer of natural rubber, and around 97% of its domestic demand for natural rubber was met from domestic production.  Natural Rubber (NR) is a commercial plantation crop from the tree species, Hevea brasiliensis. Natural Rubber is grown in tropical humid climatic conditions. Thailand, Indonesia, Malaysia, Vietnam, China and India are the major natural Rubber producers globally. Currently India is among the top four largest producers of natural rubber in the world.  In recent years, India’s domestic demand for natural rubber is increasing with a significant gap between production and consumption, leading to a substantial reliance on imports to meet the demand shortfall. Currently , NR consumption in India is 14.16 lakh tonnes ","PW-0799":"Statement 1 is correct : The government provides higher and more stable Minimum Support Prices (MSP) for food grains like rice and wheat, which incentivizes farmers to priori- tize these crops over oilseeds. Statement 2 is correct : In 2004-2005, much of India’s oil- seed farming depended on monsoon rains, making it sensitive to weather changes. The Economic Survey 2004-05 noted that irregular rainfall in 2004 caused a big drop in the production of rainfed crops like oilseeds and pulses. Most oilseed farming in India still relies on rainfall. Statement 3 is correct : By 2004, India was producing 650,000 tons of rice bran oil from 4 million tons of rice bran through sol- vent extraction. However, this was only half of the potential, as the country’s paddy production could generate 9.8 million tons of rice bran annually, but only 5 million tons were processed. The untapped potential of rice bran oil and other non-tradition- al edible oils, like tree-borne oils, contributed to higher import dependence. By 2004, India produced 650,000 tons of rice bran oil from 4 mil- lion tons of rice b","PW-0800":"Statement 1 is correct : The government sets specif- ic procurement targets for each crop season based on factors like estimated production, buffer stock requirements and market conditions. In case, there is no procurement target, the government allows the procurement agencies like the FCI to buy flexibly from the farmers. Statement 2 is incorrect : The Government of India announces MSP for a variety of crops, including cereals, pulses, oilseeds, and commercial crops like cotton and jute. Statement 3 is correct : Under the Targeted public Distribution System (TPDS), wheat and rice are allocated to States/Union Territories by the Government of India at uniform Central Is- sue Prices (CIP) for distribution to different categories, such as Antyodaya Anna Yojana (AAY) and Below Poverty Line (BPL) families. 60","PW-0801":"According to the Economic Survey 2001-02, during the period from 1997–1998 to 1999–2000, marine products were the largest agricultural export by India in terms of value due to high global demand in countries like the USA, Japan, and Eu- rope, and improved processing and storage. Here is a breakdown of the export values (in million USD) for key commodities during this period according to the Economic Sur- vey 2001-02. Even now, according to the Agricultural and Processed Food Products Export Development Authority (APEDA) and the Min- istry of Commerce and Industry, marine products have led the agricultural export chart in terms of value in the last few years. Indian Economy 253 61","PW-0802":"Option (d) is correct : Rice Production for the follow- ing year in Million tonne (MT) according to Economic Survey 2000-01 was: 1991-92 – 74.68 MT 1992-93 – 72.86 MT 1993-94 – 80.30 MT 1994-95 – 81.81 MT 1995-96 – 76.98 MT 1996-97 – 81.74 MT 1997-98 – 82.53 MT 1998-99 – 86.03 MT Given data translates into the above given graph . Thus Rice is the correct answer. Rice is the staple food of India and a cornerstone of its agri- cultural economy. India is the world’s second-largest producer of rice (after China), contributing ~20% of global production. Geographic Spread :  Grown predominantly in river basins and coastal plains.  Top states: West Bengal, Punjab, Uttar Pradesh, Andhra Pradesh, and Bihar.  Requires high rainfall (1500–3000 mm) or irrigation (e.g., Punjab’s canal systems). Crop Seasons:  Kharif (monsoon season: June–November): 85% of production.  Rabi (winter: November–April): Limited to irrigated regions like Tamil Nadu. 62","PW-0803":"","PW-0804":"Statement 1 is correct : Jowar (sorghum) is an im- portant coarse cereal grown in India, mainly in dryland regions. According to Indian Institute of Millet Research ( under ICAR ) Maharashtra consistently has the largest area under Jowar (sor- ghum) cultivation in India due to its dryland farming practices. The crop is mostly grown in the rabi season in Maharashtra and contributes significantly to food security and fodder availability in the state. Statement 2 is incorrect: According to the Economic Survey, in the late 1990s (when this question was framed), while Gujarat is a significant producer of groundnut, the leading position al- ternates with states like Andhra Pradesh depending on the year. Thus the statement claiming Gujarat as the largest producer is wrong. Year Andhra Pradesh Guja- rat Karna- taka Tamil Nadu Maha- rash- tra Other States All India 1980-81 861 1645 444 680 611 764 5005 81-82 1437 2198 658 1238 694 998 7223 82-83 1133 1312 379 853 551 1054 5282 83-84 1716 1810 739 982 807 1031 7086 84-85 1258 1572 897 986 731 991 6436 85-86 1325 448 707 1176 469 996 5121 86-87","PW-0805":"With respect to the year 1999-2000 ; U.P. (115419 in tonnes) >Maharashtra (53143) >Tamilnadu (34285) > Andhra Pradesh (18508) is the correct decreasing order of the above four sugarcane producing States. The given table shows the production of Sugarcane (in tons) of given states in the years 1998-99, 1999-2000 and 2000-2001. State 1998-99 1999-2000 2000-2001 Uttar Pradesh 116483 115419 106069 Maharashtra 47151 53143 49589 Tamil Nadu 33765 34285 33188 Andhra Pradesh 16503 18508 17690 In recent times, According to the Directorate of Suga-rcane De- velopment, production of sugarcane in the following states in 2022-2023 are as follows: State Production (in Million Tonnes) Uttar Pradesh 225.22 MT Maharashtra 123.97 MT Tamil Nadu 16.92 MT Andhra Pradesh 3.12 MT 65","PW-0806":"","PW-0807":"Statement 1 is correct : Lack of education and knowl- edge about modern farming techniques can lead to lower pro- ductivity as farmers may not adopt modern farming techniques, use improved seeds, or utilize fertilizers and pesticides effective- ly. This results in low yields, which in turn lead to reduced in- comes for farmers, further contributing to the income disparity between rural and urban areas. Statement 2 is correct: Primary products like agricultural commodities generally have lower prices than manufactured goods, which are produced in urban areas. This disparity in pricing contributes to the wage gap between rural and urban incomes. Statement 3 is correct : The industrial sector in India has re- ceived more investment than agriculture, leading to better in- frastructure, technological advancements, and higher wages in urban areas. This has resulted in significant income disparities, with urban incomes being about twice as high as those in rural areas. Urban regions benefit from better infrastructure and tech- nology, driving higher productivity and wages. In contrast, rura","PW-0808":"Statement 1 is correct : According to the Companies Act, 2013, CSR activities must benefit society at large and not be directed toward the company’s employees or their families. Ac- tivities that serve the company’s business interests or are part of its normal operations are also excluded from being considered CSR. Statement 2 is incorrect : The CSR rules mandate that eligible companies spend at least 2% of their average net profits from the preceding three financial years on CSR activities. This is a clearly defined minimum spending requirement under Section 135 of the Companies Act, 2013. SUPER HINT For S1, CSR = Corporate Social Responsibility → The focus is on society, not on the company or its employ- ees. This logically sounds valid. For S2, If no minimum spending is prescribed, companies could just say \"we spent nothing\" and still be compliant — which defeats the whole purpose of mandatory CSR. Hence likely false. 69","PW-0809":"Investments can be categorized into tangible and intangible assets. Tangible assets have a physical presence, while intangible assets lack a physical form. Intangible assets derive their value from intellectual or legal rights. Option (c) is correct :  Brand recognition is an intangible asset because it does not have a physical form but contributes significantly to a company’s value. Strong brand recognition enhances consumer trust, customer loyalty, and market competitiveness. Example: Coca-Cola’s brand value is estimated at billions of dollars, despite not being a physical asset.  Intellectual property (patents, trademarks, copyrights, trade secrets) is intangible and provides significant competitive advantage. Example: Patents for pharmaceutical drugs are valuable intangible investments for pharma companies.  Mailing List of Clients is an intangible asset because it enhances marketing capabilities and customer retention. Example: E-commerce companies leverage customer mailing lists for targeted marketing. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 256 Inventory consists of physical goods that a comp","PW-0810":"Statement 1 is incorrect : The MSMED Act, 2006 orig- inally defined medium enterprises as those with investments in plant and machinery between ₹5 crore and ₹10 crore. As per the latest guidelines of 2020 a medium enterprise presently is de- fined as one where the investment in plant and machinery or equipment does not exceed ₹50 crore and turnover does not exceed ₹250 crore and not ₹15 crore to ₹25 crore. The fol- lowing table provides the details of revised limits: Category Old Capital Old Turnover New Capital New Turn- over Micro 25 Lakh 10 Lakh 1 Crore 5 Crore Small 5 Crore 2 Crore 10 Crore 50 Crore Medium 10 Crore 5 Crore 50 Crore 250 Crore Statement 2 is correct : The Reserve Bank of India’s Master Directions on Priority Sector Lending (PSL) specify that bank loans to Micro, Small, and Medium Enterprises are eligible for classification under the priority sector but subject to certain conditions. While loans to micro and small enterprises are fully eligible, loans to medium enterprises are considered under PSL only up to a certain limit. Specifically, bank loans up to ₹10 crore ","PW-0811":"Statement 1 is incorrect : Under India’s Foreign Di- rect Investment (FDI) policy, foreign-owned e-commerce firms operating as marketplace models (e.g., Amazon, Flipkart) can- not sell their own goods. They are only allowed to provide a platform for third-party sellers. Statement 2 is correct : The FDI policy limits the degree to which foreign-owned e-commerce firms can own or control sellers on their platforms. For example, a single seller cannot ac- count for more than 25% of the total sales on the platform(as per FDI policy). SUPER HINT If foreign e-commerce players (like Amazon, Walmart-Flipkart) were allowed to sell their own goods directly, they would become inventory-based, not mar- ketplaces. This would hurt Indian MSMEs and create conflict of interest. Also, if they can't even hold large stakes in sellers (S2), then how can they sell their own goods directly(S1)? Both cannot be true at once. If S2 is true, S1 must be false. 73","PW-0812":"West Texas Intermediate (WTI) is a grade of crude oil that serves as a major benchmark for oil prices globally. WTI is a high-quality, light, and sweet crude oil. It is called “light” because it has a low density, and “sweet” because it contains low sulfur content. These characteristics make it ideal for refining into gasoline and other high-demand petroleum products. It is one of the three major benchmarks for crude oil prices, alongside Brent Crude (from the North Sea) and Dubai Crude. It is widely used as a reference price for oil in the Americas. WTI prices often make headlines because they reflect global oil market trends and have significant implications for energy costs, economic stability, and geopolitical dynamics. Indian Economy 257 74","PW-0813":"TRIMs (Trade-Related Investment Measures) are WTO rules governing investment measures that impact trade in goods. They aim to eliminate trade distortions by pro- hibiting practices like local content requirements, trade bal- ancing, and quantitative restrictions. TRIMs promote free and non-discriminatory trade, ensuring compliance with GATT prin- ciples. Its focus on trade-related regulations rather than directly regulating foreign investments, fostering a fair and open interna- tional trading environment. Statement 1 is correct: The Trade-Related Investment Mea- sures (TRIMS) Agreement of the World Trade Organization (WTO) explicitly prohibits measures that require foreign investors to meet certain performance requirements, such as quantitative restrictions on imports. These restrictions are considered trade-distorting and are not allowed under the TRIMS Agreement. Statement 2 is incorrect : The TRIMS Agreement only applies to investment measures related to trade in goods, not ser- vices. It focuses on ensuring that investment measures do not distort or restrict trade in goods. Trad","PW-0814":"Statement 1 is correct: The coal sector in India was nationalized in two phases under Prime Minister Indira Gandhi. The first phase took place in 1971 with the nationaliza- tion of coking coal mines, and the second phase occurred in 1973 with the nationalization of non-coking coal mines. This was done to ensure proper development of the coal sector and to prevent exploitation by private players. Statement 2 is incorrect : Coal blocks are not allocated on a lottery basis. The allocation of coal blocks in India is done through a transparent and competitive bidding process as per the Coal Mines (Special Provisions) Act, 2015. This pro- cess ensures fairness and efficiency in the allocation of coal re- sources. Statement 3 is incorrect : India still imports coal to meet its domestic demand, particularly high-grade coal that is not suffi- ciently available domestically. Despite having large coal reserves, India faces challenges in coal production, transportation, and quality, which necessitate imports. India is not self-sufficient in coal products. SUPER HINT For S3, \"India is self suffic","PW-0815":"UDAY (Ujwal DISCOM Assurance Yojana), launched in November 2015, aims to address the financial and oper- ational inefficiencies of power distribution companies (DIS- COMs). It seeks to improve their financial health by allowing state governments to take over 75% of their debt and service the remaining through bonds. The scheme focuses on reducing Aggregate Technical and Commercial (AT&C) losses to 15% by 2019, lowering power generation costs through energy efficien- cy, and enhancing service delivery with uninterrupted power supply and timely billing for consumers. 77","PW-0816":"Through the amendment in Mines & Minerals (Devel- opment & Regulation) (MMDR) Act, in 2015, Government of India has made provision for establishment of District Mineral Foundation in all the districts affected by mining. Statement 1 is incorrect: DMFs are not directly involved in promoting mineral exploration activities. Their focus is on the welfare of affected communities and areas, not on explora- tion or mining activities. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 258 Statement 2 is correct: The main purpose of DMFs is to protect the interests of persons and areas affe-cted by mining operations. They use funds collected from miners to implement various developmental and welfare projects, such as healthcare, education, sanitation, and infrastructure, in min- ing-affected areas. Statement 3 is incorrect: DMFs do not have any role in au- thorizing State Governments to issue licenses for mineral exploration. Licensing and regulation of mining activities are handled by the respective State Governments and the Central Government under the provisions of the Mines and Minerals (De- velopment and Regulation) ","PW-0817":"Statement 1 is correct: IREDA was incorporated in 1987 as a public limited government company under the Companies Act, 1956. It operates as a Government of India En- terprise and is under the administrative control of the Ministry of New and Renewable Energy (MNRE). In April 2024 IREDA achieved the “Navratna” status which granted it greater finan- cial and operational autonomy. Statement 2 is correct : IREDA is registered as a Non-Bank- ing Financial Company (NBFC) with the Reserve Bank of In- dia (RBI). In 2023 it was granted the status of an Infrastructure Finance Company (IFC) by the RBI enhancing its capacity to fi- nance large-scale renewable energy projects. 79","PW-0818":"Statement 1 is correct : National Investment and Manufacturing Zones(NIMZs) are large areas of land de- veloped as industrial townships with state-of-the-art in- frastructure and facilities. They are designed to promote manufacturing investments and boost industrial growth. The Na- tional Manufacturing Policy (2011) proposed the establishment of NIMZs to make India a global manufacturing hub. Statement 2 is correct : The government has introduced a single window clearance system to simplify and expedite the process of obtaining approvals and clearances for setting up and operating manufacturing units. This reduces bureaucratic delays and improves the ease of doing business. Statement 3 is correct : The Technology Acquisition and De- velopment Fund (TADF) was established to support the ac- quisition and development of advanced technologies for the manufacturing sector. It aims to enhance the competitiveness of Indian industries by promoting innovation and technology adoption. 80","PW-0819":"Eight Core Industries measures combined and individ- ual performance of production in selected eight core industries viz. Coal, Crude Oil, Natural Gas, Refinery Products, Fertil- izers, Steel, Cement and Electricity. As of 2024 Eight Core In- dustries comprise 40.27% of the weight of items included in the Index of Industrial Production (IIP). These industries have a ma- jor impact on general economic activities and also industrial ac- tivities. They significantly impact most other industries as well. The capital basis of the economy is represented by the core sector. The IIP provides the economic growth rates for various industrial categories over a certain time period. 81","PW-0820":"Statement 1 is incorrect: India does not have a poli- cy to save coal reserves for the future. Coal imports are driven by domestic supply shortages and the need for high-quality cok- ing coal, not strategic conservation. Statement 2 is correct: A significant portion of India’s power plants are coal-based, and domestic coal production often falls short of demand. This forces power plants to rely on coal imports to meet their requirements. Statement 3 is correct: India has limited reserves of high-quality coking coal, which is essential for steel produc- tion. Most of the coking coal used by steel companies is imported from countries like Australia, as domestic production is insuffi- cient and often of lower quality. Indian Economy 259 82","PW-0821":"","PW-0822":"","PW-0823":"The Special Economic Zones (SEZ) Act, 2005 was en- acted to boost economic growth by creating designated zones with special incentives for businesses. Statement 1 is correct: One of the key objectives of the SEZ Act is to develop world-class infrastructure facilities within these zones. This includes roads, power, water supply, and other utilities to attract businesses and promote industrial growth. Statement 2 is correct: The SEZ Act aims to attract foreign direct investment (FDI) by offering tax incentives, simplified regulations, and a business-friendly environment. This helps in bringing in capital and technology from abroad. Statement 3 is incorrect: The SEZ Act is not limited to pro- moting exports of services only. It aims to promote both goods and services exports. SEZs are designed to boost over- all export-oriented production, including manufacturing, IT ser- vices, and other sectors. 85","PW-0824":"MMTC has played a key role in India’s international trade landscape while also contributing to industrial growth through projects like NINL. Statement 1 is correct : MMTC Limited (Metallic Materials Trading Corporation of India) is one of India’s largest public sector trading companies and the largest in the field of inter- national trade. It handles both exports and imports, primarily dealing with metals, minerals, and other commodities. MMTC is involved in the trading of precious metals, ores, and other prod- ucts, making it the largest trading organization in India in its sec- tor. Statement 2 is correct : Neelachal Ispat Nigam Limited (NINL) is a joint venture between MMTC Limited, Government of Odisha, and other stakeholders. It was established to set up a steel plant in the state of Odisha. The venture focuses on the production of steel and other related activities, contributing to industrial growth in the region. 86","PW-0825":"","PW-0826":"Weber’s theory of industrial location emphasizes minimizing transportation and production costs as key fac- tors in determining where industries should be located. In- dustries tend to locate near raw materials (if they are heavy and bulky), energy sources, and markets to reduce transportation costs. Labour availability and cheap energy also influence loca- tion choices. The theory also highlights agglomeration, where in- dustries benefit from clustering together to share infrastructure and resources, improving efficiency and reducing costs. Option (b) is correct : The HINDALCO aluminum factory at Re- nukut, Uttar Pradesh, is primarily located due to the abundant supply of power from the Rihand Dam hydroelectric project. Aluminum production is highly energy-intensive, making prox- imity to reliable power sources a critical factor. 94","PW-0827":"The nature and size of an industry are determined by:  Capital investment in an industry is a significant determinant of its size and the type of production it can undertake. Higher capital investment often implies larger-scale operations and the ability to adopt more advanced technologies.  Business turnover represents the total value of sales, is a direct measure of the scale of economic activity within the industry. A higher turnover indicates a larger industry.  Power consumption is a good indicator of the scale of operations and the type of industry. Energy-intensive industries, like manufacturing or heavy industries, will consume more power. While the number of workers can indicate an industry’s labor intensity, it does not always deter-mine the overall size. Some in- dustries, like IT or pharmaceuticals, have high turnover and cap- ital investment but a relatively smaller workforce. 95","PW-0828":"Statement 1 is correct: Rural electrification was identified as a Basic Minimum Service under the Prime Min- ister’s Gramodaya Yojana, a flagship program aimed at im- proving rural infrastructure, including power supply, edu- cation, and health services. As per government records during this period, rural electrification was prioritized to reduce region- al imbalances. Statement 2 is correct: Since the economic reforms of 1991, India allowed 100% Foreign Direct Investment (FDI) in the power sector without any upper limit. This was done to at- tract foreign capital and technology to boost power generation and infrastructure. Statement 3 is incorrect: By 2001, the Union Ministry of Power had signed Memoranda of Understanding (MoUs) with more than 14 States. The exact number was higher, as the government was actively collaborating with multiple states to improve power generation and distribution. 96","PW-0829":"Statement 1 is correct: In India, megacities are typ- ically classified as urban areas with a popul-ation of over 5 million. Cities like Mumbai, Delhi, Kolkata, Chennai, Bengaluru, and Hyderabad fall into this category, making them some of the largest and most populous urban centers in the country. Statement 2 is incorrect: While coastal cities like Mumbai and Chennai serve as important sea ports, not all Indian megacities are located by the coast. For example, Delhi, de- spite being a large megacity, is inland and lacks direct access to the sea Statement 3 is correct: Several Indian megacities serve as either national or state capitals. Delhi is the national capital, Mumbai is the capital of Maharashtra, Chennai is the capital of Tamil Nadu, and Kolkata serves as the capital of West Bengal. These cities are not only economic powerhouses but also admin- istrative centers, making them critical to the governance and de- velopment of their respective states or the nation. 97","PW-0830":"Statement 1 is correct: Small-scale industries tend to be more labor-intensive compared to large-scale indus- tries, meaning they create more jobs with less capital invest- ment. This feature is particularly valuable in economies with a high labor supply, as it helps reduce unemployment and fosters inclusive growth. Statement 2 is correct: Small-scale industries help in spreading industrial activities across different regions, thus contributing to the decentralization of economic growth. This helps in reducing regional inequalities, promotes balanced development, and prevents industries from being concentrated in a few urban areas. Statement 3 is incorrect: Large-scale industries(not Small- scale industries ) generally perform better in export markets due to economies of scale and better access to global mar- kets. Statement 4 is incorrect: Although SSIs provide jobs to low- skill workers, this is not their primary reason for preferential treatment. 98","PW-0831":"A balance sheet is a financial statement that provides a snapshot of a company’s financial position at a specific point in time. It details the company’s assets, liabilities, and share- holders’ equity, offering insights into its financial health, size, and resource allocation. However, it has limitations in assessing Indian Economy 263 profitability and market share. From a balance sheet, one can determine the size and composition of assets and liabilities, such as cash, inventory, debt, and equity. It does not directly reveal profitability (income statement) or market share (indus- try analysis). For example, Tata Motors’ balance sheet shows as- sets worth ₹1.2 lakh crore (2023), but profitability is assessed via P&L statements. 99","PW-0832":"Option 1 is correct: India faces challenges in fos- tering entrepreneurship due to factors like risk aversion, limited access to capital, and regulatory hurdles. A shortage of skilled leadership hampers innovation and effective business strategies, which are key to industrial growth. Option 2 is incorrect: While savings are important, they are not the sole determinant of industrial development. Other factors such as access to credit, foreign investment, and govern- ment spending also play a significant role in driving industrial growth. Even with limited domestic savings, a country can attract foreign direct investment (FDI) to fuel its industries. Option 3 is correct: The lack of technology, skills, and infra- structure is a major constraint on industrial development. Modern industries depend on advanced technology, a skilled workforce, and strong infrastructure (such as transportation, communication, and energy). Deficiencies in any of these areas can severely hinder progress. For instance, an unreliable power supply can disrupt production, while a shortage of skilled work- ers can","PW-0833":"A is correctly matched with 2 : Tuticorin, located in Tamil Nadu is a major center for pearl fishing in India. The Gulf of Mannar is known for its pearl banks, and Tuticorin has historically been a hub for pearl diving and processing. B is correctly matched with 1 : Pune is a major automobile manufacturing hub in India, housing prominent companies like Tata Motors, Bajaj Auto, and Mahindra & Mahindra. The city has become synonymous with automotive production due to its well-established infrastructure and skilled workforce. C is correctly matched with 4 : Marmagao, Goa is an im- portant shipbuilding center. The Goa Shipyard Limited (GSL) is one of India’s leading shipyards, contributing significantly to the country’s maritime capabilities, including building naval and merchant ships. D is correctly matched with 3 : Pinjore, Haryana is known for manufacturing engineering goods, particularly in the production of high-precision machinery parts. The region’s industrial significance is bolstered by the Hindustan Machine Tools (HMT) factory, which specializes in machinery and tools. 101","PW-0834":"","PW-0835":"","PW-0836":"The National Renewal Fund (NRF) was established by the Government of India in1992 with the primary ob- jective of safeguarding the interests of workers affected by industrial restructuring, technological upgrades, or the closure of unviable units. The NRF aimed to provide a social safety net through retraining, redeployment, and compensation to ensure a smooth transition for the workforce during economic reforms. The NRF’s key functions included:  Worker Retraining and Redeployment: Offering training programs to equip workers with new skills, facilitating their re-employment in emerging sectors.  Voluntary Retirement Scheme (VRS) Support: Providing financial assistance to public sector enterprises to implement VRS for employees in cases of redundancy.  Counseling Services: Assisting workers in coping with job transitions through counseling and guidance. 105. The rough outline map given shows centres of cement industry labelled 1, 2, 3 and 4","PW-0837":"The Indian cement industry favours location near raw material sources, such as limestone deposits in Madhya Pradesh, Tamil Nadu, and Gujarat, to minimize transportation costs. Prox- imity to coal and power sources further optimizes production efficiency, while market access supports distribution, reflecting Weber’s cost-minimization principles. Indian Economy 265 A is correctly matched with 2: Katni is renowned for its abundant limestone reserves, making it a major hub for cement production. Key players like ACC Limited, JK Cement, and UltraTech Cement operate in the region, contributing signifi- cantly to India’s cement manufacturing capacity and industrial development. B is correctly matched with 4: Tirunelveli is a prominent ce- ment production region in Tamil Nadu. India Cements Limited set up its first plant in Sankarnagar near Tirunelveli marking a significant milestone in South India’s cement industry. C is correctly matched with 1: Sikka, situated in Gujarat, benefits from rich limestone deposits and a strategic coastal location. The region has become a key cement production ","PW-0838":"A is correctly matched with 3 : India exports a signif- icant quantity of iron ore to Japan due to its high demand for raw materials in its steel industry. B is correctly matched with 1 : Indian leather goods have a substantial market in Russia. The demand for quality leather products in Russia aligns with India’s export capabilities in this sector. C is correctly matched with 4 : The United Kingdom has historically been a major importer of Indian tea owing to long-standing trade ties and the popularity of tea in British culture. D is correctly matched with 2 : The United States of America is a significant market for Indian cotton fabrics, given the de- mand for diverse textile products. 107","PW-0839":"","PW-0840":"Inflation is the general rise in prices of goods and ser- vices within an economy wherein, the purchasing power of con- sumers decreases, and the value of the cash holdings erode. The creation of new money to finance a Budget Deficit is highly inflationary. The government prints new money or borrows directly from the central bank (RBI in India) to fund its deficit. This directly increases the money supply in the economy without a corresponding increase in goods and services. It leads to excess liquidity in the economy causing demand-pull inflation. SUPER HINT \"Which option puts extra, unlimited cash in the system without removing any? ”Only (d) fits that test.\" 109","PW-0841":"","PW-0842":"Demand-pull inflation is caused by an increase in de- mand and wherein the demand in the economy outgrows the supply in the economy. It can be summed up as a condition of ‘too much money chasing too few goods’. With reference to the Indian economy, demand-pull inflation can be caused/increased by the following : 1. Expansionary policies: Money in the market rises when the government spends more freely. It leads to an increase in demand for the goods and fuels demand-pull inflation. 2. Fiscal Stimulus: Fiscal stimulus is a government-driven strategy that involves adjusting government spending and taxes to stimulate the economy. It also increases the money in the market which leads to an increase in demand for the goods and fuels demand-pull inflation 3. Higher Purchasing Power: Consumers feel more confident and spend more when they have a better income. As a result, demand increases, driving up inflation. Rising interest rates will reduce the money supply in the mar- ket. Borrowing money will become costlier, creating a credit crunch in the economy. So, it can not cause demand to pull","PW-0843":"Statement 1 is correct : In India, food items make up a significant portion of the CPI, around 45%, reflecting the price changes consumers experience. In contrast, the WPI, which tracks wholesale prices, assigns a smaller share to food items, approximately 25-30%. The CPI measures the av- erage change in prices paid by consumers for a basket of goods and services. Food is a significant component of household bud- gets, especially in developing economies, so it has a substantial weight in the CPI. The WPI, on the other hand, tracks the prices of goods at the wholesale level (i.e., prices received by producers or wholesalers). Statement 2 is correct : The WPI focuses on measuring price changes in goods at the wholesale level and excludes services. While CPI includes both goods and services, such as healthcare, transportation, and education, which is a major dif- ference between the two indices. Statement 3 is incorrect : The RBI has not adopted the WPI as its key measure of inflation. The RBI uses the Consumer Price Index (CPI) as its primary gauge of inflation for mone- tary policy de","PW-0844":"The Consumer Price Index for Industrial Workers (CPI-IW) is compiled and released by the Labour Bureau which operates under the Ministry of Labour and Employment, Government of India. CPI-IW measures inflation and changes in the cost of living for industrial workers across various sec- tors. It serves as a benchmark for revising wages, dearness allowance (DA), and social security benefits for workers and government employees. The Labour Bureau publishes CPI-IW monthly based on data collected from major industrial centers across India. The Labour Bureau has been compiling the CPI-IW since 1944, with revisions to the base year occurring periodical- ly (e.g., 2001=100, 2016=100) to reflect changing consumption patterns. 113","PW-0845":"Statement 1 is correct: Inflation typically benefits debtors because it erodes the real value of money. When infla- tion rises, the value of the currency decreases, meaning the amount of money a debtor repays is worth less in real terms than when it was borrowed. For example, if a person took a loan of ₹1,00,000 and inflation rises by 10%, they can repay the loan in currency that is worth less, effectively reducing their real debt burden. Statement 2 is incorrect: Inflation harms bondholders, espe- cially those holding fixed-rate bonds. When inflation rises, the real return on bonds decreases because the bondholder receives a fixed interest payment. Inflation erodes the purchasing power of the bond’s future payments. For example, if a bond pays ₹5,000 per year and inflation increases by 5%, the real purchasing pow- er of those ₹5,000 payments is effectively reduced. 115","PW-0846":"","PW-0847":"Inflation is the rise in prices of goods and services within a particular economy wherein, the purchasing power of consumers decreases, and the value of the cash holdings erode. Inflation measures the average price change in a basket of com- modities and services over time. The opposite and rare fall in the price index of this basket of items is called ‘deflation’. The Cob- web Phenomenon explains fluctuations in food prices, especial- ly for crops like pulses. If prices are high in one year, farmers may plant more of those crops the next season, causing oversupply and a price drop. In the following season, prices may rise again due to reduced supply as farmers cut back on production, creat- ing a cyclical pattern of price fluctuations. Statement 1 is incorrect: While there has been a shift to- wards cultivating commercial crops like cotton, sugarcane, and oilseeds, it has not been to the extent of a 30% reduction in food grains cultivation. While commercial crops have gained ground, India’s food grain production remains significant, and a drastic decrease of 30% is not observed. Sta","PW-0848":"Pair 1 is correctly matched: A meltdown, typically triggered by a black swan event, leads to a rapid loss of finan- cial asset value and liquidity crises, as seen in India’s Sensex drop from 20,000 in 2008 to 10,000 in 2009. Pair 2 is incorrectly matched: A recession is a broader econom- ic phenomenon characterized by a significant decline in econom- ic activity spread across the economy, lasting more than a few months, normally visible in real GDP, real income, employment, industrial production, and wholesale-retail sales. While a fall in the growth rate can be a precursor to or associated with a recession, it’s not the definition of a recession itself. A fall in the growth rate means the economy is still growing, but at a slower pace. Pair 3 is incorrectly matched: An economic slowdown refers to a period of slower economic growth, but not necessarily a de- cline in GDP. GDP is still increasing (positive growth), but at a reduced rate. A “fall” in GDP signifies a contraction in the economy, which is closer to the definition of a recession. 118","PW-0849":"Statement 1 is incorrect : During 2010 (but correct at present, January 2025) the Wholesale Price Index (WPI) was on a monthly basis and on a weekly basis for primary and fuel items. However, the Cabinet Committee on Economic Affairs (CCEA) in 2012 decided to discontinue weekly data on primary and fuel items. These changes were on the recommen- dation of Abhijit Sen committee’s proposals in 2004-05. The current base year for WPI is 2011-12. Statement 2 is correct: The WPI which is published by the Office of Economic Adviser, Ministry of Commerce and Indus- try, gives less weight to food articles (24.38%) as compared to the Consumer Price Index for Industrial Workers (CPI IW), which assigns a higher weight (39.17%) to food items in the new series with base year 2016. The WPI and CPI have different weightages for various components. In the WPI, the weightage for food articles is relatively lower compared to the CPI for Indus- trial Workers (CPIIW). The CPIIW gives a higher weight to food and beverages because it reflects the consumption pattern of in- dustrial workers, who spend a sign","PW-0850":"A is the correct match with 1: Boom refers to an eco- nomic period where growth, employment, and production are at their peak which results in a high level of business activities. B is the correct match with 2: Recession indicates a slowdown where business activity diminishes, leading to lower economic indicators, generally identified by a fall in GDP in two successive quarters. C is the correct match with 3: Depression is a severe down- turn with significant negative effects on income, employment, and output. A continued recession turns into depression. D is the correct match with 4 : Recovery is a phase of improve- ment in economic conditions after a recession or depression which results in steady rise in general level of prices, income, out- put and employment. 121","PW-0851":"White goods are products for conspicuous consump- tion. They typically include large and costly household applianc- es such as refrigerators, washing machines, air conditioners, and other major home appliances. White goods typically refer to major household appliances that are traditionally white in color (although this is less of a defining characteristic now). These are durable consumer goods, often considered non-essential but as- sociated with a certain level of comfort and lifestyle. 122","PW-0852":"In India, inflation has traditionally been measured us- ing the Wholesale Price Index (WPI) and stands true for 1997. The WPI tracks the price changes of goods at the wholesale level, reflecting the prices at which goods are sold in bulk and is pub- lished by the Economic Adviser in the Ministry of Commerce and Industry. However, in recent years, the Consumer Price Index (CPI) has gained prominence as a measure of inflation, especially for policy decisions. The CPI measures price changes from the consumer’s perspective, capturing the retail prices of goods and services. The Reserve Bank of India (RBI) has adopted the CPI as the key mea- sure for its inflation targeting framework. 6. MONEY MARKET 123","PW-0853":"Collateralized Borrowing and Lending Obligations (CBLO) are short-term money market instruments used for borrowing and lending funds. They are primarily used by finan- cial institutions such as banks, mutual funds, and insurance com- panies to manage liquidity. CBLO transactions are collateralized, meaning they require secu- rities (such as government bonds) as collateral, reducing credit risk. The instrument was introduced by the Clearing Corpo- ration of India Ltd. (CCIL) to facilitate secure and efficient bor- rowing and lending of funds in the money market. CBLOs facilitate borrowing and lending transactions that are ful- ly collateralized, typically using government securities as collat- eral. CBLOs are primarily used by financial institutions to man- age liquidity and funding needs over short durations, ranging from overnight to one year.  Bond Market : The bond market is a financial marketplace where governments, corporations, and other entities issue and trade debt securities (bonds) to raise capital. Investors lend money to issuers in exchange for periodic interest payments","PW-0854":"The Central Bank Digital Currency (CBDC), or Digi- tal Rupee (e₹), is the Reserve Bank of India’s official digital cur- rency, interchangeable one-to-one with fiat currency and recog- nized as legal tender. It can be used by individuals, businesses, and government entities for transactions without needing a bank account, especially in the case of retail CBDC, which works like digital cash. CBDCs help reduce the costs of printing, transporting, and storing physical currency while improving transaction efficiency by minimizing intermediaries and enabling faster payments. Statement 1 is correct : The Digital Rupee (e₹) is issued by the RBI as Central Bank Digital Currency (CBDC) and functions as legal tender, just like physical cash. Its issuance is aligned with monetary policy objectives, including promoting financial in- clusion and reducing dependency on cash. Statement 2 is correct : Since the Digital Rupee is an obliga- tion of the central bank, it is recorded as a liability on RBI’s balance sheet, similar to physical currency notes issued by the central bank. Statement 3 is incorr","PW-0855":"","PW-0856":"The Gold Tranche(also called the Reserve Tranche) is part of a country’s quota at the IMF. The country pays a portion of this quota (currently 25%) to the IMF in the form of reserve assets (like gold or Special Drawing Rights - SDRs) and the re- maining portion in its own currency. The portion paid in reserve assets is the Reserve Tranche . The name “Gold Tranche” originated from the time when IMF quotas were partly paid in gold. Under this credit system, this reserve is readily accessible to member countries without any policy conditions, offering bal- ance of payments support when needed. Unlike other IMF credit arrangements, which require policy reforms, the Reserve Tranche acts as a financial cushion for emergencies. Countries can bor- row additional funds from the IMF through credit facilities like Stand-By Arrangements, but these are conditional and require agreed-upon economic adjustments. The Reserve Tranche re- mains a crucial tool for financial stability. 127","PW-0857":"Statement 1 is correct: Commercial paper (CP) is a money market instrument used by corporations to raise short-term fund requirements such as working capital. It’s unsecured, meaning it’s not backed by any collateral, and it’s is- sued in the form of a promissory note, which is a written promise to pay a specified amount on a specific date. Statement 2 is incorrect: Certificates of Deposit (CDs) are short-term instruments (typically with maturities of less than one year) issued by commercial banks (not the Reserve Bank of India) to individuals, corporations and financial institutions. Statement 3 is correct: Call money is a money market instru- ment used by the banks to meet their temporary require- ment of cash. They borrow and lend money from each other normally on a daily basis. It has a maturity period of one day to fifteen days and is used by banks for adjusting to their short-term liquidity imbalances. Indian Economy 271 Statement 4 is incorrect: Zero-coupon bonds do not pay periodic interest. Instead, they are sold at a discount and re- deemed at face value at maturity, with t","PW-0858":"Statement 1 is incorrect : Bitcoin operates on a decen- tralized blockchain technology, which eliminates the need for any central au- thority such as cen- tral banks to track transactions. The system is maintained by miners who vali- date transactions and add them to the pub- lic ledger called the blockchain. While central banks are increasingly exploring the implications of cryp- tocurrencies and some are even considering issuing their own digital currencies (CBDCs), they do not currently track Bitcoin transactions. Statement 2 is correct : Anyone with a Bitcoin wallet (which generates a Bitcoin address) can send and receive Bitcoins to and from any other Bitcoin address, anywhere in the world. A Bitcoin address functions as a public key, similar to a digital bank account number. This address can be shared to receive pay- ments. Sending or receiving bitcoins requires no intermediary, allowing for peer-to-peer transactions across borders which is often faster and cheaper than traditional banking systems. Statement 3 is correct : Bitcoin transactions are pseu- do-anonymous which means","PW-0859":"Gold Monetization Scheme and Sovereign Gold Bond Scheme were introduced to lower the physical demand for gold and remove the estimated 20,000 tonnes of the precious met- al from households where it was sitting inert. Sovereign Gold Bonds (SGBs) are government securities denominated in grams of gold issued by the RBI on behalf of the Government. Statement 1 is correct : Sovereign Gold Bond Scheme was launched along with the Gold Monetisation Scheme in November 2015. India has a strong cultural affinity for gold, and a significant amount of gold is held by households in the form of jewelry, bars, and coins. The objective is to reduce India’s gold imports and bring all the gold lying idle with individuals and households and put it to productive use in the economy. Statement 2 is incorrect : Neither the SGB nor the GMS is ex- plicitly designed to promote FDI in the gold and jewellery sector. Their primary focus is on domestic gold mobilization and reducing reliance on imports. While a more organized gold mar- ket resulting from these schemes could create a conducive envi- ronment for inv","PW-0860":"Venture capital (VC) is a form of private equity and a type of financing that investors provide to startup companies and small businesses that are believed to have long-term growth potential. The majority of venture capital is often provided by wealthy individuals, investment banks, and other financial organisations. They often provide mentorship and strategic guidance in addition to funds. Investors take on higher risks with the expectation of high returns if the business succeeds. In India, firms such as Sequoia Capital, Accel Partners, and Indian Angel Network are well-known VC providers. Sectors like technology, e-commerce, and fintech have seen significant VC investments. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 272 131","PW-0861":"Inflation is the general rise in prices of goods and services within a particular economy wherein, the purchas- ing power of consumers decreases, and the value of the cash holdings erode. Inflation measures the average price change in a basket of commodities and services over time. Some causes of inflation include increase in demand, reduction in supply, de- mand-supply gap, excess circulation of money, increase in input costs, devaluation of currency, rise in wages, etc. Statement 1 is correct: When the money supply in the economy increases the purchasing power of people increases leading to in- creased demand for goods and services. If this demand surpasses the supply the prices rise causing demand-pull inflation. Exam- ple: Post-COVID monetary easing by central banks led to global inflationary trends. Statement 2 is correct : If the economy’s overall production of goods and services falls (aggregate supply decreases) and demand remains the same or increases then the prices will be pushed upward causing inflation. This can happen due to factors like supply chain disruptions, natura","PW-0862":"Statement 1 is correct : When the central bank buys government securities (like bonds) from the public it injects money into the economy. The sellers of these securities re- ceive cash, increasing the money supply. This is a key tool of monetary policy known as open market operations. Statement 2 is incorrect : When the public deposits currency into commercial banks, it doesn’t increase the overall mon- ey supply. It simply changes the form of money. Currency in circulation decreases but bank deposits increase by the same amount. These deposits can then be used by banks to cre- ate credit. Thus the initial act of depositing cash is neutral with respect to the money supply. Statement 3 is correct : When the government borrows di- rectly from the central bank, it often leads to an increase in the money supply. The central bank essentially creates new money to lend to the government. This is sometimes referred to as “monetizing the debt.” Statement 4 is incorrect : When the Central Bank sells gov- ernment securities to the public, it effectively reduces the amount of money circulating i","PW-0863":"Central Public Sector Enterprises (CPSEs) en- com-passes those Government companies in which the direct holding of the Central Government is 51 per cent or more and subsidiaries of such Government companies. The Statutory Cor- porations set up under Statutes enacted by the Parliament and other companies owned or controlled, directly or indirectly by the Central Government are also categorized as CPSEs. Statement 1 is incorrect : External debt is the portion of a country’s debt that is borrowed from foreign lenders, including commercial banks, governments, or international financial insti- tutions. The primary objectives of disinvestment in CPSEs are to raise resources for development, reduce fiscal defi- cits, and promote wider ownership of CPSEs through public participation rather than repaying external debt. Statement 2 is incorrect : In many cases, the government re- tains management control by holding a majority stake (more than 50%) even after partial disinvestment. However, in stra- tegic disinvestments, management control may be transferred to private entities. Disinvestment p","PW-0864":"The Mega Food Park Scheme, launched in 2008–09, aims to significantly enhance the food processing industry by in- creasing value and reducing food waste throughout the supply chain, particularly for perishable goods. This initiative is over- seen by the Ministry of Food Processing Industries. The scheme is executed by a Special Purpose Vehicle (SPV), a corporate entity registered under the Companies Act, 2013. Based on a “Cluster” approach, the scheme focuses on developing advanced support infrastructure in specific agricultural or horti- cultural zones. This infrastructure is designed to enable the es- tablishment of modern food processing units on industrial plots within the park, supported by a well-established supply chain. Statement 1 is correct : Through a cluster-based approach, mega food parks build cutting-edge infrastructure facilities for food processing along the value chain from farm to market with strong forward and backward connections. Statement 2 is correct : The Scheme is aimed at providing a method for connecting agricultural production to the market by bringing to","PW-0865":"The National Investment Fund (NIF) was created in India to receive the proceeds from the disinvestment of public sector undertakings (PSUs). The idea was to use these funds stra- tegically for social sector development and investment. Statement 1 is incorrect: the NIF’s assets were managed by selected public sector mutual funds, namely UTI Asset Man- agement Company Ltd., SBI Funds Management Private Ltd., and LIC Mutual Fund Asset Management Company Ltd., not directly by the Union Ministry of Finance. Statement 2 is incorrect: The NIF was kept outside the Con- solidated Fund of India. This was done to ensure that the disin- vestment proceeds were used for their intended purpose (social sector development) and not simply absorbed into general gov- ernment expenditure. Statement 3 is correct: The Government appoints Asset Man- agement Companies (AMCs) from the public sector to manage the fund. Statement 4 is correct: 75% of the annual income from NIF is allocated to social sector schemes (education, health, em- ployment). 25% is used for capital investment in profitable/ revivable CPS","PW-0866":"India receives significant FDI from Mauritius primari- ly due to the Double Taxation Avoidance Agreement (DTAA) between the two countries.  DTAA is a tax treaty that prevents individuals/entities from being taxed twice on the same income.  It promotes cross-border investments by offering tax relief.  Historically, this agreement allowed Mauritius-based investors to route investments into India with tax benefits, leading to higher FDI flows compared to countries like the UK and France.  India has DTAA with several countries, including Mauritius, Singapore, USA, UK, Germany, Japan, Canada, France, Australia, Netherlands, China, and Bangladesh.  India does not have DTAA with Afghanistan, Iraq, and Pakistan. 137","PW-0867":"Internal debt refers to the funds borrowed by the government from domestic sources rather than foreign loans. It includes various instruments used to raise funds within the country. Internal borrowing refers to the process by which the government borrows funds from domestic sources within its own country to finance its expenditures without resorting to foreign loans. This can be done through various mechanisms such as Market Borrowing, Treasury Bills, and Special Secu- rities issued to the RBI. It reduces dependency on foreign loans, avoiding risks related to exchange rate fluctuations. Helps main- tain economic sovereignty and control over debt. Option (d) is correct:  The government issues bonds or securities to borrow from the domestic market. This is a major source of funding for government expenditures. It helps avoid reliance on foreign debt and minimizes risks associated with exchange rate fluctuations. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 274  Short-term borrowing instruments issued by the government, generally with a maturity of up to one year(Treasury bills). Used for managing short-term","PW-0868":"Statement 1 is incorrect : The Reserve Bank of India (RBI) mandates a minimum capital requirement for wholly owned subsidiaries (WOS) of foreign banks operating in India. As per current regulations, the minimum paid-up equity cap- ital required is ₹500 crore to ensure financial stability and a strong capital base. The WOS was to be treated on par with the existing branches of foreign banks for branch expansion with flexibility to go beyond the existing WTO commitments of 12 branches in a year and preference for branch expansion in un- der-banked areas. Statement 2 is incorrect : According to RBI guidelines, the board of directors of a Wholly Owned Subsidiary (WOS) of a foreign bank must follow these rules :  At least 51% of the board members must meet the qualifications specified under Section 10A of the Banking Regulation Act, 1949.  At least two-thirds of the directors must be non-executive, meaning they are not involved in the day-to-day operations.  At least one-third of the directors must be independent, with no ties to the subsidiary, its parent bank, or any related entity. ","PW-0869":"Statement 1 is incorrect : Liquidity Adjustment Fa- cility(LAF) is monetary policy tool of RBI to inject or absorb liquidity. Under the LAF Scheme, the Reserve Bank will continue to have the discretion to conduct overnight repo or longer term repo auctions at fixed rate or at variable rates depending on mar- ket conditions and other relevant factors. NBFCs generally do not have direct access to the LAF window of the RBI. The LAF is primarily available to scheduled commer- cial banks and primary dealers. While NBFCs can indirectly ben- efit through banks accessing LAF, they cannot access it directly. Primary Dealers (PDs) are eligible to access the Liquidity Adjustment Facility (LAF) of the Reserve Bank of India (RBI). According to RBI guidelines, a non-bank entity intending to op- erate as a Primary Dealer must first register as a Non-Banking Financial Company (NBFC) under Section 45-IA of the RBI Act, 1934. Thus, while NBFCs generally do not have direct access to the LAF, those meeting specific regulatory requirements may be granted access under certain conditions. Statement 2 is co","PW-0870":"The Reserve Bank of India (RBI) employs Open Mar- ket Operations (OMOs) as a primary tool for sterilization. OMOs involve the buying and selling of government securities in the open market. When the RBI sells government securities, it ab- sorbs liquidity from the banking system, effectively neutralizing the increase in money supply resulting from its foreign exchange interventions. This process helps in maintaining monetary sta- bility and controlling inflation. 143","PW-0871":"Central Bank Digital Currencies (CBDCs) are digital forms of a country’s fiat currency which are issued and regulat- ed by the central bank. Statement 1 is correct : Central Bank Digital Currencies (CB- DCs) can operate independently unlike traditional cross-bor- der payments that rely on the US dollar as a reserve currency and the SWIFT (Society for Worldwide Interbank Financial Telecommunication) system for messaging. It can facilitate di- rect peer-to-peer (P2P) transactions or cross-border payments without intermediaries like SWIFT. Countries like China (with its digital yuan) and India (exploring the digital rupee) are develop- ing CBDCs to reduce dependence on the US dollar and SWIFT for international transactions. The m-CBDC Bridge project which involves countries like Chi- na, Hong Kong, Thailand, and the UAE, is an example of how CB- DCs can enable cross-border payments without relying on the US dollar or SWIFT. Statement 2 is correct : One of the key features of CBDCs is their programmability. Central banks can embed specific conditions into the digital currency using smart","PW-0872":"Statement 1 is incorrect : The SHG movement in In- dia was not initiated by the State Bank of India. The Nation- al Bank for Agriculture and Rural Development (NABARD) played a pivotal role in promoting and scaling up SHGs by pro- viding financial support, capacity-building initiatives, and policy frameworks. In 1992, NABARD launched the SHG-Bank Link- age Programme which facilitated the integration of SHGs into the formal banking system. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 276 Statement 2 is correct : All members of a Self-Help Group (SHG) share responsibility for any loans taken by individual members. This system fosters mutual support and peer account- ability thereby encouraging timely repayments and financial dis- cipline. Generally banks extend loans to the SHG as a single entity, which then distributes funds among its members. In the event of a default, the group collectively ensures repayment, safeguarding its overall creditworthiness. Statement 3 is correct : Regional Rural Banks (RRBs) and Scheduled Commercial Banks (SCBs) play a crucial role in supporting Self-Help Groups (SHGs). As part","PW-0873":"Statement 1 is incorrect : When inflation is higher than the RBI aims to reduce liquidity in the market. Buying government securities injects money into the economy by increasing liquidity, which would worsen inflation. On the contrary the RBI is more likely to sell government securities to absorb excess liquidity. Statement 2 is correct : When the rupee depreciates rapid- ly its value falls relative to the U.S. dollar. This means more rupees are required to purchase one dollar, indicating a weak- ening rupee. To stabilize the rupee and prevent excessive depreciation, the Reserve Bank of India (RBI) can intervene in the foreign exchange market by selling dollars from its reserves. When the RBI sells dollars in the market, it increases the available supply of dollars in the foreign exchange market. Market participants (importers, banks, and investors) exchange rupees to buy these newly available dollars. This increases the demand for rupees. As demand for rupees rises, the pressure on the rupee to depreciate reduces. This can help stabilize or even strengthen the rupee. Statement 3 is","PW-0874":"Credit Rating is assessment of the creditworthiness of a borrower. Individuals are given ‘credit scores’, while corpo- rations and governments receive ‘credit ratings’. Statement 1 is incorrect: Credit rating agencies in India are regulated by the Securities and Exchange Board of In- dia (SEBI) under SEBI (Credit Rating Agencies) Regulations, 1999, not the Reserve Bank of India (RBI). Statement 2 is correct: ICRA (Investment Information and Credit Rating Agency of India Ltd.) was set up in 1991 by IFCI, LIC, SBI and select banks as well as financial institu- tions to rate debt instruments. The ICRA consists of a group of Companies including its subsidiaries. ICRA Limited is a public limited company listed on stock exchanges. Statement 3 is correct: In India credit rating agencies regis- tered under Securities and Exchange Board of India (SEBI) are CRISIL, ICRA, CARE, SMERA, Fitch India and Brickwork Ratings. Globally, Fitch Ratings, Moody’s Investors Service and Standard & Poor’s (S&P) control approximately 95% of ratings business. SUPER HINT For S2, have you ever read/heard any prov","PW-0875":"The Banks Board Bureau (BBB) was formed on the recommendations of ‘P. J. Nayak Committee to Review Gov- ernance of Boards of Banks. Indian Economy 277 Statement 1 is incorrect : The Banks Board Bureau (BBB) was headed by a prominent professional or former senior government official, rather than the Governor of the Re- serve Bank of India (RBI). Notably, its first Chairman was Shri Vinod Rai, who previously served as the Comptroller and Auditor General of India. Statement 2 is correct: Its primary role was to recommend ap- pointments for senior positions in Public Sector Banks (PSBs), Financial Institutions (FIs), and Public Sector Insurance Com- panies. In 2022, the BBB was replaced by the Financial Services Institutions Bureau (FSIB), which continues to carry out similar functions. Statement 3 is correct : The BBB advises PSBs on vario-us strategic matters such as: Business strategies,Capital raising plans,Governance reforms,etc. It also assists banks in addressing issues related to non-performing assets (NPAs) and improving operational efficiency. 148","PW-0876":"The Reserve Bank of India (RBI) is primarily respon- sible for maintaining price stability and controlling inflation in India. It does this through its monetary policy framework, which includes tools like the repo rate, reverse repo rate, open market operations, and cash reserve ratio (CRR). Under the Monetary Policy Framework Agreement (2016), the RBI, in collaboration with the Government of India has a mandate to maintain inflation at 4% (with a tolerance band of ±2%), i.e., between 2% to 6%. 149","PW-0877":"Statement 1 is correct : The Reserve Bank’’s affairs are governed by a central board of directors. The board is appoint- ed by the Government of India in keeping with the Reserve Bank of India Act,1934. Statement 2 is incorrect : The Constitution of India does not contain provisions granting the Central Government the au- thority to issue directions to the RBI. However, such author- ity is provided under Section 7 of the Reserve Bank of India Act, 1934. This section allows the Central Government to issue directions to the RBI in matters of public interest.Accordingly the Central Government may from time to time give such directions to the Bank as it may, after consultation with the Governor of the Bank, consider it necessary in the public interest. Statement 3 is correct : The powers and functions of the RBI Governor are derived from the Reserve Bank of India Act, 1934. The Act outlines the roles, responsibilities, and authority of the Governor in managing the affairs of the RBI. Functions of RBI Monetary Authority  Formulates, implements and monitors the monetary policy.  Maintain","PW-0878":"A Co-operative bank belongs to its members, who are at the same time the owners and the customers of their bank. Co-operative banks are under dual control of the RBI and Regis- trar of Cooperative Societies. Agriculture, some small-scale busi- nesses, and independent contractors primarily receive funding from cooperative banks. These banks are cooperative credit in- stitutions that are registered under the Cooperative Societies Act 1912. These banks work according to the cooperative prin- ciples of mutual assistance. Co-operative banks have a three-tier structure:  Primary Credit Societies-PCSs (agriculture or urban).  District Central Co-Operative Banks- DCCBs.  State Co-Operative Banks-SCBs (at the apex level). Statement 1 is incorrect : After Banking Regulation(Amend- ment) Act 2020 was passed, Most of the powers were transferred to RBI from the Registrars of the cooperative societies. Urban Cooperative Banks are subject to dual regulation by both the Re- serve Bank of India (RBI) and the respective State Governments. The RBI oversees their banking operations, while the State G","PW-0879":"Statement 2 is correct : A “lender of last resort” means that the RBI (also called banker of banks) offers loans to banks or other eligible institutions that are experiencing financial difficulty or are considered highly risky or near collapse. By doing so, it helps stabilize the financial system and prevents bank runs and thereby safeguarding public confidence in the banking sector. Indian Economy 279 Statements 1 and 3 are incorrect :  Trade and industry bodies typically borrow from commercial banks or financial markets and not directly from the central bank. The RBI’s role as a lender of last resort is limited to the banking sector to ensure financial stability.  Providing funds to cover government budgetary deficits is not part of the lender-of-last-resort function. The RBI’s support in such cases would fall under separate monetary management activities rather than emergency banking support. 152","PW-0880":"Statement 1 is correct : Short-term foreign debt is a major vulnerability during a financial crisis. When glob- al confidence deteriorates, investors can pull their short-term funds out of emerging markets very quickly. This sudden outflow of capital can cause a currency crisis, sharp interest rate increas- es, and severe economic disruption. A lower reliance on such borrowings provides greater resilience. Statement 2 is incorrect : Opening up to more foreign banks would lead to enhanced exposure to the global economy. While foreign banks can introduce advanced practices and en- hance capital availability, they also increase India’s exposure to global financial shocks. During crises these banks often prioritize their home markets, reducing support to Indian operations and exacerbating credit shortages. Greater foreign bank presence may foster interconnectedness but does not guarantee immunity, po- tentially heightening India’s vulnerability to external disruptions. Statement 3 is incorrect : Capital account conver-tibility means no restriction on the amount one can convert into forei","PW-0881":"Demand deposit accounts consist of funds held in a bank account from which deposited funds can be withdrawn at any time while a term deposit account restricts access for a predetermined time(Fixed deposits accounts, Recurring depos- its accounts). Current accounts and savings accounts are demand deposits. Money = total currency with the public + demand deposits of the public with banks. When you withdraw Rs. 1,00,000 in cash from your demand deposit account, you’re simply changing the form of your money. You’re not changing the total amount of money in the economy. Before the withdrawal: You have Rs. 1,00,000 in your bank account, which is part of the money supply (specifically, it’s part of the deposit component of the money supply). After the withdrawal: You have Rs. 1,00,000 in cash. This cash is also part of the money supply (specifically, it’s part of the currency in circulation component). The money has just moved from one “pocket” of the money supply to another. The overall quantity of money remains the same. 154","PW-0882":"Interest Coverage Ratio is a financial metric used to assess a company’s ability to meet its interest obligations on its debt. It’s calculated as: Interest Coverage Ratio = Earnings Before Interest and Taxes (EBIT) / Interest Expense Statements 1 and 2 are correct : The interest coverage ratio is a debt and profitability ratio used to determine how easily a company can pay interest on its outstanding debt. Banks use the ICR to assess the current financial health of a firm. A low ICR suggests the firm may face difficulties repaying interest on its loans, posing a higher risk to lenders. ICR trends can help banks foresee emerging risks. A declining ICR signals worsening financial health, hinting at future repayment challenges. Statement 3 is incorrect : A higher ICR implies that the firm generates sufficient earnings to cover its interest expenses comfortably, which is favorable. Conversely, a low ICR indi- cates a firm’s weakened ability to service its debt. 155","PW-0883":"Expansionary Monetary Policy is also known as Ac- commodative Monetary Policy has its main objective to in- crease the money supply in the economy through several measures such as:  Lowering interest rates.  Reducing reserve requirements for banks.  Purchasing government securities by RBI The goal of expansionary policy is to stimulate economic growth by encouraging business activities and consumer spending, while also helping reduce unemployment. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 280 Statement 1 is incorrect : Statutory Liquidity Ratio (SLR) is the percentage of a bank’s net demand and time liabilities that must be maintained in the form of liquid assets, such as cash, gold, or government securities. Reducing the SLR allows banks to have more funds available for lending, thereby increasing the money supply in the economy. Hence RBI would cut and opti- mise the Statutory Liquidity Ratio. Statement 2 is correct : Marginal Standing Facility (MSF) Rate is the rate at which banks can borrow overnight funds from the RBI against approved government securities. Increasing the MSF rate makes borrowing","PW-0884":"Rural co-operatives include District Central Co-opera- tive Banks (DCCBs), State Co-operative Banks (StCBs), and Pri- mary Agricultural Credit Societies (PACS). Statement 1 is incorrect: Although the focus of rural cooper- ative lending is agriculture, the share in credit flow to the agri- culture of rural cooperatives is only 12.1%, as compared to 76% of Scheduled Commercial Banks (SCBs), and 11.9% of Regional Rural Banks. Statement 2 is correct: A District Co-operative Central Bank (DCCB) is a cooperative bank operating at the district level in various parts of India. It was established to provide banking to the rural hinterland for the agricultural sector with the branches primarily established in rural and semi-urban areas. DCCBs mo- bilise deposits from the public and provide credit to the public and PACS. SUPER HINT For S1, When comparing local vs. national institutions, always ask: “Who has deeper pockets, broader reach, and mandatory targets?” Answer = SCBs and RRBs, not DCCBs. Hence S1 likely false. 157","PW-0885":"The Service Area Approach (SAA) was implement- ed under the purview of the Lead Bank Scheme. It was in- troduced by the Reserve Bank of India (RBI) in April 1989. The SAA aimed to facilitate the planned and orderly development of rural and semi-urban areas. Under this approach, each commer- cial bank branch in these areas was designated to serve a specific cluster of 15 to 25 villages. The designated branch was respon- sible for meeting the banking needs of its assigned service area, thereby strengthening the link between bank credit and rural development. 158","PW-0886":"Statement 1 is correct : The Reserve Bank of India (RBI) directed payment system providers to ensure that all pay- ment system data is stored only in India. This is part of the data localization policy. Statement 2 is incorrect : The RBI’s directive does not require payment systems to be owned or operated by public sector enterprises only. The policy applies to all payment system pro- viders regardless of whether they are public or private entities. It focuses on the localization of data storage rather than ownership structures. Statement 3 is incorrect : The directive does not require pay- ment system providers to submit audit reports to the Comp- troller and Auditor General of India. Instead, they are required to submit a System Audit Report (SAR) conducted by CERT- IN empaneled auditors to the RBI not later than December 31. 159","PW-0887":"The Inter-Creditor Agreement (ICA) was signed by Indian banks and financial institutions to expedite the reso- lution of stressed assets involving amounts of ₹50 crore or more under consortium lending arrangements. The ICA was part of the “Sashakt” committee recommendations which pro- posed a five-pronged strategy to tackle NPAs. The ICA provides a structured framework for multiple lenders to collaborate and resolve stressed assets efficiently. Key features include:  Majority Decision Binding : If 66% of the lenders by value agree on a resolution plan, it becomes binding on all participating lenders. This was done to prevent individual holdouts from delaying resolutions.  Timely ReAns: The agreement emphasizes prompt action, setting specific timelines to finalize and implement resolution plans.  Asset Management Approach : It encourages the formation of independent asset management companies to manage and turn around distressed assets. 160","PW-0888":"Banks Board Bureau recomm-ends for selection of heads - Public Sector Banks and Financial Institutions and helps banks in developing strategies and capital raising plans. Bank Board Bureau was established as an indep-endent or- ganisation in February 2016 based on the suggestions of the RBI appointed Nayak Committee. It was part of the Indradhanush Plan. It suggested the selection of full-time directors and non-ex- ecutive chairs for Public Sector Banks (PSBs) and state-owned financial institutions. Note : Now, Financial Services Institutions Bureau (FSIB) was put in place by the Government in place of BBB for recommend- ing candidates for PSBs heads 161","PW-0889":"A bank’s assets are what it owns and what gener- ates income for the bank. They represent how the bank uses the funds it has mobilized. A bank’s liabilities are what it owes to others. They represent the sources of funds that the bank uses to acquire assets and conduct its business. A commercial bank’s balance sheet, assets and liabilities are cat- egorized as follows: Assets:  Advances: These are loans and credits extended to customers, generating interest income for the bank.  Investments: Holdings in government securities, bonds, and other approved securities that earn returns.  Money at Call and Short Notice: Short-term funds lent to other banks or financial institutions, typically repayable on demand or within a short period. Liabilities:  Deposits: Funds accepted from the public, including savings, current, and fixed deposits, which the bank is obligated to repay. Hence, option (b) is correct. 162","PW-0890":"","PW-0891":"","PW-0892":"Statement 1 is correct : The BHIM (Bharat Interface for Money) app allows users to transfer money to anyone with a UPI (Unified Payments Interface)-enabled bank account. This is achieved through a UPI ID, mobile number, or QR code which makes it a seamless and widely accessible digital payment solution. It is a government-backed app designed to facilitate dig- ital payments which promoting interoperability among various banks. Statement 2 is incorrect : Both systems adhere to the Reserve Bank of India’s (RBI) mandate for two-factor authentication to enhance the security of digital transactions.  Chip-PIN Debit Card typically employs two-factor authentication (2FA) not four-factor:  Possession Factor: The physical debit card.  Knowledge Factor: The Personal Identification Number (PIN) known to the user.  BHIM App also utilizes two-factor authenti-cation:  Possession Factor: The mobile device registered with the user’s bank account.  Knowledge Factor: The UPI PIN set by the user. 165","PW-0893":"National Payments Corpor-ation of India (NPCI) op- erates the National Financial Switch (NFS) which is the larg- est network of shared ATMs in India which connects over 265,000 ATMs as of January,2025. NFS facilitates interoper- able cash withdrawal, card-to-card funds transfer, and interop- erable cash deposit transactions, among other services thereby linking ATMs across the country.  The National Payments Corporation of India (NPCI) was established by the RBI and the Indian Banks’ Association under the Payment and Settlement Systems Act, 2007 to enhance India’s payment infrastructure.  It is incorporated as a “Not for Profit” company under Section 25 of the Companies Act 1956 (now Section 8 of the 2013 Act).  The ten core promoter banks are State Bank of India, Punjab National Bank, Canara Bank, Bank of Baroda, Union Bank of India, Bank of India, ICICI Bank Limited, HDFC Bank Limited, Citibank and HSBC. 166","PW-0894":"The Merchant Discount Rate (MDR) is a fee charged to merchants by banks or payment gateways for accepting payments from their customers and processing digital trans- actions such as payments made through debit cards, credit cards or other electronic means. It is typically a small percentage of the transaction amount and is used to cover the costs of processing the payment. 167","PW-0895":"The Capital Adequacy Ratio (CAR) measures a bank’s ability to handle risks like credit and operational risks while meeting its obligations. Simply put, it acts as a ‘cushion’ to ab- sorb potential losses, protecting depositors and lenders. Reg- ulators set and monitor minimum CAR levels to maintain trust in the banking system and ensure stability. A strong CAR shows that a bank can handle losses without affecting its financial com- mitments, reducing risks from defaults or unexpected economic challenges. The capital adequacy ratio is computed by dividing the total capital of a bank by its risk-weighted assets. This is why the CAR is also called the Capital to Risk (Weighted) Assets Ratio (CRAR). Statement 1 is correct : Capital Adequacy Ratio (CAR) is the ra- tio of a bank’s capital in relation to its risk weighted assets and current liabilities. Statement 2 is incorrect : CAR is decided by central banks and bank regulators to prevent commercial banks from taking Indian Economy 283 excess leverage and becoming insolvent in the process. The Re- serve Bank of India (RBI) mandates speci","PW-0896":"Statement 1 is incorrect : The Reserve Bank of In- dia (RBI) manages and services both Government of India (Central Government) securities and State Government se- curities. These are called State Development Loans (SDLs). RBI acts as the debt manager for both the Government of India (GoI) and State Governments. Statement 2 is correct : In India only the Central Government issues Treasury Bills (T-bills). State Governments do not is- sue T-bills. They raise funds through bonds known as State De- velopment Loans (SDLs). Statement 3 is correct : Treasury Bills (T-Bills) are issued at a discount to their face value (par value) and redeemed at face value upon maturity. The difference between the issue price and the face value represents the interest earned by the in- vestor. For example a T-Bill with a face value of ₹100 might be issued at ₹98 and the investor earns ₹2 as interest. 170","PW-0897":"Statement 1 is incorrect : Capital infusion into Pub- lic Sector Banks (PSBs) over the last decade has not followed a steady upward trend. It has been cyclical driven primarily by spe- cific challenges such as rising non-performing assets (NPAs). The government has made substantial infusions during critical peri- ods while scaling back during others, depending on the banks’ requirements and fiscal constraints. Statement 2 is correct: In 2017 five associate banks (State Bank of Bikaner & Jaipur, State Bank of Hyderabad, State Bank of Mysore, State Bank of Patiala, and State Bank of Tra- vancore) along with Bharatiya Mahila Bank were merged with State Bank of India (SBI). This merger was aimed at im- proving operational efficiency, reducing costs, and enhancing the balance sheet of SBI. 171","PW-0898":"The National Payments Corporation of India (NPCI) is an umbrella organization established by the Reserve Bank of In- dia (RBI) and the Indian Banks’ Association (IBA) under the Payment and Settlement Systems Act, 2007, to create a robust payment and settlement infrastructure in India. Statement 1 is correct: National Payments Corpor-ation of India (NPCI) helps in promoting financial inclusion in the country by providing affordable and accessible digital payment solutions to all sections of society including rural and under- served areas. It supports initiatives like the Unified Payments Interface (UPI), Aadhaar Enabled Payment System (AEPS) and RuPay which enable seamless and low-cost digital transac- tions. Statement 2 is correct: NPCI launched RuPay as India’s first domestic card payment network to reduce dependency on international card networks like Visa and Mastercard. RuPay is UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 284 widely used in debit cards, credit cards and prepaid cards issued by Indian banks and it supports financial inclusion by offering low-cost payment solutions. The alliances with in","PW-0899":"UPI allows direct bank-to-bank transfers without the need for intermediary wallets. This has led to a decline in mo- bile wallet transactions, as users and merchants prefer UPI for its seamless and direct approach. Options (b), (c) and (d) are incorrect :  While UPI has accelerated the adoption of digital payments but it is uncertain when or if physical cash will completely disappear. Cash is still widely used, and a full transition to digital payments would depend on many economic and social factors beyond just UPI’s impact.  UPI enhances domestic digital transactions but its direct impact on a significant rise in FDI lacks strong evidence.  UPI impact is limited as many beneficiaries withdraw DBT funds in cash soon after receiving them. 174","PW-0900":"The Small Finance Banks (SFBs) were established by the Reserve Bank of India (RBI) to further financial inclusion by providing essential banking services to underserved and un- served segments of the population. Statement 1 is correct : Small Finance Banks (SFBs) focus on extending credit to micro and small enterprises, thereby sup- porting entrepreneurship and economic growth at the grassroots level. Statement 2 is correct : SFBs aim to meet the unique needs of small and marginal farmers by offering tailored financial prod- ucts and services which enhances agricultural productivity and rural development. Statement 3 is incorrect : Though SFBs support small business units and micro-entrepreneurs but the specific emphasis on “young entrepreneurs” is not explicitly stated in the RBI’s guidelines.  To ensure outreach to underserved regions, SFBs are mandated to have at least 25% of their branches in unbanked rural centers.  SFBs are required to maintain a minimum capital adequacy ratio of 15% of their risk-weighted assets which ensures financial stability and resilience. 175","PW-0901":"Statement 1 is correct: The primary function of the MPC is to determine the policy repo rate, which is the bench- mark interest rate at which commercial banks borrow mon- ey from the RBI. This rate influences other interest rates in the economy Statement 2 is incorrect: The MPC is a 6-member body con- sisting of:  3 members from the RBI, including the Governor (who acts as the chairperson).  3 external members nominated by the Government of India.  Members are appointed for a four-year term Statement 3 is incorrect : The MPC functions under the chairmanship of the Governor of the RBI, not the Union Fi- nance Minister. SUPER HINT S3 aligns with Function-person/organisation/ministry match trap as it's easy to manipulate to make it false. Is it RBI governor or FM? 176","PW-0902":"Statement 1 is correct: The Reserve Bank of India’s guidelines for licensing Payments Banks specify that enti- ties such as existing non-bank Prepaid Payment Instrument (PPI) issuers, mobile telephone companies, supermarket chains, and others owned and controlled by residents are eligible to promote Payments Banks. This initiative aims to leverage their extensive customer bases and distribution net- works to enhance financial inclusion. Statement 2 is incorrect: Payments Banks are permitted to issue ATM or debit cards but are not allowed to issue credit cards. This restriction aligns with their mandate to provide basic banking services without engaging in credit risk activities. The restriction on credit cards is a key differentiator between Pay- ment Banks and traditional banks. Statement 3 is correct : As per RBI guidelines their primary role is to accept demand deposits, provide payment and remit- tance services, and distribute financial products like insurance and mutual funds, thereby promoting financial inclusion without assuming credit risk. 177","PW-0903":"Statement 1 is correct : Core Banking Solution ​(CBS) is a centralized platform that connects all branches of a bank, allowing customers to access and manage their ac- counts from any branch, ATM, or online. It’s a software appli- cation that integrates various banking operations and provides a unified view of customer information. Statements 2 and 3 are incorrect :  The implementation of Core Banking Solutions is primarily driven by individual banks aiming to improve operational efficiency and customer service.  Core Banking Solutions are unrelated to the processes of bank mergers or acquisitions. They are technological systems that enable centralized operations and do not pertain to the takeover procedures of banks with significant non- performing assets. Core Banking Solutions (CBS) is a centralized banking sys- tem that enables banks to handle their daily operations, such as deposit accounts, loan processing, fund transfers, and cus- tomer transactions, through one unified platform.With CBS, all bank branches are connected to a central database, allow- ing customers to access b","PW-0904":"MCLR is the lowest interest rate a bank can charge for loans. It helps banks calculate the minimum interest rate for different types of loans. The Reserve Bank of India (RBI) introduced the MCLR system on April 1, 2016, to make monetary policy transmission more effective and increase transparency in setting interest rates. It replaced the base rate system, which had been used since July 2010. Statement 1 is correct: Bringing transparency in the meth- ods followed by various banks for the determination of interest rate is one of the key objectives of MCLR regime. Before banks used various methods to set lending rates which UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 286 lead to opacity and confusion for borrowers. MCLR introduced a standardized, transparent calculation method, requiring banks to disclose its components, helping borrowers better understand their loan rates. Statement 2 is correct: By standardizing the methodology for calculating lending rates, the MCLR guidelines aim to en- sure that interest rates are “fair” to Borrowers and Banks:  The transparent methodology prevents banks from arbitrari","PW-0905":"PMJDY (Pradhan Mantri Jan Dhan Yojana) is a na- tional initiative for financial inclusion, aiming to ensure that every household in the country has access to comprehensive financial services. The objective of “Pradhan Mantri Jan-Dhan Yojana (PMJDY)” is ensuring access to various financial services like availabil- ity of basic savings bank account, access to need based credit, remittances facility, insurance and pension to the excluded sec- tions i.e. weaker sections & low income groups. This deep pen- etration at affordable cost is possible only with effective use of technology. The plan includes providing universal banking access, with at least one basic bank account per household, as well as pro- moting financial literacy, credit access, insurance, and pen- sion services. Beneficiaries will receive a RuPay Debit card, which includes accident insurance coverage of ₹1 lakh. The program also plans to direct all government benefits (from central, state, and local bodies) into beneficiaries’ accounts and promote the Direct Benefits Transfer (DBT) scheme. 180","PW-0906":"","PW-0907":"Monetary policy refers to actions undertaken by the central bank (in India, the Reserve Bank of India - RBI) to manipulate the money supply, interest rates, and credit con- ditions to stimulate or restrain economic activity. Its primary goal is to maintain price stability (control inflation) while sup- porting economic growth. Statement 1 is correct : The bank rate in India is defined as the interest rate at which the Reserve Bank of India (RBI) lends money to commercial banks for long-term loans. It serves as a tool to control the money supply in the economy and manage inflation. Changes in the bank rate influence other inter- est rates in the economy. An increase in the bank rate makes bor- rowing more expensive which can slow down economic activity and inflation. Decreasing the bank rate has the opposite effect. Statement 2 is correct : Open Market Operations (OMO) in- volve the buying and selling of government securities by the RBI in the open market. When the RBI purchases government securities, it injects money into the economy, thereby increasing the money supply. Conversely, ","PW-0908":"Marginal standing facility (MSF) is a window for banks to borrow from the Reserve Bank of India in an emer- gency situation when inter-bank liquidity dries up completely. Banks borrow from the central bank by pledging govern- ment securities at a rate higher than the repo rate under li- quidity adjustment facility( LAF) . The MSF rate is pegged 100 basis points or 1 percentage point above the repo rate. Under MSF banks can borrow funds up to one percentage of their net demand and time liabilities (NDTL). Demand Liabilities Demand Liabilities of a bank are liabilities which are pay- able on demand. These include current deposits, demand lia- bilities portion of savings bank deposits, margins held against letters of credit/guarantees, cash certificates and cumulative/ recurr-ing deposits, Demand Drafts (DDs), unclaimed deposits, credit balances in the Cash Credit account etc. Time Liabilities Time Liabilities of a bank are those which are payable oth- erwise than on demand. These include fixed deposits, cash certificates, cumulative and recurring deposits, time liabili- ties portion of","PW-0909":"Banking Correspondents (BCs) also known as Bank Saathis are individuals or entities hired by banks in India (in- cluding commercial banks, Regional Rural Banks (RRBs), and Lo- cal Area Banks (LABs)) to provide banking services in areas with limited or no banking access. A BC acts as an agent for the bank, serving as a substitute for the bank’s physical branch. Statement 1 is correct: The Reserve Bank of India (RBI) launched the Business Correspondent (BC) Model in 2006 to improve financial inclusion in India. BCs play a critical role in disbursing direct benefit transfers (DBT), including sub- sidies and social security payments, to beneficiaries in rural areas. This eliminates the need for beneficiaries to travel long distances to a bank branch to collect their payments. Statement 2 is correct: BCs offer a range of basic banking ser- vices, including accepting deposits, facilitating withdrawals, and enabling other small transactions. This brings basic bank- ing services to people who previously had limited or no access. 185","PW-0910":"Statutory Reserve Requirements, such as the Cash Reserve Ratio (CRR) and Statutory Liquidity Ratio (SLR) are regulatory tools employed by the Reserve Bank of India (RBI) to ensure the stability and liquidity of the banking sys- tem. These requirements mandate that commercial banks main- tain a certain percentage of their net demand and time liabilities (NDTL) in the form of liquid asset Statement 1 is correct : When the central bank wants to in- crease the money supply in the economy, it lowers the reserve ratio. Hence it enables the Central Bank to control the amount of advances the banks can create. Statement 2 is correct : RBI requires commercial banks to keep reserves in order to ensure that banks have sufficient assets to draw on when account holders want to be paid. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 288 Statement 3 is incorrect : Reserve requirements are de- signed as “precautionary measures” to control the economy and not to stop banks from making “excessive” profit. Statement 4 is incorrect : Vault cash (cash held by banks in their vaults) is separate from CRR. CRR is the cash banks must ","PW-0911":"","PW-0912":"Priority Sector Lending (PSL) is a mandated policy by the Reserve Bank of India (RBI) that requires banks to allo- cate a certain percentage of their total lending to economically and socially important sectors that may not get adequate cred- it otherwise. RBI Mandate on PSL:  Domestic Banks & Foreign Banks (with 20+ branches): Minimum 40% of total lending should go to priority sectors.  Small Finance Banks & Regional Rural Banks (RRBs): Minimum 75% of total lending under PSL. Sectors Covered Under PSL: Category Examples 1. Agriculture Loans to farmers, self-help groups (SHGs), agricultural infrastructure 2. Micro, Small & Medium Enter- prises (MSMEs) Loans for small businesses, startups, working capital needs 3. Export Credit Loans to exporters, incentives for for- eign trade 4. Education Student loans for higher education in India and abroad 5. Housing Affordable housing loans, low-income group housing 6. Weaker Sec- tions SC/ST, women, self-employed, arti- sans, etc. 7. Renewable Energy Loans for solar, wind, biomass energy projects 8. Social Infra- structure Schools, hospitals,","PW-0913":"RRBs and LDBs provide direct credit assistance, whereas NABARD only refinances other banks. Option 1 is correct : RRBs are government-sponsored banks that provide direct credit to small and marginal farmers, ar- tisans, laborers, and small entrepreneurs. They aim to devel- op the rural economy by offering banking and financial ser- vices to low-income groups in rural areas. Example: Prathama Bank, Andhra Pradesh Grameena Vikas Bank. Option 2 is incorrect : NABARD does not grant direct credit assistance to rural households. It acts as a refinancing in- Indian Economy 289 191","PW-0914":"Option (d) is correct: Liquidity refers to how quickly an asset can be converted into cash without significant loss of value. Higher liquidity means faster conversion into spend- able money. The correct order of liquidity for the given as- sets is (Most Liquid) Currency → Demand Deposits → Sav- ings Deposits → Time Deposits (Least Liquid). Asset Type Explanation 1. Currency  Cash is the most liquid asset as it can be used immediately without conversion.  Physical cash (notes & coins) is immediately usable for transactions.  No need for conversion, accepted universally. 2. Demand Deposits  Funds in current accounts can be withdrawn anytime without notice.  Can be transferred using cheques, online banking, or ATMs.  Liquidity: Very High, just below currency. 3. Savings Deposits  More liquid than time deposits but less liquid than demand deposits.  Withdrawal limits exist (e.g., max withdrawals per month).  Liquidity: Moderate. 4. Time Deposits  Includes Fixed Deposits (FDs) and Recurring Deposits (RDs).  Money is locked for a fixed term.  Premature withdrawal leads to penal","PW-0915":"Option 1 is correct : The RBI ensures that commer- cial banks maintain a certain level of liquidity in their assets to meet the demands of their depositors. This is done through various tools such as :  Cash Reserve Ratio (CRR) – Banks must keep a certain percentage of their deposits with the RBI.  Statutory Liquidity Ratio (SLR) – Banks must maintain a percentage of their deposits in liquid assets like gold, cash, or government securities.  Liquidity Adjustment Facility (LAF) – Repo and Reverse Repo rates help manage short-term liquidity. These tools ensure banks have sufficient liquidity and prevent financial crises. Option 2 is correct : Under RBI’s Branch Autho-risation Poli- cy, banks need RBI approval for :  Opening new branches in Tier 1 & Tier 2 cities (Population above 50,000).  Expanding into rural areas and underserved regions to ensure financial inclusion. Option 3 is correct : The RBI plays a significant role in regu- lating bank mergers. It sets guidelines and approves merg- ers to ensure that they are in the interest of depositors and the stability of the financia","PW-0916":"The Lead Bank Scheme (LBS) was introduced by the Reserve Bank of India (RBI) in 1969 following the recommen- dations of the Gadgil Study Group (1969). The primary objec- tive of the scheme is to promote banking penetration, credit flow, and financial inclusion in rural areas by assigning a spe- cific bank to act as the lead bank for a district. This lead bank is responsible for coordinating banking activities and ensuring that credit reaches priority sectors like agriculture, MSMEs, and weaker sections. Key Features of Lead Bank Scheme (LBS) : 1. Each district is assigned a Lead Bank (mostly a public sector or large private bank). 2. Lead Bank is responsible for coordinating financial institutions, monitoring credit flow, and improving banking services in its district. 3. Priority Sector Lending (PSL) is a major focus, ensuring credit to agriculture, MSMEs, and weaker sections. 4. District Credit Plans (DCPs) are formulated to set targets for bank credit expansion in the region. 5. SLBC (State Level Bankers’ Committee) and DLCC (District Level Coordination Committees) ensure implemen","PW-0917":"A teaser loan is a loan with an initially low-interest rate for a fixed period, after which the rate increases gradual- ly. They are commonly used in home loans, credit cards, and other financing schemes to attract borrowers. State Bank of India (SBI) introduced teaser loans in 2009 for home loans in India. Subprime lending is the practice of lending to borrow- ers with a low credit rating that may be exposed to the risk of default in future. Statement 1 is correct : Teaser loans are often linked with subprime lending practices, where loans are extended to borrowers with lower creditworthiness. The low initial rates can lure borrowers who may struggle to repay when the rates increase, leading to a higher risk of defaults in the future. After the initial low-rate period ends, borrowers may face significantly higher payments. If they are unable to meet these higher payments,defaults can occur. This puts financial institu- tions at risk and can contribute to broader economic instability. Statement 2 is incorrect : Teaser loans in India are not primar- ily given to inexperienced entrepre","PW-0918":"In India, Commercial Banks have the highest share in the disbursement of credit to agriculture and allied activi- ties. As of 2019-20, they accounted for approximately 76.83% of the total agricultural credit disbursed because:  Priority Sector Lending (PSL) norms require banks to lend at least 18% of their Adjusted Net Bank Credit (ANBC) to agriculture.  Commercial banks have the widest reach and higher lending  Institutions like NABARD help commercial banks in refinancing agricultural loans.  Most KCC loans are provided by commercial banks.  RBI & Government have encouraged commercial banks to expand rural branches and digitize farm credit. Options (b) is incorrect: Cooperative banks have been pivot- al in providing credit to the agricultural sector, particularly in rural areas. These banks cater to small farmers, especially those with lower creditworthiness who may not have access to commercial banks. Despite their importance in the past, coopera- tive banks’ share in agricultural credit has declined due to several factors:  Weak Financial Health:  Limited Reach  Declining ","PW-0919":"Inclusive growth is economic growth that delivers social benefits, tackles inequalities and spreads benefits more fairly between people and places. In the context of the Indian economy, several initiatives contribute significantly to this objective: Statement 1 is correct : Self-Help Groups are communi- ty-based groups that enable people to come together for mu- tual support, primarily in rural areas. These groups provide a platform for individuals, especially women, to access financial services like savings, credit, and insurance. SHGs contribute to inclusive growth by empowering women, improving finan- cial literacy, and enhancing social capital. Statement 2 is correct : MSMEs play a pivotal role in India’s economic landscape by generating employment, fostering innovation, and contributing to exports. They encourage eq- uitable distribution of wealth and act as engines of econom- ic progress. The MSME sector has the highest employment growth rate, positively impacting both exports and industrial growth. Statement 3 is correct : The RTE Act mandates free and com- pulsory education f","PW-0920":"Microfinance is a financial service designed to assist low-income groups, including self-employed individuals and consumers by providing them with essential financial products.  Microfinance institutions (MFIs) provide small loans(credit facilities) to low-income individuals, particularly those who do not have access to traditional banking services. These loans are often used for income- generating activities, such as starting or expanding small businesses.  Microfinance institutions offer savings accounts to low- income individuals, allowing them to safely deposit their earnings and build financial security. Savings facilities encourage financial discipline and provide a safety net for emergencies.  Microinsurance is a key component of micro-finance, providing low-income individuals with access to affordable insurance products. These products cover risks such as health, life, and crop failure, which are critical for the financial stability of low-income households.  Microfinance institutions facilitate fund tran-sfers, enabling low-income individuals to send and receive money se","PW-0921":"The CRR is the percentage of a bank’s total deposits that it must keep as reserves with the RBI in the form of cash. This is a monetary policy tool used by the RBI to control liquid- ity in the economy. This amount cannot be used for lending or investment by banks. When the RBI increases the CRR, banks are required to keep a higher proportion of their deposits as reserves. This reduces the amount of money available with banks for lending to businesses and individuals. Option (b) is incorrect : RBI does not lend money to the pub- lic or businesses. It only regulates the money supply through tools like CRR. Option (c) is incorrect : The Union Government’s borrowing and lending activities are separate from the RBI’s monetary policy tools like CRR. Option (d) is incorrect : An increase in CRR reduces (not in- creases) the amount of money available for lending by com- mercial banks. 199","PW-0922":"The National Housing Bank (NHB) was established on July 9, 1988, under the National Housing Bank Act of 1987. Initially, it functioned as a wholly-owned subsidiary of the Reserve Bank of India (RBI), which contributed the entire paid-up capital. However, in 2019, the ownership struc- ture of NHB underwent a significant change. The Government of India acquired the entire stake from the RBI, making NHB a whol- ly-owned entity of the Government. Given that the question pertains to the year 2007, at that time, the correct answer is Reserve Bank of India. Functions of NHB The institution plays a crucial role in supervision and grievance redressal by monitoring and regulating Housing Finance Com- panies (HFCs), addressing complaints, and ensuring compliance with financial norms. In terms of financing, it provides refinance support to banks and housing finance institutions, thereby im- proving credit availability for affordable housing projects. Addi- tionally, it focuses on promotion and development by encouraging innovations in housing finance and rural housing development, while also imp","PW-0923":"Statement 1 is correct : The repo rate is the rate at which commercial banks borrow money from the Reserve Bank of India (RBI) to meet their short-term liquidity needs. It is a key monetary policy tool used to control inflation and sta- bilize the economy. If RBI increases the repo rate, borrowing be- comes more expensive, reducing liquidity in the market, which helps in controlling inflation. If RBI decreases the repo rate, borrowing becomes cheaper, in- creasing liquidity and boosting economic activity. Statement 2 is incorrect : The Gini coefficient is a measure of income inequality within a population. It ranges from 0 to 1. A higher Gini coefficient signifies greater inequality, and a lower value indicates a more equal distribution of income.  0 represents perfect equality (everyone has the same income).  1 represents perfect inequality (one person has all the income, and everyone else has none). 201","PW-0924":"Nationalized Banks are banks in which the majority stake is held by the government of India. Nationalization was car- ried out in two major waves (1969 and 1980) to bring a larger portion of the banking sector under government control, with the aim of promoting social and developmental objectives. Pri- vate Sector Banks are banks in which the majority stake is held by private individuals, companies, or institutions. Option (c) is correct : Federal Bank is not a nationalized bank. It is a private sector bank headquartered in Aluva, Kerala. 202","PW-0925":"An indirect tax is one that can be partially or complete- ly shifted from the person who pays it to others. Service Tax falls under this category as it is imposed on service providers but is typically shifted to the service recipient. Other examples are: Goods and Services Tax (GST), Customs Duty, Excise Duty, Ser- vice Tax (before GST), Value Added Tax (VAT) (before GST). A direct tax is one that the taxpayer is obligated to pay directly to the government and cannot be passed on to someone else. Exam- ples include income tax and property tax. Examples of Direct Tax- es in India are Income Tax, Corporate Tax, Wealth Tax (now abolished), Capital Gains Tax,Property Tax. Service Tax was an indirect tax imposed by the Central Gov- ernment on services provided in India until it was subsumed under the Goods and Services Tax (GST) on July 1, 2017. It was introduced under the Finance Act of 1994 and was applica- ble to various services, including those offered by travel agents, restaurants, and cable providers. 203","PW-0926":"Statement 1 is correct : The National Housing Bank, the apex institution of housing finance in India. It was established on July 9, 1988, under the National Housing Bank Act of 1987. It was initially set up as a wholly-owned subsidiary of the Reserve Bank of India (RBI). However, in 2019, the ownership structure of NHB underwent a significant change. The Government of India acquired the entire stake from the RBI, making NHB a wholly-owned entity of the Government. Given that the question pertains to the year 2004 so the statement is correct. Statement 2 is correct : The Small Industries Development Bank of India (SIDBI) was established on April 2, 1990, through an Act of Parliament. It was initially incorporated as a whol- ly-owned subsidiary of the Industrial Development Bank of India (IDBI). The Shares of SIDBI are now held by the Gov- ernment of India and twenty-two other institutions / public sector banks / insurance companies owned or controlled by the Central Government. Its key functions are:  Serves as the Principal Financial Institution for the MSME sector.  Promotes, fina","PW-0927":"The financial institutions listed have played a significant role in the development of India’s industrial, agricultural, and rural sectors. The correct chronological sequence of their establishment based on their founding years is: IFCI (1948) → ICICI (1955) → IDBI (1964) → NABARD (1982). Institution Established Type Focus Role Industrial Finance Corporation of India (IFCI) 1948 Public Sector Non-Banking Finan- cial Company Provides long-term financing for indus- trial projects in sectors such as infrastruc- ture, manufacturing, and power One of the earliest institutions cre- ated to support industrial develop- ment in post-independence India Industrial Credit and Investment Corporation of India (ICICI) 1955 Initially a Devel- opment Financial Institution; evolved into a major private sector bank Provided medium- and long-term project financing for industrial growth; now a leading private sector bank offering a range of financial products Instrumental in financing indus- trial projects and contributing to India’s economic growth Industrial Devel- opment Bank of India (IDBI) 1964 Init","PW-0928":"The money supply in an economy refers to the total stock of money available at a given point in time. The Reserve Bank of India (RBI) publishes several measures of the money supply, namely M1, M2, M3, and M4. M3 (Broad Money) is defined as M1 plus net Time Deposits with the banking system.  Currency with the public  Demand deposits with banks  Time deposits with banks Money Type Includes Narrow/ Broad Rank (Liquid- ity) M1 Currency with public (coins, currency notes), Net demand deposits held by the public with commercial banks & other de- posits with RBI Narrow Money 1 (Most Liquid) M2 M1 + savings deposits with post office Narrow Money 2 M3 M1 + time deposits with the banking system (such as fixed deposits) Borad Money 3 M4 M3 + all deposits with post office savings organizations, excluding National Savings Cer- tificates Broad Money 4 (Least Liq- uid) 206","PW-0929":"A debt trap occurs when a country borrows addi- tional funds to pay interest on existing loans, leading to an escalating debt burden and difficulty repaying the princi- pal. This cycle results in persistent borrowing, increased fiscal deficits, and potential economic instability. Central banks and governments use interest rate policies to manage inflation and economic growth. However, if the money supply grows slower than the required funds for servicing debt, the country must rely on additional borrowing, worsening the debt situation. When a country must borrow to pay interest on its outstanding loans, it is caught in a vicious cycle of debt. This situation arises when the existing revenue streams are insufficient to cover the debt ser- vicing costs, forcing the government to take on additional debt. Option (b) is incorrect : While IMF conditionalities aim to sta- bilize the economy, they do not define a debt trap. Option (c) is incorrect : Being refused loans or aid may indicate financial distress but does not define a debt trap. Option (d) is incorrect : High interest rates can ex","PW-0930":"The Reserve Bank of India established in 1935 is a cen- tral bank carries out several functions such as: UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 294 The RBI acts as the banker to the central gover-nment, man- aging its banking transactions, including the receipt and payment of money, and facilitating the government’s borrowing program. It also manages the government’s public debt and issues govern- ment securities.  The RBI is responsible for formulating, implementing, and monitoring India’s mone-tary policy. The aim is to maintain price stability while considering the objective of economic growth.  The RBI represents the Government of India in dealings with the International Monetary Fund (IMF) and manages transactions and communications between the IMF and the country.  The RBI manages the government’s borro-wing program which includes the issuance and redem-ption of government securities, to raise funds for various public expenditures. 208","PW-0931":"Farmers get resources from various sources such as Pri- mary Agricultural Cooperative Societies, Commercial Banks, District Central Cooperative Banks (DCCB), the lead banks such as SBI and PNB, IRDP and IFFCO. Farmers also get credit from informal sources such as private money lenders.  Primary Agricultural Cooperative Societies (PACS) are grassroots-level cooperative institutions that provide short- term and medium-term loans to farmers for agricultural activities.  Commercial Banks both public and private sector banks offer a range of credit products to farmers, including crop loans and investment loans.  Regional Rural Banks (RRBs) were established to enhance rural credit, RRBs focus on providing credit to small and marginal farmers, agricultural laborers, and rural artisans.  Despite the growth of institutional credit, many farmers still rely on private money lenders, especially in regions where institutional penetration is low. Options (b), (c) and (d) are incorrect :  NABARD and the Reserve Bank of India (RBI) play crucial roles in refinancing and regulating rural credit i","PW-0932":"The Statutory Liquidity Ratio (SLR) is the mini- mum percentage of a bank’s net demand and time liabilities (NDTL) that it must maintain in the form of liquid assets such as cash, gold, or government-approved securities. This requirement ensures that banks have sufficient liquidity to meet withdrawal demands and maintain financial stability. The Re- serve Bank of India (RBI) sets and regulates the SLR to control the expansion of bank credit and ensure the solvency of banks. As of December 6, 2024, the SLR is set at 18%. The RBI has the authority to adjust this rate as part of its monetary policy toolkit. 210","PW-0933":"As of 1998, the Reserve Bank of India (RBI) operated on an accounting year spanning from July to June. This system had been in place since March 11, 1940, when the RBI transitioned its accounting period from January–December to July–June. However, in 2020, the RBI decided to align its accounting year with the Government of India’s fiscal year, which runs from April to March. This change was implemented to enhance the effectiveness of monetary policy and fiscal operations. Consequently, the accounting year 2020–21 was a transitional period of nine months, from July 2020 to March 2021. Subsequently, from April 2021 onwards, the RBI adopted the April–March accounting cycle 211","PW-0934":"The total stock of money in circulation among the public at a particular point of time is called money supply. Option (b) is correct: Broad money (M3) represents the total money supply in the economy that is readily available for spending. It includes currency with the public and various bank deposits (demand and time deposits), but not the de- posits that commercial banks hold with the RBI. Broad money (M3) in India includes:  Currency with the public: This refers to all currency notes and coins in circulation outside of banks.  Demand deposits with banks: These are checking accounts or current accounts that allow depositors to withdraw funds on demand.  Time deposits with banks: These are savings accounts or fixed deposits where funds are held for a specific period and cannot be withdrawn before maturity without penalty. “Other deposits with RBI” are a component of Reserve Mon- ey (M0), also known as high-powered money. These depos- its are held by commercial banks with the Reserve Bank of India (RBI) and are part of the monetary base. While they are important for monetary polic","PW-0935":"","PW-0936":"","PW-0937":"Statement 1 is correct : One of the primary objectives of the Goods and Services Tax (GST) is to replace multiple indirect taxes like VAT, service tax, excise duty, etc., that were levied by both the central and state governments. By creating a uniform tax structure, GST promotes the creation of a single national market, eliminating the cascading effect of taxes and simplifying the tax system. Statement 2 is incorrect : GST is a domestic tax reform aimed at simplifying the indirect tax structure within India. It primarily affects internal trade and taxation and does not have a direct impact on the Current Account Deficit (CAD), which is influ- enced by factors like imports, exports, remittances, and foreign investments. While improved efficiency might contribute indi- rectly to exports, the effect on CAD would not be drastic. Statement 3 is incorrect : While GST is expected to boost eco- nomic growth by improving tax compliance, reducing logistics costs, and promoting ease of doing business, claiming that it will enormously grow the economy to the extent that India will over- take Ch","PW-0938":"Statement 1 is incorrect : An increase in sales of a product typically results in revenue or business profits, not capital gains. Capital gains arise from the sale of an asset at a price higher than its purchase price, not from the regular sale of products. Statement 2 is correct : Capital gains can arise when the value of an asset, such as property, appreciates over time. If the prop- erty is sold at a higher price than the original purchase price, the difference is considered a capital gain. Statement 3 is correct : If the value of an asset, such as a paint- ing, increases due to factors like popularity, and you sell it for a higher price than what you paid, the difference is considered a capital gain. : A capital gain is an increase in the asset’s value or investment resulting from the asset or invest- ment’s price appreciation. The following are not included under capital assets :  Any stock, consumables or raw materials that are held for the purpose of business or profession.  Goods such as clothes or furniture or paintings which are held for personal use.  Land or there is n","PW-0939":"","PW-0940":"The share of excise duty in gross tax revenue saw a sig- nificant decline in the five years leading up to 2010. This was pri- marily due to the shift toward service tax and the rationalization of indirect taxes. The reduction in excise duty rates for essential goods, introduction of exemptions, and gradual steps toward the Goods and Services Tax (GST) framework also contributed to this trend. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 298 According to the Economic Survey 2009–10, excise duty collec- tions as a percentage of total revenue declined as the government focused on reducing cascading effects in indirect taxation to pro- mote industrial growth and exports. This shift in taxation policy marked the transition of India’s indirect tax structure to a more consumption-based taxation system. Note: If this question were asked today, excise duty has been largely replaced by GST for most goods, further reducing its con- tribution to tax revenue. 219","PW-0941":"All three taxes—Fringe Benefit Tax (FBT), Interest Tax, and Securities Transaction Tax (STT)—are classified as direct taxes, as they are levied directly on entities or individuals and cannot be passed on to others.  Fringe Benefit Tax (FBT): Introduced in 2005 and abolished in 2009, it was imposed on employers for providing fringe benefits to employees.  Interest Tax: Levied on the interest income of financial institutions, phased out in the early 2000s.  Securities Transaction Tax (STT): Imposed on the purchase or sale of securities on recognized stock exchanges since 2004. These taxes were introduced under the Income Tax Act, 1961, with the intent to simplify and broaden the taxation framework. 220","PW-0942":"The Kelkar Committee Report (2002) did not recommend raising the personal income tax exemption limit specifically for widows to Rs. 1.20 lakh. Instead, the report focused on simplifying the tax system and broadening the tax base. Key recommendations included:  Abolition of Wealth Tax to streamline the tax structure.  Elimination of standard deduction for salaried employees to simplify personal income tax calculations.  Exemption from tax on dividends and capital gains from listed equities to encourage market participation. The report emphasized promoting economic grow-th by re- ducing distortions in the tax system and encouraging compliance. 221","PW-0943":"Stamp duty is a tax levied by the state government on the transfer of property/property ownership. It is governed by Section 3 of the Indian Stamp Act, 1899. The amount of stamp duty at the time of registration depends on the value of the prop- erty. It also varies based on the location of the property, as well as whether the property is newly constructed or pre-owned. Statement 1 is correct : Stamp duties on financial transactions are levied and collected by State Governments under the Sev- enth Schedule of the Indian Constitution (State List). Statement 2 is incorrect : The revenue from stamp duties is not appropriated by the Union Government but remains a vital source of income for state governments. Stamp duties play a sig- nificant role in generating non-tax revenue for states. They are imposed on documents such as property deeds, share certifi- cates, and other financial instruments. 222","PW-0944":"An indirect tax is a tax imposed on the consumption of goods and services, rather than directly on an individual’s income. The tax is paid by the consumer as part of the price of the goods or services purchased from the seller. In case of Indirect taxes, the individual who pays the tax to the government is different from the person who ultimately bears the burden of the tax.  Customs duty and excise duty are classified as indirect taxes because their burden is ultimately passed on to consumers through the pricing of goods and services. Customs duty is levied on the import and export of goods and indirectly borne by the consumers.  Excise duty is a tax on the manufacture of goods, indirectly passed on to consumers. According to the Economic Survey 2000–01, indirect taxes like excise and customs duties formed a significant part of India’s revenue during this period.  Corporation tax is a direct tax imposed on a company’s profits.  Wealth tax is a direct tax on an individual’s or entity’s net wealth, it was abolished in 2015. 223","PW-0945":"The Minimum Alternative Tax (MAT) was intro- duced in the Union Budget for 1996–97 to ensure that com- panies with substantial book profits pay a minimum amount of tax, even if their taxable income is reduced due to exemp- tions and deductions. MAT was introduced under Section 115JB of the Income Tax Act to prevent large corporations from exploiting tax loopholes and paying little to no taxes. This initiative was crucial for ensuring tax equity and broadening the corporate tax base. The MAT rate was initially set at 7.5% of book profits and has undergone periodic revisions over the years. 225","PW-0946":"Redistribution of income is best achieved through pro- gressive taxation, where higher-income groups are taxed at a higher rate, and progressive expenditure, where govern-ment spending is directed toward social welfare programs, such as education, healthcare, and poverty alleviation. This ensures eq- uitable resource distribution and addresses income inequality. Examples include India’s National Food Security Act and subsi- dies for essential services like health and education funded by a progressive tax structure. This combination promotes social eq- uity and economic stability. Options (b), (c), and (d) are incorrect:  Regressive expenditure would widen income inequality by favoring higher-income groups.  Regressive systems, in both taxation and expenditure, would exacerbate inequality.  Regressive taxation would disproportionately burden the poor, even if expenditures are progressive. 9. PUBLIC FINANCE 227","PW-0947":"Statement 1 is correct : When a company uses its funds to acquire or upgrade physical assets, it is called Capital Expenditure (CapEx). These assets can include property, plants, buildings, technology, or equipment. CapEx is intended to pro- vide long-term benefits to the organization. Statement 2 is incorrect : When a company borrows money to be paid back at a future date with interest it is known as debt financing. It is not a capital expenditure. Equity financing is the process of raising capital through the sale of shares. It is an ex- ample of non-debt capital receipts, not revenue expenditure.  Capital Expenditure (CapEx): refers to the funds a company spends on acquiring, upgrading, or maintaining physical assets such as property, buildings, technology, machinery, or equipment. These expenditures are intended to provide long-term benefits to the company by improving its production capacity, efficiency, or overall infrastructure.  Equity Financing : Equity financing is the process of raising capital through the sale of shares. It is an example of non-debt capital receipts.  ","PW-0948":"Statement 1 is correct : In India, people save through various financial options, including bank deposits, pension funds, insurance schemes, and government securities. Some of these savings are invested in government bonds and securities, help- ing the government fund its expenditures and manage its budget shortfall. Thus a portion of household financial savings is used to support government borrowing. Statement 2 is correct : The Indian government raises money by issuing dated securities, which are long-term bonds with a fixed maturity date. Their interest rates are decided by mar- ket demand and supply. The government sells these securities through auctions, where banks, financial institutions, and inves- tors place bids. These bonds make up a large part of the govern- ment’s internal debt, which is the money it owes to lenders with- in the country. The share of marketable securities in internal debt is at 76.4 per cent at end-March 2023 which is slightly moderate relative to 76.9 per cent at end-March 2022. The share of dated securities in public debt stood at 66.3 per cent at end","PW-0949":"","PW-0950":"Non-financial debt refers to the debt owed by entities that are not part of the financial sector, such as households, busi- nesses, and government bodies. This type of debt includes vari- ous forms of borrowing, such as housing loans, credit card bal- ances, and government-issued instruments like Treasury bills.  Housing Loans : Housing loans taken by house-holds are considered non-financial debt because they involve borrowing money for the purchase of property, which is a physical asset. These loans are typically not tied to financial assets like stocks or bonds.  Credit Card Debt : The amounts owed on credit cards are also considered non-financial debt. Credit card debt is a form of borrowing, but it is not related to financial assets, rather to consumption or goods and services.  Treasury Bills : Treasury bills are short-term borrowing instruments issued by the government to generate funds. Since they are issued by the government, which is outside the financial sector, they also fall under the category of non- financial debt. 231","PW-0951":"In 2016, India introduced a 6% Equalization Levy tar- geting income from online advertisement services provided by non-resident entities to Indian businesses. This measure aimed to tax digital transactions and level the playing field between do- mestic and foreign service providers. In 2020 it was expanded to include a 2% levy on e-commerce transactions by non-resident operators. Statement 1 is incorrect: The Equalization Levy was intro- duced through the Finance Act, 2016 as a separate chapter and is not part of the Income Tax Act. This distinction ensures that the levy operates independently of the existing income tax framework. Statement 2 is incorrect: Non-resident entities cannot claim a tax credit for this levy in their home countries which can po- tentially lead to double taxation. It doesn’t fall within the scope of Double Taxation Avoidance Agreements (DTAAs). Its ex- clusion from the Income Tax Act raises challenges regarding in- ternational tax credits and potential double taxation for foreign entities. 232","PW-0952":"Statement 1 is incorrect : While there was some in- crease in tax revenue from 2014 to 2018, the growth was not always steady and was subject to fluctuations, especially due to changes in the economy and tax reforms like GST in 2017. There- fore, there was an overall increase, but it wasn’t a steady rise. Statement 2 is incorrect : Fiscal deficit as a percent of GDP of India has not steadily increased in the last decade. Fig: Tax Revenue as a percentage of GDP. SUPER HINT Key directive: “steadily increased” This is an absolute qualifier — and UPSC loves to trap you with words like: “always”, “never”, “steadily”, “continuously”, “entirely”, etc. So both statements become highly suspect and likely false. 233","PW-0953":"A budget deficit occurs when government expenses ex- ceed revenue. It can be used as an indicator of the financial health of a country. It is a term more commonly used to refer to govern- ment spending and receipts rather than businesses or individu- als. When a budget deficit occurs, it means that the current expenses surpass the income generated from regular operations. To cor- rect its nation’s budget deficit, often referred to as a fiscal deficit, a government may cut back on certain expenditures or increase revenue-generating activities. Statement 1 is correct : Reducing the revenue expenditure will certainly help in bridging the gap. Reducing revenue expenditure (such as government spending on salaries, interest payments, and subsidies) directly reduces the fiscal deficit. By controlling unproductive expenditure, the government can balance its bud- get more effectively. Statement 2 is incorrect : Introducing new welfare schemes will most likely result in increasing expenditure and so will ex- panding industries which would require capital infusion. These steps will increase the","PW-0954":"Capital Budget consists of capital receipts (like disin- vestment, borrowing, loans from public or foreign governments, Reserve Bank of India, etc) and capital expenditure (like ex- penditure on development of machinery, health facilities, etc). Capital budgeting implies setting targets for projects/schemes to ensure maximum profitability. Statement 1 is correct : Capital Expenditure includes the expen- diture on the acquisition of land, building, machinery, equipment, creating assets such as roads and hospitals, repayment of govern- ment borrowings. Statement 2 is correct : Capital receipts components are Loan borrowings, disinvestments, funds received from the issue of shares or debentures, etc. Statement 3 is correct : Loans, and advances by the central gov- ernment to state and union territory governments, etc. are also included in the capital budget of the Government of India. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 302 The capital budget is divided into two parts i.e. capital re- ceipts and capital expenditure.  Capital Receipts : Capital receipts refer to incoming cash flows. They can be both n","PW-0955":"Statement 1 is incorrect : The Financial Stability and Development Council (FSDC) was set up by the government in December 2010. It serves as the top forum for financial matters. The FSDC was established well before the NITI Aayog came into existence. Statement 2 is correct: The Chairman of the Financial Stability and Development Council (FSDC) is the Union Finance Minis- ter. Statement 3 is correct : The Council monitors macro-prudential supervision of the economy, which includes functioning of large financial conglomerates. The Chairman of the Financial Stability and Development Council (FSDC) is the Union Finance Minister and its mem- bers include :  The heads of financial sector Regulators (RBI, SEBI, PFRDA & IRDAI)  Finance Secretary and/or Secretary, Department of Economic Affairs,  Secretary, Department of Financial Services,  Chief Economic Adviser. The Council can invite experts to its meeting if required. Functions of the FSDC:  To improve inter-regulatory coordination, institu-tionalise financial sector development, and strengthen the system for preserving financial s","PW-0956":"The Fourteen Finance Commission was consti-tuted (FFC) by the President on January 2, 2013 under chairmanship of Dr. Y. V. Reddy to give recommendations on specified aspects of Centre-State fiscal relations during 2015-2020. The Commission submitted its report to the President on December 15, 2014. Statement 1 is correct: The Fourteenth Finance Commission has radically enhanced the share of the states in the central divis- ible pool from the current 32% to 42% which is the biggest ever increase in vertical tax devolution. Statement 2 is incorrect : Unlike the thirteenth Finance Com- mission, the Fourteenth Finance Commission did not make any recommendation concerning sector specific-grants. Recently, The Sixteenth Finance Commission of India was es- tablished under Article 280 of the Constitution to recommend the distribution of tax revenues between the Union and the States for the five-year period commencing April 1, 2026. Terms of Reference for the Sixteenth Finance Commission: The 16th Finance Commission shall make recommendations as to the following matters, namely : i. The distr","PW-0957":"Statement 1 is incorrect : The budget is prepared by the Department of Economic Affairs. The Budget Division under Department of Economic Affairs is responsible for the preparation and submission to Parliament of the Central Govern- ments Budget other than Railways, as well as the supplementary Demands for Grants and Demands for Excess Grants. The Department of Revenue plays a key role in managing In- dia’s financial resources by overseeing tax collection and enforc- ing economic laws. It is responsible for collecting both direct taxes (such as income tax and wealth tax) and indirect taxes (like GST, customs duty, and excise duty). It does not prepare budget. Statement 2 is correct : Consolidated Fund of India (Article 266) is a fund to which all receipts are credited and all payments are debited. No money out of this fund can be appropriated (is- sued or drawn) except in accordance with parliamentary law. Statement 3 is incorrect : Provident fund deposits, savings bank deposits, remittances etc are credited to the Public Account. The Public Account is operated by the executive actio","PW-0958":"A tax-to-GDP ratio is a gauge of a nation’s tax revenue relative to the size of its economy as measured by gross domestic product (GDP). Statement 1 is correct : A decrease in the tax-to-GDP ratio may indicate that the government is collecting less tax revenue relative to the size of the economy. This can happen due to slow- ing economic growth, which reduces corporate profits, incomes, and consumption, leading to lower tax collections. However, this is not always the case, as tax policy changes (like tax cuts) can also reduce the ratio without reflecting economic slowdown. Statement 2 is incorrect : A decrease in the tax-to-GDP ratio does not necessarily indicate less equitable distribution of na- tional income. While lower tax revenue relative to the size of the economy could result from tax cuts, evasion, or shifts toward in- direct taxes, these factors do not directly determine income in- equality. The impact on equity depends on the structure of the tax system and government policies—if the decline stems from broad-based tax cuts benefiting all income groups, it may not af- fect","PW-0959":"The State Finance Commission (SFC) is the authority responsible for making recommendations to the Governor of a State regarding the principles for determining the taxes, duties, tolls, and fees that may be assigned to or appropriat- ed by the Panchayats (local self-governments) in that State. It is constituted under Article 243-I of the Indian Constitution by the Governor of each state. It makes recommendations re- garding the distribution of financial resources between the State Government and the Panchayati Raj Institutions (PRIs), including the principles for: 1. Determining taxes, duties, tolls, and fees to be assigned or appropriated by Panchayats. 2. Grants-in-aid to the Panchayats from the state’s consolidated fund. 3. Measures to improve the financial position of Panchayats. 240","PW-0960":"A fiscal stimulus refers to government measures aimed at boosting economic activity during periods of recession or economic downturn. These measures typically involve either increasing government spending, reducing taxes, or both, to en- hance aggregate demand and mitigate the effects of a recession. Statement 1 is correct: Reducing tax rates increases dis- posable income for individuals and businesses, encouraging higher consumption and investment. This surge in spending can stimulate economic activity. Statement 2 is correct: Increasing government expenditures directly injects money into the economy, leading to increased de- mand for goods and services. This can result in job creation and heightened economic output. Statement 3 is incorrect : Abolishing subsidies can lead to higher prices for certain goods and services, potentially re- ducing consumer spending. During a recession, this could fur- ther suppress demand, counteracting stimulative efforts. 241","PW-0961":"","PW-0962":"Fiscal deficit refers to the gap between the govern- ment’s total expenditure and its total revenue, excluding money from borrowings. Statement 1 is incorrect: FDI involves investment from for- eign entities into domestic businesses and assets. While FDI can stimulate economic growth, enhance infrastructure, and create jobs, it does not directly impact the fiscal deficit. This is because FDI pertains to the private sector and doesn’t directly alter government revenues or expenditures. Statement 2 is incorrect: Privatization of higher educational institutions may reduce the govern-ment’s expenditure on education but it is not a direct or widely accepted measure to control fiscal deficit. Statement 3 is correct: Reducing the size of the bureaucracy directly cuts government expenditure on salaries, pensions, and administrative costs. This is a valid measure to control fis- cal deficit as it reduces the government’s recurring expenditure. Statement 4 is correct: Selling or offloading shares of PSUs (disinvestment) is a direct measure to increase govern- ment revenue. The proceeds from di","PW-0963":"The Indira Gandhi National Old Age Pension Scheme (IGNOAPS) is a part of the National Social Assistance Pro- gramme (NSAP) launched by the Government of India to sup- port elderly individuals from below-poverty-line (BPL) house- holds. Statement 1 is incorrect: The scheme is applicable to individu- als aged 60 years or above who belong to BPL households. How- ever the eligibility is not restricted to rural areas alone as it encompasses both rural and urban BPL households. Statement 2 is incorrect : The central assistance provided under IGNOAPS is ₹200(not 300) per month for beneficia- ries aged between 60 to 79 years and ₹500 per month for those aged 80 years and above. States are encouraged to contribute an equivalent or higher amount to enhance the pension received by the beneficiaries. 244","PW-0964":"As per the Economic Survey 2001–02, the fiscal deficit and interest payments remain key challenges in public finance management. Indian Economy 305 Statement 1 is correct : The Union Budget reports external debt at historical exchange rates, meaning the exchange rates prevailing at the time the debt was incurred. This method reflects the original cost of the debt in domestic curren- cy terms. Statement 2 is correct : Persistent high government borrow- ing can lead to an increase in real interest rates. This occurs because substantial borrowing may crowd out private invest- ment, leading to higher demand for available funds and elevated interest rates. Statement 3 is correct : An increasing Fiscal Deficit to GDP ratio indicates that the government is borrowing more relative to the size of the economy. This can crowd out private investment by reducing the funds available for private entities and potentially increasing interest rates, making borrowing more expensive for businesses. Statement 4 is correct : Non-plan revenue expen-diture in- cludes obligatory expenses such as interest pay","PW-0965":"Assertion (A) is true: The fiscal deficit is the differ- ence between the government’s total expenditure and its total non-debt receipts (revenue receipts plus non-debt capital re- ceipts). It represents the total borrowing requirement of the gov- ernment. Budgetary Deficit can be termed as the excess of the total government expenditure over the total revenue generated in a financial year. The fiscal deficit is always greater than or equal to the bud- getary deficit. This is because the fiscal deficit includes all borrowings, while the budgetary deficit only looks at the gap in the revenue account. The fiscal deficit includes borro-wing to finance capital expenditure (investments in infrastructure, etc.), which is not part of the revenue account. Reason (R) is false: This is because the fiscal deficit is not solely borrowing from the Reserve Bank of India. It includes borrowing from the public, financial institutions, and external sources, as well as other liabilities like market loans and secu- rities. 248","PW-0966":"Option (d) is correct: Non-plan expenditure refers to all recurring and obligatory expenses of the government, which are not associated with specific planned development projects. It includes:  Defence expenditure: A significant part of non-plan expenditure allocated for maintaining the country’s security.  Subsidies: Expenditures on subsidies like food, fertilizers, and petroleum products are non-plan in nature.  Expenditures linked to previous plans: Commitments made during past plan periods, like spillovers of plan projects, also fall under non-plan expenditure.  Interest payments: Payments on borrowings are a substantial component of non-plan expenditure and have consistently been the largest contributor. 10. EXTERNAL SECTOR OF INDIA 249","PW-0967":"Rapid Financing Instrument (RFI) and Rapid Credit Facility (RCF) are instruments of the International Monetary Fund (IMF) which provides financial assistance to the countries in need.  Rapid Financing Instrument (RFI) : The Rapid Financing Instrument (RFI) provides rapid financial assistance, which is available to any IMF member countries facing an urgent balance of payment needs. The RFI was created as UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 306 part of a broader reform to make the IMF’s financial support more flexible to address the diverse needs of member countries. It is one of the facilities under the General Resources Account (GRA) that provide financial support to countries, including in times of crisis.  Rapid Credit Facility (RCF): The Rapid Credit Facility (RCF) provides rapid concessional financial assistance to low-income countries (LICs) facing an urgent Balance of Payments (BoP) need with no ex post conditionality where a full-fledged economic program is neither necessary nor feasible. The RCF was created under the Poverty Reduction and Growth Trust (PRGT) as part of a broader reform to","PW-0968":"Statement 1 is correct: The Nominal Effective Ex- change Rate (NEER) is an unadjusted weighted average rate at which a country’s currency exchanges for a basket of multi- ple foreign currencies. An increase in NEER signifies that the domestic currency has strengthened or appreciated relative to the selected basket of foreign currencies. An increase in NEER means that, on average, the rupee has become more valuable relative to those other currencies. It takes more of the foreign currencies to buy one unit of the rupee. Statement 2 is incorrect: Real Effective Exchange Rate (REER) is a measure of a country’s currency value relative to a basket of other currencies adjusted for inflation differentials. An increase in REER implies that the domestic currency has ap- preciated in real terms, making exports more expensive and im- ports cheaper. Consequently, a higher REER indicates a loss in trade competitiveness, not an improvement. Statement 3 is correct : If domestic inflation is higher than inflation in other countries, the REER will appreciate (be- come more expensive) even if the NEER ","PW-0969":"Statement 1 is correct: A tight monetary policy by the US Federal Reserve typically involves incre-asing interest rates to control inflation. Higher US interest rates can attract investors seeking better returns which can lead to capital outflows from emerging markets as investors move their funds to the US. This phenomenon is known as capital flight. Statement 2 is correct: Capital flight can lead to the depre- ciation of the domestic currency as investors sell off local assets. For firms with ECBs(loans in foreign currency) denom- inated in foreign currencies, a weaker domestic currency means that more local currency is required to service the same amount of foreign debt, effectively increasing the interest cost and principal repayments in domestic currency terms. Statement 3 is incorrect : Devaluation increases(not de- creases) the currency risk associated with ECBs. If a firm has borrowed in a foreign currency and the domestic currency is devalued, the firm will have to pay more in domestic currency terms to repay the loan. This increases the burden of the debt and the currency r","PW-0970":"Statement 1 is correct : Devaluation is a decrease in the value of a country’s currency relative to other cur- rencies. It means it takes more of the domestic currency to buy one unit of a foreign currency. For example, if the exchange rate changes from ₹70 to ₹80 per dollar, the rupee has been deval- ued. Devaluation makes a country’s exports cheaper for foreign buyers. This can increase demand for exports, leading to higher export volumes and potentially improving the trade balance (ex- ports minus imports). Statement 2 is incorrect : Devaluation means a decrease(not increase) in the value of the domestic currency relative to foreign currencies. It takes more of the domestic currency to buy one unit of a foreign currency. Statement 3 is incorrect : Devaluation can potentially im- prove the trade balance over time by boosting exports and reducing imports, but it is not guaranteed. The trade balance may deteriorate because import costs rise immediately, while export volumes may take time to increase. This phenomenon is called the J-curve effect. If a country devalues its currency, it","PW-0971":"Foreign Direct Investment (FDI) refers to an invest- ment made by an entity (typically a company or individual) from one country into a business or asset in another country, with the intent of establishing a lasting interest and exerting a degree of influence over the enterprise’s management and operations. It’s not just about a financial transaction but more about substantial and enduring involvement.  Foreign currency convertible bonds (FCCBs) are debt instruments issued by a company in a foreign currency, which can be converted into equity shares at a future date. Because FCCBs can be converted into equity, and thus represent a potential ownership stake so They are considered a component of FDI.  Foreign Institutional Investment (FII) are inves-tments made by foreign institutions in the financial markets of another country. In India, if an FII’s investment exceeds 10% of the post-issue paid-up equity capital of a company, it is reclassified as FD  Global Depository Receipts (GDRs) are financial instruments used by companies to raise capital from international markets. They repr","PW-0972":"Statement 1 is correct : India has historically faced a trade deficit in merchandise trade, meaning that the value of merchandise imports exceeds the value of merchandise exports. This is primarily due to India’s reliance on imports of crude oil, gold, electronics, and machinery, which are higher in value compared to its exports of textiles, gems, jewelry, and phar- maceuticals. Statement 2 is incorrect : India’s imports of iron and steel, chemicals, fertilisers, and machinery have not decreased in recent years. These imports have remained significant due to domestic demand and industrial requirements. For example, India imports a large quantity of fertilisers to meet agricultural needs and machinery for industrial and infrastructure develop- ment. Statement 3 is correct : India has a surplus in services trade, meaning that the value of services exports (e.g., IT services, software, business process outsourcing) exceeds the value of services imports. The services sector is a major contributor to India’s economy and helps offset the trade deficit in merchan- dise trade. Statement 4 is","PW-0973":"Statement 1 is correct : As of 2023 the Asian Infra- structure Investment Bank (AIIB) had 105 member's. As of January 2025 the AIIB boasts 110 approved members worldwide which indicates its extensive global reach. Statement 2 is incorrect : India is the second-largest share- holder in AIIB and holds 7.5% of the voting shares. The largest shareholder is China with 26.5% of the voting shares. Statement 3 is incorrect : The AIIB’s membership extends be- yond Asia and includes countries from Europe, Africa and the Americas. For instance nations like Canada, Egypt, and France are members and reflects the bank’s global appeal. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 308 SUPER HINT S1 and S2 itself contradicts, an organ of NITI and headed by FM, hence either is clearly false, eliminating options A and D. The name \"\"Financial stability\" make the proba- bilty of S2 being true more. 256","PW-0974":"A currency crisis occurs when a country’s currency faces a sudden and sharp depreciation, often due to specu- lative attacks or a loss of confidence in the economy. Several factors can contribute to reducing the risk of such a crisis: Statement 1 is correct : India’s Information Technology (IT) sector is a major exporter of services, earning substantial foreign exchange. These earnings increase the supply of foreign currency in the country, strengthening the Indian rupee and mit- igating the risk of a currency crisis. Statement 2 is incorrect : While government spending is crucial for economic growth, excessive expenditure can lead to higher fiscal deficits. This may result in increased borrowing, poten- tial inflationary pressures, and could negatively affect in- vestor confidence, thereby increasing the risk of a currency crisis. Statement 3 is correct : Remittances are funds sent by Indians working overseas back to India. These inflows add to the coun- try’s foreign exchange reserves, providing a buffer against currency volatility and reducing the risk of a currency crisis. 257","PW-0975":"Statement 1 is incorrect : While the government does hold a portion of India’s external debt, the majority of it is owed by non-governmental entities, primarily corpora- tions. As of end-March 2023, India’s total external debt stood at approximately USD 624.7 billion. Of this, the government’s ex- ternal debt was about USD 130.8 billion, accounting for roughly 20.9% of the total external debt. The remaining 79.1% is owed by non-governmental entities, including private sector corporations and financial institutions. Statement 2 is incorrect : While a significant portion of In- dia’s external debt is indeed denominated in US dollars, it’s not all in US dollars. Indian entities also borrow in other currencies, such as Euros, Japanese Yen, and British Pounds, among others. Diversification of currency exposure is a com- mon practice in debt management. India’s external debt is de- nominated in various currencies. As of end-March 2023, 53.1% of the debt was in US dollars, 31.1% in Indian rupees, 5.7% in Japanese yen, 3.5% in Special Drawing Rights (SDRs), 2.9% in eu- ros, and the remaining","PW-0976":"Statement 1 is correct: PPP is an economic concept that compares the value of currencies by examining the cost of a standard “basket of goods” across different countries. It determines the exchange rate required for one currency to buy the same quantity of goods and services as it would in another country. Statement 2 is incorrect: As of the latest available data, India ranks as the third-largest economy globally in terms of GDP based on PPP. According to the International Monetary Fund’s World Economic Outlook, India’s GDP (PPP) is approximately $13.17 trillion, placing it behind China and the United States. 259","PW-0977":"India enacted the Geogra-phical Indications of Goods (Registration and Protection) Act, 1999, to comply with its obligations under the World Trade Organization (WTO). As a member of the WTO, India is bound by the Agreement on Trade-Related Aspects of Intellectual Prop- erty Rights (TRIPS), which sets minimum standards for the protection of various forms of intellectual property, includ- ing geographical indications (GIs). TRIPS Agreement prescribe the minimum standards of protection that WTO members must provide for GIs. These provisions require member countries to prevent the misuse of GIs and to ensure that only authorized us- ers can use a GI on products originating from the specified region 260","PW-0978":"Statement 1 is correct: The National Intellectual Property Rights (IPR) Policy of India, adopted in 2016, serves as a comprehensive vision document to guide the future de- velopment of IPRs in the country. The policy reaffirms In- dia’s dedication to international agreements, including the Doha Development Agenda and the TRIPS Agreement. This commitment ensures that India’s IPR framework aligns with global standards and obligations. Indian Economy 309 Statement 2 is correct: The Department for Promotion of In- dustry and Internal Trade (DPIIT), formerly known as the Department of Industrial Policy and Promotion (DIPP), un- der the Ministry of Commerce and Industry, is designated as the nodal agency for regulating intellectual property rights in India. DPIIT is responsible for overseeing the implementation and enforcement of IPR laws and policies. 261","PW-0979":"Statement 1 is incorrect : The New Development Bank (NDB) was not set up by APEC (Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation). It was established by the BRICS nations (Brazil, Russia, India, China, and South Africa) in 2014 during the 6th BRICS Summit in Fortaleza, Brazil. APEC is a regional econom- ic forum comprising 21 Pacific Rim member economies. Statement 2 is correct : The headquarters of the New Devel- opment Bank is in Shanghai, China. The bank became opera- tional in 2015 and focuses on infrastructure and sustainable development projects in BRICS and other emerging economies. The headquarters was designed with a focus on innovation, effi- ciency, and sustainability which reflects the bank’s commitment to sustainable development. 262","PW-0980":"‘Import cover’ refers to the duration (typically mea- sured in months) that a country’s foreign exchange reserves can sustain its current level of imports. This metric is crucial for assessing a nation’s external vulnerability and economic sta- bility. To calculate import cover, the total foreign exchange re- serves are divided by the average monthly import expenditure. For instance, if a country has foreign exchange reserves of $60 billion and its average monthly imports amount to $10 billion, the import cover would be 6 months. A higher import cover in- dicates a stronger buffer against external economic shocks, as the country can continue to fund its import needs even during periods of reduced foreign exchange inflows. Conversely, a low- er import cover suggests greater vulnerability to external pres- sures, such as fluctuations in global commodity prices or capital outflows. 263","PW-0981":"The terms Amber Box, Blue Box, and Green Box are classifications used within the framework of the World Trade Organization (WTO) to categorize different types of agricultural subsidies based on their trade-distorting ef- fects.  Amber Box: This category includes subsidies that are considered to distort production and trade. Examples encompass measures such as price support schemes and subsidies directly related to production quantities. These are subject to reduction commitments under the WTO agreements.  Blue Box: Subsidies in this box are also trade-distorting but are conditioned upon programs that limit production. For instance, direct payments under production-limiting programs fall into this category. Blue Box subsidies are exempt from reduction commitments.  Green Box: This box contains subsidies that cause minimal or no trade distortion. They are typically government-funded and do not involve price support. Examples include research funding, environmental programs, and disaster relief payments. Green Box subsidies are permitted without limits under WTO rules. 264","PW-0982":"Statement 1 is correct: The International Monetary and Financial Committee (IMFC) is a key body within the IMF struc- ture. It discusses pressing issues related to the global economy and provides guidance to the IMF on its policies and work. It plays a crucial role in shaping the IMF’s agenda and priorities. Statement 2 is correct: The World Bank participates as an observer in IMFC meetings. This allows for coordination and collaboration between the IMF and the World Bank on issues re- lated to international finance and development. Given the inter- connectedness of their work, it’s essential for both institutions to be aligned. 265","PW-0983":"The mentioned agreements and terms are related to global trade regulations under the World Trade Organiza- tion (WTO):  Agreement on Agriculture (AoA) is a WTO agreement that sets international rules for agricultural trade, subsidies, and market access. It aims to reduce trade barriers and promote fair competition in agriculture. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 310  Agreement on the Application of Sanitary and Phytosanitary (SPS) Measures: It establishes rules for food safety and animal and plant health standards in global trade. It ensures that countries do not use health measures as a disguised trade barrier.  Peace Clause: It was introduced under the WTO’s Agreement on Agriculture. It temporarily protected agricultural subsidies from legal challenges under WTO rules. It was a major issue in India’s food security concerns at WTO negotiations. 266","PW-0984":"Statement 1 is incorrect : The rate of growth of Real Gross Domestic Product (GDP) in India has not steadily in- creased over the last decade (2005-2015). Instead, it has experienced fluctuations due to various factors such as global economic conditions, domestic policy changes, and structural reforms. For example: India experienced high GDP growth rates during the mid-2000s (around 9% in 2007-2008). The growth rate declined significantly during the global financial crisis of 2008-2009. Post-2010, growth rates recovered but re- mained volatile, with a slowdown in recent years due to factors like demonetization (2016) and the introduction of the Goods and Services Tax (GST) in 2017. Statement 2 is correct : Gross domestic product at market prices is the sum of added values of all activities which produce goods and services, plus taxes and minus subsidies on products. When measured in nominal terms (i.e., at current market prices without adjusting for inflation), India’s GDP in rupees has shown a consistent upward trend over the past decade. This steady increase reflects the overall ex","PW-0985":"Statement 1 is correct : Budget deficit is used to define a status of financial health in which expenditures ex- ceed revenue. Revenue Expenditure is the part of government spending that does not result in the production of assets such as Salaries, wages, pensions, subsidies, and interest payments etc. Reducing Revenue Expenditure involves cutting down on the government’s routine expenses, such as salaries, subsidies, and administrative costs. By streamlining operations and elimi- nating wasteful spending, the government can lower its rev- enue expenditure and reduce the budget deficit. Statement 3 is correct : Rationalizing Subsidies entails re- viewing and possibly reducing subsidies that are inefficient or benefit higher-income groups disproportionately. By targeting subsidies more effectively, the government can decrease un- necessary spending, aiding in deficit reduction. Statements 2 and 4 are incorrect :  Introducing New Welfare Schemes without corresponding revenue sources can increase government expenditure, potentially widening the budget deficit. Therefore, this action ma","PW-0986":"Convertibility of a currency means that it can be freely exchanged for other currencies and vice versa with- out restrictions. It essentially means that there are no lim- itations on the flow of the currency in and out of the coun- try. When a currency is convertible, individuals, businesses, and investors can easily convert it to other currencies to make pay- ments abroad, invest in foreign assets, or engage in other inter- national transactions. Similarly, they can convert foreign curren- cies back into the domestic currency. India has current account convertibility, meaning that there are generally no restrictions on converting rupees for trade-related purposes. There are some regulations on capital account transactions, although these have been progressively liberalized over time. 269","PW-0987":"International liquidity refers to the availability of acceptable means of payment for international transactions. It’s essentially about having enough of the currencies that are widely used and accepted in global trade and finance. Historically, gold played this role, but in the modern era, “hard currencies,” particularly the US dollar, have become the primary reserve currencies and mediums of exchange for international transactions. The “problem of international liquidity” arises when there is a shortage of these hard currencies. If countries don’t have enough dollars (or other widely accepted currencies) to pay for their imports, service their debts, or invest abroad, it can disrupt international trade and financial flows. Indian Economy 311 270","PW-0988":"Planned expenditures are defined as the ex- pend-iture on the programmes that are mentioned in our country’s current five-year plan. For example, electricity, wa- ter, communication, transportation, agriculture and other activi- ties, social services, etc. In simple terms, the Expenditure Report shows the expenditures made by Central Aid for state and federal needs and items under the Central Plan. In the context of the Union Budget of India, Non-Plan Expen- diture refers to all expenditures of the government that are not part of the Five-Year Plans. This classification was used prior to 2017, after which the distinction between Plan and Non- Plan Expenditure was removed. Non-Plan Expenditure includes both developmental and non-developmental spending and is of- ten obligatory in nature. The major components of Non-Plan Expenditure are: 1. Defence Expenditure: This includes spending on the armed forces, procurement of defense equipment, and other related activities. 2. Interest Payments: These are payments made by the government to service its debt, both domestic and foreign. 3. Salar","PW-0989":"The balance of payment(BoP) is a record of all mon- etary transactions made between the residents of one country and the rest of the world. A balance of payments deficit means the nation imports more than it exports. The current account and capital account are the two components that constitute the bal- ance of payments. Option (c) is correct: The Current Account of a country’s Bal- ance of Payments (BoP) records the transactions of goods, ser- vices, income, and current transfers between residents and non-residents. It comprises the following components:  Balance of Trade (Goods): This is the difference between the value of a country’s exports and imports of tangible goods.  Balance of Invisibles:  Services: Transactions involving services such as tourism, banking, and consulting.  Income: Earnings from investments abroad (like interest and dividends) minus payments made to foreign investors. Foreign assets are part of the Financial Account, which records investments in financial instru-ments and assets between coun- tries. SDRs are international reserve assets created by the In","PW-0990":"Statement 1, 2 and 4 are correct : The Capital Ac- count in a country’s Balance of Payments (BoP) records the transactions that involve the transfer of capital assets and liabilities between residents and non-residents. It primarily includes:  Foreign Loans are borrowings from foreign entities by the government, private sector, or other institutions.  Foreign Direct Investment (FDI) made by foreign entities in the domestic economy, typically involving a significant degree of control or influence over the business operations.  Portfolio Investment in financial assets such as stocks and bonds by foreign investors, without the intention of controlling or managing the enterprise. Statement 3 is incorrect : Private remittances (money sent by individuals working abroad back to their home country) are considered current transfers and are part of the Current Account, not the Capital Account. They represent a flow of in- come, not a capital investment. Current Account Capital Account Meaning  Records imports and exports of visible and invisibles  Short term implication transactions  Cov","PW-0991":"","PW-0992":"Foreign Direct Investment (FDI) refers to an invest- ment made by an individual or entity from one country into business interests located in another country, with the in- tent of establishing a lasting interest. This typically involves acquiring a significant degree of influence or control over the foreign company’s operations. In the context of India, FDI in- cludes:  Subsidiaries of Foreign Companies in India are companies incorporated in India that are wholly or majority-owned by foreign parent companies.  Majority Foreign Equity Holding in Indian Companies occurs when foreign investors hold more than 50% equity in an Indian company, granting them significant control over its operations.  Companies Exclusively Financed by Foreign Companies are entities in India that receive all their capital from foreign investors or parent companies, leading to substantial foreign control. On the other hand, Portfolio Investment refers to invest- ments in a country’s financial assets, such as stocks and bonds, without the intent of controlling or managing the companies. Such investments are t","PW-0993":"Statement 1 is incorrect : The World Bank does not determine currency exchange rates; these are influenced by market forces and economic indicators. The World Bank is important to the source of financial and technical assistance to developing countries around the world. Statement 2 is correct: A major factor influencing a curren- cy’s value is the demand for the goods and services that a country offers. If there’s high global demand for a country’s ex- ports, there will be a higher demand for its currency to purchase those exports. This increased demand will generally push the currency’s value up. On the contrary if demand for a country’s goods and services is low, demand for its currency will be low, putting downward pressure on its value. Statement 3 is correct: Political stability fosters investor confidence, attracting foreign investment and strengthening the currency. Political instability can lead to capital flight and currency depreciation. Statement 4 is incorrect : While the economic potential of a country (e.g., growth prospects, productivity, and inno- vation) can influenc","PW-0994":"Exports are goods and services that are produced in one country used by another. In economic terms, when foreign nationals visit a country and spend money on goods and ser- vices—such as accommodation, food, transportation, and enter- tainment—it is considered an export for the host country. This is because the country is providing services to non-residents, resulting in an inflow of foreign currency. Therefore, the expen- ditures by foreign visitors during events like the XIX Com- monwealth Games in India are classified as exports. Indian Economy 313 277","PW-0995":"Statement 1 is correct: Devaluation makes a coun- try’s exports cheaper for foreigners and its imports more expensive. This can lead to an increase in export volumes and a decrease in import volumes, which can improve the balance of trade (the difference between exports and imports of goods). An improved trade balance can help reduce the current account deficit. Statement 2 is incorrect : Reducing export subsidies can make a country’s exports less competitive internationally, potentially decreasing export volumes and worsening the current account deficit. Statement 3 is correct : While FDI and FII inflows are re- corded in the capital account, they can indirectly affect the current account. Increased FDI can boost domestic produc- tion capacity, leading to higher exports. FDI and FII inflows can strengthen the domestic currency, making imports cheaper and potentially widening the CAD. 278","PW-0996":"The International Development Association (IDA) is administered by the International Bank for Reconstruc- tion and Development (IBRD), which is part of the World Bank Group. IDA provides concessional loans and grants to the world’s poorest countries to promote economic growth and re- duce poverty. It complements the efforts of IBRD, which primari- ly supports middle-income nations. Options (b), (c), and (d) are incorrect:  International Fund for Agricultural Devel-opment (IFAD): IFAD is a specialized UN agency that focuses on transforming agriculture, rural economies, and food systems. It provides funding to smallholder farmers and vulnerable rural populations to improve food security and sustainable farming practices. Unlike IDA, IFAD does not administer large-scale concessional lending programs for broad economic reforms.  United Nations Development Programme (UNDP): UNDP works on global development goals, including poverty eradication, governance, and climate action. While UNDP and IDA both support developing countries, UNDP does not administer financial assistance through conce","PW-0997":"","PW-0998":"Assertion A is true : Since Balance of Payments (BoP) includes trade in goods, services, investments, and financial transfers, it offers a more accurate reflection of a country’s international economic engagement than just Balance of Trade (BoT) , which only captures the net export-import balance. Reason R is true : The Balance of Payments (BoP) provides a comprehensive account of a country’s international economic transactions, including both visible (goods) and invisible (ser- vices, remittances, investments) trade. In contrast, the Bal- ance of Trade (BoT) only considers the difference between exports and imports of goods, making it a less complete mea- sure of a nation’s financial standing. Thus, both A and R are true, and R correctly explains A. 283","PW-0999":"Full Convertibility refers to a currency’s ability to be freely exchanged for any other currency without restrictions, both for current account transactions (like trade in goods and services) and capital account transactions (like investments and loans). Statement 1 is correct : Full convertibility means the rupee can be freely exchanged with other international currencies without restrictions on the exchange rate, allowing it to float based on market demand and supply. Statement 2 is correct : Full convertibility would enable the rupee to be directly exchanged with any foreign currency at both domestic and international financial institutions, facilitat- ing smoother global trade and investment transactions. Statement 3 is correct : A fully convertible rupee would func- tion like an international currency, allowing unrestricted movement of capital across borders, making India more integrat- ed into the global economy. 284","PW-1000":"Assertion (A) is true : According to the annual report of the Reserve Bank of India, 2000, India further liberalized for- eign exchange regulations by lowering restrictions on current account transactions under the Foreign Exchange Management Act (FEMA), allowing individuals and businesses greater access to foreign currency for trade, education, medical expenses, and travel. This move was part of India’s economic liberalization process aimed at integrating the country into global markets. Reason (R) is false: During the same period, India’s foreign currency assets were actually increasing due to a steady inflow of foreign direct investment (FDI), robust export growth, and rising remittances from overseas Indians. Hence, the relaxation of current account transaction limits was not due to a fall in foreign currency assets, but rather to boost economic activity and international trade. Indian Economy 315 As per the Reserve Bank of India (RBI) Annual Report 2000, the liberalization of foreign exchange transactions under FEMA was undertaken to enhance India’s trade competitiveness, while ","PW-1001":"Statement 1 is correct : The Indian rupee has been fully convertible on the current account since 1994, meaning that individuals and businesses can freely exchange rupees for foreign currency for trade, services, education, travel, and remit- tances. This was a key reform under the Liberalized Exchange Rate Management System (LERMS) and later formalized under FEMA 1999. Statement 2 is incorrect : The rupee is not fully convertible on the capital account due to restrictions on capital flows, for- eign investments, and external borrowings to prevent excessive volatility and capital flight. India follows a managed convert- ibility regime under RBI regulations. Statement 3 is incorrect : The rupee is not conve-rtible into gold, as India does not follow a gold standard. The exchange rate is determined by market forces and central bank interventions, not by a fixed gold reserve system. 286","PW-1002":"The growth rate of per capita income at current prices is higher than at constant prices because the latter accounts for inflation. Current price per capita income mea- sures total income without adjusting for inflation, meaning it reflects nominal growth. Constant price per capita income is adjusted for inflation using a base year price index, giving a more accurate picture of real income growth. Since inflation increases the price of goods and services over time, the differ- ence between nominal and real per capita income growth is due to rising price levels. For example, if nominal per capita income grows by 10% and inflation is 5%, the real (constant price) per capita income would only increase by 5% after ad- justing for inflation. For 2023-24, India’s per capita income was around ₹2.12 lakh at current prices and much lower around ₹1.15 lakh at constant prices, as per MoSPI. The gap between nominal and real growth reflects the impact of inflation, driven by rising commodity prices and global uncertainties. 287","PW-1003":"Assertion (A) is true : After the economic libe-ral- ization of 1991, India’s exports rate grew significantly, driven by policy reforms, trade liberalization, and integration with global markets. For instance, India’s merchandise exports rose from around $18 billion in 1991 to over $43 billion by 2000. This period saw increased foreign investments, removal of trade barriers, and diversification of export products, particular- ly in the IT and services sector. Reason (R) is true : One of the key policy measures undertak- en during 1991 was the devaluation of the Indian rupee by nearly 20% in two successive adjustments. This made Indi- an exports cheaper and more competitive in global markets, boosting export volumes. As per the Economic Survey 1991-92, devaluation was a crucial step in addressing India’s Balance of Payments crisis, enhancing foreign exchange reserves, and ac- celerating export-driven growth. While devaluation in 1991 contributed to making exports more competitive, the sustained increase in export growth was primarily due to broader economic reforms like trade liber- a","PW-1004":"In an open economy, national income (Y) is determined by the sum of domestic consumption (C), investment (I), gov- ernment spending (G), and net exports (X - M), where exports (X) contribute positively to income, and imports (M) reduce it. The standard macroeconomic equation for national income in an open economy is : Y = C+I+G+(X−M). This formula accounts for domestic economic activity as well as international trade. Net exports (X - M) adjust income by subtracting the value of imports, ensuring only domestically produced goods and services contribute to national income. As per the International Monetary Fund (IMF) Macroeconomic Framework, this equation is widely used in national income ac- counting for open economies, including India. 289","PW-1005":"In context of the year in which this question has been asked , The Mumbai Port is India’s largest port in terms of tonnage handled for import cargo. It has historically man- aged the highest volume of cargo, including crude oil, petro- leum products, and containerized imports, making it a crucial gateway for India’s trade. 290","PW-1006":"Assertion (A) is true : Information technology (IT) has become a key sector in India’s economy, contributing sig- nificantly to GDP, exports, and employment. The growth of IT services, software development, and business process out- sourcing (BPO) has positioned India as a global leader in the industry. Government initiatives, a large English-speaking work- force, and cost advantages have further boosted IT expansion. Reason (R) is false : While software exports are indeed a major component of India’s IT sector, the country has not tradition- ally had a strong base in hardware manufacturing. Unlike software, which flourished due to outsourcing, India’s hardware sector has remained underdeveloped due to import dependen- cy, lack of infrastructure, and high production costs. Only in recent years have initiatives like “Make in India” and the Pro- duction Linked Incentive (PLI) scheme sought to strengthen domestic hardware manufacturing. 291","PW-1007":"Assertion (A) is true : Devaluation reduces the value of a country’s currency relative to foreign currencies, making its exports cheaper and more competitive in the global market. This can lead to an increase in the demand for exports. Reason (R) is true: As the local currency weakens against for- eign currencies, goods from the devaluing country become cheaper for foreign buyers. This effectively reduces the inter- national price of these goods, resulting in increased demand for exports. For instance, after India’s 1991 devaluation, exports surged as Indian goods became more competitive globally. The Economic Survey (1991-92) confirmed that devaluation played a crucial role in boosting exports and improving India’s trade balance. Thus, Reason R correctly explains Assertion A. 292","PW-1008":"The correct order of these currencies in terms of higher value per Indian rupee (as per 1998 exchange rates) was: 1. US Dollar (USD) → Highest 2. Canadian Dollar (CAD) 3. New Zealand Dollar (NZD) 4. Hong Kong Dollar (HKD) → Lowest The US dollar had the highest exchange value, while the Hong Kong dollar was the lowest among the listed currencies. 293","PW-1009":"As of 1998 and even in current times , the largest share of India’s imports, in terms of rupee value, came from the Asia and Oceania region. This was primarily due to India’s heavy de- pendence on crude oil and petroleum imports from West Asian (Middle Eastern) countries such as Saudi Arabia, Iran, Iraq, and the UAE. Additionally, India imported electronic goods, machinery, and chemicals from East Asian economies like China, Japan, and South Korea. 295","PW-1010":"Capital Account Convertibility (CAC) allows the unre- stricted exchange of the Indian rupee with foreign currencies for transactions related to investment and financial assets, such as foreign direct investment (FDI), portfolio investment, and external borrowings. Unlike current account convertibility, which deals with trade in goods and services, Capital account convertibility enables cross-border capital flows without regulatory restrictions. India has partially implemented Capital Account Convertibility, with restrictions on foreign investments in specific sectors and external borrowings. 296","PW-1011":"As per India’s Foreign Trade Data (1994-95), the highest value of imports was:  Petroleum: India imported crude oil in large quantities to meet its growing energy needs.  Capital Goods: Machinery, equipment, and industrial tools were imported to support infrastructure and manufacturing.  Pearls & Precious Stones: India has a strong diamond and jewelry industry, which relies on imported raw materials.  Chemicals: Used in pharmaceuticals, agriculture, and industries.  Iron & Steel: Required for construction and heavy industries. In 1994-95, India’s top imports were petroleum, capital goods, and pearls and precious stones, followed by chemi- cals and iron and steel. Today, petroleum remains a key im- port, but electronics, machinery, and gold have gained prom- inence, reflecting shifts in technology and consumer demand. 11. SECURITY MARKET IN INDIA 297","PW-1012":"Option 1 is correct : Insurance companies in India can trade in both Corporate Bonds and Government Securi- ties (G-Secs). The Insurance Regulatory and Development Authority of India (IRDAI) allows insurance companies to in- vest in Government Bonds, Corporate Bonds, and Infrastructure Bonds, subject to prescribed limits. Option 2 is correct : Pension funds are allowed to invest in both government securities (G-Secs) and corporate bonds. For ex- ample, the Pension Fund Regulatory and Development Authority (PFRDA) permits pension funds under the National Pension System (NPS) to invest in Government Bonds, State Develop- ment Loans (SDLs), and Corporate Debt. Since pension funds fo- cus on long-term stability, they often prefer G-Secs, which offer secure and steady returns for retirement benefits. Option 3 is correct : Retail investors can trade in both corpo- rate bonds and government securities. The RBI’s Retail Direct Scheme enables individuals to directly buy and sell government securities. Corporate bonds are available for trading on the debt segments of BSE and NSE, and retail in","PW-1013":"A financial instrument is a contractual agreement that creates a financial asset for one party and a correspond- ing financial liability or equity instrument for another party. Options 1 and 3 are correct :  Exchange-Traded Funds (ETF) are considered financial instruments as they represent a portfolio of assets (stocks, bonds, or commodities) and are traded on stock exchanges. They are intangible assets that provide claims to future cash flows or ownership interests.  A currency swap is a financial instrument used in international finance. It involves the exchange of principal and interest payments in different currencies between two parties, helping manage foreign exchange risks. Option 2 is incorrect : Motor vehicles are not financial in- struments. They are physical assets used for transportation and do not represent any contractual claim to future cash flows or monetary value in financial markets. 299","PW-1014":"Capital markets are financial markets where long- term debt or equity-backed securities are bought and sold. They facilitate the raising of capital for businesses, governments, and other entities. Capital markets include:  Government Bond Market: Government bonds are long- term debt instruments issued by the government to finance its expenditures. They are part of the capital market because they have maturities typically longer than one year.  Stock Market: The stock market is a quintessential part of the capital market, as it deals with the buying and selling of equity shares, which represent ownership in companies. Markets Not Included in Capital Markets:  Call money market is part of the money market, not the capital market. It deals with short-term funds (typically with maturities of 1 day to 14 days) used for interbank lending and borrowing. It is used to meet short-term liquidity requirements.  Treasury bills (T-bills) are short-term debt instruments issued by the government with maturities of less than one year (usually 91 days, 182 days, or 364 days) which are part of the","PW-1015":"In finance, beta is a numerical metric that gauges a stock’s volatility in relation to overall market fluctuations. It represents systematic risk, which stems from broader market movements, rather than company-specific factors. A benchmark index like the S&P 500 is assigned a beta value of 1.0 which serves as a reference point for evaluating individual stocks:  Beta > 1.0: The stock experiences greater volatility than the market. For instance, a beta of 1.3 implies that the stock is 30% more volatile than the market.  Beta = 1.0: The stock moves in sync with the market.  Beta < 1.0: The stock is less volatile compared to the market. Investors use beta to determine how a stock contributes to the overall risk of a diversified portfolio. A higher beta indicates greater risk but also the potential for higher returns, while a lower beta signifies reduced risk and lower expected returns. This concept plays a key role in the Capital Asset Pricing Model (CAPM) which estimates an asset’s expected return based on its beta and the anticipated market returns. 303","PW-1016":"Statements 1 and 2 are correct : Inflation-Indexed Bonds is a debt market securities offered by the government to protect the savings from inflation and offer positive real rates of returns. Since Inflation-Indexed Bonds (IIBs) provide inflation protection to investors, the government can offer these bonds with lower coupon rates compared to traditional bonds. The inflation adjustment compensates for the lower fixed interest. Statement 3 is incorrect : The existing tax provisions will be applicable on interest payment and capital gains on IIBs. There will be no special tax treatment for these bonds. 304","PW-1017":"The real sector refers to the segment of the economy that is involved in the production and consumption of tangible goods and services. It includes industries such as agriculture, manufacturing, construction, mining, and services like health- care, education, and transportation. Statements 1 and 2 are correct :  Farmers harvesting their crops : This is a primary sector activity directly contributing to the production of goods (agricultural produce).  Textile mills converting raw cotton into fabrics : This is a manufacturing activity, part of the secondary sector, which also belongs to the real sector. Statements 3 and 4 are incorrect :  A commercial bank lending money to a trading company: This is a financial sector activity, involving monetary transactions rather than the production of tangible goods or services. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 320  A corporate body issuing Rupee Denominated Bonds overseas : This relates to the financial sector and capital markets, as it involves raising funds rather than producing goods or services. 305","PW-1018":"Bond yield is the return an investor gets on that bond or on a particular government security. It depends on the price of the bond which is impacted by its demand. Statement 1, 2 and 3 are correct : Factor Scenario Impact Effect on Bond Yields 1. US Federal Reserve Actions Raises Inter- est Rates Capital outflows from In- dia as US bonds become more attractive. Yields rise due to lower demand for Indian bonds. Lowers Interest Rates Capital inflows to India as Indian bonds offer better returns. Yields fall due to higher demand for Indian bonds. 2. RBI Actions Increases Repo Rates (Tightening Policy) Higher borrowing costs slow down credit growth and economic activity. Yields rise as new bonds offer higher interest. Cuts Repo Rates (Eas- ing Policy) Cheaper borrowing encourages economic activity and credit flow. Yields fall as new bonds are issued at lower rates. 3. Inflation and Short- Term Interest Rates Rising Inflation Reduces the real value of bond interest payments. Yields rise to com- pensate for inflation. Falling Inflation Improves real returns on bonds, making them more attra","PW-1019":"Statement 1 is correct : Retail investors can participate in government securities (G-Secs) like Treasury Bills (T-Bills) and Government of India Bonds through schemes such as Retail Direct Scheme facilitated by the Reserve Bank of India (RBI). This allows them to invest directly in the primary market using Demat accounts. Statement 2 is correct : The NDS-OM platform, is an electron- ic trading platform, operated by the RBI, is an anonymous or- der-matching system for secondary market trading in govern- ment securities (G-Secs) Statement 3 is incorrect : CDSL is promoted by the Bombay Stock Exchange (BSE) but not by the Reserve Bank of India. It is promoted by BSE Ltd. jointly with leading banks such as State Bank of India, Bank of India, Bank of Baroda, HDFC Bank, Stan- dard Chartered Bank and Union Bank of India. 307","PW-1020":"","PW-1021":"Financial inclusion refers to providing affordable and accessible financial services, such as savings accounts, credit, and insurance, to all segments of society, especially the under- privileged and rural populations. Statement 1 is correct: In 1969 and 1980, the Government of India nationalized several major commercial banks. This move aimed to shift the focus from “class banking” to “mass bank- ing,” thereby extending banking services to the underprivileged and rural sectors. Post-nationalization, these banks expanded their branch networks into rural areas, providing financial ser- vices to previously unbanked populations. Statement 2 is correct: RRBs were established under the Re- gional Rural Banks Act of 1976 to develop the rural economy by providing credit and other facilities to small and margin- al farmers, agricultural laborers, artisans, and small entre- preneurs. The primary objective was to bridge the credit gap in rural areas and integrate them into the formal banking system, thereby promoting financial inclusion. Statement 3 is correct: The Lead Bank Scheme, introduced","PW-1022":"","PW-1023":"Pair 1 is correctly matched : Nikkei (Japan) tracks the performance of 225 major companies listed on the Tokyo Stock Exchange. Pair 2 is incorrectly matched : The Shanghai Composite In- dex (Shcomp) is the stock market index of China, not Singa- pore. The correct index for Singapore is the Straits Times Index (STI). Pair 3 is correctly matched : FTSE (UK), The Financial Times Stock Exchange (FTSE 100) represents the 100 largest companies listed on the London Stock Exchange. Pair 4 is correctly matched : Nasdaq (USA), technology-heavy stock exchange index in the United States, tracking major firms like Apple, Google, and Microsoft. 312","PW-1024":"Participatory Notes (PNs) are financial instruments used by Foreign Institutional Investors (FIIs) to invest in Indian stock markets without direct registration with the Securities and Exchange Board of India (SEBI). These instru- ments allow overseas investors, including hedge funds, to gain ex- posure to Indian equities while bypassing regulatory procedures. PNs are issued by registered FIIs and sub-accounts against underlying Indian securities. While they provide easy access to foreign investment, concerns exist regarding lack of transpar- ency and potential misuse for money laundering.As per SEBI regulations, efforts have been made to increase transparency and reduce misuse of PNs in India’s financial markets. 313","PW-1025":"Statement 1 is incorrect : LIC is not the oldest insurance company in India. The oldest insurance company is “Oriental Life Insurance Company” (established in 1818 in Kolkata). LIC was formed later in 1956 when the government nationalized over 240 private insurance companies. Statement 2 is correct : The National Insurance Company Limited was nationalized in 1972 and became a subsidiary of the General Insurance Corporation of India (GIC). Later, it was made an independent entity. Statement 3 is correct : United India Insurance Company Limited is headquartered in Chennai and is one of the four public sector insurance companies in India. As per IRDAI (In- surance Regulatory and Development Authority of India) re- ports, these insurance companies play a key role in the country’s financial sector. 314","PW-1026":"Statement 1 is incorrect : The BSE Sensex (S&P BSE Sensex) is based on 30 of the most actively traded and financial- ly strong stocks on the Bombay Stock Exchange (BSE), not 50. Statement 2 is incorrect : In Sensex calculation, stocks are as- signed weightage based on free-float market capitalization, not proportional weightage. This means stocks with higher mar- ket capitalization and more freely tradable shares have a greater impact on the index. Statement 3 is incorrect : The New York Stock Exchange (NYSE) is one of the largest stock exchanges but not the oldest. The Amsterdam Stock Exchange (Netherlands), established in 1602, is considered the world’s oldest stock exchange. As per Bombay Stock Exchange (BSE) reports, the Sensex is wide- ly used as a benchmark index for tracking the performance of the Indian equity market. 315","PW-1027":"The services sector has attracted the highest Foreign Direct Investment (FDI) inflows into India in the decade lead- ing up to 2004. This includes banking, insurance, IT, and business process outsourcing (BPO). The liberalization of FDI norms, IT boom, and rapid urbanization contributed to significant investments in financial services, telecommunications, and IT-enabled services. As per Reserve Bank of India (RBI) and Department for Pro- motion of Industry and Internal Trade (DPIIT) reports, the services sector remained the largest recipient of FDI inflows, consistently contributing over 15-20% of total FDI inflows. India’s FDI inflows are primarily driven by key sectors like ser- vices (15-20%), computer software and hardware (15%), and telecommunications (7-8%). Other major contributors include construction (5-6%), trading (5%), automobiles (4-5%), phar- maceuticals (3-4%), and renewable energy (3-4%). Initiatives like Make in India and the PLI scheme have boosted investments, particularly in electronics, clean energy, and manufacturing. In FY 2021-22, FDI reached a record $83.57 b","PW-1028":"Debenture holders are creditors of a company as they lend money to the company in exchange for a fixed interest rate over a specified period. Unlike shareholders, they do not hold ownership rights but receive priority during liquidation over eq- uity holders. Debentures are issued to raise long-term capital and are generally backed by the company’s assets or revenue-gener- ating ability. Unlike equity shareholders, debenture holders do not have voting rights in company decisions. 317","PW-1029":"The East Asian Financial Crisis (1997) demonstrated the risks of excessive reliance on short-term portfolio invest- ments, which led to currency instability and market crashes. FDI, on the other hand, is less volatile and contributes to sustainable growth. Option (b) is correct : Among the various forms of capital in- flows, Foreign Direct Investment (FDI) is considered the most stable and beneficial for a host country’s economy. Unlike For- eign Portfolio Investment (FPI) and External Commercial Borrowings (ECB), which can lead to financial volatility, FDI brings in :  Long-term capital investments in infrastructure, manufacturing, and services.  Technology transfer and skill enhancement.  Employment generation and economic stab-ility. 318","PW-1030":"A rise in SENSEX indicates an overall increase in the stock prices of a group of 30 financially strong companies listed on the Bombay Stock Exchange (BSE). These companies are selected based on market capitalization, liquidity, and sectoral representation and are considered indicators of mar- ket performance. SENSEX movements reflect investor sentiment, economic conditions, corporate earnings, and global market trends. It does not mean that the prices of all companies listed on the BSE rise simultaneously. As per the Bombay Stock Exchange (BSE) reports, Sensex is widely used by investors and analysts to gauge India’s stock market trends and investment climate. 12. HUMAN DEVELOPMENT AND SUSTAINABLE DEVELOPMENT 319","PW-1031":"Statements 1 and 3 are correct : WaterCredit is a pow- erful solution and puts microfinance tools to work in the water and sanitation sector. It helps bring small loans to those who need access to affordable financing and expert resources to make household water and toilet solutions a reality. Statement 2 is incorrect: WaterCredit is not launched by the WHO or the World Bank. It is an initiative of Water.org, a non-profit organization co-founded by Gary White and Matt Da- mon. While it may collaborate with various global partners, it is not directly under the aegis of these organizations. SUPER HINT S2 aligns with Function-person/organisation/ministry match trap as it's easy to manipulate to make it false. What possible role does WHO and World bank can play in \"Water credits''. Isn't it a misfit? Highly plausible hence likely false. 321","PW-1032":"According to the World Bank , Poverty is pronounced deprivation in well-being and comprises many dimensions. It includes low incomes and the inability to acquire the basic goods and services necessary for survival with dignity. The new ex- treme poverty line of $2.15 per person per day, which replaces the $1.90 poverty line, is based on 2017 PPPs Option (b) is correct : The official poverty line in India is de- termined based on the minimum income required to meet basic consumption needs, primarily food, adjusted for other essentials like housing, education, and healthcare. Since the cost of living and price levels differ across states due to factors like inflation, regional disparities, and market conditions, the poverty line is higher in states where the price levels are higher. For instance, states with higher urbanization or living costs like Maharashtra or Delhi might have a higher poverty line compared to states with lower living costs like Bi- har or Odisha. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 324 According to the Planning Commission, the national poverty line for rural regions in 2011–12 wa","PW-1033":"Human capital formation refers to the process of im- proving the knowledge, skills, and capacities of people, which enhances their productivity and contributes to economic growth. This involves education, training, healthcare, and other in- vest-ments in people. Statement 2 is correct : It directly reflects the essence of human capital formation, which focuses on increasing the knowledge, skill levels, and capacities of individuals. Statement 4 is correct : Human capital is considered intangible wealth, as it represents non-physical assets like skills, education, and health, which contribute to economic productivity. Statements 1 and 3 are incorrect : These refer to the accumula- tion of physical or tangible capital (like machinery, infrastruc- ture), which is different from human capital. 323","PW-1034":"","PW-1035":"Statement 1 is incorrect : The National Career Service (NCS) is an initiative of the Directorate General of Employ- ment, Ministry of Labour and Employment, not the Depart- ment of Personnel and Training.NCS offers dynamic job match- ing, career counselling, job notifications, vocational guidance, and information on skill development courses and internships. Statement 2 is incorrect : It was launched in 2015 as a mis- sion-mode project under the E-Governance Plan. It aims to bridge the gap between job-seekers and employers, as well as candidates seeking training and career guidance and agencies providing these services. It is for everyone seeking a job not just for the uneducated. It provides career counseling as well as skill and training if needed. 325","PW-1036":"","PW-1037":"Pradhan Mantri MUDRA Yojana (PMMY) launched in 2015 by the Government of India, provides collateral-free insti- tutional loans up to Rs. 10 lakhs for small business enterprises. The scheme aims to bring enterprises into the formal finan- cial system. Mantri MUDRA Yojana (PMMY) offers three loan products:  Shishu: Loans up to Rs. 50,000  Kishore: Loans between Rs. 50,000 and Rs. 5 lakh  Tarun: Loans between Rs. 5 lakh and Rs. 10 lakh An increase in the loan limit to ₹20 lakh was announced during the Union Budget 2024-25 To strengthen support for aspiring entrepreneurs. 327","PW-1038":"","PW-1039":"Statement 1 is incorrect : The National Rural Liveli- hood Mission (NRLM) does not focus on setting up new manu- facturing industries or agribusiness centers directly. Its primary focus is on promoting self-employment and organization of the rural poor through self-help groups (SHGs). Statement 2 is correct : NRLM aims to strengthen self-help groups (SHGs) and provide skill development to enhance the livelihood options of the rural poor. Statement 3 is incorrect : NRLM does not involve the free dis- tribution of agricultural inputs like seeds, fertilizers, or irrigation equipment. These activities are covered under different agricul- tural schemes. The Deen Dayal Antyodaya Yojana – National Rural Live- lihoods Mission (NRLM), launched by the Ministry of Ru- ral Development in June 2011, is a restructured version of the Swarna Jayanti Gram Swarozgar Yojna (SGSY). It aims to strengthen institutional frameworks for the rural poor, enhancing access to financial services and sustainable liveli- hoods. The mission targets 7 crore rural poor families across 600 districts, 2.5 lakh Gram Panc","PW-1040":"Accredited Social Health Activists (ASHAs) are com- munity health workers under the National Rural Health Mis- sion (NRHM), trained to promote maternal and child health, facilitate access to healthcare services, and provide basic health education on nutrition, immunisation, and hygiene. Statement 1 is correct : ASHAs assist women in accessing healthcare facilities for antenatal check-ups, delivery, and post- natal care. Statement 2 is correct : ASHAs are trained to use pregnancy test kits for early detection and guiding women accordingly. Statement 3 is correct : One of the core responsibilities of ASHAs is to educate the community about nutrition, immunisa- tion, family planning, and hygiene. Statement 4 is incorrect : ASHAs are not trained to conduct deliveries. They are responsible for facilitating access to skilled birth attendants and institutional deliveries but do not perform the deliveries themselves. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 326 330","PW-1041":"Janani Suraksha Yojana (JSY) is a safe motherhood intervention under the National Rural Health Mission (NRHM). Statement 1 is correct : The primary goal of Janani Suraksha Yojana (JSY) is to reduce maternal and infant mortality by en- couraging pregnant women to opt for institutional deliveries in healthcare facilities, ensuring safe childbirth under professional supervision. Statement 2 is correct : JSY is a centrally sponsored scheme, which integrates cash assistance with delivery and post-de- livery care to help cover expenses related to childbirth, making institutional deliveries more accessible. Statement 3 is incorrect : JSY does not compensate for wage loss during pregnancy or confinement. Its focus is on promoting safe deliveries through financial support for delivery costs, not income replacement. 331","PW-1042":"The Employees’ State Insurance (ESI) Scheme is a social security and health insurance program for Indian work- ers, managed by the Employees’ State Insurance Corpora- tion (ESIC) under the Ministry of Labour and Employment. Launched in 1952 under the ESI Act, 1948, it provides financial protection to employees against sickness, maternity, disability, and work-related injuries. This Act applies, in the first instance, to non-seasonal factories employing 10 or more persons. Statements 1, 2, 3 and 4 are correct : The ESI Scheme ini- tially covered factories but has expanded to include hotels and restaurants, motor transport undertakings, newspaper es- tablishments, private medical institutions, shops, cinemas, educational institutions, and more. It applies to establishments with 10 or more employees (20 in some states) and covers em- ployees earning up to ₹21,000/month (₹25,000 for persons with disabilities). 332","PW-1043":"National Water Mission is one of the eight missions launched under the National Action Plan on Climate Change (NAPCC) for combating the threats of global warming. The main objective of NWM is “conservation of water, minimising wast- age and ensuring its more equitable distribution both across and within States through integrated water resources devel- opment and management”. Statements 1 and 2 are correct : It seeks to ensure that a considerable share of the water needs of urban areas are met through recycling of waste water and ensuring that the water requirements of coastal cities with inadequate alternative sources of water are met through adoption of new and ap- propriate technologies such as low temperature desalination technologies that allow for the use of ocean water. Statement 3 is incorrect : All the rivers of Himalayan origin will be linked to the rivers of peninsular India is part of the Inter- linking of Rivers Project, not the National Water Mission. Statement 4 is incorrect : The NWM focuses on water conser- vation and efficiency but does not provide reimbursements for","PW-1044":"Statement 1 is incorrect : DRDAs does not act as Pan- chayati Raj Institutions. They are autonomous bodies that coordinate rural development programs, while Panchayati Raj Institutions are separate local self-governance bodies. Statement 2 is incorrect : No such provisions are there for DRDAs to undertake an area-specific scientific study of the caus- es of poverty and malnutrition and prepare detailed remedial measures. Statement 3 is correct : One of the key roles of DRDAs is to coor- dinate efforts across sectors and departments to ensure the effective implementation of various rural development schemes. Statement 4 is correct : DRDAs are responsible for monitoring and ensuring the proper utilization of funds allocated to an- ti-poverty and rural development programs. Indian Economy 327 334","PW-1045":"Aam Admi Bima Yojana (AABY) is a Government of In- dia Social Security Scheme administered through Life Insurance Corporation of India (LIC) that provides Death and Disability cover to persons between the age group of 18 yrs to 59 yrs, un- der 48 identified vocational/ occupational groups /rural landless households. Statement 1 is correct: The scheme covers the head of the fam- ily or an earning member in a rural landless household. It provides life and disability insurance benefits to economically weaker sections. Statement 2 is incorrect: The age eligibility for this scheme is 18 to 59 years, not 30 to 65 years. It provides insurance cover for a sum of Rs 30,000/- on natural death, Rs. 75,000/- on death due to accident, Rs. 37,500/- for partial permanent disability (loss of one eye or one limb) due to accident and Rs. 75,000/- for total permanent disability (loss of two eyes or two limbs or loss of one eye and one limb) due to accident. Statement 3 is correct: The scheme provides a scholarship of ₹100 per month for up to two children of the insured, studying in classes 9 to 12. The","PW-1046":"In India, female literacy is defined as the percent- age of females aged 7 years and above who can read, write, and understand a simple message in any language. As per the 2001 Census of India, the correct sequence of the descending order of female literacy rates for the states mentioned is:  Kerala (87.86%)  Mizoram (86.75%)  Goa (75.51%)  Nagaland (61.46%) 336","PW-1047":"Statement 1 is incorrect : The Poverty Reduction and Growth Facility(PRGF) was actually established by the International Monetary Fund (IMF), not the Internation- al Development Association (IDA). The PRGF was the IMF’s concessional lending facility for low-income countries, aimed at supporting programs that foster durable growth and poverty re- duction.The PRGF focuses on promoting sustainable economic growth and reducing poverty through concessional loans with low interest rates. It has been replaced by the Poverty Re- duction and Growth Trust (PRGT). Statement 2 is correct : The Singapore Regional Training In- stitute (STI) is the International Monetary Fund’s (IMF) regional training center for the Asia-Pacific region. Established in 1998, the STI aimed at enhancing the capacity of officials from the re- gion in areas by providing training in macroeconomic analysis and policy and related subjects as a part of a programme of the IMF institute. 337","PW-1048":"The Indian Human Development Report (IHDR) does not give a separate Unemployment Related Index for each sample village. The IHDR uses a composite index ap- proach to measure human development. It combines indi- cators across key dimensions such as  Infrastructure and Amenities Index: This index reflects access to basic infrastructure like sanitation, drinking water, electricity, and other amenities that contribute to well-being.  Education Related Index: This index combines indicators related to literacy rates, school enrollment, educational attainment, and other measures of educational progress.  Health Related Index: This index includes indicators of health status, such as life expectancy, infant mortality rates, access to healthcare facilities, and other health-related measures.  Unemployment is typically analyzed as a separate factor or included as a component within broader indices (like a poverty index or a standard of living index) rather than being a standalone index at the village level. Collecting reliable and granular unemployment data at the village level across a lar","PW-1049":"Employment Assurance Scheme (EAS) was launched on 2nd October, 1993, covering all the 1778 blocks under- Revamped Public Distribution System (RPDS). These blocks Indian Economy 329 were identified mainly in DPAP, DDP, Hill and Tribal areas. The main objective of the EAS was also on the lines of JRY, i.e. to pro- vide gainful employment during lean agriculture season in the form of manual works to all able bodied adults who were in need and desirous of working, but unable to find anything to do. The assurance of 100 days of employment was extended to men and women above 18 years and below 60 years of age, re- siding in the villages of the blocks covered by EAS. A maxi- mum of two adults per family were to be provided assured employment of 100 days under the scheme. The secondary objective was to develop economic infrastructure and commu- nity assets and resources for sustained employment and devel- opment. 342","PW-1050":"Madhya Pradesh was the first Indian state to pre- pare and release its Human Development Report (HDR) in 1995, under the guidance of Professor Amartya Sen.The Madhya Pradesh HDR was a pioneering effort in India, focusing on various dimensions of human development within the state, including health, education, and standard of living. The report aimed to assess and improve the well-being of its citizens by ana- lyzing these critical areas. This initiative set a precedent for other Indian states to develop their own HDRs, contributing to a more localized understanding of human development challenges and facilitating targeted policy interventions. The Human Development Index (HDI) was introduced in 1990 by the United Nations Development Programme (UNDP) through its Human Development Report (HDR). It was con- ceptualized by economist Mahbub ul Haq and Nobel laureate Amartya Sen. The HDI was created to shift the focus of develop- ment economics from purely economic growth (e.g., GDP) to a broader measure of human well-being, encompassing health, education, and living standards. It remains ","PW-1051":"Option (b) is correct : In the 1990s, poverty rates among various social and religious groups in India exhibited significant disparities. Government statistics from that peri- od indicate that the Scheduled Tribes (STs) in states such as Bihar, Odisha (formerly Orissa), Madhya Pradesh, and Ma- harashtra experienced some of the highest levels of pover- ty. Several factors contributed to the high poverty rates among Scheduled Tribes in these states during the 1990s:  Geographical Isolation: Many ST communities resided in remote areas, limiting their access to essential services and economic opportunities.  Limited Access to Education and Healthcare: Educational and healthcare facilities were often inadequate or inaccessible, hindering human capital development.  Economic Marginalization: Dependence on traditional livelihoods, coupled with limited integration into the broader economy, exacerbated economic vulnerabilities. 344","PW-1052":"In India Persons Below Poverty Line(BPL) is classi- fied based on entitlement of a prescribed food basket mea- sured in calorie and then converted into monetary terms for easy implementation into policies and programmes.  The Planning Commission constituted a task force under the chairmanship of YK Alagh in 1979 to construct a poverty line for rural and urban areas on the basis of nutritional requirements and related consumption expenditure.  The expert group under Suresh Tendulkar in 2009 also followed the calorie approach based on a consumption basket but added health and education along the calorie consumption basket.  Another Expert group was constituted in 2014 under C Rangarajan also followed a calorie approach but suggested adding clothing, house rent, conveyance and education, and a behaviorally determined level of other non-food expenses. 345","PW-1053":"The Human Poverty Index (HPI) was introduced in the Human Development Report (HDR) 1997 by the United Nations Development Programme (UNDP). HDI (Human Devel- opment Index) measures overall development based on three parameters: life expectancy, education (mean years of school- ing and expected years of schooling), and per capita income. HPI (Human Poverty Index) focuses on deprivation in three areas:  Longevity (probability of not living beyond 40)  Knowledge (adult illiteracy rate)  Standard of living (access to clean water, healthcare, and underweight children) 346","PW-1054":"Most international agencies that fund development pro- grams in India through intergovernmental bilateral agreements primarily provide:  Technical Assistance: Many agencies offer expertise, knowledge sharing, and capacity-building support to help implement development projects effectively.  Soft Loans: A significant portion of funding comes in the form of soft loans, which are required to be paid back but with low interest rates and long repayment periods. These loans are often concessional and designed to support development without imposing a heavy financial burden.  Grants: Some agencies provide grants, which do not need to be repaid. These are typically used for social sector projects like health, education, and poverty alleviation. Only few agencies provide food assistance in some cases (e.g., during emergencies or specific programs), it is not the primary form of support from most international agencies. 13. IMPORTANT INDEX AND REPORTS 347","PW-1055":"Ease of Doing Business Index is published by the World Bank. It is an aggregate figure that includes different pa- rameters which define the ease of doing business in a country. It is calculated by adding up the distance to frontier ratings of vari- ous economies. The “regulatory best practices” for conducting business serve as the basis for the distance to frontier score, which compares economies based on that parameter. The index for ease of doing business is calculated based on the follow- ing indicators: Construction permits, registration, obtaining financing, tax payment mechanisms, etc. 348","PW-1056":"The Index of Eight Core Industries (ICI) is a month- ly production index that measures the performance of eight crucial sectors of the Indian economy. These industries collec- tively account for 40.27% of the weight of items included in the Index of Industrial Production (IIP) as of September 2024. The eight core industries and their respective weights in the ICI are as follows : Refinery Products : 28.04% Electricity : 19.85% Steel : 17.92% Coal : 10.33% Crude Oil : 8.98% Natural Gas : 6.88% Cement : 5.37% Fertilizers : 2.63% 349","PW-1057":"The World Economic Outlook (WEO) is a report by the International Monetary Fund (IMF) that analyses key parts of the IMF’s surveillance of economic developments and policies in its member countries. The World Economic Outlook (WEO) presents the IMF’s analysis and projections of global economic developments and classifies their analysis by region and stage of economic development. It is published twice a year in April and October, with updates in January and July. Other Report published by IMF: Global Financial Stability Report 350","PW-1058":"Disguised unemployment occurs when more work- ers are employed than necessary, contributing little to no additional output. In such cases, removing some workers would not impact overall productivity. This condition is commonly ob- served in the agricultural sector of developing countries, where labor redundancy is prevalent. The defining characteristic of disguised unemployment is zero marginal productivity of labor, meaning additional workers do not increase output. 351","PW-1059":"The Multidimensional Poverty Index (MPI), developed by the Oxford Poverty and Human Development Initiative (OPHI) in collaboration with the United Nations Development Pro- gramme (UNDP), is designed to measure acute poverty by evalu- ating multiple deprivations that individuals face across three key dimensions: health, education, and living standards. Statement 1 is correct : The index assesses depriv-ations in education (such as years of schooling and school atten- dance), health (including child mortality and nutrition), and living standards (evaluated through indicators like access to electricity, sanitation, drinking water, housing, cooking fuel, and asset ownership). Indian Economy 331 Statement 2 is incorrect : Purchasing power parity (PPP) is an economic metric used to compare the relative value of curren- cies and the cost of goods across countries. The MPI focuses on non-monetary deprivations at the household level and does not incorporate national-level economic indicators like PPP. Statement 3 is incorrect : Budget deficits and GDP growth rates are macroeconomic indicators","PW-1060":"The Central Statistical Organization (CSO) under the Ministry of Statistics and Programme Implementation (MoSPI) is responsible for publishing the “Energy Statistics” report from time to time. This publication provides compre- hensive data on energy production, consumption, and resources in India, covering sectors like coal, petroleum, natural gas, elec- tricity, and renewable energy. The Ministry of Statistics and Programme Implementation (MoSPI) is a government body responsible for statistical data collection, analysis, and dissemination in India. It oversees the Central Statistical Office (CSO) and the National Sample Sur- vey Office (NSSO). MoSPI publishes key reports like Economic Census, Energy Statistics, and National Accounts Statistics which aids in policy formulation and economic planning. 353. The current Price Index (base 1960) is nearly 330","PW-1061":"","PW-1062":"","PW-1063":"Statement 1 is correct : A convertible bond is a fixed-in- come corporate debt security that yields interest payments, but can be converted into a predetermined number of common stock or equity shares. Convertible bonds generally offer a lower coupon rate or rate of return in exchange for the value of the option to convert the bond into common stock. Investors will generally accept a lower coupon rate on a convertible bond, compared with the coupon rate on an otherwise identical regular bond, because of its conversion feature. Statement 2 is correct : Equity (stock) prices tend to rise with inflation. Companies’ earnings and assets often appre- ciate during inflationary periods. Therefore, the option to convert a bond into equity provides a hedge against infla- tion. If inflation rises and the company performs well, its stock price is likely to increase. The bondholder can then convert the bond into equity at a more favorable price, thus benefiting from the rising prices and protecting their investment’s real value (purchasing power). This acts as a form of indexation (linking to a p","PW-1064":"Opportunity cost: refers to the value of the next best alternative foregone when a choice is made. Even if a com- modity is provided “free” to the public, resources (such as gov- ernment funds, labor, or infrastructure) are still required for its provision. Option (c) is correct : If a commodity is provided free to the public by the Government, then the opportunity cost is trans- ferred from the cons-umers of the product to the tax-paying public. As per microeconomics, the opportunity cost is zero for free goods such as air and common goods such as fish/grazing land. For public goods such as street lights and defence, the op- portunity cost is involved (The government could have spent that much money on street lights rather than on the military). So, the opportunity cost is not zero. 357","PW-1065":"","PW-1066":"Economic growth refers to an increase in a country’s output of goods and services over time, typically measured by the rise in Gross Domestic Product (GDP). Capital formation, also known as investment, is a crucial driver of economic growth. It involves increasing the stock of capital goods (machinery, equipment, infrastructure) that are used to produce other goods and services. Capital formation necessarily leads to economic growth as:  Increased Productivity: Capital goods enhance the productivity of labor. For example, a worker with a machine can produce more than a worker without one. Increased capital stock enables workers to produce more output, leading to economic growth.  Expansion of Production Capacity: Investment in capital goods expands the economy’s ability to produce goods and services. New factories, equipment, and infrastructure allow for greater output, contributing to economic growth.  Technological Progress: Capital formation is often associated with technological progress. New capital goods often embody newer, more efficient technologies, which further boost pr","PW-1067":"","PW-1068":"The balance of payments (BoP) records the transac- tions in goods, services and assets between residents of a coun- try with the rest of the world for a specified time period typically a year. The balance of payments (BOP) also known as balance of international payments, summarises all transactions that a country’s individuals, companies, and government bodies com- plete with individuals, companies, and government bodies out- side the country. These transactions consist of imports and ex- ports of goods, services, and capital, as well as transfer payments, such as foreign aid and remittances. Indian Economy 333 361","PW-1069":"","PW-1070":"Deficit financing refers to the practice of funding government expenditure by borrowing or creating mon- ey, usually by printing currency. It involves a budget deficit, where expenditure exceeds revenue. In a developing country like India, there is a need for heavy public investment in in- frastructure, social welfare schemes, and industrial devel- opment. Deficit financing helps the government to mobilize additional resources for large-scale development projects such as roads, dams, power plants, and education systems when tax revenues fall short. During periods of recession, defi- cit financing can stimulate demand in the economy by increasing public expenditure. 363","PW-1071":"","PW-1072":"The bank rate (also known as the discount rate) is the interest rate at which commercial banks can borrow money directly from the central bank (in India’s case, the Reserve Bank of India or RBI). When the RBI lowers the bank rate, it be- comes cheaper for commercial banks to borrow funds. Low- er bank rate means banks can borrow from the RBI at a low- er interest rate. To maintain their profit margins, commercial banks then lower their own lending rates (the interest rates they charge on loans to businesses and individuals). Lower lending rates encourage borrowing by businesses and individuals. This leads to an increase in credit availability and money supply in the market. Option (b),(c) and (d) are incorrect :  A lower bank rate leads to more, not less, liquidity.  A change in the bank rate has a direct impact on market liquidity.  While lower interest rates on loans might indirectly influence deposit behavior over the long term, the direct and immediate effect of a lower bank rate is on borrowing and lending, and thus liquidity. Deposit mobilization is a separate function of co","PW-1073":"The “base effect” refers to how unusually high or low inflation in the previous period can affect the calculation and interpretation of the inflation rate in the current peri- od. It’s a statistical phenomenon, not a real economic event.  Low Base Effect: If inflation was very low or even negative in the previous year (the “base” period), even a moderate increase in prices in the current year can appear as a high inflation rate simply because the comparison is being made against a very low base. This can give the impression of a rapid acceleration of inflation, even if the price increases are not exceptionally large in absolute terms.  High Base Effect: Conversely, if inflation was very high in the previous year, even a substantial increase in prices in the current year might appear as a low inflation rate because the comparison is being made against a high base. This can mask the true extent of current price increases. 367","PW-1074":"Option (b) is correct: According to United Nations Population Fund (UNFPA), demographic dividend means, “the economic growth potential that can result from shifts in a population’s age structure, mainly when the share of the work- ing-age population (15 to 64) is larger than the non-work- ing-age share of the population (14 and younger, and 65 and older)”. 368","PW-1075":"Closed Economy  Does not have economic relations with the rest of the world.  Activities taking place outside the territory do not affect the economic activities.  There is no difference b/w national income and domestic income.  It is an imaginary economy.  A closed economy is completely self- sufficient, which means that no imports enter and no exports leave the country. Open Econ- omy  An open economy has economic relations with other countries.  Economic activities of such an economy are affected by international fluctuations.  The size of national income may be greater or smaller than the domestic income.  It is a realistic economy.  Eg: USA, Singapore, Finland, etc. 369","PW-1076":"","PW-1077":"A non-banking financial company (NBFC) is a com- pany registered under the Companies Act, 1956 that pro- vides banking services without holding a banking license. It is regulated by the RBI under the RBI Act, 1934. Indian Economy 335 It engaged in the business of loans and advances, acquisition of shares/stocks/bonds/debentures/securities issued by Gov- ernment or local authority or other marketable securities of a like nature, leasing, hire-purchase, insurance business, chit fund business but does not include any institution whose prin- cipal business is that of agriculture activity, industrial activity, purchase or sale of any goods (other than securities) or provid- ing any services and sale/purchase/construction of immovable property. Difference Between NBFCs and Banks Feature NBFCs Banks Regulator RBI (Non-Bank- ing Financial Companies Division) RBI (Banking Regula- tion Act) Accepts Demand Deposits (Savings & Current Accounts)? No Yes Part of Payment and Settlement System? No Yes Can Issue Cheques? No Yes Lending Activities? Yes Yes Statement 1 is incorrect: NBFCs can engage in","PW-1078":"In financial terminology, a “bear” refers to an inves- tor who anticipates that the price of a particular security or the overall market will decline. Acting on this belief, such in- vestors may engage in strategies like short selling, where they sell securities they do not currently own with the intention of re- purchasing them later at a lower price, thereby securing a profit. Options (b), (c) and (d) are incorrect:  An investor who expects prices to rise is called a bull, not a bear. Bulls are optimistic about the market and buy securities with the expectation of selling them at higher prices in the future.  A shareholder or bondholder is simply an investor who owns shares or bonds, regardless of their market outlook.  A lender or bondholder is not necessarily a bear. A bear is specifically an investor with a pessimistic outlook on the market or a security. 372","PW-1079":"In India, the interest rates on savings accounts were de- regulated by the Reserve Bank of India (RBI) in 2011. This dereg- ulation allowed individual banks to set their own interest rates on savings deposits. At the time when question was asked they were fixed by RBI ,which now stands deregulated . 373","PW-1080":"","PW-1081":"“Commercial Banks refer to both scheduled and non-scheduled commercial banks which are regulated un- der Banking Regulation Act, 1949.” Commercial banks operate on a ‘for-profit’ basis. They primarily engage in the acceptance of deposit and extend loans to the general public, businesses and the government. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 336 Statement 1 is correct: Commercial banks often have tie-ups with brokerage firms or have their own investment wings to assist customers in buying and selling shares and secu- rities. This service falls under the category of investment and wealth management services. Banks like SBI, ICICI, and HDFC Bank provide these services through demat accounts and trading platforms. Statement 2 is correct: Many commercial banks have spe- cialized departments to act as executors and trustees for the wills of their customers. In this role, banks manage the estate of deceased individuals and ensure that assets are distributed according to the terms of the will. Examples include RBI-autho- rized banks offering trust services. 375","PW-1082":"","PW-1083":"Statement 1 is incorrect: The Reserve Bank of In- dia was nationalised with effect from 1st January, 1949 on the basis of the Reserve Bank of India (Transfer to Public Ownership) Act, 1948. All shares in the capital of the Bank were deemed transferred to the Central Government on payment of a suitable compensation. Before nationalization, RBI was a pri- vately owned entity since its establishment in 1935 under the Reserve Bank of India Act, 1934. Statement 2 is incorrect: The borrowing program of the Gov- ernment of India is handled by the Department of Econom- ic Affairs (DEA), Ministry of Finance, not the Department of Expenditure. The DEA is responsible for managing the govern- ment’s debt, including the issuance of government securities and bonds. 376","PW-1084":"Statement 1 is correct : The sex ratio is a demographic measure used to assess the number of females per 1,000 males in a population. It is an important indicator of gender balance and social development within a region or country. As per the Census of India 2001, the sex ratio (number of females per 1,000 males) in Haryana was 861 and in Punjab was 876. Both states had sex ratios below the national average of 933, reflecting a histor- ical preference for male children and gender imbalance. Both the states have improved their sex ratio as per the census 2011 with Haryana at 879 and Punjab at 895. Statement 2 is incorrect : The two states with the lowest pop- ulation density as per the 2001 census are Arunachal Pradesh (13 per sqKM) and Mizoram (42 per sqKM), not Meghalaya and Mizoram. Currently Arunachal Pradesh is still the least dense Indian state at 17 people per sqKM as per the 2011 census. Statement 3 is correct : As per the Census of India 2001, Ker- ala recorded both the highest literacy rate (90.92%) and the highest sex ratio ( 1,058 females per 1,000 males) among all Indian ","PW-1085":"","PW-1086":"The product life cycle is the length of time that a prod- uct is available to customers. It starts when a product (a good or a service) is introduced into the market and ends when it’s removed from the shelves.  Product Development is the initial stage where the product is being conceptualized, designed, and developed. No sales occur during this stage, and the company incurs significant costs.  When a product is introduced in the market sales are slow, and marketing costs are high as the company tries to create awareness and attract customers.  In the Growth phase the product gains acceptance, and sales start to increase rapidly. Profits begin to rise, and competitors may enter the market.  During the Maturity phase sales growth slows down as the product reaches peak market penetration. Competition intensifies, and companies focus on differentiating their product to maintain market share.  Sales and profits decline due to market saturation, changing consumer preferences, or technological advancements. Companies may discontinue the product or revamp it. 379","PW-1087":"A consumer is said to be in equilibrium when they allocate their limited income in such a way that they maximize their total satisfaction (utility) from the goods and services they consume i.e. he is able to fulfil his need with a given lev- el of income. This concept is based on the theory of consumer behavior in economics. Conditions for Consumer Equilibrium:  Budget Constraint: The consumer has a fixed level of income and faces given prices for goods and services. The total expenditure on goods and services cannot exceed the consumer’s income.  Utility Maximization: The consumer allocates their income in such a way that the marginal utility per unit of money spent is equal across all goods and services.  No Further Reallocation: The consumer cannot increase their total utility by reallocating their income between goods and services. 380","PW-1088":"Supply-side economics is an economic theory that focuses on boosting economic growth by increasing the sup- ply of goods and services. It emphasizes the role of produc- ers (businesses and entrepreneurs) in driving economic ac- tivity. The key principles of supply-side economics include:  Tax Cuts: Reducing taxes on businesses and individuals to incentivize production, investment, and work.  Deregulation: Reducing government regulations to lower the cost of production and encourage entrepreneurship.  Incentives for Investment: Providing incentives for businesses to invest in capital, technology, and innovation.  Increased Productivity: Focusing on policies that enhance productivity and efficiency in the economy. Supply-side economics emphasizes the producer’s perspective because it believes that by enabling producers to operate more efficiently and profitably, the overall economy will grow. This growth, in turn, benefits consumers through increased employ- ment, lower prices, and higher quality goods and services. 381","PW-1089":"As per the 1991 Census, the literacy rates for the men- tioned Union Territories were:  Pondicherry (Puducherry): 74.91%  Delhi: 76.09%  Andaman & Nicobar Islands: 73.74%  Chandigarh: 78.73%  Dadra & Nagar Haveli: 39.45% 382","PW-1090":"","PW-1091":"A is matched with 4: Dr. C. Rangarajan headed the Disinvestment Commission in the 1990s, which was tasked with recommending strategies for the disinvestment of shares in Public Sector Enterprises (PSEs) to improve efficien- cy and reduce the fiscal burden on the government. B is matched with 2: The Omkar Goswami Committee was formed to examine the issue of industrial sickness and sug- gest measures for the revival of sick industries. It focused on identifying the causes of industrial sickness and recommending policy interventions. C is matched with 1: Dr. Raja Chelliah chaired the Tax Re- forms Committee in the early 1990s, which laid the foundation for India’s tax reforms. The committee recommended simplifying the tax structure, broadening the tax base, and reducing tax rates to promote economic growth. D is matched with 3: The R.N. Malhotra Committee was con- stituted in 1993 to recommend reforms in the insurance sec- tor. Its recommendations led to the opening up of the insurance sector to private players and the establishment of the Insurance Regulatory and Development Authority ","PW-1092":"Hawala transactions refer to an informal and unof- ficial system of transferring money across borders without using formal bank-ing channels or regulatory oversight. It involves a network of brokers (hawaladars) who facilitate the transfer of money between individuals or entities in dif- ferent countries. For example, if Person A in Country X wants to send money to Person B in Country Y, they give the money to a ha- waladar in Country X. The hawaladar then instructs their coun- terpart in Country Y to deliver the equivalent amount to Person B. No physical movement of money occurs across borders, and the transaction is based on trust and informal records. Options (b), (c) and (d) are incorrect :  Unauthorized stock transfers without using stock exchanges fall under insider trading or securities fraud and not Hawala.  Received as commission for services rendered to overseas investors/buyers/sellers in assisting them to get over the red tape and/or in getting preferential treatment” refers to bribery or facilitation payments to bypass bureaucratic hurdles, which is a corruption issue.","PW-1093":"The average household size refers to the average number of people living in a household. It is calculated using the following formula: Average Household Size=Total Population/Total Number of Households. For example, if a country has a population of 100 million and 20 million households, the average household size would be: 100,000,000/20,000,000=5 persons per household. Based on the 1991 Census data, the average household sizes (number of persons per household) for the given states are as follows: 1. Uttar Pradesh: 6.2 persons per household 2. West Bengal: 5.4 persons per household 3. Gujarat: 5.5 persons per household 4. Kerala: 5.3 persons per household The average household size in India has been decreasing over the decades due to declining birth rates, urbanization, and changes in family structures. States like Uttar Pradesh and Bihar have larger household sizes due to higher fertility rates and joint fam- ilies. Kerala and Tamil Nadu have smaller household sizes due to better education, family planning, and higher migration. v v v","PW-1094":"Pair 1 is incorrectly matched: Chandraketugarh is not located in Odisha. It is actually an archaeological site in West Bengal, near Kolkata. It is known for its historical significance as an ancient trading hub and port town, dating back to the pre- Mauryan and Gupta periods. It is an urban centre of the ancient state of Gangaridai belonging to the trans-Bengal region at the interface of West Bengal and Bangladesh. The antiquity of the area dates back to eras as early as 4th century BCE, a period much prior to the Mauryan era and shows evidence in the continuity of subsequent Sunga, Kushana, Gupta, Pala and Sena dynasties. Pair 2 is correctly matched : Inamgaon is a chalcolithic site in Maharashtra. After the disintegration of the Indus civilization, in a phase known as the Early Jorwe (1400– 1000 BC), hundreds of agrarian villages flourished in the Deccan region of west-central India. Environmental degradation, combined with unsustainable agricultural practices, contributed to the abandonment of many communities around 1000 BC. Inamgaon was one of a handful of villages to persist in","PW-1095":"Korkai, Poompuhar, and Muchiri were prominent ancient port cities in South India that played a crucial role in maritime trade.  Korkai : Korkai, situated in the Thoothukudi district of Tamil Nadu, emerged as a significant port city during ancient times, notably flourishing during the era of Tamil Sangam literature. It served as the primary port for the Pandya Kingdom during this period.  Poompuhar: Alternatively known as Kaveripattinam, it stands out as an ancient port city with a vibrant maritime trading legacy. Positioned on the banks of the Kaveri River in the Mayiladuthurai district of Tamil Nadu, it served as the primary port for the esteemed Chola Kingdom.  Muchiri : Muchiri, alternatively referred to as Muziris, stood as an ancient port city situated in what is now Kerala, close to the town of Kodungallur. It held substantial importance as a trading hub within the Indian Ocean trade network throughout the ancient and medieval eras. Tondi and Muchiri emerged as pivotal ports within the realm of the Chera kingdom. Hence, all the three sites mentioned were well known as Ports ","PW-1096":"Vatakkiruttal, also known as Vadakiruthal or Vadakiruttal, was particularly prevalent during the Sangam period (3rd century BCE to 2nd Century CE). Tamil Kings, in a bid to uphold their honor and prestige, were willing to face death by fasting, a practice known as “Vatakkiruttal.” 5","PW-1097":"India’s historical sites highlight diverse peculiarities as Bhimbetka’s prehistoric rock art, Nalanda’s ancient university, Sanchi’s stupas, Dholavira’s urban planning, Pattadakal’s Chalukyan temples, and Khajuraho’s erotic sculptures, reflecting the subcontinent’s rich contributions to art, architecture, and education across areas. Pair 1 is incorrectly matched: Burzahom (Kashmir) had a well- developed bone tool industry. Other finds at Burzahom include pits and coarse pottery. Rock-cut shrines were not a feature of the Burzahom site. Pair 2 is correctly matched: Chandraketugarh is located in the Ganges delta in West Bengal. It is known for its rich collection of terracotta plaques and figurines that date back to the pre- Mauryan and Gupta periods. Pair 3 is correctly matched: Ganeshwar is located in the northeastern part of Rajasthan. Hundreds of copper artifacts have been found at this site which suggests it must have been a copper working center. 6","PW-1098":"Pair 1 is correctly matched: Eripatti was a special kind of land donated by individuals. The revenue from it was set aside for the maintenance of tanks in the village. Pair 2 is incorrectly matched: During the Chola administration, occasionally a very large village would be administered as a single unit and this was called Taniyur. These villages were not necessarily just large administrative units but could also be village settlements that were either wholly or largely populated by Brahmins or associated with religious functions. Pair 3 is correctly matched: Ghatikas were educational institutions, often associated with temples, where learning took place. These colleges were centers for higher education, particularly in subjects like philosophy, logic, and religious studies. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 36 Here is a list of similar historical terms related to land revenue, administration, and education in ancient India: Term Description Brahmadeya Land grants given to Brahmins, often leading to the formation of Agrahara villages. Devadana Land donated to temples for religious and charitable ","PW-1099":"Ancient India made significant contributions to science, particularly in mathematics, astronomy, and medicine. Achievements include the concept of zero and the decimal system, advancements in surgery and the accurate calculations of the Earth’s circumference. Statement 1 is correct: Ancient Indian texts like the Sushruta Samhita (6th century BC) describe specialized surgical instruments for procedures such as surgery, eye treatments, and plastic surgery, indicating well-developed surgical knowledge by the 1st century AD. Statement 2 is incorrect: There has been no documented proof of organ transplants in the 3rd century AD. The concept of organ transplantation is much more modern, developing in the 20th century. Statement 3 is correct: Aryabhata, in the 5th century AD, improvised the concept of sine ( jya in Sanskrit) in his book and used it in astronomical calculations. Aryabhata’s work in trigonometry laid the foundation for later developments in mathematics. Statement 4 is correct: The concept of cyclic quadrilaterals, where a quadrilateral can be inscribed in a circle, was known ","PW-1100":"As mentioned in Arthshastra, Guilds, also known as Shrenis or Trade Guilds, played a significant role in ancient Indian society. These organizations brought together artisans, merchants, and traders to promote their collective interests, provide protection, and facilitate trade. Statement 1 is incorrect: The king or local rulers protected guilds and ensured compliance with state regulations, but guilds operated autonomously and were not always formally registered with the central authority. Statement 2 is correct: Guilds had significant control over the economic activities of their members. They were responsible for regulating various aspects of production, trade, and commerce, which included setting wages, standards of workmanship, prices for goods, and rules of operation. Statement 3 is correct: Guild members were entitled to impeach and punish a chief found guilty of misconduct. The Arthashastra describes the role of guilds in resolving disputes through a Shreni court, where matters related to trade, contracts, and disagreements were handled by the guild’s officials. SUPER HINT Fo","PW-1101":"Manigrama was a well-known corporation of merchants in ancient India, particularly in South India. It played a crucial role in trade and commerce, often dealing with long- distance trade. 10","PW-1102":"Kula, Vamsa, and Gotra were terms associated with the social and family structure of ancient Indian society, particularly in relation to lineage and ancestry. In contrast, Kosa referred to the treasury and was a key element in state administration. Mentioned in Kautilya’s Arthashastra, Kosa was one of the seven components of Kautilya's Saptanga policy, which included Swamin (Ruler), Amatya (Ministers), Janapada (Territory), Durg (Forts), Kosa (Treasury), Bala (Army), and Mitra (Friend or Ally). 2. HARAPPAN CIVILIZATION (INDUS VALLEY) 11","PW-1103":"","PW-1104":"","PW-1105":"The Harappan Civilization, discovered in 1921 at Harappa (Pakistan), spanned Punjab, Sindh, Balochistan, Gujarat, Rajasthan, and western Uttar Pradesh, predating Chalcolithic cultures and showing greater development. Statement 1 is incorrect: The Indus Valley Civilization differed from Mesopotamian and Egyptian civilizations, as it lacked grand palaces and temples ruled by powerful kings or priests. Instead, archaeological evidence suggests that their cities featured well-planned structures, public buildings, and granaries, emphasizing urban planning and administrative efficiency rather than monumental architecture. Statement 2 is correct: Seals and figurines, such as the Priest- King and various fertility symbols, imply reverence for deities associated with fertility, nature, and possibly mother goddesses, indicating a worship system that involved both male and female divine figures. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 38 Statement 3 is incorrect: No trace of Horses has been found in the Indus Valley. The use of chariots is associated with later cultures, such as the Vedic civilization, and is not","PW-1106":"Indus Valley Civilization, one of the earliest urban cultures, is notable for its advanced urban planning, trade systems, and crafts, yet it was largely secular in nature with no dominant religious structure. Statement 1 is correct: The Indus Valley Civilization is often considered more secular compared to other ancient civilizations like Mesopotamia or Egypt, where religion played a dominant role in daily life and governance. Although evidence of religious practices exists (e.g., figurines, seals depicting deities, the Great Bath which may have had ritual significance), there is no clear evidence of a theocratic society or large, grandiose temples. The focus of the Indus civilization appears to be on urban planning, trade, and practical aspects of daily life. Statement 2 is correct: The Indus Valley Civilization is one of the earliest known civilizations to have used cotton for textile production. Evidence of cotton cultivation has been found at several Indus sites, such as Mohenjo-Daro and Harappa, where cotton fibers have been discovered, indicating its use in making cloth. Also, ","PW-1107":"The Indus Valley Civilization (Harappan Civilisation) flourished between 2600 BC and 1900 BC ​in the northern region of the Indian subcontinent. It was prominently spread over Sindh, Balochistan, Punjab, Haryana, Rajasthan, Gujarat, Western U.P. and Northern Maharashtra. 16","PW-1108":"","PW-1109":"The Indus Valley Civilization was highly materialistic, with advanced urban infrastructure, standardized weights, and extensive trade networks. In contrast, the Rig Vedic Civilization had a more pastoral economy, focusing on cattle wealth and ritualistic offerings rather than large-scale material production or urban development. Statement 1 is correct: The Rigvedic Aryans are described in the Rigveda as using advanced weapons and armor, including coats of mail and helmets. In contrast, the Indus Valley Civilization shows no evidence of such organized military gear, suggesting a less militaristic society. Statement 2 is incorrect: The Rigvedic Aryans knew gold, silver, and copper, while the Indus Valley Civilization used copper and bronze, lacking iron. Iron technology emerged after the decline of the Indus Valley, during the later Vedic period. Statement 3 is correct: The horse seems to have been unknown to the inhabitants of Mohenjo-Daro and Harappa. Horse remains found at Surkotada, dating to around 2000 BCE, suggest the possibility of horses in the Indus Valley. However, Sándor Bö","PW-1110":"Vedic Aryans used to worship manifestations of forces of nature as Gods in the form of Indra, Agni, Soma, Varuna. Mother Earth and Rivers, especially Saraswati, were worshiped as the goddess. The hymns in the Rigveda reflect reverence for natural forces like fire, wind, and the sun, with a strong emphasis on rituals and offerings.  Yajna was a method of worship that involved offering sacrifices. It included Vedic chants singing and a sacrificial mantra. The Vedic mantra was chanted while sacrificing havan samagri in the fire during a yajna.  Bhakti (devotion) and image worship became more prominent in later religious developments. 19","PW-1111":"The concepts of Dharma and Rita were central to the Vedic civilization of India, shaping its moral, social, and cosmic order. Dharma and rita are interconnected, with rita providing the cosmic framework within which dharma operates. Together, they create a moral universe where every action aligns with the natural order. These concepts guide both personal behavior and societal norms, ensuring that individuals act in accordance with the universal laws and maintain harmony in all aspects of life. Statement 1 is correct: In the Vedic context, dharma refers to the concept of obligations and duties. It is about the righteous conduct and the moral responsibilities one has to oneself and to society. Statement 2 is correct: Rita is the principle of natural order which regulates and coordinates the operation of the universe and everything within it. It is the cosmic order or the fundamental moral law governing the functioning of the universe. 20","PW-1112":"The Atharvaveda, known as the “Veda of magical formulas” or the “Veda of charms and spells,” includes numerous incantations aimed at warding off evil and curing diseases. 21","PW-1113":"“Aryan” primarily refers to a linguistic or speech group rather than an ethnic or racial group. It is associated with the Indo-Aryan languages, which are a branch of the larger Indo- European language family. The term was historically used to describe the speakers of these languages, who migrated to the Indian subcontinent and other parts of Asia. However, the details of the migration and the exact identity of these groups remain subjects of scholarly debate. 22","PW-1114":"Vedic literature consists of the Vedas, which are the oldest religious texts of India, comprising hymns, rituals, and philosophical teachings. It includes four Vedas—Rigveda, Yajurveda, Samaveda, and Atharvaveda—and their associated texts like the Brahmanas, Aranyakas, and Upanishads. The river most mentioned in early Vedic literature is the Sindhu. It is mentioned over 150 times in the Rig Veda, the oldest known Hindu text. The Sindhu is identical to the Indus River and is considered to be a sacred river associated with fertility, abundance and prosperity. Other rivers that are mentioned in early Vedic literature include the Saraswati, Yamuna and Ganges. Saraswati is called naditama or the best of the rivers in the Rig Veda. 23","PW-1115":"Brahmavadini refers to women who sought spiritual knowledge and philosophical understanding of Brahman, the ultimate reality. These women ascetics were known for their intellectual pursuits, poetic abilities, and compositions of Vedic hymns. Among the prominent women Vedic scholars, we find references to Maitreyi, Viswambhara, Apala, and Lopamudra, to name a few. 4. HISTORY OF MAURYAN AGE 24","PW-1116":"Ashoka’s religious philosophy evolved from a belief in traditional Hindu practices to the adoption of Buddhism, emphasizing non-violence (ahimsa), compassion, and moral conduct. His Edicts reflect his commitment to dharma, promoting tolerance, welfare, and ethical governance. In Major Rock Edicts 7 and 12, Ashoka explicitly advocates for religious tolerance and the coexistence of all religions. He emphasized that all ascetics (spiritual teachers) should be honored, irrespective of their faith, and that people should respect each other’s beliefs. These edicts reflect Ashoka’s commitment to dhamma (righteousness), which promoted peaceful co-existence. 26","PW-1117":"Ashokan edicts and inscriptions, carved on pillars and rocks across the Indian subcontinent, convey Ashoka’s policies of Dhamma, promoting non-violence, religious tolerance, and moral conduct. The Kanaganahalli inscription located in Kanganahalli (in present-day Gulbarga, Karnataka), is a significant discovery. The inscription and relief depict Ashoka in the form of a portrait and a reference to his title, “Ranyo Ashoka,” highlighting his role as a ruler. 27","PW-1118":"","PW-1119":"","PW-1120":"The Maurya (321 BCE – 185 BCE), Sunga (185 BCE – 73 BCE), and Kanva dynasties (73 BCE – 30 BCE) represent significant eras in ancient Indian history, spanning the rule from centralized imperial administration to regional governance and eventual fragmentation. Statement 1 is correct: The last Mauryan ruler, Brihadratha, was assassinated by his commander-in-chief, Pushyamitra Sunga, who then established the Sunga dynasty (185 BCE). Statement 2 is correct: The last Sunga king, Devabhuti, was assassinated by his minister Vasudeva Kanva, a Brahmana, who subsequently usurped the throne and founded the Kanva dynasty (73 BCE). Statement 3 is correct: The last ruler of the Kanva dynasty was overthrown by the Andhras (also known as the Satavahanas) around 30 BCE, marking the end of the Kanva dynasty and the establishment of the Satavahana dynasty in central India. 30","PW-1121":"Buddhism and Jainism part of the Shramana traditions are two ancient Indian religions that originated around the same time, during the 6th century BCE. They emphasized asceticism, non-violence, and liberation from the cycle of rebirth. They offered alternative philosophies to Vedic ritualism, focusing on personal spiritual practices and ethical living. Statement 1 is incorrect: Vardhaman Mahavira’s mother, Trishala, was the sister (and not daughter) of Chetaka, a chief of the Lichchhavi clan. The Lichchhavis were known for their democratic and republican system of governance. Statement 2 is correct: Gautama Buddha’s mother, Maya Devi, was a princess from the Koshalan dynasty. She was married to King Suddhodana of the Shakya clan and was the mother of Siddhartha Gautama, who later became the Buddha. Statement 3 is correct: Parshvanatha, the twenty-third Tirthankara of Jainism, was associated with Benaras (Varanasi), where he was born. According to Jain tradition, he was born into a royal family and preached a doctrine of non- violence, truth, and asceticism. The serpent symbol is asso","PW-1122":"","PW-1123":"Military governorship in ancient India, particularly during the periods of the Mauryan, Gupta, and Kushana empires, was a key feature of the administrative structure. Amongst the given options, Greeks were the first who introduced military governorship in India. They appointed their Governors called Strategos. These military governors had both military and administrative authority and were responsible for maintaining control and collecting taxes. The practice was further continued by subsequent foreign invaders and Indian rulers as well such as Sakas, Parthians and later Mughals. 33","PW-1124":"The Alexander’s invasion of India in 326 B.C is a pivotal moment in ancient history, marking the encounter between Greek and Indian civilizations. At the time of Alexander’s invasion in 326 B.C., the northern part of India was under the rule of the Nanda dynasty (343 - 321 BCE). The king of the Nanda dynasty at the time of Alexander’s invasion of India was Dhanananda. 34","PW-1125":"The Huns, a nomadic group originating from the Asian steppes, were a significant force during period. Their invasions played a key role in the broader process of the Western Roman Empire’s decline. After the Hun invasion in the 4th to 5th century, the Roman Empire weakened. This led Indian traders to shift their focus to Southeast Asia. With the decline of Roman trade routes, maritime trade increased with Sri Lanka, Myanmar (Burma), Indonesia, and Cambodia. Indian merchants also spread Hinduism, Buddhism, and Indian culture to these regions. During this time, Indian-influenced kingdoms like Srivijaya and Funan became important trade partners. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 42 35","PW-1126":"","PW-1127":"The Mahajanapadas were sixteen ancient kingdoms or republics in northern and northeastern India around the 6th century BC. They were significant in shaping India’s political, social, and cultural landscape, with each having its own system of governance. Magadha was the most powerful city-state in India during the 6th century B.C located in present-day Bihar. It was the nucleus of several larger kingdoms or empires between the 6th century BCE and the 8th century CE. The supremacy of Magadha continued under the Nanda (4th century BCE) and Mauryan (4th-2nd century BCE) dynasties. Under the Mauryan dynasty, the empire included almost the entire subcontinent of India. 37","PW-1128":"The Greeks (2nd century BCE to 1st century CE in northwestern India), Kushanas (1st to 3rd century CE across northern India and Central Asia), and Shakas (2nd century BCE to 4th century CE in western India) were key powers during the Post-Mauryan period. Greek, Kushanas and Shakas needed legitimacy for their rule for people to accept them as their king. Accepting religion in the local area was the best way to achieve legitimacy. Buddhism provided the easiest entry in comparison to Hinduism which had strict birth related caste structure. 38","PW-1129":"","PW-1130":"Ashoka’s Edicts represent some of the earliest and most extensive inscriptions in Indian history, providing valuable insights into his policies and beliefs. Carved on rocks, pillars, and caves throughout his empire, these edicts reveal Ashoka’s commitment to Dhamma (moral law). The Assertion (A) is true: Ashoka’s edicts emphasize the importance of social harmony and ethical conduct over specific religious devotion. For example, in Rock Edict XII, Ashoka urged people to respect all religions and avoid criticism of other faiths. Similarly, Rock Edict VII emphasizes religious tolerance and harmony, stating that all religions should coexist peacefully. The Reason (R) is also true: His focus was on equity and moral values rather than endorsing a particular religion. Ashoka’s edicts spread ideas of equity, justice, and moral conduct rather than promoting any single religion, even though he embraced Buddhism. Thus, Both statements are true, and R correctly explains A. 40","PW-1131":"The Major Rock Edicts of Ashoka are a series of inscriptions on rock surfaces across the Indian subcontinent, issued by the Mauryan emperor Ashoka to communicate his policies, ethical principles, and the spread of Dhamma (moral law). Ancient History 43 Option (c) is correct: The Ashoka Major Rock Edicts II and XIII are significant because they provide information about the Sangam Kingdom, which was located in the southern part of India. Rock Edict II mentions the Tamil kingdoms and provides insights into the connections and diplomatic interactions between Ashoka’s Mauryan Empire and the southern kingdoms, particularly emphasizing the relationship with Cholas, Pandyas, and Satyaputras. Rock Edict XIII is famous for describing Ashoka’s Kalinga War and its consequences. It focuses on Ashoka’s messages of Dhamma, non-violence, and the dissemination of his moral teachings to various regions, as shown in the Ashoka Empire 250 BC map. 41","PW-1132":"","PW-1133":"The Matsya Mahajanapada was located in present- day Rajasthan, covering areas like Jaipur and Alwar. Avanti in modern day Madhya Pradesh, was a powerful Mahajanapada with its capital at Ujjain. It played a significant role in the political and cultural landscape of ancient India, known for its rivalry with Magadha. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 44 Vatsa situated around modern-day Allahabad (Prayagraj) and centered on Kausambi, Vatsa was known for its trade and economic prosperity. The Anga Mahajanapada covered eastern Bihar and parts of Bengal, with Champa as its capital. It was an important commercial and cultural hub, often in conflict with its neighboring powers like Magadha, as shown in Mahajanapadas Map (500 BC). The Mahajanapadas were sixteen powerful kingdoms that emerged in ancient India around the 6th century BCE, during the Early Historic period. These kingdoms formed the basis of early Indian civilization, political organization, and culture. Sixteen Mahajanapadas were Magadha, Anga, Kashi, Kosala, Avanti, Vatsa, Gandhara, Kamboja, Chedi, Vajji, Malla, Kuru, Panchala, Matsya, Suras","PW-1134":"Post-Gupta India saw the rise of regional kingdoms and fragmented political power. This period marked a decline in centralized rule, leading to a more decentralized political landscape. Option (b) is correct: Due to Hun invasions, the Gupta kingdom was weakened in its power and several independent kingdoms arose in north India such as Yashodharman of Malwa, the Maukharis of Kanauj, the Maitrakas in Saurashtra and others. Pushyabhuti of Thanesar (Haryana) also carved an independent state around that time. After the coming of Tomars of Delhi in the 8th century, later by the 11-12th century, long after the decline of Gupta’s, Chauhans of Rajasthan, Solankis of Gujarat, Parmars of Malwa, and Chandels of Bundelkhand started ruling north India. It is only during the 14th CE, the Yadavas of Devagiri (Maharashtra) became an important ruling dynasty of Deccan. SUPER HINT For S1, If question itself says “decline of Guptas until rise of Harshavardhana” → it implies some form of Guptas still existed in parts. Hence likely true. For S3, Harsha himself belonged to Pushybhuti dynasty, so by definit","PW-1135":"During the Gupta period, different land measures were known in different regions such as Nivartana, Kulyavapa, and Dronavapa. These units of measurement, including Kulyavapa and Dronavapa, are mentioned in inscriptions from Bengal, as well as in texts like the Arthashastra and other regional inscriptions of the Gupta period. The term ‘’vap” means ‘’to sow”. Kulyavapa means the area required to sow one kulya of grain and the Dronavyapa was the area required to sow one drona of grain. One kulya is equal to eight drona. 46","PW-1136":"","PW-1137":"During the Gupta period, forced labor (vishti) became a source of income for the state and was also looked upon as a form of taxation on the subjects. Vishti was forced labor instead of taxes hence no weekly wages were entitled. Anyone from the family can be sent as a forced laborer, not particularly the eldest son of the family. The Gupta period was a time of significant economic and administrative development in ancient India, and taxes played a crucial role in the functioning of the state. The types of taxes during the Gupta period include Land Tax (Bhojabhaga or Bhaga),Trade and Market Taxes (Sulka), Water tax, Vishti,etc. SUPER HINT For option B, “Totally absent” → extreme phrase = red flag. False. For Option C, Logical contradiction: you can’t be both forced and regularly paid like a voluntary worker. False. For option D, Specificity = red flag, Sounds artificially constructed — eldest son clause looks too precise for ancient systemic Vishti. Forced labor ≠ primogeniture rule. Hence likely false too. 48","PW-1138":"The feudal system in ancient India was a socio- economic and political structure characterized by a hierarchy of landownership and obligations, where land was held in exchange for service, primarily military or administrative. Assertion(A) is true: The feudal system, a hierarchical system of land-use and protection, originated in ancient India due to military campaigns. This is true because, during wars and conquests, victorious rulers granted land to military officers and local chiefs as a reward for their service. These landholders, called samantas, later became hereditary lords, leading to the emergence of feudal structures. Reason (R) is also true: During the post Mauryan and Gupta period feudal system became the main state apparatus as the Guptas granted large land tracts (agraharas and bhukti) to Brahmins, officers, and feudatories (samantas). These landholders gained administrative and military control, further decentralizing power. Reason (R) is not a correct explanation of Assertion(A): Feudal system expanded through other factors, not simply the Gupta period .The emergence ","PW-1139":"","PW-1140":"","PW-1141":"","PW-1142":"","PW-1143":"Hoysala Dynasty: Originating from the Indian subcontinent, the Hoysala Empire held sway over a significant portion of present-day Karnataka from the 10th to the 14th centuries. While the Hoysalas initially established their capital at Belur, it was later relocated to Halebidu. Gahadavala Dynasty : Following the dissolution of the Pratihara empire, several Rajput states emerged in northern India. Among these, the Gahadavalas of Kanauj (12th to 13th century), the Paramaras of Malwa, and the Chauhans of Ajmer were the most prominent. Kakatiya Dynasty : The Kakatiya dynasty ruled the region comprising present day Telangana and Andhra Pradesh during the 12th and 14th centuries. Their capital was Warangal in Telangana. The distinct style of Kakatiya-era architecture is seen in the Thousand Pillar Temple and Ramappa Temple near Warangal. Yadava Dynasty: The Yadava dynasty ruled in the 12th–14th -century and comprised the Hindu kingdom of central India in what is now the Indian state of Maharashtra. Originally a feudatory of the Western Chalukyas of Kalyani, the dynasty became paramount in t","PW-1144":"Yuan Chwang, the Chinese traveler, provided a detailed account of India during the 7th century, noting its thriving culture, well-organized society, and vibrant Buddhist institutions. He described India’s cities, roads, and religious life. Ancient History 47 Statement 1 is incorrect: Roads and river routes were not completely robbery-free. He described the condition of roads as generally safe, but he also noted that there were occasional dangers and robberies on certain routes. Hiuen-Tsang himself was looted a couple of times. Statement 2 is correct: Criminal law was very severe. He mentioned that the judicial system in India involved ordeals by fire, water, and poison as a way to determine guilt or innocence. Statement 3 is correct: Duties were to be paid at trade barriers without fail. It was a source of income for the kingdom. SUPER HINT For S1, “Completely immune” = extreme phrase. Red flag. In any large kingdom, especially ancient ones, some degree of theft/robbery is natural. Saying zero crime is utopian. Even in modern states with strong policing, no place is “completely immun","PW-1145":"","PW-1146":"Assertion (A) is true: The Prayag Assembly was convened by Harshavardhana around AD 643. This assembly is a significant historical event where Harshavardhana gathered numerous scholars, monks, and dignitaries. Chinese traveler Xuanzang (Hiuen Tsang), was also present at the assembly and provided a detailed account of it. While it is true that Harshavardhana promoted Mahayana Buddhism during his reign, the assembly was not solely focused on promoting this form of Buddhism. Reason (R) is false: Harshavardhana organized the Prayag Assembly not just to promote Mahayana Buddhism but also to strengthen his rule and encourage religious discussions. The assembly was open to different beliefs. 60","PW-1147":"","PW-1148":"The Saka Era is a historical calendar that begins in 78 A.D., marking its epoch in Indian history. The Vikrama Samvat is another significant calendar system in India, which starts from 58 B.C.. To convert a Saka year to Vikrama Samvat, 136 years are added to the Saka year. Therefore, adding 136 years to 465 (Saka year) results in 601, which corresponds to a Vikrama Samvat year. Ancient History 49 7. ART, LITERATURE AND CULTURE DURING ANCIENT TIMES 62","PW-1149":"Statement 1 is incorrect : A parable is a succinct, didactic story, in prose or verse, that illustrates one or more instructive lessons or principles. The Upanishads do contain parables (short stories with moral or philosophical lessons). Examples include : Nachiketa and Yama in the Katha Upanishad, which explores the concept of the soul and immortality. Statement 2 is correct : The Upanishads (1000–500 BCE) were composed during the later Vedic period, forming the philosophical core of Hinduism. The Puranas, on the other hand, were compiled much later (mostly between 3rd to 10th century CE), making Upanishads earlier than Puranas. Upanishads : The Upanishads are ancient Indian texts that explore deep philosophical and spiritual ideas. They form the core of Vedanta philosophy and focus on concepts like Brahman (the ultimate reality), Atman (the soul), and Moksha (liberation). The Upanishads emphasize self-inquiry, meditation, and the relationship between the individual soul and the universe. Composed in Sanskrit mostly between 800 BCE and 200 BCE, they are considered the concluding pa","PW-1150":"Ancient and medieval Indian playwrights and dramatists, like Bhasa, Kalidasa, and Bhavabhuti, created masterpieces that blended poetry, philosophy, and performance.  Bhavabhūti was an 8th-century scholar of India noted for his plays and poetry, written in Sanskrit. He is known as \"Poet of Karun Rasa\" for his work named as Uttararamacharita. His written plays include Mahavircharitra and Malatimadhava.  Hastimalla was a Kannada poet and playwright during Hoysalas' reign. He wrote 8 plays including 'VikrantKaurava' and 'Subhadra Harana'  Kshemeshvara was an 11th-century Sanskrit poet from Kashmir in India. One of the important works attributed to him is the Dasavatar Charita. 64","PW-1151":"Statement 1 is incorrect : The distinction between Mitakshara and Dayabhaga is not based on caste i.e. upper or lower castes but on regional variations of Hindu law. Mitakshara was prevalent in most parts of India, whereas Dayabhaga was primarily followed in Bengal and parts of Assam. Statement 2 is correct : Both were Hindu law books and governed property rights and inheritance. The Mitakshara was written by Vijnanesvara, a scholar in the Kalyani Chalukya court in the late 11th century. The Dayabhaga was authored by Jimutavahana, a 12th-century scholar from Bengal. In the Mitakshara system, sons acquire a right to ancestral property by birth, meaning they have a share in the joint family property during the father’s lifetime. In the Dayabhaga system, sons do not have a right to the property until the father’s death. Statement 3 is incorrect : The Mitakshara system historically favored male descendants, with females becoming coparceners only after the Hindu Succession Act, 2005. In contrast, the Dayabhaga system provides relatively better property rights to women, allowing both male ","PW-1152":"Statement 1 is incorrect: Panini, the great grammarian, is not associated with Pushyamitra Shunga. He is traditionally believed to have lived during the Maurya period, possibly around the 4th century BCE. Pushyamitra Shunga, however, founded the Shunga dynasty around 185 BCE, well after Panini’s time. Panini is most famous for his work “Ashtadhyayi”, a treatise on Sanskrit grammar. Statement 2 is incorrect: Amarasimha, an eminent scholar and lexicographer, is associated with the Gupta period, not Harshavardhana. He is known for compiling the Amarakosa, a famous Sanskrit lexicon. Amarasimha is believed to have lived during the reign of Chandragupta II of the Gupta Empire (c. 4th century CE), not during Harshavardhana’s reign (7th century CE). Statement 3 is correct: Kalidasa, one of the greatest classical Sanskrit poets and playwrights, is traditionally associated with the Gupta period, specifically with Chandragupta II, also known as Chandragupta Vikramaditya (r. 375-413 CE). Kalidasa is believed to have flourished at the Gupta court, and his works such as “Abhijnanasakuntalam”, “Meg","PW-1153":"","PW-1154":"","PW-1155":"Statement 1 is incorrect: The Ikshvaku dynasty ruled Andhra Pradesh during the 3rd–4th century CE. The Ikshvakus primarily followed Brahmanical traditions but were not hostile to Buddhism. Their reign saw the coexistence of multiple religious traditions . Many Buddhist stupas and viharas were constructed during their rule, particularly in Nagarjunakonda. Statement 2 is correct : The Pala dynasty (8th–12th century CE) ruled over Bengal and Bihar and was known for its strong patronage of Mahayana Buddhism. They played a significant role in establishing major Buddhist centers such as Vikramashila, Nalanda, and Somapura Mahavihara. Rulers like Dharmapala and Devapala actively promoted Buddhism, not only within India but also in regions like Tibet. 69","PW-1156":"Takshasila (Taxila) was a vital ancient city located between the Indus and Jhelum rivers, functioning as a prominent educational and cultural center. It was renowned for its university, attracting scholars like Chanakya and Panini, and played a key role in Indian history. 70","PW-1157":"Milinda’s period is separated by centuries with other given personalities.  Bimbisara (approx. 558–491 BCE) was the ruler of Magadha and a contemporary of Gautama Buddha (c. 563–483 BCE).  Prasenjit (6th century BCE) was the king of Kosala and also lived during the time of Buddha.  Milinda (Greek king Menander I) ruled much later, in the 2nd century BCE. He was not a contemporary of the other three, making him the correct answer. 71","PW-1158":"Travel accounts Megasthenes, Fa-Hien,Xuanzang and I-Tsing provide invaluable insight into ancient India. Option (b) is correct:  Megasthenes was an ancient Greek traveler and diplomat sent from Hellenistic king Seleucus I. He visited India during the Mauryan era (321-185 BC). He compiled his account on India in the famous book called ‘Indica’.  Fa-Hien was a Chinese Buddhist monk and explorer who traveled through India in search of Buddhist Scriptures during the Gupta period (4th Century CE to 6th Century CE).  Hiuen Tsang (629-645 C.E) or Xuanzang was a Chinese Buddhist monk who traveled to India during the reign of King Harsha Vardhana to obtain the Buddhist scriptures, He is also known as the “Prince of Pilgrims,”.  I-Tsing was a Chinese Buddhist monk and traveler who journeyed to India. After visiting the important Buddhist sites in Magadha, he spent ten years (676-685) at the renowned Nalanda monastery 74","PW-1159":"Sohgaura copper-plate inscription is among the earliest records highlighting the Mauryan state’s concern for preserving food grains during crises. Issued during the Mauryan period, it details a directive for famine relief by storing grains, showcasing a significant step in disaster preparedness by the state. This inscription reflects the Mauryan administrative foresight in dealing with natural calamities and highlights the organized approach of the empire. Options (b), (c) and (d) are incorrect:  Rummindei Pillar Edict of Ashoka is associated with Ashoka’s spread of Dhamma, focusing on moral and ethical governance rather than food grain preservation.  Prayaga-prasasti is an inscription that commemorates the achievements of Emperor Samudragupta. It is a eulogy that highlights the military and political prowess of the Gupta dynasty.  The Mehrauli Pillar inscription of Chandragupta II primarily commemorates victories and royal patronage rather than providing instructions for crisis management or food grain preservation. 75","PW-1160":"Pair 1 is correctly matched: Lothal, located in present-day Gujarat, was a major port city of the Indus Valley Civilization. It is renowned for its well-planned dockyard, which is considered one of the earliest known examples of a dockyard in the world, indicating the importance of maritime trade. Pair 2 is correctly matched: Sarnath is where Gautama Buddha delivered his first sermon, marking the beginning of his teachings on the Middle Path. Pair 3 is incorrectly matched: The Lion Capital of Ashoka is not associated with Rajgir but was found at Sarnath. The Lion Capital of Ashoka is a famous sculpture from the Mauryan period and is now the national emblem of India. Pair 4 is correctly matched: Nalanda was a renowned center of Buddhist learning, attracting scholars from across Asia. Nalanda University (Bihar) was one of the greatest centers of Buddhist learning in ancient India, flourishing under the Gupta and Pala dynasties. It attracted scholars from across Asia, including China, Korea, and Tibet. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 52 76","PW-1161":"The correct order of development (from oldest to newest): Urban Culture arose with the Indus Valley Civilization (~2600 BCE), marking the emergence of planned urban centers.(4) Iron Plough usage began around the 1st millennium BCE, enhancing agricultural output.(3) Punch-marked Silver Coins started circulating by the 6th century BCE as early currency.(2) Gold Coins were introduced during the Kushan period, establishing high-value currency standards.(1) 77","PW-1162":"The four yugas—Krita (Satya), Treta, Dvapara, and Kali—form a cyclical model in Hindu cosmology, depicting a gradual decline in virtue and dharma over time. A full Yuga cycle lasts 4,320,000 years (12,000 divine years), and a Kalpa, or epoch, consists of a thousand such cycles. Option (c) is correct: Based on Yuga Duration Table given below: Yuga Duration (in years) Krita (Satya) 1,728,000 years (4,800 divine years) Treta 1,296,000 years (3,600 divine years) Dvapara 864,000 years (2,400 divine years) Kali 432,000 years (1,200 divine years) 78","PW-1163":"The Jagannath Puri Temple, located in Odisha, is one of the holiest pilgrimage sites in India, dedicated to Lord Jagannath, a form of Lord Vishnu. It is famous for its annual Rath Yatra (chariot festival), attracting millions of devotees. The Devadasi system involved dedicating women to serve deities through rituals and dance, often leading to social exploitation. The Jagannath Puri Temple in Odisha is historically associated with this tradition, where Devadasis were committed to temple service, showcasing both devotion and the cultural acceptance of the practice in temple life. Over time, this system drew criticism due to its exploitative aspects, prompting reforms. The association of Devadasis with the Jagannath Temple highlights Odisha’s rich religious culture and complex socio-religious customs. 79","PW-1164":"Yavanapriya is a term in ancient Sanskrit texts referring to pepper, a commodity highly prized in early Indo- Mediterranean trade. The term “Yavanapriya” is made up of two Sanskrit words, “Yavana” referring to Greeks and “priya” meaning loved. Ancient Sanskrit texts used this term to denote the commodity loved by the Greeks from India. This lucrative trade in spices, particularly pepper, was crucial for India’s ancient economy and helped establish India as a prominent player in global commerce. v v v","PW-1165":"The membrane bioreactor (MBR) has emerged as an efficient compact technology for municipal and industrial wastewater treatment. These systems have the advantage of combining a suspended growth biological reactor with solids removal via filtration. Membranes in MBR systems are designed to function efficiently in compact spaces while effectively removing contaminants like nitrogen, phosphorus, bacteria, biochemical oxygen demand (BOD), and total suspended solids (TSS). The filtration process supports higher biomass concentrations, enabling the use of smaller bioreactors. The effluent from MBRs contains low concentrations of bacteria, total suspended solids (TSS), and biochemical oxygen demand (BOD). This facilitates high-level disinfection. Effluents are readily discharged to surface streams or can be sold for reuse, such as irrigation. 2","PW-1166":"Nitric oxide is a naturally synthesized molecule in the human body that plays a crucial role in vasodilation, which is the widening of blood vessels. It is produced by endothelial cells lining the blood vessels through the action of the enzyme nitric oxide synthase (NOS) on L-arginine. Nitric oxide diffuses into the smooth muscle cells of blood vessels. It activates an enzyme called guanylate cyclase, which increases the production of cyclic guanosine monophosphate (cGMP). cGMP causes the relaxation of smooth muscles, leading to the widening of blood vessels (vasodilation). By relaxing the smooth muscles of blood vessels, nitric oxide increases blood flow and helps regulate blood pressure. It also has important functions in immune response and neurotransmission. 3","PW-1167":"Metagenomics delves into the study of microbes within their native habitats. “Aerial metagenomics” entails collecting air samples from a specific setting to capture the genetic material (DNA) of various microorganisms, encompassing bacteria, viruses, fungi, and other microscopic life forms. 4","PW-1168":"Microsatellite DNA, alternatively known as short tandem repeats (STRs), represents a genetic marker characterised by repetitive sequences of DNA. Highly polymorphic, microsatellites exhibit varying lengths attributed to discrepancies in the number of repeat units. By scrutinising the discrepancies in microsatellite DNA sequences within individuals or populations, scientists can evaluate genetic diversity, population structure, and evolutionary links both within species and across different species. 5","PW-1169":"Statement 1 is incorrect: Covishield does not use an mRNA platform. It is manufactured by the Serum Institute of India (SII) in partnership with AstraZeneca and Oxford University. It is based on a viral vector platform. It uses a chimpanzee adenovirus vector (ChAdOx1) which is modified to carry genetic instructions for the SARS-CoV-2 spike protein. When the vaccine is administered, the adenovirus enters human cells and stimulates the production of the spike protein, triggering an immune response. mRNA vaccines do not use a viral vector 9 Science and Technology Science and Technology 531 Statement 2 is correct: DNA Barcoding helps in the identification of species even from minute amounts of tissue which can help tackle problems like the illegal trade of endangered species. It can be a tool to distinguish among species that look alike. Statement 3 is correct: DNA barcoding, widely used in fish species, is a viable method for authenticating processed food. Using DNA barcoding, natural resource managers can monitor the illegal trade of products made of natural resources like hardwood tre","PW-1170":"Bollgard I and Bollgard II are genetically modified (GM) cotton varieties developed by Monsanto (now part of Bayer) to provide resistance to bollworm, a major pest of cotton plants. Option (b) is correct: Bollgard I was the first genetically modified cotton variety which was engineered with a gene from the bacterium Bacillus thuringiensis (Bt). This gene enables the cotton plant to produce a toxin that is harmful to bollworms thereby offering pest resistance. Bollgard II is an advanced version which incorporates two Bt genes (Cry1Ac and Cry2Ab) and provides broader protection against a wider range of pests, including the pink bollworm. These genetically modified crops are designed to reduce pesticide dependency and enhance crop yields by making the plants resistant to pests that typically damage cotton bolls. 9","PW-1171":"DNA barcoding is a taxonomic method used to identify an organism as belonging to a specific species by analyzing a short, standardized genetic marker in its DNA. This technique involves comparing an individual’s DNA sequence to a reference library of similar DNA sequences which enables accurate species identification. Statement 1 is incorrect: DNA barcoding does not help in determining the age of an organism. Age estimation typically requires other techniques such as dendrochronology for plants or radiocarbon dating for animals, not genetic markers. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 532 Option (d) is correct: In a lab setting, Petri dishes can be used to induce cell division in isolated plant and animal cells. Cell culture is the process by which cells from a multicellular organism are grown under controlled conditions outside their natural environment. In the lab, cells are cultured in a petri dish or flask and maintained in nutrient-rich media. These cells can undergo mitotic cell division if conditions are favorable, leading to the formation of cell populations. 10","PW-1172":"RNA interference (RNAi) is a biological process in which RNA molecules inhibit gene expression or translation, by neutralizing targeted mRNA molecules. This technology has gained immense popularity because of its potential in gene silencing, therapeutic applications, and agricultural improvements. Statement 1 is correct: RNAi technology is primarily used to silence specific genes by targeting the messenger RNA (mRNA) produced by a gene. When RNAi molecules (small interfering RNA or siRNA) are introduced into cells, they bind to complementary mRNA, causing its degradation and preventing protein translation. This has vast potential in treating genetic diseases caused by overactive or malfunctioning genes. Gene therapies targeting diseases like amyotrophic lateral sclerosis (ALS) and Huntington’s disease use RNAi to silence mutant genes causing the disease. Statement 2 is correct: Numerous studies have demonstrated that RNAi can provide a more specific approach to inhibit tumor growth by targeting cancer-related genes (i.e., oncogene). Researchers are investigating RNAi-based therapeuti","PW-1173":"Somatic Cell Nuclear Transfer (SCNT) is a technique used in cloning, where the nucleus of a somatic cell (any cell of the body other than a sperm or egg cell) is transferred into an egg cell whose nucleus has been removed. The SCNT-derived blastocyst used in reproductive cloning is implanted into the uterus of a surrogate mother, where it develops into a foetus and is carried to term. Option (c) is correct: SCNT is used in reproductive cloning of animals . This technique allows the creation of genetically identical animals, such as Dolly the sheep, the first mammal cloned from an adult somatic cell in 1996. The process involves taking the nucleus from a somatic cell (e.g., skin cell) of an adult animal and transferring it into an enucleated egg cell. The egg, now containing the somatic cell nucleus, begins to divide and develop into an embryo. This embryo can then be implanted into a surrogate mother to produce an offspring that is genetically identical to the donor animal. Fig.: Some classic examples of successful applications of biotechnology 12","PW-1174":"Genome sequencing is the process of determining the complete DNA sequence of an organism’s genome by identifying the precise order of nucleotides—adenine (A), thymine (T), cytosine (C), and guanine (G)—that make up its genetic material. This comprehensive analysis provides critical insights into an organism’s genetic information, including variations, mutations, and functional elements such as genes and regulatory regions. Statement 1 is correct: Genome sequencing can be used to identify specific genes or genetic markers in crops that confer resistance to diseases or tolerance to environmental stresses like drought. This allows plant breeders to select plants with these beneficial traits and accelerate crop improvement. Science and Technology 533 Statement 2 is correct: Genome sequencing speeds up the breeding process. Instead of relying on traditional trial- and-error methods to cross plants, scientists can use genome information to make more precise genetic selections. Statement 3 is correct: Genome sequencing can also help researchers understand how crops interact with pathogens (","PW-1175":"Viruses are obligate intracellular parasites, meaning they require a host cell to replicate. They can infect bacteria, fungi, plants, animals, and other viruses. Viruses that infect bacteria are called bacteriophages (or simply phages). These viruses play a crucial role in regulating bacterial populations. Phages attach to bacterial cells, inject their genetic material, and hijack the bacterial machinery to replicate themselves. This process often leads to the destruction (lysis) of the bacterial cell. Viruses that infect fungi are called mycoviruses (Mycophages). They do not have an extracellular phase (i.e., they lack the ability to move outside fungal cells). They are linked to plant diseases because they weaken fungi that help plant growth. Cryphonectria hypovirus 1 (CHV1) infects chestnut blight fungus (Cryphonectria parasitica). Plant viruses are well-known pathogens that cause significant economic losses in agriculture such as the Tobacco Mosaic Virus (TMV), Potato Virus Y (PVY), and Tomato Spotted Wilt Virus (TSWV). Plant viruses are typically transmitted by insects, nematode","PW-1176":"","PW-1177":"Mycorrhizae is a symbiotic association between a fungus and a plant. The term ‘mycorrhiza’ refers to the role of the fungus in the plant’s rhizosphere, its root system. Mycorrhiza plays important roles in plant nutrition, soil biology and soil chemistry. Statement 1 is correct: Trees host mycorrhizal fungus in their roots so they can absorb nutrients from the ground and resist the drought condition. These fungi exchange the carbon from the tree for vital nutrients including nitrogen, phosphate, and potassium from the soil. Statement 2 is correct: Mycorrhizal plants can withstand unfavourable soil conditions, high pH levels, droughts, and poisonous heavy metals. Statement 3 is correct: Mycorrhizae are symbiotic relationships between plant roots and specific soil fungi that are important for the ecosystem’s nutrient cycling and that help shield plants from environmental and cultural stress. Additionally, mycorrhizal fungi’s synthesis of oxalic acid contributes to disease suppression. 16","PW-1178":"Recombinant DNA technology entails changing genetic material outside of an organism to produce living organisms or their products with improved and desired traits. Using the appropriate vectors, this approach entails inserting DNA fragments from a number of sources that have the desired gene sequence. Manipulation in an organism’s genome is carried out either through the introduction of one or several new genes and regulatory elements or by decreasing or blocking the expression of endogenous genes through recombining genes and elements. Recombinant DNA technology, also known as genetic engineering, enables the transfer of genes across different species, including: Across different species of plants: Genes can be transferred between various plant species to introduce desirable traits. From animals to plants: Animal genes can be introduced into plants to confer new characteristics. From microorganisms to higher organisms: Microbial genes can be inserted into higher organisms, such as plants or animals, to impart beneficial properties. 17","PW-1179":"Brinjal is a resilient crop that thrives even in drought- prone areas and is cultivated throughout most of the country. In India, Bt brinjal was the first food crop to undergo evaluation for potential commercial release. Statement 1 is incorrect: A gene called cry1Ac from the soil bacterium Bacillus thuringiensis(and not fungus) was inserted into the brinjal to develop Bt Brinjal. This brinjal has been genetically modified to withstand insects like the Brinjal Fruit and Shoot Borer (Leucinodes orbonalis). Statement 2 is incorrect: Farmers will be free to save and sow as many seeds from Bt Brinjal open-pollinated cultivars as they like. They are not terminator seeds. Statement 3 is correct: Public resistance to Bt brinjal in India was driven by fears of allergic reactions, toxicity and long- term health effects. Statement 4 is correct: Environmentalists feared that introducing Bt brinjal could negatively impact biodiversity. The primary concern was the potential for cross-pollination with native brinjal varieties, which could lead to genetic contamination and loss of indigenous strain","PW-1180":"Genetic engineering is the direct manipulation of an organism’s genes using biotechnology techniques, allowing for the alteration of its DNA. Statement 1 is correct: GE crops have been engineered to withstand drought conditions which allows them to maintain productivity under water scarcity. For instance, genetically modified wheat with enhanced drought tolerance has been developed. Statement 2 is correct: Biofortification through genetic engineering has led to crops with enhanced nutritional profiles. Example: Golden Rice has been engineered to produce beta-carotene, a precursor of vitamin A. Statement 3 is incorrect: Genetic engineering for space- specific traits (like enhanced photosynthesis in low light or microgravity) is not a major application of genetically engineered plants presently. Research is ongoing into growing plants in space (Ex-NASA’s experiments with growing lettuce on the International Space Station) but these efforts primarily focus on optimizing growth conditions rather than genetically engineering plants. Statement 4 is correct: Genetic engineering has been use","PW-1181":"DNA Sequencing means determining the order of the four chemical building blocks - called “bases” - that make up the DNA molecule. This sequence informs scientists the kind of genetic information that is carried in a particular DNA segment. Statement 1 is correct: Pedigree analysis is the examination of a particular trait that is inherited from generation to generation. It helps in understanding the inheritance pattern of that trait and determining whether it is dominant or recessive. A thorough pedigree analysis using pedigree files received via DNA sequencing from the relevant breed organisations will certainly help in interpreting the pattern of inheritance of a livestock. Statement 2 is correct: Mapping genes allows researchers to identify genetic variations associated with diseases. This understanding facilitates the development of targeted therapies and personalized medicine approaches. Science and Technology 535 Statement 3 is incorrect: Knowledge of gene positions enables the identification of genes responsible for disease resistance. This information can be utilized to breed ","PW-1182":"Golden rice is a genetically modified variety of rice specifically engineered to address vitamin A deficiency. The grains of Golden rice are biofortified with beta-carotene, a precursor of vitamin A (pro-vitamin A). When consumed, beta- carotene is converted into vitamin A in the human body, making golden rice an important dietary intervention to combat vitamin A deficiency, particularly in developing countries where this deficiency is prevalent and can lead to serious health issues like blindness. 22","PW-1183":"","PW-1184":"The Ministry of Rural Development was designated as the nodal ministry for implementing the National Biodiesel Mission during its initial phases. The mission focused on cultivating Jatropha curcas, a non-edible oilseed crop, on wastelands to produce biodiesel. Jatropha is a plant of Latin American origin, which is now widespread throughout arid and semi-arid tropical regions of the world. This initiative aimed to achieve energy security, promote rural development, and provide an alternative source of livelihood for farmers in marginal and degraded lands. 24","PW-1185":"Enzyme-linked immunosorbent assay (ELISA) is a laboratory technique that detects and measures the amount of specific substances in a solution. Statement 1 is incorrect: The ELISA (Enzyme-Linked Immunosorbent Assay) test is primarily used to detect the presence of antibodies or antigens in the blood, and it is widely employed for diagnosing infections such as HIV, rather than cancer. It is not the first or basic test for cancer detection. Cancer is typically diagnosed using imaging techniques (e.g., MRI, CT scans), biopsies, or specific blood marker tests. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 536 Statement 2 is incorrect: The Rh factor, also known as the Rhesus factor, is a protein that can be present on the surface of red blood cells. Individuals with this protein are classified as Rh-positive (Rh+), while those without it are Rh-negative (Rh-). Globally, the distribution of Rh factor is not evenly split. Approximately 94% of the world’s population is Rh-positive, and only about 6% is Rh-negative. This distribution varies among different populations and regions. 25","PW-1186":"Dr. V. Mohan Reddy is renowned for performing a successful open-heart procedure called the arterial switch operation on an infant. This operation is a complex cardiac surgery used to correct transposition of the great arteries, a congenital heart defect where the major arteries are reversed. This breakthrough surgery provided new hope for treating congenital heart diseases in infants and gained recognition as a landmark achievement in pediatric cardiac surgery. 26","PW-1187":"Stem cells are undifferentiated cells with the potential to develop into various specialized cell types, offering promise for regenerative medicine and disease treatment Statement 1 and 2 are incorrect: The blastocyst stage of embryos is a common source of embryonic stem cells, but it is not the only source. Stem cells can also be derived from adult tissues (adult stem cells) and umbilical cord blood. As of current techniques, obtaining embryonic stem cells typically requires the destruction of the blastocyst. Alternative methods are being actively researched to derive stem cells without causing harm to the blastocyst. Statement 3 is correct: Stem cells, such as embryonic stem cells have the ability to self-renew and regenerate themselves in vitro indefinitely under appropriate conditions. This property makes them valuable for research and therapeutic applications. Statement 4 is correct: Indian research centers, such as the National Centre for Biological Sciences (NCBS) and the Indian Council of Medical Research (ICMR), have successfully created a few stem cell lines capable of diff","PW-1188":"Monsanto, an American multinational company, developed an insect-resistant cotton variety known as Bt cotton. This transgenic cotton incorporates a gene from the bacterium Bacillus thuringiensis (Bt), enabling the plant to produce Bt toxins that are effective against specific insect pests, particularly lepidopteran larvae like the cotton bollworm. The introduction of the Bt gene allows the cotton to produce its own insecticide, reducing the need for external chemical insecticides. 28","PW-1189":"DNA fingerprinting is biotechnique based on analysis of specific regions of DNA that are unique to each individual. This makes it a powerful forensic tool. Assertion (A) is true: DNA fingerprinting, also known as DNA profiling, has become a powerful tool in forensic science for identifying individuals. It is widely used to establish paternity and to identify suspects in criminal cases, including rape and assault. The unique genetic makeup of each individual allows forensic experts to match DNA samples from crime scenes with those of suspects or to determine biological relationships. Reason (R) is true: Trace evidence such as hair, saliva, and dried semen can provide sufficient DNA for analysis. Even small biological samples left at crime scenes can be collected and processed to extract DNA, which can then be compared to known samples to identify individuals. Both Assertion (A) and Reason (R) are true, and Reason (R) correctly explains why DNA fingerprinting is effective in establishing paternity and identifying criminals in rape and assault cases. The ability to analyze DNA from mini","PW-1190":"Insect-resistant cotton, commonly known as Bt cotton, has been genetically engineered by inserting a gene from the bacterium Bacillus thuringiensis (Bt). This bacterium naturally produces a protein toxic to specific insect pests, such as bollworms, but is safe for humans and non-target organisms. The Bt gene produces a protein that disrupts the digestive system of the pests upon ingestion, ultimately killing them. Bt cotton has significantly reduced the dependence on chemical insecticides and has become a widely adopted technology for pest management in cotton farming. 30","PW-1191":"","PW-1192":"Cloning is the process of creating genetically identical copies of an organism, cell, or DNA sequence. It can be natural (as in identical twins) or artificial (like somatic cell nuclear transfer, used in Dolly the sheep). Assertion (A) is true: Dolly the sheep, born in 1996, was the first mammal successfully cloned from an adult somatic cell, making her a landmark achievement in biotechnology. Reason (R) is false: Dolly was not produced through in vitro fertilization (IVF), which involves the fusion of sperm and egg outside the body. She was created using somatic cell nuclear transfer (SCNT), a process in which the nucleus of a somatic cell (in Dolly’s case, a mammary gland cell) was transferred into an enucleated egg cell (an egg cell with its nucleus removed). The resulting cell was stimulated to divide and develop into an embryo, which was then implanted into a surrogate sheep for gestation. 33","PW-1193":"","PW-1194":"About the Wolbachia Method Wolbachia is a type of bacterium, that can be introduced into mosquitoes to diminish their capacity for transmitting diseases. Fig: Wolbachia method Wolbachia method is used to control the population of mosquitoes and thus helps in controlling viral diseases such as zika, dengue, and chikungunya spread by the mosquitoes. In this method, the male Aedes Aegypti mosquitoes with Wolbachia mate with wild female mosquitoes that do not have Wolbachia, the eggs will not hatch and thus leads to sterilisation. 36","PW-1195":"Probiotics are live microorganisms that are intended to have health benefits when consumed or applied to the body. Statement 1 is correct: Probiotics can be composed of bacteria, yeast, or both. The most common types of bacteria used as probiotics are Lactobacillus and Bifidobacterium, while Saccharomyces boulardii is an example of a yeast that is sometimes used as a probiotic. Statement 2 is incorrect: Probiotics contain microorganisms that are similar to or the same as those naturally present in our bodies, especially in the digestive tract. Our gut microbiota consists of many types of bacteria, some of which are also found in probiotic products. These probiotics are often called “good” or “friendly” bacteria because they support gut health. Statement 3 is correct: Some probiotic bacteria, like Lactobacillus, produce an enzyme called lactase, which helps in the digestion of milk sugar (lactose). Lactase breaks down lactose into simpler sugars, making it easier for the body to absorb. This is especially helpful for people who are lactose intolerant and have difficulty digesting dair","PW-1196":"Mitochondrial diseases are a group of genetic disorders caused by dysfunction in the mitochondria, the cell’s energy- producing structures. Science and Technology 539 Statement 1 is correct: Mitochondrial Replacement Therapy (MRT) is an advanced reproductive technique designed to prevent the transmission of mitochondrial diseases from mother to child. MRT involves replacing defective mitochondria in an egg or embryo with healthy mitochondria from a donor. This can be achieved through methods such as: Spindle Transfer: Performed before fertilization, where the nuclear DNA from the mother’s egg is transferred to a donor egg with healthy mitochondria, followed by fertilization. Pronuclear Transfer: Conducted after fertilization, where the pronuclei (genetic material) from a fertilized egg are transferred into a donor zygote that has healthy mitochondria. These techniques aim to ensure that the resulting child inherits healthy mitochondria, thereby preventing mitochondrial diseases. Statement 2 is correct: A child inherits mitochondrial diseases entirely from the mother and not from the ","PW-1197":"ACE2 (Angiotensin Converting Enzyme 2) is a protein on the surface of many cell types and tissues, including the lungs, heart, blood vessels, kidneys, liver, and gastrointestinal tract. It serves as the entry point for certain coronaviruses, notably SARS-CoV-2, the virus responsible for COVID-19. The virus’s spike protein binds to the ACE2 receptor, facilitating its entry into host cells and leading to infection. 40","PW-1198":"Gene therapy is the ability to improve genes through the correction of misplaced (mutated) genes or site-specific alterations with therapeutic treatment as the target. A gene abnormality that has been identified in a child or embryo can be corrected using a variety of techniques known as gene therapy. In this instance, genes are injected to treat an illness into a person’s cells and tissues. Statement 1 is correct: Genetic modifications can be made to germ cells (sperm or eggs) of prospective parents. Techniques like CRISPR/Cas9 allow for precise editing of DNA in these cells, potentially preventing the transmission of genetic diseases to offspring. Statement 2 is correct: Genome editing technologies, such as CRISPR/Cas9, allow scientists to precisely modify DNA at the early embryonic stage to correct genetic defects. This approach, called germline editing, involves altering the genome of an embryo at its earliest stage of development, ensuring that all cells in the resulting organism carry the change. These genetic modifications are heritable, meaning they can be passed down to futu","PW-1199":"Statement 1 is correct: The Zika virus is primarily transmitted by the Aedes aegypti mosquito which is also the primary vector for dengue fever. This mosquito species thrives in tropical and subtropical regions, making it a common carrier for both diseases. The Aedes aegypti mosquito is well- adapted to urban environments and breeds in stagnant water, such as in containers, flower pots, and discarded tires. Statement 2 is correct: Zika virus can be transmitted through sexual contact unlike other mosquito-borne diseases like dengue or chikungunya. The virus can remain in semen for an extended period even after symptoms have resolved. Zika virus infection during pregnancy can cause severe birth defects such as microcephaly. 42","PW-1200":"According to the Food Safety and Standards (Packaging and Labeling) Regulations, 2011, pre-packaged items in India must display key information, including:  Nutrition information  List of ingredients (including additives)  Vegetarian/Non-vegetarian label  Date of manufacture and packing  Best-before date  Lot number, Code number, or Batch number The regulations mandate that foods containing allergens such as cereals containing gluten, nuts, soybeans, milk, and fish must declare the presence of these allergens on the label. However, the regulations do not require a specific medical recommendation regarding allergic reactions 43","PW-1201":"Muscle contraction is a complex physiological process regulated by nerve impulses and the interaction of muscle proteins actin and myosin. Key minerals involved in muscle contraction include: Calcium (Ca), Sodium (Na) , Potassium (K), Magnesium (Mg). Option 1 is correct: Calcium ions are essential for muscle contraction. They bind to regulatory proteins within muscle fibers, facilitating the interaction between actin and myosin, the proteins responsible for muscle contraction. Without adequate calcium, muscles cannot contract properly. Option 2 is correct: Iron helps to support continued function- ing of the muscle by supporting energy production in your mus- cle cells, so that muscle fibres always have the energy they need to contract properly. Also supports healthy circulation so that muscles can receive additional oxygen from the bloodstream and helps muscles store oxygen to power muscle contractions. Option 3 is correct: Sodium is crucial for initiating and transmitting nerve impulses that lead to muscle contrac- tion. It helps generate action potentials in nerve cells, which the","PW-1202":"Biopesticides are various biologically active natural substances that exist in nature and have inhibitory effects on crop diseases and insect pests. In general, the creation of biopesticide depends to a large extent on biological resources. Option (d) is correct: Three major classes of biopesticides are: Class of Biopesticides Description Examples Microbial Pesticides Consist of microorganisms (bacteria, fungi, viruses, or protozoa) as active ingredients for pest control. These may be naturally occurring, dead or alive, or genetically engineered. Bacillus thuringiensis (Bt) – produces toxins harmful to specific insects. Fungal Biopesticides Some fungi act as biopesticides by infecting and killing pests. Entomopathogenic fungi target insects, while others combat plant pathogens. Entomopathogenic fungi – infect and kill insects. Plant- Incorporated- Protectants (PIPs) Pesticidal substances that plants produce from inserted genetic material. Genetically modified corn and cotton, Neem oil (Azadirachta indica) – possesses insecticidal properties. 45","PW-1203":"Statement 1 is correct: Ultraviolet (UV) radiation effectively neutralizes harmful microorganisms like bacteria, viruses, and protozoa. It damages their DNA by disrupting the thymine bases, preventing reproduction and rendering them harmless. Statement 2 is incorrect: UV radiation does not remove chemical compounds or gases that cause undesirable odors in water. These require additional processes like activated carbon filtration or oxidation techniques. Statement 3 is incorrect: UV radiation does not affect solid particles, turbidity, or water clarity. These issues require mechanical filtration or sedimentation processes, such as sand filters or coagulation methods. 46","PW-1204":"A stem cell is a special type of cell that can develop into different cell types and has the ability to self-renew, helping in growth, repair, and regeneration of tissues in the body. Statement 1 is incorrect: Stem cells are not exclusive to mammals. They can be derived from a variety of organisms, including plants, non-mammalian animals, and other sources. For instance, plants have meristematic cells (responsible for the root and shoot growth of plants), which function similarly to stem cells in animals. Statement 2 is correct: Stem cells, especially induced pluripotent stem cells (iPSCs) and embryonic stem cells, are used in drug screening and toxicity testing. They help in assessing drug responses in a controlled laboratory setting. Statement 3 is correct: Stem cells have significant applications in regenerative medicine, including treatments for blood disorders (like leukemia), neurodegenerative diseases, and tissue repair. Bone marrow transplants, for example, rely on hematopoietic stem cells. 47","PW-1205":"Any substance that can inhibit the formation of unstable molecules known as free radicals, which harm DNA, cell membranes, and other components of cells, is referred to as an “antioxidant.” Free radicals grab electrons from other molecules in order to complete their electron complement, which causes those molecules to suffer damage. Regular consumption of fresh fruits and vegetables is recommended because they are rich sources of antioxidants. Antioxidants play a crucial role in maintaining health and promoting longevity by neutralizing free radicals produced during metabolism. Free radicals are unstable molecules that can damage cells, proteins, and DNA, contributing to ageing and various diseases. By donating electrons, antioxidants stabilize free radicals, thereby preventing cellular damage and supporting overall health. 3. DISEASES 48","PW-1206":"Adenoviruses are non-enveloped, double-stranded DNA viruses that infect a wide range of hosts, including humans. They are known for their ability to efficiently infect various cell types. A retrovirus is a virus that uses RNA as its genetic material. Upon infection with a retrovirus, a cell converts the retroviral RNA into DNA, which in turn is inserted into the DNA of the host. Statement 1 is incorrect: Adenoviruses possess linear, double-stranded DNA genomes whereas retroviruses have single-stranded RNA genomes. Upon infecting a host cell, retroviruses use the enzyme reverse transcriptase to convert their RNA into double-stranded DNA, which is then integrated into the host’s genome. Statement 2 is correct: Adenoviruses are known to cause respiratory illnesses, including symptoms similar to the common cold. AIDS (Acquired Immunodeficiency Syndrome) is caused by the Human Immunodeficiency Virus (HIV), which is a retrovirus. 49","PW-1207":"A Recombinant Vector Vaccine is a vaccine that uses a genetically modified virus or bacterium as a carrier to deliver pathogen-specific genes, triggering an immune response. Statement 1 is correct: Recombinant vector vaccines are developed using genetic engineering to insert genes encoding antigens into harmless viruses or bacteria, which serve as vectors. These vectors deliver the genetic material into the body, enabling the expression of target antigens and triggering an immune response against the pathogen. Examples include viral vector vaccines like Oxford-AstraZeneca (ChAdOx1 nCoV-19) and Sputnik V for COVID-19. Statement 2 is correct: Both bacteria (such as Salmonella) and viruses (such as adenoviruses and vesicular stomatitis virus) can be used as vectors to deliver genetic material into host cells to stimulate an immune response. 50","PW-1208":"Statement 1 is correct: PCVs protect against infections caused by Streptococcus pneumoniae, which can lead to pneumonia, meningitis, and sepsis. This is particularly important in India, where pneumococcal diseases contribute significantly to child mortality. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 542 Statement 2 is correct: By preventing pneumococcal infections, PCVs decrease the need for antibiotics, thereby mitigating the risk of developing and spreading antibiotic-resistant bacteria. Statement 3 is incorrect: Like other vaccines, PCVs can have mild side effects such as fever, redness at the injection site, and, in rare cases, allergic reactions. No vaccine is completely free of side effects. SUPER HINT See, S2 uses \"CAN be reduced\", hence possibility logic likely true, but S3 uses absolute term \"NO SIDE effect\". is it possible a vaccine cause no side effect? unlikely hence S3 false. 51","PW-1209":"Antimicrobial Resistance (AMR) is the ability of microorganisms like bacteria, viruses, fungi, and parasites to resist the effects of antimicrobial drugs, making infections harder to treat. When microorganisms such as bacteria develop resistance to multiple drugs, it is specifically termed Multidrug Resistance (MDR), posing a serious challenge to effective treatment. Statement 1 is incorrect: Multi-drug resistance is primarily a result of microbial adaptation, excessive antibiotic use, and misuse rather than human genetic predisposition. Genetic predisposition is a genetic trait that, in response to environmental factors, may influence the potential phenotypic development of an individual organism within a species or community. Antibiotic resistance is not related to the genetic tendency of a small minority of persons in a society. Statement 2 is correct: Misuse of antibiotics, such as incorrect dosing, premature discontinuation of prescribed antibiotics, or self-medication, allows bacteria to survive and develop resistance. WHO mentions inappropriate use of antibiotics as a major dr","PW-1210":"The Cas9 protein, often referred to as “molecular scissors,” is an enzyme utilized in targeted gene editing. It originates from the CRISPR (Clustered Regularly Interspaced Short Palindromic Repeats) system, which serves as an adaptive immune mechanism in bacteria. Guided by a specific RNA sequence, Cas9 binds to a complementary DNA sequence and introduces a double-stranded break. This break facilitates targeted modifications, such as gene insertion, deletion, or correction. Cas9 has revolutionized genetic research and therapy by enabling precise edits in the genomes of various organisms, including plants, animals, and humans. This technology holds potential for treating genetic disorders, developing disease-resistant crops, and advancing gene therapy. 53","PW-1211":"Birds can act as carriers of plant pathogens. As they move through crops, pathogens may stick to their feathers, beaks, or feet, transferring them from infected plants to healthy ones. Dust particles often carry fungal spores or bacterial cells. When dust is blown by the wind, these pathogens can travel to new areas, causing infections in plants far from the original source. Rainwater, particularly during heavy downpours or storms, can facilitate the spread of pathogens. Raindrops pick up pathogens from infected plants or soil and splash them onto healthy plants, promoting disease transmission. Science and Technology 543 Wind plays a significant role in transporting pathogens such as fungal spores, bacteria, or insect vectors contaminated with viruses. This mechanism allows pathogens to infect plants located far from the initial infection site. SUPER HINT You can try, The \"NOT\" approach for all statements, this tests the improbability of negating a statement—if de- nying its impact seems highly unlikely, the statement is plausibly true. For Example: Birds or Rain or Wind NOT Spread p","PW-1212":"Pair 1 is correctly matched: Lip items like lipsticks and other cosmetics including eye shadow, blush, compact powder, shampoo, and body lotion frequently include the contaminant lead. Pair 2 is correctly matched: In some sodas and soft drinks, the citrus flavour is sometimes prevented from breaking out by the food additive brominated vegetable oil. Pair 3 is correctly matched: MSG is commonly added to Chinese fast food and other processed foods to enhance flavor. While it is generally recognized as safe, some individuals may experience sensitivity to MSG, leading to symptoms like headaches or nausea. 56","PW-1213":"Viruses can infect bacteria and are commonly known as bacteriophages. They attach to bacterial cells and inject their genetic material, leading to the production of new viral particles within the bacterial host. Viruses that infect fungi are termed mycoviruses. These viruses can influence the physiology and pathogenicity of their fungal hosts. Notably, studies have shown that fungi can acquire viruses and viroids from plants, indicating cross-kingdom transmission. Numerous viruses infect plants, causing a variety of diseases that can significantly impact agricultural productivity. These plant viruses can be transmitted through various means, including insect vectors, mechanical damage, and seed transmission. Ex- Tobacco Mosaic Virus (TMV), infect plants, causing diseases that affect crop yields and quality. 57","PW-1214":"","PW-1215":"Pair 1 is correctly matched: Scurvy is caused by a deficiency of Vitamin C (ascorbic acid). It leads to symptoms like bleeding gums, bruising, fatigue, and poor wound healing. Pair 2 is correctly matched: Rickets occurs due to Vitamin D deficiency, which impairs calcium absorption, leading to soft and weak bones in children. In adults, it can lead to osteomalacia. Pair 3 is incorrectly matched: Night blindness is caused by a deficiency of Vitamin A, not Vitamin E. Vitamin A is crucial for maintaining healthy vision, particularly in low-light conditions. Vitamin E deficiency, on the other hand, may lead to nerve and muscle damage or immune system issues. Vitamin Deficiency and Associated Conditions: Vitamin Deficiency Condition Vitamin A Night blindness Vitamin B1 Beriberi Vitamin B2 Ariboflavinosis Vitamin B3 Pellagra Vitamin B5 Paresthesia Vitamin B6 Anemia Vitamin B7 Dermatitis, enteritis Vitamin B9 & Vitamin B12 Megaloblastic anemia Vitamin C Scurvy, Swelling of Gums Vitamin D Rickets & Osteomalacia Vitamin E Less fertility Vitamin K Non-clotting of blood UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 544 ","PW-1216":"Diphtheria has not been eradicated in India. It remains a public health concern, with cases still reported annually. It is a bacterial disease caused by Corynebacterium diphtheriae. It primarily affects the respiratory system, causing symptoms such as a sore throat, fever, and difficulty breathing. A characteristic thick gray membrane forms on the throat and tonsils in severe cases. Diphtheria spreads through respiratory droplets or contact with contaminated objects. It is preventable through the DPT (Diphtheria-Pertussis-Tetanus) vaccine, which is part of India’s Universal Immunization Programme (UIP). Chickenpox has not been eradicated in India. It is a common infectious disease, particularly among children, and continues to occur throughout the country. It is caused by the Varicella-zoster virus (VZV), a highly contagious virus that spreads through respiratory droplets or direct contact with blisters. Symptoms include an itchy rash with red spots or blisters, fever, and fatigue. Following extensive surveillance and immunization campaigns, the World Health Organization (WHO) declar","PW-1217":"Viruses are microscopic infectious agents that require a host cell to reproduce. They consist of genetic material (DNA or RNA) surrounded by a protein coat (capsid). They can cause a wide range of diseases in humans, animals, and plants. Statement 1 is correct: Viruses are obligate intracellular parasites and lack the metabolic machinery, including enzymes, to generate energy. They depend entirely on their host cells for energy and replication. Statement 2 is incorrect: Viruses cannot replicate or survive in synthetic media alone. They require living host cells for replication. Common methods of culturing viruses include using cell cultures, embryonated eggs, or live animals. Statement 3 is incorrect: ​While some viruses are transmitted through biological vectors (e.g., mosquitoes for dengue), many are transmitted by other means such as: Respiratory droplets (e.g., influenza virus), Direct contact (e.g., herpes simplex virus), Fomites (e.g., contaminated surfaces). 61","PW-1218":"Tattoos may cause diseases because tattoo instruments come in contact with blood and bodily fluids if the instruments are used on more than one person without being sterilised. However, tattoo-related infections are uncommon in sterile, contemporary tattoo parlours using single-use needles. Hepatitis B is a bloodborne infection caused by the Hepatitis B virus (HBV) and is spread through contact with infected blood or bodily fluids. Unsafe tattooing practices, such as using unsterilized needles or contaminated ink, can easily transmit Hepatitis B. Studies show that Hepatitis B has a significantly high transmission risk through needlestick injuries or exposure to infected blood. HIV is transmitted through contact with infected blood, semen, vaginal fluids, or breast milk. Though the risk of HIV transmission through tattooing is lower compared to Hepatitis B, it exists if contaminated needles are used. Chikungunya is primarily transmitted through the bite of infected Aedes mosquitoes and is not spread through blood or contaminated instruments. 4. INFORMATION AND COMMUNICATION TECHNOLOGY","PW-1219":"Radar (Radio Detection And Ranging) is an electromagnetic sensor used for detecting, locating, tracking, and recognising objects of various kinds at considerable distances. It operates by transmitting electromagnetic energy toward objects, commonly referred to as targets, and observing the echoes returned from them. The targets may be aircraft, ships, spacecraft, automotive vehicles, astronomical bodies, or even birds, insects, and rain. Besides determining the presence, location, and velocity of such objects, radar can sometimes obtain their size and shape as well. Statement 1 is incorrect: Radar technology is being used in the fight against narcotics, but they are being used for interdiction of suspicious flights/aircraft in countries like Guatemala, Brazil and Bolivia and not directly in the identification of narcotics on passengers or in the aircraft. Statement 2 is correct: Radars, especially Doppler weather radars, are widely used to track precipitation, storm patterns, and weather conditions. Statement 3 is correct: Radars, such as avian radars, are used to monitor the movemen","PW-1220":"","PW-1221":"Software as a Service (SaaS) refers to software provided by a third party as a service where hosting and maintenance are managed by the provider. Unlike traditional methods requiring local deployment and maintenance SaaS allows direct access to software via thin clients such as web browsers. Statement 1 is correct: SaaS applications often provide customization options, allowing users to adjust the user interface (UI) and modify data fields according to their business requirements. However, customization is typically limited to certain areas defined by the service provider and may not involve deep structural changes. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 546 Statement 2 is correct: SaaS platforms are accessible via the internet and can be used across devices, including desktops, laptops, and mobile devices. This accessibility is a key feature of SaaS, as users can access their applications and data on the go through web browsers or mobile apps. Statement 3 is correct: Email services such as Outlook, Hotmail, and Yahoo Mail are classic examples of SaaS. They deliver email functionality over the interne","PW-1222":"Statement 1 is correct: A fundamental principle of Web 3.0 is to grant users ownership and control over their personal data, reducing reliance on centralized entities. This shift aims to enhance privacy and security for individuals. Statement 2 is correct: Web 3.0 leverages blockchain technology to create decentralized applications, including social networks. These platforms operate without central authorities, offering users greater control over content and data. Statement 3 is correct: Decentralization is a hallmark of Web 3.0, where control is distributed among users instead of being held by centralized corporations. This collective operation is facilitated through decentralized networks and consensus mechanisms. Feature Web 1.0 Web 2.0 Web 3.0 Web 4.0 Timeframe Roughly 1989- 2005 Roughly 2005-present Evolving Emerging Key Characteristic \"Read-only\" web \"Interactive\" or \"social\" web \"Semantic\" or \"decentralized\" web \"Intelligent\" or \"symbiotic\" web Focus Information consumption User- generated content, social interaction Data understanding, decentralization Intelligent connectivit","PW-1223":"Quantum computers are machines that use the properties of quantum physics to store data and perform computations. A classical computer performs operations using classical bits, which can be either 0 or 1. Quantum computer uses quantum bits or Qubits, which can be both 0 and 1 at the same time. Qubits (or quantum bits) are the units of computation in quantum computers. They take advantage of quantum mechanics characteristics, which regulate how matter behaves at the atomic level. Quantum computers are faster, more accurate, & energy efficient. Two important phenomena of quantum physics that are used to achieve functioning of quantum computing are: 1. Superimposition: Each quantum bit (basic unit of information in a quantum computer) can represent both a 1 and a 0 at the same time, which is known as superposition. 2. Quantum Entanglement: Subatomic particles become “entangled” (connected) in quantum entanglement, which means that any change in one upsets the other, even though they are at opposite ends of the universe. 67","PW-1224":"Short-Range Devices (SRDs) are communication technologies designed for limited-distance operations, typically within a few meters to a few hundred meters. Option 1 is correct: CCTV systems use video cameras to transmit signals to specific monitors for surveillance purposes. The transmission range of CCTV systems is generally confined to the premises being monitored, making them short-range by design. Option 2 is correct: RFID employs electromagnetic fields to automatically identify and track tags attached to objects. They are typically short-range, with passive RFID tags readable from up to a few meters and active tags extending up to 100 meters. Option 3 is correct: WLANs enable wireless network communication within a localized area, such as a home or office, using high-frequency radio waves. The effective range of WLANs is usually within 100 meters, categorizing them as short-range communication technologies. 68","PW-1225":"Statement 1 is correct: AI-powered systems are used in smart grids and industrial automation to minimize electricity consumption. AI algorithms analyze energy consumption patterns and adjust systems in real-time to reduce waste and improve efficiency. Statement 2 is correct: AI advancements such as natural language processing (NLP) and generative models like GPT can create meaningful short stories and songs. Tools like OpenAI’s GPT-3 and AI music generators demonstrate the ability to produce creative content that resonates with human audiences. Note: UPSC did not consider this option as correct probably because Generative AI was not so advanced at that time. Statement 3 is correct: AI is widely used in healthcare for disease diagnosis. Machine learning algorithms analyze medical data such as imaging scans, genetic information, and patient records to detect diseases like cancer, diabetes, and cardiovascular conditions with high accuracy. AI systems like IBM Watson and Google DeepMind are prominent examples. Statement 4 is correct: AI-powered text-to-speech (TTS) systems such as Google","PW-1226":"Visible Light Communication (VLC) uses visible light for data communication. Optical wireless communications methods include VLC as a subset. Because light-producing equipment (such as indoor/outdoor lamps, TVs, traffic signs, commercial displays, and car headlights/taillights) are utilised everywhere, VLC can be employed as a communications channel for ubiquitous computing. Statement 1 is correct: Visible Light Communication (VLC) operates within the visible light spectrum which ranges from approximately 375 nm (violet) to 780 nm (red). VLC uses light-emitting diodes (LEDs) to transmit data by modulating light intensity. Statement 2 is incorrect: VLC is considered a short-range communication technology due to the limitations of light propagation. It is effective over short distances such as within a room or confined space and is not designed for long-range communication like radio frequency (RF) technologies. Statement 3 is correct: VLC has the potential to transmit data at very high speeds often exceeding the data rates of Bluetooth. VLC can achieve data rates in the range of gigab","PW-1227":"Statement 1 is correct: Cost of restoration of the computer system in case of malware disrupting access to one’s computer is generally covered under cyber insurance policies. If a malware attack disrupts access to your computer system the insurance can covers the expenses related to restoring the system to its original state. Statement 2 is incorrect: Cyber insurance policies do not cover physical damage to hardware. They primarily focus on digital and financial losses. If a computer is physically damaged by a miscreant, it would fall under general insurance or property insurance rather than cyber insurance. These insurance policies are primarily focused on addressing losses arising from cybercrimes affecting data and software. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 548 Statement 3 is correct: Cyber insurance often covers the cost of hiring cybersecurity experts, consultants, or negotiators to minimize financial and reputational losses in case of cyber extortion such as ransomware attacks. Statement 4 is correct: Cyber insurance policies often provide coverage for legal defense costs if a third party ","PW-1228":"Blockchain technology is a decentralized and secure system for recording and verifying transactions across multiple computers. It uses cryptography to link blocks of data together in a chain, making it difficult to alter or tamper with the information. This technology has applications in various fields, including finance, supply chain management, and healthcare. Statement 1 is correct: Blockchain operates as a decentralized and distributed ledger, allowing all participants to view transactions without granting control to any single user. This transparency and lack of central authority are fundamental characteristics of blockchain technology. Statement 2 is incorrect: While blockchain gained prominence through cryptocurrencies like Bitcoin, its applications extend far beyond digital currencies. Blockchain’s versatile structure supports various uses, including supply chain management, healthcare data management, and identity verification, among others. Statement 3 is correct: Public blockchain platforms, such as Ethereum, enable developers to build decentralized applications (dApps) wi","PW-1229":"Statement 1 is incorrect: LTE is a 4G (Fourth Generation) wireless communication standard, not 3G. It offers higher data transfer speeds compared to 3G technologies. VoLTE is a service that allows voice calls to be transmitted over the LTE network thereby providing high-quality voice services. Both LTE and VoLTE are associated with 4G technology, not 3G. Statement 2 is incorrect: LTE is not a data-only technology as it supports both data and voice services. However without VoLTE, voice calls on LTE networks typically fall back to 3G or 2G networks (a process called Circuit-Switched Fallback, or CSFB). VoLTE is not voice-only as it enhances voice call quality and efficiency while still supporting data services. 73","PW-1230":"Statement 1 is incorrect: AR overlays digital elements onto the real world, enhancing the user’s perception without replacing the physical environment. Examples include Pokémon Go and AR navigation apps. Statement 2 is incorrect: VR creates an immersive digital environment that replaces the real world entirely, isolating the user through devices like VR headsets. Examples include virtual classrooms and gaming environments. Statement 3 is correct: Augmented Reality enhances the user’s experience by integrating digital elements with their physical environment in real-time. AR applications utilize cameras on smartphones, tablets, or PCs to superimpose virtual features, such as graphics or text, over the real-world view displayed on the device’s screen. Statement 4 is correct: Virtual Reality isolates the user from their physical surroundings by immersing them in a fully simulated digital environment. VR systems achieve this through specialized devices, such as VR headsets, which block out external visual and auditory input. This technology is commonly used for gaming, training simulatio","PW-1231":"A digital signature is a type of electronic signature that can be used to verify the identity of the person sending a message or signing a document and to guarantee that the message’s or document’s original content hasn’t changed. Digital signatures are portable and impossible for anyone to forge. Statement 1 is incorrect: A digital signature is a cryptographic technique used to validate the authenticity and integrity of digital messages or documents. It is not primarily used to identify the certifying authority. A digital certificate serves that purpose by linking a public key with the identity of the certificate authority that issued it. Statement 2 is incorrect: While digital signatures can authenticate the origin of a message or document, their primary function is to ensure that the content has not been altered and to verify the sender’s identity in the context of that specific document. They are not typically used as general proof of identity for accessing information or servers; other mechanisms, such as passwords or digital certificates, serve that purpose Statement 3 is corre","PW-1232":"Electronic devices can be comfortably worn on the body are known as wearables. Real-time information tracking is done with these wearable gadgets. They have motion sensors that capture an image of user’s daily activity and sync it with laptops or mobile devices. Statement 1 is correct: Wearable devices like smartwatches and fitness trackers equipped with GPS can track a person’s real-time location which makes them useful for navigation, fitness activities, and safety purposes, especially for outdoor enthusiasts and travelers. Statement 2 is correct: Wearables can monitor sleep by analyzing heart rate, movement, and breathing patterns. Devices like the Oura Ring provide detailed insights into sleep quality, helping users identify issues and improve their overall sleep health. Statement 3 is correct: Certain wearables such as modern hearing aids and Apple’s AirPods Pro assists people with hearing impairments by amplifying sounds and reducing background noise, offering an affordable and efficient solution for mild-to-moderate hearing loss. SUPER HINT Observed Logic means using your real","PW-1233":"For assessing chlorophyll content from remote sensing data utilising a multispectral imaging system, the Normalized Area Vegetation Index (NAVI) has been developed. The most widely used instruments are radiometers and photometers, which can collect radiation that is emitted and reflected at a variety of frequencies. Additionally, they can be used to identify the emission spectra of different substances, providing information on atmospheric chemical concentrations. Statement 1 is correct: Satellite remote sensing such as hyperspectral imaging can estimate chlorophyll levels in vegetation by analyzing specific spectral wavelengths. This technique is widely used to evaluate plant health and productivity over large regions without requiring direct sampling. Statement 2 is correct: Advanced remote sensing tools, including drones with multispectral sensors, help monitor methane emissions from rice paddies. By integrating environmental data with computational models, these methods provide a non-invasive way to assess emissions across agricultural landscapes. Statement 3 is correct: Remote s","PW-1234":"GPS technology uses a network of satellites to pinpoint a user’s location on Earth. By receiving signals from multiple satellites, GPS devices can calculate precise latitude, longitude, and altitude coordinates. This technology has revolutionized navigation, transportation, and many other fields. Options 1 is correct: Smartphones use GPS to determine the user’s precise location which enables location-based services such as navigation, ride-sharing apps, geotagging, and emergency location tracking. Option 2 is correct: Financial institutions use GPS-derived time stamps to record the exact time of transactions, aiding in audit trails and fraud detection. GPS ensures that banking systems across different locations operate in sync, which is crucial for real-time processing and settlements. Options 3 is correct: GPS provides precise time references that are vital for synchronizing the operations of power grids, helping in load balancing and efficient energy distribution. 78","PW-1235":"Statement 1 is incorrect: ​ Smart India Hackathon (SIH) 2017 was not a centrally sponsored scheme for developing Smart Cities. It is a nationwide initiative to promote innovation and problem-solving among students by leveraging digital technology. The event was organized by the Ministry of Human Resource Development (MHRD) and the All India Council for Technical Education (AICTE) in collaboration with other government bodies. Statement 2 is correct: SIH was launched to encourage young minds to develop innovative solutions to challenges faced by ministries, departments, and public sector organizations. It provided a platform for students to collaborate on real-world problems using digital technology. Statement 3 is incorrect: The Smart India Hackathon is not related to making financial transactions digital. The initiative aimed at promoting digital financial transactions is the Digital India campaign, which includes programs like Unified Payments Interface (UPI), BHIM app, and Aadhaar-enabled payment systems. 80","PW-1236":" It is legally mandatory for service providers, data centres, and body corporate to report cybersecurity incidents to the Indian Computer Emergency Response Team (CERT-In). Under the Information Technology (IT) Act, 2000, and the Information Technology (The Indian Computer Emergency Response Team and Manner of Performing Functions and Duties) Rules, 2013. CERT-In is the national nodal agency for responding to cybersecurity incidents and ensuring the security of India’s cyber infrastructure. Science and Technology 551 :  The Indian Computer Emergency Response Team (CERT) imposes rules on service providers, intermediaries, data centres, body corporate or persons who provide the information called for or comply with the direction of CERT. They need to report cyber incidents within a reasonable time so that CERT-In may have scope for timely action. 81","PW-1237":"Statement 1 is correct: LiFi (Light Fidelity) uses visible light, ultraviolet, or infrared light to transmit data. This technology works through light-emitting diodes (LEDs), which modulate light signals at extremely high speeds to carry information. Unlike traditional radio frequency-based wireless systems, LiFi leverages the light spectrum for communication. Statement 2 is correct: LiFi is a wireless communication technology that does not require cables for data transmission. In laboratory conditions, it has demonstrated speeds significantly faster than WiFi, reaching up to 224 Gbps. However, its performance depends on line-of-sight and is more suitable for indoor environments. 82","PW-1238":"Near Field Communication (NFC) is a short-range wireless technology that allows devices to communicate by tapping or bringing them close together. NFC is used in various applications, including contactless payments, data exchange, and access control. Statement 1 is correct: NFC is a short-range wireless communication technology that enables devices to exchange data over distances typically up to 4 centimeters. It operates by generating electromagnetic fields through inductive coupling at a frequency of 13.56 MHz, which facilitates the transfer of information between devices. This contactless technology is widely used in mobile payments, access control, and data exchange. Statement 2 is incorrect: NFC technology is designed for an operation distance of a few centimeters(not meter). This makes it more difficult for attackers to record the communication between an NFC Forum Device and an NFC Forum Tag compared to other wireless technologies which have a working distance of several meters. Statement 3 is correct: NFC technology incorporates encryption methods to secure data transmission,","PW-1239":"Biometrics identification is a form of identification and access control. Biometric identifiers are the distinct, measurable characteristics used to label individuals. Physiological characteristics are distinguished from behavioural traits when classifying biometric identifiers. Fingerprint, palm veins, face recognition, DNA, palm print, hand geometry, iris recognition, retina, and odour/scent are examples of physiological biometric identifiers. Visible and near - infrared light used captures and analyzes the unique patterns in the colored part of the eye surrounding the pupil. It is a highly reliable and accurate biometric method used in security and access control systems. It is used in Aadhaar biometric identification in India. Retinal scanning maps the unique pattern of blood vessels in the retina at the back of the eye. This method is highly accurate but less commonly used due to its intrusive nature, requiring the user to position their eye close to the scanner. Voice recognition analyzes the unique characteristics of an individual’s voice, such as tone, pitch, and rhythm, for ","PW-1240":"","PW-1241":"The 2.4 GHz and 2.5 GHz ISM band (Industrial, Scientific, and Medical) is a part of the radio frequency spectrum commonly used for short-range communication technologies. This range is globally available for unlicensed use, making it ideal for a variety of wireless communication applications. Bluetooth devices, cordless phones, microwave ovens, Wi-Fi baby monitors, wireless cameras, and RFID systems operate in the 2.4 to 2.5 GHz range of the radio frequency band. While it allows a variety of devices to operate within it, managing interference is a key challenge in environments with multiple devices using the same frequency. This range is commonly used due to its balance between range and data capacity, making it suitable for short- range communication and other applications. 87","PW-1242":"WiMAX (WIMAX forum was formed in June 2001 to promote conformity and interoperability) is a communication technology that provides high-speed wireless broadband internet access. It is designed to offer both fixed and mobile broadband services over long distances, often as a replacement or supplement to traditional wired broadband technologies like digital subscriber line (DSL) or cable. Broadband Internet Access, Wireless Backhaul (for wireless link between a cellular base station and the core network) and Mobile Broadband etc. are based on WiMAX technology. It provides high-speed internet access, bridging the connectivity gap for both urban and rural areas, especially in the last-mile segment. 89","PW-1243":"Statement 1 is correct: Adam Osborne introduced the first portable computer, the Osborne 1, in 1981, which marked the beginning of portable computing. The computer featured a 12.7-centimetre (5-inch) screen and weighed Nearly 12 kg. However, the machine still required an AC outlet for power. Statement 2 is correct: Ian Wilmut is a British scientist who, in 1996, led the team that cloned Dolly the sheep. Dolly was the first mammal cloned using somatic cell nuclear transfer (SCNT), a process where the nucleus of an adult somatic cell is transferred into an enucleated egg cell. Dolly’s creation marked a major milestone in the field of biotechnology and cloning. Science and Technology 553 90","PW-1244":"Statement 1 is correct: A smart card is a physical card embedded with an integrated circuit chip, which can be a microcontroller or a memory chip. This chip enables the card to store and process data, making it useful for applications like secure identification and payment systems. Statement 2 is correct: Digital technology relies heavily on modern communication infrastructures, including satellites and fiber optics, which enable high-speed and efficient data transmission. Statement 3 is incorrect: Digital libraries are organized collections of digital materials, such as text, images, and multimedia, which can be accessed through the internet or local electronic systems, making them available in multiple forms. 91","PW-1245":"In computing, memory is typically measured in units such as 1 byte = 8 bit ( short for binary digit) or megabytes (MB). A byte is the basic unit of digital information storage and consists of eight binary digits, commonly referred to as bits. Each bit represents a binary value of either 0 or 1, enabling a byte to store 2^8 (256) possible values, ranging from 0 to 255 in decimal notation. This structure forms the foundation of data representation in computers. 92","PW-1246":"","PW-1247":"Statement 1 is correct: Carbon fibre is a material consisting of very thin filaments of carbon atoms. Carbon fibers are fibers characterized by a carbon content of 90% or higher. The principal rationale behind the aerospace industry’s adoption of carbon fiber lies in the weight reduction it offers. Statement 2 is incorrect: Carbon fibre is environmentally friendly and exhibits a longer life cycle. There are numerous technologies to recycle carbon fibres. 95","PW-1248":"Nanoscience is the study of matter at the nanoscale dimensions between approximately 1 and 100 nanometers or 1,000 times smaller than the width of a human hair. At these incredibly small scales, materials have unique phenomena that enable new applications. Statement 1 is incorrect: Other than lab-made, nanoparticles are also naturally found in the environment and are formed through processes such as volcanic eruptions, forest fires, and photochemical reactions. Examples include naturally occurring metal nanoparticles like silver (AgNPs) and gold nanoparticles (AuNPs) in water bodies. Statement 2 is correct: Metallic oxide nanoparticles, including titanium dioxide (TiO₂) and zinc oxide (ZnO), are commonly used in cosmetics like sunscreens and makeup. These nanoparticles provide UV protection and enhance the product’s properties, such as its texture and durability. Statement 3 is correct: The increasing use of nanoparticles in commercial products has raised concerns about their environmental and health impacts. Certain nanoparticles, like titanium dioxide used in some products, have be","PW-1249":"Carbon nanotubes are cylindrical structures made of carbon atoms arranged in a hexagonal lattice. They possess exceptional strength, high electrical conductivity, and unique mechanical properties, making them promising materials for applications in electronics, materials science, and nanotechnology. Statement 1 is correct: Carbon nanotubes (CNTs) have been widely researched for their role in drug delivery systems. Their unique hollow structure allows them to transport therapeutic molecules directly to targeted cells, improving treatment precision and effectiveness. Functionalization of CNTs enhances biocompatibility and minimizes toxicity. Statement 2 is incorrect: Carbon nanotubes have applications in tissue engineering, including constructing artificial blood vessels. Their mechanical strength and ability to support cell growth make them useful for creating scaffolds that mimic natural capillaries, promoting tissue repair. However, UPSC in its official answer key has not given recognition to this development and marked statement 2 as incorrect. Statement 3 is correct: Due to their ","PW-1250":": Nanotechnology is a field of science and engineering that deals with the manipulation of matter on an atomic and molecular scale, typically between 1 to 100 nanometers. It involves the design, synthesis, characterization, and application of materials, devices, and systems at this incredibly small scale. This emerging field has the potential to revolutionize various sectors, including medicine, electronics, materials science, and energy, by creating new materials with unique properties and developing innovative technologies with unprecedented capabilities. Statement 1 is correct: Targeted drug distribution by nanoscale drug carriers is one of the fundamental tenets of nanomedicine. Numerous nanoscale drug delivery technologies, such as liposomes, dendrimers, quantum dots, nanotubes, polymeric biodegradable nanoparticles, and nanocapsules, have been studied. Statement 2 is correct: Nanotechnology plays a significant role in gene therapy by creating nanocarriers that can deliver genetic material, such as DNA or RNA, to specific cells. These nanocarriers protect genetic material from d","PW-1251":"","PW-1252":"Stars are classified based on their size, mass, and brightness into categories such as giant stars and dwarf stars. Giant stars are massive, highly luminous stars that burn They are often in the later stages of stellar evolution. Dwarf stars, on the other hand, are smaller, less luminous, Red dwarfs, the most common type, can burn for trillions of years, while white dwarfs are the remnants of low to medium- mass stars after they exhaust their nuclear fuel. Statement I is incorrect: Giant stars have much shorter lifespans than dwarf stars. Giant stars burn fuel quickly because of their high mass and energy, while red dwarf stars use fuel slowly, allowing them to last billions or even trillions of years. Statement II is correct: Giant stars have much higher core temperatures and pressures, leading to faster nuclear fusion rates compared to dwarf stars. This high rate of fusion results in a shorter lifespan. SUPER HINT S2 mentions greater rate of nuclear reaction in giant star hence logically it must last less due to early fuel finish, this contradicts with S1. Hence correct answer is e","PW-1253":"Pair 1 is not correct: Cepheids, also known as Cepheid Variables, are stars that periodically brighten and dim. Due to their behaviour, these objects can function as cosmic indicators, extending their usefulness as yardsticks for distances up to several tens of millions of light-years away, owing to a consistent relationship between their brightness and other factors. Pair 2 is not correct: A nebula is a very large cloud of gas and dust in outer space. A dead star’s explosion, such as a supernova, releases gas and dust, which in turn forms certain nebulae (more than one nebula). Other nebulae are places where brand-new stars are only starting to develop. It is for this reason that some nebulae are referred to as “star nurseries.” Pair 3 is correct: Pulsars are extremely compact, rapidly spinning neutron stars that have a diameter of no more than 20 km (12 miles). They are virtually entirely made of neutrons that are formed when massive stars run out of fuel and collapse. 101","PW-1254":"The term “Global Navigation Satellite System” (GNSS) encompasses any satellite network offering positioning, navigation, and timing (PNT) services either globally or within specific regions.The Quasi- Zenith Satellite System (QZSS) stands as a regional GNSS owned by the Government of Japan, aiming to bolster coverage in East Asia and Oceania while complementing GPS. 102","PW-1255":"A solar storm is a disturbance on the Sun that can release a burst of energy and particles into space. These eruptions, such as solar flares and coronal mass ejections, can impact Earth by disrupting communication systems, damaging satellites, and even causing power outages. Statements 1 and 7 are correct: These solar explosions propel bursts of particles and electromagnetic fluctuations into Earth’s atmosphere that could lead to the malfunction of satellites, which might impact high-frequency communication blackouts, satellite anomalies, GPS scintillations, airline communication. Statement 2 is incorrect: Solar storms affect the Earth’s magnetosphere and ionosphere but do not directly cause tsunamis, which are triggered by seismic activity, underwater landslides, or volcanic eruptions. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 556 Statement 3 is correct: The solar explosions propel bursts of particles and electromagnetic fluctuations into Earth’s atmosphere that could destroy transformers in power systems. Statement 4 is correct: Energy, radiation and high energy particles emitted by solar flares can tr","PW-1256":"Astronomical distances are measured in light-years to effectively express the vast distances in space using a consistent and universal unit. A light-year represents the distance light travels in one year in a vacuum, which is approximately 9.46 trillion kilometers (5.88 trillion miles). Astronomers calculate the distances of stars and other celestial objects in the time it takes for light to reach us since estimating distances in miles or kilometres is inadequate on the cosmological scale. Since the speed of light is known to be constant throughout the universe and for high precision, astronomical distances are expressed in terms of light-years. The fastest light can move is in vacuum. 104","PW-1257":"","PW-1258":"","PW-1259":"General theory of relativity, is a geometric theory related to gravitation published by Albert Einstein in 1915 and currently defines gravitation in modern physics. A coherent account of gravity as a geometric property of space and time, or four-dimensional spacetime, is provided by general relativity, which generalises special relativity and improves Newton’s law of universal gravitation. In particular, the energy and momentum of all matter and radiation present have a direct relationship to the curvature of spacetime. Statement 1 is correct: According to General Relativity, light travels along the curved spacetime shaped by the gravity of massive objects. This phenomenon, known as gravitational lensing, has been observed in effects such as Einstein’s Cross and the bending of starlight around the Sun. Science and Technology 557 Statement 2 is correct: General Theory of Relativity showed that space and time are malleable or flexible, and predicted that our universe was ever expanding. Statement 3 is correct: The theory of relativity states that massive objects distort spacetime aroun","PW-1260":"Statement 1 is correct: The Polar Satellite Launch Vehicle (PSLV) is primarily used to place satellites in Sun- Synchronous Polar Orbits (SSO), which are ideal for Earth observation, remote sensing, and resource monitoring. The Geosynchronous Satellite Launch Vehicle (GSLV) is used to place communication satellites into Geostationary Transfer Orbit (GTO), from where they move into Geostationary Orbit (GEO) for telecom and broadcasting services. Statement 2 is incorrect: Geostationary satellites (which remain fixed over a location) are launched into Geostationary Orbit (GEO) at 35,786 km altitude, usually by GSLV, not PSLV. PSLV typically places satellites in Low Earth Orbit (LEO) or Sun-Synchronous Orbit (SSO), where they move relative to the Earth’s surface. Statement 3 is incorrect: GSLV Mk III (now LVM3) is actually a three-stage launch vehicle: First stage: Two solid rocket boosters (S200) Second stage: A liquid-fueled core stage (L110) Third stage: A cryogenic stage (C25) There is no fourth stage in GSLV Mk III, making the statement incorrect. SUPER HINT For S2, PSLV places sate","PW-1261":"The terms ‘Event Horizon’, ‘Singularity’, ‘String Theory’, and ‘Standard Model’ are primarily associated with the observation and understanding of the Universe. Event Horizon is the boundary of a black hole where escape velocity exceeds the speed of light and thus nothing, including light, can escape once crossed. A gravitational singularity is a region in space where matter is infinitely dense, and gravitational forces become infinite. It is found at the center of black holes, where spacetime curvature becomes infinite, and the equations of general relativity fail to provide a meaningful description. String Theory is a theoretical framework in physics that attempts to reconcile quantum mechanics and general relativity by positing that fundamental particles are not point-like but rather one-dimensional “strings.” It is a candidate for a theory of everything, aiming to explain all fundamental forces and particles in the Universe. Standard Model is the theory in particle physics that describes three of the four known fundamental forces (electromagnetic, weak, and strong interactions) a","PW-1262":"The evolved Laser Interferometer Space Antenna (eLISA) is a mission led by the European Space Agency (ESA) to detect and measure gravitational waves. Gravitational waves are ripples in spacetime caused by massive cosmic events, such as merging black holes or neutron stars. eLISA aims to provide a new way of observing the universe by directly measuring these waves which are otherwise invisible to traditional telescopes. Unlike ground-based detectors like LIGO, eLISA will operate in space, allowing it to observe lower-frequency gravitational waves that cannot be detected on Earth. : Other Projects to Measure The Gravitational Waves Project Country (Locations) Remarks LIGO (Laser Interferometer Gravitational- Wave Observatory) Observatories in the USA and Italy Made the first direct detection of gravitational waves in 2015. LIGO-India India, Planned Ground-based interferometer that collaborates with LIGO to detect gravitational waves. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 558 Virgo Italy Virgo collaborates with LIGO and KAGRA to pinpoint the origins of these waves. KAGRA (Kamioka Gravitational Wave Dete","PW-1263":"AstroSat is the first dedicated Indian astronomy mission aimed to study celestial sources in X-ray, optical and UV spectral bands. The payloads cover the energy bands of Ultraviolet (Near and Far), limited optical and X-ray regime (0.3 keV to 100keV). The ability to simultaneously observe multiple celestial objects at multiple wavelengths with a single satellite is one of the special aspects of the AstroSat project. Statement 1 is incorrect: India has joined the exclusive club of nations with its own space observatory with the successful launch of ASTROSAT, joining the US, Japan, Russia, and Europe. ASTROSAT, India’s first dedicated multi-wavelength space observatory, will aid in the knowledge of the cosmos. Statement 2 is incorrect: AstroSat with a lift-off mass of 1515 kg was launched into a 650 km orbit inclined at an angle of 6 deg to the equator by PSLV-C30 from Satish Dhawan Space Centre, Sriharikota. 111","PW-1264":"Mangalyaan/Mars Orbiter Mission (MOM), the maiden interplanetary mission of ISRO, was launched on PSLV-C25. It entered into Martian orbit in its first attempt. MOM had completed 1000 Earth days in its orbit well beyond its designed mission life of six months. Statement 1 and 3 are correct: The Mangalyaan launched by ISRO is also called the Mars Orbiter Mission. With this India became the first Asian nation to reach Mars orbit, and the first nation in the world to do so in its first attempt. Statement 2 is incorrect: It is India’s first interplanetary mission and ISRO has become the fourth space agency to reach Mars, after the Soviet space Programme, NASA and the EuropeanSpace Agency. 112","PW-1265":"The IceCube Neutrino Observatory is the first of its kind, designed to explore the cosmos from deep within the ice at the South Pole. It is operated by the IceCube Collaboration, an international team of scientists conducting research in this field. By detecting high-energy cosmic neutrinos, IceCube enables the study of some of the universe’s most violent astrophysical events, including stellar explosions, gamma-ray bursts, and catastrophic interactions involving black holes and neutron stars. Statement 1 is correct: The IceCube Neutrino Observatory is the largest neutrino detector globally, occupying a cubic kilometer of ice at the South Pole. It detects high-energy neutrinos from cosmic sources like supernovae, black holes, and gamma-ray bursts. Statement 2 is correct: IceCube plays a critical role in the search for dark matter by detecting neutrinos produced when dark matter particles, such as WIMPs (Weakly Interacting Massive Particles), interact or annihilate. This makes it a vital tool in astrophysical and particle physics research. Statement 3 is correct: IceCube’s detectors a","PW-1266":"","PW-1267":"The Goldilocks Zone, or habitable zone, refers to the region around a star where conditions are “just right” for liquid water to exist on a planet’s surface—a key factor for life as we know it. This zone depends on the star’s size and temperature. Earth lies within the Sun’s Goldilocks Zone, enabling its rich biodiversity. Exoplanets within their star’s habitable zones, such as Kepler-452b, are prime candidates in the search for extraterrestrial life. 115","PW-1268":"An optical illusion is characterized by visually perceived images that differ from object than reality. The information that is gathered by the eye is processed in the brain that gives a perception that does not tally with a physical measurement of the stimulus source. Statement 1 is correct: There are no known objects of a similar size as the sun (or moon) when it is high in the sky. The sun, however, appears even larger when it is low in the sky because we can see distant objects near the horizon that we know to be large. Thus, the size of the sun at dusk is a visual illusion. Statement 2 is correct: There are many different colours in light. Red is the colour that moves the farthest out of all of those others. As the sun sets, crimson (deep, rich red colour) is the final hue to be seen. Red is the last colour to appear when the other colours begin to fade. Therefore, the colour of the sun at dawn is due to optical illusion. Statement 3 is incorrect: Moon being visible at dawn is not an optical illusion as the moon is visible somewhere in the sky at dawn during the entire half of t","PW-1269":"Pair 1 is incorrectly matched: The Cassini-Huygens mission was a collaborative project between NASA, the European Space Agency (ESA), and the Italian Space Agency (ASI) to study Saturn and its moons, not Venus. Huygens probe landed on Titan, Saturn’s largest moon in 2005 and provided valuable data about its atmosphere and surface. Pair 2 is correctly matched: The Messenger (MErcury Surface, Space ENvironment, GEochemistry, and Ranging) spacecraft was a NASA mission designed to study Mercury. It orbited Mercury and mapped its surface, studying its geology, and investigating its magnetic field and exosphere. Pair 3 is correctly matched: The Voyager 1 and Voyager 2 spacecraft were launched by NASA in 1977 to explore the outer planets of the solar system. Voyager 1 flew by Jupiter and Saturn, providing detailed images and data about these planets and their moons. Voyager 2 visited all four outer planets: Jupiter, Saturn, Uranus, and Neptune. The spacecraft are now in interstellar space, continuing to transmit data about the heliosphere and beyond. 117","PW-1270":"Statement 1 is correct: The Also known as \" God Particle\" is associated with the Higgs field, which permeates the universe. Elementary particles acquire mass through their interaction with this field. Without the Higgs mechanism, particles would remain massless, preventing the formation of atoms and, consequently, the existence of matter as we know it. This discovery confirms the Standard Model’s explanation of mass acquisition. Statement 2 is incorrect: The Part of Invisible energy field ,if Higgs field doesn't ok provide mass to particles then there will be no gravity and no life. is not a key item that will open the way for teleportation but it will certainly help to understand mass , time and travel in time and space. Statement 3 is incorrect: In the near or far future, the Higgs Boson may help us to create an unbelievable energy source which can pave the way for better fuels for our Nuclear missions but at present, direct connection between detection of Higgs Bosons and creation of better fuels for nuclear missions is not established. 118","PW-1271":"The Big Bang theory states that at some point of time the entire space was contained in a single point of very high density and temperature, from where the Universe has been witnessing expansion in all directions ever since. According to Hubble’s law, the expansion of the universe is such that the velocity at which the galaxy is moving away from the observer is increasing with time. Statement 1 is correct: Cosmic Microwave Background (CMB) is thought to be leftover radiation from the Big Bang, i.e., the time when the universe began. According to the theory, when the universe was born it underwent rapid inflation and expansion. (The universe is still expanding today, and the expansion rate appears different depending on observation). The CMB represents the heat left over from the Big Bang. Statement 2 is correct: American astronomer Edwin Hubble was the first to describe the redshift phenomenon (galactic redshift) and tie it to an expanding universe (galaxies are drifting apart). Redshift and Blueshift describe how light changes with movement of objects in space closer or farther from","PW-1272":"Artificial satellites are launched into orbit for a variety of purposes, including communications, navigation, Earth imaging, weather observation, and scientific study. In satellites, humans typically experience a sense of weightlessness because the net force acting on our body is practically zero. This is due to the satellite’s centrifugal force, which cancels out the size of the earth’s gravitational pull. On the other hand, the earth’s gravitational pull is required for the satellite to continuously change its direction, giving acceleration for the satellite’s direction-changing process. Science and Technology 561 121","PW-1273":"Statement 1 is correct: Asteroids are primarily composed of rock and metal and are remnants from the early solar system. In contrast , Comets are made of ice, dust, and rocky material and originate from the Kuiper Belt or Oort Cloud. Statement 2 is incorrect: Asteroids are predominantly located in the asteroid belt between Mars and Jupiter. Comets originate from distant regions of the solar system: short-period comets come from the Kuiper Belt beyond Neptune, and long-period comets originate from the distant Oort Cloud. They are not typically found between Venus and Mercury. Statement 3 is correct: As comets approach the Sun, the heat causes their icy components to sublimate, forming a glowing coma and often a visible tail that points away from the Sun due to solar wind. Asteroids, being rocky and lacking volatile materials, do not exhibit such features. 122","PW-1274":"Statement 1 is correct: Geostationary Orbit is a type of geosynchronous orbit. The earth rotates in the same direction that satellites do. It lasts for roughly 24 hours and holds its place in relation to the earth. Statement 2 is correct: The orbit must be nearly circular, ensuring that the satellite’s distance from Earth remains constant throughout its revolution. An elliptical orbit would cause the satellite to move closer and farther from Earth, disrupting its stationary position. Statement 3 is correct: A Geostationary Orbit (GEO) is a special case of a Geosynchronous Orbit (GSO) where the satellite orbits exactly in the Earth’s equatorial plane (0° inclination). This ensures that the satellite appears fixed over a specific point on Earth. Statement 4 is incorrect: Geostationary orbit is at an altitude of around 35,786 km. 123","PW-1275":"Oceansat-2, launched by ISRO in 2009, is an Earth observation satellite designed to study oceanic and atmospheric conditions. It supports applications like ocean forecasting, fishing zone mapping, and monitoring coastal and atmospheric parameters. Statement 1 is correct: Oceansat-2 is equipped with sensors such as the Scatterometer and Ocean Color Monitor (OCM), which help assess atmospheric parameters like water vapour content. Statement 2 is correct: By measuring sea surface winds and temperatures, the satellite is capable of understanding and predicting monsoon dynamics, which are closely tied to oceanic and atmospheric interactions. Statement 3 is correct: The Ocean Color Monitor onboard can detect chlorophyll concentrations, sediment levels, and other indicators of water quality, helping monitor and assess pollution in coastal regions effectively. 124","PW-1276":"Bhuvan (means Earth in Sanskrit) is a Geoportal of ISRO, to evince the Indian Earth Observation capabilities from the Indian Remote Sensing (IRS) series of satellites. It is an interactive versatile Earth-Browser which showcases multi-sensor, mutli-platform and multitemporal images with capabilities to overlay thematic information along with near real- time information from Automatic Weather Stations (AWS), Potential Fishing Zone (PFZ) information, disaster support related information like forest fire alerts, periodic agricultural drought assessment etc. Bhuvan provides 2D/3D imaging and visualization of India’s geographic data. It allows users to access and analyze spatial information, similar to Google Earth, but with a focus on Indian data and applications such as urban planning, agriculture, and disaster management. But due to security concerns, the images available do not include any military installations in India. 125","PW-1277":"","PW-1278":"","PW-1279":"ISRO successfully conducted a rocket test using cryogenic engines at the Liquid Propulsion Systems Centre (LPSC) located in Mahendragiri in Tamil Nadu. ISRO Propulsion Complex (IPRC) is equipped with the state-of-the- art facilities necessary for realising the cutting edge propulsion technology products for the Indian space programme. Formerly, IPRC was known as LPSC, Mahendragiri. The IPRC is responsible for developing cryogenic propulsion systems essential for high- performance launch vehicles. A cryogenic engine uses supercooled liquids, typically liquid oxygen (LOX) and liquid hydrogen (LH2) as propellants. These engines are highly efficient because cryogenic fuels have a higher specific impulse, meaning they provide greater thrust for a given mass of fuel. 129","PW-1280":"","PW-1281":"METSAT (renamed as Kalpana - 1) was the first in the series of exclusive meteorological satellites built by ISRO. Statement 1 is correct: India successfully launched its first full-fledged meteorological satellite, METSAT using the PSLV-C4 rocket. ​It was India’s first dedicated meteorological satellite, designed to monitor weather conditions and cyclone development in the Indian Ocean region. Statement 2 is correct: PSLV-C4 carried METSAT (1,060 kg) into a geosynchronous transfer orbit (GTO), marking the first time PSLV carried a payload exceeding 1000 kg into GTO. This demonstrated ISRO’s ability to deploy heavier payloads into higher orbits, advancing India’s space technology capabilities. 132","PW-1282":"INSAT or the Indian National Satellite System is a series of multipurpose Geo-stationary satellites launched by ISRO to satisfy the telecommunications, broadcasting, meteorology, and search and rescue needs of India. Statement 1 is correct: The INSAT-series of satellites were launched from foreign stations like Kourou in French Guiana or Kennedy Space Center in the USA. Statement 2 is correct: The PSLV (Polar Satellite Launch Vehicle) was used to launch many of the IRS (Indian Remote Sensing) satellites, which are used for Earth observation. Statement 3 is correct: India’s first cryogenic engine was used for the third stage of the GSLV (Geosynchronous Satellite Launch Vehicle) for the first time in the launch of GSLV-D3 in 2010. Statement 4 is correct: GSAT-1, India’s first geostationary communication satellite, was launched in 2001, and its payloads were designed to provide digital broadcast and communication services, including internet services. 133","PW-1283":"A satellite is an object in space that orbits or circles around a bigger object. There are two kinds of satellites: natural (such as the moon orbiting the Earth) or artificial (such as the International Space Station orbiting the Earth). Almost every planet having at least one moon. Assertion (A) is true: Satellites are launched in the eastward direction to take advantage of the Earth’s rotational velocity, which gives the rocket an initial boost in speed. This helps the rocket reach the required escape velocity more efficiently. Reason (R) is false: While the Earth’s rotation does provide a velocity boost but it does not directly help the satellite attain escape velocity (the speed needed to break free from Earth’s gravity, approximately 11.2 km/s). Instead, the Earth’s rotation helps the satellite achieve orbital velocity (the speed needed to stay in orbit, approximately 7.8 km/s for low Earth orbit). 7. DEFENCE TECHNOLOGY 134","PW-1284":"Fifth-generation fighter aircraft typically have features like stealth, advanced avionics, sensor fusion, and supercruise capability. Examples include the F-35 Lightning II (USA), F-22 Raptor (USA), Su-57 (Russia), and J-20 (China). They differ from fourth-generation aircraft primarily in their stealth features. Fifth-generation aircraft have a low electro- magnetic signature, which makes it difficult for enemy radar to detect them. At the same time, fifth-generation aircraft have powerful sensors and new weapons, so they are able to register the signature of enemy aircraft and take them out. Option 1 is incorrect: Rafale is a 4.5-generation multirole fighter developed by Dassault Aviation (France). It features advanced avionics, stealth enhancements, and superior maneuverability but lacks full stealth and sensor fusion, which are key traits of fifth-generation aircraft. Option 2 is incorrect: MiG-29 is a fourth-generation fighter developed by Russia, primarily designed for air superiority with high agility but lacks stealth technology. Option 3 is incorrect: Tejas MK-1 is an indigen","PW-1285":"Statement 1 is not correct: Ballistic missiles are rocket-powered only during the initial (boost) phase of flight, following an arcing trajectory to the target after that. Ballistic missiles travel well outside earth’s atmosphere. In contrast, cruise missiles are jet-propelled at subsonic speeds throughout their journeys. Cruise missile flies within the earth’s atmosphere and uses jet engine technology. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 564 Statement 2 is not correct: The Defence Research and Development Organisation (DRDO) of India developed the land- based intercontinental ballistic missile known as Agni-V. The BrahMos is a medium-range Ramjet Supersonic Cruise Missile that may be fired from a submarine, ship, aircraft, or land. The BrahMos is undoubtedly the world’s fastest supersonic cruise missile. SUPER HINT Content in both statements are interchanged. The term ballistic itself implies launch-arc-fall motion like a can- non shell — this requires rocket power at least initially, not a jet engine. While , Cruise = implies long “drive-like” flight. Cruise ships, cruise control — all constant-s","PW-1286":"The Shourya is a canisterised missile system that can be easily handled, transported and stored within the canister for longer shelf-life. The high manoeuvrability of the missile makes it less vulnerable to available anti-missile defence systems. Statement 1 is incorrect: The Can carry a payload of 200 to 1000 kg .Propellant - Solid fuel is a hypersonic surface-to-surface tactical missile. It is known to travel at speeds of up to Mach 7.5, which is slightly less than Mach 8. Statement 2 is incorrect: The range of the Shourya missile is approximately 750–1900 km, depending on its payload, but its operational range typically does not exceed 1600 km in standard configurations. 137","PW-1287":"Statement 1 is incorrect: INS Sindhughosh is not an aircraft carrier. It is a diesel-electric submarine of the Sindhughosh class, which is based on the Russian Kilo- class submarines. It is used for anti-submarine warfare, reconnaissance, and intelligence gathering. Statement 2 is incorrect: INS Viraat is not a submarine. It was an aircraft carrier and served as the flagship of the Indian Navy for many years. It played a significant role in enhancing India’s naval power before being decommissioned in 2017. 138","PW-1288":"India purchased the Barak anti-missile defence systems from Israel. The Barak system is developed by Israel Aerospace Industries (IAI) in collaboration with Rafael Advanced Defense Systems, is a surface-to-air missile designed to intercept and destroy incoming threats such as anti-ship missiles, aircraft, and drones. It is part of India’s naval defence system and is installed on various Indian Navy warships to enhance their anti-missile capabilities. 139","PW-1289":"5.5 ton class helicopter with twin engines. is an Advanced Light Helicopter (ALH) developed by Hindustan Aeronautics Limited (HAL) for military and civilian applications. Equipped with twin Shakti engines, it operates at altitudes up to 20,000 feet, making it suitable for diverse terrains. Dhruv is used for troop transport, search and rescue, reconnaissance, medical evacuation, and disaster relief. Its variants include the armed Rudra and the upgraded Mark III. As a symbol of India’s self- reliance in defense, Dhruv has been exported to countries like Nepal and Mauritius, enhancing India’s defense diplomacy. 140","PW-1290":"Statement 1 is correct: In November 2006, the Defence Research and Development Organisation (DRDO) of India conducted a successful test of the Prithvi Air Defence (PAD) system, which used the Prithvi-II missile as an interceptor to destroy an incoming target missile. The Prithvi-II missile has been instrumental in validating India’s BMD technologies, ensuring readiness to protect against ballistic missile threats. This test marked a significant milestone in India’s ballistic missile defence program. Statement 2 is correct: While the primary role of the Prithvi-II is as a surface-to-surface missile but it has been adapted for air defense purposes also. It is part of India’s Ballistic Missile Defense (BMD) system, which is designed to protect major cities from ballistic missile attacks. 141","PW-1291":"The Galileo Project is a multi-satellite navigation system being developed by the European Union (EU). Galileo consists of 24 satellites orbiting Earth at an altitude of 23,000 km. The signals of Galileo are freely transmitted to anyone who has a device capable of receiving its signals (e.g., smartphone). Galileo is four times more accurate than GPS providing 1 meter accuracy and a broad range of services. It is designed to provide an independent global positioning system (GPS) for civilian and commercial use, reducing reliance on GPS systems controlled by other countries, such as the United States. Galileo aims to offer highly accurate and reliable positioning and timing information worldwide, supporting applications in transportation, telecommunications, and other critical sectors. 8. NUCLEAR TECHNOLOGY 142","PW-1292":"RTGs are lightweight and compact devices that generate electricity from the heat produced by the natural radioactive decay of isotopes, typically Plutonium-238 . They are commonly used in space missions where solar power is insufficient, such as deep-space probes and rovers. Statement 1 is incorrect: RTGs generate heat through natural radioactive decay, not by controlled nuclear fission, which involves splitting atomic nuclei to release energy. Therefore, they cannot be classified as miniature fission reactors. Statement 2 is correct: Due to their lightweight, compact design, RTGs have been extensively used in space missions such as Voyager, Curiosity Rover, and Perseverance Rover. They offer a durable and reliable power source, especially for spacecraft operating in deep space, where solar panels are ineffective. Statement 3 is correct: Plutonium-238 is widely used in RTGs due to its high heat output during decay and low levels of unwanted radiation. While Pu-238 is not naturally occurring, it is mainly produced as a by-product of nuclear weapons development. For example, during the","PW-1293":"IAEA safeguards apply to nuclear reactors using imported uranium as part of India’s international agreements. These safeguards ensure that the imported fuel is strictly used for civilian purposes and not diverted for military use. However, not all nuclear reactors in India are placed under IAEA safeguards. Reactors using domestic uranium are not subject to these safeguards allowing flexibility for strategic programs. By keeping reactors using domestic uranium outside IAEA safeguards, India maintains the flexibility to support its strategic programs without external oversight. As of recent data, out of India’s 22 operational reactors, 14 are under IAEA safeguards because they utilize imported fuel. :  Reactors Using Imported Uranium - Under IAEA Safeguards  India imports uranium through civil nuclear cooperation agreements with countries like the U.S., Russia, and France. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 566  Reactors using imported uranium must be placed under IAEA safeguards to ensure peaceful usage.  Example: Kudankulam Nuclear Power Plant (uses Russian-supplied fuel).  Reactors Using Dom","PW-1294":"Sub-atomic particles are particles that are smaller than an atom. They are the basic building blocks of atoms. They are primarily categorized into two groups: elementary particles which are indivisible, and composite particles which are combinations of elementary particles. Option (b) is correct: In the year 2008, the organization that conducted a complex scientific experiment in which sub-atomic particles were accelerated to nearly the speed of light was the European Organization for Nuclear Research (CERN). CERN operates the Large Hadron Collider (LHC), where particles are accelerated to extremely high speeds to explore fundamental physics. The experiment helps in understanding the Standard Model of Particle Physics exploring dark matter and studying the properties of fundamental forces. 145","PW-1295":"ITER, which stands for International Thermonuclear Experimental Reactor, is a massive international collaboration aimed at harnessing the power of nuclear fusion. This groundbreaking project is being constructed in Cadarache, Southern France. ITER aims to replicate nuclear fusion, where light atomic nuclei combine to release vast energy, offering a limitless, clean power source. Using a tokamak design, it employs powerful magnetic fields to heat plasma to over 150 million degrees Celsius. The project is a global collaboration involving China, the EU, India, Japan, Korea, Russia, and the US. India has provided in-wall shielding components and the cryo lines and cryo distribution system, crucial for the reactor’s operation. 146","PW-1296":"In 2005, the Indira Gandhi Centre for Atomic Research (IGCAR) made significant progress in reprocessing the uranium- plutonium mixed carbide fuel used in the Fast Breeder Test Reactor (FBTR). Reprocessing the spent fuel from the FBTR posed significant challenges due to its intense radioactivity and the distinct chemical characteristics of the mixed carbide fuel. The accomplishment of successful reprocessing showcased India’s expertise in managing and recycling this advanced type of nuclear fuel. It also provided critical knowledge for the advancement of next-generation fast breeder reactors, including the Prototype Fast Breeder Reactor (PFBR) at Kalpakkam. 9. MISCELLANEOUS 147","PW-1297":"Pumped-storage hydropower (PSH) is primarily discussed in the context of long-duration energy storage. It is a type of hydroelectric power generation that stores excess electricity by pumping water from a lower reservoir to an upper reservoir during times of low energy demand. When energy demand is high, the stored water is released back down through turbines to generate electricity. This technology helps balance grid fluctuations, integrate renewable energy sources like wind and solar, and provide a reliable backup power supply. Science and Technology 567 148","PW-1298":"The exhaust pipe emission from Fuel Cell Electric Vehicles (FCEVs) powered by hydrogen is water vapour. These vehicles use hydrogen fuel cells to generate electricity through an electrochemical reaction between hydrogen and oxygen. The only by-product of this process is water (H₂O), which is released as vapour, making FCEVs a clean and environmentally friendly transportation option. Fuel cells are unique in terms of the variety of their potential applications; they can use a wide range of fuels and feedstocks and can provide power for systems as large as a utility power station and as small as a laptop computer. : Working of Hydrogen Fuel Cells  Simply put, fuel cells work by combining hydrogen gas (H2) with oxygen from the air - and the resulting chemical reaction produces electricity.  Hydrogen atoms enter the fuel cell at the anode, while oxygen is fed to the cathode. The fuel cell consists of a membrane coated with a catalyst. When the hydrogen molecules hit the catalyst, they’re split into hydrogen ions and electrons.  The membrane lets positively charged hydrogen ions pass t","PW-1299":"Green hydrogen is expected to play a prominent role in decarbonising heavy industries, including oil refineries, steel mills and fertiliser plants. Green hydrogen is produced by breaking down water in an electrolyser using only renewable energy, resulting in no carbon emissions. The production of fertiliser demands substantial energy, typically sourced from fossil fuels like natural gas. However, green hydrogen offers a promising alternative, serving either as an electricity source or directly utilised in the ammonia production process, which is crucial for manufacturing fertilizer. Oil refineries significantly contribute to greenhouse gas emissions through their energy-intensive operations and dependence on fossil fuels. However, integrating green hydrogen into refinery operations offers a viable solution to mitigate this impact by either substituting or complementing fossil fuels, thereby decreasing their carbon footprint. Hydrogen can play a vital role in refining procedures like hydrocracking and hydrotreating, enhancing fuel quality by eliminating impurities. The steel industry ","PW-1300":"Statement 1 is correct: Finely ground basalt rock is dispersed across agricultural lands to expedite the natural absorption of carbon dioxide from the atmosphere. This is known as enhanced rock weathering, where silicate minerals react with CO₂, forming stable carbonates and reducing atmospheric carbon, as well as improving the fertility of the soil. Statement 2 is correct: This method, referred to as ocean alkalinity enhancement, encompasses the addition of lime (calcium oxide or calcium hydroxide) to the oceans to elevate their alkalinity. By doing so, it boosts the oceans’ ability to absorb and retain carbon dioxide from the atmosphere, thus assisting in carbon sequestration. Statement 3 is correct: The process known as carbon capture and storage (CCS) involves capturing carbon dioxide emissions from industrial processes and storing them underground. Abandoned subterranean mines can be utilised as viable storage sites, where the captured carbon dioxide is injected into these locations as carbonated waters. 151","PW-1301":"An accelerometer is an electromechanical device used to measure acceleration forces. These forces may be static like the continuous force of gravity or dynamic force to sense movement or vibrations. Statement 1 is correct: Upon a collision, the crash sensor, typically an accelerometer, transmits a signal to the airbag control unit to deploy the airbags almost immediately. Statement 2 is correct: Accelerometers in laptops protect hard drives from damage. If the laptop were to suddenly drop while in use, the accelerometer would detect the sudden free fall and immediately turn off the hard drive to avoid hitting the reading heads into the hard drive platter. Statement 3 is correct: Accelerometer is used in smartphones as it detects the rotation of their display between portrait and landscape mode depending on the tilt of the phone. 152","PW-1302":"Statement 1 is correct: The use of biofilters to remove toxins from wastewater and waste gases has advanced in recent decades. In order to remove contaminants from a fluid stream, biofilters fix microorganisms to an inorganic/organic medium (carrier), which has the ability to break down a wide range of chemicals. By removing uneaten fish feed, they additionally perform waste treatment. Statement 2 is correct: By constructing a biofilter correctly, it is possible to regulate ammonia and nitrite concentrations at levels safe for fish. Through the biofiltration process, ammonia nitrogen is converted into nitrite nitrogen, which is subsequently transformed into less harmful nitrate nitrogen, ensuring a conducive environment for fish. Statement 3 is incorrect: Biofilters do not increase phosphorus as a nutrient for fish in water. Phosphorus (P) is actually removed by biofilters to prevent eutrophication in waters. 153","PW-1303":"Green hydrogen is a renewable energy source that, unlike coal and oil, solely releases water vapour and leaves no residue in the air. Statement 1 is correct: Hydrogen, a zero-carbon fuel, can be used to power automobiles through both hydrogen internal combustion engines and hydrogen fuel cells.Hydrogen engines utilize hydrogen in an internal combustion engine, operating similarly to the way gasoline powers conventional engines. Statement 2 is correct: Clean hydrogen may be created and injected into natural gas pipelines to create blends that can be utilised to provide heat and power with fewer emissions than just natural gas. Statement 3 is correct: A fuel cell harnesses the chemical energy of green hydrogen or alternative fuels to generate electricity in a clean and efficient manner. When hydrogen serves as the fuel, the sole byproducts produced are electricity, water, and heat. SUPER HINT Again, \"CAN\" and “Some” = possibility logic, not abso- lute. If even one example exist, the statement is likely correct. UPSC uses \"can\" and “some” to lower the bur- den of proof → harder to elimi","PW-1304":"A biofilm is a collection of microbial cells that are encased in a polysaccharide-based matrix and are permanently attached to a surface (i.e., cannot be removed by gentle rinsing). Microorganisms that form biofilms include bacteria, fungi, and protists. Noncellular materials such as mineral crystals, corrosion particles, clay or silt particles, or blood components, depending on the environment in which the biofilm has developed, may also be found in the biofilm matrix. Statement 1 is correct: Biofilms may form on a wide variety of surfaces, including living tissues, food and food processing surfaces, indwelling medical devices (devices in the body like catheters, heart valves), human and animal tissue, industrial or potable water system piping, or natural aquatic systems. Statement 2 is correct: Biofilms are a significant concern in the food industry, forming on surfaces such as cutting boards, conveyor belts, and food packaging equipment. Contaminated biofilms can lead to foodborne illnesses caused by pathogens like Listeria monocytogenes, Salmonella, and Escherichia coli. Statemen","PW-1305":"A pressure cooker is a sealed chamber that traps the steam generated as its contents are heated. As steam builds, pressure increases, driving the boiling point of water past 212°F (100°C). In general, this higher temperature shortens cooking times and, due to a lack of evaporation, extracts flavor more efficiently from foods. Statement 1 is correct: The area of the hole directly influences the pressure and temperature inside the cooker. The hole in the lid is where steam escapes through the pressure regulator (weight valve). A smaller hole allows less steam to escape, which increases the pressure inside, raising the boiling point of water and increasing the cooking temperature. If the hole is larger, more steam escapes, reducing the pressure and lowering the cooking temperature. Statement 2 is incorrect: A higher flame heats the pressure cooker faster but it does not increase the maximum cooking temperature once the cooker reaches its operating pressure. The pressure and temperature inside the cooker are controlled by the pressure regulator (weight valve), not the external flame. Onc","PW-1306":"The artificial culture media, also referred to as the growth medium, is a setting for the development of many kinds of microorganisms. The agarose and nutrients needed for the microorganism’s growth are present in the culture medium. This medium is first sterilised to prevent contamination, which prevents the growth of undesirable microorganisms and ensures that it only contains the microbes of interest. Option 1 is correct: Bacteria can be easily grown on artificial or synthetic media as these provide the necessary nutrients for their growth. These media typically include essential components like carbon, nitrogen, vitamins, and minerals. For instance, nutrient agar and broth are commonly used for culturing bacteria, and Escherichia coli can be grown on Luria- Bertani (LB) agar. Option 2 is correct: Fungi, including yeasts and molds, can thrive on artificial media specifically formulated for their growth. Media such as Sabouraud dextrose agar and potato dextrose agar are designed to support fungal growth by providing nutrients and maintaining an acidic pH, which inhibits bacterial c","PW-1307":"Statement 1 is correct: Sodium Lamps emit light omnidirectionally (360 degrees), necessitating the use of reflectors to direct light toward the desired area. LED Lamps emit light directionally (typically around 180 degrees), allowing for more efficient illumination with minimal light loss. Statement 2 is incorrect: Sodium Lamps have a shorter operational lifespan compared to LEDs. LED Lamps offer a longer lifespan, often exceeding that of sodium lamps, leading to reduced maintenance and replacement costs. Statement 3 is correct: Sodium Lamps produce a nearly monochromatic light, resulting in poor color rendering and making it difficult to distinguish colors under their illumination. LED Lamps provide a broad spectrum of visible light, offering superior color rendering and enhancing visibility and safety in street lighting applications. 159","PW-1308":"Bisphenol A (BPA) is an industrial chemical primarily used in the production of polycarbonate plastics and epoxy resins. Polycarbonate plastics are known for their durability and clarity and are commonly utilized in items such as water bottles, food storage containers, and eyewear. It has been identified as an endocrine disruptor, meaning it can interfere with the body’s hormonal systems. Research has linked BPA exposure to various health issues, including reproductive disorders, metabolic disease, and developmental problems in children. Due to these concerns, many regulatory agencies have evaluated the safety of BPA in consumer products. 160","PW-1309":"Triclosan is an ingredient added to many consumer products intended to reduce or prevent bacterial contamination. It is added to some antibacterial soaps and body washes, toiletries, toothpastes, and some cosmetics. Some short-term animal studies have shown that exposure to high doses of triclosan is associated with a decrease in the levels of some thyroid hormones. Other studies have raised the possibility that exposure to triclosan contributes to making bacteria resistant to antibiotics. 161","PW-1310":"Water is often referred to as the “universal solvent” because it can dissolve more substances than any other liquid. This exceptional ability is primarily due to its dipolar nature. A water molecule has a bent shape, with the oxygen atom carrying a partial negative charge and the hydrogen atoms carrying partial positive charges. This polarity allows water molecules to surround and interact with various solutes, effectively breaking them apart and dissolving them. Water can develop a strong attraction to another substance, such as salt (NaCl) to the point where it can interfere with the attractive forces holding the sodium and chloride in the salt complex together and dissolve it. In organic chemistry, a dipolar compound or simply dipole is an electrically neutral molecule carrying a positive and a negative charge in at least one canonical description. 162","PW-1311":"A drone, technologically, is an unmanned aircraft. They are formally known as unmanned aerial vehicles (UAVs). A drone is essentially a flying robot that can be remotely piloted or can fly on its own using software-controlled flight plans in embedded systems in conjunction with onboard sensors and GPS. Statement 1 is correct: Modern agriculture has increasingly adopted drones for the application of pesticides and fertilizers. These drones offer precision in spraying, ensuring uniform coverage and reducing the exposure of farmers to harmful chemicals. For instance, a study published in Springer highlights that drones equipped with advanced sensors and high-resolution cameras can distinguish between healthy and infested crops, allowing for targeted pesticide application. Statement 2 is correct: Drones equipped with visual and thermal cameras are utilized in geological studies to inspect active volcano craters. They can safely approach hazardous areas, capturing high-resolution images and collecting gas samples. Researchers from the German Research Centre for Geosciences (GFZ) successfu","PW-1312":"Statement 1 is correct: Both plants and animals contain eukaryotic cells, their cell structures are quite similar. The plasma membrane, nucleus, cytoplasm, ribosomes, and mitochondria in general make up each eukaryotic cell. The plant cell differs significantly from other cells in that it has a hard cell wall surrounding it. While the cells of other species are surrounded by a cell wall, cellulose and proteins are present in plant cells. Statement 2 is incorrect: Both plant and animal cells have a plasma membrane that surrounds the cytoplasm and regulates the movement of substances in and out of the cell. The plasma membrane is essential for maintaining homeostasis and facilitating communication between the cell and its environment in both plant and animal cells. Statement 3 is correct: A mature plant cell typically contains a single, large central vacuole, which can occupy up to 90% of the cell’s volume. This vacuole stores water, nutrients, and waste products and helps maintain turgor pressure, providing structural support to the plant. Animal cells often have multiple small vacuol","PW-1313":"Pronuclear transfer is an advanced reproductive technique primarily utilized to prevent the transmission of mitochondrial diseases from mother to offspring. Mitochondrial diseases are genetic disorders caused by mutations in mitochondrial DNA (mtDNA), which is inherited exclusively from the mother. These disorders can lead to severe health issues, affecting organs with high energy demands, such as the brain, heart, and muscles. 165","PW-1314":"Statement 1 is incorrect: Solar power is capable of operating both surface and submersible pumps. Surface Pumps are installed above the water surface and are suitable for applications where water is drawn from shallow sources. They can be effectively powered by solar energy. Submersible pumps are designed to operate underwater. These pumps are ideal for deep wells or boreholes. Solar-powered submersible pumps are widely used for extracting water from significant depths. Statement 2 is incorrect: Solar power can be utilized to run both centrifugal and piston (positive displacement) pumps. Centrifugal Pumps are commonly used in solar applications for higher flow rates with lower lift. They are efficient when adequate solar power is available. Piston Pumps also known as positive displacement pumps, piston pumps are suitable for applications requiring high lift with lower flow rates. Their ability to maintain efficiency under varying conditions makes them well-suited for solar-powered systems. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 572 SUPER HINT Solar power is just a source of electricity. It can power a","PW-1315":"Tissue culture (TC) is the cultivation of plant cells, tissues, or organs on specially formulated nutrient media. Under the right conditions, an entire plant can be regenerated from a single cell. Commercial planting of sugarcane uses setts (cuttings that can form roots) at a rate of 6 to 8 tonnes per hectare, or around 10% of total production. Statement 1 is correct: Due to its bulky attire and physical restrictions, the tissue culture method is becoming uneconomical. Planting excised axillary canestalk buds, sometimes referred to as budchips, would help reduce the mass and enhance the quality of the seed cane. After four to five weeks, healthy settlings are transplanted on a well-prepared field with a row spacing of 90 cm and a gap of 30 cm between each settling (small setts). Statement 2 is incorrect: Due to moisture loss from the other cut end, the germination percentage of a single bud sett is extremely low. Numerous studies and trials demonstrate that the germination rate of 3 bud sets is higher than the setts having more or less than three buds. Additionally, even if the entir","PW-1316":"Atal Innovation Mission (AIM) by NITI Aayog is Government of India’s flagship initiative to promote a culture of innovation and entrepreneurship in the country and was setup in 2016. Towards this end AIM has taken a holistic approach to ensure creation of a problem-solving innovative mindset in schools and creating an ecosystem of entrepreneurship in universities, research institutions, private and MSME sector. :  AIM has launched the Atal Tinkering Lab (ATL) program. It is a state-of-the-art space established in a school with a goal to foster curiosity and innovation in young minds, between grade 6th to 12th across the country through 21st century tools and technologies.  Atal Incubation Centres or AICs are business incubators established by AIM at universities, institutions and corporates to promote innovation and entrepreneurship among young innovators of the country.  Atal Community Innovation Centres to promote the benefits of technology led innovation to the unserved/ underserved regions of India including Tier 2, Tier 3 cities, aspirational districts, tribal, hilly and coas","PW-1317":"Statement 1 is incorrect: The Indian Patents Act, 1970 (as amended in 2005) explicitly excludes biological processes for the production or propagation of plants and animals from patentability. The Act states that “plants and animals in whole or any part thereof, including seeds, varieties, and species, and essentially biological processes for the production or propagation of plants and animals” are not patentable. Statement 2 is incorrect: India had an Intellectual Property Appellate Board (IPAB), which was established in 1958 to handle disputes related to patents, trademarks, and copyrights. However, IPAB was abolished in 2021 under the Tribunals Reforms (Rationalisation and Conditions of Service) Ordinance, 2021. After its abolition, patent, trademark, and copyright appeals are now handled by the High Courts. Science and Technology 573 Statement 3 is correct: Under the Indian Patents Act, 1970, plants and plant varieties cannot be patented. Instead, plant varieties are protected under the PPVFR Act, 2001, which grants breeders’ rights but not patents. 169","PW-1318":"Statement 1 is correct: The Earth’s magnetic field has undergone numerous reversals over geological time scales. These geomagnetic reversals occur at irregular intervals averaging approximately every 300,000 years though it varies. Statement 2 is incorrect: Over 4000 million years ago earth’s early atmosphere lacked oxygen and was primarily composed of gases like methane, ammonia, water vapor, and carbon dioxide. The current level of oxygen (around 21%) accumulated much later due to photosynthetic activity by living organisms. Statement 3 is correct: Living organisms particularly cyanobacteria played a significant role in modifying the Earth’s early atmosphere by producing oxygen through photosynthesis. This process led to the Great Oxygenation Event around 2.4 billion years ago. This marked a pivotal shift from an oxygen-poor to an oxygen-rich atmosphere, profoundly influencing the evolution of life. 170","PW-1319":"3D printing, also known as additive manufacturing, is a method of creating a three dimensional object layer-by-layer using a computer simulated design. A 3D item is produced by the additive method of 3D printing, which involves building up layers of material. Options 1 is correct: 3D printing is widely used in the food industry to create intricate designs, especially with edible materials like chocolate and sugar. This technique enables customization and the production of unique shapes that are difficult to achieve with traditional methods. Options 2 is correct: Researchers have successfully used 3D printing to fabricate bionic ears by integrating biological cells with conductive materials. This method not only replicates the structure of a human ear but also enhances its functionality by embedding electronics, potentially improving hearing capabilities. Option 3 is correct: In the automotive sector, 3D printing is used for rapid prototyping, creating tools, and manufacturing parts. It speeds up the design process, reduces production costs, and enables the creation of lightweight com","PW-1320":"Statement 1 is correct: OLEDs can be manufactured on flexible materials such as polyethylene terephthalate (PET), which allows the creation of foldable and bendable screens. Unlike LCDs, which require rigid glass substrates, OLEDs can use lightweight and flexible plastics, enabling the development of innovative designs like foldable smartphones and rollable displays. Statement 2 is correct: The flexibility and thinness of OLEDs make them suitable for rollable screens that can be integrated into textiles or wearable devices. This innovation enables the creation of electronic clothing or fabrics with embedded displays, providing new possibilities in wearable technology. Statement 3 is correct: OLED technology supports the development of transparent displays because it does not rely on a backlight. OLEDs produce light on their own, making it possible to create see-through screens that overlay digital content on real-world environments. 172","PW-1321":"The International Thermonuclear Experimental Reactor (ITER) is a collaborative international project involving countries such as India, China, the European Union, Japan, Korea, Russia, and the United States. Its primary goal is to demonstrate the feasibility of nuclear fusion as a sustainable and large-scale energy source by replicating the fusion processes that power the sun. If ITER succeeds then the immediate advantage for India would be the capability to construct fusion reactors for power generation. Fusion energy offers a carbon-free and environmentally sustainable alternative, with the potential to provide a significant amount of power compared to fossil fuels. 173","PW-1322":"Fly ash is a fine powder produced as a byproduct of burning pulverized coal in thermal power plants. It is collected from the flue gases through electrostatic precipitators or bag filters before the gases are released into the atmosphere. Fly ash is composed of small, glassy, spherical particles and is categorized as an industrial waste material. Statements 1 is correct: Fly ash is utilized in manufacturing bricks, known as fly ash bricks, which are used in building construction. These bricks offer advantages such as uniformity, reduced weight, and enhanced strength compared to traditional clay bricks. Statements 2 is correct: Fly ash is commonly used as a supplementary cementitious material in concrete. It can replace a portion of Portland cement, leading to benefits like improved workability, reduced heat of hydration, and increased long-term strength. Additionally, incorporating fly ash contributes to sustainability by recycling industrial waste and reducing greenhouse gas emissions associated with cement production. Statement 3 is incorrect: While fly ash primarily consists of si","PW-1323":"Statement 1 is correct: In a hydrogen fuel cell, hydrogen (H₂) reacts with oxygen (O₂) from the air in an electrochemical reaction. This process generates electricity along with water (H₂O) and heat as by-products. Since no harmful emissions are released, this is considered a clean energy technology. Statement 2 is incorrect: Fuel cells are highly adaptable and can be designed for various applications, ranging from powering large buildings and vehicles to smaller portable devices such as laptops. Proton Exchange Membrane Fuel Cells (PEMFCs) are particularly suitable for portable devices due to their compact size and efficiency. Statement 3 is incorrect: Fuel cells generate electricity in the form of Direct Current (DC). However, many applications require Alternating Current (AC) to operate and thus an inverter is typically used to convert the DC produced by the fuel cell into AC. 175","PW-1324":"Statement 1 is correct: The National Innovation Foundation-India (NIF) was established in 2000 with the support of the Department of Science and Technology (DST), Government of India. In 2010 NIF became an autonomous body under the DST. Statement 2 is incorrect: NIF’s primary mission is to strengthen grassroots technological innovations and outstanding traditional knowledge in India. It focuses on scouting, supporting, and scaling up innovations developed by individuals and local communities at the grassroots level rather than concentrating on advanced scientific research in collaboration with foreign institutions. Its primary goal is to support and scale up innovations by common people, especially in rural areas. 176","PW-1325":"The Agni-IV is an intermediate-range ballistic missile developed by India’s Defence Research and Development Organisation (DRDO) Statement 1 is correct: The Agni-IV is designed as a surface- to-surface missile, capable of being launched from the ground to strike terrestrial targets. It enhances India’s strategic strike capabilities. Statements 2 is incorrect: The Agni-IV utilizes a two- stage solid propellant system, not liquid propellant. Solid propellants offer advantages such as easier handling and longer storage life, which are beneficial for ballistic missiles. Statements 3 is incorrect: The Agni-IV has a range of around 4,000 km and is capable of carrying a payload of up to one tonne, including nuclear warheads. A range of 7,500 km would classify the missile as an intercontinental ballistic missile (ICBM), but the Agni-IV is categorized as an intermediate-range ballistic missile (IRBM). 178","PW-1326":"Photosynthesis is the process by which green plants, algae, and certain bacteria convert light energy into chemical energy, producing glucose and releasing oxygen. The functions of the chlorophyll, a green pigment, are related to the transformation of inefficient solar energy into useful chemical energy. During photosynthesis, plants capture light energy (free energy) and convert it into chemical energy, storing it as potential energy in the bonds of glucose molecules. This stored energy can later be used by the plant for various metabolic processes. 6H2O + 6CO2 → C6H12O6+ 6O2 179","PW-1327":"Vegetative propagation is a fascinating form of asexual reproduction where new plants grow from specialized vegetative parts like stems, roots, or leaves rather than seeds. Statement 1 is correct: Vegetative propagation is a process in which new plants are grown from the vegetative parts of the parent plant. As this method does not involve sexual reproduction, the offspring are genetically identical to the parent, creating a clonal population. This technique ensures uniformity among the progeny, making it particularly useful for preserving desirable traits in cultivated plants. Statement 2 is incorrect: Standard methods of vegetative propagation generally do not eliminate viruses rather they often perpetuate viral infections because the new plants are exact genetic clones of the infected parent plant. Statement 3 is correct: Unlike seed-based propagation, which is often dependent on specific seasons, methods like cuttings, layering, or tissue culture can be carried out continuously as long as the required conditions and resources are provided. ​ Vegetative propagation can typically b","PW-1328":"Chemical Change involves the transformation of one material into another, the creation of new materials with unique properties, and the creation of one or more new substances. Option 1 is incorrect: Crystallization is a physical process where a dissolved substance transitions from a liquid solution to a solid crystalline form. In the case of sodium chloride (table salt), when a saturated salt solution evaporates, salt crystals form. This process does not alter the chemical composition of sodium chloride. Option 2 is incorrect: Melting is the phase transition of a substance from solid to liquid. When ice (solid water) melts, it becomes liquid water. This change is purely physical, as the molecular structure of H₂O remains unchanged during the process. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 576 Option 3 is correct: Souring of milk is a chemical change resulting from the fermentation process. Bacteria in the milk convert lactose (milk sugar) into lactic acid, leading to a decrease in pH and the characteristic sour taste. This transformation alters the chemical composition of the milk, producing new subst","PW-1329":"Transgenic crops are developed by introducing foreign genes into a plant’s genome to confer new traits, such as pest resistance or improved nutritional content. Statement 1 is incorrect: Budding and grafting are traditional horticultural techniques used to propagate plants. In grafting, tissues from one plant are inserted into those of another so that the two sets of vascular tissues may join together. These methods do not alter the genetic makeup of the plants. Statement 2 is correct: Cytoplasmic male sterility (CMS) refers to the complete or partial inability of plants to produce functional male gametes. Male Sterility prevents the plant from producing viable pollen, thereby rendering it incapable of self-fertilization. CMS systems are extensively used in hybrid crop production because they simplify the process of controlling male sterility, eliminating the need for manual emasculation during cross-breeding. This enhances efficiency and consistency in hybrid seed production. Statement 3 is correct: Gene silencing refers to techniques used to suppress the expression of specific gene","PW-1330":"Statement 1 is correct: Maize is a primary source for commercial starch production. Through a wet milling process, maize kernels are separated into components such as starch, oil, protein, and fiber. The extracted starch is utilized in multiple industries, including food, paper, and textiles. Statement 2 is correct: Maize oil, also known as corn oil, can be used as a raw material for biodiesel production. Through a chemical process called transesterification, the oil reacts with short-chain alcohols such as methanol or ethanol, using a catalyst to produce biodiesel efficiently. Statement 3 is correct: Maize plays a significant role in the production of various alcoholic beverages. Its starch is broken down into sugars, which are subsequently fermented to produce alcohol. This process is crucial in crafting drinks like bourbon whiskey, which traditionally uses a mash containing at least 51% maize. 183","PW-1331":"","PW-1332":"A food chain represents the transfer of energy through a series of organisms, starting from green plants (primary producers) and progressing through successive consumers. For example: Grasses → Grasshopper → Frog → Snake → Hawk/ Eagle. Each step in the food chain is referred to as a trophic level, indicating the organism’s position in the chain. Food chains begin with producers and end with top carnivores. In marine ecosystems, phytoplankton serve as primary producers. These include:  Diatoms (unicellular algae)  Coccolithophores (unicellular eukaryotic protists),  Cyanobacteria (blue-green algae such as Synechococcus, Prochlorococcus, Nostoc, and Spirogyra)  Dinoflagellates (flagellated protists) Crustaceans, a group of arthropods that includes crabs, lobsters, shrimp, krill, and barnacles, feed on diatoms. In turn, herrings, a type of fish, consume crustaceans, completing this segment of the marine food chain. 185","PW-1333":"Statement 1 is correct: PV technology directly converts sunlight into electricity using semiconductor materials like silicon. When sunlight hits the PV cells, it excites electrons, generating Direct Current (DC) electricity. This is a clean and efficient method of harnessing solar energy for electricity. Solar thermal systems use solar collectors to capture the Sun’s heat. This heat is typically used to produce steam, which drives turbines connected to generators, producing electricity. Solar thermal is often used in large-scale power plants and heating systems. Statement 2 is incorrect: PV systems initially produce Direct Current (DC), which is then converted to Alternating Current (AC) using inverters for compatibility with the electrical grid and household appliances. Solar Thermal systems generate heat, which is used to produce AC electricity through conventional turbines and generators. Statement 3 is incorrect: India has established manufacturing capabilities for both Solar Thermal and Photovoltaic technologies. The country is expanding its PV manufacturing capacity, aiming to ","PW-1334":"The carbon cycle is a biogeochemical process where carbon atoms continuously move between the atmosphere, oceans, soil, and living organisms through processes like photosynthesis, respiration, decomposition, and combustion. Through photosynthesis, plants absorb atmospheric CO2 to produce glucose, while animals release CO2 through respiration, and when organisms die, decomposition returns their carbon to the soil and atmosphere, completing this vital planetary cycle. Statement 1 is correct: Volcanic eruptions release CO₂ stored in Earth’s mantle into the atmosphere, contributing to the carbon cycle. Statement 2 is correct: Respiration is the process by which organisms, including plants and animals, convert organic compounds into energy, producing CO₂ as a byproduct. This CO₂ is then released into the atmosphere. Statement 3 is incorrect: Photosynthesis is the process by which green plants, algae, and some bacteria absorb CO₂ from the atmosphere and, using sunlight, convert it into glucose and oxygen. This process removes CO₂ from the atmosphere. Statement 4 is correct: When organisms ","PW-1335":"Ecological succession is the process of change in the species structure of an ecological community over time. Types of Succession: Primary Succession occurs on newly formed or exposed land where no previous life existed (e.g., bare rock, lava flows). Pioneer species like lichens and mosses initiate the process, gradually leading to the development of soil and a stable ecosystem. Secondary Succession happens in areas where an ecosystem previously existed but was disturbed (e.g., after a forest fire or flood). Soil is already present, and recovery occurs more quickly than in primary succession. Option (b) is correct: Lichens are among the first organisms to colonize bare rock or barren environments, breaking down minerals to create soil and paving the way for other plants and organisms. They are unique composite organisms resulting from a symbiotic association between a fungus and a photosynthetic partner, which can be either green algae or cyanobacteria. In this partnership, the fungal component, known as the mycobiont, provides structure and protection, while the photosynthetic partn","PW-1336":"After harvest, fruits and vegetables remain metabolically active, with respiration being a key manifestation of this activity. Respiration involves the breakdown of stored nutrients to release energy for cellular processes. This process can be effectively slowed by lowering the temperature, which decreases the metabolic rate. Since harvested fruits and vegetables are no longer connected to the plant’s roots, they cannot acquire additional nutrients. As a result, they rely entirely on their stored nutrients for energy. Once these reserves are depleted, the produce begins to degrade. Therefore, controlling the rate of respiration through proper storage conditions, such as refrigeration, is crucial to preserving fruits and vegetables for longer periods and maintaining their quality. 190","PW-1337":"Ball bearings are used to reduce friction between the surfaces. A ball bearing is a specific kind of rolling-element bearing that uses balls to keep the bearing races apart. A ball bearing’s main functions are to support radial and axial loads and lessen rotational friction. In order to reduce friction between surfaces and also because the effective area of contact between the wheel and axle is reduced, ball bearings are used in bicycles, vehicle axles, etc. 191","PW-1338":"A rainbow is formed when sunlight interacts with raindrops in the atmosphere, and this process involves three key physical phenomena: dispersion, refraction, and internal reflection. Dispersion occurs as sunlight, which consists of multiple colors, is separated into its constituent wavelengths when it passes through a raindrop, with each color bending by a different angle. Refraction takes place at the interface of air and water when sunlight enters the raindrop, causing the light to bend due to a change in its speed. This bending happens twice—first as the light enters the drop and again as it exits. Internal reflection occurs when the light, after being refracted, reflects off the inner surface of the raindrop. The combined effect of these phenomena results in the formation of a colorful arc in the sky, known as a rainbow. 192","PW-1339":"Transplanted seedlings often experience root injury during transplantation, which can lead to difficulties in establishment and growth. The majority of the water that is finally delivered to the plant’s top growth is absorbed by tiny roots that are farther from the plant and are covered by even smaller hairs. These delicate roots are typically killed after a transplant either by being chopped to reduce the size of the root ball or by drying out. It’s referred to as transplant shock. Transplant shock refers to a number of stresses that occur in recently transplanted trees and shrubs. It involves failure of the plant to root well, consequently the plant establishes poorly in the landscape. New transplants frequently experience stress due to a shortage of water because their root systems are not yet well established. Water stressed plants may be more vulnerable to harm from other factors, such as the environment, insects, or disease. 193","PW-1340":"Biomass gasification is a process that converts biomass (organic materials like wood, crop residues, and animal waste) into syngas (synthetic gas) by heating it in a controlled environment with limited oxygen or steam. Statement 1 is correct: Rice husk, groundnut shells, and coconut shells can all be utilised in the biomass gasification process. Statement 2 is incorrect: Biomass gasification involves burning of biomass in a limited supply of air to provide a combustible gas consisting of carbon monoxide, carbon dioxide, hydrogen, methane, water, nitrogen, along with contaminants like small char particles, ash and tars. Statement 3 is incorrect: Combustible syngas is frequently used as a fuel for internal combustion engines or as a step in the synthesis of other compounds. Consequently, the flammable gases produced by biomass gasification can be used for direct heat generation as well as in internal combustion engines. 195","PW-1341":"Graphene is a single layer of carbon atoms arranged in a hexagonal honeycomb lattice, making it the thinnest, strongest, and most conductive material known. It has remarkable applications in electronics, energy storage, and nanotechnology due to its high strength, flexibility, and conductivity. Statement 1 is correct: Graphene, a two-dimensional, atomic- scale, honey-comb lattice is an allotrope of carbon in which one atom forms each vertex. It is the basic structural unit of other allotropes, including graphite, charcoal, carbon nanotubes and fullerenes. Graphene has remarkably good electrical conductivity. Statement 2 is correct: It is often cited as about 100 times stronger than the strongest steel with a hypothetical thickness of 3.35Å(approx.) which is equal to the thickness of a graphene sheet. Carbon atoms are linked together in a single layer to form the hexagonal structure that makes up graphene. Graphene is so much thinner than paper (a million times thinner), that it is actually regarded as two dimensional. Statement 3 is incorrect: Graphene is a single layer (monolayer) o","PW-1342":"Lead poisoning is a toxic condition caused by the accumulation of lead in the body, typically through exposure to contaminated air, water, soil, or consumer products. It affects multiple organ systems, particularly the nervous system, and can lead to severe health issues such as cognitive impairment, developmental delays, and organ damage.  Option 1 and 3 are correct: Even after the stricter regulations, major sources of lead pollution include mining, smelting, manufacturing, and recycling, with the production of lead- acid batteries for automobiles accounting for over three- quarters of global lead usage.  Other common sources of lead poisoning include lead- based paint, contaminated soil, children’s toys and jewelry, drinking water from lead pipes, workplace and hobby hazards (such as mining and smelting), lead-glazed ceramics, pottery, leaded crystal, imported candy, and mini blinds.  Option 2 and 4 are incorrect:  Pens and pencils are incorrect as modern pencils mostly contain graphite, not lead, and pens use regulated ink formulations.  Hair oils and cosmetics are incorrect","PW-1343":"","PW-1344":"Statement 1 is correct: Thorium composes 0.0006% of the earth’s crust whereas Uranium composes 0.00018% of the earth’s crust, where a substantial amount of Uranium is found in dissolved seawater. Thus, Thorium(Th) is comparatively far more abundant in nature than uranium(U). Statement 2 is correct: Uranium-233, produced from thorium, is generally considered to have higher energy output compared to natural uranium, with estimates suggesting it could produce significantly more energy per unit mass, though the exact ratio can vary depending on reactor design and conditions. Statement 3 is correct: Thorium-based reactors generate less long-lived radioactive waste compared to uranium-based reactors. The waste from thorium has a lower proportion of transuranic elements like plutonium, which are highly radioactive and pose disposal challenges.\" 199","PW-1345":"Biologists studying various forms of life on Earth have identified a common characteristic among all living organisms. The matter within every living organism on Earth primarily consists of four chemical elements: hydrogen, oxygen, carbon, and nitrogen. Option (b) is correct: Carbon, hydrogen, and nitrogen are the elements that were primarily responsible for the origin of life on Earth. These elements are fundamental in the formation of organic compounds, such as proteins, nucleic acids, and lipids, which are essential for life. The combination of carbon, hydrogen, and nitrogen forms the basis of amino acids, nucleotides, and other critical biomolecules involved in the origin of life on Earth. 200","PW-1346":"Capillarity (or capillary action) is the ability of a liquid to flow in narrow spaces, such as thin tubes or porous materials, without the assistance of external forces and even against gravity. It occurs due to the cohesion (attraction between liquid molecules) and adhesion (attraction between the liquid and solid surface), along with surface tension. Statement 1 is correct: The oil in the wick of a lamp rises due to the capillary action of threads in the wick. Absence of capillarity would certainly make it difficult to use Kerosene lamps. Statement 2 is incorrect: There is no capillary action in using a straw to consume the soft drink as the consumer applies additional pressure from the mouth to consume the soft drink. Statement 3 is correct: A blotting paper soaks ink by the capillary action of the pores in the blotting paper. The blotting paper will not be useful without the capillarity phenomenon. Statement 4 is correct: The root-hairs of plants draw water from the soil through capillary action. Therefore absence of capillarity phenomenon would adversely affect the growth of tre","PW-1347":"In severe winter, a lake’s surface freezes while the bottom remains liquid due to the anomalous density behavior of water. Unlike most substances, water reaches its maximum density at 4°C, meaning that as it cools, denser water sinks while colder, lighter water (below 4°C) stays at the surface. When temperatures drop below 0°C, the surface water freezes first, forming an insulating ice layer that prevents further heat loss from the deeper water, keeping it in a liquid state. This phenomenon protects aquatic life, as it prevents the entire lake from freezing solid 202","PW-1348":"Microbial fuel cells (MFCs) are a bioelectrochemical technique, proposed to generate power using electrons from biological reactions in microorganisms. Statement 1 is correct: These devices primarily use bacteria as catalysts to break down organic and inorganic substances, generating electrical current. Statement 2 is incorrect: Microorganisms oxidise organic compounds, not inorganic substrates in the anode chamber, producing electrons and protons (reaction of anodes). Statement 3 is correct: An MFC typically consists of two electrodes: the anode and the cathode. At the anode, bacteria decompose organic matter in wastewater, producing electrons and protons. The electrons travel through an external circuit to the cathode, generating electricity, while the protons move from the anode to the cathode. At the cathode, the electrons and protons combine with an electron acceptor, such as oxygen, to form water. As a result, MFCs can be implemented in wastewater treatment facilities to purify water and generate electricity. 203","PW-1349":"Moderator is used in a nuclear reactor for slowing down the neutrons produced during the fission reaction so that the chain reaction can be sustained. Due to its high moderating ratio and low neutron absorption cross section, heavy water makes a good moderator. Deuterium oxide, popularly known as heavy water (D2O), is a hydrogen isotope with a mass double that of regular hydrogen and oxygen. However, In nuclear power reactors, heavy water can also be utilized as a coolant. 204","PW-1350":"Trans fatty acids (TFA) or trans fats are a form of unsaturated fat and come in both natural and artificial forms. Trans fats are the most harmful type of fats which can cause an adverse effect on a human body than any other dietary constituent. Statement 1 is correct: Artificial trans fats are generated through an industrial process that adds hydrogen to liquid vegetable oils to form them more solid. That is hydrogen is made to react with the oil to produce fats that resemble pure ghee or butter. If items do not contain trans-fats, it means the food products are not made out of hydrogenated oils and animal fats/oils. Statement 2 is incorrect: This is incorrect because not all animal fats contain trans fats. While small amounts of naturally occurring trans fats are found in some animal products, the harmful trans fats that raise cardiovascular risks are primarily from industrial hydrogenation, not from natural animal fats. Statement 3 is correct: If items do not contain trans fats, it suggests that the oils used are less likely to harm the cardiovascular health of consumers, as oils ","PW-1351":"Statement 1 is correct: An LED is a type of semiconductor light source with two leads. It is a p-n junction diode, which when turned on emits light. A fluorescent lamp is a low-pressure mercury-vapour gas-discharge light. In a CFL, an electric current is driven through a tube containing argon and a small amount of mercury vapor. This generates invisible ultraviolet light that excites a fluorescent coating (called phosphor) on the inside of the tube, which then emits visible light. Statement 2 is incorrect: LED bulbs are much more efficient than CFL bulbs in terms of power consumption and life years. Statement 3 is correct: LED bulbs consume less power as compared to CFL. LED bulbs are expensive as compared to CFL bulbs. LED bulbs are much more efficient than CFL bulbs. 206","PW-1352":"Aspartame is a non-saccharide artificial sweetener approximately 200 times sweeter than sucrose, and is commonly used as a substitute of sugar in foods and beverages. The commercial names for it are NutraSweet, Equal, and Canderel. It is a methyl ester of the aspartic acid / phenylalanine dipeptide. Since Aspartame is several times sweeter than table sugar, hence food items made with small quantities of aspartame yield fewer calories on oxidation. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 582 207","PW-1353":"Oilzapper is an eco-friendly technology for oil sludges and oil spills remediation. Oilzapping is the new technique using bacteria to get rid of oil spills. It is a bio-remediation technique that involves the use of oil zapping bacteria. In essence, Oilzapper is a concoction of five distinct bacterial strains that have been immobilised and combined with a carrier substance (powdered corn cob). The Oilzapper consumes the hydrocarbon molecules found in crude oil and oily sludge, a dangerous hydrocarbon waste product produced by oil refineries, and transforms them into harmless CO2 and water. This is exactly what its witty name implies. 208","PW-1354":"The blood group of the couple is AB Positive and O Negative. So their biological sons will have either blood group A or B. Thus we can infer that the blood group of the adopted son will be O. 209","PW-1355":"Statement 1 is correct: DVD stands for “Digital Versatile Disk” or “Digital Video Disc”. It is a type of digital optical disc storage that can hold any kind of digital data but is frequently used to store pictures, audio, and video in standard definition. Blu-ray Disc is a digital disc storage format similar to CD and DVD, that is designed to record and play a large amount of data with high-definition quality. Statement 2 is correct: Blu-ray Disc media include these features: 50GB capacity - Each disc can hold more than 10 standard DVDs. Statement 3 is incorrect: The size of the Blu-ray disc is 120 millimetres in diameter with 1.2 millimetres thickness, which is the same as the size of a CD and DVD. 210","PW-1356":"The tissue just beneath the bark called the phloem layer is in charge of moving food produced by photosynthesis from the leaves to the roots. This process is called girdling, and it is fatal to trees because it disrupts the transport of nutrients. Without this nourishment, the roots eventually perish and stop supplying the leaves with water and nutrients. Later, the leaves wither. Because its roots are starved of vitality, a tree that has had its bark removed in a circular pattern all around near its base gradually dries up and dies. 211","PW-1357":"Statement 1 is incorrect: The presence of ions, and not ozone, in the Ionosphere is responsible for radio communication. Ozone is primarily present in the Stratosphere and not in the Ionosphere. Statement 2 is incorrect: They have frequencies from 300 GHz to as low as 3 kHz and corresponding wavelengths from 1 millimetre to 100 kilometres. They have a long range of wavelengths, so they can have very small wavelengths as well. Science and Technology 583 212","PW-1358":"Bt Brinjal is the first Genetically Modified food crop in India that has reached the approval stage for commercialization. Bt Brinjal is a genetically modified (GM) crop created by inserting Cry1Ac gene from the soil bacterium Bacillus thuringiensis into Brinjal. Brinjal plants now have resistance to lepidopteran pests such the Brinjal Fruit and Shoot Borer (Leucinodes orbonalis) and Fruit Borer as a result of the gene’s insertion (Helicoverpa armigera). 10. PHYSICS 10.1 Mechanics 213","PW-1359":"The elongation of a wire under a load depends on its length, cross-sectional area and the material of the wire. In this case, all four wires are made of the same material, which means that the material`s properties will not be a factor in determining the elongation. The elongation (ΔL) of a wire under a given load is determined by Hooke’s Law and is given by the formula: ΔL = F⋅L/A⋅Y​ F: Force applied (which is same for all wires) L: Length of the wire A: cross sectional area of the wire (depends on diameter (d), i.e. (πd2/4)) Y: Young’s modulus of the material (same for all the wires) On substituting the values ; elongation (ΔL) ∝ L/d2 The elongation is proportional to L/d2, and the wire with the highest value of L/d2 will elongate the most, which comes out to be for the wire with length 3m and diameter 1.5mm. 214","PW-1360":"The time taken to empty a vessel depends on the flow rate of liquid through the tap. The flow rate is determined by Torricelli’s theorem, which states: v = √2gh, where; v is the velocity of liquid exiting the tap, g is the acceleration due to the gravity h is the height of the liquid column above the tap (identical for all vessels). Water, Kerosene and Mercury have different densities, but we can see that velocity is independent of the densities of the liquid. Viscosity (resistance to flow) affects the ease with which the liquid flows through the tap. Kerosene has the lowest viscosity among the three, followed by water, and mercury has the highest viscosity. Since kerosene has the lowest viscosity, it encounters the least resistance to flow, meaning it will flow out the fastest and empty first. 215","PW-1361":"The Earth revolves around the Sun in an almost circular orbit. The approximate radius of Earth›s orbit (the average distance from the Sun) is r = 1 Astronomical Unit (AU) = 1.496 × 1011m. The circumference of the orbit will be given by C = 2πr, substituting r = 1.496 × 1011m, we will get C = 9.4 × 1011m. Time taken for one revolution: The Earth takes approximately 1 year to complete one orbit. Time in seconds will be T = 3.156 × 107s. Mean Orbital Velocity: The mean velocity(v) will be given by: v = distance/time, substituting the values: v = 9.4 × 1011m/3.156 × 107s = 29.8 km/s ≈ 30 km/s. 216","PW-1362":"Density is a physical property that represents the compactness of a substance. It is defined as the mass of a substance per unit volume. The higher the density, the more mass is packed into a given volume.  Gold is known for its high density. It is a dense metal with a density of approximately 19.3 grams per cubic centimeter (g/cm³). This makes gold denser than both steel and mercury.  Mercury is a liquid metal at room temperature and has a relatively low density compared to both gold and steel. Its density is approximately 13.6 g/cm³, making it less dense than gold but denser than steel.  Steel, which is an alloy primarily composed of iron and carbon, has a lower density than gold but is still relatively dense compared to many other materials. The density of steel varies depending on its composition, but it typically ranges from around 7.7 g/cm³ to 8.1 g/cm³. 217","PW-1363":"","PW-1364":"When a spherical body moves in a circular path with uniform angular velocity ω, it undergoes uniform circular motion. Even though the angular velocity is constant, the direction of the velocity vector changes continuously, resulting in centripetal acceleration. The centripetal acceleration is always directed toward the centre of the circular path. The magnitude of the centripetal acceleration is given by: a=ω2r. where, ω= angular velocity and r = radius of the circular path. 219","PW-1365":"The question is based on the principle of buoyancy, which means that an object fully or partly immersed in fluid experiences an upthrust or buoyant force equal to the weight of the fluid displaced. When a weightless balloon filled with water is immersed into water, it displaces an amount of water equivalent to its own volume, in this case, 200 cc. The weight of this displaced water in terms of gravitational pull is equal to the weight of the balloon under these conditions. Since both weights are identical (as the balloon is also filled with water), they cancel out each other, resulting in a net weight of the balloon in water to be zero. 220","PW-1366":"Assertion (A) is true: Weight is the force of gravity acting on an object, and gravity weakens as the distance from the Earth›s center increases. Since altitude represents a greater distance from the Earth›s center, the force of gravity and thus the weight of the body diminish. Reason (R) is true: The Earth is not a perfect sphere, being slightly flattened at the poles and bulging at the equator, this fact does not primarily explain the decrease in weight with altitude. The primary reason lies in the inverse square law of gravity, which states that the force of gravity between two objects decreases proportionally to the square of the distance between them. Hence, Reason (R) does not correctly explain the Assertion (A). 221","PW-1367":"Statement 1 is correct: When a vehicle takes a sharp turn at high speed, the centrifugal force may push the vehicle outwards. This can cause the vehicle to tilt outwards and potentially overturn about its outer wheels. Statement 2 is incorrect: This is less likely to happen. The centrifugal force pushes the vehicle outwards, not inwards. Statement 3 is correct: If the friction between the tires and the road is insufficient to provide the necessary centripetal force, the vehicle may skid outwards, away from the center of the turn. Statement 4 is incorrect: Skidding typically occurs outwards, not inwards, due to the centrifugal force. 222","PW-1368":"When the oil tanker accelerates forward, the oil inside experiences an inertial force (pseudo force) acting in the opposite direction to the acceleration. This causes the free surface of the oil to tilt. 1. The rear end of the tanker has larger depth because the inertial force pushes the oil backward. 2. The front end has smaller depth as the oil moves away from it. Thus, The free surface of the oil becomes inclined, with the rear end having a larger depth 223","PW-1369":"","PW-1370":"Viscosity is a measure of a fluid›s resistance to flow. It describes the internal friction of a moving fluid. Glycerine is a viscous liquid, meaning it has a relatively high resistance to flow at room temperature. Assertion (A) is false: The viscosity of liquids generally decreases with an increase in temperature. This is because higher temperatures lead to increased molecular motion, which weakens the intermolecular forces that cause viscosity. Reason (R) is true: Kinetic energy is the energy of motion. When the temperature of a substance increases, the molecules gain more kinetic energy, causing them to move faster. 225","PW-1371":"Density is a measure of how much mass is packed into a given volume. Buoyancy is the tendency of an object to float in a fluid. An object floats if its density is less than the fluid’s density and sinks if its density is greater. If the densities are equal, the object remains neutrally buoyant, neither sinking nor floating. Assertion (A) is true: Iron is denser than water, so it sinks in water. However, mercury is denser than iron, so an iron ball will float on mercury. Reason (R) is false: Specific gravity is the ratio of the density of a substance to the density of a reference substance (usually water). Mercury is denser than iron, so its specific gravity is higher. 226","PW-1372":"Given:  Mass added to fully submerge the cube: m= 0.2 kg  The Cube floats 2 cm above water when mass is removed.  Density of water: ρ = 1000 kg/m3 Using Archimedes’ principle: 1. When fully submerged: ρ.l3 = m(cube) + m(added) 2. When floating 2 cm above water: Submerged volume: V(submerged) = l2.(l - 0.02) Mass of the cube: m(cube) = ρ.V(submerged) Equating: l3 = l2.(l-0.02)+0.2/1000 Testing options: For l = 10 cm, the equation holds true. 227. The mass of a body on earth is 100 kg (acceleration due to gravity, ge = 10 m/s2","PW-1373":"Mass is a measure of the amount of matter in an object and does not change with location. Therefore, the mass of the body on Earth and on the Moon remains the same.It is measured in kilograms (kg) and represents the amount of matter in an object. What changes is the weight of the object, which depends on the gravitational acceleration. Weight is the force exerted by gravity on an object. Weight depends on both the mass of the object and the local gravitational acceleration. It is calculated using the formula: Weight = Mass × Gravitational acceleration (g) The weight on the Moon will be less because the gravitational acceleration there is only 1/6th of Earth’s gravity. 228","PW-1374":"Statement 1 is correct: At the mean position, the pendulum has maximum velocity and is moving in a straight line for an instant with no force along its path and hence producing zero acceleration. Statement 2 is correct: In one complete oscillation, the bob passes through the mean position twice - once moving in each direction, hence attaining the maximum velocity twice in a complete oscillation. Statement 3 is incorrect: At the extreme position, the bob has zero velocity as it stops for an instant before reversing the direction. However, at this point the acceleration is maximum because bob completely comes under the force of gravity and hence produces maximum acceleration. Statement 4 is correct: In an ideal situation, due to air resistance and internal friction, the amplitude of oscillation decreases with time. 229","PW-1375":"The motion of an object traveling in a straight line can be represented on a distance-time graph, with the shape of the graph depending on whether the motion is uniform (straight line) or non-uniform (curved line). Uniform motion represents a constant change in displacement per second. The distance time graph for uniform motion is a straight line, that is, equal distance is covered by the equal units of time. Option (d) represents the graph where change in displacement per second is constant. Therefore, velocity is constant and hence it performs uniform motion. 230","PW-1376":"Option 1 is incorrect: While radial tyres improve handling and durability, they primarily reduce rolling resistance, which can have a minor impact on fuel efficiency. However, their primary benefit is not directly linked to significant fuel savings. Option 2 is correct: A streamlined body reduces aerodynamic drag, allowing the car to move more efficiently through the air. This directly improves fuel efficiency, especially at higher speeds. An example of a car with a streamlined body is the Tesla Model S. Its sleek, aerodynamic design minimizes air resistance, improving both fuel efficiency (or energy efficiency in the case of electric cars) and performance. Option 3 is correct: Multipoint Fuel Injection ensures that the right amount of fuel is injected into each cylinder, improving combustion efficiency and reducing fuel consumption. Option 4 is incorrect: While a catalytic converter reduces harmful emissions, it does not directly affect fuel efficiency. Its primary function is to convert toxic gases like carbon monoxide into less harmful substances. Direction: The following item con","PW-1377":"According to Newton’s first law of motion, “ A body at rest will remain at rest, and a body in motion will continue in uniform motion in a straight line unless acted upon by an external force”. According to Newton’s second law of motion, “The rate of change of momentum of a body is directly proportional to the applied force and occurs in the direction of the force”. Assertion (A) is true: When the man whistles, he expels air from his lungs. This expelled air has mass and velocity, creating momentum in the forward direction and thus creating reaction force which pushes the man backward on the frictionless surface. This is based on Newton’s second law of motion. Reason (R) is true: The statement that ‘ if no external force acts on a system, its momentum cannot change’ is clearly stating Newton›s first law of motion which is clearly not explaining the Assertion (A). Thus, Reason (R) merely states Newton’s First Law of Motion and doen’s explain the Assertion (A) which is based on Newton’s Second Law of Motion. 232","PW-1378":"Both the bullet and the monkey experience the same downward acceleration due to gravity provided the air resistance is negligible. When the hunter fires the bullet, the bullet starts moving along a curved trajectory due to the combined effects of its horizontal velocity and the vertical acceleration caused by gravity. When the monkey jumps, it also begins to fall freely under gravity with an initial vertical velocity of zero. Science and Technology 587 Since the hunter aims directly at the monkey at the moment of firing, the bullet and the monkey will both fall the same vertical distance due to gravity at the same time. Therefore, the bullet will hit the monkey at the point aimed. 233","PW-1379":"","PW-1380":"To solve this, we use the formula for velocity under constant acceleration: v = u + at Where, v is the final velocity, u is the initial velocity, a is the acceleration, t is the time. Given, Initial velocity u = 0 (the ball is dropped), Acceleration a = 9.8 m/s2, Time t = 2 seconds Substitute into the formula: v = 0 + (9.8)(2) = 19.6 m/s Thus, the velocity after 2 seconds is 19.6 m/s. 235","PW-1381":"Surface tension is the force that acts on the surface of a liquid, causing it to contract and minimize its surface area. This effect occurs because molecules at the surface of the liquid experience a net inward force due to the attractive forces between the molecules. As a result, the liquid tends to form shapes that have the least surface area, such as spherical droplets. This tendency to minimize surface area is why liquid droplets form spherical shapes in free space, as a sphere has the smallest surface area for a given volume. 236","PW-1382":"A vector quantity is a physical quantity that has both magnitude and direction. In addition to how much of a quantity there is, you also need to know the direction in which it acts. Some examples of vector quantities include force, velocity, acceleration and displacement. Momentum is a vector quantity because it has both magnitude and direction (it depends on the direction of motion and the velocity of the object). 237","PW-1383":"When a girl is sitting on a swing, her center of mass is lower. When she stands up, her center of mass rises. The period of a swing depends on the length of the swing and the position of the center of mass. The period T of a simple pendulum (which is a good approximation for a swing) is given by the formula: T = 2p L g Where: T is the period (time for one complete oscillation) L is the length of the swing (distance from the pivot point to the center of mass), g is the acceleration due to gravity. When the girl stands, the increased height of the center of mass results in a shorter period (the swing oscillates faster), as the effective length of the pendulum decreases. 238","PW-1384":"The height of a projectile is determined by the vertical component of the initial velocity, which increases with the angle of projection (vsinθ). In the diagram, as the initial inclination increases, the ball reaches a greater height, which aligns with the laws of projectile motion. Therefore, the larger the initial inclination, the greater the height reached is a valid conclusion. 239","PW-1385":"","PW-1386":"","PW-1387":"A simple machine (like a lever, pulley, or inclined plane) helps reduce the amount of force needed to do work. While the amount of work (force × distance) remains the same, the machine allows you to apply a smaller force over a greater distance to achieve the same result. Essentially, it provides a mechanical advantage, enabling you to use less force to perform a task. For example, using a pulley system can help lift a heavy load with less effort, but the work done (in terms of energy) remains unchanged. 10.2 Heat and Thermodynamics 244","PW-1388":"Statement 1 is incorrect: Steam at 100°C contains significantly more heat than boiling water at 100°C. This is because steam has absorbed additional energy in the form of latent heat of vaporization which is the energy required to convert water at 100°C into steam at the same temperature without changing its temperature. Statement 2 is incorrect: The latent heat of fusion of ice (the energy required to convert ice at 0°C to water at 0°C) is approximately 334 kJ/kg while the latent heat of vaporization of water (the energy required to convert water at 100°C to steam at 100°C) is approximately 2260 kJ/kg. Statement 3 is correct: In an air-conditioner the refrigerant absorbs heat from the room air at the evaporator coils and cools the air. This heat is then transported to the condenser coils, where it is released to the outside environment. This process is based on the principles of thermodynamics and the refrigeration cycle. 245","PW-1389":"The rate at which an object cools depends on its surface area-to-volume ratio and temperature difference with the surroundings. A higher surface area-to-volume ratio allows more heat to be dissipated into the surroundings, leading to faster cooling. The sphere has the largest surface area compared to the cube and circular plate. The larger the surface area, the more heat can be radiated or transferred to the surroundings, which leads to a faster cooling rate. The sphere cools faster than the circular plate and cube for the same radius. The more heat the sphere can radiate, the quicker it will reach room temperature compared to objects with smaller surface areas. Note: Here, we can ignore the impact of volume as the sphere, disc or cube all are hollow with negligible thickness. 246","PW-1390":"Thermal conductivity is a property of a material that indicates its ability to conduct heat. It is defined as the amount of heat that passes through a unit area of a material over a unit of time, when there is a temperature difference across the material. Assertion (A) is true: When copper and glass are heated to the same temperature, copper feels hotter to the touch because it has a much higher thermal conductivity than glass. Copper transfers heat to your skin more quickly than glass which makes it feel hotter. Reason (R) is true: While it is true that copper has a higher density than glass, the reason copper feels hotter is due to its thermal conductivity, not its density. R is Not a Correct Explanation of A: The reason (R) correctly states that copper is denser than glass, but density alone does not determine how hot an object feels to the touch. The primary factor is thermal conductivity, which determines how quickly heat is transferred from the object to your skin. Directions: The following item consist of two statements, one labeled as the Assertion (A) and the other as Reason","PW-1391":"The boiling point of a substance is the temperature at which its vapour pressure equals the external atmospheric pressure, causing it to change from a liquid to a gas. Assertion (A) is true: The boiling point of water decreases with increasing altitude because atmospheric pressure decreases at higher altitudes. At lower pressure the water molecules require less energy to escape into the vapor phase, so water boils at a lower temperature. For example, at sea level, water boils at 100°C, but at higher altitudes, it can boil at temperatures as low as 90°C or even lower. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 590 Reason (R) is false: Atmospheric pressure decreases with increasing altitude. As you go higher in the atmosphere, the air becomes less dense, and the pressure exerted by the atmosphere decreases. This is why mountaintops have lower atmospheric pressure compared to sea level. 248","PW-1392":"When water is heated from to, it exhibits an unusual behavior due to the anomalous expansion of water. Between 0°C and 4°C, water contracts, meaning its volume decreases as the temperature increases. At 4°C, water reaches its minimum volume (maximum density). Above 4°C the water starts expanding which means its volume increases as the temperature increases further. This behavior is quite unique to water and is crucial for the survival of aquatic life in cold climates. 249","PW-1393":"","PW-1394":"","PW-1395":"","PW-1396":"Assertion (A) is false: Radio waves (a type of electromagnetic wave) do not bend in a magnetic field. Electromagnetic waves such as radio waves travel in straight lines in a vacuum or uniform medium unless they are refracted, reflected, or diffracted by physical obstacles or changes in the medium. A magnetic field does not cause electromagnetic waves to bend. Reason (R) is true: Radio waves are indeed electromagnetic waves, which are oscillations of electric and magnetic fields that propagate through space. They are part of the electromagnetic spectrum and include frequencies ranging from about 3 kHz to 300 GHz. Directions: The following two items consist of two statements, one labeled as the Assertion (A) and the other as Reason (R). You have to answer these items using the code given below. (2008) 254","PW-1397":"Statement 1 is correct: Magenta and yellow are primary colors in the subtractive color model (used in printing). When they intersect, the resulting color is red, as magenta absorbs green and yellow absorbs blue. The remaining reflected light is red. Statement 2 is correct: Cyan and magenta are also primary colors in the subtractive color model. Cyan absorbs red light, and magenta absorbs green light. When cyan and magenta overlap, they absorb red and green light, leaving blue light to be reflected. :  Subtractive color mixing occurs when colors are created by subtracting (absorbing) certain wavelengths of light and reflecting others. It is used in pigments or filters, where primary colors cyan, magenta, and yellow combine to produce secondary colors (e.g., magenta + yellow = red). 255","PW-1398":"Statement 1 is incorrect: The frequency of sound produced by a flute is inversely proportional to its length. A shorter flute produces sound waves of higher frequency (higher pitch), while a longer flute produces sound waves of lower frequency (lower pitch). Statement 2 is incorrect: Sound (or seismic waves) in rocks travels in both longitudinal (P-waves) and transverse (S-waves) forms. Longitudinal waves compress and expand the material, while transverse waves move the material perpendicular to the direction of propagation of the wave. 256","PW-1399":"Mach Number is the ratio of an object’s speed to the speed of sound in the surrounding medium: Mach Number = Object’s Speed / Speed of Sound ​The speed of sound in air is primarily influenced by temperature and to a lesser extent by atmospheric composition. Assertion (A) is false: The speed of sound depends on the temperature of the medium. At higher altitudes (e.g., 15 km) the temperature is much lower than at sea level. The speed of sound decreases with decreasing temperature. Therefore, at 15 km altitude, the speed of sound is lower than at sea level. If the aircraft is moving at Mach 1 at both altitudes, its actual speed will be lower at 15 km because the speed of sound is lower there. Reason (R) is true: The velocity of sound depends on the temperature of the surrounding medium. This is also true because the speed of sound is given by v=√γRTM, where γ is the specific heat ratio, R is the gas constant, T is the absolute temperature and M is the molecular mass of the gas. A decrease in temperature reduces the speed of sound. Directions: The following two items consist of two state","PW-1400":"The speed of sound depends on the medium through which it travels. Sound travels faster in denser and more elastic materials because the particles are closer together and can transmit vibrations more efficiently. The speed of sound in different media follows this general order: solids > liquids > gases. The speed of sound in wood varies depending on the type of wood but it is generally much higher than in air or water. For example, in hardwoods like oak, the speed of sound can be around 3300–3600 m/s. Wood is a solid and sound travels fastest because the molecules are tightly packed and can transmit vibrations very efficiently. 258","PW-1401":"The diffusion of light in the atmosphere occurs mainly due to dust particles and aerosols, which scatter sunlight in all directions. This scattering, known as Mie scattering, happens when particles like dust or water droplets are comparable in size to the wavelength of light, scattering all wavelengths almost equally. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 592 It causes the sky to appear uniformly bright and ensures visibility even in shadows. Other aerosols like Water Vapors, Smoke, etc can also contribute to the diffusion effect. However, dust particles are the most prominent cause in this context. 259","PW-1402":"Statement 1 is incorrect: According to Rayleigh scattering, light with shorter wavelengths (e.g., blue light) is scattered more than light with longer wavelengths (e.g., red light). Statement 2 is incorrect: The refractive index of water is approximately 1.33, so the speed of light in water is about 1/1.33 ≈ 0.75 × the speed in a vacuum. Statement 3 is correct: Radio waves are a type of electromagnetic radiation generated when electrical charges oscillate in an antenna. These oscillations create alternating electric and magnetic fields that propagate as waves. This principle is the basis of wireless communication technologies like radio, TV, and mobile networks. Statement 4 is correct: The Doppler effect is used in radar guns to measure the speed of moving vehicles by analyzing the frequency shift of reflected radio waves. 261","PW-1403":"A mirage is primarily caused by terrestrial heating and the refraction of light. Mirage causes deceptive appearance of a distant object or objects caused by light ray bending (refraction) in different density layers of air. Terrestrial Heating: The ground is intensely heated by the sun (such as a hot road or desert). This heats the air near the surface, making it less dense than the cooler air above. The temperature gradient creates a gradient in the refractive index of the air. Refraction of Light: Light from the sky or distant objects passes through the layers of air with varying temperatures and densities. The light bends (refracts) as it moves from cooler, denser air to hotter, less dense air. This bending creates the illusion of water or a mirrored surface on the ground. 262","PW-1404":"Assertion (A) is true: When a stick is dipped in water at a slanting position and observed from the side, the stick appears short and bent at the water’s surface. This happens because of refraction, where light rays change direction when they pass from water (denser medium) to air (rarer medium). Refraction is the bending of light as it passes from one medium to another medium with a different refractive index. Reason (R) is false: The reason given in the statement refers to scattering of light, which is incorrect in this context. The phenomenon responsible for the apparent bending and shortening of the stick is refraction, not scattering. Scattering involves the redirection of light by particles in the medium and is unrelated to the bending of the stick’s image. Direction: The following item consists of two statements, one labeled as the Assertion (A) and the other as Reason (R). You have to answer this item using the code given below. (2001) 263","PW-1405":"When light waves pass from air to glass, the wavelength and velocity are affected. Velocity decreases because the speed of light in glass is less than in air due to the higher refractive index of glass. Wavelength also decreases because it is directly proportional to the velocity of light in the medium (λ=v/f, where ‘f’ is the frequency). Frequency remains unchanged because it is determined by the source of the light and does not depend on the medium. Science and Technology 593 264","PW-1406":"","PW-1407":"","PW-1408":"Assertion (A) is true: The glass beads on traffic signals are designed to reflect light efficiently. When light hits them, they undergo a reflective process, causing the beads to glow brightly and making the signal more visible from various angles. Reason (R) is true: This describes the phenomenon of total internal reflection (TIR), which occurs when light moves from a denser medium (like glass) to a rarer medium (like air) and the angle of incidence exceeds the critical angle. In the case of the glass beads, light entering the bead at a steep angle is totally internally reflected, making them glow brightly. Thereby, Reason (R) correctly explains Assertion (A). 267","PW-1409":"In the case of a compact disc (CD), when sunlight or any other light source hits its surface, the following optical phenomena occur. Diffraction: The CD’s surface contains tiny, closely spaced grooves that act like a diffraction grating. This causes the light to spread out into different colors, creating the rainbow effect that is visible. Refraction: Light also passes through the transparent plastic layer of the CD, and as it enters and exits this layer, it bends due to the change in the refractive index between the plastic and air. Transmission: Some light also passes through the CD material, further contributing to the observed effects. Together, these phenomena—refraction, diffraction, and transmission—combine to produce the beautiful rainbow-like colors seen when a CD is viewed in sunlight. 268","PW-1410":"A is matched with 1: High speed is often measured in terms of the Mach number, which is a ratio of an object’s speed to the speed of sound in the surrounding medium. Mach number represents the speed of an object relative to the speed of sound in the surrounding medium. B is matched with 2: The unit used to measure the wavelength of light or electromagnetic waves is the angstrom (1 angstrom = 10^-10 meters). C is matched with 3: The unit of pressure is the Pascal (Pa), which is defined as one newton per square meter (N/m²). D is matched with 4: The unit of energy is the Joule (J). UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 594 269","PW-1411":"When light passes from one medium to another, its speed and direction change due to differences in the refractive indices of the two media. This phenomenon is known as refraction. Statement 1 is correct: In a denser medium (with a higher refractive index), light travels slower. When light moves into a less dense medium (with a lower refractive index), it speeds up. As a result, the light bends away from the normal (the imaginary line perpendicular to the surface at the point of incidence). The object appears to be closer from the surface than it actually is, as seen in the case of a coin in water when viewed from above. Statement 2 is correct: If a person is underwater looking at a coin above the surface, the coin appears higher than its actual position, not lower. This is because light bends away from the normal when moving from water (denser) to air (rarer). 270","PW-1412":"When a mirror is rotated by an angle θ, the reflected ray will rotate by twice that angle, i.e. 2θ. This is due to the law of reflection, which states that the angle of incidence is equal to the angle of reflection. If the mirror is rotated by an angle θ , both the incident and reflected rays will rotate, causing the reflected ray to change direction by an angle of 2θ . 271","PW-1413":"Total internal reflection occurs when light travels from a medium with a higher refractive index to a medium with a lower refractive index, and the angle of incidence exceeds the critical angle. From the given options, total internal reflection can take place when light travels from Diamond to glass. This is because diamond has a higher refractive index than glass, so when light travels from diamond to glass, it can undergo total internal reflection if the angle of incidence is greater than the critical angle. 10.4 Electricity and Magnetism 272","PW-1414":"","PW-1415":"","PW-1416":"Assertion (A) is false: In an alternating current (AC) system the current reverses direction periodically. The rate at which this reversal occurs is determined by the frequency of the supplied AC voltage. The standard AC supply frequency in many countries including India is 50 Hz. The AC completes one full cycle (positive and negative half-cycles) in 1/50th of a second. In one full cycle, the current changes direction twice (once at the positive peak and once at the negative peak). Therefore in a 50 Hz system the current changes direction 2 × 50 = 100 times per second, not 60 times per second. Science and Technology 595 Reason (R) is true: The standard AC frequency in many countries (including India) is indeed 50 Hz. This means that the AC completes 50 cycles per second. 275","PW-1417":"Option (b) is correct: Resistance (R) of a length l, resistivity r and area of cross-section A is given by l R A = ρ For the two wires, Therefore, the resistance of the thicker wire is 10 Ω. 276","PW-1418":"A fluorescent lamp or fluorescent tube is a gas discharge lamp that uses electricity to excite mercury vapour. The excited mercury atoms produce short-wave ultraviolet light that then causes a phosphor to fluoresce, producing visible light. The choke coil reduces current in the circuit. A choke coil, also known as an inductor, is used in fluorescent tubes to limit the current flowing through the circuit. It provides impedance to the alternating current (AC) which helps in stabilizing the current and preventing it from reaching excessively high levels. The choke coil does not step up or step down the voltage (these functions are typically performed by a transformer). 277","PW-1419":"Statement 1 is correct: The filament in a light bulb is typically made of tungsten. When the filament is not uniform , the thinner sections tend to heat up more, leading to higher temperatures and stress, which can cause premature failure. Statement 2 is correct: Light bulbs typically contain an inert gas, like argon, to prevent oxidation of the filament and improve lifespan. Complete evacuation of the bulb is not possible. A small quantity of gases left behind which expands on heating by heat through filament. If the bulb is not evacuated properly, the filament would burn out quickly causing the bulb to have a short life. Statement 3 is correct: The wires supporting the filament are designed to withstand high temperatures. However if they are not robust enough or if the filament heats up too much, and they can melt, causing the bulb to fail. 278","PW-1420":"Statement 1 is correct: Most car batteries are 12-volt lead-acid batteries. This is the standard voltage for automotive applications as it provides sufficient power for starting the engine and running electrical systems in vehicles. Statement 2 is incorrect: The electrolyte used in a car battery is sulfuric acid (H₂SO₄), not hydrochloric acid. Sulfuric acid is mixed with distilled water to create the electrolyte solution, which facilitates the electrochemical reactions in the battery. Statement 3 is incorrect: The electrodes in a car battery are made of lead (Pb) and lead dioxide (PbO₂), not copper. The negative electrode (anode) is made of pure lead, and the positive electrode (cathode) is made of lead dioxide. Statement 4 is correct: The capacity of a car battery is expressed in ampere-hours (Ah). This unit measures the amount of charge a battery can deliver over time. For example, a 50 Ah battery can theoretically deliver 1 ampere of current for 50 hours or 5 amperes for 10 hours. 279","PW-1421":"Assertion (A) is true: The flow of electric current through a conductor causes energy dissipation in the form of heat due to the collisions between free electrons and the metal atoms. Reason (R) is true: As electrons travel through a metal as they collide with metal atoms causing the atoms to vibrate more and collide with each other which produces heat. The phenomenon is known as Joule heating. When current flows through the metal wire, the free electrons that carry the current interact with the metal atoms, transferring energy and causing the atoms to vibrate more, leading to a temperature increase due to Joule heating. The amount of heat generated depends on factors such as the wire’s resistance, the current, and the duration of the current flow. This effect is the foundation for devices like electric heaters. Thus Reason (R) explains Assertion (A) 281","PW-1422":"","PW-1423":"Assertion (A) is true: A transformer is designed to change the voltage level of an alternating current (AC) by using electromagnetic induction, either increasing (stepping up) or decreasing (stepping down) the voltage. Reason (R) is false: A transformer only works with alternating current (AC) because it relies on the changing magnetic field created by the alternating current to induce voltage in the secondary coil. It does not function with direct current (DC). 283","PW-1424":"Domestic electrical wiring is primarily a parallel connection, meaning that appliances and devices are connected in parallel to the power supply. This ensures that each device receives the same voltage, and turning one device on or off does not affect the others. Parallel wiring also allows for individual control of appliances and prevents overloading of a single circuit. In a series connection, devices share the same current, and the total resistance adds up, which can cause voltage drops, as seen in old-fashioned Christmas lights where if one bulb fails, the entire string goes out. 10.5 Modern Physics 284","PW-1425":"","PW-1426":"Statement 1 is incorrect: A geo-stationary satellite orbits the Earth at an altitude of approximately 35,786 km(not 10,000 km) above the equator. This altitude ensures that the satellite’s orbital period matches the Earth’s rotational period, making it appear stationary from the ground. Statement 2 is correct: FM (Frequency Modulation) is less affected by noise because noise primarily affects amplitude, not frequency. This makes FM transmission superior in quality compared to AM (Amplitude Modulation). 287","PW-1427":"Nuclear fission is the process in which a heavy atomic nucleus, such as uranium-235 or plutonium-239, splits into two smaller nuclei, releasing a large amount of energy. Statement 1 is correct: Each fission reaction releases multiple neutrons, which are crucial for sustaining the chain reaction. Statement 2 is correct: The neutrons produced in fission reactions are used to initiate further fission events. Statement 3 is correct: Graphite (a moderator) slows down fast neutrons, increasing the likelihood that they will cause further fission reactions, thus making reaction sustainable over longer periods. Statement 4 is incorrect: Not every neutron released will necessarily cause further fission, as some neutrons may escape the reactor or fail to cause fission if not properly moderated. 288","PW-1428":"","PW-1429":"A TV remote control typically uses radio waves to communicate with the TV set. Radio waves are a form of electromagnetic radiation that enables the remote to send signals over short distances to control the television. Radio waves are widely used in radio and television broadcasting, enabling the transmission of audio and video signals over long distances. They are also essential in wireless communication systems, including mobile phones, Wi-Fi, and satellite communication. Note: In many sources, infrared waves are identified as the mechanism behind the functioning of TV remote controls, but this option is not provided in the given choices. :  Light waves: Light waves are used in technologies like fiber optics for high-speed internet and communication.  Sound waves: Sound waves are used in audio devices, medical imaging (ultrasound), and sonar systems.  Microwaves: Microwaves are used in radar, satellite communications, and cooking (microwave ovens). 290","PW-1430":"One astronomical unit (AU) is a unit of measurement used in astronomy to describe distances within our solar system. It represents the average distance between Earth and the Sun, which is approximately 149.6 million kilometers (or about 93 million miles). Light-Year (ly): A light-year is the distance that light travels in one year in a vacuum. It is commonly used to measure vast distances between stars and galaxies. Parsec (pc): A parsec is another unit of distance used in astronomy, equal to about 3.26 light-years or 3.086 × 10^13 kilometers. It is used primarily for measuring distances to stars and galaxies. Sidereal Day: A sidereal day is the time it takes for Earth to complete one full rotation relative to the stars, which is about 23 hours, 56 minutes, and 4 seconds. This is different from a solar day, which is based on the position of the Sun and is 24 hours. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 598 291","PW-1431":"The industrial ages gave us the understanding of sunlight as an energy source. India is endowed with vast solar energy potential. About 5,000 trillion kWh per year energy is incident over India’s land area with most parts receiving 4-7 kWh per sqm per day. Solar photovoltaic power can effectively be harnessed providing huge scalability in India. Statement 1 is correct: Solar water heaters are widely used for residential purposes. Statement 2 is correct: Solar-powered pumps are increasingly utilized for small-scale irrigation. Governments under PM KUSUM are advocating for proliferation of such pumps. Statement 3 is correct: Solar street lights are common in both rural and urban areas. Statement 4 is correct: Solar microgrids and standalone systems can provide electricity to remote villages and small towns. 10.6 Space Physics 292","PW-1432":"Statement 1 is correct: A jet engine relies on the oxygen in the Earth’s atmosphere for combustion. In space, where there is no atmosphere, a jet engine cannot function because it cannot obtain the necessary oxygen for burning fuel. Statement 2 is incorrect: Rockets do carry their own supply of oxygen, but typically, the oxygen is not in gas form. It is usually stored as a liquid oxidizer (e.g., liquid oxygen, LOX) along with the fuel. 293","PW-1433":"Statement 1 is incorrect: INSAT-4A was launched on December 5, 2005, using an Ariane 5 rocket from Kourou, French Guiana (not New Mexico). Statement 2 is correct: Arianespace was responsible for launching INSAT-4A using the Ariane 5 rocket, a major commercial launch vehicle used for heavy payloads like communication satellites. Statement 3 is correct: Tata Sky, an Indian Direct-to-Home (DTH) service provider, uses the INSAT-4A satellite for providing satellite television services in India. 294","PW-1434":"A black hole is a region in space where gravity is so intense that not even light or any form of radiation can escape from it. This extreme gravitational pull is a result of its very high density, as the mass of the black hole is compressed into a very small volume, creating a gravitational field strong enough to trap light and radiation. Event Horizon: The boundary around a black hole beyond which nothing, not even light, can escape due to the extreme gravitational pull. Singularity: The point at the center of a black hole where gravity is infinitely strong, and matter is thought to be crushed to an infinitely small point with infinite density. Schwarzschild Radius: The radius of the event horizon, which depends on the mass of the black hole. It defines the size of the black hole’s event horizon. Accretion Disk: A rotating disk of matter, such as gas and dust, that orbits a black hole. The matter in the disk heats up as it spirals toward the event horizon. Hawking Radiation: A theoretical prediction by physicist Stephen Hawking that black holes can emit radiation due to quantum effe","PW-1435":"A comet is a small celestial body composed of ice, dust, and rocky material that orbits the Sun in an elliptical path. When it gets close to the Sun, the heat causes its icy nucleus to vaporize, forming a glowing coma. Option (c) is correct: The tail of a comet is directed away from the Sun due to the solar wind and radiation pressure exerted by the Sun. The Sun emits charged particles (mainly electrons and protons) that interact with the comet’s nucleus and coma, pushing gas and dust away. This creates a glowing tail that always points opposite the Sun, regardless of the comet’s orientation. The tail’s direction can change as the comet moves, influenced by factors like solar wind intensity, the coma’s shape, and the Sun’s magnetic field. Science and Technology 599 296","PW-1436":"Hydrogen fuel cell vehicles produce water (H2O) as the only byproduct or “exhaust” when hydrogen reacts with oxygen in the fuel cell to produce electricity. The reaction is: 2H2 + O2 → 2H2O This clean process makes hydrogen fuel cell vehicles environmentally friendly, emitting only water vapor. 298","PW-1437":"Ammonium chloride (NH4Cl) is a primary component of the electrolyte paste used in dry cells. Zinc chloride (ZnCl2) serves as the negative electrolyte, and it is often mixed with ammonium chloride in a paste to form the electrolyte for the dry cell. These components, along with a zinc anode and a carbon cathode, are commonly used in the construction of dry cells, which power small devices such as flashlights and radios. 299","PW-1438":"","PW-1439":"Ionic compounds are chemical compounds composed of positively and negatively charged ions held together by strong electrostatic forces of attraction. Statement 1 is correct: Ionic compounds generally dissolve in water due to its high polarity, but alcohols are less polar compared to water, which makes most ionic compounds insoluble in alcohol. Statement 2 is incorrect: In the solid state, the ions in ionic compounds are fixed in a rigid lattice structure and cannot move freely, which prevents the conduction of electricity. 301","PW-1440":"","PW-1441":"The half-life of a radioactive substance is the time it takes for half of the substance to decay. After each half-life:  At the end of 1 half-life (4 months), 50% of the substance remains.  At the end of 2 half-lives (8 months), 25% of the substance remains, meaning 75% (three-fourths) of the substance has decayed. Thus, it takes 8 months for three-fourths of the substance to decay. 305","PW-1442":"Astatine, Francium, and Tritium are radioactive elements: Astatine is a halogen with no stable isotopes. Francium is an alkali metal, highly unstable and radioactive. Tritium is a radioactive isotope of hydrogen. Zirconium is not radioactive. It is a stable, non-radioactive metal widely used in industries like nuclear reactors and construction. 306","PW-1443":"Assertion (A) is true: Large cold storage plants often use ammonia as a refrigerant because it has high efficiency in transferring heat. Ammonia is widely used in industrial refrigeration due to its thermodynamic properties and relatively low cost. Domestic refrigerators, on the other hand, typically use chlorofluorocarbons (CFCs) or their replacements, like HFCs, due to their non-toxic and non-flammable nature. Reason (R) is false: Ammonia cannot be liquefied at ambient temperature and low pressure. It requires a higher pressure or lower temperature to be liquefied. Ammonia is typically stored and transported as a liquid under pressure or at low temperatures. Therefore, while the assertion is correct, the reason is false. 308","PW-1444":"Explosions in mines are often caused by the presence of methane gas, which mixes with air to form an explosive mixture. This phenomenon is known as a “firedamp explosion.” Methane is highly flammable and can ignite when exposed to a spark or heat, leading to devastating consequences in mining environments. 309","PW-1445":"Barium is used in X-ray imaging because it effectively absorbs X-rays, which makes it show up clearly on X-ray images. This property helps in creating a clear contrast between the stomach and surrounding tissues, allowing doctors to examine the stomach’s structure more easily. 310","PW-1446":"Cobalt-60 is a radioactive isotope that emits gamma rays. These high-energy rays are used in radiation therapy for cancer treatment because they can penetrate deep into tissues and target cancer cells effectively while minimizing damage to surrounding healthy tissues. Related terms: Proton therapy is a type of cancer treatment that uses protons to precisely target and destroy tumor cells, minimizing damage to surrounding healthy tissues. It is particularly effective for tumors near sensitive areas, offering fewer side effects compared to conventional radiation therapy. 311","PW-1447":"A is matched with 2: Dr. Raja Ramanna was a distinguished Indian physicist best known for his role in the development of India’s nuclear program, including the Pokhran-I nuclear test in 1974. B is matched with 5: Dr. Swaminathan is renowned for his contributions to the Green Revolution in India, which transformed the country into a self-sufficient food producer. His focus on developing high-yield and disease-resistant crop varieties, combined with sustainable agricultural practices, earned him global recognition in agricultural science. C is matched with 4: Prof. Udupi Ramachandra Rao was a visionary space scientist who led the design and launch of India’s first satellite, Aryabhata, in 1975. Also as the chairman of ISRO, he contributed significantly to advancing India’s space program. D is matched with 3: Prof. Meghnad Saha is celebrated for the Saha Ionization Equation, which explains the physical and chemical conditions in stars. He also made notable contributions to thermodynamics. 312","PW-1448":"Zirconium is an essential element for the construction of nuclear reactors due to its unique properties: Low Neutron Absorption: Zirconium has a low neutron absorption cross-section, making it ideal for use in nuclear reactors as it does not interfere significantly with the nuclear chain reaction. High Corrosion Resistance: It is resistant to corrosion in the presence of coolant water, including high-temperature water, which is commonly used in nuclear reactors. Strength and Durability: Zirconium alloys are strong and durable, making them suitable for structural components like cladding for fuel rods. This combination of properties makes zirconium critical in the nuclear industry. 313","PW-1449":"An alpha particle consists of two protons and two neutrons, which is exactly the nucleus of a helium atom (He2+). The mass of an alpha particle is very close to the mass of a helium atom as the mass of electrons is insignificant in comparison with protons and neutrons. 11.2 Inorganic Chemistry 314","PW-1450":"","PW-1451":"","PW-1452":"","PW-1453":"Selenium is a semiconductor, meaning it has electrical conductivity that lies between that of metals and insulators. Its conductivity increases with exposure to light, making it useful in solar cells and photoelectric applications. Therefore, selenium is not a poor conductor of electricity. 318","PW-1454":"","PW-1455":"","PW-1456":"","PW-1457":"Statement 1 is correct: Baking soda (NaHCO3) is used in some fire extinguishers, especially for small grease or electrical fires. When heated, baking soda releases carbon dioxide (CO2), which helps to smother the fire by displacing oxygen. The chemical reaction is: 2NaHCO3 → H2O + CO2 + Na2CO3 Statement 2 is correct: Quick lime (CaO) is an important component in the manufacture of glass. It is used to stabilize the mixture and help in the formation of glass. Statement 3 is correct: Gypsum (CaSO4 · 2H2O) is heated to produce Plaster of Paris (CaSO4 · ½H2O). The heating process removes part of the water content, leaving behind plaster of Paris, which is used for molding and casting. The chemical reaction is: 2 CaSO4 · 2H₂O → 2 CaSO4·½H2O + 3 H2O (released as steam) 322","PW-1458":"","PW-1459":"","PW-1460":"Assertion (A) is true: Coal-based thermal power stations contribute to acid rain because they release large amounts of sulfur dioxide (SO₂) and nitrogen oxides (NOₓ) into the atmosphere during coal combustion. These gases react with water vapor, oxygen, and other chemicals in the atmosphere to form sulfuric acid (H₂SO₄) and nitric acid (HNO₃), which then fall as acid rain. Reason (R) is true: When coal burns, it produces carbon dioxide (CO₂) and, to a lesser extent, carbon monoxide (CO), both of which are oxides of carbon. However, while oxides of carbon contribute to global warming, they do not directly contribute to acid rain. Oxides of carbon (CO₂ and CO) are emitted when coal burns, but they are not primary reasons for acid rain. Acid rain is primarily caused by sulfur dioxide (SO₂) and nitrogen oxides (NOₓ). Hence Reason (R) does not correctly explain the Assertion (A). UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 604 326","PW-1461":"The oxidation number indicates the oxidation state of an element in a compound, reflecting the number of electrons lost or gained relative to its neutral atom. The oxidation number formula is based on the principle that the algebraic sum of the oxidation numbers of all atoms in a molecule or ion equals the overall charge of the compound or ion. It is equal to zero for a neutral compound . A is matched with 3: In CaO, oxygen has an oxidation number of –2. Since the compound is neutral, the oxidation number of calcium(Ca) is calculated as: x + 1(−2) = 0 ⇒ x = +2. B is matched with 4 : In NaAlH₄, sodium is +1, hydrogen (as a hydride) is -1, and the oxidation number of aluminium(Al) is calculated as: 1(+1) + x + 4 (−1) = 0 ⇒ x = +3. C is matched with 1: In MnO₂, oxygen has an oxidation number of –2, so for manganese(Mn): x + 2(−2) = 0 ⇒ x = + 4. D is matched with 2: In H₂S₂O₇, hydrogen is +1, oxygen is -2, and sulfur(S)’s oxidation number is calculated as: 2(+1) +2(x) +7(−2) = 0 ⇒ 2 + 2x−14 = 0 ⇒ x = +6. . 327","PW-1462":"Assertion (A) is true: Synthetic detergents, unlike soap, work efficiently in hard water because they do not form insoluble scum with calcium and magnesium ions, which are present in hard water. This enables better lathering. Reason (R) is true: Synthetic detergents are mainly non-ionic or anionic, allowing them to form soluble complexes with calcium and magnesium ions, preventing scum formation. Unlike soap, which forms insoluble salts, these detergents continue to lather in hard water. Reason (R) correctly explains Assertion (A) because synthetic detergents form soluble complexes with calcium and magnesium, preventing scum and aiding lathering in hard water. Direction: The following item consists of two statements. One labeled as the ‘Assertion (A)’ and the other as “Reason (R)”. You have to answer this item using the code given below: 328","PW-1463":"","PW-1464":"Statement 1 is incorrect: Ionization potential (or Energy) increases across a period (left to right) because of increasing nuclear charge, which leads to a stronger attraction between the electrons and the nucleus, making electron removal harder. The effective nuclear charge (Z_eff) increases as protons are added, while shielding remains nearly constant. Statement 2 is correct: Electron affinity generally becomes less negative down a group. As the atomic size increases, the added electron is farther from the nucleus and experiences greater shielding, reducing the energy released during electron addition. Across a period, electron affinity generally becomes more negative, reflecting stronger attraction to added electrons. Thus, in a group of elements, electron affinity decreases as atomic weight increases. Statement 3 is incorrect: Electronegativity increases across a period due to increasing nuclear charge, which enhances the ability to attract bonding electrons. However, group-wise, it decreases as atomic size and shielding increase, reducing the effective pull of the nucleus on bon","PW-1465":"","PW-1466":"","PW-1467":"","PW-1468":"Assertion (A) is true: This is done to ensure safety because diluting sulphuric acid is an exothermic process, meaning it releases heat. Adding water to concentrated sulphuric acid can cause a rapid release of heat, leading to a violent reaction and potential splattering of acid. By adding acid to water slowly while stirring, the heat generated is more easily dissipated. Reason (R) is true: Specific heat is the amount of heat energy required to raise the temperature of a substance. Water has a relatively high specific heat, meaning it can absorb and distribute a large amount of heat without a significant change in temperature. This property of water allows it to handle the heat generated during the dilution of sulphuric acid without causing a sudden increase in temperature. Thus Reason (R) correctly explains Assertion (A). UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 606 335","PW-1469":"A is matched with 4: Diamond is an allotrope of carbon where carbon atoms are arranged in a tetrahederal face- centered cubic crystal lattice. B is matched with 1: Marble is primarily composed of recrystallized carbonate minerals, most commonly calcite (calcium carbonate -CaCO₃) or dolomite (calcium magnesium carbonate- CaMg(CO3)2 C is matched with 2: Sand is primarily composed of silicon dioxide or silica (SiO₂), commonly known as quartz. Quartz is a crystalline mineral made of silicon and oxygen atoms. D is matched with 3: Ruby is a variety of the mineral corundum (Al₂O₃), with trace amounts of chromium giving it the pink to blood-red color. 336","PW-1470":"Coke is a solid, porous, carbon-rich substance produced by heating coal in the absence of air in a process called coking. It is primarily composed of carbon and is used in various industrial processes. Statement 1 is correct: Coke reduces iron ore (mostly iron oxide, Fe₂O₃) to iron by giving up electrons. This makes it the reducing agent in the reduction process. Statement 2 is incorrect: Limestone is used to remove impurities from the blast furnace when making iron. The impurities are mostly silicon dioxide (also known as sand). The calcium carbonate in the limestone reacts with the silicon dioxide to form calcium silicate (also known as slag). Statement 3 is correct: Coke also serves as a fuel in the blast furnace, providing the necessary heat to melt the iron ore and to drive the chemical reactions. Statement 4 is incorrect: Coke acts as a reducing agent, not an oxidizing agent. 339","PW-1471":"","PW-1472":"Assertion (A) is true: Sodium is highly reactive and reacts vigorously with air (oxygen) and moisture, which could lead to fire or explosion. Storing it under kerosene prevents contact with air and moisture, ensuring safety. Reason (R) is false: Sodium does not melt when exposed to air but instead reacts with oxygen and moisture to form sodium oxide (Na₂O) or sodium hydroxide (NaOH). The melting of sodium occurs only when it is heated to its melting point (98°C), which is unrelated to its reaction with air. Directions: The following two Items consist of statements. One labeled as the ‘Assertion (A)’ and the other as ‘Reason (R)’. You have to answer these items using the code given below: (1998) 341","PW-1473":"Fluorine is the most reactive halogen because: Small Atomic Size: Fluorine has the smallest atomic radius among halogens, leading to a strong attraction for electrons. High Electronegativity: It is the most electronegative element in the periodic table, making it highly effective in gaining electrons. Low Bond Dissociation Energy: The F-F bond in molecular fluorine is weak due to electron repulsion between the two small atoms, which makes it highly reactive. Reactivity Trend in Halogens: Fluorine > Chlorine > Bromine > Iodine 342","PW-1474":"","PW-1475":"Micronutrients are essential elements required by plants in very small quantities (typically less than 100 mg/ kg of plant dry matter). Despite their minimal requirement, these nutrients play a critical role in various physiological and biochemical processes necessary for plant growth and development. Sodium is not considered an essential micronutrient for most plants. It may play a role in some specific plants, such as C4 plants, but it is not universally required as a micronutrient. Other important micronutrients are Iron (Fe), Manganese (Mn), Zinc (Zn), Copper (Cu), Boron (B), Molybdenum (Mo), Chlorine (Cl), Nickel (Ni). 11.3 Organic Chemistry 344","PW-1476":"","PW-1477":"Bisphenol A (BPA) is an industrial chemical extensively used in the production of polycarbonate plastics and epoxy resins. Polycarbonate plastics made using BPA are commonly employed in the manufacture of reusable water bottles, food containers, and baby bottles due to their durability and lightweight properties. Epoxy resins containing BPA are used as coatings for the inside of food and beverage cans to prevent corrosion and contamination. However, BPA is a controversial substance because it can leach into food and beverages under high temperatures or prolonged storage. It is considered a potential endocrine disruptor that may interfere with hormonal activity, prompting regulatory bodies worldwide to evaluate its safety in food-related applications. 346","PW-1478":"","PW-1479":"Option 1 is correct: Benzene was used in the past for dry cleaning but has been largely discontinued due to its toxicity and carcinogenicity. Option 2 is correct: Carbon tetrachloride was commonly used for dry cleaning in earlier times but has been replaced by safer alternatives due to environmental concerns. Option 3 is incorrect: Sodium carbonate (washing soda) is not typically used in dry cleaning; it is more commonly used in laundry detergents and cleaning solutions. Option 4 is correct: Trichloroethylene is widely used as a dry cleaning solvent due to its ability to dissolve oils, greases, and waxes without damaging fabrics. 349","PW-1480":"LNG is natural gas that has been cooled to a liquid form, making it easier to transport across long distances where pipelines are not feasible. Liquefied Natural Gas (LNG) and Natural Gas Liquids (NGL) play crucial roles in the global energy market, facilitating the storage, transportation, and consumption of natural gas. Statement 1 is correct: LNG is natural gas cooled to approximately -162°C at normal atmospheric pressure, making it a liquid for ease of storage and transportation in specialized cryogenic tanks. Statement 2 is incorrect : The first LNG terminal in India was built at Dahej, Gujarat, not Hassan. Statement 3 is correct: Natural Gas Liquids (NGLs), such as ethane, propane, butane, and natural gasoline, are extracted from natural gas and can be separated from LPG. 350","PW-1481":"Liquefied Petroleum Gas (LPG) is a mixture of hydrocarbons, primarily propane and butane, used as a fuel for cooking, heating, and vehicles. It is stored in liquid form under pressure and is widely distributed through cylinders or pipelines for domestic and industrial use. Assertion (A) is false: The main constituents of LPG are propane (C₃H₈) and butane (C₄H₁₀), not methane. Reason (R) is true: Methane (CH₄) is the main component of natural gas, which can be directly used for domestic and industrial purposes when supplied through pipelines. Direction: The following item consists of two statements. One labeled as the ‘Assertion (A)’ and the other as “Reason (R)”. You have to answer this item using the code given below: (2005) 351","PW-1482":"Fuel gases are gaseous compounds used for heating, cooking, and industrial processes. Common types include CNG, LPG, coal gas, and water gas, each with specific compositions that make them efficient and versatile energy sources. A is matched with 3: Compressed Natural Gas (CNG) mainly contains methane (CH₄) and a small amount of ethane (C₂H₆). Science and Technology 609 B is matched with 4: Coal gas consists of hydrogen (H₂), methane (CH₄), and carbon monoxide (CO), produced during coal carbonization. C is matched with 2: Liquefied Petroleum Gas (LPG) is a mixture of butane (C₄H₁₀) and propane (C₃H₈). D is matched with 1: Water gas is a mixture of carbon monoxide (CO) and hydrogen (H₂), produced by passing steam over heated coal. 352","PW-1483":"Detergents are cleaning agents used to remove dirt, grease, and stains from surfaces and fabrics. Key additives like sodium sulphate prevent clumping by keeping the powder dry, while sodium silicate maintains alkalinity, enhancing the cleaning efficiency. Statement 1 is correct: Sodium sulphate is added to keep the washing powder dry by preventing it from absorbing moisture. Statement 2 is correct: Sodium silicate is used to maintain the alkalinity of the detergent, which enhances the cleaning action by breaking down grease and dirt. 353","PW-1484":"","PW-1485":"Assertion A is true: Phenyl, a common household germicide, contains phenol derivatives that disrupt bacterial cell membranes and denature proteins, making it effective against germs. Reason R is true: Phenol, also called carbolic acid, is a well- known antiseptic and disinfectant due to its ability to kill bacteria, fungi, and viruses. This explains the germicidal property of phenyl. Thus, both Assertion (A) and Reason (R) are true, and R correctly explains A. 356","PW-1486":"","PW-1487":"Assertion (A) is true: Formic acid (HCOOH) is indeed a stronger acid than acetic acid (CH₃COOH). The difference arises because formic acid lacks the electron-donating methyl group (-CH₃) present in acetic acid. This absence makes formic acid’s proton release (ionization) easier, enhancing its acidity. Reason (R) is true: While formic acid is an organic acid, this fact does not explain why it is stronger than acetic acid. Acidity is determined by the molecular structure and not merely by virtue of being organic. 358","PW-1488":"The distinctive pungent odour of garlic is due to sulphur-containing compounds, mainly allicin. These compounds are formed when alliin is converted by the enzyme alliinase during chopping or crushing. 359","PW-1489":"Eugenol is the active component in clove oil, contributing to its distinct aroma and analgesic properties. It is widely used in dental care and as a natural preservative. 360","PW-1490":"Mustard gas ( sulfur mustard) was widely used as a chemical weapon during World War I. It causes blistering of the skin and mucous membranes, along with severe respiratory damage. 361","PW-1491":"","PW-1492":"","PW-1493":"Acid rain occurs when certain pollutants in the atmosphere react with water vapor to form acids, which then fall to the ground as rain, snow, or fog. The pollutants responsible for acid rain are primarily oxides of nitrogen and oxides of sulfur. Option 1 is incorrect: Hydrogen itself does not form acidic oxides under typical environmental conditions. The concept of oxides of hydrogen is not commonly associated with acid rain. Option 2 is correct: Nitrogen oxides , such as nitrogen dioxide , combine with water vapor in the atmosphere to form nitric acid, which contributes to acid rain. Option 3 is correct: Sulfur oxides , such as sulfur dioxide, react with water vapor to form sulfuric acid, which is another major contributor to acid rain. Science and Technology 611 365","PW-1494":"When carbon monoxide (CO) is inhaled, it binds to hemoglobin in red blood cells with a much stronger affinity than oxygen. Hemoglobin normally binds to oxygen to transport it throughout the body, but CO binds more tightly, forming carboxyhemoglobin. This reduces the ability of hemoglobin to carry oxygen effectively, leading to a decrease in oxygen supply to vital organs and tissues. Carbon monoxide (CO) has approximately 200-250 times more affinity for hemoglobin than oxygen, which means it competes with oxygen for binding sites on hemoglobin. 366","PW-1495":"Beach sand minerals are naturally occurring mineral particles found on coastal beaches, often derived from the erosion of rocks and shells. The primary components of beach sand include quartz, a durable and abundant mineral, along with other minerals like feldspar, mica, and ilmenite, as well as heavier minerals such as zircon, rutile, and monazite. The beach sands of many parts of Kerala are known to contain a variety of heavy minerals. Option 1 is correct: Ilmenite is one of the most abundant minerals in the beach sands of Kerala. It is a source of titanium dioxide, which is used in various industrial applications, including the manufacture of paints and pigments. Odisha is the leading producer of ilmenite, contributing nearly 69% of the total production followed by Kerala and Tamil Nadu . Option 2 is correct: Zircon is another important mineral found in Kerala’s beach sands. It is used in the production of refractory materials and as a gemstone. Zircon occurs in close association with other heavy minerals such as ilmenite, rutile and monazite in beach sands, along the coastal trac","PW-1496":"Photochemical smog is a type of air pollution that occurs when sunlight reacts with pollutants like nitrogen oxides and volatile organic compounds (VOCs), including hydrocarbons. The reaction leads to the formation of ozone, which is a key component of photochemical smog. Key Components of Photochemical Smog are:  Nitrogen Oxides – Released from vehicles, industrial emissions, and power plants. They react with sunlight to form ozone.  Hydrocarbons: Organic compounds that also contribute to ozone formation when exposed to sunlight.  Ozone : The primary harmful product of photochemical smog, which can cause respiratory problems and damage to vegetation.  Methane is a potent greenhouse gas, but it does not directly form photochemical smog. While it can contribute indirectly to smog formation by reacting with other pollutants, it is not a primary component like ozone, hydrocarbons, or nitrogen oxides. 368","PW-1497":"Water pollution in rivers is primarily measured by the Dissolved Oxygen (DO) level, which indicates the amount of oxygen available for aquatic organisms. A low DO level signifies high pollution, as pollutants like organic waste decompose and consume oxygen, making the water uninhabitable for aquatic life. BOD (Biochemical Oxygen Demand) is the amount of oxygen required by microorganisms to decompose organic matter in water over a specific period (usually 5 days at 20°C). High BOD indicates organic pollution, such as from sewage or agricultural runoff, while low BOD signifies cleaner water. COD (Chemical Oxygen Demand) is the total amount of oxygen required to chemically oxidize both organic and inorganic matter in water. COD provides a broader measure of pollution than BOD, including oxygen demand from inorganic substances. 369","PW-1498":"The physico-chemical characteristics of water in water sources are primarily affected by effluents discharged from various sources, including industries, sewage, and agricultural runoff. Effluents introduce pollutants like organic matter, chemicals, heavy metals, and nutrients into water bodies, leading to significant changes in water quality. How Effluents cause Changes:  Chemical Changes: Effluents can alter the pH, increase the concentration of harmful chemicals, and introduce toxic substances. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 612  Nutrient Loading: Excessive nutrients (like nitrates and phosphates) from effluents can cause eutrophication, leading to algal blooms.  Dissolved Oxygen Levels: Organic pollutants increase the Biological Oxygen Demand (BOD), reducing dissolved oxygen levels and harming aquatic life.  Turbidity and Color: Effluents can increase turbidity, reduce light penetration, and alter the color of the water. 12. BIOLOGY 12.1 Botany 370","PW-1499":"The carbon cycle is a natural process that involves the movement of carbon between the atmosphere, oceans, soil, rocks, and living organisms. Respiration, decay of organic matter, volcanic action, fossil fuel combustion, deforestation, ocean-atmosphere exchange adds carbon to the cycle.  All living organisms (plants, animals, and microorganisms) respire and breaking down glucose and oxygen to release energy, CO₂, and water. This process adds carbon dioxide to the atmosphere.  When dead plants, animals, and other organic materials decompose microbes break them down. During decomposition CO₂ and methane (CH₄) are released into the atmosphere.  Volcanic eruptions release stored carbon dioxide from the Earth’s mantle into the atmosphere. This is a natural source of CO₂ emissions. During photosynthesis plants, algae, and some bacteria absorb CO₂ from the atmosphere and use sunlight to convert it into glucose and oxygen. This process removes carbon dioxide from the atmosphere rather than adding it. 371","PW-1500":"Insectivorous plants like Venus flytraps and pitcher plants grow in nitrogen-poor, acidic, or waterlogged soils. They capture and digest insects to obtain essential nutrients such as nitrogen and phosphorus which are scarce in their environment. This adaptation allows them to thrive in nutrient- deficient habitats where other plants struggle. Though they perform photosynthesis but their carnivorous behavior supplements their nutritional needs which enables them to survive in challenging conditions. 373","PW-1501":"Mon 863 maize was genetically modified to produce a protein called Cry3Bb1 derived from the soil bacterium Bacillus thuringiensis (Bt). This protein is toxic to the corn rootworm which is a major pest that damages maize crops. By incorporating this trait, Mon 863 reduces the need for chemical pesticides and improves crop yields. 374","PW-1502":"","PW-1503":"Statement 1 is correct: Pongamia pinnata, also known as the Indian beech tree, grows naturally in arid and semi-arid regions of India. It is highly drought-tolerant, making it a suitable bio-diesel crop for areas with limited water availability. Statement 2 is correct: The seeds of Pongamia pinnata are rich in lipid content(oleic acid) which is a key component in the production of bio-diesel. The high oil yield from the seeds makes Pongamia a viable and sustainable bio-diesel source. Recently, it has been used for ethanol production. 377","PW-1504":"Saffron spice is made from the stigma of the Crocus sativus flower, commonly known as the saffron crocus. The stigmas are handpicked, dried, and processed to produce saffron. Each flower has only three stigmas, making the harvesting process labor-intensive and contributing to saffron’s high value. The stigmas are highly prized for their distinctive flavor, aroma, and vibrant golden color. 378","PW-1505":"Statement 1 is correct: The sweet orange plant is propagated through the grafting technique where a scion (shoot) from a desired sweet orange tree is grafted onto the rootstock of a compatible plant. This ensures the plant retains the desired traits such as high fruit quality and disease resistance. Statement 2 is correct: The jasmine plant is commonly propagated by layering technique, particularly mound layering or air layering. This method involves bending a healthy branch to the ground or wrapping it with moist materials to encourage root development, which helps maintain the plant’s genetic identity and growth potential. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 614 379","PW-1506":"Methane (CH₄) is a potent greenhouse gas with a global warming potential over 25 times greater than carbon dioxide (CO₂) over a 100-year period. The primary sources of methane emissions can be categorized into natural and anthropogenic (human-caused) sources. Option 1 is correct: Rice fields emit methane due to the anaerobic decomposition of organic matter in waterlogged conditions. This is a significant contributor to global methane emissions, particularly in rice-producing countries. Option 2 is correct: Coal mining releases methane trapped within coal seams during the mining process. This is known as fugitive methane emissions and is a key source of industrial methane. Option 3 is correct: Domestic animals, particularly ruminants like cattle and sheep, produce methane during enteric fermentation, a digestive process where microbes break down food in the stomach. Option 4 is correct: Wetlands are natural sources of methane, produced through the anaerobic decomposition of organic material in water-saturated soils. 380","PW-1507":"","PW-1508":"In pitcher plants (Nepenthes) the leaf is modified into a pitcher-shaped structure that traps and digests insects. This adaptation helps the plant supplement its nutrient intake in poor soil conditions, such as those found in bogs or marshes. Pitcher plants are carnivorous in nature .The rim of the pitcher has nectar glands or patterns that attract insects. Once inside the insect faces slippery walls or downward-facing hairs that trap it. It falls into digestive fluid at the bottom where enzymes break it down. The plant absorbs the nutrients and thrives in nutrient-poorhabitats like bogs. 383","PW-1509":"Plant chlorophyll absorbs light most efficiently in the blue (around 430–450 nm) and red (around 640–680 nm) regions of the spectrum. These wavelengths drive the light- dependent reactions of photosynthesis, converting light energy into chemical energy. This energy is then used to convert carbon dioxide and water into glucose and oxygen. The absorption of blue light helps in the energy conversion, while red light plays a key role in the process of creating sugars. The green light is mostly reflected bach which is why plants appear green to us. Science and Technology 615 384","PW-1510":"Cellulose is a natural polysaccharide and the primary structural component of plant cell walls, providing strength and rigidity. It is widely used in industries for making paper, textiles, and derivatives like cellulose acetate and cellulose nitrate for various applications. Assertion (A) is true: Cellulose acetate, derived from cellulose, is used in the manufacture of shatterproof plastics, including glass used for eyewear and safety applications. These derivatives provide durability and impact resistance, essential for safety applications. Reason (R) is true: Polysaccharides such as cellulose are not soluble in water due to their extensive hydrogen bonding and crystalline structure. This insolubility is a key property of cellulose, which contributes to its stability and strength when used in manufacturing materials like shatterproof glass. Hence, Reason (R) provides the correct explanation of Assertion (A). 385","PW-1511":"Statement 1 is correct: Spirogyra and Ulothrix are types of blue green algae that can be found in both freshwater and marine environments. They are typically found in ponds, rivers, and even oceans in some cases. Spirogyra is known for its spiral-shaped chloroplasts and forms slimy green filaments/ mats on the water surface, especially when nutrients like nitrogen and phosphorus are abundant while Ulothrix is characterized by its simple, unbranched filaments and typically grows in both freshwater ponds and coastal regions. These algae play an important role in the aquatic food chain. Statement 2 is correct: Chameleons have a unique ability to move their eyes independently of each other. They can focus one eye on an object in front while the other eye looks in a different direction, even behind them. This independent eye movement enables them to have a 360-degree view of their surroundings, aiding in predator detection and prey surveillance. 386","PW-1512":"Saturated fats are typically solid at room temperature and are found in animal products like butter, lard, and fatty cuts of meat, as well as some plant oils like coconut and palm oil. They are composed of fatty acids with no double bonds between carbon atoms, making them less reactive. Unsaturated fats are liquid at room temperature and are mainly found in plant-based oils (such as olive, sunflower, and canola oil) and fish. They contain one or more double bonds between carbon atoms which introduce “kinks” in the structure making them more reactive and beneficial for heart health when consumed in moderation. Assertion (A) is true: Unsaturated fats have at least one double bond between carbon atoms, making them more reactive. These double bonds are sites where chemical reactions can occur more easily compared to the single bonds in saturated fats. Reason (R) is false: Unsaturated fats contain at least one double bond in their carbon chain, not only single bonds. Saturated fats have only single bonds. 387","PW-1513":"Statement 1 is correct: Molasses is a thick, dark syrup that remains after the extraction of sugar from sugarcane or sugar beets. It is a common by-product in the sugar industry. It serves as a feedstock for producing synthetic chemical fertilizers and ethanol. Statement 2 is correct: Bagasse, the fibrous residue left after extracting juice from sugarcane, is commonly used as a biofuel in the sugar industry to generate steam and electricity, making the process more energy-efficient. Statement 3 is incorrect: Sugar is produced from various raw materials including sugarcane and sugar beets. Other sources for sugar production include sorghum and palm sap. 388","PW-1514":"Dichogamy refers to the condition in a bisexual flower where the male (androecium) and female (gynoecium) reproductive organs mature at different times to prevent self- pollination. This ensures cross-pollination between different plants or flowers which increases genetic diversity. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 616 389","PW-1515":"Stem cutting is a common asexual propagation method where a section of the stem, with at least one node and some leaves is cut from a parent plant and rooted to grow a new, genetically identical plant. This method helps maintain desirable plant traits. Bougainvillea, carnations, grapes, and cocoa can all be propagated by stem cuttings.  Bougainvillea is propagated using hardwood( during the dormant season) or softwood ( during spring/summer from young growth) cuttings depending on the season.  Carnations: Stem cuttings taken from side shoots in spring/ summer. Must have two nodes and leaves for successful propagation.  Grapes: Dormant hardwood cuttings taken during winter with 3 nodes. Ideal for maintaining grapevine traits.  Cocoa: Propagated using young, tender stem cuttings during the rainy season. Cuttings should have at least two nodes and leaves. 390","PW-1516":"","PW-1517":"","PW-1518":"Epiphytes, commonly known as “air plants,” are plants that depend on other plants primarily for mechanical support. They grow on the surface of other plants (like trees) to access better light and air circulation, but they do not take nutrients from the host plant. While they do not parasitize the host but they can absorb water and nutrients from rain, dew, and air humidity through specialized structures like spongy roots. Epiphytes are typically found in humid environments and include species like orchids, mosses, and ferns. They do not rely on the host for food or shade, as they can photosynthesize and derive most of their nutrients from the air and rain. 393","PW-1519":"Blue-green algae, also known as cyanobacteria are often used as biofertilizers in rice cultivation. They have the ability to fix atmospheric nitrogen into a form that plants can use, enriching the soil with nitrogen and improving crop growth. 394","PW-1520":"A phytotron is a facility that provides an environment where various environmental factors such as temperature, humidity, light, and CO2 levels can be controlled precisely to study plant growth and development. This setup helps scientists to conduct experiments on plants in a controlled and reproducible environment. Phytotron is neither related with growing plants in disease free conditions nor conserving endangered species of plants. 395","PW-1521":"Soft drinks, especially colas, often contain caffeine, which is a stimulant. Caffeine can help to increase alertness and reduce fatigue, and it is commonly added to colas and other energy drinks. 396","PW-1522":"Canola oil is derived from a type of mustard plant that has been specially bred to have very low levels of erucic acid, which is a substance that can be harmful in large amounts. This makes canola oil safe and suitable for human consumption. Canola oil is known for being rich in unsaturated fatty acids, especially omega-3 and omega-6 fatty acids, making it a heart- healthy cooking oil. It has a long shelf life due to its stability, and its mild flavor makes it suitable for a variety of culinary uses. 397","PW-1523":"Mycorrhiza is a symbiotic association between fungi and the roots of higher plants. In this relationship, the fungi help the plants by increasing water and nutrient absorption (especially phosphorus), while the plants provide carbohydrates (like glucose) to the fungi. This mutualistic relationship is beneficial to both organisms and plays a crucial role in plant growth and soil health. 398","PW-1524":"Ergotism is historically known as “St. Anthony’s Fire” is directly linked to the consumption of grains (such as rye, barley, wheat, and oats) contaminated with the ergot fungus (Claviceps purpurea). The fungus infects the grains, producing sclerotia (ergot bodies) that contain toxic alkaloids. These alkaloids can cause two forms of ergotism: Convulsive ergotism which is cracterized by seizures, hallucinations, and muscle spasms. Gangrenous ergotism which leads to restricted blood flow, causing tissue death and gangrene in extremities. 399","PW-1525":"In industrial applications, a wide range of microorganisms are used due to their ability to carry out various biochemical processes that are beneficial for different industries. The following microorganisms are widely used: Bacteria is used in industries such as fermentation, bioremediation, and food production (e.g., yogurt, cheese, and antibiotics). Microalgae is used in the production of biofuels, aquaculture feed, and nutraceuticals. They are also involved in carbon sequestration. Fungi is widely used in the pharmaceutical industry for the production of antibiotics (such as penicillin) and enzymes. They are also used in fermentation and the production of organic acids. 400","PW-1526":"A is matched with 4: Fruit develops from the ovary of the flower after fertilization. The ovary, which contains the ovules, transforms into the fruit as the seeds inside mature. This process is an essential part of the plant’s reproductive cycle. B is matched with 1: Seed originates from the ovule after fertilization. The ovule, located inside the ovary, contains the female gamete (egg cell). Once fertilized by the male gamete (pollen), the ovule develops into a seed, which contains the embryo and stored food for the new plant. C is matched with 3: Wood is produced from the stem of the plant. The stem, with its vascular tissues (xylem and phloem), supports the plant and transports nutrients. The xylem, which is a type of vascular tissue, forms the wood, providing structural support and helping in water transport. D is matched with 2: Starch is primarily produced in the leaf. During photosynthesis leaves use sunlight, water, and carbon dioxide to produce glucose. Some of this glucose is converted into starch, a storage form of sugar, and is stored in the chloroplasts of the leaf. 401","PW-1527":"Seedless tomatoes can be produced through a process called parthenocarpy where fruits develop without fertilization and thus contain no seeds. This is achieved by spraying hormones like gibberellins or auxins on the flowers of the tomato plants. These hormones promote fruit development without the need for fertilization leading to seedless fruits. 404","PW-1528":"A is matched with 2: Photosynthesis occurs in the chloroplasts where light energy is converted into chemical energy forming glucose and oxygen. B is matched with 1: Mineral uptake happens at the plasma membrane, where ions and nutrients are absorbed into the cell. C is matched with 3: Respiration takes place in the mitochondria, where glucose is broken down to release energy in the form of ATP. D is matched with 4: Protein synthesis occurs at the ribosomes where mRNA is translated into proteins. 405","PW-1529":"The potato is a modified stem known as a tuber. It is an underground stem that stores food and is capable of producing new shoots (vegetative reproduction). The “eyes” on the surface of a potato are actually buds from which new potato plants can grow. The sweet potato is also a modified root (specifically, a storage root) and not a stem. The coconut is a fruit and contains a seed, not a modified stem. Its outer husk is a part of the fruit, not a stem modification. 12.2 Zoology 406","PW-1530":"Some species of ants such as leafcutter ants ( of genus Atta and Acromyrmex) are well-known for cultivating fungi. These ants cut leaves and use them to grow fungi in specialized underground gardens. The fungi serve as the primary food source for the ant colony. This relationship between ants and fungi is a classic example of mutualism where both species benefit. The ants provide the fungi with a controlled environment and a constant supply of plant material while the fungi provide the ants with a nutritious food source. Leafcutter ants are primarily found in Central and South America, 407","PW-1531":"","PW-1532":"Hepatitis B is a viral infection that primarily affects the liver and can lead to chronic disease. HIV is a virus that attacks the immune system, weakening the body’s ability to fight infections. Statement 1 is correct: Hepatitis B transmission occurs through contact with infected blood, semen, or other body fluids. It’s 50 to 100 times more contagious than HIV because it can survive longer outside the body and can be transmitted with a smaller amount of the virus. HIV (Human Immunodeficiency Virus) needs a higher viral load and specific conditions to spread. Statement 2 is correct: The Hepatitis B virus attacks and damages the liver, causing inflammation and scarring (called cirrhosis). This chronic inflammation weakens the liver and makes it more susceptible to liver cancer. Liver cancer specifically hepatocellular carcinoma (HCC) is strongly associated with chronic HBV infection. People with chronic Hepatitis B infection have a much higher risk of developing HCC compared to those who do not have the infection. 409","PW-1533":"The flying fox is a type of megabat belonging to the Pteropus genus in the Pteropodidae family. These large bats have wingspans ranging from 1.5 to 1.8 meters and are known for their fox-like faces, which is how they got their name. Flying foxes are found mostly in tropical and subtropical areas, particularly in coastal regions and tropical forests of India. As frugivores, they primarily feed on fruit and play a vital role in pollination and seed dispersal, contributing to the health of their ecosystems. Unlike smaller insect-eating bats, flying foxes do not rely on echolocation. Instead, they use their sharp vision to navigate and find food. This makes them unique compared to other bat species. 411","PW-1534":"Salamander-Python-Kangaroo sequence follows a correct evolutionary progression:  Salamanders are amphibians to the class Amphibia. Amphibians evolved from fish and are characterized by their ability to live both in water (as larvae) and on land (as adults).  Pythons are reptiles in the class Reptilia which have evolved from amphibians. Reptiles are vertebrates with dry skin, and they lay eggs on land (as opposed to amphibians, which generally need water for reproduction).  Kangaroos are mammals, specifically marsupials in the class Mammalia. Mammals evolved from reptiles. Kangaroos are one of the few mammals that give birth to underdeveloped offspring, which then continue to develop in a pouch. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 620 412","PW-1535":"The giant panda (Ailuropoda melanoleuca) belongs to the Ursidae family, which includes all modern bears such as grizzly, polar, and black bears. Though classified as carnivores, giant pandas are mainly herbivores, with bamboo making up to 99% of their diet. They have a unique “thumb” (modified wrist bone) that helps them grasp bamboo. These solitary creatures are recognized by their black and white fur and have a slow metabolism due to their low-calorie diet. Pandas are found in the mountainous regions of China and are classified as vulnerable because of habitat loss and low reproductive rates. Females are only fertile for a few days each year, making reproduction difficult. Conservation efforts have helped increase their population. The giant panda is a symbol of wildlife conservation and through panda diplomacy, it has helped strengthen diplomatic ties between China and other countries. IUCN Status: The IUCN Red List (International Union for Conservation of Nature) currently classifies the giant panda as Vulnerable. 413","PW-1536":"The Dugong (Dugong dugon) is a marine mammal found in shallow coastal waters of the Indo-Pacific. It is closely related to manatees. The dugong has a torpedo-shaped body with a fluked tail (similar to a whale’s) and two front flippers. Its skin is grayish-brown, and it has a rounded, wrinkled face that helps it forage for seagrass, its primary food source. Dugongs can grow up to 3 meters in length and weigh up to 400 kg. Dugongs are herbivores and feed mainly on seagrass, earning them the nickname “sea cows”. They play a crucial role in maintaining healthy seagrass ecosystems. However, dugongs are vulnerable due to habitat loss, hunting, bycatch, and seagrass degradation. Conservation efforts focus on protecting their habitats through marine protected areas and reducing fishing gear entanglements. 414","PW-1537":"","PW-1538":"The king cobra (Ophiophagus hannah) is a snake whose diet primarily consists of other snakes, including venomous species such as kraits, pythons, and even other cobras. The name “Ophiophagus” literally means “snake-eater.” King Cobras are solitary creatures and are primarily active during the day (diurnal). King Cobras are found in forests, grasslands, and hilly terrains across South and Southeast Asia. The King Cobra is the longest venomous snake in the world, growing up to 5.6 meters (18.5 feet). 416","PW-1539":"The pH level of blood in a normal person typically ranges from 7.35 to 7.45. This is considered slightly alkaline and is crucial for maintaining the proper function of enzymes and other biochemical processes in the body. The normal pH range of blood is tightly regulated by the body through mechanisms like buffer systems (such as the bicarbonate buffer system) to prevent drastic shifts in pH that could be harmful. A pH below 7.35 is considered acidosis, while a pH above 7.45 is considered alkalosis. Both conditions can disrupt normal physiological processes. The body maintains this narrow pH range to ensure optimal conditions for enzyme activity, oxygen transport, and metabolic reactions. 417","PW-1540":"Assertion (A) is true: The liver plays a crucial role in the digestion of fats. The liver’s primary role is to produce bile, which is essential for the digestion and absorption of fats. Science and Technology 621 Bile is stored in the gallbladder and released into the small intestine when fat is detected in the stomach. Bile emulsifies fats by breaking them down into smaller droplets. This makes it easier for digestive enzymes, primarily lipase from the pancreas, to act on the fats and break them down further. Reason (R) is false: The liver does not produce fat-digesting enzymes. The production of fat-digesting enzymes occurs in the pancreas, not the liver. Lipase enzyme is secreted by the pancreas and is responsible for breaking down triglycerides (fats) into glycerol and fatty acids. Lipase works on the small fat droplets that have been emulsified by bile. 418","PW-1541":"","PW-1542":"","PW-1543":"Robert Webster is renowned for his research on the influenza virus. His studies have been instrumental in understanding the genetics and epidemiology of influenza viruses. He has worked extensively on avian influenza, focusing on how the virus mutates and its ability to infect humans, especially during the H5N1 and H1N1 outbreaks. Webster has helped shape our understanding of how influenza viruses evolve and spread, helping to develop vaccines and antiviral strategies. 422","PW-1544":"The appendix is a small, tube-like structure that is attached to the large intestine. It is located at the junction where the small intestine (specifically the ileum) meets the large intestine. This area is known as the cecal junction, and the appendix is attached to the cecum, which is a pouch-like structure in the lower right abdomen. The appendix is thought to be a vestigial organ, meaning it may have once had a more significant function in digestion but is now largely considered to be without a clear, vital role. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 622 423","PW-1545":"Parathyroid Hormone (PTH) is crucial for regulating the levels of calcium and phosphate in the blood. It increases blood calcium levels by stimulating the release of calcium from bones, increasing calcium absorption in the intestines, and reducing calcium excretion through the kidneys. It decreases blood phosphate levels by increasing phosphate excretion in the urine through the kidneys. The parathyroid hormone is secreted by the parathyroid glands, which are small glands located behind the thyroid gland. 424","PW-1546":"Insects primarily breathe through the tracheal system, a highly specialized network of tubes that deliver oxygen directly to their tissues and remove carbon dioxide. The tracheal system consists of tubes (tracheae) that branch out from the insect’s spiracles (small openings on the body surface) to deliver oxygen directly to the cells. Air enters through the spiracles and travels through the tracheae, which are connected to smaller branches called tracheoles that penetrate the tissues of the insect. This allows for efficient gas exchange at the cellular level. air sac dorsal tracheal trunk Thoracic spiracles First abdominal spiracle Spiracular branch Ventral branch Ventral tracheal truck Eight abdominal spiracle Visceral branch 425","PW-1547":"The fertilization of the ovum (egg) by the sperm typically occurs in the fallopian tube. Fertilization occurs in the ampullary region of the fallopian tube, where sperm meets the egg after ovulation. The fertilized egg (zygote) then travels down the fallopian tube to the uterus for implantation and further development. 426","PW-1548":"","PW-1549":"","PW-1550":"","PW-1551":"The small intestine is an essential part of the human digestive system, responsible for digesting food and absorbing nutrients. It consists of three sections: the duodenum, jejunum, and ileum. The ileum is the longest part of the small intestine, measuring approximately 2.5 meters in length. It makes up the last part of the small intestine, connecting to the large intestine through the ileocecal valve. It is rich in villi (tiny finger-like projections) that increase the surface area for nutrient absorption. It absorbs essential nutrients like vitamins (B12), fat-soluble vitamins, and bile salts. The jejunum is about 2.5 meters long. While it is shorter than the ileum, it is thicker and has a more vascular structure. It is the primary site for the absorption of nutrients from digested food. It is specially adapted to absorb proteins, carbohydrates, and lipids. Its walls are lined with a large number of villi that aid in nutrient absorption. The rich blood supply to the jejunum allows for efficient nutrient transport to the rest of the body. The duodenum is the shortest section of the ","PW-1552":"Statement 1 is incorrect: The common bile duct transports bile from the liver and gallbladder and releases it into the duodenum, not the stomach. Bile aids in the emulsification of fats during digestion. The common bile duct is a vital component of the biliary system. It is formed by the union of the common hepatic duct and the cystic duct and its primary function is to carry bile from the liver and gallbladder. Statement 2 is correct: The pancreatic duct carries digestive enzymes and bicarbonate from the pancreas into the duodenum. These enzymes play a crucial role in breaking down carbohydrates, proteins, and fats in the small intestine. 431","PW-1553":"Nutritional calcium is a vital mineral required for the growth and maintenance of strong bones and teeth. It also plays a crucial role in muscle function, nerve signaling, and blood clotting. Rice is not a significant source of calcium. While it provides carbohydrates and small nutrients it does not contain notable calcium levels. Fortified rice may contain added calcium but regular rice lacks this essential mineral for bone health. Options (b), (c), and (d) are incorrect: Ragi or finger millet is an excellent plant-based source of calcium. It provides a good amount of calcium which is important for strong bones and teeth. Ragi is highly valued in regions where it is cultivated as a nutritious calcium-rich food. Skimmed milk is a good source of calcium and helps maintain bone health. Despite having reduced fat content skimmed milk retains high calcium levels. Dairy products like skimmed milk are among the best natural calcium sources. Eggs contain small amounts of calcium mainly found in the yolk. However they are not considered a major source of calcium compared to dairy products or","PW-1554":"Statement 1 is correct: Caffeine, a constituent of tea and coffee is a diuretic. It means it increases urine production by promoting fluid loss from the body. It acts by inhibiting the reabsorption of sodium and water in the kidneys which leads to increased urination. Statement 2 is correct: Citric acid is a common additive in soft drinks. It is used to add tartness and flavor, and it also helps to preserve the drinks. Citric acid occurs naturally in citrus fruits such as lemons and oranges, and its acidic nature helps balance the sweetness of soft drinks and prolong shelf life. Statement 3 is correct: Ascorbic acid, commonly known as Vitamin C, plays a crucial role in the synthesis of collagen, a protein that is essential for the structure of bones, teeth, skin, blood vessels, and cartilage. Deficiency in Vitamin C can lead to scurvy, a condition characterized by weakened connective tissue, bleeding gums, and joint pain due to impaired collagen formation. Statement 4 is incorrect: Citric acid primarily serves as a flavoring agent and preservative. While it has antioxidant properties","PW-1555":"","PW-1556":"","PW-1557":"Meningococcal meningitis is a severe bacterial infection caused by Neisseria meningitidis. It inflames the protective membranes (meninges) surrounding the brain and spinal cord. It spreads through respiratory droplets and can lead to life-threatening complications like sepsis, brain damage, or death if untreated. Statement 1 is incorrect: Meningococcal meningitis is not transmitted by mosquito bites. It spreads through respiratory droplets when an infected person coughs, sneezes, or talks. It can also spread through close contact, such as kissing or sharing items like utensils or drinks. Statement 2 is correct: Vomiting and neck pain are common symptoms of meningococcal meningitis. Individuals may also experience fever, headache, sensitivity to light, confusion, and seizures. 437","PW-1558":"Statement 1 is incorrect: Dengue is not caused by a protozoan but by the dengue virus (DENV), of the Flaviviridae family. The virus spreads through bites from infected Aedes mosquitoes, primarily Aedes aegypti and Aedes albopictus. Statement 2 is incorrect: Retro-orbital pain, which refers to pain behind the eyes, is a common symptom of dengue fever. Patients often experience severe headache accompanied by retro-orbital pain during the febrile phase of the illness. Statement 3 is correct Many dengue patients experience a skin rash, which usually appears a few days after the fever starts. Some people even develop a “white islands on a red sea” rash, where parts of the skin turn white amid the redness. Nosebleeds (epistaxis) and bleeding gums, are common in dengue patients particularly in severe forms like dengue hemorrhagic fever (DHF) or dengue shock syndrome (DSS). 438","PW-1559":"Foot and mouth disease (FMD) is a highly infectious viral disease that affects cloven-hoofed animals, including cattle, sheep, goats, and pigs. It is caused by the foot-and- mouth disease virus (a member of the Picornaviridae family). The disease spreads rapidly through direct contact, contaminated feed, or aerosols. Anthrax is a severe bacterial disease caused by Bacillus anthracis. It primarily affects cattle, sheep, and goats, but can also infect humans through spores present in contaminated soil, water, or feed. Symptoms include sudden death, high fever, difficulty breathing, and bleeding from body openings. The disease is zoonotic, meaning it can spread from animals to humans. Black Quarter, also known as Blackleg, is an infectious bacterial disease caused by Clostridium chauvoei. It mainly affects young cattle and sheep which results in painful swelling of muscles, fever, lameness, and rapid death due to toxin production. The disease spreads through ingestion of spores present in soil, which activate under favorable conditions. Cowpox is an infectious viral disease caused by th","PW-1560":"The process of conversion of complex food substances to simple absorbable forms is called digestion and is carried out by our digestive system by mechanical and biochemical methods. Assertion A is False: Protein digestion is not limited to the small intestine alone. Protein digestion begins in the stomach, where the enzyme pepsin breaks down proteins into smaller peptides. The process continues in the small intestine, where pancreatic enzymes (like trypsin and chymotrypsin) and intestinal enzymes (like peptidases) further break down peptides into amino acids. Reason R is True: The pancreas secretes several protein- digesting enzymes such as trypsin, chymotrypsin, and carboxypeptidase into the small intestine. These enzymes play a crucial role in breaking down proteins into smaller peptides and amino acids. 440","PW-1561":"Reproduction is the process by which organisms produce offspring. It ensures the continuation of a species. There are two main modes of reproduction: Asexual Reproduction involves a single parent and produces offspring that are genetically identical to the parent. Examples include binary fission (in bacteria), budding (in yeast), and parthenogenesis (in some insects). Sexual Reproduction involves two parents (usually of different sexes) and combines genetic material from both parents to create offspring with unique genetic variations. Examples include fertilization in animals and pollination in plants. Assertion A is True: Amoeba, a unicellular protozoan reproduces asexually through binary fission, a process where the parent cell divides into two genetically identical daughter cells. Process of Binary Fission in Amoeba: Growth Phase: The Amoeba increases in size, accumulating nutrients required for division. Nuclear Division (Mitosis): The nucleus undergoes mitotic division, ensuring that both daughter cells receive an identical set of genetic material. Cytoplasmic Division: The cyto","PW-1562":"Assertion (A) is true: Diabetes insipidus(DI) is a condition characterized by the inability to properly regulate water balance in the body. It leads to excessive urination (polyuria) and dehydration. As a result, individuals with DI often experience intense thirst (polydipsia) to compensate for the excessive water loss. Reason (R) is false: Diabetes insipidus is caused by either insufficient secretion of vasopressin (antidiuretic hormone) or the kidneys’ inability to respond to vasopressin. Excess secretion of vasopressin is not associated with DI. Excess secretion of vasopressin would lead to water retention, not excessive thirst. Thus, the Assertion A is true but the Reason R is false. 442","PW-1563":"Workers in the coal mining industry are most affected by pneumoconiosis. Pneumoconiosis is a lung disease caused by the inhalation of dust, particularly mineral or industrial dust over a prolonged period. It primarily affects workers in industries where they are exposed to high levels of airborn e particles. Coal workers’ pneumoconiosis (CWP), also known as black lung disease, is caused by prolonged inhalation of coal dust, making coal miners the most affected group. Other forms of pneumoconiosis include silicosis (caused by silica dust, affecting quarry and glass industry workers) and asbestosis (caused by asbestos exposure). 443","PW-1564":"Statement 1 is correct: Vitamin A is essential for maintaining healthy tear production and eye lubrication. Its deficiency can cause xerophthalmia, leading to dryness in the conjunctiva and cornea due to impaired lacrimal gland function. If left untreated, it can result in severe eye damage and vision impairment. Statement 2 is correct: Vitamin B1 (thiamine) plays a crucial role in energy metabolism and nerve function. Its deficiency leads to beriberi, which occurs in two forms: Wet beriberi affects the cardiovascular system, potentially causing heart enlargement, rapid heartbeat, and heart failure. Dry beriberi impacts the nervous system, leading to muscle weakness, nerve damage, and digestive issues such as indigestion. Statement 3 is correct: A lack of Vitamin C results in scurvy, characterized by muscle pain, joint discomfort, and fatigue. Since Vitamin C is essential for collagen synthesis and its deficiency weakens connective tissues, leading to pain, fragile blood vessels, and slow wound healing. Statement 4 is correct: Vitamin D is vital for calcium absorption in the intestin","PW-1565":"Insulin is a protein-based hormone produced by beta cells in the pancreas, specifically in the Islets of Langerhans. It consists of two peptide chains (A and B) connected by disulfide bonds and plays a crucial role in regulating blood glucose levels. By promoting glucose uptake in cells, it helps maintain energy balance and prevents hyperglycemia. Insulin was first discovered by Frederick Banting and Charles Best in 1921. It is the first recombinant DNA-based drug approved for human use. Science and Technology 627 445","PW-1566":"Statement 1 is incorrect: Pangolins (scaly anteaters) are fascinating toothless mammals covered in protective keratin scales. They use their long, sticky tongues to capture ants and termites, making them nature’s pest controllers. India is home to two species of pangolins: Indian Pangolin (Manis crassicaudata) is found across most parts of India, except for the northeastern states. Chinese Pangolin (Manis pentadactyla) inhabits the forests of northeast India, including Assam, Arunachal Pradesh, and Meghalaya. Pangolins are the most trafficked mammals in the world due to demand for their scales and meat. Statement 2 is correct: Hoolock Gibbon is India’s only ape species and is a true acrobat of the rainforest. Unlike monkeys, gibbons lack tails and move gracefully through the trees using brachiation (swinging from branch to branch). These lesser apes are found in Northeast India, especially in Assam (Hoollongapar Gibbon Sanctuary) Arunachal Pradesh, Meghalaya, Mizoram, Manipur, Nagaland and Tripura. Hoolock gibbons are known for their melodious calls, which echo through the dense fore","PW-1567":"A fatty acid is a type of carboxylic acid that consists of a long hydrocarbon chain with a carboxyl group (-COOH) at one end. Fatty acids are a major component of fats and oils and are essential for many biological functions. Assertion A is True: Fatty acids are essential components of a balanced diet. They play crucial roles in energy storage, cell membrane structure, and the synthesis of signaling molecules. Certain fatty acids, known as essential fatty acids, cannot be synthesized by the human body and must be obtained through diet such as: Linoleic acid (LA): An omega-6 fatty acid. Alpha-linolenic acid (ALA): An omega-3 fatty acid. Reason R is False: Though humans cannot synthesize certain essential fatty acids like omega-3 and omega-6 but their body can produce other fatty acids. Through de novo lipogenesis saturated and some monounsaturated fatty acids are synthesized from acetyl-CoA derived from carbohydrates and proteins. The body lacks the enzymes to introduce double bonds at the omega-3 and omega-6 positions which makes these polyunsaturated fatty acids essential in the die","PW-1568":"Statement 1 is correct: The femur, or thigh bone is the longest and strongest bone in the human body. It stretches from the hip to the knee and provides crucial support and stability,allowing us to walk, run, and jump. The femur can withstand forces up to 816–1,134 kg before breaking, making it one of the strongest structures in our skeletal system. Statement 2 is correct: Cholera is a severe bacterial infection caused by Vibrio cholerae. It spreads mainly through contaminated water or food, leading to acute diarrhea and dehydration. In extreme cases a person with can lose up to 20 liters of fluid per day making rapid treatment with rehydration therapy essential. Statement 3 is incorrect: Athlete’s foot (Tinea Pedis) is not caused by a virus, but by fungal infection. Dermatophyte fungi thrive in warm, damp environments like locker rooms, swimming pools, and sweaty shoes. The infection causes itchy, peeling, and cracked skin between the toes, making it a common concern among athletes and hence the name. 449","PW-1569":"The word AIDS stands for Acquired Immuno Deficiency Syndrome. This means deficiency of the immune system, acquired during the lifetime of an individual. ‘Syndrome’ means a group of symptoms. AIDS is caused by the Human Immunodeficiency Virus (HIV), a member of a group of viruses called retrovirus. It leads to various symptoms such as UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 628 Swollen lymph nodes occur due to immune system deterioration, commonly affecting the neck, armpits, and groin. Night sweats and recurring fevers are signs of opportunistic infections as the body struggles to regulate temperature. Memory loss and cognitive impairment arise when the virus affects the nervous system, leading to neurological complications. Significant weight loss results from chronic infections, metabolic changes, and increased energy demands. 451","PW-1570":"Statement 1 is incorrect: The renal artery is responsible for delivering oxygenated blood from the heart to the kidneys for filtration. After the kidneys filter the blood by removing waste products and excess substances, the cleansed blood is returned to the systemic circulation via the renal vein, not the renal artery. Statement 2 is correct: From Bowman’s capsule, the glomerular filtrate(filtered liquid) passes into the proximal convoluted tubule (PCT), where essential substances, including glucose, are actively reabsorbed. This reabsorbed glucose along with other nutrients is then transported into the peritubular capillaries and eventually returned to the bloodstream via the renal vein. This ensures that the body retains necessary nutrients while excreting waste. 452","PW-1571":"Statement 1 is correct: When hydrochloric acid (HCl) from the stomach enters the duodenum, it lowers the pH of intestinal contents. This triggers S-cells in the duodenal lining to release secretin. Secretin signals the pancreas to release bicarbonate-rich fluid. This fluid neutralizes the acid, creating an optimal environment for digestive enzymes to function. Statement 2 is correct: Enterogastrone refers to a group of hormones secreted by the duodenal mucosa when dietary fats are present. These hormones, including secretin and cholecystokinin (CCK) slows down gastric motility and inhibit stomach secretions. This regulation ensures that chyme moves gradually from the stomach to the small intestine, promoting better fat digestion and absorption. 454","PW-1572":"The mechanisms of organic evolution refer to the processes by which populations of organisms change over time, leading to the diversity of life forms seen today. These mechanisms explain how species evolve, adapt, and sometimes go extinct. The loss of limbs in snakes is explained by Lamarck’s Theory of Use and Disuse, which suggests that organs that are frequently used develop and strengthen while those that are not used weaken and eventually disappear over generations. Snakes evolved from lizard-like ancestors that originally had limbs. As they adapted to a burrowing or slithering lifestyle, they stopped using their limbs for movement. According to Lamarck’s theory, since the limbs were not used, they gradually reduced in size and eventually disappeared over many generations. 455","PW-1573":"Genetics is the study of heredity and variation in living organisms. It explores how traits are passed from parents to offspring through genes which are the units of heredity located on chromosomes. Option (b) is correct: Pleiotropy occurs when a single gene affects multiple, seemingly unrelated phenotypic traits. Mutations in such a gene can have widespread effects due to its influence on various biological processes This occurs because the gene product (e.g., a protein) may participate in multiple biochemical or physiological pathways. For example, the gene responsible for sickle cell anemia affects multiple traits: red blood cell shape, resistance to malaria, and oxygen transport efficiency. Science and Technology 629 456","PW-1574":"Hormones are chemical messengers secreted by endocrine glands directly into the bloodstream. They regulate various physiological processes, such as growth, metabolism, reproduction, and mood. Examples include Insulin (protein), cortisol (steroid), thyroxine,etc. Statement 1 is correct: Somatotropin, also known as human growth hormone (HGH), is secreted by the anterior pituitary gland. Its release is stimulated by growth hormone-releasing hormone (GHRH) which is released as a result of exercise Statement 2 is correct: In men, progesterone is synthesized not only in the Leydig cells of the testicles but also in the adrenal glands. It serves as a precursor to testosterone and plays roles in various physiological processes. Statement 3 is correct: In females, the adrenal glands contribute to the production of androgens, including testosterone. These hormones are involved in various bodily functions, including the maintenance of muscle mass and libido. Statement 4 is incorrect: Stress typically triggers the adrenal glands to increase the secretion of cortisol, a hormone that helps the bod","PW-1575":"Foot-and-mouth disease (FMD) is a highly contagious viral illness affecting cloven-hoofed animals such as cattle, sheep, goats, and pigs. The causative agent is the foot-and-mouth disease virus (FMDV), classified within the family Picornaviridae, genus Aphthovirus. FMDV is a non- enveloped, positive-sense single-stranded RNA virus. There are seven immunologically distinct serotypes of FMDV: A, O, C, SAT1, SAT2, SAT3, and Asia1, which do not confer cross-immunity. Transmission of FMDV occurs through direct contact with infected animals, exposure to contaminated feed, water, equipment, or clothing, and via aerosols over short distances. The virus is highly resilient, capable of surviving in various environmental conditions, which contributes to its rapid spread among susceptible animal populations. 458","PW-1576":"A is matched with 3: Asiatic Wild Ass (Equus hemionus khur) or Khur, is an Endangered equid found in the Little Rann of Kutch, Gujarat. It has a chestnut brown coat with a dark dorsal stripe and can run at 70 km/h. It is adapted to arid landscapes and survives on minimal water and grazes on grasses and fruits. Conservation efforts, including the Wild Ass Sanctuary, have helped stabilize its population. B is matched with 2: Barasingha (Rucervus duvaucelii) is recognized for its 12-tined antlers. It inhabits grasslands and swamps in Kanha and Dudhwa National Parks. Barasinghas are social grazers, feeding on grasses and aquatic plants. Once critically endangered due to habitat loss, their population has improved due to conservation initiatives such as habitat restoration and anti-poaching measures. C is matched with 4: Chinkara (Gazella bennettii) is a small, agile antelope found in arid and semi-arid regions like the Thar Desert. It has a reddish-buff coat, white underparts, and distinctive facial markings. Chinkaras are solitary browsers, feeding on leaves and fruits, and can survive ","PW-1577":"","PW-1578":"Viviparous animals give birth to live young, rather than laying eggs. However most echinoderms reproduce through external fertilization, releasing eggs and sperm into the water column. Viviparity is relatively rare among echinoderms. Notable exceptions include certain species of brittle stars and sea stars, such as Cryptasterina hystera, which exhibit viviparous reproduction. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 630 461","PW-1579":"A is matched with 2: ​Arber and Smith discovered endonucleases (restriction enzymes). They are enzymes that cut DNA at specific sequences, essential for genetic engineering and molecular biology. These restriction enzymes, such as EcoRI, allow precise DNA modifications, facilitating cloning, genome mapping, and recombinant DNA technology, forming the foundation of modern genetic research and biotechnology applications. B is matched with 1: Feldman developed transgenic plants using Agrobacterium T-DNA. It is a method for introducing foreign genes into plant genomes. This technique revolutionized agriculture by creating genetically modified crops like Bt cotton with enhanced traits like pest resistance and drought tolerance. C is matched with 4: Polymerase Chain Reaction (PCR) was discovered by Kary Mullis. It enables rapid DNA amplification, crucial in forensic science, disease diagnosis, and genetic research. Using DNA polymerase and temperature cycling, PCR exponentially multiplies DNA sequences, allowing precise genetic analysis. It plays a pivotal role in applications like DNA fin","PW-1580":"Assertion (A) is true: Alcohol, including whisky is a diuretic. It inhibits the production of vasopressin (also known as antidiuretic hormone or ADH), which is responsible for regulating water retention in the body. When vasopressin levels drop, the kidneys produce more urine, leading to increased urination. This effect explains why alcohol consumption causes increased thirst and dehydration-related symptoms after drinking. Reason (R) is false: Alcohol actually inhibits the secretion of vasopressin, rather than speeding it up. Vasopressin helps the kidneys reabsorb water, and when its secretion is reduced, the body loses more water through urine, causing dehydration and increased urination. Alcohol interferes with the brain’s communication pathways, affecting areas controlling balance, memory, speech, and judgment. Alcohol slows down the central nervous system, impairing coordination and judgment. Alcohol can cause intellectual impairment, headaches, memory loss, and slowed thinking. 464","PW-1581":"Assertion (A) is false: Glycine, serine, and tyrosine are non-essential amino acids which means they can be synthesized by the human body and do not need to be obtained through diet. Glycine and serine are produced from intermediate metabolites such as glucose and tyrosine is derived from phenylalanine, an essential amino acid. Hence, their dietary intake is not compulsory. Reason (R) is true: Essential amino acids are those that the human body cannot synthesize on its own and must be obtained from the diet. There are nine essential amino acids: histidine, isoleucine, leucine, lysine, methionine, phenylalanine, threonine, tryptophan, and valine. These amino acids are vital for protein synthesis and other metabolic functions. 465","PW-1582":"Speciation is the process by which new and distinct species evolve from a common ancestor. Hugo deVries believed that mutation caused speciation and hence called it saltation (single step large mutation). Mutations are permanent changes in the DNA sequence, which can lead to new traits in a population. Some mutations provide adaptive advantages, increasing survival and reproduction. Over time, accumulation of mutations can result in significant genetic divergence, leading to speciation. Science and Technology 631 466","PW-1583":"Ticks and mites belong to the class Arachnida making them closely related to spiders and scorpions. They possess eight legs (in their adult stage), two body segments (cephalothorax and abdomen), and lack antennae, distinguishing them from insects. Ticks are primarily ectoparasites, feeding on the blood of vertebrates, while mites can be parasitic, free- living, or plant-feeding. Examples include the Deer Tick (Ixodes scapularis), which spreads Lyme disease, and the Scabies Mite (Sarcoptes scabiei), responsible for scabies. 467","PW-1584":"In eye donation, the part of the eye that is transplanted is the cornea. The cornea is the clear, dome- shaped front surface of the eye that allows light to enter and is responsible for focusing light onto the retina. It can become damaged due to injury, disease, or aging. A corneal transplant replaces the damaged cornea with healthy tissue from a deceased donor. Option (b) is incorrect: The lens is located behind the cornea and focuses light onto the retina. It is not transplanted during eye donation, as it can be replaced with an artificial lens in procedures like cataract surgery. Option (c) is incorrect: The retina is a sensitive tissue lining the back of the eye that converts light into neural signals. Retinal damage cannot currently be treated through transplantation during eye donation. Option (d) is incorrect: The whole eye is not transplanted due to the complexity of the organ and the high risk of rejection. 469","PW-1585":"","PW-1586":"The complementary nature of the two DNA strands ensures accurate replication and transmission of genetic information. Adenine (A) always pairs with Thymine (T), and Guanine (G) always pairs with Cytosine (C) on the opposite strand. This allows for precise copying of the genetic information during cell division. 472","PW-1587":"Metastasis is the process through which cancer cells spread from the primary tumor to distant parts of the body, forming secondary tumors in organs such as the lungs, liver, bones, or brain. This process is responsible for nearly 90% of cancer-related deaths, showcasing the aggressive and life- threatening nature of malignant tumors. The process begins with Epithelial-to-Mesenchymal Transition (EMT), where cancer cells gain the ability to migrate and invade surrounding tissues. These cells then enter the bloodstream or lymphatic system (intravasation) and travel to other parts of the body. While in circulation, they evade immune system attacks and other hostile conditions. Upon reaching a new site, the cells exit blood vessels (extravasation) and adapt to the local environment to form secondary tumors. Interestingly, some metastatic cells can remain dormant for years before becoming active again, contributing to cancer recurrence. 473","PW-1588":"Enzymes are biological catalysts, crucial for various biological processes, including digestion, metabolism, and DNA replication. Hormones are chemical messengers produced by endocrine glands which regulate various physiological processes, such as growth, development, metabolism, reproduction, and mood. A is matched with 2: Ptyalin, also known as salivary amylase, is an enzyme present in saliva that breaks down starch into maltose and smaller polysaccharides during digestion. B is matched with 3: Pepsin is a proteolytic enzyme secreted in the stomach. It helps digest proteins into smaller peptides by breaking peptide bonds in acidic conditions. C is matched with 1: Renin is an enzyme secreted by the kidneys in response to low blood pressure. It converts angiotensinogen (produced by the liver) into angiotensin I, which is further converted to angiotensin II, a potent vasoconstrictor. D is matched with 5: Oxytocin is a hormone produced by the hypothalamus and secreted by the pituitary gland. It induces the contraction of smooth muscles, particularly in the uterus during childbirth and ","PW-1589":"Antigens are recognized by the immune system as foreign substances, which stimulates the production of specific antibodies by B-cells (a type of white blood cell). Antibodies bind to antigens, marking them for destruction by other immune cells or neutralizing their harmful effects. Antigens can be proteins, polysaccharides, or lipids. For example, the spike protein of the SARS-CoV-2 virus acts as an antigen, triggering an immune response and the production of antibodies in infected individuals or after vaccination. The immune response involves two types of lymphocytes: 1. B-cells produce antibodies that target antigens. 2. T-cells destroy infected cells displaying antigens. 475","PW-1590":"","PW-1591":"The combination of ribosomes and the endoplasmic reticulum plays a pivotal role in protein synthesis. Ribosomes are the molecular machines responsible for translating messenger RNA (mRNA) into polypeptide chains, which then fold into functional proteins. They can be found floating freely in the cytoplasm or attached to the endoplasmic reticulum. The ER is a network of membranous tubules within the cell. The rough ER (RER) is studded with ribosomes on its cytoplasmic surface, making it the site of protein synthesis for proteins destined for secretion or for use in the cell membrane. After synthesis, these proteins are folded and undergo post- translational modifications within the RER. 477","PW-1592":"","PW-1593":"Human bones are rigid organs that form the skeleton. They provide structure, support, protection for internal organs, and enable movement. Bones are also classified based on their development and function as either axial (skull, spine, ribs, and sternum) or appendicular (limbs and girdles).The human skeleton consists of approximately 206 bones. A is matched with 4: The sternum, commonly known as the breastbone is a flat bone situated at the center of the thoracic cage, connects to the ribs via costal cartilage. It plays a vital role in protecting the heart and lungs while serving as a structural anchor for the ribcage. B is matched with 1: The clavicle, or collarbone is an S-shaped bone which stabilizes the shoulder girdle and assists in transmitting mechanical forces from the upper limb to the axial skeleton. C is matched with 2: The patella, known as the kneecap is a sesamoid bone embedded within the tendon of the quadriceps muscle, protecting the knee joint. D is matched with 3: The scapula, or shoulder blade is a flat, triangular bone located on the posterior aspect of the ribcag","PW-1594":"Statement 1 is correct: Tapeworms, belonging to the class Cestoda are fascinating parasites with a unique reproductive strategy. Each segment of their body, called a proglottid, contains both male and female reproductive organs, making them hermaphroditic. This adaptation allows tapeworms to self-fertilize or cross-fertilize, ensuring reproductive success even in limited host environments. Their reproductive efficiency is one reason they thrive as internal parasites. Statement 2 is correct: Roundworms, or nematodes (phylum Nematoda), exhibit sexual dimorphism, meaning individuals are either male or female. Males are typically smaller and possess specialized structures like spicules for mating. This separation of sexes enhances genetic diversity, a critical factor for survival in diverse environments. Nematodes are one of the most abundant and diverse groups of animals on Earth, found in almost every ecosystem. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 634 Statement 3 is correct: Filariasis is caused by parasitic nematodes like Wuchereria bancrofti and Brugia malayi, which are transmitted to humans via mo","PW-1595":"Assertion (A) is false: Humans have 46 chromosomes (23 pairs), one of which determines sex. This pair consists of XX in females and XY in males. During reproduction, the mother always contributes an X chromosome, while the father can contribute either an X or a Y chromosome. If a sperm carrying an X chromosome fertilizes the egg, the offspring will be female (XX), whereas if a sperm carrying a Y chromosome fertilizes the egg, the offspring will be male (XY). Since the sperm determines the final chromosomal combination, the father plays the major role in sex determination. Reason (R) is true: Females have two X chromosomes (XX), while males have one X and one Y chromosome (XY). 481","PW-1596":"The silkworm yields the fiber of commerce during its larval stage,specifically when it starts to spin its silk cocoon. The silkworm (the larval stage of the silk moth Bombyx mori) produces the fiber of commerce during its larval stage. This stage is when the silkworm starts spinning its silk to form a protective cocoon around itself. The silk produced by the larva is collected and used commercially to make silk fabric. Therefore, the correct stage when the silkworm yields the fibre of commerce is the larva. The imago is the adult moth stage in the silkworm’s life cycle. After metamorphosis, the adult moth does not produce silk. Its role is to mate and lay eggs, continuing the life cycle. Therefore, the silkworm does not yield silk during the imago stage. 482","PW-1597":"A is matched with 2: Haemophilia is a genetic disease caused by mutations in clotting genes. It is inherited via X chromosome. Under this, blood does not clot properly due to a deficiency of clotting factors (such as Factor VIII in Haemophilia A or Factor IX in Haemophilia B). This leads to excessive bleeding even from minor injuries. B is matched with 3: Diabetes is primarily a hormonal disorder related to insulin production or the body’s inability to use insulin effectively. Type 1 diabetes is due to insufficient insulin production (autoimmune) while Type 2 is due to insulin resistance. C is matched with 1: Rickets is caused by a deficiency of vitamin D, calcium, or phosphate, leading to weakened bones. It is not genetic or hormonal but results from nutritional deficiencies. D is matched with 4: Ringworm is a fungal infection caused by dermatophytes, affecting skin, hair, nails resulting in ring- shaped patches. 483","PW-1598":"Blood glucose levels are commonly measured in milligrams per decilitre (mg/dL). This unit expresses the amount of glucose (in milligrams) present in a decilitre (0.1 liters) of blood. It is the standard measurement used in most clinical settings to monitor and diagnose conditions like diabetes. Other units include millimoles per liter (mmol/L), used in countries like the UK, where 1 mg/dL equals 0.0555 mmol/L. 484","PW-1599":"Endocrine glands secrete hormones that regulate various bodily functions, from growth and metabolism to stress responses. A is matched with 2: The gonads (ovaries in females and testes in males) are responsible for producing sex hormones. In females the ovaries secrete progesterone which plays a key role in regulating the menstrual cycle and maintaining pregnancy. In males the testes primarily produce testosterone but it also produces progesterone in smaller amounts. B is matched with 3: Known as the master gland, pituitary gland secretes growth hormone (GH) (stimulates growth, cell reproduction, and regeneration), thyroid-stimulating hormone (TSH) (regulates metabolism), prolactin (stimulates milk production), and antidiuretic hormone (ADH) (maintains water balance). C is matched with 1: Pancreas regulates blood sugar levels through insulin (lowers blood glucose) and glucagon (raises blood glucose) and plays a major role in carbohydrate, fat, and protein metabolism. D is matched with 4: The adrenal glands located on top of the kidneys produce cortisone, a glucocorticoid hormone invo","PW-1600":"","PW-1601":"The small pouch containing silica gel found in bottles of medicine (tablets or powder) is primarily used to absorb moisture. Silica gel is a desiccant, meaning it has a high affinity for water molecules. It absorbs moisture from the surrounding environment, preventing the tablets or powder from degrading due to humidity. This helps maintain the stability and efficacy of the medicine. Silica gel has a porous structure that traps water molecules through adsorption. Moisture can cause tablets to crumble or powders to clump, reducing their effectiveness and shelf life. 487","PW-1602":"Endoscopy is a medical procedure that uses a flexible tube with a light and camera (endoscope) to explore the inside of the body, such as the stomach, intestines, or other organs. The technique relies on the phenomenon of total internal reflection to transmit light through fiber-optic cables inside the endoscope. Total internal reflection occurs when light traveling through a denser medium (such as glass or optical fibers) strikes the boundary with a less dense medium (like air) at a certain angle, causing the light to reflect entirely back into the denser medium instead of refracting out. 488","PW-1603":"","PW-1604":"","PW-1605":"A is matched with 1: Adrenaline, produced by adrenal gland is associated with the body’s response to stress, especially during situations of anger, fear, or danger. It triggers the “fight or flight” response, increasing heart rate, blood pressure, and energy supply. B is matched with 3: Estrogen is indeed the primary female sex hormone that regulates the development of female reproductive tissues and secondary sexual characteristics such as breast development and menstruation. C is matched with 4: Insulin is a hormone that regulates blood glucose levels, facilitating the uptake of glucose by cells for energy. D is matched with 2: Pheromones are chemicals released by animals or humans that influence the behavior of others, particularly related to attracting partners through the sense of smell. 491","PW-1606":"A is matched with 3: Atropine is an alkaloid used primarily to dilate the pupil during eye exams or surgeries. It is also used in emergency situations to treat heart trouble, especially in cases of bradycardia (slow heart rate). B is matched with 1: Ether is an anesthetic and was historically used for local anesthesia or as a general anesthetic in surgeries. C is matched with 2: Nitroglycerine is used to treat heart trouble, especially angina (chest pain) by dilating blood vessels and reducing the heart’s workload. D is matched with 4: Pyrethrin is a natural insecticide, derived from chrysanthemums, used for mosquito control and to manage other pests like lice. 492","PW-1607":"Royal haemophilia (also known simply as haemophilia) is a sex-linked recessive genetic disorder. It is an X-linked recessive genetic disorder characterized by impaired blood clotting due to deficiencies in clotting factors, primarily Factor VIII (Haemophilia A) or Factor IX (Haemophilia B). It primarily affects males, as the gene responsible for haemophilia is located on the X chromosome. Females can be carriers. Queen Victoria of England was a carrier of haemophilia B and passed the trait to several of her children, including her son Leopold, who died from a hemorrhage after a fall when he was 30. 493","PW-1608":"Lathyrism is a neurological disorder caused by the excessive consumption of khesari dal (also known as Lathyrus sativus), a type of legume commonly grown in India and some other regions. The condition is linked to the presence of toxic compounds in the dal, specifically β-ODAP (β-oxalylamino-L- alanine), which can cause damage to the nervous system, leading to symptoms like paralysis, muscle weakness, and spasticity. 494","PW-1609":"The Tambalacoque tree (Sideroxylon grandiflorum), also known as the Dodo tree, usually relied on the Dodo bird for seed germination. The seeds of this tree required scarification (softening of the seed coat) through the Dodo›s digestive system. The Dodo (Raphus cucullatus), a flightless bird endemic to Mauritius, became extinct in the late 1600s due to over-hunting by humans and the introduction of non-native animals like rats and pigs. After the extinction of the Dodo, natural reproduction of the Tambalacoque tree declined significantly. 496","PW-1610":"Aerobic respiration is the process by which glucose is completely oxidized in the presence of oxygen to produce carbon dioxide, water, and energy (in the form of ATP). The overall reaction is: C6​H12​O6​+ 6O2​ → 6CO2​+ 6H2​O+ Energy (ATP) 497","PW-1611":"Fish, especially oily fish like salmon, mackerel, and sardines are rich in polyunsaturated fatty acids (PUFAs) such as omega-3 fatty acids (e.g., EPA and DHA). These fatty acids are essential for various health benefits such as: Reducing the risk of cardiovascular diseases. Improving brain function and development. Reducing inflammation. 498","PW-1612":"A is matched with 4: Malaria is Caused by protozoan parasites of the genus Plasmodium (e.g., Plasmodium falciparum, Plasmodium vivax), transmitted through the bite of infected female Anopheles mosquitoes. India’s National Malaria Elimination Programme (NMEP) aims to eliminate malaria by 2030 under the National Center for Vector Borne Diseases Control (NCVBDC). WHO has approved RTS,S/AS01 (Mosquirix) vaccine for children. B is matched with 3: Polio is caused by the poliovirus (genus Enterovirus) which spreads via contaminated food, water, or contact. Widely available vaccines (OPV and IPV) prevent polio. India’s Pulse Polio Programme launched in 1995 achieved polio-free certification in 2014. C is matched with 2: Tuberculosis is caused by Mycobacterium tuberculosis. It primarily affects the lungs and spreads through the air. The BCG vaccine provides TB prevention in children. India’s National Tuberculosis Elimination Programme (NTEP) offers free treatment and nutrition support under Nikshay Poshan Yojana, aiming for elimination by 2025. D is matched with 1: Ringworm is a fungal infect","PW-1613":"Haemophilia is a genetic disorder where the blood does not clot properly due to a deficiency of clotting factors (such as Factor VIII in Haemophilia A or Factor IX in Haemophilia B). This leads to excessive bleeding even from minor injuries. 500","PW-1614":"","PW-1615":"Oxygen transportation in the human body is essential for cellular respiration, which generates energy in the form of ATPs. This process ensures oxygen is delivered to tissues and carbon dioxide is removed efficiently . Oxygen enters the body through the lungs (2), binds to hemoglobin in the blood (1), and is transported to the tissues (3) where it is utilized for energy production. This sequence reflects the physiological process of oxygen transport. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 638 502","PW-1616":"","PW-1617":"","PW-1618":"","PW-1619":"","PW-1620":"","PW-1621":"A is matched with 5: Malaria is caused by the Plasmodium parasite which infects red blood cells. The parasite multiplies in the blood leading to symptoms such as fever, chills, and anemia. B is matched with 4: Filaria, or lymphatic filariasis is caused by parasitic worms (Wuchereria bancrofti, Brugia Science and Technology 639 malayi, etc.) that infect the lymphatic system including lymph nodes. This leads to swelling and conditions like elephantiasis. C is matched with 2: Encephalitis is an inflammation of the brain which is often caused by viral infections (e.g., herpes simplex virus, Japanese encephalitis virus). It affects brain tissue and can lead to neurological symptoms. D is matched with 1: Leukaemia is a type of cancer that affects the bone marrow and blood. It involves the overproduction of abnormal white blood cells which disrupts normal blood cell production. 509","PW-1622":"The genome of yeast (Saccharomyces cerevisiae) was the first eukaryotic genome to be fully sequenced. The sequencing was completed in 1996 which marked a major milestone in genomics. 511","PW-1623":"Plastic surgery is the earliest medical advancement among the options listed. It dates back to ancient India, where Sushruta, known as the «Father of Surgery,» described advanced reconstructive surgical techniques in the 6th century BCE. He performed reconstructive procedures such as rhinoplasty (nose reconstruction). These procedures were significantly ahead of their time and predates other medical milestones by centuries. 512","PW-1624":"As per the WHO reports around 1996 , Tuberculosis (TB) which is caused by Mycobacterium tuberculosis was responsible for the highest number of deaths globally. It primarily affects the lungs and is prevalent in developing countries due to poverty, overcrowded living conditions, and limited access to healthcare. TB has remained a significant global health burden despite being curable and preventable. However, currently Heart diseases are the largest reason behind human mortality. 513","PW-1625":"Xerophthalmia, caused by Vitamin A deficiency, is a critical public health issue in India. It primarily affects children and can lead to dryness of the conjunctiva and cornea, eventually resulting in blindness if left untreated. Addressing this condition through improved dietary intake and supplementation programs is a top priority for reducing malnutrition and its consequences in India. 514","PW-1626":"Option (b) is correct: A is matched with 2: Carotene, specifically beta-carotene, is a provitamin A carotenoid found in plant foods. It is converted into vitamin A (retinol) in the human body which plays a crucial role in vision, immune function, and skin health. B is matched with 1: Enzymes are biological catalysts that speed up chemical reactions in the body. Pepsin is a digestive enzyme produced in the stomach that breaks down proteins into smaller peptides. C is matched with 4: Hormones are signaling molecules produced by glands that regulate physiological processes. Progesterone is a steroid hormone involved in the menstrual cycle, pregnancy, and embryogenesis. D is matched with 3: Proteins are large biomolecules made of amino acids that perform a variety of functions in the body. Keratin is a structural protein found in hair, nails, and the outer layer of skin. 515","PW-1627":"Diabetes mellitus is characterized by higher blood sugar levels (hyperglycemia) due to either insufficient insulin production or reduced insulin sensitivity. Type 1 diabetes (previously known as insulin-dependent, juvenile or childhood-onset) is characterized by deficient insulin production and requires daily administration of insulin. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 640 Type 2 diabetes affects how your body uses sugar (glucose) for energy. It stops the body from using insulin properly, which can lead to high levels of blood sugar if not treated. 516","PW-1628":"Option 1, 2 and 4 are correct: AIDS (Acquired Immunodeficiency Syndrome), caused by the HIV virus, is transmitted through: Sexual intercourse: HIV is primarily transmitted through unprotected sexual contact, including vaginal and anal intercourse with an infected partner. The virus is present in bodily fluids such as semen and vaginal secretions. Blood transfusion: Receiving blood transfusions contaminated with HIV can transmit the virus. HIV can be transmitted from an infected mother to her child during pregnancy, childbirth, or breastfeeding. This mode of transmission is known as vertical or mother-to-child transmission. It is transferred from an infected mother to her foetus across the placenta. These are the primary modes of transmission as confirmed by WHO. Option 3 is incorrect: HIV cannot be transmitted through mosquitoes or other blood-sucking insects because the HIV virus does not survive or replicate in these organisms. 517","PW-1629":"Malnutrition refers to a state of improper nutrition, which can arise from overnutrition (excess intake of food or nutrients), undernutrition (deficiency of essential nutrients), and imbalanced nutrition (inadequate or excessive intake of specific nutrients relative to others). Overnutrition: Consuming excessive calories or nutrients can lead to obesity and associated health issues like diabetes, cardiovascular diseases, and metabolic disorders. Undernutrition: A lack of essential nutrients causes deficiencies like protein-energy malnutrition (e.g., kwashiorkor, marasmus), anemia, and weakened immunity. Imbalanced nutrition: A diet lacking in proper proportions of macronutrients (carbohydrates, proteins, fats) and micronutrients (vitamins, minerals) can cause health problems, even if calorie intake is sufficient. All these conditions impair the body’s ability to function optimally and lead to health complications. 518","PW-1630":"","PW-1631":"Besides proteins and carbohydrates, milk is a rich source of calcium and potassium, which are essential for strong bones, teeth, and maintaining fluid balance. Calcium is essential for bone health, muscle function and nerve signaling. Potassium is an important electrolyte that helps regulate fluid balance, muscle contractions and nerve signals. 520","PW-1632":"Subcutaneous fat is a layer of fat located just beneath the skin. It primarily acts as an insulator which reduces heat loss from the body by trapping heat and maintaining body temperature. This insulation is particularly beneficial in cold environments, helping to conserve energy and prevent hypothermia. 521","PW-1633":"Option (c) is correct: The major chemical compound that constitutes kidney stones is Calcium Oxalate. These stones are common and can cause severe pain during urination. Calcium oxalate is formed when calcium in the urine binds with oxalate, a compound found in certain foods (e.g., spinach, nuts) or produced as a by-product of metabolism. High concentrations of calcium and oxalate in urine, combined with low fluid intake, promote the crystallization of calcium oxalate. Options (a), (b), and (d) are incorrect: Urea is not a major component of kidney stones because it is a waste product of protein metabolism that is typically excreted in the urine. Other types of kidney stones can contain calcium carbonate, calcium phosphate, uric acid, or struvite, but calcium oxalate stones are the most common. Factors such as dehydration, high oxalate intake, and certain medical conditions can increase the risk of kidney stone formation","PW-1634":"Ahmad Shah Abdali invaded India because the Marathas had expelled his son, Timur Shah, from Lahore in 1758. Timur Shah was Abdali’s viceroy in Punjab, and his removal by the Marathas was seen as a direct challenge to Abdali’s authority. This greatly angered him, and he decided to take revenge. In 1760, he marched towards India to reclaim Punjab and restore his influence. This was the main reason behind the Third Battle of Panipat in 1761. Option (b) is incorrect : Adina Beg Khan was a Mughal officer who played an important role in Punjab’s politics. However, he did not invite Abdali to invade India. In fact, he had earlier invited the Marathas to fight against Abdali’s influence in Punjab. Option (c) is incorrect : Abdali had financial interests in India, and he did demand revenue from Mughal territories. However, this was not the main reason for his invasion. By 1760, the Mughal administration had already weakened, and the real power in North India was shifting towards the Marathas and other regional powers. Abdali’s main enemy at this time was not the Mughals but the Marathas, who ","PW-1635":"Lord Dalhousie is considered “the creator of the map of India”. Doctrine of Lapse was introduced by Lord Dalhousie. This policy allowed the British to annex any Indian princely state if the ruler died without a natural heir or was deemed incompetent. The doctrine was based on the idea that the British, as the paramount power, had the right to decide the succession of Indian states. States annexed under this policy:  Satara (1848): The first state to be annexed under the Doctrine of Lapse.  Jhansi (1853): Annexed after the death of Raja Gangadhar Rao without a male heir.  Nagpur (1854): Annexed after the death of Raghoji III without a natural heir. Annexation of Awadh (1856): Awadh (or Oudh) was a wealthy and strategically important state in northern India, ruled by the Nawabs of Awadh. Unlike the states annexed under the Doctrine of Lapse, Awadh had a legitimate ruler, Nawab Wajid Ali Shah, who had a natural heir. Therefore, the Doctrine of Lapse could not be applied here. To justify the annexation, the British accused Nawab Wajid Ali Shah of misgovernance and claimed that the peo","PW-1636":"Dalhousie annexed these states under the Doctrine of Lapse policy ,which was based on the idea that if a ruler of a princely state died without a natural male heir (i.e., no biological son or successor), the state would “lapse” or pass into the hands of the British Crown. Satara was annexed in 1848. Sambalpur was annexed in 1849 and Jhansi in 1853. These annexations and especially annexation of Awadh in 1856 under the pretext of misgovernance were the major cause of the revolution of 1857. Satara 1848 Sambalpur and Jaitpur 1849 Baghat 1850 Udaipur 1852 Jhansi 1853 Nagpur 1854 Tanjore and Arcot 1855 Awadh 1856 Modern History 77 like France, Turkey, and Persia to secure alliances against the British. He sought military and technological support through these diplomatic efforts, showcasing his modern approach to foreign relations. A pioneer of military innovations, he effectively used rocket artillery and introduced administrative reforms like a new calendar, coinage, and revenue systems.  Haider Ali was the ruler of Mysore from 1761 to 1782 and is known for expanding his kingdom and m","PW-1637":"Statement 1 is incorrect: The Gajapati Dynasty came to an end in the 1540s, and the United East India Company of the Netherlands was established in March 1602. The Dutch set up their first factory in Masulipatnam, Andhra Pradesh in 1605. Statement 2 is correct: The Portuguese under the command of Alfonso de Albuquerque captured Goa from the Bijapur Sultanate in 1510. Goa remained a key Portuguese colony for over four centuries. Statement 3 is correct: In 1639, the English East India Company acquired a piece of land at the site of present-day Chennai (Madras) from the local Nayak rulers, who were successors to the Vijayanagara Empire. 8","PW-1638":"Statement 1 is incorrect: In the Third Battle of Panipat, Ahmad Shah Abdali/Durrani, the ruler of Afghanistan defeated the Maratha Peshwa’s forces led by Sadashivrao Bhau in 1761. Ibrahim Lodi was defeated by Turko-Mongol Babar in the first Battle of Panipat in 1526 ending the Sultanate in Delhi and establishing the Mughal in India. Statement 2 is incorrect: Tipu Sultan was killed in the Fourth Anglo Mysore war while defending Seringpatam in 1799 and the British placed a Wodeyar heir under Subsidiary Alliance. Statement 3 is correct: Mir Jafar, who was the commander-in- chief (Bakshi) of Siraj-ud-Daulah’s army, secretly conspired with the British East India Company, led by Robert Clive, to overthrow Siraj. Several influential figures in Bengal, including Mir Jafar, Rai Durlabh, Jagat Seth, and Omichand, were dissatisfied with Siraj’s rule due to his erratic leadership and hostility toward the British. 5","PW-1639":"The arrival of European trading powers in India marked a turning point in the subcontinent’s history. The Portuguese, Dutch, English, and French came at different times, competing for control over trade and resources.  The Portuguese were the first Europeans to arrive in India, with Vasco da Gama reaching Calicut in 1498.  The Dutch East India Company established trading posts in India starting in the early 17th century, , with their first factory in Masulipatnam (in Andhra) in 1605.  The English East India Company began operations in India in the early 17th century, with their first factory established in Surat in 1613. Over time, they became dominant in India.  The French were the last Europeans to arrive as traders in India. The French East India Company was founded in 1664, and they established their first factory in Surat in 1668, followed by Pondicherry (Puducherry) in 1674. 11","PW-1640":"The Dutch established factories on the Coromandel coast, in Gujarat, Uttar Pradesh, Bengal and Bihar. Amongst the above , they opened their earliest factory at Pulicat in 1609. Their other principal factories in India were at Surat (1616), Bimlipatam (1641), Karaikal (1645), Chinsura (1653), Kasimbazar (near Murshidabad), Balasore, Patna, Nagapatam (1658) and Cochin (1663). 13","PW-1641":"The Subsidiary Alliance was a diplomatic strategy introduced by Lord Wellesley in 1798, aiming to maintain British control over Indian states. Option (c) is correct: The Subsidiary Alliance aimed to establish British paramountcy over the Indian States and to ensure their military and political subservience to the British East India Company. Securing a fixed income for the company was not the primary objective of the system. Hyderabad was the first state to come under it. The native Indian ruler had to pay for the maintenance of the British army and if he failed to make the payment, a portion of his territory was taken away and ceded to the British. They could not engage in alliances with other powers without British consent. SUPER HINT \"Subsidiary Alliance\" suggests a political-military arrangement, \"If I were a colonial strategist like Lord Wellesley, what would I want from this system?\" Military advantage without direct cost, Justification to interfere in Indian state affairs, Diplomatic cover against global threats (like Napoleon). All yes! What I don’t need from this is: A fixed,","PW-1642":"","PW-1643":"","PW-1644":"","PW-1645":"The governance of British India underwent significant changes over time, with key administrative reforms reshaping the roles and designations of officials. Statement 1 is incorrect: Robert Clive, often referred to as the “founder of the British Empire in India,” served as the Governor of Bengal twice (1757–1760 and 1765–1767). However, he was not the first Governor-General of Bengal. This title belongs to Warren Hastings, who was appointed as the first Governor- General of Bengal under the Regulating Act of 1773. Statement 2 is correct: William Bentinck became the first Governor-General of India in 1833 under the Charter Act, which extended the Governor-General of Bengal’s authority to all British territories in India. 20","PW-1646":"","PW-1647":"The 18th century in India was a tumultuous period marked by battles involving European powers and Indian states, vying for dominance over trade, territory, and political control. Key battles during this era shaped the trajectory of British colonial rule and defined European influence in India.  The Battle of Ambur (1749), during the Second Carnatic War, marked the start of Anglo-French rivalry, with the French backing Chanda Sahib and the British supporting Muhammad Ali.  The Battle of Plassey (1757) saw Robert Clive’s British East India Company defeat Siraj-ud-Daulah, establishing British political control in India.  The Battle of Wandiwash (1760), in the Third Carnatic War, ended French ambitions in India with a British victory.  The Battle of Buxar (1764) secured British control over Bengal, Bihar, and Odisha, defeating a coalition of the Nawab of Awadh, Mughal Emperor Shah Alam II, and Mir Qasim. 22","PW-1648":"Statement 1 is incorrect: Warren Hastings, the first Governor-General of India, did not establish a regular police force. Instead, he reorganized the existing system of policing and appointed a superintendent of police for each district. The British-style police system was introduced later by Lord Cornwallis in 1786. Statement 2 is correct: The Regulating Act of 1773 established the Supreme Court in Calcutta with jurisdiction over Bengal, Bihar, and Orissa, hearing civil, criminal, and commercial cases, and exercising both original and appellate jurisdiction. Statement 3 is correct: The Indian Penal Code (IPC) was drafted by the first Law Commission of India established in 1834 under the Charter Act of 1833 under the chairmanship Thomas Babington Macaulay and was formally enacted in 1860 during the time of the British East India Company. 23","PW-1649":"The 18th and 19th centuries were marked by a series of wars between the British and various Indian powers as part of the British East India Company’s efforts to consolidate control.  Pair 1 is incorrectly matched: AD 1767–69 marks the First Anglo-Mysore War, not the First Anglo-Maratha War. The First Anglo-Maratha War occurred later, from 1775 to 1782.  Pair 2 is correctly matched: AD 1790–92 corresponds to the Third Mysore War, fought between the British East India Company and Tipu Sultan.  Pair 3 is correctly matched: AD 1824–26 corresponds to the First Anglo-Burmese War, which resulted in British territorial expansion in Burma.  Pair 4 is incorrectly matched: AD 1845–46 marks the First Sikh War, not the Second Sikh War. The Second Sikh War occurred in 1848–49. 24","PW-1650":"","PW-1651":"","PW-1652":"The expansion of British India was a significant aspect of British’s colonial policy, with the British seeking to expand the territory of British India through annexations, wars, and treaties. Option (b) is correct: The last major extension of British Indian territory occurred during Lord Dalhousie’s tenure as Governor-General (1848– 1856). Dalhousie is particularly noted for his aggressive policy of annexation and territorial expansions. For example, under Doctrine of Lapse(Jhansi, Satara, Nagpur,etc) and on the basis of Misgovernance (Awadh) were annexed. 27","PW-1653":"One of the major factors in the decline of indigo cultivation was the invention of synthetic dyes in the 19th century. This breakthrough led to the development of a wide range of synthetic dyes that were cheaper, easier to produce, and more effective than natural indigo. By the 1880s, synthetic dyes became widely available, reducing the global demand for natural indigo. SUPER HINT Think about what causes a widespread decline in a commercial cash crop. Not a local protest(A). Not just moral opposition(C). You need a market-based, structural reason that impacts the entire economic viability of the crop. Option B aligns most closely with this. 29","PW-1654":"The Munda Rebellion (1899–1900), led by Birsa Munda, was a major tribal uprising in Chotanagpur (now Jharkhand), known as Ulgulan (\"The Great Tumult\"). It opposed the zamindari system (introduced in 1874), which replaced the traditional Khuntkari system(land belonged collectively to the Munda clans), creating landlords (zamindars) and tenants (ryots). This led to heavy taxation, exploitation by moneylenders, and forced labor (Beth Begari). Birsa Munda mobilized tribals against British rule and earned the title ‘Dharti Abba’ (Earth Father). The revolt was ultimately suppressed, and Birsa Munda died in prison in 1900. 30","PW-1655":"The Santhal Rebellion (1855-56) in the Rajmahal Hills was sparked by the oppression of revenue officials, police, moneylenders, and landlords (referred to as “dikus” by the Santhals). Led by Sido and Kanhu, the Santhals revolted, declaring independence from the British. The rebellion was suppressed by 1856 after extensive military action. Statement (1) is correct: After the Santhal Uprising (1855– 56), the British created the Santhal Parganas in 1855 by carving out areas from Bhagalpur and Birbhum districts to provide the Santhals with a separate administrative region. Statement (2) is correct: The British introduced legal restrictions on land transfers, making it illegal for a Santhal to transfer land to a non-Santhal. This was done to prevent exploitation by moneylenders (Mahajans) and landlords (Zamindars), which had been a major cause of the rebellion. Modern History 83 31","PW-1656":"Tebhaga Peasant Movement (1946) in Bengal aimed to reduce landlords’ share of the harvest from one-half to one-third. The movement, led by the Bengal Provincial Kisan Sabha, called for the implementation of the Floud Commission recommendations, demanding two-thirds of the produce for sharecroppers (bargadars) instead of the previous one-half. The main slogan, “nij khamare dhan tolo,” urged sharecroppers to keep their paddy in their own homes, not at the landlord’s. The movement was strongest in North Bengal, particularly among the Rajbanshis and Muslims. 32","PW-1657":"Tribal revolts in 19th-century India were driven by the disruption of traditional tribal life, which centered on shifting cultivation, hunting, and forest produce during colonial rule. Option (d) is correct:  The influx of non-tribals and the imposition of settled agriculture led to land loss for tribals. Restrictions on forest resources and shifting agriculture, along with the introduction of moneylenders, reduced tribals to landless laborers and bonded peasants.  The establishment of government monopolies on forests (1865-1878) further exploited tribes. Tribal egalitarianism was replaced by caste-based inequalities, and the influence of Christian missionaries also fueled resentment leading to uprisings like the Kol Rebellion (1832), Santhal Rebellion (1855-56), and Munda Rebellion (1899-1900). 33","PW-1658":"In the latter part of the 18th century, following the grant of Diwani (revenue collection rights) of Bengal by the Mughal emperor in 1765, the British East India Company began establishing contact with the Garos. The estates bordering the Garo Hills, previously semi-independent, came under British control. However, like the Mughals, the British did not seek to directly govern these estates. Instead, the Zamindars were entrusted with maintaining order, including controlling the Garos. Conflict between the Zamindars and Garos continued until it escalated, leading to the British annexation of the Garo Hills in 1873. 34","PW-1659":" Santhal Rebellion (1855–1856) also referred to as the Santhal Hul was a tribal uprising against oppressive landlords and colonial policies in the Bengal Presidency.  Mutiny of the Sepoys (1857–1858) or the First War of Independence was a widespread revolt by Indian soldiers in the British East India Company’s army. It took place shortly after the Santhal Rebellion.  Indigo Revolt (1859–1860) also called the Neel Bidroha, this uprising occurred in Bengal against the exploitation by British planters who forced farmers to grow indigo under harsh conditions.  Deccan Riots (1875) erupted in western India as a protest against oppressive practices by moneylenders and increasing rural indebtedness. 35","PW-1660":"Statement 1 is incorrect: Dr. Rakhmabai was an Indian physician and a feminist. At the young age of eleven, she was married to Dadaji Bhikaji, who was then nineteen. The Rakhmabai case did not centrally involve the women’s right to gain education. Statement 2 is correct: The Rakhmabai case of 1884 was instrumental in the drafting of the Age of Consent Act in 1891. Statement 3 is correct: She was married off at the young age of eleven with Dadaji Bhikaji, who was nineteen years old. In 1885, after 12 years of marriage, Bhikaji filed a petition in the court and sought “restitution of conjugal rights”. 37","PW-1661":"On 24 September 1873, Jotirao Govindrao Phule formed Satyashodhak Samaj to focus on the rights of depressed groups such as women, the Shudra, and the Dalit in Maharashtra. The Satyashodhak Samaj opposed idolatry and the caste system, advocating for reason and equality. It rejected the need for priests and promoted simple religious practices for all. The group’s viewpoints were voiced through the Deenbandhu newspaper. Members included Muslims, Brahmins, and government officials, with financial support primarily from Phule’s Mali caste. 38","PW-1662":"Option (1) is incorrect: The Calcutta Unitarian Committee (1823) was founded by Rammohan Roy, Dwarkanath Tagore, and William Adam to promote Unitarian beliefs and social reforms, but Keshab Chandra Sen was not involved in its formation. Option (2) is correct: The Tabernacle of New Dispensation (1881) was established by Keshab Chandra Sen as part of his Nava Vidhan (New Dispensation) movement, which aimed to integrate the teachings of Hinduism, Christianity, Islam, and other religions into a universal faith. It reflected his belief in religious harmony and spiritual unity Option (3) is correct: Indian Reform Association (1870), focusing on social reforms such as women's rights, education, widow remarriage, and temperance (restrictions on alcohol consumption). The association played a crucial role in advocating progressive changes in Indian society. 39","PW-1663":"Indian Social Conference (1887) was formed by M. G. Ranade and Raghunath Rao in Madras. It was a separate social reform organ of the Indian National Congress as they did not want to include social reforms in their deliberations. It advocated inter-caste marriage, opposed polygamy and kulinism and launched “Pledge Movement to pledge against Child Marriage” 40","PW-1664":"The Brahmo Samaj, founded by Raja Ram Mohan Roy in 1828, was a reformist movement aimed at promoting monotheism, social equality, and the abolition of social evils like Sati and child marriage. It sought to reform Hinduism by advocating for reason, rationality, and rejection of idol worship and caste discrimination. Statement 1 is correct: Brahmo Samaj vehemently opposed idolatry or idol worship. Statement 2 is correct: The chief aim of Brahmo Samaj was the worship of the eternal God. It was against priesthood, rituals and sacrifices. Statement 3 is incorrect: Brahmo Samaj spread the religious treasure and teachings of Vedas but never claimed that Vedas are infallible. SUPER HINT S1 and S2 both show rationalist, reformist, anti-ritualistic tendencies(Group 1). S3 implies scriptural orthodoxy(Group 2). Therefore, Group 2 logically contradicts Group 1, This eliminates option A and D. Since Brahmo Samaj is historically known (even without exact recall) as a liberal, reformist movement, S3 cannot logically align with its ideology. 41","PW-1665":"The given statements refer to notable figures and reform movements in Indian history, particularly Arya Samaj, Brahmo Samaj, and Sarvodaya Samaj. Modern History 85 Statement 1 is incorrect: Arya Samaj was established in 1875, not in 1835. It was founded by Swami Dayananda Saraswati to promote Vedic ideals and social reform. Statement 2 is incorrect: Lala Lajpat Rai, a prominent nationalist leader, was a staunch supporter of Arya Samaj and its principles. He did not oppose its appeal to the Vedas but actively advocated its social reform agenda. Statement 3 is correct: Keshab Chandra Sen, as a prominent leader of Brahmo Samaj, played a significant role in championing women’s education and addressing social issues like child marriage and dowry. Statement 4 is correct: Vinoba Bhave founded the Sarvodaya movement, which focused on the welfare of all sections of society, particularly through initiatives like the Bhoodan movement. It also worked with refugees. 6. EARLY PHASE NATIONAL MOVEMENT (1885-1905) 42","PW-1666":"Option (b) is correct: The First Session of the Indian National Congress (INC) took place in Bombay (now Mumbai) in December 1885. It was chaired by Womesh Chunder Bonnerjee. Other Key Congress Sessions: Year Place President Highlights 1886(2nd Session) Calcutta Dadabhai Naoroji merger of National Congress and National Conference 1887 Madras Syed Badruddin Tyabji first Muslim President 1888 Allahabad George Yule first British President 1905 Benaras Gopal Krishna Gokhale expressed resentment against the partition of Bengal 1906 Calcutta Dadabhai Naoroji the word ‘swaraj’ mentioned for the first time. 1907 Surat Rash Behari Ghosh split in the Congress into the Moderates and the Extremists. 44","PW-1667":"The Indian National Congress (INC), founded in 1885, initially aimed to promote political dialogue between Indians and the British government. Early sessions focused on constitutional reforms, Indian rights, and critique of economic impact of British rule. Statement 1 is incorrect: The first session of the Indian National Congress (INC) was held in Bombay (now Mumbai) in 1885, not in Calcutta. Statement 2 is correct: The Second Session of the Indian National Congress (1886) was indeed presided over by Dadabhai Naoroji. Statement 3 is correct: The Indian National Congress and the Muslim League held their sessions in Lucknow in 1916, where they concluded the Lucknow Pact. The Lucknow Pact was a historic agreement, marking a significant step towards Hindu- Muslim unity and paving the way for joint political efforts in the struggle for self-rule. 7. INDIAN NATIONAL MOVEMENT – I (1905-1918) 45","PW-1668":"Ghadar Party was a revolutionary group organised around a weekly newspaper “The Ghadar” with its headquarters at San Francisco and branches along the US coast and in the Far East. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 86 Option (d) is correct: The moving spirits behind the Ghadar Party were Lala Hardayal, Ramchandra, Bhagwan Singh, Kartar Singh Saraba, Barkatullah and Bhai Parmanand, Rash Behari Bose, etc. Barindra Kumar Ghosh was associated with a revolutionary group called Jugantar and Jogesh Chatterjee was associated with the Hindustan Republican Association/ Army (HRA). 46","PW-1669":"Swadeshi Movements were large-scale protests against the partition of Bengal. Later, the movement spread to other regions of the nation. New means of protest like processions, public meetings, and boycotts of imported goods were used. Statement 1 is correct: Emphasis was placed on Self-Reliance (Atma Shakti), honour, social and economic regeneration of the villages. Swadeshi textile mills, banks, etc, were set up. At Tuticorin, V.O. Chidambaram Pillai founded the Swadeshi Steam Navigation Company. This gave a boost to indigenous artisans. Statement 2 is correct: The National Council of Education, established in 1906, was created to organize and promote national education in India, with a particular emphasis on teaching in the vernacular languages. SUPER HINT The word “Swadeshi” literally means \"of one’s own country\". Naturally, this would boost local industry, crafts, handlooms, etc. Hence S1 likely true. National education (free from colonial influence) aligns perfectly with Swadeshi ideals too, Hence S2 also likely true. 47","PW-1670":"Champaran Satyagraha (1917) was undertaken after Mahatma Gandhi learned about the abuses suffered by farmers, who were forced into growing indigo by British planters and estate owners. Under the Tinkathia system in Champaran, tenants were forced to grow indigo on 3/20th of their land for landlords. European planters imposed high rents and illegal fees, sparking passive resistance. This marked the beginning of Gandhian methods and the involvement of peasants in the Indian National Movement. 48","PW-1671":"","PW-1672":"The Swadeshi Movement (1905–1908) was a key turning point in the history of the Indian National Congress that later led to a split between the moderates and extremists in the party . The movement, which was sparked by the partition of Bengal by the British in 1905, saw the rise of extremist leaders like Bal Gangadhar Tilak, who advocated for more radical measures to achieve self-rule, while the moderates, led by figures like Gopal Krishna Gokhale and Dadabhai Naoroji, supported gradual reforms within the British system. The differences over the approach to achieving independence eventually led to the split at the Surat Session of 1907. Modern History 87 51","PW-1673":"Partition of Bengal (1905) was made public by the British Government in 1903 and partition came into force in October 1905. The reasons given by the British was that Bengal was too big to be administered and this division of Bengal into eastern and western Bengal would develop Assam. The Partition of Bengal was annulled during the visit of the Royal Majesties, George V and Queen Mary to India. King George V announced the abrogation in the Delhi Durbar in December , 1911. 52","PW-1674":"The Ghadar Party was a revolutionary organisation centred on the weekly newspaper “The Ghadr,” which had branches in the Far East and along the US coast in addition to its San Francisco headquarters. The Ghadr programme aimed to organise official assassinations, disseminate anti-imperialist and revolutionary literature, coordinate with Indian troops stationed abroad, get weapons, and spark a simultaneous uprising across all British colonies. Their plans were encouraged by two events in 1914, the Komagata Maru incident and the outbreak of the First World War. The Ghadr Party’s inspirational forces were Lala Hardayal, Ramchandra, Bhagwan Singh, Kartar Singh Saraba, Barkatullah, etc. 53","PW-1675":"Statement 1 is correct: The Kheda Satyagraha (1918) was a protest against the British government’s tax demands on Gujarat farmers whose crops had failed due to drought. Despite the revenue code allowing remission, the government insisted on full payment, threatening to seize property. Led by Sardar Vallabhbhai Patel and others, Gandhi encouraged farmers to resist paying taxes peacefully. The government eventually agreed to return confiscated property and suspend tax collection for the year. Statement 2 is incorrect: Permanent Settlement was introduced by Lord Cornwallis in 1793 and it was confined in the areas of Bengal, Bihar, Orissa, Varanasi (United Provinces), Northern Karnataka. It was never introduced in Gujarat. 54","PW-1676":"The Champaran Satyagraha was a significant event in India’s freedom struggle, marked by Mahatma Gandhi’s efforts to address the exploitation of indigo farmers. Statement 1 is incorrect: Dr. Rajendra Prasad was not the one who persuaded Gandhi to visit Champaran. It was Raj Kumar Shukla, a local farmer and indigo cultivator, who approached Gandhi and urged him to look into the plight of the peasants suffering under the oppressive indigo cultivation system. Statement 2 is correct: Acharya J.B. Kriplani was one of the leaders who supported Gandhi during the Champaran investigation. As a nationalist leader, Kriplani actively worked alongside Gandhi to address the grievances of the oppressed farmers and contribute to the success of the movement. 55","PW-1677":"The Calcutta session of the Indian National Congress in 1906 was significant for its adoption of four key resolutions that defined the strategies of the Congress during the Swadeshi movement. These resolutions were: boycotting British goods, resolution on nationalist education system independent of British control, resolution on Swadeshi, adoption of the demand for Swaraj or self-rule. However, the “Annulment of partition of Bengal” was not among these resolutions. 56","PW-1678":"The Swadeshi Movement was initiated as a direct response to the partition of Bengal announced by Lord Curzon in 1905. The partition was perceived as a deliberate attempt to fragment the Bengali-speaking population along religious lines, thereby weakening the unity of the nationalist movement. The movement focused on boycotting British goods and promoting locally made products, advocating for self-reliance and economic independence. Leaders like Rabindranath Tagore, Aurobindo Ghosh, and Bal Gangadhar Tilak played key roles. Initially strong in Bengal, it spread nationwide, fostering national pride and unity. 57","PW-1679":"The date 16th October 1905 is historically significant as it marks the Partition of Bengal, a controversial administrative decision by Viceroy Lord Curzon. The Partition of Bengal in 1905 aimed ostensibly for administrative efficiency divided the province along religious lines, with East Bengal primarily Muslim and West Bengal predominantly Hindu. It was met with widespread protests and ignited a strong nationalist movement. While the partition was annulled in 1911, it left a lasting impact fueling the Swadeshi and Boycott movements. 58","PW-1680":"Mahatma Gandhi’s first Satyagraha in India was initiated in Champaran, Bihar, in 1917. The farmers were forced to grow indigo under oppressive conditions, often receiving very low prices for their crops, and were subjected to high taxes. Gandhi’s non-violent protest led to an official inquiry, resulting in relief for the farmers and marking a significant victory for the Indian freedom movement. This marked the beginning of his non- violent struggle for social and economic justice in the country. 59","PW-1681":"The London Muslim League was founded in 1908 by Syed Ameer Ali and other Muslim leaders. He was a prominent figure in the Muslim community, played a significant role in promoting the interests of Indian Muslims on an international platform. In 1909 he became the first Indian to be appointed as a member of the Judicial Committee of the Privy Council. He served in this prestigious position until his death in 1928, leaving a lasting impact on the representation of Indians in British institutions.  Aga Khan – Leader of the Ismaili Muslims, founded the All India Muslim League (1906), promoted Muslim education, social reforms, and was a key figure in Indian-Muslim political representation.  Liaquat Ali Khan – Pakistan’s first Prime Minister, key associate of Jinnah, helped draft Pakistan Resolution (1940), played a major role in India's partition and Pakistan’s early governance.  M.A. Jinnah – Founder of Pakistan, leader of the All India Muslim League, instrumental in the Pakistan Movement, key figure in Lucknow Pact (1916) and Lahore Resolution (1940). Modern History 89 62","PW-1682":"Upon returning to India from South Africa, Mahatma Gandhi initiated his first successful satyagraha in Champaran in 1917. The movement arose in response to the plight of indigo farmers in Bihar, who were compelled by British planters to grow indigo under oppressive conditions, leading to widespread exploitation. To support these farmers, Gandhi led a peaceful and nonviolent resistance movement, advocating for their rights and justice. 63","PW-1683":"The Indian Councils Act of 1909, also known as the Minto-Morley Reforms, was the shortest-lived of all of Britain’s constitutional experiments in India. It lasted only 10 years, until the 1919 Montague Chelmsford Reforms that lasted for the next 16 years. The Indian Councils Act of 1861 lasted for 31 years and it was replaced by the Indian Councils Act of 1892 which lasted for next 17 years. 65","PW-1684":"","PW-1685":"The Komagata Maru Incident (1914) involved a Japanese steamship, the Komagata Maru, carrying 376 Indian passengers (mostly Sikhs) attempting to migrate to Canada but were denied entry to Canada under discriminatory immigration laws and were forced to return to Calcutta, India. Gandhi ji stayed in South Africa for 21 years and fought for the rights of the non-Europeans in South Africa. Gandhi returned to India in 1915 and toured India on the advice of Gopal Krishna Gokhale. Tilak established the Indian Home Rule League in April 1916 in Belgaum. The league focused its activities in Maharashtra, Karnataka, Central Province, and Berar, excluding Bombay. The objective was to achieve self-government for India. 67","PW-1686":"Indian Muslims were generally not attracted to the Extremist movement because of the movement’s emphasis on Hindu symbolism, rituals, and historical references. The extremists believed in sacrificing everything including life for the cause of the motherland. They tried to instill self respect and patriotism in the people by invoking past heroes like Ashoka, Shivaji, Maharana Pratap, and this approach alienated many Muslims who felt that their religious and cultural identity was not adequately represented or respected. 68","PW-1687":"In 1920, the All India Home Rule League, founded by Bal Gangadhar Tilak and Annie Besant, changed its name to the Swarajya Sabha. This was in line with the growing demand for complete self-rule (Swarajya) and the influence of the Non-Cooperation Movement led by Mahatma Gandhi. It aimed to promote the idea of “Home Rule” and played a key role in mobilizing public opinion, laying the groundwork for India’s struggle for independence. 72","PW-1688":"Statement 1 is correct: Rowlatt Act was passed on the recommendations of the Sedition Committee chaired by Sir Sidney Rowlatt. Statement 2 is correct: In organising his satyagraha, Gandhiji tried to utilise three types of political networks: The Home Rule Leagues; Certain Pan-Islamist groups and Satyagraha Sabha. Statement 3 is incorrect: The two time periods are not the same. The incident of Rowlatt Satyagraha took place in 1919 and the Demonstrations against the arrival of Simon Commission took place in 1928, thus the two events cannot coincide. 73","PW-1689":"","PW-1690":"Assertion (A) is true: In 1911, Gopal Krishna Gokhale, a prominent member of the Imperial Legislative Council, introduced a bill urging the government to assume responsibility for providing compulsory education. However, the bill was rejected by the council due to insufficient popular support. Reason (R) is True: One of the reasons to refuse to provide compulsory education was the fear that discontent would have increased against the British administration if every cultivator could read. Modern History 91 Option (c) is incorrect: Mahatma Gandhi moved the Non cooperation resolution in the Special Session of Congress at Calcutta in 1920. Option (d) is incorrect: Decision to participate in the Round Table Conference in London was taken in the Karachi Session of Congress in 1931. 74","PW-1691":"The Indian Statutory Commission, commonly referred to as the Simon Commission under the chairmanship of Sir John Simon arrived in British India in 1928. The Simon Commission originated as a result of the Government of India Act, 1919 (Montagu-Chelmsford Reforms), which introduced Dyarchy in provinces. The Act had a provision that after ten years, its impact would be reviewed to decide further constitutional reforms. It was appointed by the British government to assess India’s constitutional development and recommend constitutional reforms. The main reason behind the agitation against the Simon Commission was that there were no Indian members of the panel and only seven British members of the British Parliament. This was viewed as racist and colonialist. SUPER HINT The question isn’t what the commission did, it’s why people were already agitating as it arrived. So, logically, the reason must have been known before any report or recommendation came out. This eliminates (b) and (d), For Option A, Logically, people always want progress or change. Saying “never wanted review” is too absol","PW-1692":"","PW-1693":"Statement 1 is correct: In the Lahore Session of Indian National Congress (1929), the resolution on ‘Poorna Swaraj’ or complete independence was passed. The Congress also decided to boycott the First Round Table Conference because the British refused to include Indian demands for a Constituent Assembly and full self-rule. Statement 2 is incorrect: The rift between the extremists and moderates took place in the Surat Session(1907) and the split was resolved in the Lucknow Session 1916. Statement 3 is incorrect: The Two-Nation Theory, proposed by Sir Syed Ahmad Khan and later championed by the Muslim League, argued that Hindus and Muslims in India were two distinct nations with separate religious, cultural, and social identities. But it is not associated with the Lahore Session of Indian National Congress. 77","PW-1694":"The Nehru Report, drafted in response to Lord Birkenhead’s challenge, was prepared by a committee led by Motilal Nehru. Key members included Tej Bahadur Sapru, M.S. Aney, Subhash Chandra Bose, and G.R. Pradhan. Option (b) is correct: Recommendations were:  Dominion status on lines of self-governing dominions but not full independence.  Rejection of separate electorates. Joint electorates with reservation of seats for Muslims at the Centre and in areas where they were in minority.  Nineteen fundamental rights, including the rights to form unions, the right to equal treatment for women, and universal adult suffrage.  Responsible government at the Centre and in provinces.  Provisions to protect the cultural and religious rights of minorities. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 92 78","PW-1695":"The Rowlatt Act was officially known as the Anarchical and Revolutionary Crimes Act, 1919. Popular indignation arose because it allowed the government to detain individuals suspected of anti-government activities without trial for up to two years, violating basic civil rights.  The Rowlatt Act (1919) was unrelated to religion. Its primary focus was on curbing political activities, particularly revolutionary movements against British rule.  The Act did not address education in any form. Its provisions targeted political dissent and civil liberties rather than cultural or educational systems.  The Act was not specifically aimed at trade unions. Its focus was on political repression, targeting freedom fighters and those involved in revolutionary activities. 80","PW-1696":"Mahatma Gandhi founded the Ahmedabad Textile Labour Association in 1920 to improve the working and living conditions of textile workers in Ahmedabad. The association emphasized non-violent methods and arbitration to resolve labour disputes, aligning with Gandhian principles.  N.M. Joshi was labour leader and founder of the All India Trade Union Congress (AITUC) in 1920 but unrelated to this association. 81","PW-1697":"The Rowlatt Act was passed in 1919 during the viceroyalty of Lord Chelmsford (1916–1921). Officially known as the Anarchical and Revolutionary Crimes Act, 1919, it aimed to curb revolutionary activities by allowing imprisonment without trial for up to two years, essentially denying people their basic civil rights. 82","PW-1698":"The Jallianwala Bagh massacre (April 13, 1919) was a tragic event where British General Reginald Dyer ordered his troops to fire on a peaceful gathering of unarmed Indians, killing hundreds, in protest associated with the repressive Rowlatt Act. The Act allowed the British government to imprison people without trial, which infringed upon basic civil liberties. 83","PW-1699":"The Lahore session of the Indian National Congress was held in 1929 under the presidency of Jawaharlal Nehru. During this session, the Congress adopted the historic resolution to demand Purna Swaraj (complete independence) from British rule. It was also decided to celebrate 26th January 1930 as Independence Day, marking the declaration of India’s resolve for full sovereignty. This session marked a significant shift in the freedom struggle, moving away from dominion status demands to the goal of complete independence. 84","PW-1700":"The Ghadar revolutionaries were primarily based in North America, particularly in regions like California, USA, and British Columbia, Canada. They established the Ghadar Party in 1913 to organize revolutionary activities against British colonial rule in India specifically in cities like San Francisco and Vancouver. The party played a significant role in spreading revolutionary ideas and organizing uprisings, particularly during World War I, aiming to incite mutiny in the British Indian Army and disrupt British operations in India. Central America, West America, and South America regions did not serve as significant bases for the Ghadar revolutionaries. Modern History 93 85","PW-1701":"The resolution on Fundamental Rights and the National Economic Program was drafted by Pandit Jawaharlal Nehru for the Karachi session of the Indian National Congress in 1931. The Resolution on Fundamental Rights guaranteed free speech and free press, the right to form associations, the right to assemble, universal adult franchise, equal legal rights irrespective of caste, creed and sex, free and compulsory primary education, protection to culture, language, the script of minorities and linguistic groups 86","PW-1702":"In October 1920, M.N. Roy (Manabendra Nath Roy) headed a group of Indians in Tashkent, Uzbekistan, to establish the Communist Party of India (CPI). This marked the formal introduction of communism in India. The party was founded with the support of the Comintern (Communist International), reflecting global efforts to spread Marxist ideologies. This group, influenced by the Bolshevik Revolution of 1917 in Russia, sought to establish a Marxist-oriented political organization in India. 87","PW-1703":"The U.P. Kisan Sabha was formed in February 1918 to address the grievances of peasants in the United Provinces (now Uttar Pradesh). It was initiated by Madan Mohan Malviya, Gauri Shankar Misra, and Indra Narain Dwivedi, who worked together to mobilize the peasantry against oppressive taxes, such as high rents, land revenue, and exploitation by landlords. Jawaharlal Nehru was not directly associated with the formation of U.P. Kisan Sabha. 88","PW-1704":"The Montagu-Chelmsford Report, published in 1918, proposed constitutional reforms for India, recommending the introduction of dyarchy in provinces and expanding the legislative councils. These recommendations formed the basis for the Government of India Act, 1919. 90","PW-1705":" Minto-Morley Reforms (1909) were constitutional reforms introduced by the British government to expand the legislative councils and include elected Indian representatives.  The recommendations of the Montagu-Chelmsford Report (1919) led to the Government of India Act, 1919, and introduced dyarchy in the provinces.  Chauri-Chaura Outrage (1922) occurred during the Non- Cooperation Movement. It was a violent incident where a police station was attacked by a mob, leading to a significant shift in Gandhi’s strategy. Gandhi called off the Non- Cooperation Movement across the country, as he felt that it had deviated from its non-violent goal.  Dandi March (1930) led by Mahatma Gandhi, this was a major event in the Civil Disobedience Movement, aimed at protesting the British salt tax. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 94 91","PW-1706":"When the Congress leaders condemned the Montagu- Chelmsford Report (1918) for not granting enough self- governance to India, many moderate leaders led by Surendra Nath Banerjee who were dissatisfied with Congress’s position left the party and formed the Indian Liberal Federation. This organization aimed to support gradual constitutional reforms and believed in constitutional methods for achieving Indian self- rule. 93","PW-1707":"The Khudai Khidmatgars, led by Khan Abdul Ghaffar Khan (the Frontier Gandhi), were a nonviolent movement advocating for Pashtun unity and independence from British rule. Inspired by Gandhian principles of non-violence, they focused on social reform and opposed British colonialism. Active in the North-West Frontier Province, they also opposed the partition of India and the creation of Pakistan, as reflected in the 1947 Bannu Resolution, which called for an independent Pashtunistan rather than joining Pakistan. The movement played a key role in the broader Indian independence struggle. 95","PW-1708":"The moderate phase of the Indian National Congress, characterized by the policy of prayer and petition, ended as Bal Gangadhar Tilak and other Extremist leaders like Lala Lajpat Rai and Bipin Chandra Pal advocated for Swaraj (self-rule) and direct action. Extremists under Tilak’s leadership adopted a more assertive stance, focusing on mobilizing the masses and boycotting British institutions through the Swadeshi Movement. 96","PW-1709":"The Simon Commission was set up in 1927 by the British government to review the working of the Government of India Act, 1919, and suggest constitutional reforms. However, it was boycotted by Indians across the political spectrum because all its members were British, and there was no Indian representation. This exclusion was seen as an insult to Indian self-respect and aspirations for greater autonomy. The boycott led to widespread protests, including the famous slogan “Simon Go Back.” 97","PW-1710":"Edwin Montagu, the Secretary of State for India, described the Jallianwala Bagh Massacre of April 13, 1919 as “Preventive Murder”. The massacre occurred when General Dyer ordered troops to open fire on a peaceful gathering in Amritsar, killing hundreds of unarmed Indians. This brutal act was carried out under the pretext of maintaining law and order but was widely condemned as a deliberate and excessive use of force. Montagu’s term reflected the British government’s internal criticism of this event, which intensified Indian demands for independence. 98","PW-1711":"The Khilafat Movement (1919–1924) was a pan-Islamic political campaign led by Indian Muslims, aimed at preserving the Ottoman Caliphate after World War I. Following the defeat of the Ottoman Empire, British and Allied forces sought to dismantle the caliph’s power, prompting Indian Muslims, particularly under leaders like Ali Brothers (Shaukat Ali and Mohammad Ali), to demand its restoration. A is true: Khilafat Movement united urban Muslims with the broader National Movement, as leaders like Maulana Mohammad Ali and Maulana Shaukat Ali joined Gandhi’s Non-Cooperation Movement. Cities like Delhi and Bombay saw significant participation in protests and boycotts. R is true: Both the Khilafat and the National Movement were united in their opposition to British imperialism, fostering Hindu-Muslim unity during the Non-Cooperation Movement. R is the correct explanation of A: The shared anti-imperialist goal served as a binding factor that drew urban Muslims into the larger nationalist fold. 99","PW-1712":"The Non-Cooperation Movement, launched in 1920, aimed to achieve Swaraj through non-violent means. However, the Chauri-Chaura incident in February 1922, where protesters clashed with police and set a police station on fire, killing 22 policemen. A is true: Gandhi did stop the Non-Cooperation Movement in 1922 believing that the movement had strayed from its non- violent principles. R is true: The violence at Chauri-Chaura was the pivotal reason for Gandhi’s decision. R is the correct explanation of A: The abandonment of non- violence conflicted with Gandhi’s philosophy, making the incident a decisive factor in halting the movement. 100","PW-1713":"The Sarabandi Campaign was led by Vallabhbhai Patel in Gujarat. It was a non-violent protest where farmers refused to pay taxes, highlighting the oppressive tax policies of the British. This campaign strengthened Patel’s leadership role in the independence movement. It showcased the growing unity and defiance among Indians against British exploitation, setting the stage for future movements like the Civil Disobedience Movement. 103","PW-1714":"The Anarchical and Revolutionary Crime Act of 1919 was a draconian law enacted by the British government to curb revolutionary activities in India. It became infamous for its oppressive measures and the widespread protests it provoked. It was famously called the Rowlatt Act, which was passed in 1919, and it allowed the British government to imprison individuals without trial for up to 2 years and suppress civil liberties under the pretext of curbing revolutionary activities. 104","PW-1715":"The Government of India Act was passed by the British parliament in 1935 and came into effect in 1937. It was based on a report by a Joint Select Committee, led by Lord Linlithgow, set up the two houses of the British parliament. Some of the key features of the Act were :  The creation of a ‘Federation of India’ that consisted of two levels: a central executive and parliament, and below it, provinces and princely states. Hence, Statement 1 is correct.  It discarded the ‘dyarchy’ system at the provincial level and allowed for the emergence of popularly elected provincial legislatures. Dyarchy was introduced at the central level, key subjects like defence and foreign affairs were under the direct control of the Governor General. Hence, Statement 2 is incorrect.  A federal court was established.  The franchise was expanded to 14% of the population from 3%.  Separate electorates were provided for Muslims, Sikhs and others, but not to Depressed Classes.  The governor enjoyed critical emergency powers. SUPER HINT For S2, Would the British Empire in 1935 be willing to hand over Defenc","PW-1716":"Cripps Mission (1942) headed by Stafford Cripps was sent to India with constitutional proposals to seek Indian support for World War II. Because of the reverses suffered by Britain in South-East Asia, the Japanese threat to invade India seemed real now and Indian support became crucial. Statement (1) is incorrect: After the war the Constituent Assembly would be formed with members from Provinces (elected through proportional representation and not nominated) and Princely states (nominated). A new Constitution making body and the Government would negotiate a treaty for transfer of Power. Statement (2) is correct: The proposal allowed any Province unwilling to accept the new Constitution to have the right to remain outside the Indian Union and negotiate a separate arrangement with Britain regarding its future. This provision was later seen as a precursor to the partition of India. SUPER HINT For S1, It says: \"members nominated by the Provincial Assemblies...\" Think logically: Assemblies are elected bodies. So why would they nominate rather than elect representatives? In any democratic ","PW-1717":"","PW-1718":"Statement 1 is correct: During the early 1900s, Mahatma Gandhi was instrumental in getting the indentured labour system abolished in the British Empire. He also supported Manilal Doctor’s campaign to get a resolution passed in the INC meeting condemning the indentured labour system in all British territories. Statement 2 is incorrect: Lord Chelmsford invited Gandhi to Delhi at a War Conference. Gandhi agreed to move people to enlist in the army for WW-I hoping such support would lead to political reforms and greater self-rule for India. Statement 3 is correct: Indian National Congress was declared illegal upon breaking of salt law. The British government arrested thousands of Congress leaders and activists, and Gandhi was imprisoned for leading the movement. 111","PW-1719":" Second Round Table Conference was held in London, between September 7, 1931 to December 1, 1931. The Indian National Congress nominated Gandhi as its sole representative.  The Quit India Movement, launched by Mahatma Gandhi in August 1942, called for an immediate end to British rule in India. It was a mass civil disobedience movement, marked by protests, strikes, and widespread arrests.  The Royal Navy Mutiny of 1946, also known as the Naval Uprising, involved Indian sailors protesting against harsh conditions, low wages, and discrimination in the British Royal Navy. The mutiny spread across several naval bases, becoming a significant part of the larger Indian independence movement. 112","PW-1720":"The Gandhi Salt Satyagraha (1930) was a non-violent protest against the British monopoly on salt production and its heavy taxation. Led by Mahatma Gandhi, it involved the famous Salt March to Dandi, symbolizing defiance against British colonial rule and mobilizing mass support for India’s independence movement. Such symbolic marches were organised throughout India. C Rajagopalachari organised a march from Tiruchirapalli to Vedaranniyam on Tanjore coast. Annie Besant (1847–1933) – A British socialist and theosophist who championed India's self-rule, she founded the Home Rule League (1916) and became the first woman president of the Indian National Congress (1917). She actively promoted education, theosophy, and Indian nationalism. V.O. Chidambaram Pillai (1872–1936) – A freedom fighter and nationalist from Tamil Nadu, he founded the Swadeshi Steam Navigation Company (1906) to challenge British shipping dominance. He was imprisoned for his involvement in the Swadeshi Movement and is often called \"Kappalottiya Tamizhan\" (The Tamil Helmsman). 115","PW-1721":"A high-powered mission of three British Cabinet members- Lord Pethick-Lawrence (the Secretary of State for India), Sir Stafford Cripps(President of the Board of Trade) and A. V. Alexander(the First Lord of the Admiralty) reached Delhi on 24th March 1946. Statement 1 is correct: The Cabinet Mission proposed a Three- tier executive and legislature at provincial, section and union levels which essentially means a federal government. All subjects other than Union subjects and residuary power would vest in the provinces of British India. Statements 2 and 3 are incorrect: The plan did not include the enlargement of the powers of the Indian Court nor provided for more Indians in the ICS. 116","PW-1722":"The Radcliffe Committee was appointed by the British government in 1947 tasked with demarcating the borders between the newly independent nations of India and Pakistan. The division primarily focused on the regions of Punjab and Bengal, where large Hindu and Muslim populations coexisted. The resulting Radcliffe Line was announced on August 17, 1947, two days after India’s independence. The border division led to massive population displacement, causing widespread violence and communal riots, with millions of people migrating across the new borders, resulting in significant loss of life and property. 117","PW-1723":"In 1942, the British Government sent the Cripps Mission to India to secure Indian support for Britain’s war effort during World War II. The Cripps Proposals offered India dominion status after the war and promised a constituent assembly to frame a new constitution, but these were largely seen as insufficient and vague. The Congress (led by Mahatma Gandhi) demanded immediate independence and rejected the Cripps Proposals. When the British government failed to provide clear and concrete plans for independence, Gandhi called for a mass movement of civil disobedience, demanding that the British “Quit India”. 118","PW-1724":"In 1937, after the Government of India Act, 1935, which allowed for provincial autonomy, the Indian National Congress (INC) formed ministries in eight out of eleven provinces in India. Lord Linlithgow, the Viceroy of India, declared India’s involvement in World War II on behalf of the British government. As a result of this unilateral declaration Congress ministries resigned as a protest against the British government’s failure to consult Indian leaders regarding India’s participation in the war. 119","PW-1725":"The Quit India Resolution was ratified in a Congress meeting at Gowalia Tank on 8th August 1942. Apart from the Quit India Movement, other resolutions involved the Civil Disobedience Movement against British Rule. Mantra of “Do or Die” was adopted in this Session by Gandhiji. The British Govt responded to the call of Gandhi by arresting all major Congress leaders the very next day. Gandhi, Nehru, Patel, etc. were all behind the bars. This left the movement in the hands of the younger leaders like Jayaprakash Narayan and Ram Manohar Lohia, besides many regional leaders also rose up to lead this movement in their respective regions. 120","PW-1726":"The Quit India Movement was one of the largest anti- colonial movements. It started on August 8, 1942, under the leadership of Mahatma Gandhi. The immediate causes were the failure of Cripps mission, hardships caused during World War II and the Japanese knocking at the doors of Indian borders. Even before the movement could formally be launched all major leaders of congress were put behind the bars by the British. In this situation various secret and underground activities under the leadership to younger congress leaders kept the movement going. In this environment, Usha Mehta, a young congress leader started an underground Radio to give fuel to the movement. 121","PW-1727":"The Cripps Mission of 1942 was sent by the British government to secure Indian support during World War II in exchange for a promise of post war constitutional reforms. The Congress Party engaged in negotiations, although the proposal was ultimately rejected. Option (c) is correct: Pandit Jawaharlal Nehru and Maulana Abul Kalam Azad were the official Congress negotiators with the Cripps Mission. They rejected the proposal because it did not grant immediate independence, allowed provinces to opt out of a united India, and retained British control during the war. Gandhi famously referred to the offer as a “post-dated cheque on a crashing bank”, reflecting the discontent with the mission’s limited concessions. 122","PW-1728":"Statement 1 is correct: The Bombay Manifesto openly opposed the preaching of socialist ideals, fearing that such policies would disrupt free enterprise and harm industrial growth. It was a response to the increasing influence of socialism within the Congress Party. Statement 2 is incorrect: However the manifesto did not get support from a large section of the business community across India. The business community was positive about the government intervention and hand holding in running the enterprises and economy. 123","PW-1729":"After the Quit India Movement of 1942, C. Rajagopalachari proposed a solution to the constitutional deadlock between the Indian National Congress,the Muslim League and the British Government through his pamphlet titled “The Way Out”. It suggested that the Congress should accept the League’s demand for Pakistan through a plebiscite in Muslim-majority areas, provided the British granted complete independence to India. His proposal was an attempt to resolve the growing communal tensions and the deadlock over India’s future governance. 124","PW-1730":"The Karachi session of 1931, presided over by Sardar Patel, was significant for its adoption of the Resolution on Fundamental Rights and Economic Programme drafted by Jawaharlal Nehru laying the foundation for India’s socio- economic vision.The Resolution advocated for key socio- economic reforms such as labor rights, minimum wages, equality, and universal adult suffrage. The resolution underscored Congress’ commitment to political independence and social justice, serving as a foundation for shaping governance priorities in independent India. 125","PW-1731":"The Dandi March, also known as the Salt Satyagraha, was a pivotal event in India’s independence movement. Led by Mahatma Gandhi, it began on March 12, 1930, from Sabarmati Ashram and ended on April 6, 1930, in Dandi, Gujarat. Covering 240 miles, Gandhi and his followers protested against the British salt tax by producing salt from the sea, violating colonial laws. Option (c) is correct: This act of nonviolent resistance marked the formal launch of the Civil Disobedience Movement, which aimed to challenge British authority through mass protests and the boycott of imperial policies. 126","PW-1732":"Mahatma Gandhi gave the slogan “Do or Die” during his speech at the Gowalia Tank Maidan in Bombay on August 8, 1942. The Quit India Movement, also known as the August Movement or August Kranti Movement, began on this day. Gandhi’s speech was a final push to force the British to leave India. He said, “We shall do or die. We shall either free India or die in the attempt; we shall not live to see the perpetuation of our slavery”. Modern History 101 127","PW-1733":"Mahatma Gandhi chose the Satyagrahis for the Individual Satyagraha movement which is also known as ‘Delhi Chalo Movement’. The movement began on October 17, 1940. It was non-violent and symbolic in nature, and was meant to affirm the right to speech. The movement was a response to the August Offer made by the then Viceroy of India, Linlithgow. Following were the first few satyagrahis in Individual Satyagraha: Satyagrahi Name 1 Vinoba Bhave 2 Pandit Jawaharlal Nehru 3 Brahma Dutt 128","PW-1734":"The Cripps Proposals were introduced by Sir Stafford Cripps in March 1942 during World War II to secure Indian support for the Allied war effort. Cripps aimed to address India’s demand for self-rule by offering a post-war framework. Statement 1 is incorrect: The Cripps Proposals did not offer full independence to India. Instead, it offered the possibility of dominion status for India, which meant self-government within the British Commonwealth. Statement 2 is correct: The Cripps Proposals included provisions for the creation of a Constitution-making body in India. This body, called the Constituent Assembly, would be responsible for drafting the new constitution. It would consist of representatives from various Indian provinces and political parties, with the authority to shape the country’s future governance 129","PW-1735":"Aruna Asaf Ali was an important figure in the Indian freedom struggle. She actively participated in various underground activities and played a significant role in the Quit India Movement. These activities included organizing secret meetings, distributing leaflets and pamphlets, and spreading awareness about the movement. One of the most iconic moments of Aruna Asaf Ali’s involvement in the Quit India Movement was when she hoisted the Indian National Congress flag at the Gowalia Tank Maidan in Bombay (now Mumbai). 130","PW-1736":"In March 1942, the British government sent the Cripps Mission to gain full Indian cooperation in the war effort. The mission was led by Sir Stafford Cripps, a senior left-wing Labourite and a member of Prime Minister Winston Churchill’s War Cabinet. About reasons for sending Cripps Mission:  Because of the reverses suffered by Britain in South-East Asia, the Japanese threat to invade India seemed real and Indian support became crucial.  There was pressure on Britain from the Allies (USA, USSR, China) to seek Indian cooperation.  Indian nationalists had agreed to support the Allied cause if substantial power was transferred immediately and complete independence given after the war. 131","PW-1737":"In June 1945, Lord Wavell, the Viceroy of India, proposed the Wavell Plan at the Simla Conference to reconstitute the Viceroy’s Executive Council. The plan’s key features included: 1. All members of the Executive Council would be Indian except the governor general and commander-in-chief. 2. Equal representation for Caste Hindus and Muslims. 3. All portfolios, including that of War Members were to be held by the Indians. 4. The Viceroy/Governor-General would retain veto power, but its use would be minimal. 132","PW-1738":"In the 1936-37 elections, the Indian National Congress formed a ministry in 8 out of 11 provinces under the Government of India Act, 1935. Congress ministries were formed, focusing on education, economic reform, and civil liberties. Assertion (A) is true: In 1939, all Congress ministries resigned from their positions in the provinces. The resignations marked the end of Congress-led governance under the Government of India Act, 1935, intensifying the freedom struggle. Reason (R) is true: Congress ministries resigned in 1939 because the Viceroy declared India a belligerent in WWII without consulting Indian leaders. While Congress believed India should decide independently, they also opposed supporting Britain’s war against Germany under colonial rule. This lack of consultation was the direct cause of their resignation. Therefore Reason (R) correctly explains the Assertion (A). UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 102 133","PW-1739":"The Wavell Plan (1945), proposed by Lord Wavell, aimed to resolve the political deadlock between the Indian National Congress and the Muslim League. It proposed forming a framework for an interim government. Assertion (A) is true: According to the Wavell Plan, the number of Hindu and Muslim members in the Executive Council were to be equal. Reason (R) is false: Wavell Plan did not aim to prevent partition but rather to create a framework for political dialogue and the transfer of power from British rule to Indian self-rule. 134","PW-1740":"Dr. Rajendra Prasad held the portfolio of Food and Agriculture in the Interim Government formed in the year 1946. About portfolios in interim government: Portfolio Minister Defence Baldev Singh Finance Liaquat Ali Khan Labour Jagjivan Ram External Affairs and Commonwealth Relations Jawaharlal Nehru 135","PW-1741":"The Quit India Movement (QIM) was a mass civil disobedience campaign launched by the Indian National Congress in August 1942, led by Mahatma Gandhi, demanding an end to British rule in India. Statements 1 and 2 are incorrect: Mahatma Gandhi promoted non-violent resistance during the Quit India Movement but did not ask government servants to quit their roles. He focused on mass civil disobedience and non-cooperation, urging Indians to refuse support for British rule and demand independence. Gandhi ji did not ask soldiers to leave their posts. Statement 3 is correct: Gandhi preached self-rule (Swaraj) and independence from British rule, advocating for the princely states to embrace their people’s sovereignty. 136","PW-1742":"In the 1936-37 elections, the Indian National Congress formed a ministry in 8 out of 11 provinces under the Government of India Act, 1935. Congress did not secure a majority in Punjab. Instead, the Unionist Party, a coalition of landlords and representatives of various religious communities, led by Sir Sikandar Hayat Khan, formed the government with support from the Muslim League. 137","PW-1743":"The Lahore Session of the Indian National Congress, held in December 1929, was a landmark event in India’s struggle for independence. Under the presidency of Jawaharlal Nehru, this session marked a significant shift in the Congress’s approach towards British rule. The Congress formally adopted the resolution of Purna Swaraj (complete independence), rejecting the earlier goal of dominion status within the British Empire. Option (b) is correct: One of the key outcomes was the authorization given to the Congress Working Committee to launch a program of civil disobedience if the British government failed to meet Indian demands. 138","PW-1744":"The Shimla Conference (1945) aimed to discuss India’s future governance but failed due to Congress-Muslim League disagreements. The Royal Indian Navy Mutiny (1946) saw Indian sailors revolt against British rule, protesting poor conditions and discrimination. Statement 1 is incorrect: The conference took place in June 1945 under Lord Wavell, who served as Viceroy from 1943 to 1947. Mountbatten only assumed the role in March 1947, shortly before India’s independence. Statement 2 is correct: The Indian Navy Revolt began on February 18, 1946, with sailors in Bombay and Karachi protesting poor conditions and discrimination. They demanded national independence and the release of INA and political prisoners, symbolizing India’s growing nationalist sentiment. 139","PW-1745":"The Round Table Conferences (1930-1932) were three meetings in London between British officials and Indian leaders to discuss constitutional reforms. Statement 1 is correct: At the First Round Table Conference in London in 1930, Dr. B.R. Ambedkar represented the depressed classes (now Scheduled Castes) and demanded separate electorates to ensure their adequate representation and protect their interests. Statement 2 is incorrect: The Poona Pact was an agreement between Dr. B.R. Ambedkar and Mahatma Gandhi(his representatives) in 1932. It provided reserved seats for the depressed classes (Scheduled Castes) in provincial legislatures and ensured their political representation. This pact replaced the separate electorates initially proposed for depressed classes. Statement 3 is correct: The Indian National Congress, led by Mahatma Gandhi, boycotted the Third Round Table Conference in London in 1932. The Congress had reservations about the British government’s proposals, believing the discussions would not yield a satisfactory outcome for India’s future. 140","PW-1746":"Government of India Act, 1935, which introduced significant constitutional reforms. All the three given statements are correct: The Government of India Act, 1935 provided for:  Provincial autonomy, granting greater powers to provincial legislatures.  The establishment of a Federal Court to resolve disputes between the central and provincial governments.  The creation of an All-India Federation at the center, though it was never fully implemented.  The expansion of the electorate, allowing more Indians to vote.  The introduction of a bicameral legislature at the center, consisting of the Council of States and the Federal Assembly. 141","PW-1747":"Statements 1 and 2 are correct:  Act Provided for abolition of diarchy in the Governor’s provinces, transferring more power to the provincial governments.  The Act granted the Governors the power to veto legislative action and allowed them to enact laws without the consent of the legislative bodies in certain circumstances. Statement 3 is incorrect: The Government of India Act, 1935 retained separate electorates based on communal representation, allowing distinct voting rights for communities like Muslims, Sikhs, and other minorities. 142","PW-1748":"The Interim Cabinet was formed in September 1946 as part of the transition to India’s independence. It was established under the Cabinet Mission Plan and acted as the provisional government of India. It included leaders from the Indian National Congress and later some members from the Muslim League. Option (b) is correct: Jawaharlal Nehru was the head of the Interim Cabinet, which was formed in September 1946. He held the position of Vice President of the Executive Council (equivalent to Prime Minister). Other Interim Cabinet Members Important Positions C.H. Baba Works, Mine and Power. John Mathai Industries and Supplies. Asaf Ali Railways and Transport. Baldev Singh Defence. Jagjivan Ram Labour. Liaquat Ali Khan Finance (Muslim League). I.I. Chundrigar Commerce (Muslim League). UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 104 144","PW-1749":"The Bardoli Satyagraha was a significant peasant movement in Bardoli, Gujarat in 1928, led by Sardar Vallabhbhai Patel. It was sparked by the British government’s decision to increase land revenue by 22%, which severely affected the farmers. He organized the farmers to refuse to pay the increased taxes, leading to a successful non-violent protest that resulted in the reversal of the tax hike. His leadership earned him the title “Sardar” (leader) from the women of Bardoli for his success in forcing the British to roll back the revenue hike. 145","PW-1750":"The Cripps Mission was sent to India in March 1942 by the British government to secure Indian support for the British war effort during World War II. The mission, led by Sir Stafford Cripps, aimed to offer India greater autonomy in return for cooperation. The Cripps Mission proposed the creation of an Indian Union with Dominion status after the war, which would grant India a degree of self-governance but still leave it under British sovereignty. The Cripps Mission was a failure because it did not meet the expectations of Indian political leaders and both Indian National Congress and Muslim League rejected the proposals. 146","PW-1751":"Ever since the 1857 revolt, to secure princely states as a safeguard against potential political instability and to reward their loyalty the policy of annexation was discontinued. The Government of India Act of 1935 proposed a federal union (that never came to existence) that included both British India and the princely states, which were ruled by Indian monarchs but under British control. The 1935 Act did not aim for direct political control over the princely states. It allowed them autonomy while including them in the federal structure. The British sought to manage relations, not control them completely. The real intention behind including princely states into the proposed federal union, through Government of India Act, 1935, was to ensure that these states would act as a balance against the anti-imperialist nationalist movement. 147","PW-1752":"Jivatram Bhagwandas Kripalani ascended to a prominent position within the Congress Party. He was elected President of the Indian National Congress in November 1946 and steered the organisation through the critical days of the transfer of power and the partition of India in 1947. 148","PW-1753":"In the early 1930s, the Indian National Congress (INC) led India’s nationalist movement, while the labour movement grew with workers protesting for better conditions. Despite this, the labour movement had limited involvement in the broader nationalist struggle. They felt the Congress was not adequately addressing the issues important to workers, like social and economic reforms. Assertion (A) is true: The labour movement in the early 1930s was growing, but its participation in the larger Indian nationalist movement was weak. Workers were more focused on their immediate economic struggles, like better wages and working conditions, rather than the broader nationalist cause. Reason (R) is true: Some labour leaders criticised the Indian National Congress (INC) for representing the interests of the middle class and the bourgeoisie rather than the working class. Due to this the effect of labour participation in nationalist upsurge was weak. Thus, Reason (R) explains Assertion (A). 149","PW-1754":"The Cabinet Mission reached Delhi on March 24, 1946. The Mission engaged in extensive discussions with Indian leaders from all parties and groups on the following issues:  the formation of an interim government, and  the principles and processes for drafting a new constitution that would grant India independence. The Cabinet Mission (1946) proposed a federal union for India, with autonomy for provinces and safeguards for minorities. The Cabinet Mission Plan was initially accepted in principle by both the Congress and the Muslim League but disagreements soon emerged, particularly over the grouping of provinces. The Muslim League eventually rejected the plan, and Jinnah called for “Direct Action.” This failure to agree on the plan is widely regarded as the last major chance to prevent the partition of India. Modern History 105 150","PW-1755":"The Chittagong Armoury Raid, took place on April 18, 1930 was organized by Surya Sen, also known as Masterda Surya Sen. He was the leader of the Indian Republican Army, a revolutionary group that aimed to seize arms and ammunition from the British armoury in Chittagong. Other participants of Chittagong Armoury Raid were Ananta Singh and Subodh Roy. 151","PW-1756":"","PW-1757":"The Indian National Army (INA) was formed during World War II with the objective of fighting against British rule in India. The idea of INA was first conceived in Malaya by Captain Mohan Singh in 1942. The Indian National Army was officially formed in Singapore in 1943. It was led by Subhas Chandra Bose, who sought support from the Axis powers (primarily Japan) to organize an army that could help achieve Indian independence. Bose gave the INA the slogan “Chalo Delhi” to inspire the troops to march towards Delhi to overthrow British rule. 153","PW-1758":"As the partition of India became imminent in 1947, Mahatma Gandhi opposed the idea of dividing the country along communal lines. Gandhi proposed that Muhammad Ali Jinnah, the leader of the Muslim League, be invited to form the central government of India as a last-ditch effort to avoid partition. Gandhi believed this move would address Jinnah’s demand for Muslim representation and avert the division of the country. However, this suggestion was not accepted by either the Congress or the Muslim League. 154","PW-1759":"The native state of Tripura, a princely state during British rule, became involved in the freedom movement due to its geographical proximity to Bengal and the political dynamics of the early 20th century. The native state of Tripura became part of the freedom movement early in the 20th century because some groups in the state were against the king’s rule and his support from the British. They wanted to challenge the king’s power and reduce British influence in the region. These efforts were linked to the larger fight for India’s independence, inspired by the freedom movement in nearby Bengal and other areas. 155","PW-1760":"The Quit India Movement (August Movement) of 1942 was a significant phase in India’s struggle for independence. The movement saw widespread participation from various sections of society, including students, workers, and peasants. Assertion (A) is true: Lord Linlithgow considered the Quit India Movement a significant challenge, as it led to widespread uprisings, destruction of infrastructure, and disruption of administration. Reason (R) is true: In regions like Bihar, Uttar Pradesh, Bengal, and Maharashtra, peasants actively participated, leading to violent clashes with British authorities, giving the movement a mass character. Reason (R) correctly explains the Assertion (A). UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 106 156","PW-1761":"During the time of India’s partition in 1947, as the Indian subcontinent was divided into India and Pakistan, there were various political movements and regional aspirations for different parts of British India. Some groups in Punjab, including the Akali Dal, proposed that the province should remain united and independent instead of being split between India and Pakistan. They were worried about the division of the region. However, this idea was not accepted, and Punjab was divided between India and Pakistan. 157","PW-1762":"The Balkan Plan refers to a proposal that aimed at dividing India which was one of the strategies considered to address the political situation leading to the partition of India in 1947. The idea was inspired by the division of Balkan States in Europe. Balkan Plan (1947) was the brainchild of Lord Mountbatten. He proposed dividing India into smaller regions along religious lines and transferring power to separate provinces with Punjab and Bengal given the option to vote for partition of their provinces. 158","PW-1763":"Subhash Chandra Bose saw World War II as an opportunity for India to leverage Britain’s vulnerability. He believed the war could be exploited to push for India’s independence, leading to his efforts to collaborate with Axis powers like Germany and Japan to form the Indian National Army (INA). 160","PW-1764":"Sardar Patel was one of the prominent Congress leaders who supported the Cabinet Mission Plan. He saw it as a pragmatic approach to achieving independence while preserving India’s unity, even though it meant compromises like grouping provinces.  Mahatma Gandhi was skeptical of the Cabinet Mission Plan as he felt it complicated India’s unity by endorsing groupings and did not adequately ensure safeguards for weaker sections.  Jawaharlal Nehru initially supported the plan but later expressed reservations, particularly about the grouping of provinces, which he felt could weaken a strong central authority. Maulana Abul Kalam Azad supported the Cabinet Mission Plan but was more cautious about its implementation, especially due to the communal tensions it could exacerbate. 161","PW-1765":"The Quit India Movement (1942), also called the August Movement, saw widespread participation from peasants, students, and workers, making it a mass struggle. A is true: The Quit India Movement (1942 saw unprecedented participation from all sections of society, and its intensity led Lord Linlithgow to compare it to the Sepoy Mutiny of 1857. R is true: Peasantry participation was significant in regions like Bihar, Uttar Pradesh, and Bengal, as the movement mobilized rural masses. R the correct explanation of A: The scale of peasantry uprising during August Movement made it clear that independence was imminent, and rebellion against British rule was very serious. 162","PW-1766":" The August Offer (1940) was a constitutional framework proposed by the British government to gain Indian cooperation in WWII, offering Dominion status after the war. It was rejected by Indian leaders.  The Quit India Movement (1942) was a mass civil disobedience movement launched by the Indian National Congress demanding an immediate end to British rule.  The I.N.A Trial (1945-46) of Indian National Army officers at the Red Fort led to widespread public outrage and rise in nationalist sentiment.  The Royal Indian Naval Ratings’ Revolt (1946) by Indian naval personnel in Bombay and other cities, demonstrated the growing discontent among the armed forces. 163","PW-1767":"Lord Mountbatten was appointed Viceroy of India in 1947 with the task of overseeing the transfer of power from British rule. His primary goal was to keep India united, but escalating communal tensions and Jinnah’s demand for Pakistan made this impossible. After failed negotiations for a united India, Mountbatten proposed the 3rd June Plan, which led to the partition of India into two nations—India and Pakistan. He expedited the process, ensuring the transfer of power was completed by August 15, 1947, despite the challenges posed by widespread violence and political divisions. 164","PW-1768":"The Cripps Mission (1942) was a British initiative to secure Indian support for World War II by offering limited self-government, but it was rejected by Indian leaders due to its insufficient concessions on independence. A is true: The Congress rejected the Cripps proposals because they offered dominion status instead of full independence and allowed provinces to opt out of the Indian union, which could lead to fragmentation. R is true: The rejection of the proposals had nothing to do with the racial composition of the Cripps Mission. There was no protest from Congress or other parties about the all white composition of the Mission. Instead, it was due to the lack of substantive promises for Indian self-rule. R is not a correct explanation of A: The Cripps Mission was rejected by the Indian National Congress primarily because it did not offer full independence, lacked clear provisions for self- rule, and did not address the concerns of both the Congress and the Muslim League in a satisfactory manner. 165","PW-1769":"Liyaqat Ali Khan was given the Finance portfolio in the 1946 Interim Government, granting the Muslim League significant influence over India’s financial policy. Other portfolios in Interim Government 1946:  The Foreign Affairs portfolio was held by Jawaharlal Nehru.  Sardar Vallabhbhai Patel was in charge of the Home Affairs, Information, and Broadcasting portfolio.  The Defence portfolio was assigned to Baldev Singh. 166","PW-1770":"The Indian National Congress reluctantly agreed to the partition in 1947 primarily to prevent large-scale communal riots and bloodshed. Communal tensions between Hindus and Muslims had escalated to violent proportions, particularly after the Direct Action Day in 1946 and the failure of attempts to find a united solution. Congress leaders, including Nehru and Patel realized that accepting partition was the only way to avoid a full-scale civil war and ensure a relatively peaceful transition to independence. 167","PW-1771":"At the time of India’s Independence in 1947, Mahatma Gandhi was not a member of the Congress. He had distanced himself from formal political roles and the organizational activities of the Indian National Congress, instead, he focused on social reform, communal harmony, and grassroots movements. Gandhi was deeply involved in peace efforts during the communal riots that accompanied Partition, working tirelessly in Bengal and Delhi to curb violence and promote unity. Despite his lack of an official role, he remained a guiding moral force for Congress leaders. 168","PW-1772":"The British Prime Minister Ramsay MacDonald had proposed separate electorates for the Depressed Classes in the Communal Award, which Gandhi opposed, fearing it would fragment Indian society permanently and weaken the national movement. The Poona Pact (1932, not 1934) was an agreement between Mahatma Gandhi and Dr. B.R. Ambedkar, mediated by the British Government, to resolve the issue of separate electorates for the Depressed Classes (Harijans). Option (d) is correct: The pact provided for joint electorates with reserved seats for the Depressed Classes in the general constituencies instead of separate electorates. This ensured representation for the Depressed Classes while maintaining social unity. The number of reserved seats in provincial legislatures was increased, and provisions were made for their upliftment. 169","PW-1773":"","PW-1774":"The Government of India Act, 1947 was the legal framework that formalized the partition of British India into two independent dominions, India and Pakistan, marking the end of British rule. Lord Mountbatten, as the last Viceroy of India, oversaw the implementation of the Act, ensuring the transfer of power and the division of territories on August 15, 1947. A is false: British sovereignty did not continue in free India after August 15, 1947. India became a dominion within the Commonwealth, and sovereignty transferred to the Indian people. R is true: Lord Mountbatten, the last British Governor-General, was appointed for a transitional period post-independence, but this does not imply the continuation of British sovereignty. 171","PW-1775":"Referring to the 1930–32 meetings as three separate conferences is technically incorrect because they were essentially three sessions of the same conference, aiming to address the same issues, such as constitutional reforms and representation. The Indian National Congress boycotted the First and Third Conferences but participated in the Second, represented by Gandhi. The fragmented nature of Indian representation and the British Government’s control over the proceedings also reduced their significance. 172","PW-1776":"Acharya Narendra Dev was a prominent leader of the Congress Socialist Party (CSP), formed in 1934 as a socialist wing within the Indian National Congress. He, along with leaders like Jayaprakash Narayan and Ram Manohar Lohia, advocated for socialism as a means of achieving socio-economic equality in India. The CSP worked within the Congress framework to influence its policies toward socialism and economic justice. 173","PW-1777":"","PW-1778":"The Covenanted Civil Service of India, later known as the Indian Civil Service, was created by Lord Cornwallis during his tenure as Governor-General (1786–1793). He reorganized India’s administration, introducing a system where British recruits were sent to India as high-paid administrators with various privileges. Civil Services in British India were classified as covenanted and uncovenanted services on the basis of the nature of work, pay-scales and appointing authority. 175","PW-1779":"","PW-1780":"The Vernacular Press Act was enacted in 1878 by Lord Lytton to curb the growing influence of Indian-language newspapers that were critical of British rule. It imposed strict controls on the press, particularly targeting vernacular (Indian- language) publications. However, Lord Ripon, who succeeded Lytton as Viceroy, repealed the Act in 1882, marking a significant step towards promoting press freedom and reducing colonial censorship in India. 177","PW-1781":"A is matched with 2: Lord Macdonald was responsible for the Communal Award in 1932, which introduced separate electorates for different communities. B is matched with 3: Lord Linlithgow is associated with the August Offer (1940), which was a British offer to India’s political leaders during World War II to gain support. C is matched with 1: Lord Dalhousie is known for implementing the Doctrine of Lapse in the 1840s, which allowed the British to annex Indian princely states if a ruler died without a male heir. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 110 D is matched with 4: Lord Chelmsford is associated with the introduction of Dyarchy through the Government of India Act 1919, which divided the government into areas of central and provincial responsibilities. 180","PW-1782":"The Forward policy was a set of foreign policies that aimed to extend British control and influence in the region, especially towards Afghanistan and Central Asia. It was adopted during Viceroyalty of Lord Lytton (1876-1880) in India. The policy involved securing control of targeted territories through invasion, annexation, or by creating compliant buffer states. Other notable events that took place during his tenure as Viceroy include Great Indian Famine, Second Anglo-Afghan War, Arms Act, Vernacular Press Act. 181","PW-1783":"Lord Wellesley ensured British dominance in India. Serving as Governor-General from 1798 to 1805, Wellesley was known for his aggressive expansionist policies. He implemented the Doctrine of Subsidiary Alliance, signed treaties with Indian states, and pursued territorial acquisition, greatly expanding British control over India amidst European turmoil. Lord Wellesley’s Subsidiary alliance system was applied for taking over the administration of Tanjore and Carnatic. He also concluded the Treaty of Bassein (1802) with the Peshwas. 182","PW-1784":"The statement is attributed to Lord Curzon, who served as the Viceroy of India from 1899 to 1905. This remark reflects his deep opposition to the Indian National Congress (INC) and his belief in maintaining British control over India. Appointment of Police Commission (1902) under Sir Andrew Frazer to review police administration, Partition of Bengal (1905) and curbing press freedom through Official Secrets Act (1904) were other instances of Lord Curzon’s suppressing acts during his tenure. While Curzon believed his policies would weaken the Congress, many of his actions galvanized the nationalist movement instead. The backlash led to the Swadeshi Movement and laid the groundwork for a more united and organized fight for Indian independence. 183","PW-1785":"Thugs were a secret criminal network in India, active between the 14th to the 19th century, known for their ritualistic strangulation of travelers to rob them. Captain William Henry Sleeman was a British officer in India who played a key role in the suppression of the Thuggee cult in the early 19th century. He was appointed during Lord William Bentick's tenure, during Lord William Bentinck's tenure (1828– 1835). He led several successful campaigns against the thugs, and his efforts led to the eventual dismantling of the organization. 184","PW-1786":" Governor-General of Presidency of Fort William in Bengal (under Regulating Act, 1773): This title refers to the position created by the Regulating Act of 1773, with Warren Hastings as the first appointee. However, in this case, Lord Cornwallis (Charles Cornwallis) is relevant because of his significant tenure under the same title.  Governor-General of India (under Charter Act, 1833): The Charter Act of 1833 centralized administration and established the title of Governor-General of India, with Lord William Bentinck being the first. In this context, Lord Dalhousie (James Andrew Broun-Ramsay), a later Governor-General, aligns with this description.  Governor-General and Viceroy of India (under Indian Council Act, 1858): The Indian Council Act of 1858 replaced the East India Company’s rule with direct Crown governance. Lord Canning was the first to hold this dual role. The relevant entry in the list is Lord Minto (Gilbert John Elliot-Murray- Kynynmound).  Governor-General and Crown Representative (under Government of India Act, 1935): This Act retained the Governor-General as the C","PW-1787":"","PW-1788":"The “Instrument of Instructions” from the Government of India Act of 1935 were important guidelines from the British Government. They directed the Governors in British India on how to use their discretionary powers. In 1950, these guidelines influenced the Directive Principles of State Policy in the Constitution of India (Part IV). These principles help the State create laws and policies that improve people’s welfare and build a fair and just society. 187","PW-1789":"The Constituent Assembly was partly elected and partly nominated. The elections for the Constituent Assembly(Total 389 seats) was held in 1946 according to the plan of the Cabinet Mission. The elected members were indirectly elected by the members of the Provincial Legislative Assembly. The election happened based on Proportional Representation through Single Transferable Vote. Princely States nominated their representatives. 188","PW-1790":"Dr. B.R. Ambedkar initially formed the Scheduled Castes Federation Party but lost the Bombay Presidency election to an Indian National Congress (INC) candidate . He was a prominent leader of the Dalits and an expert in law and economics. In 1946, after his defeat in the Bombay elections, Dr. B.R. Ambedkar was elected to the Constituent Assembly from a seat in West Bengal. He later became the Chairman of the Drafting Committee responsible for framing the Indian Constitution and served as the first Minister of Law and Justice in independent India’s Cabinet. 12. ADMINISTRATIVE CHANGES AFTER 1857 189","PW-1791":"Statement (1) is incorrect: The Montagu-Chelmsford Reforms of 1919 introduced a diarchy system in provincial governments, where key areas like finance and law & order remained under British control, while other departments were transferred to Indian ministers. It also paved the way for the creation of a bicameral legislature at the centre. It recommended the voting rights to women in limited numbers to be extended on the basis of property, tax or education. Statement (2) is correct: Government of India Act, 1935 divided the powers between the Centre and provinces. It abolished dyarchy in the provinces and introduced ‘provincial autonomy’ in its place, while adopting the dyarchy at the Centre. It further extended the principle of communal representation to the depressed classes (Scheduled Castes), women and labour (workers). SUPER HINT For S1, Even in Britain, women above 21 did not get full voting rights until 1928. So the idea that “all women above 21” in India — a colony — were granted voting rights in 1919 is logically absurd. Likely false. 190","PW-1792":"The Charter Act of 1813 renewed the East India Company’s charter for another 20 years, ending its monopoly on trade with India (except for trade in tea and opium with China). It also allocated funds for promoting education in India and acknowledged the need for social and economic reforms. It gave missionaries permission to travel to India was one of the key components of this law. Statement 1 is correct: The Charter Act 1813 ended the trade monopoly of the East India Company except for the trade in tea, opium, and with China. Statement 2 is correct: company’s territories in India came under the sovereignty of the British Government through this Act. Statement 3 is incorrect: The revenue of India was controlled by the British parliament through Pitt’s India Act 1784. 191","PW-1793":"The Government of India Act, 1935 divided powers between the Centre and provinces into three lists: Federal (59 items), Provincial (54 items), and Concurrent (36 items). It granted residuary powers to the Governor-General, who could authorize either legislature to legislate on such matters. 192","PW-1794":"The Government of India Act, 1919 introduced dyarchy at the provincial level, dividing executive powers between the Governor and elected ministers. The system increased provincial authority, with the Governor as the chief executive. Subjects were divided into two lists: reserved and transferred. The reserved list (e.g., law and order, finance) was managed by the Governor and his executive council. The transferred list (e.g., education, health) was administered by ministers from the elected legislative council. This dual scheme of governance was known as ‘dyarchy’. 193","PW-1795":"The Butler Committee, chaired by Sir Harcourt Butler in 1927, investigated the relationship between British India and the princely states. Its 1929 report reaffirmed the doctrine of paramountcy, clarifying that the British Raj’s control over the princely states was not just contractual but a dynamic, evolving relationship shaped by history and policy. The committee recommended that the financial relationship between the Raj and the states should be fair. 194","PW-1796":"Montague-Chelmsford Proposals had the scheme of constitutional reforms, known as the Montagu-Chelmsford (or Mont-Ford) Reforms, which led to the enactment of the Government of India Act of 1919. It introduced diarchy (rule of two individuals/parties) at the provincial government level. The diarchy was implemented in eight provinces: Assam, Bengal, Bihar and Orissa, Central Provinces, United Provinces, Bombay, Madras and Punjab. 195","PW-1797":"The Montagu-Chelmsford Reforms which became the Government of India Act in 1919, defined the jurisdiction of the central and provincial governments. It introduced dyarchy in eight provinces, where executive powers were shared between the Governor and elected ministers. Subjects were divided into ‘reserved’ (e.g., law, finance) managed by the Governor and his council, and ‘transferred’ (e.g., education, health) handled by ministers from the legislative council, increasing provincial authority. 196","PW-1798":"Queen Victoria’s Proclamation (1858) ended East India Company rule, bringing India directly under British Crown control. Lord Canning became the first Viceroy and Governor- General. Statement 1 is correct: The proclamation was read out by Lord Canning at a durbar held on November 1, 1858 at Allahabad. The proclamation put an end to the era of further expansion of the British Empire in India. Statement 2 is correct: Queen Victoria’s proclamation of 1858 aimed at ending the rule of the company and transferring all the powers to the British crown after the 1857 revolt. It also promised non- interference in the religious affairs of the people, grant of equal protection of law and respect for ancient rights and customs of the people. Statement 3 is incorrect: Queen Victoria’s Proclamation (1858) is aimed at improving the administrative machinery of supervision and control over the Indian government. Modern History 113 197","PW-1799":"The Ilbert Bill Controversy (1883) arose from Lord Ripon’s attempt to reform India’s legal system. Under the existing laws, a European could be tried only by a European judge or magistrate, which was seen as discriminatory against Indian judges. To end this injustice, C.P. Ilbert proposed a bill in 1883 that would allow Indian judges to try Europeans. The proposal faced strong opposition from the European community in India. The Ilbert Bill controversy made educated Indians aware of the need of an all Indian organisation, resulting in the formation of Indian National Congress in 1885. 198","PW-1800":"Statements 1 and 3 are correct: GoI Act 1919 introduced the dual scheme of governance known as ‘dyarchy’ in the executive government of the provinces. By demarcating and separating the central and provincial subjects, it relaxed the central control over the provinces. It introduced bicameralism and direct elections in the country. The devolution of legislative authority by the center to the provinces was done in the Government of India Act, 1919. Statement 2 is incorrect: The Indian Council Act, 1909 or the Morley-Minto Reforms introduced separate communal electorates for Muslims. It was put into place to appease the moderates (in Congress) and introduces separate electorates based on religion. Lord Minto came to be known as “Father of the Communal Electorate in India”. 199","PW-1801":"The Government of India Act, 1935 divided powers between the Centre and provinces into three lists: Federal (59 items), Provincial (54 items), and Concurrent (36 items). It abolished dyarchy in provinces, replacing it with provincial autonomy, while retaining it at the Centre. The Act introduced bicameralism in six provinces and extended communal representation to Scheduled Castes, women, and labor. It also abolished the Council of India created by GoI Act 1858. 200","PW-1802":"Sir William Wedderburn was President of INC in Bombay, 1889 and Allahabad, 1910 sessions. Together with Dadabhai Naoroji and other supporters of India, Sir William Wedderburn and W. S. Caine established the “Indian Parliamentary Committee” in 1893. The Indian Parliamentary Committee’s mission is to lobby the House of Commons for political reforms in India. In 1895, Wedderburn represented India on the Welby Commission (i.e. Royal Commission) on Indian Expenditure. 201","PW-1803":"The British introduced modern communication systems in colonial India to enhance administrative efficiency and control. They developed an extensive railway network, postal system, and telegraph lines to facilitate military movement, trade, and governance. These innovations unified diverse regions, boosted economic integration, and significantly influenced India’s modernization, despite serving colonial interests. Majority of developments happened under the rule of Governor General Dalhousie. Statement 1 is correct: The first telegraph line in India was laid between Kolkata (formerly Calcutta) and Diamond Harbour in 1850. It became operational in 1851. Statement 2 is correct: The first Export Processing Zone in India was set up in Kandla, Gujarat, in 1965. It was established to promote exports and boost foreign trade. 202","PW-1804":"Statement 1 is incorrect: Charter Act of 1853 did not abolish the East India Company’s monopoly of Indian trade. The company’s monopoly on trade with India was abolished earlier by the Charter Act of 1813, and the monopoly on trade with China ended with the Charter Act of 1833. The Charter Act of 1853 primarily focused on restructuring the administration of India and introduced a merit-based civil service. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 114 Statement 2 is correct: Government of India Act, 1858 abolished the rule of the East India Company after the revolt of 1857 and transferred the administration of India directly to the British Crown. It marked the beginning of the British Raj. 203","PW-1805":"The Revolt of 1857, also known as the First War of Indian Independence, marked a major uprising against British rule in India. Triggered by political, economic, and social grievances, it united soldiers, peasants, and rulers. Option (d) is correct: Tantia Tope, originally named Ramchandra Panduranga, was a prominent leader of the 1857 Revolt from Kanpur, alongside Nana Sahib and Azimullah Khan. Betrayed by Mansingh, Raja of Narwar, loyal to the Scindia of Gwalior who opposed the revolt, Tantia Tope was captured and hanged on April 18, 1859. 204","PW-1806":"Kunwar Singh, a prominent leader of the Revolt of 1857, belonged to Jagdispur, located in present-day Bihar. He was a key figure in the rebellion and is remembered for his bravery and leadership despite being in his 80s at the time of the revolt. Other prominent leaders: Leader of 1857 Revolt Location Mangal Pandey Barrackpore Bahadur Shah Zafar Delhi General Bakht Khan Delhi Tantia tope Kanpur Azimullah Kanpur Begum Hazrat Mahal Lucknow Maulvi Ahmadullah Faizabad 205","PW-1807":"Chittor (located in present-day Rajasthan) was not strongly affected by the Revolt of 1857. The revolt had a strong impact on regions like Jhansi, Jagdishpur, and Lucknow, where prominent leaders such as Rani Lakshmibai, Kunwar Singh, and Begum Hazrat Mahal played significant roles in the rebellion. However, Chittor remained largely untouched by the uprising. Major Centers affected by Revolt of 1857: 206","PW-1808":"The Ilbert Bill was introduced in 1883 by Sir Courtenay Ilbert, the then Law Member of the Viceroy’s Council, to amend the criminal procedure code in British India. The bill sought to allow Indian judges, including the district magistrates, to try British offenders in criminal cases. At the time, only British judges had the authority to try European offenders. The proposal faced strong opposition from the European community in India, leading to protests. The British government eventually modified the bill, allowing Indian judges to try Europeans only if they consented. The controversy highlighted racial discrimination in colonial India. 207","PW-1809":"Pre-Congress associations like Madras Association, Indian Association were, active before the formation of the Indian National Congress in 1885, laid the groundwork for India’s political awakening. These associations united educated Indians to demand reforms and fostered early nationalist sentiment. Option (d) is correct: The Poona Sarvajanik Sabha, established in 1867 in Pune, aimed to promote education, social welfare, and political reforms in India. In 1875, it submitted a petition to the House of Commons, demanding direct representation for India in the British Parliament. The petition argued that India, as part of the British Empire, deserved a voice in the legislative process to address Indian concerns and prevent policies harmful to its progress. Modern History 115 208","PW-1810":"The Indian Councils Act of 1861 strengthened the Viceroy’s authority over his Executive Council by replacing corporate functioning with a portfolio system. In the portfolio system individual members of the Viceroy’s Executive Council were assigned specific departments to manage, replacing the previous collective decision-making process. This shift strengthened the Viceroy’s authority, enabling more efficient governance. Before the Act, the Council functioned collectively but after it, the Viceroy had greater centralized control with Council members responsible for key areas like finance, law, and home affairs. This reorganization reinforced British control over colonial governance. 209","PW-1811":"The remark, “In this instance we could not play off the Mohammedans against the Hindus,” by Sir Charles Aitchison, refers to the Revolt of 1857. During the rebellion, the British were frustrated because their usual strategy of dividing Hindus and Muslims was ineffective. Instead of fighting each other, both communities united against the British, which posed a significant challenge to British rule. This unity between Hindus and Muslims during the revolt was unexpected and disrupted British efforts to exploit religious divisions. 210","PW-1812":"The Educated Indians largely remained neutral and regarded the Revolt of 1857 as a reactionary movement that sought to restore the feudal order and resist the social, political, and economic changes brought about by modernity. They viewed the uprising as a protest by traditional forces, including rulers, landlords, and soldiers, who were unwilling to adapt to the evolving world. These educated individuals, exposed to Western ideas, had high hopes that British rule would bring about an era of modernization through reforms like education, infrastructure development, and legal systems. 13. ECONOMIC POLICIES OF THE BRITISH 211","PW-1813":"Statement 1 is incorrect : In Ryotwari system the government revenue was a fixed amount, irrespective of crop output, and was to be paid in cash. Thus during periods of bad crops or low prices the peasants were forced to pay the land revenue, even if it required borrowing from moneylenders . Statement 2 is correct : In the Zamindari system the revenue was invariable, regardless of the harvest, and had to be paid punctually. According to the Sunset Law, if payment did not come in by sunset of the specified date, the zamindari was liable to be auctioned. SUPER HINT For S1, would a colonial revenue system — dependent on land tax — really exempt peasants systematically in bad years? That’s wishful logic, not colonial logic. Hence likely false. 212","PW-1814":"Pair 1 is incorrectly matched: Aurang is a Persian term referring to a warehouse where goods are collected before being sold. Pair 2 is correctly matched: The term Banian (or Banyan) was used during the colonial period to refer to Indian agents or intermediaries who acted as local representatives or agents for European trading companies, including the East India Company. They helped the company in business dealings, acted as middlemen, and facilitated trade. Pair 3 is correctly matched: A Mirasidar was a landowner or hereditary holder of land in South India under the Ryotwari settlement system. The East India Company recognized mirasdars as the only proprietors of land, dismissing tenants’ rights completely. They acted as a designated revenue payer of the state. 213","PW-1815":"The Old World refers to the continents of Europe, Asia, and Africa, known to Europeans before the discovery of the Americas. The New World refers to the Americas, including North and South America, which were “discovered” by Europeans after Christopher Columbus’s voyages in the late 15th century. Tobacco, cocoa, and rubber were domesticated in the ‘New World’ and introduced into the ‘Old World’ through the European explorers in the late medieval or early modern era. The Columbian exchange was the widespread transfer of plants, animals, culture, human populations, technology, diseases, and ideas between the Americas, West Africa, and the Old World in the 15th and 16th centuries. SUPER HINT Sugarcane, cotton, and wheat are all Old World crops — deduced entirely through ecological fit, civilizational association, and climate logic. Giving option A as correct. 215","PW-1816":"","PW-1817":"The East India Company was originally formed in Britain for pursuing trade with the East Indies in Southeast Asia. It ended up trading mainly with the Indian subcontinent and China, where the main items of trade were cotton, silk, tea and opium. Also Bengal produced saltpeter, a key ingredient for making gunpowder, which was in high demand for both domestic use and export. 217","PW-1818":"Option (c) is correct: Permanent Settlement  Started by Lord Cornwallis in 1793.  Prevalent in Bengal, Bihar, Orissa, Varanasi (United Provinces), and Northern Karnataka.  Covered 19% of British India.  A new section of Zamindars was appointed who would provide 10/11th part of the revenue collected to the British while keeping the remaining. Modern History 117 Ryotwari System  Started by Thomas Munro and Alexander Reed in 1820.  Started in the Baramahal district of Tamil Nadu and later spread to Madras, parts of Bombay, East Bengal, Assam and Coorg (Karnataka).  Covered 51% of British India.  Ryots (farmers) were given ownership and other rights over the land and were required to pay the revenue directly to the government. Involved high taxes and strict collection. Mahalwari System  The Mahalwari system was introduced by Holt Mackenzie in 1822.  Prevalent in United Provinces, Central Provinces and Punjab.  Covered 30% of British India.  The village or mahal served as the unit for collecting revenue. Village land belonged to the community and it was the responsibility of t","PW-1819":"The Trade Disputes Act 1929 was a British Act of Parliament passed to regulate industrial disputes in India. The main objective of the Act was to make provisions for the establishment of Courts of Inquiry(tribunals) and Boards of Conciliation with a view to investigate and settle trade disputes. Strikes and lockouts in public utility services were prohibited without prior notice. Such strikes were illegal and punishable under the Act. Motilal Nehru called it “ The slavery of India Bill”. 219","PW-1820":"Statement 1 is incorrect: The Factory Act of 1881, passed during Lord Ripon’s tenure, aimed to improve working conditions in factories using mechanical power and employing at least 100 workers. It prohibited the employment of children under 7, limited children aged 7-12 to 9-hour workdays, and required dangerous machinery to be properly fenced. However, it did not address the formation of trade unions. Statement 2 is correct: Narayan Meghaji Lokhande (1848– 1897) is regarded as the father of the trade union movement in India. He worked to improve the conditions of textile mill workers and took courageous stands on caste and communal issues. He played a key role in reducing daily working hours from 16 to 10 hours in mills. 220","PW-1821":"Dadabhai Naoroji, R.C. Dutt, Ranade, Gokhale, and G. Subramania Iyer were among the moderate leaders who established Indian nationalism on the principles of anti- imperialism by formulating the first comprehensive economic critique of colonialism. Option (d) is correct: Dadabhai Naoroji (Grand Old man of India) in “Poverty and UnBritish Rule in India” propounded Drain of Wealth Theory. Romesh Chandra Dutta in “The Economic History of India” pointed to the absence of protection for India’s infant industries, and the negative implications of even constructive efforts like the railways which facilitated the import of British manufactured goods.G. V. Joshi pointed out that the development in India was like a subsidy to the British Industries. Justice Mahadev Govind Ranade, G. Subramaniam Iyer, G.K. Gokhale etc. examined every facet of the economy and subjected the entire range of economic issues and colonial economic policies to minute scrutiny. 221","PW-1822":"Statement 1 is correct: The Ryotwari System was started by Thomas Munro and Alexander Reed. It was started in the Baramahal district of Tamil Nadu and later spread to Madras, parts of Bombay, East Bengal, Assam and Coorg. Ryots were required to pay the revenue directly to the government Statement 2 is correct: Ryots (farmers) were given the ownership and other rights (Pattas) over the land. Statement 3 is correct: The Ryotwari System involved high taxes (50% in dryland and 60% in wetland) and the taxes had to be paid regardless of the harvest, leading to peasant distress. The land was surveyed and an assessment for its productivity before imposing taxes. This assessment was based on the quality and size of the land, and the tax was usually a fixed portion of the estimated crop yield. Mahalwari System Permanent Settlement Ryotwari Settlement Punjab and UP Bombay and Madras Bengal Bihar and Orissa UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 118 222","PW-1823":"Statement 1 is correct: Dadabhai Naoroji (Grand Old man of India) wrote the “Poverty and UnBritish Rule in India” in which he propounded The Drain of Wealth Theory and exposed the economic exploitation of Indians by the British. Statement 2 is incorrect: Swami Dayanand Saraswati, Swami Vivekananda, etc. interpreted the ancient texts and restored the self confidence of Indians, not Dadabhai Naoroji. Swami Dayananda Saraswati even gave the call to “go back to vedas”. Statement 3 is incorrect: Raja Rammohan Roy, Ishwar Chandra Vidyasagar, Keshav Chandra Sen, Atmaram Pandurang, etc. emphasized the need for eradication of all social evils before anything else. 223","PW-1824":"Statement 1 is incorrect: After getting the Diwani rights of Bengal, Bihar, and Orissa in 1765 the major aim of the British East India Company was to increase their land revenue collection without caring of its consequences on cultivators and peasants. Statement 2 is incorrect: The first recorded use of Artillery in India is at the Battle of Adoni in 1368 by the Bahamani kings against the Raja of Vijaya-nagar. Statement 3 is incorrect: Tobacco and Red Chillies were introduced by Portuguese not British. 224","PW-1825":"The Permanent Land Revenue Settlement of Bengal was extended to the provinces of Bihar and Orissa by Lord Cornwallis in 1793. The land where the zamindars had previously been responsible for collecting revenue was given to them as ownership. The demand for land revenue was predetermined and out of controlled revenue, 10/11th part was given to the company. Option (d) is correct: The reforms increased the litigation after the introduction of the land settlement system and the main reason for this was the relief at the front of Court Fee and now everybody could drag anybody to the courts. 225","PW-1826":"Dadabhai Naoroji in “Poverty and UnBritish Rule in India” (1901), propounded the Drain of Wealth Theory. It refers to the constant one way flow of wealth from India to England for which India got no return. Home Charges played a significant role in the Drain of Wealth from India. Statement 1 is correct: Funds used to support the India Office in London. Statement 2 is correct: Funds used to pay salaries and pensions of British personnel engaged in India. Statement 3 is incorrect: There are no clear references to using these funds for waging wars outside India by the British. Note: Here official answer given by UPSC is Option (b), However confusion with Statement 3 is understandable. 226","PW-1827":"The Whitley Commission (1929), also known as the Royal Commission on Labour in India, was established by the British colonial government to investigate labour conditions in India. Chaired by Sir William Whitley, its purpose was to examine issues like wages, working hours, and living conditions of industrial workers. It recommended improving labour welfare, establishing labour unions, and creating welfare funds, along with measures for industrial peace, better working conditions, and health and safety improvements for workers. 227","PW-1828":"The Oudh Commercial Bank, founded in 1881 in Faizabad, Uttar Pradesh, was the first Indian-managed bank to be established as a limited liability company. It was created by local businessmen and marked a significant shift in India’s banking sector, which had previously been dominated by the British. The bank’s establishment highlighted the increasing involvement of Indians in economic activities, especially in banking, and it aimed to provide financial services to local industries and trade, representing a milestone in Indian- controlled commercial banking. 228","PW-1829":"The Permanent Settlement of 1793, introduced by Lord Cornwallis. It fixed land revenue that zamindars had to pay to the British government permanently. While it aimed to create a loyal class of landlords, it led to peasant exploitation and failure to issue pattas (land agreements) to farmers due to a lack of effective oversight. The zamindars often did not issue pattas because there was no effective supervision or enforcement by the British government, leaving farmers vulnerable to exploitation. 229","PW-1830":"The British colonial economic model transformed India into a supplier of raw materials like cotton, indigo, and iron ore, which were sent to Britain for processing. India was forced to sell these materials at low prices and buy British-made goods at higher prices. Industrial development in India was discouraged to prevent competition with British industries, keeping India dependent on Britain for finished goods and limiting its own industrial growth. The lack of heavy industries discouraged independent industrial development. 230","PW-1831":"Imperial Preference was a British colonial trade policy that granted preferential treatment to British goods in its colonies, including India. British goods were sold at lower tariffs or duty-free, while colonies like India were required to sell raw materials to Britain at favorable prices. This system subordinated the economic interests of colonies, prevented the development of Indian industries, and ensured Britain’s economic dominance. It also reinforced political control, making colonies dependent on Britain for both manufactured goods and trade. 231","PW-1832":"The Drain Theory was propounded by Dadabhai Naoroji arguing that the British colonial rule in India resulted in the economic drain of wealth from India to Britain. Naoroji contested that a significant portion of India’s resources, including revenue and raw materials, were being transferred to Britain without equivalent returns. Sir Syed Ahmed Khan had a moderate approach and believed that British Rule could benefit India particularly in terms of education and infrastructure. He advocated for cooperation with the British and emphasized the need for Indian Muslims to adopt Western education and progress within the colonial framework. Supporters of the Drain Theory were Dadabhai Naoroji,R.C. Dutt, M.G. Ranade etc. 14. DEVELOPMENT OF EDUCATION 232","PW-1833":"Ishwar Chandra Vidyasagar (1820-1891) was appointed as the secretary of the governing body of Bethune School/ College. The Bethune Female School, established in 1849 in Kolkata (then Calcutta) was one of the first schools in India dedicated to the education of girls. It was founded by John Elliot Drinkwater Bethune, a prominent social reformer and advocate for women's education in India. Vidyasagar was a strong advocate for women's rights and education, and his involvement with the Bethune School was part of his broader efforts to reform Indian society, including his campaigns for widow remarriage and the abolition of child marriage. It was mainly due to his efforts that the Hindu Widows’ Remarriage Act, 1856 was passed. 233","PW-1834":"Fort William College was established in 1800 by Lord Wellesley, the Governor-General of India in Calcutta (now Kolkata). The primary purpose of the college was to train British civil servants in Indian languages, customs, and laws to improve the efficiency of the East India Company's administration in India. Lord Wellesley recognized that British officials often lacked knowledge of Indian languages, culture, and traditions which hindered effective governance. The college was designed to train newly recruited British civilians in Indian languages (such as Persian, Sanskrit, Arabic, and regional languages) and familiarize them with local customs and laws. He believed that a well-trained administrative cadre would help the East India Company govern India more effectively and reduce reliance on Indian intermediaries. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 120 234","PW-1835":"Wood’s Dispatch (1854) is known as the Magna Carta of English Education in India. Under this government was to take up the responsibility for the Education of masses. It provided for hierarchy of Educational Institutions i.e. three tier education system. It also emphasised on Female, Vocational Education and teachers’ training. The Dispatch proposed secular education in Government Institutions. Statement 1 is correct : The Despatch advocated for the introduction of a Grants-in-Aid system to encourage private and missionary enterprises in education. Under this scheme, financial assistance was provided to educational institutions that met certain standards thereby promoting the expansion and improvement of education. Statement 2 is correct : It systematised the hierarchy from vernacular primary schools in villages at bottom, followed by Anglo-Vernacular High Schools and an affiliated college at the district level and affiliating universities in the presidency towns of Calcutta, Bombay and Madras. Statement 3 is incorrect: The Woods Dispatch recommended English as the Medium of Instruct","PW-1836":"Statement 1 is correct: The idea of supporting educated Indians and promoting knowledge of contemporary sciences in the country was enshrined into the Charter Act of 1813. The Charter Act of 1813 permitted Christian missionaries to propagate English and preach their religion. It mandated the company to allocate one lakh rupees annually for the revival and improvement of literature and the promotion of science among the inhabitants of British India. The Act emphasized the need to educate Indians in Western sciences and literature which indirectly laid the foundation for English education. Statement 2 is correct: A “General Committee of Public Instruction” was established by the Governor-General-in- Council in 1823 with the task of allocating one lakh rupees for educational purposes under the Presidentship of Lord Macaulay. Lord Macaulay’s Minute resolved the debate in favor of the Anglicists, directing the limited government resources toward the teaching of Western sciences and literature through the medium of the English language. Statement 3 is correct: The Orientalist-Anglicist Con","PW-1837":"Pair 1 is incorrectly matched: The Sanskrit College at Benaras was founded in 1791 by Jonathan Duncan (not William Jones). The objective was to promote the study of Hindu law and philosophy among the people of Benaras., Sir William Jones was a renowned philologist and scholar who founded the Asiatic Society in 1784 in Calcutta, aiming to encourage Oriental studies. Pair 2 is correctly matched: The Calcutta Madrasah was established by Warren Hastings in 1781 for the study of Muslim law and related subjects to promote the study of Islamic law and jurisprudence among the Muslim population. Pair 3 is incorrectly matched: Fort William College was set up by Lord Richard Wellesley in 1800 for training of civil servants of the Company in languages and customs of Indians. 237","PW-1838":"The Hindu College in Calcutta, established in 1817, played a pivotal role in the advancement of modern education in India. This institution was founded through the collaborative efforts of Raja Rammohan Roy, David Hare, and Alexander Duff. This institution played a pivotal role in the Bengal Renaissance, fostering a generation of thinkers and reformers who significantly influenced Indian society.  Henry Louis Vivian Derozio was an influential teacher and poet at Hindu College. He was known for inspiring free thinking among his students.  Ishwar Chandra Vidyasagar was a renowned scholar and reformer who was associated with Sanskrit College and made significant contributions to education and social reforms in Bengal. He was not connected to the establishment of Hindu College. Modern History 121  Keshab Chandra Sen was prominent leader of the Brahmo Samaj and social reformer. He was educated at Hindu College but did not play a role in its founding. 238","PW-1839":"The Wood’s Despatch of 1854, often called the “Magna Carta of English Education in India,” laid the foundation for modern educational policies in colonial India. Its primary focus was to establish a comprehensive system of education, emphasizing scientific learning and rational thinking over traditional religious teachings. The dispatch included support for education for girls and encouragement for private and missionary involvement. It provided government grants to qualifying schools. In it’s three tier educational hierarchy of Education, vernacular languages for basic education, English and Indian languages at the secondary level and English at the Higher level i.e. at University level (Calcutta, Bombay, and Madras). 239","PW-1840":"The chronological sequence is Macaulay’s Minute (1835) → Wood’s Despatch (1854) → Hunter Commission (1882) → Sargent Report (1944).  Macaulay’s Minute on Education (1835): Drafted by Lord Macaulay, it played a pivotal role in establishing English as the medium of instruction in Indian schools.  Wood’s Education Despatch (1854) was issued by Sir Charles Wood, then President of the Board of Control for the East India Company and stressed on emphasizing scientific learning and rational thinking over traditional religious teachings.  Indian Education Commission (Hunter Commission) (1882) was headed by William Wilson Hunter and recommended that primary education be provided in vernacular languages and highlighted the importance of expanding primary education.  The Sargent Education Report (1944) proposed compulsory and free education for children up to the age of 14, intending to raise educational standards to international levels. 240","PW-1841":"The accurate chronological order is Hindu College (1817), Adam’s Report (1835), Wood’s Despatch (1854), and University of Calcutta (1857).  Founded in 1817, the Hindu College in Calcutta was established through the joint efforts of Raja Rammohan Roy, David Hare, and Alexander Duff.  Adam's Report: William Adam, a Scottish missionary, conducted surveys on indigenous education in Bengal and Bihar between 1819 and 1838. His reports provided a detailed account of the state of education during that period.  The Wood’s Despatch of 1854, known as the “Magna Carta of English Education in India,” established a modern educational framework focused on scientific learning. The dispatch recommended the creation of universities in Calcutta, Madras, and Bombay. Following this recommendation, the University of Calcutta was established on January 24, 1857. 15. PROMINENT PERSONALITIES IN MODERN HISTORY 241","PW-1842":"Sakharam Ganesh Deuskar, originally from Maharashtra but residing in Bengal, was aligned with the ideas of Aurobindo Ghosh. He published Desher Katha in 1904, which sold over 15,000 copies before it was banned by the colonial authorities in 1910. Deuskar is also credited with introducing the Shivaji festival in Bengal. Additionally, he is believed to be the first to use the term ‘swaraj’ in a modern political context, in his 1902 pamphlet on Shivaji. Statement 1 and 2 are correct: In overwhelming detail, the book “Desher Katha” summarised the work of M. G. Ranade and D. Naoroji in a popular idiom and warned in its concluding chapter against the colonial state’s “hypnotic conquest of the mind”. “Desher Katha” had an immense repercussion in Bengal, captured the mind of young Bengal and assisted more than anything else in the preparation of the Swadeshi Movement. Statement 3 is incorrect: Deuskar uses the word ‘desh’ in the context of the whole country. SUPER HINT For S3, If ‘desh’ referred only to Bengal, the book’s message wouldn’t inspire national Swadeshi sentiment. That’s a contrad","PW-1843":"Gopal Baba Walangkar (1840-1900) was also known as Gopal Krishna, born into a family of the untouchable Mahar caste in Maharashtra. Gopal Baba Walangkar developed a racial theory to explain the oppression and also published the first journal targeted at the untouchable people. Vital-Vidhvansak (Destroyer of Brahmanical or Ceremonial Pollution), published in 1888 by Walangkar, was among the first journals targeted at the Dalit community, started publishing in 1888. He also wrote articles for Marathi-language newspapers such as Sudharak and Deenbandhu, as well as composed couplets in Marathi that were intended to inspire the people. 245","PW-1844":"Pair 1 is correctly matched: On 30 September, 1932, Mahatma Gandhi founded the All India Anti Untouchability League, to remove untouchability in society. This league for social transformation resonated throughout the nation, including in Bihar, where enthusiastic support was seen. Pair 2 is correctly matched: Sahajanand Saraswati, a prominent peasant leader, was the first President of the All India Kisan Sabha (AIKS), founded in 1936 in Lucknow. The organization aimed to address the issues faced by peasants and advocate for agrarian reforms. Pair 3 is correctly matched: The Self-Respect Movement was started by E.V. Ramaswamy Naicker in Tamil Nadu in 1925 with the aim of destroying the contemporary Hindu social order in its totality and creating a new, rational society without caste. 246","PW-1845":"Pair 1 is correctly matched: All India Liberal Federation was founded by Surendra Nath Banarjea and some of its prominent leaders were Tej Bahadur Sapru, V. S. Srinivasa Sastri and M. R. Jayakar. Tej Bahadur Sapru was one of the presidents of Indian National Liberal Federation. It advocated for gradual constitutional progress and dominion status for India. Pair 2 is correctly matched: K.C. Neogy was a member of the Constituent Assembly of India, a member of the first Cabinet of independent India and the chairman of the first Finance Commission of India. Pair 3 is correctly matched: Puran Chand Joshi was an early leader of the communist movement in India. He served as the first General Secretary of the Communist Party of India from 1935 to 1947, playing a crucial role in shaping the party's direction during a formative period. Modern History 123 247","PW-1846":"The Hind Mazdoor Sabha (HMS), established in 1948, is one of the prominent trade union organizations in India. Founded by notable leaders such as Ashok Mehta, T.S. Ramanujam, and G.G. Mehta, HMS aimed to represent the interests of Indian workers and promote their rights and welfare. The organization played a vital role in advocating for labor reforms, improving working conditions, and securing fair wages for workers across various industries. Other prominent trade unions in India were :  All India Trade Union Congress (AITUC): Founded in 1920 by Lala Lajpat Rai and others, AITUC is one of the oldest trade unions in India and is affiliated with the Communist Party of India (CPI).  Indian National Trade Union Congress (INTUC): Established in 1947 by Sardar Patel, INTUC is associated with the Indian National Congress (INC).  Bharatiya Mazdoor Sangh (BMS) : Founded in 1955 by Dattopant Thengdi, BMS is linked to the Rashtriya Swayamsevak Sangh (RSS) and focuses on the rights and welfare of workers.  Centre of Indian Trade Unions (CITU) : Formed in 1970 by E.M.S. Namboodiripad, P. Sund","PW-1847":"Lala Lajpat Rai was popularly known as Punjab Kesari. He was the INC’s president at the 1920 Calcutta Special Session. In 1921, he founded Servants of the People Society, a non-profit welfare organisation, in Lahore. He also wrote biographies of Mazzini, Garibaldi, Shivaji, and Shrikrishna. He led a non- violent march in protest against the Simon Commission and was brutally assaulted by the police. He succumbed to a heart attack later, with the assault likely contributing to his weakened condition. 249","PW-1848":" Neeldarpan was a Bengali play written in 1860 by Dinabandhu Mitra. It depicted the plight of indigo farmers under British rule, particularly the oppressive system imposed by British planters. The play was later translated into English by Michael Madhusudan Dutt and became influential in the Indigo Revolt  In 1863, Satyendranath Tagore became the first Indian to clear the Indian Civil Services (ICS) Examination. He was the elder brother of Rabindranath Tagore and worked towards administrative and social reforms.  Arya Samaj was founded by Swami Dayanand Saraswati in 1875 in Bombay. It aimed to promote Vedic knowledge and social reform, rejecting idol worship and advocating for women's education.  Bankim Chandra Chattopadhyay wrote Anandamath, a Bengali novel in 1882. It featured the famous song Vande Mataram, which later became an important slogan in the Indian freedom movement. 250","PW-1849":"Pair 1 is correctly matched: Raja Radhakanta Deb was the first President of the British Indian Association while Debendranath Tagore was its secretary. The British Indian Association was one of the earliest political organizations in India, formed by merging the Landholders' Society and the Bengal British India Society. Pair 2 is incorrectly matched: Gazulu Lakshminarasu Chetty (1806–1868) was a merchant, social reformer, and political leader from Madras. However, he did not found the Madras Mahajan Sabha. The Madras Mahajan Sabha (1884) was founded by M. Veeraraghavachari ,P. Rangaiah Naidu,G. Subramania Iyer and others. Pair 3 is correctly matched: Surendranath Banerjee (1848– 1925) was a nationalist leader and one of the early political activists in India. He founded the Indian Association in 1876 in Calcutta. The Indian Association played a crucial role in mobilizing Indians against British policies and was a precursor to the Indian National Congress. 251","PW-1850":"Statement 1 is incorrect: The first woman President of the Indian National Congress was Annie Besant in the 1917 Calcutta Session. Sarojini Naidu became the first Indian woman President of INC in 1925 Kanpur Session. Statement 2 is correct: Badruddin Tyabji (1844–1906) was the first Muslim President of the Indian National Congress. He presided over the third session of the INC in 1887 (Madras Session). He was a progressive leader, reformist, and the first Indian to practice law in the Bombay High Court. 252","PW-1851":"Annie Besant (1847–1933) made her first visit to India as a member of the Theosophical Society. She had embraced Theosophy after meeting Helena Blavatsky in 1889. Following her arrival, the society relocated its headquarters to Adyar, near Madras (now Chennai). Besant went on to serve as the society’s president from 1907 until her passing in 1933. In Benares, she established the Central Hindu College (CHC) and later founded the newspapers New India and Commonweal to promote her ideas and advocacy. Statement 1 is correct: Annie Besant was instrumental in initiating the Home Rule Movement in India. In 1916 she established the All India Home Rule League which advocated for self-governance and dominion status for India within the British Empire. This movement sought to promote political awareness and mobilize Indian citizens towards the cause of self-rule. Statement 2 is incorrect: The Theosophical Society was founded in 1875 in New York by Helena Blavatsky, Henry Olcott, and William Judge. Annie Besant joined in 1889 after meeting Blavatsky and later became its president in 1907 andserv","PW-1852":"Dr. Bhimrao Ramaji Ambedkar was born on April 14, 1891. He started the Bahiskrit Bharat newspaper to address the cause of the depressed classes. In 1942, he was appointed to the Executive Council of the Viceroy as a Labour member, in 1946. At the same time he published his book, Who were Shudras? After Independence, in 1947, he was appointed as a Minister of Law and Justice in Nehru’s first cabinet. Statement 1 is incorrect: The Peasants and Workers Party of India was not founded by Dr. B.R. Ambedkar. It was established in 1947 by leaders like Keshavrao Jedhe and Shankarrao More in Maharashtra. The party primarily focused on the issues of peasants and workers but was not directly associated with Ambedkar or his political movements. Statement 2 is correct : Dr. B.R. Ambedkar founded the All India Scheduled Castes Federation (AISCF) in 1942 to advocate for the rights and representation of Scheduled Castes (Dalits) in India. This party was established to address the social and political marginalization of Dalits and to ensure their participation in the democratic process. Statement 3 is","PW-1853":"Mahatma Gandhi undertook a fast unto death in 1932 primarily to oppose the Communal Award announced by British Prime Minister Ramsay MacDonald. On August 16, 1932, Ramsay MacDonald announced the Communal Award which provided separate electorates for different communities, including Dalits (then termed Depressed Classes). This meant Dalits would vote separately from Hindus in elections, a move opposed by Gandhi as he believed it would divide Hindu society permanently. Mahatama Gandhi saw it as a British tactic of \"divide and rule\" to weaken the unity of Indians. In protest, he began a fast unto death on September 20, 1932, while in Yerwada Jail, Pune. Dr. B.R. Ambedkar eventually negotiated with Gandhi and agreed to the Poona Pact on September 24, 1932. The Poona Pact replaced separate electorates with reserved seats, ensuring fair representation of Dalits in the legislature while keeping the Hindu community intact. 255","PW-1854":"Gopal Krishna Gokhale (1866–1915) was a moderate nationalist, social reformer, and one of the founding leaders of the Indian National Movement. He was a mentor to Mahatma Gandhi and played a key role in influencing early nationalist politics. The British government offered Gokhale the title of Knighthood and a position in the Council of the Secretary of State for India but he chose to decline both honors. His refusal was based on his commitment to India's self-governance, as he believed accepting such honors would mean complicity with colonial rule. He was a strong advocate of constitutional reforms and gradual political progress, promoting Swaraj (self- rule) within the British Empire. 256","PW-1855":"During World War II, Subhas Chandra Bose (1897– 1945) raised an army called the Free Indian Legion (Azad Hind Legion) with the help of Nazi Germany. This was part of his efforts to liberate India from British rule by seeking foreign assistance. In 1941 he escaped from British house arrest in India and reached Germany via Afghanistan and the Soviet Union. In 1942, he formed the Free Indian Legion (also called the \"Legion Freies Indien\" in German) composed of Indian prisoners of war (POWs) captured by German forces in North Africa. This legion was trained by the Nazis and was intended to be deployed in British India through Afghanistan. However, as the war situation changed he shifted his base to Japan in 1943, where he took charge of the Indian National Army (INA), which had been established earlier by Rashbehari Bose. 257","PW-1856":"Aurobindo Ghosh, a prominent figure in the Indian independence movement, provided a scathing critique of the moderate politics of the Indian National Congress in his series of articles titled New Lamps for Old. In these articles, he argued that the moderate approach of relying on petitions, prayers, and constitutional reforms was ineffective in achieving India’s independence. He advocated for a more aggressive and militant approach, including boycotts, strikes, and civil disobedience. 258","PW-1857":"Naoroji, the ‘Grand Old Man of India,’ pioneered the analysis of British rule’s economic impact in his work Poverty and Un-British Rule in India (1901). His theory of economic drain exposed the exploitation of India’s resources by the British, fueling nationalist sentiment. By calling British rule “Un-British,” Naoroji critiqued the hypocrisy of colonial claims, challenging the narrative of British benevolence. His critique laid the foundation for future debates on colonial exploitation and inspired future leaders advocating for India’s self-rule. 259","PW-1858":"J B Kripalani started his career as a teacher and later became the principal of the Gujarat Vidyapith, a university established by Mahatma Gandhi in 1920. He was deeply influenced by Gandhi's ideas and played a significant role in the freedom movement. He was the president of the Indian National Congress during the crucial phase of Indian independence in 1947. 260","PW-1859":"Madame Bhikaji Cama, a Parsi revolutionary who had developed contacts with French socialists worked from Paris and Geneva. She published the journal Bande Mataram. Statement 1 is incorrect: Madam Bhikaji Cama actually unfurled the first version of the Indian National Flag at the Second International Socialist Congress held in Stuttgart, Germany, in 1907, not Paris. The flag was co-designed by Madam Cama, Vinayak Damodar Savarkar and Shyamji Krishna Varma. The flag had green, saffron, and red stripes, with “Vande Mataram” written on it in Devanagari script, and symbols representing different communities of India. Statement 2 is correct: Madam Bhikaji Cama did serve as the private secretary to Dadabhai Naoroji, a key figure in the Indian National Congress and a prominent advocate for India’s independence. Statement 3 is correct: Bhikaji Cama was born into a wealthy Parsi family in Bombay (now Mumbai) in 1861. Her father, Sorabji Framji Patel was a well-known merchant and philanthropist. 261","PW-1860":"Statement 1 is correct: Ishwar Chandra Vidyasagar, a key figure in the Bengali Renaissance, played a significant role in the development of women’s education in India. While he was associated with the Bethune School, which was founded by J.E.D. Bethune in 1849, Vidyasagar’s efforts greatly contributed to the promotion of female education in Bengal. Hence, the statement is correct in associating him with this cause. Statement 2 is correct: Bankim Chandra Chattopadhyay was one of the early notable figures of Indian literature. The first graduate of Calcutta University was actually Bankim Chandra and he received his degree in 1858. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 126 Statement 3 is incorrect: While Keshav Chandra Sen was a prominent social reformer who campaigned against Sati, it was Raja Ram Mohan Roy whose efforts led to the enactment of the Bengal Sati Regulation Act of 1829, which banned the practice of Sati. The law was passed by Governor-General William Bentinck. 262","PW-1861":"Fabianism is a socialist movement that advocates for gradual reforms through parliamentary means, as opposed to revolutionary methods. It was developed by the Fabian Society in the UK, where ideas of democratic socialism were promoted. Annie Besant was a prominent member of the Fabian Society and played a key role in advocating for Fabian principles, which aimed at social reform and the creation of a welfare state. Her efforts were crucial in spreading the ideas of Fabianism through her writings and political activism. Annie Besant popularized the Theosophical Society in among Indians. Through her constant efforts and generous contributions from a few wealthy Indians, she opened the Central Hindu College at Benares in 1898, with Dr. Arthur Richardson as its principal. 263","PW-1862":"Subhash Chandra Bose founded the All India Forward Bloc in 1939 after resigning from the presidency of the Indian National Congress due to ideological differences with Mahatma Gandhi and other Congress leaders. The Forward Bloc was a left- wing nationalist political party aimed at consolidating the radical forces within the Congress and achieving complete independence for India. It’s moto was “All Power to the Indian People”. It mobilized youth, workers, and farmers for direct action against British rule. It mainly attracted radical nationalists, socialists, and workers who were dissatisfied with Congress' moderate policies. 264","PW-1863":"Rabindranath Tagore, the Nobel laureate and poet was knighted by the British Crown in 1915. However, in 1919 following the Jallianwala Bagh massacre and the repressive Rowlatt Act he renounced his Knighthood in a letter to the Viceroy, Lord Chelmsford as an act of powerful protest against British atrocities. His act was widely celebrated as a bold statement of defiance. In a strongly worded letter to the British Viceroy, Tagore wrote: “The time has come when badges of honor make our shame glaring in their incongruous context of humiliation, and I for my part wish to stand shorn of all special distinctions, by the side of my countrymen.” 265","PW-1864":"Maulana Hasrat Mohani, a prominent figure in the Indian freedom movement, was a strong advocate for complete independence from British rule. He was one of the key leaders who pushed for the idea that Swaraj, or self-rule, should be interpreted as absolute freedom, devoid of any foreign influence or control. His stance was a significant departure from the moderate demands for self-governance and paved the way for more radical calls for full sovereignty during the independence struggle. Hasrat Mohani started bringing out a magazine in the name of ‘Urdu-e-Mualla’ in 1903. 266","PW-1865":"The All-India States People’s Conference (AISPC) was established in 1927 as a federation of political movements within the princely states of British India. Its primary aim was to unite these states and create a platform for them to demand political and administrative rights under British rule. In 1939, Jawaharlal Nehru was elected the president of the All-India States People’s Conference. He played a crucial role in advocating for the rights and aspirations of the people in the princely states. 267","PW-1866":"Subhash Chandra Bose, while delivering the presidential address at the 51st Session of the Indian National Congress (INC) in Haripura (1938) proposed the introduction of the Roman script for Hindi to make the language more accessible especially for non-Hindi speakers. Bose believed that adopting the Roman script would help simplify learning Hindi for Indians from different linguistic backgrounds and improve its adaptability. He emphasized that language should not be a barrier in national unity and sought a pragmatic approach to linguistic communication. Most leaders and linguists, including Mahatma Gandhi and Jawaharlal Nehru, opposed the idea of Romanizing Hindi. After independence, the Devanagari script was retained for Hindi, and English was kept as an associate official language to bridge linguistic diversity. 268","PW-1867":"Surendranath Banerji was among the earliest Indians to join the Indian Civil Service (ICS). He successfully passed the ICS exam in 1869 in England and was appointed as an assistant magistrate. Later he was dismissed by the British government on the pretext of a minor procedural issue related to his handling of a case. Many believed that racial discrimination was the real reason behind his dismissal, as British officers were uncomfortable with Indians holding powerful administrative positions. This injustice fueled Banerji’s nationalist spirit, and he dedicated himself to the cause of Indian self-rule. He became a key political leader and co-founded the Indian National Association in 1876 which later merged with the Indian National Congress (INC). 269","PW-1868":"The description perfectly matches Gopal Krishna Gokhale, one of the most respected leaders of the Indian freedom struggle.  Gokhale graduated from Elphinstone College, Bombay (Mumbai), in 1884 at the age of 18. He was one of the first Indian graduates of the university.  He became a professor of history and political economy at Fergusson College, Pune. He also became associate editor of the newspaper 'Sudharak' which was run by his mentor M.G. Ranade.  He became secretary of the Pune Sarvajanik Sabha, an organization that worked for Indian political rights. He was also involved in provincial-level conferences advocating for self-governance.  In 1895 at the age of 29 Gokhale became Secretary of the Indian National Congress (INC).  In 1897 Gokhale testified before the Welby Commission (Royal Commission on Indian Expenditure) in England and advocated for financial autonomy for India.  He was elected to the Bombay Legislative Council in 1900 at the age of 34.  In 1902 he was nominated to the Imperial Legislative Council, where he became a key advocate for Indian self- governance a","PW-1869":"Mahatma Gandhi suggested the winding up of the Indian National Congress after India attained independence. He believed that the Congress had achieved its primary goal of securing independence and should now transform itself into a Lok Sevak Sangh (People's Service Organization) to focus on social and economic reconstruction rather than remaining a political party. His suggestion was not accepted by the Congress leadership. 271","PW-1870":"Mahadev Govind Ranade was jurist and social reformer who worked for education, women empowerment, widow remarriage and against child marriages. He established the Indian National Social Conference(INSC) in 1887. He was also among the initial members of Indian National Congress(INC) and addressed his INSC along with the annual sessions of the INC. 272","PW-1871":"Statement 1 is incorrect: JL Nehru was the first Prime Minister and Union Minister of External affairs of Independent India. He was the President of INC at Lahore Session in 1929 where the congress passed the resolution of Purna Swaraj. In the Karachi session he was credited for drafting resolutions on Fundamental Rights and National Economic Programme. Kripalani was the Congress president in 1947. Statement 2 is incorrect: Rajendra Prasad was the president of the Constituent Assembly. Statement 3 is incorrect: The first Congress-led government in the United Provinces (now Uttar Pradesh) was formed in 1937 but it was headed by Govind Ballabh Pant, not Jawaharlal Nehru. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 128 16. ASSOCIATIONS, JOURNALS, BOOKS AND PLAYS 273","PW-1872":"Abul Kalam Azad, a prominent freedom fighter and scholar, brought out the journal Al-Hilal in 1912. It was a weekly published in Urdu, aimed at promoting political consciousness among Muslims and opposing British colonial rule. Other works of Abul Kalam Azad were Al-Balagh, Gubhar-e-Khatir, and India wins Freedom. Option (b),(c) and (d) are incorrect :  Muhammad Ali Jauhar published and edited the weekly English-language newspaper “The Comrade.” The newspaper was banned in 1914 under the Press Act.  Shyamji Krishna Verma served as the editor of “The Indian Sociologist” journal.  The Zamindar newspaper was edited by Zafar Ali Khan but started by his father, Maulvi Sirajuddin Ahmad, in Sialkot as a farmer’s paper. 275","PW-1873":"Faiz Ahmed Faiz (1911–1984) was one of the most celebrated Urdu poets of the 20th century. He was a prominent figure in progressive literature and a vocal advocate for social justice, human rights, and anti-imperialism. The poem \"Subh-e- Azadi\" (Dawn of Freedom) was written by Faiz in 1947 which reflects on the partition of India and the bittersweet nature of independence. The poem captures the disillusionment and pain of partition, juxtaposing the joy of freedom with the tragedy of communal violence and displacement. The opening lines of the poem, \"Ye daagh daagh ujala, ye shab-gazida sahar\" (This stained light, this night-bitten dawn), are iconic and encapsulate the mixed emotions of the time. 276","PW-1874":"The song \"Amar Sonar Bangla\" (My Golden Bengal) was written by Tagore in 1905 during the Swadeshi Movement, which was a protest against the partition of Bengal by the British colonial government. The song was a rallying cry for unity and resistance against colonial rule. The song's emotional appeal and patriotic fervor made it immensely popular among Bengalis. It later became the national anthem of Bangladesh after the country's liberation in 1971. 277","PW-1875":"Somprakash was started by Ishwar Chandra Vidyasagar and played a pivotal role in fostering nationalism during the era of colonial India. Its weekly publication every Monday earned it the name “Somprakash.” Its impact was particularly pronounced in raising the awareness of the ryots, challenging landlord injustices and the exploitation of indigo farmers and vociferously criticizing the British taxation policies that burdened the impoverished masses. Moreover, it played a significant role in advocating for industrialization. 278","PW-1876":"Chandra Vidyasagar (1820–1891) was a renowned Bengali social reformer, educator, and writer during the 19th century. He played a pivotal role in advocating for women's rights, including widow remarriage and the abolition of polygamy. The book \"Bahubivah\" (Polygamy) was written by Vidyasagar as a critique of the practice of polygamy in Hindu society. He argued against the custom, highlighting its detrimental effects on women and families. His work was part of a broader effort to reform Hindu social practices and promote gender equality. His writings and activism contributed significantly to the passage of the Widow Remarriage Act of 1856 and other social reforms in colonial India. 279","PW-1877":"Bankim Chandra Chatterjee’s novel Anand Math (1882) is based on the historical events of the Sanyasi Rebellion. The Sannyasi Rebellion (1763–1800) was led by Hindu ‘sannyasis’ and Muslim ‘fakirs’ in Bengal against British economic oppression and restrictions on religious activities. It was triggered by the Bengal famine of 1770 and excessive taxation and it became an early symbol of resistance to colonial rule. 280","PW-1878":"","PW-1879":"","PW-1880":"A is matched with 1: The Chittagong Armoury Raid was led by Surya Sen and Kalpana Dutt, aimed at seizing arms from the British. The raid was conducted in April 1930 and involved 65 activists under the banner of Indian Republican Army—Chittagong Branch. B is matched with 3: Abhinav Bharat was set up by Vinayak Damodar Savarkar and his brother Ganesh Damodar Savarkar in the year 1904, as a secret organization during the Indian War of Independence with the aim of overthrowing British rule. C is matched with 4: Anushilan Samiti traces its history back to 1902 when it was established by Barrister Promotha Mitter and his friends in present-day Kolkata. Aurobindo Ghosh was closely associated with the Samiti. D is matched with 2: Kuka Movement was a socio-religious reform movement led by Guru Ram Singh in Punjab. 283","PW-1881":"A is matched with 4: The First Indian War of Independence was written by Vinayak Damodar Savarkar. It is a seminal work that describes the 1857 revolt as the first war of Indian independence. B is matched with 3: Anand Math was written by Bankim Chandra Chatterji. It is a famous Bengali novel that inspired the Swadeshi movement and features the iconic patriotic song Vande Mataram. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 130 C is matched with 2: Life Divine was written by Sri Aurobindo. The Life Divine explores the evolution of consciousness and the integration of spiritual and material life. D is matched with 1: Sadhana was written by Rabindranath Tagore. It is a collection of essays that reflects his thoughts on humanism and spirituality. 285","PW-1882":"In 1904, Vinayak Damodar Savarkar and his brother Ganesh founded the Abhinav Bharat Society (Young India Society) as a secret organization during India’s struggle for independence. The organization was inspired by Giuseppe Mazzini's Young Italy and aimed to overthrow British rule in India through armed revolution. Initially started as “Mitra Mela” in Nashik while Savarkar was a student, it was involved in assassinations of British officials. The group aimed to overthrow British rule. In 1904, Vinayak Savarkar named it Abhinav Bharat, inspired by Giuseppe Mazzini’s Young Italy. Prafulla Chaki and Khudiram Bose were associated with Jugantar Party (Bengal Revolutionaries) Bhagat Singh was a member of Hindustan Socialist Republican Association (HSRA). 286","PW-1883":"Pair 1 is correctly matched: Theodore Beck served as the Principal of the Mohammedan Anglo-Oriental College (now Aligarh Muslim University) in Aligarh. Pair 2 is correctly matched: The Ilbert Bill was introduced in 1883 during the Viceroyalty of Lord Ripon. It aimed to allow Indian judges to try European defendants. Pair 3 is correctly matched: Pherozeshah Mehta was one of the founding members of the Indian National Congress (INC) and played a prominent role in its early years. Pair 4 is incorrectly matched: Badruddin Tyabji was a prominent lawyer and an important figure in the Indian National Congress. He was the first Muslim to preside over a session of the Congress in 1887. He was not associated with the Muslim League. 288","PW-1884":"The Ghadar Party was established in 1913 by Indian expatriates, primarily in San Francisco, United States. Its primary aim was to overthrow British rule in India through armed rebellion. Option (b) is correct: Lala Har Dayal (1884–1939) was a prominent Indian revolutionary and intellectual who played a key role in the Indian independence movement, particularly as a founder of the Ghadar Party in 1913. Some of the prominent Ghadar leaders were: Baba Gurmukh Singh, Kartar Singh Saraba, Sohan Singh Bhakna, Rahmat Ali Shah, Bhai Parmanand, and Mohammad Barkatullah. 289","PW-1885":"The Servants of India Society was founded in 1905 by Gopal Krishna Gokhale to promote India’s welfare and self- reliant development. The society focused on legal reforms and education, which aligned with the professional interests of these three individuals. Option (d) is correct: M.C. Setalvad, B.N. Rao, and Alladi Krishnaswamy Iyer were members of the Society. Alladi Krishnaswamy Iyer was also a member of the Constituent Assembly of India. He was a lawyer and legal expert who contributed his expertise to the drafting and formulation of the constitution. M.C. Setalvad and B.N. Rao were also pioneers in Indian Legal and constitutional Studies. 290","PW-1886":"","PW-1887":"Surendranath Banerjee, M.K. Gandhi, Subhas Chandra Bose, and Lala Lajpat Rai were prominent freedom fighters who played pivotal roles in India’s struggle for independence, advocating nationalism, non-violence, armed resistance, and social reforms. A is matched with 4: Sir Surendranath Banerjee was a key figure in early Indian nationalism, advocating for reforms within the framework of British rule. His book, A Nation in Making, reflects his vision for India’s future. B is matched with 1: Hind Swaraj was authored by M.K. Gandhi (1909) critiques Western civilization and advocates for self- rule through self-reliance, traditional values, and non-violence, marking a significant shift in nationalist thought. C is matched with 2: Subhas Chandra Bose wrote the The Indian Struggle (1942) which outlines his analysis of India’s independence movement and his call for more radical action against British colonialism. D is matched with 3: The Story of My Deportation (1908) by Lala Lajpat Rai is an Autobiographical writing. 292","PW-1888":"A is matched with 4: Abhinav Bharat Society was founded by V.D. Savarkar, a revolutionary nationalist group aimed at overthrowing British rule. The society was inspired by Giuseppe Mazzini's Young Italy and played a significant role in organizing revolutionary activities in India and abroad. B is matched with 1: Anushilan Samiti was a revolutionary group based in Bengal, influenced by Aurobindo Ghosh. It aimed to achieve independence through armed revolution and was involved in several high-profile actions against British rule. C is matched with 2: Gadar Party was founded by Lala Hardayal and other Indian expatriates in the United States and Canada, and it aimed for armed rebellion against British rule. D is matched with 3: The Swaraj Party was founded in 1923 by Chittaranjan Das and Motilal Nehru after the suspension of the Non-Cooperation Movement. The party aimed to contest elections and obstruct British governance from within the legislative councils. 17. MISCELLANEOUS 293","PW-1889":"With reference to Indian History, Alexander Rea, A. H. Longhurst, Robert Sewell, James Burgess and Walter Elliot were all associated with archaeological excavations.  Alexander Rea (1858-1924) was an archaeologist who worked mainly in South British India and is known for unearthing a sarcophagus from the hillocks of Pallavaram in Tamil Nadu. He arrived in India in 1882 and became assistant of Burgess in the Archaeological Survey of India (A.S.I.), Madras Division. He went on to become Superintendent of the Archaeological Survey of Southern India (1902).  Albert Henry Longhurst (1876-1955) was an archaeologist and art historian who worked in India and Ceylon. He was in charge of the systematic digging of Nagarjunakonda (1927- 1931).  Robert Sewell (1845-1925) was a civil servant in the Madras Presidency in colonial India. He undertook archaeological work at the Amaravati stupa. The site had previously been surveyed by Colin Mackenzie and Walter Elliot (1803-1887).  James Burgess (1832-1916) was the founder of the Indian Antiquary in 1872 and an important archaeologist of British I","PW-1890":"Statement 1 is correct : St. Francis Xavier, along with St. Ignatius of Loyola and others, co-founded the Society of Jesus (Jesuit Order) in 1534. The Jesuits were established to promote education, missionary work, and counter the Protestant Reformation. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 132 Statement 2 is incorrect : He died on December 3, 1552, on Shangchuan Island (Sancian Island), off the coast of China, while waiting for a ship to take him to mainland China for missionary work. His body was later brought to Goa, where it is enshrined in the Basilica of Bom Jesus, a church dedicated to him. Statement 3 is correct : The Feast of St. Francis Xavier is celebrated annually on December 3 in Goa. 295","PW-1891":"Statement (1) is incorrect: The first woman to preside over the Congress was Annie Besant in 1917. Sarojini Naidu became President in 1925. Sarojini Naidu was a prominent leader and the first Indian woman to become the President of the Indian National Congress. Statement (2) is correct: Chittaranjan Das (C.R. Das) was elected President of the Indian National Congress in 1922. However, he was imprisoned during the Non-Cooperation Movement and conducted his presidential duties from jail. Statement (3) is incorrect: A.O. Hume was a founder but never served as its President. The first Britisher to preside over the Congress was George Yule in 1888. Statement (4) is correct: Alfred Webb, an Irish nationalist, presided over the 10th session of the Congress in 1894. His election symbolized the solidarity between Indian nationalists and Irish freedom fighters. 296","PW-1892":"The paintings of Abanindranath Tagore, a prominent figure in the Bengal School of Art, are classified as revivalistic because they aimed to revive Indian cultural and artistic traditions during British rule. He drew inspiration from Mughal miniatures, Ajanta frescoes, and Japanese wash techniques, moving away from Western realism and promoting a distinctly Indian art style. Abanindranath Tagore’s works, such as Bharat Mata symbolized national pride and cultural heritage, blending art with India’s freedom movement. 297","PW-1893":"Alam Ara (1931) was India’s first feature-length talkie film, directed by Ardeshir Irani. It marked the beginning of sound in Indian cinema and revolutionized the film industry. It was a musical drama based on a Persian story, and it featured several songs, which was a major draw for audiences at the time. The film had a huge impact on Indian cinema, especially in terms of introducing sound and dialogue, which made it a landmark in the history of Indian cinema. 298","PW-1894":"The advertisement refers to the first screening of moving pictures in India by the Lumière Brothers’ Cinématographe. This historic event took place on July 7, 1896, at Watson’s Hotel in Bombay (now Mumbai). It marked the introduction of cinema to India, which later evolved into one of the largest film industries in the world. The Times of India published this advertisement, highlighting the marvel of “life- sized photographic pictures,” a technological wonder of that era. 300","PW-1895":"A is matched with 4: The first session of the National Conference was held at Calcutta in 1883 to discuss political issues and laid the groundwork for the Indian National Congress, which was established in 1885. B is matched with 3: The All-India Muslim League was formed on December 30, 1906 at Dacca (now Dhaka) to represent the interests of Indian Muslims. C is matched with 2: All India State Peoples Conference was formed in 1927. This conference united representatives from princely states to push for democratic reforms . D is matched with 1: Announcement of Communal Award from Whitehall by the British government in August 1932 introduced separate electorates for minorities, including Dalits (then termed Depressed Classes), causing widespread controversy. v v v","PW-1896":"The Constituent Assembly convened its inaugural meeting on December 9, 1946. In accordance with French tradition, Dr. Sachchidananda Sinha, the eldest member, was chosen as the interim President of the Assembly. Subsequently, Dr Rajendra Prasad was elected as the Assembly's President. 2","PW-1897":"The Charter Act of 1833 marked the final step towards the centralization of British power in India. It elevated the Governor-General of Bengal to the position of Governor-General of India, granting him full civil and military authority over the entire British-ruled territory in India, with Lord William Bentinck becoming the first Governor-General of India. The Act also stripped the Governors of Bombay and Madras of their legislative powers. Under this Act, laws were referred to as \"Acts\" instead of \"Regulations,\" as was the case under previous acts. Additionally, it ended the East India Company's role as a commercial entity, transforming it into a purely administrative body. 3","PW-1898":"The Government of India Act 1919 introduced the system of ‘dyarchy’ in provincial governance. It divided subjects into two categories: reserved and transferred. Reserved subjects like law and order, land revenue, administration of justice, finance, and police were controlled by the governor and his executive council of bureaucrats. Transferred subjects like education, health, and local self-government were managed by ministers elected from the legislative council. This was aimed at increasing Indian representation in the government, though real power remained with the British. The Act came into effect in 1921. Key Features of the Government of India Act 1919 Act  Bicameral Legislature: The Indian legislature was now composed of:  Council of State (Upper House): Partially elected.  Legislative Assembly (Lower House): Majority elected, but with limited powers.  Increased Participation of Indians: The number of Indians in government increased, but British officials retained veto power.  Separate Electorates Extended: More communities (such as Sikhs, Anglo-Indians, and Europeans) we","PW-1899":"The Constituent Assembly of India, tasked with drafting the Constitution, formed several committees to address specific aspects of the Constitution. One of these was the Union Constitution Committee, which focused on defining the federal structure and relationship between the union and the states. Jawaharlal Nehru was appointed as the Chairman of the Union Constitution Committee. B.R. Ambedkar was the Chairman of the Drafting Committee, which was responsible for the final wording of the Constitution. J. B. Kripalani and Alladi Krishnaswami Ayyar were also influential members of the Constituent Assembly but did not chair this committee. 6","PW-1900":"The Indian Constitution is a unique blend of influences from various countries, incorporating their best practices into its framework.  Directive Principles of State Policy were inspired by Ireland. The Irish Constitution provided the model for including socio-economic rights in the form of guiding principles for state policy.  Fundamental Rights were borrowed from the United States of America. The American Bill of Rights served as the inspiration for ensuring basic human rights in India.  The Concurrent List in Union-State Relations was influenced by Australia, reflecting their federal structure.  The concept of India as a Union of States with greater powers to the Union was derived from Canada, which has a strong federal system with residual powers vested in the central government. List–I (Items in the Indian Constitution) List–II (Country from which it was derived Parliamentary System of Government United Kingdom President as Supreme Commander of Armed Forces United States of America Procedure for Amendment of the Constitution South Africa Emergency Provisions (National Emerge","PW-1901":"In modern times, The Doctrine of ‘Due Process of Law’ has its origins in the USA Constitution . The due process of law doctrine not only examines whether a law exists to deprive a person of life or liberty but also assesses its fairness, justice, and non-arbitrariness. Unlike \"Procedure established by law,\" where the judiciary focuses only on the legality and competence of the legislation, the Supreme Court, in the case of due process, also evaluates the law’s rationale and reasonableness. While \"Due Process\" primarily concerns legal procedures, it also emphasizes fairness and justice in law enforcement, aligning with the principles of natural justice, such as the right to a fair hearing, the right to be heard, and the right to an impartial tribunal. SUPER HINT It would be illogical to say due process is same as pro- cedure established by law, even plain reading of both can prove both are different, hence eliminate option B. \"Equality before law\" (Article 14) is not even the same article as due process (A. 21), Hence Clearly false. Now, \"Natural justice\" = fairness + impartiality + r","PW-1902":"The State refers to a political institution that represents a sovereign people organised under one independent government within a definite territory and subject to no outside control. Under the Montevideo Convention on the Rights and Duties of States 1933, The term 'State' is best defined using the four essential elements of statehood, as recognized in political science and international law.  Population: A community of persons.  Territory: A defined geographical area.  Government: An organized political authority.  Sovereignty: Independence from external control. 10","PW-1903":"The doctrine of Separation of Powers entails the division of the legislative, executive, and judicial functions of government among different orgAns: This demarcation prevents the concentration of excessive power by any branch of the Government. It thus helps to safeguard the liberty and rights of the people in a democracy. Article 50 of the Directive Principles of State Policy mentions separation of judiciary from the executive. 11","PW-1904":"Originally, the Indian Constitution recognized the Right to Property as a Fundamental Right under Article 19(1)(f) and Article 31.  Later, the 44th Constitutional Amendment Act, 1978 abolished the Right to Property as a Fundamental Right.  It was then made a legal right under Article 300-A of the Constitution.  Article 300-A states: \"No person shall be deprived of his property save by Authority of Law.\"  Thus, the Right to Property in India is now a legal right available to any person, not a Fundamental Right. 12","PW-1905":"The common agreement between Gandhism and Marxism is the final goal of stateless and classless society, whereas means to achieve these final goals differ. A stateless society does refer to a society without a centralized government or formal state institutions, it typically implies a system where people govern themselves through communal, decentralized methods without the need for a coercive state apparatus.  According to Karl Marx, the State is an instrument of oppression and an organ of the bourgeoisie that only works for maintaining class dominance. Therefore, he strives for class struggle and revolution which will ultimately result in a stateless society.  Mahatma Gandhi gave the concept of Ramarajya, an ideal society characterised by self-governing individuals living in harmony without centralised political authority. He believed in achieving this stateless society through non-violent means, emphasizing moral and ethical self-discipline. Gandhi's vision aligns with the idea of enlightened anarchy. 13","PW-1906":"Bureaucracy is the executive branch of government, responsible for implementing decisions made by the elected officials. Bureaucrats are selected through a merit-based process to manage state affairs. In India, the primary role of the bureaucracy is to ensure the execution of government policies. While political leadership may change with elections, the bureaucracy remains constant, providing stability and continuity in governance. This ensures that policies are carried out consistently, regardless of changes in the political leadership. Polity 159 14","PW-1907":"According to OECD the term social capital can be defined as “networks together with shared norms, values and understandings that facilitate co-operation within or among groups”. It consists of trust, mutual understanding, shared values and behaviour that bind together the members of a community and make cooperative action possible. Such interaction enables people to build communities, to commit themselves to each other, and to knit the social fabric. The proportion of literates in the population and the size of population in the working age group can be the examples of human capital. The stock of its buildings, other infrastructure and machines is the example of physical capital. 15","PW-1908":"Dialectical materialism is the philosophical foundation of Karl Marx’s theory of class struggle. It asserts that social and economic progress occurs through contradictions and conflicts between different economic classes, leading to revolutionary change. Marx argued that human history is shaped by material conditions rather than ideas alone, and that class struggle between the proletariat (working class) and bourgeoisie (capitalist class) would eventually lead to a socialist society. 16","PW-1909":"Option (1) is incorrect: The NSAP’s primary constitutional foundation lies in the Directive Principles of State Policy, not Fundamental Rights. While it contributes to the socio-economic conditions that enhance the enjoyment of Fundamental Rights, it is not designed or implemented as a means of enforcing them. Option (2) is incorrect: Fundamental Duties (Part IVA, Article 51A) are directed towards citizens and do not impose obligations on the state. The NSAP is not linked to the fulfillment of Fundamental Duties. Option (3) is correct: The National Social Assistance Programme (NSAP) launched by the Government of India aims to provide social assistance to the elderly, disabled, and other vulnerable sections of society. It directly aligned with the Directive Principles of State Policy (DPSP), which guide the government towards social welfare under:  Article 41: The State is directed to provide public assistance in case of old age, sickness, and disablement, which is the primary aim of NSAP.  Article 42: Deals with just and humane conditions of work, which is indirectly addressed thro","PW-1910":"The Fifth Schedule of the Constitution governs the administration and control of Scheduled Areas and Scheduled Tribes. Article 244(1) defines these areas as specified by the President. In the landmark Samatha v. State of Andhra Pradesh (1997) case, the Supreme Court ruled that transferring tribal land to private parties, including for mining, is null and void, reinforcing safeguards for tribal rights. The Governor, with advice from the Tribal Advisory Council (TAC), can make regulations for peace and good governance in these areas. These can include restrictions on land transfers, allotments, and money-lending activities involving scheduled tribes. 22","PW-1911":"The Ninth Schedule of the Indian Constitution was added by the 1st Amendment (1951) to protect the laws included in it from judicial scrutiny on the ground of violation of fundamental rights. At this time, Jawaharlal Nehru was the Prime Minister of India. He remained in the office from the year 1947 to 1964. This schedule deals with the provisions as to validation of certain Acts and Regulations of the state legislatures primarily dealing with land reforms and abolition of the zamindari system and of the Parliament dealing with other matters. 23","PW-1912":"The framers of the Indian Constitution decided to guarantee every adult Indian citizen the right to vote. This right is enshrined in both the Constitution and the Representation of the People Act, 1951. Article 326 of the Constitution ensures that every citizen above the age of 18 has the right to vote. Additionally, Section 62 of the Representation of the People Act, 1951, states that the right to vote is available to all individuals who are registered on the electoral roll of a constituency. Polity 161 24","PW-1913":"","PW-1914":"The fifth and the sixth schedule of the Constitution of India deals with the provisions related to the protection of the interests of the Scheduled Tribes.  Fifth Schedule: Deals with the provisions relating to the administration and control of scheduled areas and scheduled tribes in any state except 4 states of Assam, Meghalaya, Tripura & Mizoram. The Constitution defines Scheduled Areas as the areas defined so by the Presidential notification and are mentioned in the 5th schedule of the Constitution.  Sixth Schedule: The 6th Schedule of the Indian Constitution provides special provisions for the administration of tribal areas in Assam, Meghalaya, Tripura, and Mizoram. It provides for the organisation of autonomous district and regional councils to safeguard the rights and interests of indigenous tribal communities, with powers over local governance, land, and customary laws. 28","PW-1915":"Tenth Schedule added by 52nd Amendment Act deals with the provisions as to disqualification on grounds of defection. On the basis of a petition by any other member, a legislator may be removed from office on the grounds of defection by the Presiding officer of a legislature. The Chairman or Speaker of that House is tasked with making the final determination regarding disqualification due to defection. 29","PW-1916":"Parliamentary System entails that the Executive is responsible to the legislature for its policies and legislations. The Constitution of India provides for a parliamentary form of government, both at the Centre and in the States. The Parliamentary Government is also known as Cabinet Government/Responsible Government/Westminster Model. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 162 Some of its features are included in the details of statements analysis are as follows: Statement 1 is correct: In the Parliamentary System of Government members of the Cabinet are members of the Parliament. Statement 2 is correct: The ministers in the Parliament hold the office till they enjoy the confidence of the Parliament. Statement 3 is incorrect: The Head of the state is President and he/she does not head the cabinet, he is considered to be the nominal executive. The head of Govt(PM) heads the cabinet. 30","PW-1917":"Statement 1 is Incorrect: The Constitution of India originally had 22 parts, though with amendments, it now has 25 parts. Thus, the statement that the Constitution has 20 parts is incorrect. Statement 2 is Incorrect: Originally, the Constitution had 395 Articles, but due to amendments, the number of Articles has increased to 448. Statement 3 is correct: Schedule Added by Amendment Purpose Ninth Schedule First Amendment Act (1951) Protects certain laws (mainly land reforms) from judicial review. Tenth Schedule Fifty-Second Amendment Act (1985) Deals with disqualification of legislators on grounds of defection (Anti-Defection Law). Eleventh Schedule Seventy-Third Amendment Act (1992) Defines powers, authority, and responsibilities of Panchayati Raj institutions. Twelfth Schedule Seventy-Fourth Amendment Act (1992) Lists functions and responsibilities of municipalities. 4. PREAMBLE 31","PW-1918":"The Preamble to the Indian Constitution is a brief introductory statement that reflects the hopes and aspirations of the people. The ideals behind the Preamble to Indian Constitution is based on ‘Objective Resolution’ which were drafted by Jawaharlal Nehru and adopted by the Constituent Assembly on January 22, 1947. The original Preamble, adopted by the Constituent Assembly in 1949, declared India a “Sovereign Democratic Republic”. Later, it was amended by the 42nd Constitutional Amendment Act (1976), and added three new words–“Socialist, Secular and Integrity”. 32","PW-1919":"The Preamble to the Constitution of India is part of the Constitution but lacks independent legal force. It outlines guiding principles like justice, liberty, and equality. The Supreme Court in Keshavananda Bharati (1973) affirmed it as integral to understanding the Constitution’s philosophy, although it doesn’t confer enforceable rights. It serves as a guiding tool for interpreting the Constitution’s objectives.  In 1976, Preamble was amended by the 42nd Constitutional Amendment Act to add \"Socialist, Secular, and Integrity\".  In the Berubari Union Case (1960), the Supreme Court had earlier held that the Preamble is not a source of power or substantive rights and has no independent legal effect. It also held that Preamble is not an operative part of the Constitution and lacks legal force. 33","PW-1920":"Liberty is generally understood not as the absence of restraint or mere freedom to do whatever one likes, but as the freedom to develop one’s full potential within the framework of laws and rights that ensure the same freedom for others. This idea aligns with the concept of positive liberty, which is the ability to act in ways that allow personal and collective growth, while also respecting the freedoms of others. SUPER HINT Break down the options using two filters: Is it positive or negative in tone? Is it balanced or extreme? Option A, Sounds reactive and negative — liberty as shield, not as freedom. Also narrow — only about political rulers. Op- tion B, Feels absolute, like no rules at all(negative tone). That’s not liberty — that’s anarchy. Similarly Option C, disguised as liberty but actually promoting lawless- ness(negative tone). Option D, Balanced + Empowering = Hence, Most appropriate Polity 163 34","PW-1921":"","PW-1922":"The preamble to the Indian Constitution assures to all citizens- liberty of thought,liberty of expression, liberty of belief, liberty of faith and worship. However, economic liberty is not directly mentioned in the Preamble. While economic rights and the goal of economic justice are addressed in the Directive Principles of State Policy, the Preamble does not specifically include economic liberty as one of its stated objectives. 36","PW-1923":"The Preamble to the Constitution of India reflects the vision and values of the framers, including justice, liberty, equality, and fraternity. It outlines the objectives of the Constitution, such as ensuring social, economic, and political justice, and promoting unity and dignity. In the Berubari case, the court held that the Preamble was not part of the Constitution’s operative provisions, meaning it did not have legal force in itself, although it could help in interpreting the Constitution’s provisions. The Supreme Court has affirmed its importance in the Kesavananda Bharati case (1973), where it was recognized as integral to understanding the Constitution makers intent and philosophy, and it overturned opinion in the Berubari case. So, now Preamble stands as part of the constitution. 37","PW-1924":"“Economic Justice” is a key objective of the Indian Constitution, reflected both in the Preamble and the Directive Principles of State Policy (DPSP). Option(b) is correct:  The Preamble highlights economic justice as part of broader social, economic, and political justice, emphasizing non- discrimination based on economic factors.  The DPSP, inspired by socialist principles, aims to reduce inequalities and promote social and economic welfare. The 44th Amendment (1978) amended Article 38 by adding Article 38(2) to the DPSP, mandating the state to minimize income and status disparities and ensure equitable access to opportunities and resources. 38","PW-1925":"The Constitution of India was adopted by the Constituent Assembly on 26th November 1949, as noted in the Preamble, marking the completion of the drafting process. The X stands for this date in the Preamble. However, it came into effect on 26th January 1950, to honor the Purna Swaraj Declaration of 1930, when India resolved to seek complete independence. The Preamble reflects the ideals of justice, liberty, equality, and fraternity, while the Constitution’s official enforcement began on Republic Day. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 164 5. CITIZENSHIP 39","PW-1926":"The Constitution of India addresses the issue of citizenship in Part II (Articles 5 to 11). It provides a framework for determining who would be considered a citizen of India on January 26, 1950. Statement 1 is correct: The Indian Constitution provides for single citizenship, where citizens owe allegiance only to the Indian Union. Indian citizenship ends if a person voluntarily acquired foreign citizenship. A person can acquire only one domicile by choice by taking up fixed residence in a state or region. Statement 2 is incorrect: In India, the Head of the State is the President and as per the Indian constitution both a citizen by birth as well as a naturalised citizen are eligible for the office of President. Statement 3 is incorrect: A foreigner who has previously received Indian citizenship, can be deprived of his citizenship. The Citizenship Act (1955) provides for acquisition and loss of citizenship. Indian citizenship can be terminated in cases where: the citizenship is obtained by fraud, shown disloyalty to the Constitution of India, unlawfully exchanged goods or information w","PW-1927":"A Writ of Prohibition is a judicial order issued by the Supreme Court or High Courts to a lower court or tribunal, directing it to stop continuing proceedings in a case that exceeds its jurisdiction or is legally improper. It is issued before a lower court delivers its judgment. It is a preventive writ, stopping a court from acting beyond its powers. The Supreme Court can issue it under Article 32, and the High Courts can issue it under Article 226 of the Constitution of India.  Habeas Corpus, a Latin term meaning \"to produce the body,\" is a court order requiring that a detained individual be brought before the court within 24 hours to assess the legality of their detention. If detention is found illegal, the person is released; otherwise, they remain in custody.  Mandamus, a Latin term meaning \"command,\" is a writ issued by higher courts to ensure public officials fulfil their duties. It cannot be granted against private individuals or companies but is directed at public authorities, companies, tribunals, or lower courts, compelling them to perform their obligations or refrain fro","PW-1928":"The Constitution of India does not specifically guarantee a right to privacy. However, through various judgments over the years, the Courts of the country have interpreted the other rights in the Constitution to give rise to a (limited) right to privacy— primarily through Article 21—the right to life and liberty.  In Justice K.S. Puttaswamy vs. Union of India (2017), the Supreme Court unanimously ruled that privacy is a fundamental right protected under Article 21 and Part III of the Constitution, affirming its intrinsic link to life, personal liberty, and fundamental freedoms.  The Bench also ruled that the right to privacy is not absolute but is subject to reasonable restrictions (as is every other fundamental right). 42","PW-1929":"Statement 1 is correct: The word Mandamus means “we command”. It directs activity and commands issued by the court to public officials asking him to perform. It is issued against any public body, corporation, inferior court, tribunal or government for the same purpose. Mandamus cannot be issued against a private individual or body. Statement 2 is incorrect: In specific situations, Mandamus can be used against a government corporation and/or company and if a private entity till it is entrusted with a public duty. Supreme Court in Pradeep Kumar Biwas vs Indian Institute of Chemical Biology 2002 has deliberated upon this in detail. Statement 3 is correct: The meaning of the word Quo Warranto is “By what authority or warrant”. Quo Warranto is issued by the court to inquire into the legality of the claim of a person to a public office. Unlike the other writs, this can be sought by any interested person and not necessarily by the aggrieved person. Note: UPSC has given Option (d) as the official answer. SUPER HINT For S2, Mandamus will not lie\" → absolute claim \"Even if it is a Govt company","PW-1930":"In K.S. Puttaswamy v. Union of India (2017), the Supreme Court ruled that the Right to Privacy is a fundamental right under Article 21 of the Constitution, which guarantees the right to life and personal liberty. The Court emphasized that privacy is integral to personal dignity and autonomy. It further held that privacy must be protected from arbitrary state actions, marking a significant expansion of constitutional rights in India.  Article 15 prohibits discrimination on grounds of religion, race, caste, sex, or place of birth, ensuring equality for all citizens.  Article 19 guarantees fundamental freedoms, including the right to freedom of speech, assembly, and movement.  Article 29 protects cultural and educational rights, safeguarding the rights of minorities to preserve their language, culture, and script. 44","PW-1931":"Article 14 of the Indian Constitution guarantees equality before the law and equal protection of the laws. If a legislation grants the executive or administrative authorities unguided and uncontrolled discretionary power, it violates the principle of rule of law and equality. This is because such unchecked discretion can lead to arbitrariness, which goes against the very essence of equality and fairness under Article 14. Therefore, any legislation with unrestrained discretionary powers could be deemed unconstitutional under Article 14.  Article 28 (Fundamental Right): Prohibits religious instruction in educational institutions wholly funded by the State but allows it in institutions administered by religious groups.  Article 32 (Fundamental Right): Provides the right to constitutional remedies, allowing individuals to approach the Supreme Court for the enforcement of fundamental rights.  Article 44 (Directive Principles of State Policy): Advocates for a Uniform Civil Code (UCC) to ensure uniform personal laws across all communities in India. 45","PW-1932":"The protection against untouchability is specifically provided under Article 17 of the Indian Constitution, which is part of the Right to Equality. Article 17 explicitly abolishes untouchability and makes its practice an offense. It is a direct form of discrimination based on caste, and its prohibition is a cornerstone of the right to equality in India. Articles 14 to 18 deals with ‘Right to Equality’:  Equality before Law (Article 14)  Prohibition of discrimination based on grounds of religion, race, caste etc. (Article 15)  Equality of opportunity in matters of public employment (Article 16)  Abolition of Untouchability (Article 17)  Abolition of titles (Article 18) 46","PW-1933":"Statement 1 is correct: The Preamble of the Indian Constitution reflects the principles of the Universal Declaration of Human Rights (UDHR) by emphasizing justice, liberty, equality, and fraternity. The Article 3 of Universal Declaration of Human Rights (UDHR) (1948) says that “Everyone has the right to life, liberty and security of person.” Statement 2 is correct: DPSPs are the principles that aim at providing social and economic justice and set the path towards the welfare state. This DPSP has a resemblance with UDHR Article 22. The article 22 of UDHR 1948 says that “Everyone, as a member of society, has the right to social security.” UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 166 Statement 3 is correct: Fundamental duties (Article 51A) are basically civic and moral obligations of all citizens of India. Similarly Article 29 of the UDHR emphasizes the reciprocal relationship between individual rights and duties to the community. SUPER HINT You can try, The \"NOT\" approach for all statements, this tests the improbability of negating a statement—if de- nying its impact seems highly unlikely, the statement i","PW-1934":"Article 21 of the Constitution of India guarantees the “right to life and personal liberty”, which the Supreme Court has interpreted to include the right to marry a person of one’s choice. In several landmark judgments, the Court has emphasized that this right is part of an individual’s personal liberty, and any interference with it must meet strict scrutiny under the Constitution. In the famous Hadiya case(Shafin Jahan v. Asokan K.M.), the court held that the right to choose a partner is essential to a person’s meaningful existence and autonomy.  Right to Life: Ensures the protection of life and dignity, not just mere existence.  Right to Personal Liberty: Prevents arbitrary arrest and detention, ensuring freedom of movement and choices.  Right to Privacy: Recognized as a fundamental right (Puttaswamy case, 2017).  Right to a Clean Environment: Includes protection against pollution and ecological degradation.  Right to Live with Dignity: Covers humane conditions, health, and shelter.  Right to Die with Dignity: Includes passive euthanasia .  Protection Against Arbitrary State","PW-1935":"Statement 1 is incorrect: The National Council for Teacher Education (NCTE) lays down the minimum qualifications for teachers, not the State Councils of Teacher Education. Statement 2 is correct: The Teacher Eligibility Test (TET) is conducted as per NCTE guidelines and is a mandatory requirement for teaching primary classes in government and private schools. Statement 3 is incorrect: More than 90% of teacher education institutions are privately managed, and only a small percentage are directly run by State Governments. 49","PW-1936":"Statement 1 is correct: The Ninth Schedule and Article 31-B of the Indian Constitution was added by the 1st Amendment (1951) to protect the laws included in it from judicial scrutiny on the ground of violation of fundamental rights. A law passed by the Parliament and inserted into the Ninth Schedule receives protection under Article 31-B (validation of certain Acts and Regulations) and is thus exempt from judicial review. However in IR Coelho vs State of Tamil Nadu, 2007, the SC ruled that all laws (including those in the Ninth Schedule) would be open to Judicial Review if they violated the basic structure of the constitution. Statement 2 is incorrect: The mandate of Ninth schedule is to prevent judicial scrutiny but according to the Kesavananda Bharati Case, 1973, any violation with the ‘basic structure’ of the Constitution is open to challenge in court of law. Again in IR Coelho vs State of Tamil Nadu, 2007, the SC ruled that all laws (including those in the Ninth Schedule) after 24 April 1973 would be open to Judicial Review if they violated the basic structure of the constitution","PW-1937":"The concept of ‘Rule of Law’ was propounded by A.V. Dicey. It is a cornerstone of democratic governance, ensuring that everyone, including government officials, is governed by law. Statement 1, 2 and 4 are correct: The concept of ‘equality before law’ as enshrined in Article 14 of constitution is aligned with “Rule of Law” whose key features include:  Limitation of Powers: Government authority must be constrained by law to prevent misuse of power.  Equality Before the Law: All individuals, irrespective of status, are equal before the law.  Liberty and Civil Rights: The Rule of Law protects individual freedoms and rights, ensuring the state cannot infringe on them arbitrarily. Polity 167 Statement 3 is incorrect: The government is responsible/ accountable to the people. While citizens have duties and responsibilities, the Rule of Law primarily focuses on how power is exercised by the government and how citizens are protected under the law. SUPER HINT What is the logical relationship between rule of law and people's responsibility? None!, Rule of Law is about government’s accountabi","PW-1938":"Statement 1 is correct: As under Article 23 (Right Against Exploitation) of the constitution, the expression ‘traffic in human beings’ includes: Selling and buying of men, women and children like goods, Immoral traffic in women and children, including prostitution, Devadasis, Slavery. Statement 2 is incorrect: Abolition of Untouchability is provided in the Constitution of India but it comes under Right to Equality, under Article 17. Statement 3 is incorrect: The Cultural and Educational Rights (under Articles 29 and 30) cover protection of interests of minorities; they don’t come under Rights Against Exploitation. Statement 4 is correct: Article 24 (Right Against Exploitation) ensures prohibition of employment of children in factories etc. The Commissions for Protection of Child Rights Act, 2005 was enacted to provide for the establishment of a National Commission and State Commissions for Protection of Child Rights and Children’s Courts for providing speedy trial of offences against children or of violation of child rights. 53","PW-1939":"In India, rights and duties are interdependent and complementary. The Constitution guarantees fundamental rights and duties, ensuring that individuals’ freedoms are balanced with responsibilities towards society. Rights, such as freedom of speech and equality, are linked with corresponding duties to prevent harm to others and maintain social order. Fundamental duties, like respecting the Constitution and upholding national sovereignty, are crucial for the stability of the state. Both rights and duties work together to promote justice, equality, and fraternity, as reflected in the Preamble, ensuring the progress and well-being of society and the nation. Similarly, One cannot enjoy their Right to a clean environment if others do not perform their duty of protecting and conserving the environment. Hence, Rights are correlative with Duties. 54","PW-1940":"","PW-1941":"Statement 1 is correct: Though the Constitution of India does not define the term ‘minorities’. Article 30 of the Constitution mandates that all minorities have the right to establish and administer educational institutions of their choice. Statement 2 is incorrect: As per the constitution, there is no provision of communal representation in Lok Sabha. Statement 3 is correct: The objective of the Prime Minister’s 15-Point Programme is to enhance opportunities for education and ensure an equitable share for minorities in economic activities and employment, through existing and new schemes, enhanced credit support for self-employment, and recruitment to State and Central Government jobs in those districts which have substantial minority populations. 57","PW-1942":"The Universal Declaration of Human Rights (UDHR), adopted by the United Nations General Assembly in 1948, enshrines several fundamental human rights. Let’s analyze each of the given rights:  Right to Education: Article 26 of UDHR explicitly recognizes the right to education. It states that education shall be free, at least in the elementary and fundamental stages, and that higher education shall be equally accessible to all based on merit.  Right to Equal Access to Public Service: Article 21(2) of UDHR guarantees that everyone has the right to equal access to public service in their country. This ensures that no one is discriminated against in accessing government-provided services.  Right to Food: Article 25(1) of UDHR recognizes the right to an adequate standard of living, including food, clothing, housing, and medical care. This establishes food as a fundamental human right necessary for survival and well- being. 58","PW-1943":"The United Nations Convention on the Rights of the Child (UNCRC), adopted in 1989, is a comprehensive human rights treaty that recognizes the full range of rights for children. The Convention outlines four broad categories of rights for children:-  Survival Rights include the child’s right to life, adequate nutrition, healthcare, and a standard of living adequate for development.  Development Rights encompass the right to education, access to information, and opportunities for personal, cultural, and social development.  Participation Rights include the child’s right to freedom of expression, thought, association, and participation in decisions affecting their lives.  Protection Rights safeguard children from exploitation, abuse, and harm.  The Right to Recreation is included under development rights, while the Right to Expression falls under participation rights. Together, all three options: development, expression, and recreation are recognized as rights of the child under the UNCRC. 59","PW-1944":"Statement 1 is incorrect: Article 301 pertains to the freedom of trade, commerce, and intercourse throughout India, not the Right to Property. Currently, The Right to Property is covered under Article 300A of the Indian Constitution. Statement 2 is Correct: The Right to Property, initially a Fundamental Right under Article 31, was made a legal right through the 44th Constitutional Amendment Act of 1978 and placed under Article 300A. Statement 3 is Incorrect: Article 300A was indeed inserted by the 44th Constitutional Amendment Act of 1978, but not by the Congress government. The 44th Amendment removed the Right to Property from the list of Fundamental Rights and made it a legal right under Article 300A. This change was made during the Janata Party government, not the Congress Party government. Polity 169 60","PW-1945":"A is matched with 2: Article 14 of the Indian Constitution guarantees equality before the law and equal protection of the laws within India, ensuring that no person is discriminated against unfairly by the state. B is matched with 1: Article 15 prohibits discrimination on grounds of religion, race, caste, sex, place of birth, or any of them thereby promoting social justice and inclusivity. C is matched with 4: Article 16 provides for equality of opportunity for all citizens in matters of employment or appointment to any office under the State. No citizen can be discriminated against or be ineligible for any employment or office under the State on grounds of only religion, race, caste, sex, descent, place of birth or residence. D is matched with 3: Article 17 abolishes untouchability, a social evil, and forbids its practice in any form, aiming to uplift marginalized communities and promote social harmony. Together, these provisions protect individual dignity and promote equal treatment in all spheres. 61","PW-1946":"Article 24 prohibits the employment of children below the age of 14 years in factories, mines, or any other hazardous employment. This is part of the Fundamental Rights under the Right against Exploitation. Options(b), (c) and (d) are incorrect:  Article 45 pertains to the Directive Principle of State Policy, focusing on providing free and compulsory education for children below 14 years.  Article 330 relates to the reservation of seats for Scheduled Castes and Scheduled Tribes in the House of the People (Lok sabha).  Article 368 deals with the amendment provisions in the Indian Constitution. 62","PW-1947":"A is matched with 2: Article 16 (2) states that no citizen can be discriminated against or be ineligible for any employment or office under the State on grounds of only religion, race, caste, sex, descent, place of birth or residence. B is matched with 4: Article 29 (2) ensures that no citizen shall be denied admission to any state-maintained or state- aided educational institution on grounds of religion, race, caste, language, or any of them. C is matched with 3: Article 30 (1) grants minorities the right to establish and administer educational institutions of their choice. D is matched with 1: Article 31 (1) refers to the protection of property rights and ensures no person shall be deprived of their property except by the authority of law. 63","PW-1948":"The Right to Equality, enshrined as Fundamental Rights in Articles 14 to 18 of the Indian Constitution, ensures that all citizens are treated equally before the law and have access to the same legal protection.  Article 14 guarantees equality before the law and equal protection of the laws.  Article 15 prohibits discrimination based on religion, race, caste, sex, or place of birth or any of them.  Article 16 states that no citizen can be discriminated against or be ineligible for any employment or office under the State on grounds of only religion, race, caste, sex, descent, place of birth or residence. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 170  Article 17 abolishes untouchability, outlawing its practice.  Article 18 prohibits the conferment of hereditary titles, maintaining equality by ensuring no citizen is bestowed with aristocratic privileges (except for military and academic distinctions). 64","PW-1949":"Dr. B.R. Ambedkar regarded the Right to Constitutional Remedies (Article 32) as the “heart and soul of the Constitution” because it provides the means to enforce all other Fundamental Rights. Article 32 empowers individuals to directly approach the Supreme Court in case of violation of their Fundamental Rights, ensuring their protection and justiciability. 65","PW-1950":"The Constitution of India protects religious and linguistic minorities through various provisions.  Article 29: Ensures the preservation of distinct culture, language, and script of minorities.  Article 30: Grants minorities the right to establish and administer educational institutions.  Article 25: Safeguards religious freedom for all individuals.  Article 350A: Mandates education in the mother tongue for linguistic minorities.  Article 350B: Provides for a Special Officer for Linguistic Minorities to safeguard their rights. However, Ethnic minorities are not specifically recognized in the Indian Constitution. 66","PW-1951":"Certain rights under the Indian Constitution are available only to Indian citizens and are not extended to foreign nationals or non-citizens. These rights are provided under Article 15,16,19,29 and 30. Article 19(1)(g) gives Indian citizens the right to practice any profession, or to carry on any occupation, trade, or business. However, foreign nationals (including a British citizen) do not have this right under the Indian Constitution. 67","PW-1952":"The term “boycott” originates from the name of Captain Charles Boycott, a British land agent in Ireland. In 1880, Irish tenants protested against his harsh treatment by refusing to cooperate with him or work on his land. This form of non-cooperation was later adopted globally as a political tool of protest. The other terms: Gherao, Bandh, and Hartal are not derived from personal names. 68","PW-1953":"","PW-1954":"Under the Indian Constitution, the Directive Principles of State Policy (DPSP), found in Part IV, outline the aims and objectives that the State should strive to achieve in order to promote social and economic justice. Among these, certain principles aim to reduce economic disparities and ensure that wealth is not concentrated in the hands of a few.  Article 38:The State is directed to promote the welfare of the people by securing a social order based on justice, ensuring the distribution of wealth and resources so that there are no inequalities.  Article 39 (b):The State should direct its policies towards ensuring that the ownership and control of material resources are distributed in such a way that it serves the common good.  Article 39 (c):The State should ensure that the economic system does not result in the concentration of wealth and means of production in the hands of a few. Polity 171 70","PW-1955":"DPSP embodies the concept of a ‘welfare state’. A welfare state refers to a concept of government in which the state plays a key role in the economic and social well-being of its citizens. Article 38 (1) states that “The State shall strive to promote the welfare of the people by securing and protecting as effectively as it may a social order in which justice, social, economic and political, shall inform all the institutions of the national life”. 71","PW-1956":"Part IV of the Constitution of India deals with the Directive Principles of State Policy (DPSP), which are outlined in Articles 36 to 51. Statement 1 is incorrect: The DPSP are not enforceable by courts. According to Article 37, the DPSPs are not justiciable (i.e., they cannot be enforced through legal action in courts). They are not legally binding and do not carry any legal consequences if violated. Statement 2 is correct: The provisions of the Directive Principles of State Policy are not enforceable by any court. This means that citizens cannot directly approach the courts for the enforcement of these principles, unlike Fundamental Rights (which are enforceable in court). Statement 3 is correct: Although DPSPs are not enforceable by courts, they are intended to influence the state’s policies and lawmaking process. They act as guiding principles for the government to ensure that the laws passed are aligned with the values of social justice, equality, and welfare. SUPER HINT \"If DPSPs were enforceable by courts, then what would be the difference between DPSPs and Fundamental Rights?","PW-1957":"Article 50 (Part IV,Directive Principle of State Policy) specifically addresses the separation of the judiciary from the executive. This principle is rooted in liberal-intellectual ideals, which align with the doctrine of separation of powers. The separation ensures that the legislative, executive, and judicial branches function independently, preventing the concentration of power in one branch. By doing so, it helps safeguard individual rights and freedoms, crucial for a functioning democracy. 73","PW-1958":"Statement 1 is correct: Free legal services are available to the groups of society that are listed under Section 12 of the Legal Services Authorities Act, they are:  Women and children  Members of SC/ST  Industrial workmen  Victims of mass disaster, violence, flood, drought, earthquake industrial disaster  Disabled persons  Persons in custody  Persons whose annual income does not exceed ₹1 lakh or may be prescribed by the State Government  Beggars or those who have fallen victim to human trafficking. Statement 2 is correct: Income limit for Transgender is Rs. 2,00,000. Statement 3 is incorrect: Though there is a provision for free aid to members of SC and ST community, the Legal Services Authority does not mention Other Backward Classes (OBC) while providing free legal services. Statement 4 is incorrect: The provision of free legal services to Senior Citizens is dependent on the rules framed by the respective state governments who can prescribe income limits. As a result, not all elderly people qualify for free legal assistance. SUPER HINT For S4, \"All Senior citizens\" is an ","PW-1959":"The 42nd Constitutional Amendment Act of 1976, was enacted during the Emergency period under Prime Minister Indira Gandhi. It significantly altered the Constitution adding in the Preamble socialist, secular, and integrity objectives. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 172 Option (b) is correct: The 42nd Amendment Act of 1976 added three new Directive Principles to the original list and they are:  Article 39 A: To promote equal justice and to provide free legal aid to the poor.  Article 43 A: To take steps to secure the participation of workers in the management of industries.  Article 48 A: To protect and improve the environment and to safeguard forests and wildlife. Other additions to DPSPs were :  44th Constitutional Amendment Act, 1978 added Article 38(2): The State shall strive to minimize inequalities in income, status, facilities, and opportunities among individuals and groups residing in different areas or engaged in different occupations.  86th Amendment Act of 2002: It modified Article 45 and introduced Article 21A, making elementary education a fundamental right. 75","PW-1960":"The directive principles are in the nature of instruments of instruction to the government of the day to achieve certain ends by their actions. Directive Principles of State Policy does not impose any limitations on any organ of the State but they act as moral and political obligations for the state to pursue welfare-oriented policies. It is a guideline that the government of the day can use for the welfare of the socially and economically backward classes while framing any rules. It is the fundamental rights that constitute limitations upon state action (whether legislative or executive). SUPER HINT DPSPs are guiding principles, not binding restrictions. They are meant to guide legislation and executive actions — not limit them. So logically, \"limitation\" ≠ guidance. Hence both statements are likely false. 76","PW-1961":"Statement 1 is correct: The Directive Principles deals with a very comprehensive economic, social and political programme for a modern democratic State. Article 38 deals with the promotion of the welfare of the people by securing and protecting a social order by ensuring social, economic and political justice and by minimising inequalities in income, status, facilities and opportunities. B.R. Ambedkar opined that the Directives have great value because they lay down that the goal of Indian polity is ‘economic democracy’ as distinguished from ‘political democracy’. Statement 2 is correct: According to Article 37 Directive Principles are not enforceable in any court, but the principles therein laid down are nevertheless fundamental in the governance of the country. 77","PW-1962":"The Directive Principles of State Policy (DPSP) are mentioned under Articles 36 to 51 of the Indian Constitution. The DPSPs have been borrowed from the Constitution of Ireland. It constitutes a comprehensive socio economic and political programme for a modern democratic State. DPSP embodies the concept of a ‘welfare state’. Article 38 (1) states that “The State shall strive to promote the welfare of the people by securing and protecting as effectively as it may a social order in which justice, social, economic and political, shall inform all the institutions of the national life”. 78","PW-1963":"Article 51 is clear in dealing with the international peace and security and for achieving the same it directs the State to focus on:  Maintaining just and honourable relations with the nations.  Foster respect for international law and treaty obligations.  Encourage settlement of international disputes by arbitration. 79","PW-1964":"According to Article 37 of the Indian Constitution, though Directive Principles of State Policy (DPSP) are not enforceable by any court, but the principles therein laid down are nevertheless fundamental in the governance of the country and it shall be the duty of the State to apply these principles in making laws. DPSP constitutes a comprehensive socio-economic and political programme for a modern democratic State. DPSP are ‘positive in nature’, which embodies the concept of a ‘welfare state’ and not that of a ‘police state’. DPSP are the constitutional instructions or recommendations to the State in legislative, executive and administrative matters. Polity 173 80","PW-1965":"The Directive Principles of State Policy (DPSP) are mentioned under Articles 36 to 51 of the Indian Constitution. Directive Principles of State Policy are classified into Socialist, Gandhian and Liberal-Intellectual. The Gandhian principles of DPSP include:  Article 40 of the Constitution deals with Organising Village Panchayats and endows them with necessary powers and authority to enable them to function as units of self- government.  The idea of Promoting Cottage Industries on an individual or co-operation basis in rural areas is based on Gandhian Principles and is mentioned under Article 43. Socialistic Principles Gandhian Principles Liberal- Intellectual Principles Article 38 – Social justice Article 40 – Village panchayats Article 44 – Uniform civil code Article 39 – Equal pay, resource distribution Article 43 – Promotion of cottage industries Article 45 – Early childhood care Article 41 – Right to work, education, and public assistance Article 46 – Education & economic interests of SC/STs Article 48A – Protection of environment Article 42 – Maternity relief Article 47 – Nutr","PW-1966":"Option (1) is correct: Directive Principle of State lays down the provisions of education under :  Article 45: Provides for early childhood care and education.  Article 46: Promotes educational and economic interests of weaker sections (SCs, STs, and other disadvantaged groups). Option (2) is correct: Rural and Urban Local Bodies  The Schedule 11 added by the 73rd Constitutional Amendment Act of 1992, specifies the powers, responsibilities and authority of Panchayat and under Article 243-G the Panchayati Raj Institutions have allowed 29 subjects to work in their local areas and Education is one of them.  The Schedule 12 added by the 74th Constitutional Amendment Act of 1992, specifies the powers, responsibilities and authority of Municipalities and under the Article 243-W the Constitution provides for 18 subjects to the Municipalities including education. Options (3) and (4) are correct :  Fifth Schedule: Governs Scheduled Areas and Tribes, ensuring educational development for tribal communities through special provisions.  Sixth Schedule: Grants Autonomous District Councils (A","PW-1967":"Statement 1 is Incorrect: The prohibition of traffic in human beings and forced labour is covered under Article 23, which is part of the Fundamental Rights, not the Directive Principles of State Policy (DPSP). Statement 2 is correct: The prohibition of intoxicating drinks and drugs which are injurious to health, except for medicinal purposes, is included in the Directive Principles of State Policy under Article 47, which directs the state to improve public health and to prohibit harmful substances. 83","PW-1968":"Statement 1 is Incorrect: The provision of free and compulsory education for children in the 6-14 age group was included in the Constitution of India through the Eighty-sixth Amendment (not the Seventy-sixth) in 2002, which inserted Article 21A. Statement 2 is correct: Sarva Shiksha Abhiyan (SSA) aims to provide universal education and includes the promotion of computer education in rural areas as part of its broader educational reforms. Statement 3 is correct: Education was moved to the Concurrent List under Item 25 by the Forty-second Amendment in 1976. This allows both the Centre and states to legislate on education. 84","PW-1969":"Statement 1 is incorrect: The Constitution of India does encourage equal pay for equal work for both men and women under Article 39(d), which is part of the Directive Principles of State Policy. The Directive Principles call for the state to ensure that there is no discrimination between men and women in terms of equal pay for equal work. Statement 2 is correct: The Constitution of India does not provide a specific definition of backward classes. However, it provides for affirmative action through Articles 15(4), 16(4), and 46 to promote the welfare of backward classes, but leaves the identification and classification of such groups to the state. 85","PW-1970":"The Directive Principles of State Policy (DPSP) aim to establish social and economic democracy in India. These principles serve as guidelines for the state to promote the welfare of the people and create a just society. DPSPs are enshrined in Part IV of the Indian Constitution, spanning from Articles 36 to 51. Unlike Fundamental Rights, DPSPs are non-enforceable by courts. However, they act as instruments of instruction for governments, guiding them to undertake positive actions towards achieving social and economic equity. 86","PW-1971":"The Indian Constitution’s Directive Principles of State Policy (DPSP) include Article 51, which underscores the nation’s commitment to promoting global peace and security. Key provisions of Article 51 covers:  Maintenance of Just and Honorable Relations: Advocates fair and respectful international relations.  Respect for International Law: Upholds adherence to global legal principles.  Peaceful Resolution of Disputes: Supports resolving conflicts through diplomacy and negotiation 8. FUNDAMENTAL DUTIES 87","PW-1972":"","PW-1973":"One of the Fundamental Duties is to “To protect the sovereignty, unity and integrity of India\" A-51 A (c). among the 11 Fundamental Duties. Article 51A of part IV-A of the Indian Constitution deals with the Fundamental Duties. These duties are the moral and civic obligations that all citizens of a nation have. In 1976, the Fundamental Duties were first recommended by the Swaran Singh Committee by 42nd Constitutional Amendment Act, 1976. Polity 175 Justice J.S. Verma Committee was established in 1999 to make recommendations on how to enforce fundamental duties in India. The committee's goal was to instill civic consciousness and a sense of responsibility in citizens. 89","PW-1974":"Article 51A of part IV-A of the Indian Constitution deals with the Fundamental Duties. These duties are the moral and civic obligations that all citizens of a nation have. To vote in public elections is not a fundamental duty as it is not included in article 51A. List of Fundamental Duties:  To abide by the Constitution and respect National Flag and National Anthem (Not national song)  To follow the noble ideals that inspired the struggle for freedom.  To protect the sovereignty, unity and integrity of India.  To render national service when called upon to do so.  To promote the common spirit of brotherhood amongst all Indians + to renounce practices derogatory to the dignity of women.  To preserve the rich heritage of the country’s culture.  To protect the national environment including forests, lakes, wildlife, etc.  To develop scientific temper, humanism and spirit of reform and inquiry.  To safeguard public property and to abjure violence.  To strive towards excellence in all spheres of individuals.  To provide opportunity for education to his child between the age 6 a","PW-1975":"Part XX of the Indian Constitution outlines the procedure for amending the Constitution. Article 368, which falls under this part, states that Parliament, in the exercise of its constituent power, may amend any provision of the Constitution through addition, variation, or repeal, following the prescribed procedure.  Addition: Introducing new provisions into the Constitution (e.g., Fundamental Duties were incorporated through the 42nd Amendment).  Variation: Modifying existing provisions (e.g., the voting age was lowered from 21 to 18 by the 61st Amendment).  Repeal: Removing provisions from the Constitution (e.g., Right to Property ceased to be a Fundamental Right after the 44th Amendment). SUPER HINT You can try, The \"NOT\" approach for all statements, this tests the improbability of negating a statement—if de- nying its impact seems highly unlikely, the statement is plausibly true. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 176 92","PW-1976":"","PW-1977":"Statement 1 is incorrect: It was the 39th Constitutional Amendment (1975), passed during the Emergency, that placed elections for key offices like Prime Minister beyond judicial review. The 44th Amendment (1978) reversed several provisions of the 42nd Amendment, restoring civil liberties and the right to property. Polity 177 Statement 2 is correct: The 99th Constitutional Amendment aimed to establish the National Judicial Appointments Commission (NJAC). But in 2015, the Supreme Court struck it down, affirming the collegium system. Justice JS Kehar, who was part of the bench that struck down the NJAC, emphasized that NJAC undermined the judicial independence which is crucial for safeguarding citizens’ rights. Collegium System in India: The Collegium System is used for the appointment and transfer of judges in the Supreme Court and High Courts. It is not mentioned in the Constitution but evolved through Supreme Court rulings. 95","PW-1978":"Statement 1 is incorrect: Though the 42nd Amendment Act of 1976 curtailed the power of HC in judicial review and debarred the HC from considering the constitutional validity of any central law. But the 43rd Amendment Act of 1978 restored the original position of the HC. Moreover now the HC is considered as the principal civil courts of original jurisdiction in each state and union territory. They can declare any central law to be constitutionally invalid in their jurisdiction. Statement 2 is incorrect: The Constitution of India allows for amendments under Article 368 but the Supreme Court has the authority to review constitutional amendments, particularly to ensure that such amendments do not violate the basic structure of the Constitution. The Kesavananda Bharati case (1973) established the basic structure doctrine, where the Supreme Court ruled that Parliament could amend the Constitution but could not alter its basic structure. SUPER HINT For S1, a general observation can tell that HC's in India do declare central laws invalid, we have integrated judiciary! Saying they cannot decl","PW-1979":"Statement 1 is incorrect: An amendment of the Constitution can be initiated by the introduction of a bill in either house of the Parliament. (not only in Lok Sabha). Statement 2 is incorrect: If the bill seeks to amend the Federal provisions of the Constitution, then it must also be ratified by the legislatures of half of the states by a simple majority and not all the states. 97","PW-1980":"","PW-1981":"The Eighth Schedule of the Indian Constitution lists the officially recognized languages of India. This schedule was expanded in 2003 through the Constitution (Ninety-second Amendment) Act, which added four additional languages: Bodo, Dogri, Maithili, and Santhali. This amendment increased the total number of languages in the Eighth Schedule from 18 to 22.  The 93rd Constitutional Amendment Act enables reservations for socially and educationally backward classes in admission to educational institutions including private educational institutions, whether aided or unaided by the State, other than the minority educational institutions.  The 91st Constitutional Amendment Act limits the number of ministers in the Council of Ministers, including the Prime Minister, to a maximum of 15% of the total members of the Lok Sabha (House of the People)(Similarly it applies to State CoM also.) UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 178  90th Constitutional Amendment Act provided for maintaining the erstwhile representation of the Scheduled Tribes in the Assam legislative assembly from the Bodoland Territorial Area","PW-1982":"According to the 91st Constitution Amendment Act,2003, the number of ministers, including the Prime Minister or Chief Minister, cannot exceed 15% of the total membership of the Lok Sabha at the Centre or the Legislative Assembly at the State level. It was formulated primarily to address concerns about the excessive size of the Council of Ministers and to strengthen anti-defection laws. The Act aimed to streamline the functioning of the Indian government and curb political opportunism. The 93rd Amendment Act of 2005 added Clause (5) to Article 15 of the Indian Constitution, allowing the government to make special provisions for the advancement of socially and educationally backward classes, Scheduled Castes, and Scheduled Tribes in education. This includes reservations in private educational institutions, both aided and unaided by the government, except for minority institutions. The Ninety-fifth Amendment of the Constitution of India, officially known as The Constitution (Ninety-fifth Amendment) Act, 2009, extended the period of reservation of seats for the Scheduled Castes and Sched","PW-1983":"The 104th Constitution Amendment Bill deals specifically with the issue of reservation or quota for Socially and Educationally Backward Classes (SEBCs) in private educational institutions. It was aimed to extend the reservations or affirmative action to private educational institutions so that SEBCs could access quality education in private institutions as well. Before this amendment, reservation policies applied primarily to government-run institutions, and private institutions were largely free to admit students on their own terms, without any mandatory quota for backward classes. 101","PW-1984":"The 98th Constitutional Amendment Bill was introduced in India to reform the judicial appointment process by establishing a National Judicial Commission (NJC). The NJC was proposed to replace the existing collegium system, which had been criticized for its lack of transparency and accountability in selecting judges. The Commission would have included the Chief Justice of India, senior judges, and members from the executive, ensuring a more inclusive and structured process for judicial appointments. However, the proposed amendment did not come into effect, as it was struck down by the Supreme Court, which upheld the collegium system in its 2015 judgment. Probably UPSC has mistakenly used word ‘Act instead of bill’. 102","PW-1985":"","PW-1986":"","PW-1987":"A Financial Emergency under Article 360 of the Indian Constitution can be declared if the President believes that India’s financial stability or credit is threatened. It allows the central government to assume control over state finances and redistribute resources. Statement 1 is correct: Article 360 of the Indian Constitution specifies that a proclamation of financial emergency must be approved by both Houses of Parliament within two months of being issued; if not, it will automatically cease to operate after this period. Statement given aligns with the provisions under Article 360, making this statement accurate. Statement 2 is incorrect: While it is true that during a financial emergency, the President has the authority to issue directions for the reduction of salaries and allowances of persons serving in connection with the Union’s affairs, it is not true that Judges of the Supreme Court and High Courts are exempt from such reductions. In fact, the President is empowered to apply these measures to all public servants, including judges, during a financial emergency. Therefore, thi","PW-1988":"Article 355 states that “It shall be the duty of the Union to protect every State against external aggression and internal disturbance and to ensure that the government of every State is carried on in accordance with the provisions of this Constitution.” 11. FUNDS WITH GOVERNMENT OF INDIA 111","PW-1989":"Article 266 further says, No money out of this fund can be issued except in accordance with a parliamentary law. Thus, the authorization for the withdrawal of funds from the Consolidated Fund of India must come from the Parliament of India. Article 266 states that all receipts are credited to the Consolidated fund of India, and all payments are debited from it. All the legally authorised payments on behalf of the Government of India are made out of this fund 112","PW-1990":"The Consolidated Fund of India is the primary fund of the Union Government where all its revenues, including taxes, loans, and other receipts for the conduct of government business, are deposited. According to the Constitution of India, all government spending must be approved by Parliament and drawn from this fund. The accounts of Government are kept in three parts: 1. Consolidated Fund of India 2. Contingency Fund of India and 3. Public Account Different Funds With GoI CONSOLIDATED FUND OF INDIA (ARTICLE 266) PUBLIC ACCOUNT OF INDIA (Article 266) CONTINGENCY FUND OF INDIA (Article 267) It is a fund to which all receipts are credited and all payments are debited. All the legally authorised payments on behalf of the Government of India are made out of this fund. No money out of this fund can be issued except in accordance with a parliamentary law. All public money other than those which are credited to the CFI shall be credited here. Includes provident fund deposits, judicial deposits, savings bank deposits, departmental deposits, remittances and so on. Operated by executive action. ","PW-1991":"A constitutional government is one where the powers of the government are limited by a constitution, ensuring rule of law, separation of powers, and the protection of citizens' rights. It operates within legal limits set by the constitution, preventing arbitrary rule and ensuring accountability. Checks and balances are in place to prevent the misuse of power, while fundamental rights and freedoms of citizens remain safeguarded. Although both democratic and non-democratic states can have a constitution, a true constitutional government ensures that all authorities function within legal constraints, upholding transparency, fairness, and accountability. SUPER HINT If the question asks 'What is a constitutional govern- ment?', then the correct option must logically involve the Constitution. Only option D does that — so it's the most likely correct. 114","PW-1992":"Statement 1 is correct: Indian Parliamentary system is based on constitutional supremacy, hence power of the Parliament to legislate is limited. Whereas, the British Model is based on Parliamentary sovereignty. So, as regards the legislation, the British Parliament is supreme. Statement 2 is correct: In India, the Supreme Court has judicial review powers and can examine the constitutionality of parliamentary laws and amendments. Under Article 145(3), Cases involving substantial constitutional questions can be referred to a Constitution Bench . This also ensures that Parliament operates within constitutional limits and cannot amend the Basic Structure (Kesavananda Bharati case, 1973). In Britain, the scenario is different, here Parliament is supreme, and no court can question or strike down its laws. Unlike India, there is no concept of judicial review over parliamentary legislation, making Parliament's decisions final and legally unchallengeable. Difference between INDIAN & BRITISH MODELS INDIAN MODEL BRITISH MODEL  Republican system: Head of State (President) is indirectly elected.","PW-1993":"A Parliamentary System of Government is characterized by the executive (Government) being accountable to the legislature (Parliament). Its other key features generally include :  Collective Responsibility: The Council of Ministers, led by the Prime Minister, is collectively responsible to the Lok Sabha (Lower House in India).  Motion of No Confidence: The government can be removed by the Parliament through a vote of no confidence.  Executive from the Legislature: The Prime Minister and Ministers are drawn from the legislature and remain in office as long as they have its confidence. 116","PW-1994":"A constitutional government is a system in which the powers of the government are limited by a constitution. This ensures that government actions are guided by established laws rather than arbitrary decisions. The core idea of a constitutional government is limited government, where authority is regulated, checked, and balanced by a legal framework. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 182 117","PW-1995":"Democracy thrives on active citizen participation. It is shaped by the collective wisdom, judgment, and moral character of the people. Unlike authoritarian systems that concentrate power in a few hands, democracy nurtures the intelligence and character of individuals. It empowers ordinary men and women to take part in decision- making. This ensures that governance reflects public interest, accountability, and justice. People can express their opinions, contribute to society, and help shape the nation's future. Democracy stands out for fostering widespread involvement and collective responsibility. SUPER HINT Democracy is for the people, by the people, and of the people. If a question asks about the superior virtue of democracy, the correct option must directly refer to the people. Only option A does that — so it’s most likely correct 118","PW-1996":"India follows a Parliamentary System of Government, where the executive (Council of Ministers, led by the Prime Minister) is collectively accountable to the legislature (Lok Sabha). This fundamental principle is outlined in Article 75(3) of the Indian Constitution, which mandates that the Council of Ministers remains collectively responsible to the Lok Sabha. This provision ensures executive accountability and is a defining feature of parliamentary democracy. 119","PW-1997":"A constitutional government is one that operates within the framework of a Constitution. The principle of constitutionalism emphasizes limiting the power of the state to ensure it remains fair and accountable, preventing any form of autocratic rule. Statement 1 is incorrect: Places effective restrictions on individual liberty in the interest of State Authority” is not characteristic of a Constitutional Government. One of the fundamental principles of a constitutional government is to protect individual rights and freedoms and not to restrict them unnecessarily in favor of state authority. Statement 2 is correct: A constitutional government limits the authority of the state to prevent it from infringing on individual rights and freedoms. This is achieved through mechanisms such as constitutional checks and balances, the separation of powers, and the judicial review of government actions. 120","PW-1998":"Statement 1 is incorrect: The Advocate General of a State in India is appointed not by the President but directly by the Governor of the concerned State. This appointment is made under Article 165 of the Indian Constitution. He holds office during the pleasure of the Governor. Statement 2 is incorrect: The jurisdiction of High Courts is defined by the Constitution of India, not the Civil Procedure Code (CPC). High Courts possess original, appellate, and sometimes advisory jurisdiction, but this is based on constitutional provisions and specific statutes, not the CPC. 121","PW-1999":"Statement 1 is incorrect: The Central Administrative Tribunal (CAT), a quasi judicial body, was established in 1985 under Article 323 -A of the Constitution through the Administrative Tribunal Act 1985 during Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi’s tenure, not during Lal Bahadur Shastri’s term (1964- 1966). Statement 2 is correct: The Central Administrative Tribunal (CAT) members come from both judicial and administrative backgrounds. They include judges qualified for High Courts and officers from Central or State Governments, appointed by the President of India. This mix ensures swift and effective justice in administrative matters related to grievances of central and state government employees. 122","PW-2000":"Statement 1 is correct: The number of ministries on 15th August 1947 was 18. At the time of independence, the government had basic departments like Home Affairs, Defence, Finance, External Affairs, etc, to handle the essential governance functions. The number of ministries was quite small as the nation was just beginning to organize itself administratively after the end of British rule. Statement 2 is incorrect: In 2009, the number of ministries of the Indian government was much higher than 36. At present in November 2024 there are 53 ministries in the central government of India covering a wide range of administrative, governance, and policy functions. 123","PW-2001":"","PW-2002":"Statement 1 is incorrect: As per Article 54 of the Constitution, the President of India is elected by the Members of an Electoral College consisting of :  The elected members of both Houses of Parliament.  The elected members of the Legislative Assemblies of all States [including the National Capital Territory of Delhi and the Union Territory of Puducherry].  The Members nominated to either House of Parliament or the Legislative Assemblies of States, including NCT of Delhi and Union Territory of Puducherry, are not eligible to be included in the Electoral College. Statement 2 is incorrect: The higher the number of elective Assembly seats, the higher the value of the vote of each MLA of that State is not always true as it depends on the ratio of the total population to the total number of elective seats. Statement 3 is incorrect: The value of the vote of each MLA of Madhya Pradesh is less than that of Kerala, as it depends on the ratio of the total population to the total number of elective seats. Statement 4 is correct: Based on the ratio of the total population to the total numbe","PW-2003":"Statement 1 is incorrect: If the election of a person as President is declared void by the Supreme Court, acts done by him before the date of such declaration of the Supreme Court are not invalidated and continue to remain in force. Statement 2 is incorrect: Where an assembly is dissolved, the members cease to be qualified to vote in Presidential elections, even if fresh elections to the dissolved assembly are not held before the Presidential elections. Statement 3 is incorrect: When a bill is sent to the President after it has been passed by the Parliament, he can give his assent to the bill, withhold his assent to the bill or return the bill (if it is not a money bill) for reconsideration of the Parliament. No time limit has been fixed by the Constitution within which the President has to give his/her assent to the bill. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 184 SUPER HINT S1 is an extreme statement and violates common sense. The President performs major constitutional functions — signing laws, appointments, pardons, etc. If those be- come invalid, it would create a constitutional crisis. So logica","PW-2004":"The President of India is elected indirectly by the Electoral College and it is conducted in accordance with the system of proportional representation by means of single transferable vote. Statement 1 is correct: The President of India is elected by an electoral college consisting of: 1. Elected members of the two Houses of Parliament and Legislative Assemblies of the States 2. States includes national capital territory of Delhi and the Union territory of Pondicherry The value of votes of MLAs would differ from State to State as it is based on population criterion and population of each state has a different value. Statement 2 is incorrect: The value of vote of each MP is the same whether it is Lok Sabha or Rajya Sabha. There shall be uniformity in the scale of representation of the different states at the election of the President as follows: Value of vote of an MLA of a state: (Population of state / Total number of elected members of state legislative assembly) * 100 Value of vote of an MP: (Total value of votes of MLA’s of all states/ Total number of elected members parliament) * ","PW-2005":"Statement 1 is incorrect: As per the Article 53(1), the executive power of the Union shall be vested in the President and shall be exercised by him either directly or through officers subordinate to him in accordance with this Constitution. Statement 2 is incorrect: The Cabinet Secretary is the top- most executive official and senior-most civil servant of the Government of India and he/she is the ex-officio head of the Civil Services Board. 128","PW-2006":"The executive organ of government is responsible for implementing and enforcing laws and policies enacted by the legislature. It is typically headed by the President or Prime Minister and includes various government departments and agencies. Statement 1 is correct: India follows a Parliamentary type of Government in which the President is the constitutional head of the state. He is the Executive head of India. Article 77(3) of the Indian Constitution says that the President shall make rules for the more convenient transaction of the business of the Government of India, and for the allocation among Ministers of the said business. Statement 2 is incorrect: Article 77(1) of the Indian Constitution lays down all executive action of the Government of India shall be expressed to be taken in the name of the President. SUPER HINT S2 aligns with Function-person/organisation/ministry match trap as its easy to manipulate to make it false. Is it PM or President? 129","PW-2007":"India follows a Parliamentary type of Government in which the President is the constitutional head of the state. He is the Executive head of India and all the executive powers of the Union shall be vested in him. The President lays Reports and Statements before the parliament of the following bodies:  Reports of the Comptroller and Auditor General  Annual report of UPSC  Reports of Finance Commission.  Reports of Special officers of SC & ST  Report of the National Commission for Scheduled Castes and Scheduled Tribes  Report of the National Commission of Backward Classes. Polity 185 130","PW-2008":"","PW-2009":"Statement 1 is incorrect: The formula: The value of the vote of an elected Member of Legislative Assembly equals = [{State Population / (Number of Elected MLAs of the state} X 1000]. Thus the equation should have 1000 at the place of multiplication not 100. Statement 2 is correct: The statement is slightly incorrect because the value of vote of an elected member of the Parliament equals the total value of the votes of all elected MLAs divided by total number of elected MPs. Statement 3 is incorrect: For the 2003 question the latest Presidential election was held in 2002 which had 4896 electors. 133","PW-2010":"The formula for electing the President of India considers each state’s population and the number of elected members in the state’s Legislative Assembly. In 1997 R K Narayanan with nearly 95% defeated T N Seshan who got nearly 5% vote. The census used in the election was 1971 due to complex interplay of politics and constitutional provisions. Even the Presidential election 2022 used the 1971 census. The 84th Constitutional Amendment act 2001 froze the use of census data from 1971 till 2026. 134","PW-2011":"Article 54 states that the President is elected by an electoral college consisting of members from both Houses of Parliament and elected members from State Legislative Assemblies, including those from Delhi and Pondicherry. Under Article 61, any of the two Houses of Parliament initiates impeachment with a 14-day written notice to the President signed by one-fourth of its members. The resolution must pass by a two-thirds majority of the membership. The other House investigates the charges. If the investigating House also passes the resolution by a two-thirds majority of membership, the President is impeached. The president has the right to appear and to be represented at such an investigation. The Article 61 does not mention the State Legislatures. 14. VICE-PRESIDENT 135","PW-2012":"Statement 1 is incorrect: In accordance with Article 64 of the Constitution of India, the Vice President of India is the ex-officio Chairman of Rajya Sabha. The House also elects a Deputy Chairman from among its members. Hence, the Deputy Chairman of the Rajya Sabha is the member of that house. Statement 2 is correct: The Vice President is elected indirectly by an electoral college consisting of all members of parliament (Both elected & nominated). The election is conducted in accordance with the system of proportional representation by means of single transferable vote. Vice President of India The Vice President of India is the second-highest constitutional authority and serves as the ex-officio Chairman of the Rajya Sabha (Upper House of Parliament).  Election & Term:  Elected indirectly by Members of Parliament (MPs) from both Houses through a secret ballot using the Single Transferable Vote (STV) system.  Serves a 5-year term but can be re-elected.  Powers & Responsibilities:  Acts as Rajya Sabha Chairman – Presides over sessions but votes only in case of a tie.  Acts as Pr","PW-2013":"The Vice President of India is the second-highest constitutional office in the country, serving as the ex officio Chairman of the Rajya Sabha. In case of the President’s absence or vacancy, the Vice President assumes the role of acting President. Mohammad Hidayatullah and Shankar Dayal Sharma were Vice-President and later became President of India. Fakhruddin Ali Ahmad and Neelam Sanjiva Reddy were never a vice-President but did become President of India. 137","PW-2014":"According to Article 67(b) of the Constitution, Vice- President can be removed from office through a resolution passed by a majority of all current members of the Council of States(Rajya sabha), which must also be approved by the House of the People. However, no such resolution can be introduced unless at least fourteen days’ notice is given before moving the resolution. This process ensures sufficient time for discussion and consideration before any action is taken. Hence the most appropriate answer is Rajya Sabha. 15. PRIME MINISTER 138","PW-2015":"As per the Article 75(1) of the Indian Constitution, the Prime Minister is appointed by the President, who also appoints other ministers on the advice of the Prime Minister. A person who is not a member of the Parliament/State legislature can be appointed as PM/CM for six months, within which time, he should be elected to the Parliament/State legislature as per Supreme Court judgments. 139","PW-2016":"Statement 1 is incorrect: Under Article 75, the President appoints the Prime Minister, and the other Ministers are appointed by the President based on the Prime Minister’s advice. The Cabinet Secretary has no official role in the creation of either Ministries or Departments of the Government of India. Statement 2 is correct: According to Article 75 of the Constitution of India, after the general elections or ministry reshuffling, the Prime Minister advises the President on the appointment of ministers to various ministries. The President, acting on the advice of the Prime Minister, formally assigns ministries to the elected ministers. 140","PW-2017":"Assertion (A) is false: As per the Article 75(3) the Council of Ministers shall be collectively responsible to the House of the People (Lok sabha) only. Reason (R) is true: As per article 75(5) A Minister who for a period of six consecutive months is not a member of either House of Parliament shall at the expiration of that period cease to be a Minister. Thus members of both houses can be a Minister of the Union Government of India. However a person that is not a member of either house can be a minister for a maximum of 6 months. 141","PW-2018":"Statement 1 is correct: Jawaharlal Nehru was in PM’s Office for four terms (1947-52, 1952-57, 1957-62 and 1962-64 until death). Statement 2 is incorrect: JL Nehru represented Phulpur Lok Sabha Constituency near Allahabad. Indira Gandhi represented Rae Bareilly while Rajiv Gandhi represented Amethi LS constituencies. Statement 3 is correct: Morarji Desai, from the Janata Party, became the first non-Congress Prime Minister on March 24, 1977. 142","PW-2019":"","PW-2020":"As per Article 75(1), the Prime Minister advises the President on the appointment of ministers, and the President is bound to act on this advice. While the Prime Minister can nominate any individual to be appointed as a minister, they must become a Member of Parliament within six months, as per Article 75(5). The Prime Minister is not required to consult the President when selecting ministers, making it clear that the discretion in this matter lies entirely with the Prime Minister, not the President. 16. PARLIAMENT 144","PW-2021":"Statement 1 is incorrect: The President shall in respect of every financial year cause to be laid before both the Houses of Parliament a statement of estimated receipts and expenditure of the Government of India for that year. The Union Finance Minister on behalf of the President, lays the annual Financial Statement before both the houses of Parliament. Statement 2 is correct: As per Article 113(3) of the Constitution, no demand for a grant can be made except on the recommendation of the President. Note: UPSC has given option (c) as the official answer. The term ‘budget’ has nowhere been used in the Constitution. It is the popular name for the ‘annual financial statement’ that has been dealt with in Article 112 of the Constitution. The budget is a statement of the estimated receipts and expenditure of the Government of India in a financial year, which begins on 1 April and ends on 31 March of the following year. 145","PW-2022":"Statement 1 is correct: As per Article 96 of the Constitution, the Speaker shall not preside while a resolution for their removal is under consideration. Statement 2 is incorrect: The Speaker has the right to speak and participate in the proceedings related to the resolution for their removal. Statement 3 is incorrect: At such a time he can vote in the first instance, though not in the case of an equality of votes. SUPER HINT For S1, Common sense test: Can someone under re- moval scrutiny act as referee in their own trial? Clearly no. Hence likely true. For S2, Now this sounds too ex- treme. Even an accused in a trial has the right to speak in self-defense. Logically, the Speaker must be allowed to present their case. Hence S2 likely false. Giving option A as correct. 146","PW-2023":"When the Lok Sabha is dissolved, all business, including bills, motions, resolutions, notices, petitions and so on pending before it or its committees lapse. They (to be pursued further) must be reintroduced in the newly constituted Lok Sabha. However, some pending bills do not lapse on the dissolution of the Lok Sabha. The position with respect to the lapsing of bills is as follows : Statement 1 is correct: As per Rule 206 of the Lok Sabha Rules and Article 107(5) of the Constitution, any bill (whether it originated in the Lok Sabha or was transmitted to it by the Rajya Sabha) pending in the Lok Sabha automatically lapses upon its dissolution Statement 2 is correct: If the Lok Sabha passes a bill, but it is pending in the Rajya Sabha, the bill lapses on the dissolution of the Lok Sabha (Article 107(5)). Statement 3 is incorrect: If the President has already notified their intention to convene a joint sitting, then the bill remains alive and does not lapse even if the Lok Sabha is dissolved. Example: In 1970, the Banking Service Commission (Repeal) Bill was scheduled for a joint sitt","PW-2024":"","PW-2025":"Statement 1 is correct: Article 109 outlines the special procedure for the passage of Money Bills, that include the exclusive role of the Lok Sabha and limited powers of the Rajya Sabha. Statement 2 is correct: As per Article 109, a Money Bill shall not be introduced in the Council of States. Polity 189 Statement 3 is correct: Rajya Sabha can only suggest amendments ; it can neither amend nor reject the bill.  If Lok Sabha accepts Rajya Sabha’s recommendations, the Money Bill is deemed passed with the accepted amendments.  If Lok Sabha rejects all Rajya Sabha recommendations, the Money Bill is deemed passed in its original form, without any amendments suggested by the Council of States.  If Rajya Sabha fails to return a Money Bill within 14 days, it is deemed passed by both Houses in its original form as approved by Lok Sabha. Statement 4 is incorrect: After a Money Bill has been passed by the House of the People, it shall be transmitted to the Council of States for its recommendations, and the Council of States shall, within a period of fourteen days from the date of receipt of t","PW-2026":"Statement 1 is correct: The Lok Sabha Ethics Committee was first constituted as an ad hoc committee in 2000 by Speaker Late G.M.C. Balayogi, following a Committee of Privileges recommendation during the 13th Lok Sabha. It became a permanent committee in 2015. Statement 2 is incorrect: Any person can complain against a Member through another Lok Sabha Member of Parliament, along with evidence of the alleged misconduct and an affidavit stating that the complaint is not “false, frivolous, or vexatious”. If the Member himself complains, the affidavit is not needed. Statement 3 is correct: The Committee does not entertain complaints based only on media reports or on matters that are sub-judice. The Committee makes a prima facie inquiry before deciding to examine a complaint. It makes its recommendations after evaluating the complaint. The Committee presents its report to the Speaker, who asks the House if it should be considered. A half-hour discussion is also provided. 150","PW-2027":"Delimitation means the act or process of fixing the limits or boundaries of territorial constituencies in a country having a legislative body. In India, such Delimitation Commissions have been constituted four times:  1952 under the Delimitation Commission Act, 1952  1963 under the Delimitation Commission Act, 1962  1973 under the Delimitation Act, 1972  2002 under the Delimitation Act, 2002 Under Article 82, Parliament enacts a Delimitation Act after each Census, while Article 170 mandates the division of states into territorial constituencies as per the Delimitation Act. The ‘Delimitation Commission’ is set up under an act of Parliament. 151","PW-2028":"Statement 1 is incorrect : A Finance Bill (other than a Money Bill) is not solely a Money Bill, so the Rajya Sabha has the power to suggest amendments or reject it. However, If the finance bill is a money bill Rajyasabha has no power to amend or reject the bill. Statement 2 is correct : As per Article 110, Rajya Sabha has no power to amend or reject a Money Bill. It can only make recommendations, which the Lok Sabha may accept or reject. If Rajya Sabha does not act within 14 days, the Money Bill is deemed to have been passed. Statement 3 is correct : For the Money Bill, the Lok Sabha's decision is final. So there is no question of deadlock. However, for a Finance Bill(other than Money Bill), in case of a disagreement, a joint sitting of both Houses may be called, as it is a normal Bill and not a Money Bill. 152","PW-2029":"Statement 1 is correct: The election date of the Deputy Speaker of Lok Sabha is not fixed in the Constitution. However, according to Rule 8 of the Rules of Procedure and Conduct of Business in Lok Sabha,  The Speaker decides the date of election of the Deputy Speaker.  The election usually happens after the Speaker's election, but there is no constitutional or statutory time limit for it. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 190 Statement 2 is incorrect: There is no such mandatory provision that the election of a candidate, as Deputy Speaker of Lok Sabha, shall be from either the principal opposition party or the ruling party. It is only by convention that the position of Deputy Speaker is offered to the opposition party in India. Statement 3 is correct: In case of the absence of the Speaker, the Deputy Speaker presides over the sessions of the Lok Sabha and conducts the business in the house, during such time he/she enjoys the same power as the Speaker when presiding over the sitting of the House. Statement 4 is incorrect: The appointment of the Deputy Speaker of the Lok Sabha is not initiated by","PW-2030":"Statement 1 is incorrect: The proclamation of Emergency must be approved by both the Houses of Parliament within one month from the date of its issue. If approved by both the Houses of Parliament, the emergency continues for six months, and can be extended to an indefinite period with an approval of the Parliament for every six months. Statement 2 is correct: A No-Confidence Motion can only be initiated and passed in the Lok Sabha (House of the People). The Rajya Sabha (Upper House) cannot move or pass a No-Confidence Motion against the government. Statement 3 is incorrect: As per Article 61, when a President is to be impeached for violation of the Constitution, the charges can be initiated by either House of Parliament. The impeachment resolution needs to be passed by not less than a majority of two- thirds of the total membership in each house. 154","PW-2031":"Statement 1 is incorrect: The constitution mentions the word ‘council of ministers’, however it doesn’t classify ministers into 4 categories. Generally, the Prime Minister and other Ministers are collectively known as the Council of Ministers. Statement 2 is correct: As per 91st Constitutional Amendment Act, the total number of Central Council of Ministers/State Council of Ministers including Prime Minister/ Chief Minister should not be more than 15% of total strength of Lok Sabha. It aimed at curbing the growing size of Cabinets at both the Union and State levels, which had often led to inefficient governance, excessive expenditure, and political instability. The goal was to promote good governance, encourage coalition politics, and reduce the influence of “buying loyalty” by offering ministerial positions. SUPER HINT For S1, Trap Alert: “The Constitution classifies...” UPSC loves to trap you with “Constitution does this” when in reality it’s convention, rule, or practice. Hence likely false, eliminates options A and C. 155","PW-2032":"Statement 1 is correct: The objective of the scheme is to enable MPs to recommend works of developmental nature with emphasis on the creation of durable community assets based on the locally felt needs to be taken up in their Constituencies. Statement 2 is correct: M.Ps are to recommend every year, works costing at least 15% of the MPLADS entitlement for the year for areas inhabited by Scheduled Caste population and 7.5% for areas inhabited by S.T. population. Statement 3 is incorrect: The released funds under the MPLAD scheme are non-lapsable i.e. if the money is not utilised, it gets carried to the next year subject to the fulfillment of certain criterion. Statement 4 is correct: The district authority should visit and inspect at least 10% of the works every year. It is also expected to involve the MPs in such activities. 157","PW-2033":"","PW-2034":"Statement 1 is correct: As per Article 85(1), the Constitution gives the power to the President to summon a session of Parliament to meet at such a place as he/she thinks fit. The gap between two sessions must not exceed 6 months. Statement 2 is incorrect: By convention, Parliament meets for three sessions in a year. However the Constitution does not stipulate it. Article 85(1) of the Indian Constitution states \"The President shall from time to time summon each House of Parliament to meet, and six months shall not intervene between its last sitting in one session and the date appointed for its first sitting in the next session.\" This means that according to the Constitution of India, Parliament must meet at least once every six months, but the number of sessions is not fixed. Statement 3 is correct: There is no provision about the minimum number of days that the Parliament is required to meet in a year. 159","PW-2035":"","PW-2036":"The Fiscal Responsibility and Budget Management (FRBM) Act, 2003 aims to ensure fiscal discipline in India by setting targets for government borrowing, fiscal deficits, and public debt. Its objective is to reduce the fiscal deficit and maintain macroeconomic stability. As per the act the Central Government is required to lay before both Houses of Parliament the following fiscal policy statements every financial year, alongside the annual financial statement and demands for grants:  Medium-term Fiscal Policy Statement  Fiscal Policy Strategy Statement  Macro-economic Framework Statement UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 192 161","PW-2037":"","PW-2038":"In India, independent regulators in sectors like telecommunications, insurance, and electricity play a crucial role in ensuring that these sectors function efficiently and fairly. Statement 1 is correct: Ad Hoc Committee set up by Parliament: Temporary committees formed for specific purposes, including reviewing regulators. Statement 2 is correct: Parliamentary Department Related Standing Committee: Main body responsible for scrutinizing independent regulators in sectors like telecommunications, insurance, and electricity. Statement 3 is incorrect: Finance Commission: Primarily deals with financial devolution between the Union and States, not regulatory reviews. Statement 4 is incorrect: Financial Sector Legislative Reforms Commission (FSLRC): Was a one-time commission (2011) to review financial sector laws, not independent regulators. Statement 5 is incorrect: NITI Aayog: Works as a policy think tank, but does not formally review regulators. SUPER HINT S5, NITI is policy advisory, not a regulatory reviewer. No enforcement or oversight mandate. Most Likely false, eliminates options C","PW-2039":"Statement 1 is incorrect: The Communist Party of India (CPI) was the single largest opposition party in the First General Election. CPI won in 16 seats. The Indian National Congress (INC) won a landslide victory, winning 364 of the 489 seats and nearly 45% of the total votes polled. Statement 2 is correct: In 1969, an official leader of the opposition was recognized for the first time. However, it was given statutory recognition in 1977. They are also entitled to the salary, allowances and other facilities equivalent to that of a cabinet minister. Statement 3 is incorrect: In order to receive the status of opposition party and Consequent Leader of Opposition in Loksabha tag a party should secure 10% of the total strength of the House i.e. 55 seats in the Lok Sabha. 164","PW-2040":"","PW-2041":"Article 110 of the Constitution states that a bill is deemed to be a money bill if it contains ‘only’ provisions dealing with all or any of the following matters:  The imposition, abolition, remission, alteration or regulation of any tax;  The regulation of the borrowing of money by the Union government;  The custody of the Consolidated Fund of India or the Contingency Fund of India, the payment of moneys into or the withdrawal of money from any such fund;  The appropriation of money out of the Consolidated Fund of India;  Declaration of any expenditure charged on the Consolidated Fund of India or increasing the amount of any such expenditure;  The receipt of money on account of the Consolidated Fund of India or the public account of India, or the custody or issue of such money, or the audit of the accounts of the Union or of a state;  Any matter incidental to any of the matters specified above. 166","PW-2042":"For a candidate to stand for election to the Lok Sabha (the lower house of the Indian Parliament), certain eligibility criteria must be met, as stipulated by the Section 33 of Representation of the People Act, 1951 and the Constitution of India such as: 1. The candidate must be a citizen of India 2. The age of the candidate should not less than 25 years of age 3. The candidate must be registered as an elector for a parliamentary constituency. SUPER HINT For A, \"Residing\" is too generic. Even a foreign national or a minor may reside in India — does that qualify them to contest Lok Sabha? Clearly no. Hence false. For B, PM Modi contested from Varanasi despite being from Guja- rat. Hence likely false. For D, A 5 year old is a Citizen of India, can S/He contest? Clearly No! Hence most logical choice left is option C. 167","PW-2043":"Statement 1 is incorrect: The Indian constitution adopts the first-past-the-post (FPTP) system of elections where a candidate is declared elected if he/she gets a plurality of the votes, not necessarily 50 percent of the total votes polled. This means that the candidate with the highest number of votes among all contenders is declared the winner, even if they do not achieve an absolute majority. Statement 2 is incorrect: Under Article 93, Speaker and Deputy speaker are elected by the house. This is a convention (not constitutional provision) that usually the Speaker’s post goes to the majority party and the Deputy Speaker’s to the Opposition. This is an established convention to maintain a balance of power and ensure that the ruling party does not control both the key positions. SUPER HINT For Option A, just required normal observation, Have candidates ever won elections even when many others contested, and they got only 30-35% votes?” Yes, fre- quently — especially in multi-cornered contests. Hence S1 likely false. For S2, The phrase “as per the Constitu- tion” is the trap. 168","PW-2044":"The Parliament of India exercises control over the Council of Ministers (including the Prime Minister and other ministers) through various mechanisms such as:  Adjournment Motion is introduced to draw attention of the House to a definite matter of urgent public importance which is definite, factual, urgent, matter of recent occurrence. It needs the support of 50 members to be admitted. It involves an element of censure against the government and hence Rajya Sabha is not permitted to make use of this device.  Question Hour is a crucial tool used by the members of Parliament to question the Council of Ministers regarding their decisions, actions, and the functioning of their departments. During Question Hour (usually the first hour of every sitting in the Lok Sabha and Rajya Sabha), members can ask both oral and written questions on any matter within the jurisdiction of the government. In addition to the ministers, the questions can also be asked to the private members. It has been mentioned in the Rule of Procedure and Conduct of Business in Lok Sabha.  Supplementary questions are ","PW-2045":"Statement 1 is incorrect: A Private Member bill can be introduced by any member of the Parliament other than a minister. A bill introduced by a Minister in the Parliament is generally called a government bill. A Private member bill generally reflects the stand of the opposition party on public matters. There is less likelihood that the Parliament will adopt it. Its rejection by the House has no implication on the parliamentary confidence in the government or its resignation A 1-month notice is required before introducing the Bill. They are discussed only on Fridays in both Houses of Parliament during Private Members’ Business hours. Constitutional Amendment can be moved by Private member bill. Statement 2 is incorrect: As of now around 14 private member’s bills have been passed since independence in Indian Parliament. Examples: The Hindu Marriage (Amendment) Bill 1956, The Orphanages & Other Charitable Homes (Supervision & Control) Bill 1960. Marine Insurance Bill 1959 etc. None have been passed in both Houses since 1970. SUPER HINT For S1, trap lies in the phrase \"not elected but on","PW-2046":"According to Article 249 of the Constitution. Parliament can legislate on a matter enumerated in the State List if a resolution is passed by the Rajya Sabha .The resolution must be passed by a majority of not less than two-thirds of the members present and voting. This means the majority is calculated based on the number of members present and voting, not the total membership of the Rajya Sabha. This is subject to the National Interest clause. The Parliament can legislate on State List matters when it is required in the national interest. 171","PW-2047":"Statement 1 is incorrect: As per Article 107(3), No bill lapses on prorogation. Prorogation does not affect the bills pending before the House. Statement 2 is correct: A Bill pending in the Rajya Sabha, which has not been passed by the Lok Sabha, shall not lapse on dissolution of the Lok Sabha. Conditions under which Bill lapses: 1. Bills pending in the Lok Sabha (whether originating in the Lok Sabha or transmitted to it by the Rajya Sabha) 2. Bills passed by the Lok Sabha but pending in the Rajya Sabha. (Note – A bill originating in Lok Sabha lapses) Conditions under which Bills does not lapse: 1. Bill not passed by the two Houses due to disagreement and if the president has notified the holding of a joint sitting before the dissolution of Lok Sabha 2. Bill pending in the Rajya Sabha but not passed by the Lok Sabha. 3. Bill passed by both Houses but pending assent of the president. 4. Bill passed by both Houses but returned by the president for reconsideration of Houses. Polity 195 172","PW-2048":"Statement 1 is correct: According to Article 109 of the Constitution of India Rajya Sabha cannot amend or reject the Money Bill.The Rajya Sabha can keep the Money Bill for a maximum period of 14 days. It should return the bill with or without recommendation to Lok Sabha and after which Lok Sabha may accept or reject recommendation. Statement 2 is correct: The Demands for Grants (which are the detailed estimates of expenditure) are voted in the Lok Sabha. The Rajya Sabha does not have the power to vote on these demands, although it can discuss them. According to Article 113 of the Constitution, only the Lok Sabha has the power to approve or reject the Demands for Grants. No demand for a grant shall be made except on the recommendation of the President. Statement 3 is incorrect: The Rajya Sabha enjoys equal status with the Lok Sabha on the matter of discussion of Annual Financial Statement (Article 112). While the Rajya Sabha can discuss the budget, it cannot vote on it or pass it. The Rajya Sabha can only make recommendations, which the Lok Sabha can either accept or reject. The main ","PW-2049":"As per Article 108. The President of India can call for a joint sitting if the Lok Sabha and Rajya Sabha disagree on a bill). In the case of a joint sitting of both Houses of Parliament, the bill is required to be passed by a simple majority of the members present and voting. It is extraordinary machinery provided by the Constitution to resolve a deadlock between the two Houses over the passage of a bill:- 1. If the bill is rejected by the other House; 2. If the Houses have finally disagreed as to the amendments to be made in the bill; or 3. If more than six months have elapsed from the date of the receipt of the bill by the other House without the bill being passed by it.  Joint sitting applies only to ordinary and financial bills, not money bills or constitutional amendment bills.  If the bill (under dispute) has already lapsed due to the dissolution of the Lok Sabha, no joint sitting can be summoned. But, the joint sitting can be held if the Lok Sabha is dissolved after the President has notified his intention to summon such a sitting (as the bill does not lapse in this case). ","PW-2050":"Statement 1 is correct: The Constitution of India does not explicitly mention the No-Confidence Motion. The Constitution provides the framework for parliamentary procedures but leaves the details of the procedures, including the No-Confidence Motion, to the Rules of Procedure of the Lok Sabha. The motion of No Confidence is a part of parliamentary practice that allows the Lok Sabha to hold the government accountable by voting whether or not they have confidence in the Council of Ministers headed by the Prime Minister. Statement 2 is correct: A No-Confidence Motion can only be introduced in the Lok Sabha (the Lower House of Parliament). According to the Rules of Procedure of the Lok Sabha, the motion requires the support of at least 50 members to be introduced. The Rajya Sabha (the Upper House) does not have the provision to introduce a No-Confidence Motion against the government. A No-Confidence Motion is a tool used to test the majority support for the government. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 196  No-Confidence motion need not state the reasons for its adoption in the Lok Sabha.  It can b","PW-2051":"The Estimates Committee was set up in 1950, on the recommendation of John Mathai. It consists of 30 members, all from the Lok Sabha and it is the largest committee. These members are elected by the Lok Sabha every year from amongst its own members, according to the principles of proportional representation by means of a single transferable vote. The minister cannot be the members of the estimates committee. The chairman of the committee is appointed by the Speaker from amongst its members and he is invariably from the ruling party. Its function is to examine the budget and also suggest economies of public expenditure. It also suggests an alternative policy of bringing policy of economies. 176","PW-2052":"Statement 1 is correct: A cabinet secretary is appointed for a fixed period of time, usually two years. A Cabinet Secretary holds the responsibility of preparation of agenda for Cabinet Meetings. Statement 2 is correct: The Prime Minister has direct control over the cabinet secretariat. The Cabinet Secretary is the administrative head of the secretariat. It also gives secretariat assistance to the Cabinet Committees. Statement 3 is incorrect: The Cabinet Secretariat facilitates government decision-making by providing interministerial coordination. However, the Ministry of Finance is entrusted with the allocation of financial resources to the Ministries. 177","PW-2053":"Statement 1 is incorrect: Parliamentary Committee on Public Accounts consists of 22 members of which 15 are from Lok Sabha and 7 from Rajya Sabha. It is formed every year with its members serving one-year terms in office. The chairperson of the PAC is usually a member of the opposition party in the Lok Sabha. Statement 2 is correct: It scrutinises appropriation and finance accounts of the Government. The Committee ensures that the government does not misuse or misappropriate public funds. Statement 3 is correct: The CAG audits the accounts of the government and submits reports to Parliament which is scrutinized by PAC to ensure that public funds are being used efficiently and according to the law. CAG acts as a guide, friend and philosopher of the committee. 178","PW-2054":"Statement 1 is incorrect: As per Article 75(3) of the constitution “the Council of Ministers shall be collectively responsible to the House of the People” not to the whole Parliament which includes both Rajya Sabha and Lok Sabha. Statement 2 is correct: Article 75(2) of the Constitution of India mandates that the Ministers shall hold office during the pleasure of the President. Statement 3 is correct: According to Article 78, it is the duty of the Prime Minister to communicate to the President all decisions of the Council of Ministers relating to the administration of the affairs of the union and proposals for legislation. 179","PW-2055":"Money Bill is defined under Article 110 of the Indian Constitution. It is concerned with financial matters like the imposition, abolition, remission, alteration or regulation of any tax. It is introduced only on the recommendation of the President and only in Lok Sabha. It must be passed in Lok Sabha by a simple majority of all members present and voting. Following this, it may be sent to the Rajya Sabha for its recommendations. Rajya Sabha has limited power with respect to money bills so no chance of any disagreement. Rajya Sabha can keep it for a maximum period of 14 days.The Rajya Sabha cannot amend or reject the bill. It should return the bill with or without recommendation. Lok Sabha may accept or reject recommendation. 180","PW-2056":"The Parliament is empowered to make laws on all matters listed in the Union List and the Concurrent List of the Constitution. Under Article 253 of the Constitution of India, Parliament can make laws for the whole or any part of India to give effect to international treaties, agreements, or conventions, and this can be done without the consent of any State. Article 253 says that it can also formulate laws on any matter pertaining to the State List if it is deemed necessary for the implementation of international treaties or agreements concluded with foreign nations. This is a unique provision where Parliament can legislate beyond its usual jurisdiction without requiring the consent of the states. 181","PW-2057":"Adjournment Motion is one of the devices of Parliamentary proceedings. The purpose of an Adjournment Motion is to raise an issue of urgent public importance that requires immediate discussion in the Parliament. It is typically used to bring up issues related to national or regional significance, like natural disasters, economic crises, or controversial government actions. The motion requires the approval of the Speaker or Chairman, and if allowed, the matter is debated in the House. It needs the support of 50 members to be admitted. 182","PW-2058":"Statement 1 is incorrect: As per Article 80 of the Constitution, the Rajya Sabha consists of members nominated members (not more than 12) and representatives of States (indirectly elected by legislative councils of states) and Union Territories ( to be chosen in such manner as parliament may prescribe by law) . U.T of NCT of Delhi and Puducherry have representation in Rajya sabha who are chosen through indirect election by their respective legislative assemblies . Statement 2 is incorrect: The Chief Election Commissioner (CEC) does not have the authority to adjudicate election disputes. While the ECI supervises elections, disputes are handled by Election Tribunals or High Courts. The Supreme Court and High Courts have the power to adjudicate such matters. Election Petitions under Part III of the Presidential and Vice Presidential Elections Act, 1952 are also filed directly in the Supreme Court. Disputes relating to the election of members of Parliament and state legislatures lie within the original jurisdiction of High Courts. Statement 3 is incorrect: According to Article 79 of the ","PW-2059":"Statement 1 is incorrect: The Speaker is the presiding officer of the Lok Sabha. Article 93 to 97 of the Constitution of India deals with the provisions of the Presiding officer of the Lok Sabha. Usually, the Speaker remains in office during the life of the Lok Sabha. There is no role of the President in removing the Speaker. Hence, The Speaker of the Lok Sabha does not hold office during the pleasure of the President. It should be noted here that, whenever the Lok Sabha is dissolved, the Speaker does not vacate his office and continues till the newly-elected Lok Sabha meets. Statement 2 is incorrect: According to Article 93 of the Constitution, the Speaker must be a member of the Lok Sabha at the time of their election. The condition to become a member within six months applies to ministers under Article 75(5), not to the Speaker. Statement 3 is correct: The Speaker of the Lok Sabha has to vacate his office earlier in any of the following three cases:  If he ceases to be a member of the Lok Sabha;  If he resigns by writing to the Deputy Speaker; and  If he is removed by a resolut","PW-2060":"The Rajya Sabha has been given four exclusive or special powers that are not enjoyed by the Lok Sabha:  It can authorise the Parliament to make a law on a subject enumerated in the State List (Article 249).  It can authorise the Parliament to create new All-India Services common to both the Centre and states (Article 312).  Resolution for the removal of the vice-president can be introduced only in the Rajya Sabha not in the Lok Sabha (Article 67).  A proclamation for declaring a national emergency, President’s rule, or a financial emergency (under Articles 352, 356, and 360) can remain in effect even if it is approved only by the Rajya Sabha in case the Lok Sabha is dissolved before or during the emergency period. 185","PW-2061":"Provision of Joint sitting of two houses of parliament is given under Article 108. It is an extraordinary mechanism to break a deadlock between the two Houses over the passage of a bill. The president can summon joint sitting for the purpose of deliberating and voting on the bill.It is applicable to ordinary bills or financial bills only and not to money bills or Constitutional amendment bills. The quorum to constitute a joint sitting shall be one-tenth of the total number of members of the Houses. The Speaker of Lok Sabha presides over a joint sitting. In their absence, the Deputy Speaker takes charge, followed by the Deputy Chairman of the Rajya Sabha. If none are available, members present elect a presiding officer. 186","PW-2062":"The Delimitation Commission is appointed by the President of India and works in partnership with the Election Commission of India. Composition: Generally, the Delimitation Commission comprises a serving or retired Supreme Court judge as the Chairperson, an Election Commissioner nominated by the Chief Election Commissioner, and the State Election Commissioners of the respective states. Objective: To determine the number and boundaries of constituencies, to identify seats reserved for SC/ST. Delimitation Commissions have been set up four times : 1952, 1963, 1973 and 2002 under the Acts of 1952, 1962, 1972 and 2002. Statement 1 is correct: The act of Delimitation is redrawing boundaries of Lok Sabha and Assembly constituencies to represent changes in population and done on the basis of the preceding Census. Its objective is to ensure that all population groups are fairly represented, with equitable geographic distribution so that no political party benefits. A Delimitation Commission is in charge of carrying out this exercise, and its decisions are binding and cannot be challenged in co","PW-2063":"Statement 1 is correct: Article 112 of the Indian Constitution deals with placing annual financial statements in Parliament. It outlines the estimated revenue and expenditure of the government for the upcoming financial year. It is a key tool for Parliament to examine, debate, and approve the government’s financial plans: Statement 2 is correct: Article 114 mandates that the government can withdraw money from the Consolidated Fund of India only after receiving approval from Parliament after passage of the Appropriation Bill. Statement 3 is correct: If the government needs extra funds, it requests supplementary grants via a Supplementary Appropriation Bill. A Vote-on-Account provides interim funds until the full budget is approved. It is passed (or granted) after the general discussion on budget is over. It is generally granted for two months for an amount equivalent to one-sixth of the total estimation. Polity 199 Statement 4 is incorrect: There is no such Parliamentary budget office to review programs of Government. The Estimate Committee of parliament reviews policies and continuou","PW-2064":"If the Union Budget is not passed by the Lok Sabha, it indicates a lack of confidence in the government's financial proposals. Since the government is responsible for presenting and managing the budget, this failure typically results in a crisis of confidence. In such a scenario, the Prime Minister and the Council of Ministers are expected to resign, as the government's authority is effectively undermined. 189","PW-2065":"Statement 1 is incorrect: During the time of approaching elections, it is not practical to present a full budget, therefore the government presents an interim budget. Interim Budget can be presented by all governments whether incumbent or regular or caretaker. Statement 2 is correct: The Appropriation Bill becomes an Act after Presidential assent, authorizing withdrawals from the Consolidated Fund of India. Since its enactment takes time, the government cannot withdraw funds beyond March 31. To address this, the Lok Sabha grants a ‘Vote on Account’, allowing advance funds for essential expenses, usually for two months, covering one-sixth of the total estimated expenditure, until the Appropriation Bill is passed. A vote-on-account contains only the expenditure of the government’s budget while an Interim Budget is a complete set of accounts i.e. it includes both expenditure and receipts. 190","PW-2066":"The Speaker of the Lok Sabha is the presiding officer and the highest authority of the Lok Sabha, the lower house of the Parliament of India. The Speaker is elected generally in the first meeting of the Lok Sabha following general elections and is responsible for conducting the business in the house and maintaining discipline and decorum. G.V. Mavalankar served as the first Speaker of the Lok Sabha, the lower house of the Indian Parliament, from 1952 until his death in 1956. 191","PW-2067":"The Public Accounts Committee (PAC) was established in 1921, following its initial mention in the Government of India Act, 1919. The committee scrutinizes reports from the Comptroller and Auditor General (CAG) of India to identify irregularities or inefficiencies in government spending. It is reconstituted annually under Rule 308 of the Rules of Procedure and Conduct of Business in the Lok Sabha. Statement 1 is correct: Members of the Public Accounts Committee (PAC) are elected annually by Parliament through proportional representation using a single transferable vote, ensuring fair representation for all parties. The Speaker appoints the Chairman from among its members. Statement 2 is incorrect: The committee consists of 22 members-15 from Lok Sabha and 7 from the Rajya Sabha. Generally, the Chairman is appointed from the opposition party. It does not comprise any eminent personalities from industry and trade. 192","PW-2068":"Statement 1 is correct: Article 249 empowers the Rajya Sabha to pass a resolution allowing Parliament to legislate on matters in the State List if it is in the national interest. This resolution requires a two-thirds majority and remains in effect for one year, with the possibility of extension through subsequent resolutions. Statement 2 is incorrect: The proclamation of emergency must be approved by a special majority of both the Houses of Parliament within one month from the date of its issue under article 352(6). If a proclamation of emergency is issued when the Lok Sabha is dissolved, or if it dissolves within one month without approval, the proclamation remains valid for 30 days from the first sitting of the newly reconstituted Lok Sabha, provided the Rajya Sabha approves it in the meantime. If approved by both the houses, the Emergency continues for 6 months and can be extended to an indefinite period with an approval of the Parliament for every six months. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 200 193","PW-2069":"","PW-2070":"Statement 1 is incorrect: The receipts under Public accounts mainly consist of the receipts of National Savings Certificate, Provident funds and other deposits where the Govt. acts as a banker and returns the fund after completion of the contract. This account is operated by executive action. Therefore, the disbursement out of this account does not need authorization of the Parliament. Statement 2 is correct: The Indian Constitution provides for the establishment of a Consolidated Fund and a Public Account of India and of the states under Article 266 and a Contingency Fund of India and for each State under Article 267. Statement 3 is correct: The Railway Budget was presented separately from the General Budget till 2017. In the year when the question was asked The Railway Budget was presented separately and Appropriations and disbursements under the Railway Budget were subject to the same form of parliamentary control as other appropriations and disbursements. 196","PW-2071":"According to Article 138(1) of the Constitution of India, Parliament has the power to confer additional jurisdiction on the Supreme Court in matters included in the Union List. This means that if the Parliament deems it necessary, it can pass a law to grant the Supreme Court the authority to hear and decide on specific matters that fall within the jurisdiction of the union list. Also under article 138(2) the Supreme Court shall have such further jurisdiction and powers with respect to any matter as the Government of India and the Government of any State may confer by special agreement. 197","PW-2072":"According to Article 368 of the Indian Constitution, an amendment to the Constitution can be initiated only by introducing a Bill in either House of Parliament. The Bill must be passed in each House by a majority of the total membership of that House and by a two-thirds majority of the members present and voting (Special Majority). Once both Houses pass the Bill, it is presented to the President, who must give assent. Upon the President’s assent, the Constitution stands amended in accordance with the terms of the Bill. 200","PW-2073":"Statement 1 is correct: For the Committees on Public Accounts and Public Undertakings, 15 members are elected from the Lok Sabha and 7 members from the Rajya Sabha. In the case of the Committee on Estimates, all the 30 members are elected from the Lok Sabha. Statement 2 is correct: The Ministry of Parliamentary Affairs renders secretarial assistance to the Cabinet Committee on Parliamentary Affairs, which recommends prorogation of both the Houses of the Parliament and the Government’s stand on Private Members’ Bills and Resolutions. Statement 3 is correct: The Ministry of Parliamentary Affairs is responsible for nominating Members of Parliament (MPs) to various committees, councils, boards, and commissions established by the Government of India across different ministries. 201","PW-2074":"In 2002, the amount of security deposited for general category and SC/ST category candidates were ₹10,000 and ₹5,000 respectively for Lok Sabha elections. However , after some amendments in RPA Act 1951, Security Deposit Amounts (as of 2024) is: 1. Lok Sabha Elections (Lower House of Parliament):  General Category Candidates: ₹25,000  SC/ST Candidates: ₹12,500 2. State Legislative Assembly Elections:  General Category Candidates: ₹10,000  SC/ST Candidates: ₹5,000 A candidate’s security deposit is forfeited if they fail to secure more than one-sixth (16.67%) of the valid votes polled in their constituency. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 202 202","PW-2075":"Under Article 83(2) of the Indian Constitution, the term of the Lok Sabha is normally five years. Under Article 352 of the Indian Constitution, the President of India can proclaim an emergency on the grounds of war, external aggression and armed rebellion, external aggression, armed rebellion, or internal disturbance. During such a proclamation, the term of the Lok Sabha can be extended by one year at a time through a resolution passed in both Houses of Parliament with a special majority, which requires the support of at least two-thirds of the members present and voting in both Houses. This extension is valid only as long as the emergency remains in force and cannot continue beyond six months after the emergency ends. 203","PW-2076":"","PW-2077":"Statement (1) and (2) are correct: Both Lok Sabha and Rajya Sabha can introduce a bill for Constitutional amendment and pass it with a two-thirds majority of the members present and voting. Statement (3) is incorrect: While the State Legislatures can ratify amendments related to certain matters (like changes to the federal structure) which require ratification by the legislatures of at least half of the states (via simple majority), they cannot initiate amendments. Statement (4) is incorrect: The President does not have the power to initiate a constitutional amendment. The President’s role is to give assent to a bill passed by Parliament for an amendment. 208","PW-2078":"Statement (1) is correct: According to article 84 of the Constitution of India, the President is not a member of either the Lok Sabha or the Rajya Sabha, but he should be qualified for election as a member of the Lok Sabha. Statement (2) is correct: As per article 79 of the Constitution, the Parliament of India consists of three components: the President, the Lok Sabha (House of the People), and the Rajya Sabha (Council of States). 17. HIGHER JUDICIARY: SC AND HC 210","PW-2079":"Statement 1 is correct: Pursuant to the recommendations made by the H N Sanyal Committee, the Contempt of Courts Act, 1971 was passed to bring transparency and more clarity in the concept of contempt of court. Statement 2 is correct: The Supreme Court and the High Courts of India have been empowered with the power to penalise for Contempt of Court under Articles 129 and 215 respectively of the Constitution of India. Statement 3 is incorrect: The Constitution of India does not define Civil Contempt and/or Criminal Contempt. However, the expression has been defined by the Contempt of Court Act of 1971. Statement 4 is correct: Article 142 (2) of the Indian Constitution empowers the Supreme Court to make any order necessary for securing the attendance of any person, the discovery or production of any documents, or the investigation or punishment of any contempt of itself, subject to the provisions of any law made in this behalf by Parliament. The Parliament passed the Contempt of Court Act of 1971 pursuant to this. Types of Contempt:  Civil Contempt: Willful disobedience of a judgment, ","PW-2080":"Statement 1 is incorrect: The term “advocate” under the Advocates Act, 1961 refers to a person who has been enrolled as an advocate in the state Bar Council and is authorized to practice law in courts. Corporate lawyers and patent attorneys, however, are not excluded from recognition as advocates. Corporate lawyers often practice in corporate law firms, while patent attorneys handle intellectual property law. Statement 2 is correct: The Bar Council of India is responsible for overseeing legal education, setting standards for law colleges, and recognizing institutions that offer law degrees. This power extends to setting norms and conditions for legal education to meet the standards required to practice law in India. SUPER HINT For S1, Spot the trap: It plays on the term “recognised as advocates”, trying to split legal professionals into arbi- trary buckets. The nature of work or job title (e.g., gov- ernment counsel, corporate lawyer, patent attorney) is not what determines “advocate” status — what matters is Bar enrollment. Hence likely false. 213","PW-2081":"","PW-2082":"Judges (Inquiry) Act, 1968 was passed to regulate the procedure for the investigation and proof of the misbehaviour or incapacity of a judge of the Supreme Court or of a High Court. Statement 1 is incorrect: As per the Judges (Inquiry) Act, 1968, a removal motion signed by 100 members (Lok Sabha) or 50 members (Rajya Sabha) is to be given to the Speaker/ Chairman. The speaker has the discretion to accept or reject the motion. Polity 205 Statement is 2 incorrect: The Constitution of India does not define and gives details of the expression ‘incapacity and proved misbehaviour’ of the Judges of the Supreme Court of India which are the ground for the impeachment of the Judges. Statement 3 is correct: The details of the process of impeachment of the Judges of the Supreme Court of India is governed by the Judges Enquiry Act (1968). Statement 4 is correct: If the motion for the impeachment of a Judge is taken up for voting, the law requires that the motion be passed by a ‘special majority’ i.e. majority of the total membership of the House and majority of not less than two thirds members pr","PW-2083":"Article 142 of the Indian Constitution deals with the Enforcement of decrees and orders of the Supreme Court and orders as to discovery, etc. The SC Supreme Court in the exercise of its jurisdiction may pass such decree or make such order as is necessary for doing complete justice in any cause or matter pending before it. Article 142 empowers the Supreme Court to make orders that may not be bound by existing laws enacted by Parliament, enabling the Court to act in ways that ensure complete justice. 216","PW-2084":"The custodian of the Constitution of India refers to the body or entity responsible for interpreting and upholding the provisions of the Constitution. This includes the interpretation of laws, the protection of fundamental rights, and ensuring that the government acts in accordance with the Constitution. Article 32 of the Indian Constitution grants the Supreme Court the power to enforce the fundamental rights of citizens through writ jurisdiction. The Supreme Court is considered the final interpreter and guardian of the Constitution. It can examine the constitutionality of laws and actions taken by the Parliament or State Legislatures and can strike down any law that it finds to be unconstitutional. 217","PW-2085":"Article 124(1) of the Indian Constitution mandates the establishment of the Supreme Court, consisting of the Chief Justice of India and such other judges as Parliament may prescribe from time to time. Option (b) is correct: The power to increase the number of Supreme Court judges lies with Parliament. Under the Supreme Court (Number of Judges) Amendment Bill, 2019, the number of judges was increased by three, bringing the total number of judges, including the Chief Justice, to 34, up from 31. 218","PW-2086":"According to Article 131, the Supreme Court has original jurisdiction over disputes between two or more states. It also handles disputes between the Central Government and one or more states, or between different states and the Centre. The Supreme Court’s original jurisdiction is exclusive in such federal disputes, meaning only the Court can resolve these matters. This ensures that conflicts between the Government of India and states are directly addressed by the Supreme Court. 219","PW-2087":"The original jurisdiction of the Supreme Court of India refers to matters that can be directly brought before the Court without needing to pass through lower courts. The Constitution of India under Article 32 and 131 outlines the original jurisdiction of the Supreme Court. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 206 Statement 1 is correct: According to Article 131, a dispute between the Government of India and one or more States. Statement 2 is incorrect: As per Article 329 (b), no election to either House of Parliament or to the House or either House of the Legislature of a State shall be called in question except by an election petition presented to such authority and in such manner as may be provided for by or under any law made by the appropriate Legislature. Hence as it cant be taken to SC court directly it does not come under original jurisdiction. Statement 3 is incorrect: Article 131 doesn’t mention UT anywhere. Further, the original jurisdiction mentioned in 131 is regarding issues between the federal units. Statement 4 is correct: According to Article 131, a dispute between two or more states","PW-2088":"Statement 1 is correct: Under Article 124(2) and its interpretations in various SC judgments, The judges of the SC are appointed by the President based on the recommendations of the collegium system, which involves the Chief Justice of India and senior judges of the SC ( In case of elevating a HC judge, CJ of concerned HC is also consulted). Statement 2 is incorrect: SC judge can be removed from his office by an order of President. The President can order for removal of SC Judge only after an address by Parliament has been presented to him in the same session for such removal. Statement 3 is correct: The salaries, allowances and pensions of the judges and the staff as well as all the administrative expenses of the SC are charges on the Consolidated Fund of India. Thus they are non-votable by the Parliament. Statement 4 is incorrect: Under Article 146. The Chief Justice of India can appoint officers and servants of the SC and can also prescribe their conditions of service. 221","PW-2089":"A PIL lets individuals, NGOs, or groups file lawsuits to protect public interest, tackling significant social, environmental, or economic issues, often involving systematic or structural problems that affect many people. Statement 1 is incorrect: Justice V R Krishna Iyer served the Supreme Court as a judge but never as Chief Justice. Statement 2 is correct: Justice V R Krishna Iyer, a pioneer of Public Interest Litigation (PIL) in India, expanded the judiciary’s scope to address public grievances and protect marginalized groups. Along with V R Krishna Iyer, Justice P.N. Bhagwati, a key figure in the development of the PIL movement, significantly contributed to its growth through landmark cases such as S.P. Gupta vs. Union of India (1981), Hussainara Khatoon vs. State of Bihar (1979) expanding access to justice for public grievances. 222","PW-2090":"In India, Judges of the High Courts and Supreme Court are appointed by the President and enjoy a high degree of security of tenure. The mode of removal of these judges is an important aspect of the judicial independence enshrined in the Constitution. Statement 1 is correct: According to Article 124(4) of the Constitution, a judge of the Supreme Court can only be removed through impeachment by the Parliament, following the same procedure prescribed for the removal of a High Court Judge under Article 217(1). Statement 2 is incorrect: As per Article 220 of the Constitution of India, retired judges of the High Courts are not allowed to practice in the same High Court where they served as a judge. However, they can practice in other courts or before any authority in India. This provision prevents any conflict of interest or unfair advantage that might arise if a retired judge were allowed to practice in the same High Court where they had previously served. 223","PW-2091":"India’s justice system is a three-tiered structure comprising the Supreme Court at the top, followed by High Courts in each state or group of states, and subordinate courts at the district and local levels. This system ensures the rule of law, protection of rights, and fair adjudication of disputes. Assertion (A) is False: India has 28 states but only 25 High Courts. Some, like the Guwahati High Court, serve multiple states. Therefore, not every state has its own High Court. Reason (B) is True: The Indian Constitution provides for High Courts for each state (Article 214) but Article 231 also enables the Parliament to establish common HC for two or more states or for two or more States and a Union territory. Polity 207 224","PW-2092":"PILs protect disadvantaged communities who can’t seek justice themselves. They can be filed in the Supreme Court and High Courts under Article 32 (right to move the Supreme Court) and Article 226 (power of High Courts to issue writs). Justice P.N. Bhagwati introduced Public Interest Litigation (PIL) in India in the 1980s, broadening the judiciary’s role to address public grievances and protect marginalized communities. His efforts democratized the judicial process, allowing direct court access for significant public matters. This made the justice system more accessible and responsive to societal issues. However, the concept was first pioneered by Justice V.R. Krishna Iyer in cases like Mumbai Kamgar Sabha vs. Abdulbhai Faizullabhai (1976) and Fertilizer Corporation Kamgar Union vs. Union of India (1981). Justice Bhagwati significantly expanded PILs through landmark cases like Hussainara Khatoon vs. State of Bihar (1979) and S.P. Gupta vs. Union of India (1981). 225","PW-2093":"The judges and the Chief Judge of a HC are appointed by the President after consultation with the Chief Justice of India and the Governor of the concerned state. Statement 1 is incorrect: Article 220 of the Indian Constitution prohibits retired High Court judges from practicing in the same High Court but allows them to practice in other courts in India, including the Supreme Court. Statement 2 is incorrect: Article 217 of the Indian Constitution stipulates that a person can be appointed as a High Court judge if they have held a judicial office in India for at least ten years or have served as an advocate of a High Court (or High Courts in succession) for at least ten years. 226","PW-2094":"The Indian Constitution provides for High Courts for each state (Article 214) but Article 231 also enables the Parliament to establish common HC for multiple states and UTs. The number of High Courts went from 24 to 25 after establishment of the Andhra Pradesh High Court in Amaravati in 2019. Statement 1 is incorrect: In 2005 there were only 24 HCs. Statement 2 is correct: Punjab, Haryana, and the Union Territory of Chandigarh share the Punjab and Haryana High Court, which is located in Chandigarh. Statement 3 is correct: The National Capital Territory of Delhi is served by its own High Court, the Delhi High Court, which has jurisdiction exclusively over Delhi. 227","PW-2095":"The Supreme Court of India, established under Article 124 of the Constitution, came into existence on January 26, 1950. It initially operated from the old Parliament House. Statement 1 is incorrect: Article 138 of the Indian Constitution provides that Parliament may, by law, extend the jurisdiction of the Supreme Court. Statement 2 is correct: According to Article 146 for the Supreme Court and Article 229 for High Courts of the Constitution, the Chief Justice of India and Chief Justice of that high Court respectively, Chief Justice has the power to appoint officers and servants of the court. Their administrative expenses of the supreme court are charged on the Consolidated Fund of India. 228","PW-2096":"The National Human Rights Commission of India (NHRC), established on October 12, 1993, under the Protection of Human Rights Act 1993, promotes and protects human rights in India. It investigates complaints, recommends actions, reviews policies, and advises the government. Option (c) is correct: Originally, the Protection of Human Rights Act 1993 allowed only a retired Chief Justice of India to be appointed as NHRC Chairperson. In 2019, this was amended to include retired Supreme Court judges as eligible candidates. 229","PW-2097":"In India, a High Court (HC) can have jurisdiction over more than one state or Union Territory. This means that a High Court may serve as the judiciary for multiple states and Union Territories. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 208 Option (b) is correct: The Andaman and Nicobar Islands, a Union Territory of India, come under the jurisdiction of the Kolkata High Court. This arrangement is due to the geographical and administrative placement of the islands under the jurisdiction of West Bengal. 230","PW-2098":"The parliament of India, while exercising the power under article 221, has made provision that the salary and Allowances of a HC judge be charged upon the Consolidated fund of State while Pension upon the Consolidated Fund of India.  Consolidated Fund of India (Article 266) covers central government expenses, including Supreme Court judges’ salaries.  Consolidated Fund of the State (Article 266), includes all state revenues and loans and covers state expenses.  The Contingency Fund of India [ Article 267(1)] of the Indian Constitution is a reserve fund for meeting unforeseen and urgent expenditures, placed at the disposal of the President of India.  The Contingency Fund of the State [Article 267(2)] of the Indian Constitution, is a reserve for unforeseen and urgent expenditures, available to the Governor of the state. 231","PW-2099":"Under article 143 of the Indian Constitution, the President can seek the Supreme Court’s opinion on public importance matters. However, this advice is provided only if the President asks for it; the Supreme Court does not offer advice on its own initiative. This process is known as the Advisory Jurisdiction of the Supreme Court under Article 143. 232","PW-2100":"Article 214-231 deals with the provisions of High Courts in India. Article 214 provides for a HC in each state while article 231 enables a HC to be shared with multiple states. Statement 1 is incorrect: After the establishment of the Andhra Pradesh High Court in 2019, there were 25 High Courts in India. Statement 2 is correct: Three high courts (Guwahati, Bombay and Punjab & Haryana High Courts) have jurisdiction over more than one state. Statement 3 is incorrect: Delhi is the only UT having its own HC. Statement 4 is correct: Judges of the High Court hold office till the age of 62. However the judges of supreme court hold office till the age of 65. Note: In this question though 2 statements are correct, but \"d\" is the most appropriate option . 233","PW-2101":"","PW-2102":"Article 227 grants High Courts the power of superintendence over all subordinate courts and tribunals within their jurisdiction. For this purpose the Chief Justice of a HC has to take decisions of administrative nature. When the Chief Justice of a High Court acts in an administrative capacity, his actions can be subject to judicial scrutiny under Article 226 of the Indian Constitution, and a bench of the High Court may examine such matters. Article 226 of the Indian Constitution empowers High Courts to issue certain writs to enforce the rights of individuals. The Supreme Court issues writs under article 32. Habeas Corpus To release a person unlawfully detained. Mandamus To compel a public authority to perform its duty. Prohibition To prevent lower courts from exceeding their jurisdiction. Certiorari To transfer a matter from a lower court to a higher court. Quo Warranto To challenge the legality of a person’s claim to a public office. 18. JUDICIAL REVIEW 236","PW-2103":"","PW-2104":"Statement 1 is correct: The objective of National Legal Services Authority (NALSA) is to provide free legal services to weaker sections of society for securing justice and are not denied to any citizen by reasons of economic or other disabilities. Statement 2 is correct: In every State, there is a State Legal Service Authority to give effect to the policies and directions of the NALSA and to give free legal services to the people and conduct Lok Adalats in the State. 238","PW-2105":"Lok Adalats are alternative dispute resolution forums established under the Legal Services Authorities Act, 1987, to provide affordable, speedy, and amicable settlement of disputes. They emphasize conciliation and compromise, handling both pre-litigation cases and pending disputes in courts. Statement 1 is incorrect: Lok Adalats have jurisdiction to settle disputes at both the pre-litigation stage and cases pending before any court. They aim to reduce the burden on courts and provide speedy justice through compromise and amicable settlements. Statement 2 is incorrect: Lok Adalats can deal with both civil and certain criminal matters of a compoundable nature. These include disputes related to matrimonial issues, partition suits, motor vehicle claims, and cheque bounce cases under Section 138 of the Negotiable Instruments Act. Statement 3 is incorrect: A Lok Adalat consists not only of serving or retired judicial officers but also other members, such as lawyers, social workers, or professionals, who assist in mediating disputes. Hence, None of the statements are correct. 240","PW-2106":"Lok Adalats are alternative dispute resolution mechanisms in India, aimed at providing a speedy and cost- effective resolution to disputes. Statement 1 is correct: An award made by a Lok Adalat is deemed to be a decree of a civil court and is enforceable as such. Moreover, no appeal lies against it in any higher court, ensuring finality and quick resolution of the dispute. Statement 2 is incorrect: Matrimonial and family disputes are covered under Lok Adalats. In fact, they often serve as a platform for resolving family-related disputes, including matters related to divorce, child custody, and maintenance. 241","PW-2107":"In India, there are three High Courts (excluding UTs) that have jurisdiction over more than one state. These are: 1. Punjab and Haryana High Court - Jurisdiction over Punjab and Haryana. 2. Bombay High Court - Jurisdiction over Maharashtra, Goa, and the Union Territory of Dadra and Nagar Haveli and Daman and Diu. 3. Guwahati High Court - Jurisdiction over Assam, Nagaland, Mizoram, and Arunachal Pradesh. 242","PW-2108":"Lok Adalats. established under the Legal Services Authorities Act, 1987, are a key mechanism for resolving disputes through amicable settlements.  They address a broad spectrum of cases, including consumer disputes, such as those with mobile cellular companies, which are commonly resolved due to their potential for quick compromise.  Additionally, Lok Adalats frequently handle motor accident compensation claims under the Motor Vehicles Act, 1988, as they involve monetary settlements that can be resolved without prolonged litigation.  Pension-related disputes, often involving retired government employees, are also taken up to ensure timely resolution and delivery of justice to senior citizens. These cases, being non-complex in nature and suitable for settlement, are ideally suited for Lok Adalats, which aim to reduce the burden on regular courts while providing cost-effective and speedy justice to litigants. 243","PW-2109":"The District and Sessions Court is one of the highest courts in a district, and it plays a crucial role in the judicial system of India. Statement 1 is correct: The highest criminal court at the district level is indeed the Court of the District and Sessions Judge. This court deals with serious criminal cases, including those that may involve the death penalty. Statement 2 is correct: District Judges are appointed by the Governor of the state, but the appointment is made in consultation with the High Court, ensuring that the process follows legal norms and includes judicial oversight. Polity 211 Statement 3 is correct: To be eligible for the appointment of District Judge, a person must be either an advocate or pleader with at least seven years of standing or an officer in the judicial service of the Union or State. This ensures that the person has the required legal experience and qualifications. Statement 4 is correct: When a Sessions Judge awards the death penalty, it must be confirmed by the High Court. This is a safeguard to ensure that the most severe punishment is not handed do","PW-2110":"According to Article 236 of the Constitution of India, the term “district judge” encompasses various judicial positions, including:  Judge of a city civil court  Additional district judge  Joint district judge  Assistant district judge  Chief judge of a small cause court  Chief presidency magistrate  Additional chief presidency magistrate  Sessions judge  Additional sessions judge  Assistant sessions judge Notably, the term does not include the position of tribunal judge. Tribunal judges operate within specialized tribunals and are not classified under the term “district judge” as per the constitutional definition. 20. STATE LEGISLATURE 245","PW-2111":"Statement 1 is correct: The Speaker of the Legislative Assembly vacates his office in three cases: 1. If he ceases to be a member of the assembly; 2. Speaker Resigns by writing to the deputy speaker and vice versa and 3. Removed by the resolution passed by a majority of all the members of the assembly. Statement 2 is incorrect: Article 179 provided that, whenever the Assembly is dissolved, the Speaker shall not vacate his office until immediately before the first meeting of the Assembly after the dissolution. 246","PW-2112":"Statement 1 is incorrect: As per Article 171, the maximum strength of the Legislative Council of the state cannot be more than one third of total strength of assembly. However, the size of the Legislative Council cannot be less than 40 members. The constitution has fixed the maximum and minimum limits but actual strength is fixed by Parliament. Statement 2 is incorrect: The members of the Legislative Council are indirectly elected. The Chairman of the Legislative Council is elected by the members from amongst itself. 247","PW-2113":"Statement 1 is incorrect: The Constitution of India provides under Article 170 that the Legislative Assembly of a State shall consist of not more than 500 members and not less than 60 members. However, there are exceptions for smaller states like Sikkim, Mizoram, and Goa. The limit mentioned in the statement (450 members) is incorrect. Statement 2 is correct: As per Article 173 of the Constitution of India, a person is eligible to be a member of the Legislative Assembly only if they are at least 25 years of age. This is a constitutional requirement for candidacy in the Legislative Assembly elections. 248","PW-2114":"The state with the largest number of seats reserved for Scheduled Tribes (STs) in the Lok Sabha is Madhya Pradesh. Madhya Pradesh has a significant tribal population, including communities like Gonds and Bhils, and the reservation of seats in the Lok Sabha is proportionate to the tribal population in the state. The reserved seats ensure representation of Scheduled Tribes in Parliament to address their issues and protect their rights. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 212 21. GOVERNOR 249","PW-2115":"Statement 1 is correct: Article 176(1) states that, through the legislative powers of the Governor, he can address the state legislature at the commencement of the first session after each general election and the first session of each year. Statement 2 is incorrect: Article 208 of the Indian Constitution empowers State Legislatures to create rules for regulating their procedures and business. The state legislature can formulate its own ad hoc rules or rely on the Speaker’s discretion for procedural clarity. Each state’s legislative assembly has its autonomy in procedural matters, and there is no binding provision mandating the use of Lok Sabha rules unless adopted by the state legislature itself. SUPER HINT For S2, State Legislature ≠ subordinate to the Union Parliament in terms of procedure. Lok Sabha rules aren’t automatically binding on states — states are federally autonomous in procedural functioning. This statement suggests an automatic fallback — which is an over generalization hence likely false. 250","PW-2116":"Statement 1 is correct: As per Article 361, which deals with the ‘Protection of President and Governors’, states that ‘no criminal proceedings whatsoever shall be instituted or continued against the President, or the Governor of a State, in any court during his term of office’. However, after giving two months’ notice, civil proceedings can be instituted against him during his term of office in respect of his personal acts. Statement 2 is correct: As per Article 158, which deals with the ‘Conditions of Governor Office’, states that ‘the emoluments and allowances of the Governor shall not be diminished during his term of office’. 251","PW-2117":"Statement 1 is incorrect: The Chief Secretary is ‘chosen’ by the Chief Minister. As the appointment of Chief Secretary is an executive action of the Chief Minister, it is taken in the name of the Governor of the State. Statement 2 is incorrect: Though the Administrative Reforms Commission, in its report on State Administration in 1969, had recommended that a Chief Secretary should have a minimum tenure of three to four years, there is no fixed tenure for the post of Chief Secretary of a State. SUPER HINT S1 aligns with Function-person/organisation/ministry match trap as its easy to manipulate to make it false. Is it CM or Governor? For S2, \"Fixed tenure\", it can be negated by just real life observation of system around you. Such a top post bureaucratic having fixed tenure, wow! 252","PW-2118":"Statement 1 is correct: Under Article 356, President’s Rule is imposed if the President, upon receipt of the report from the Governor of the State or otherwise, is satisfied that a situation has arisen in which the government of the State cannot be carried on in accordance with the provisions of the Constitution. This comes under the discretionary power of the Governor. Statement 2 is incorrect: Article 164 (1) states that Chief Minister shall be appointed by the Governor and the other Ministers shall be appointed by the Governor on the advice of the Chief Minister, and the Ministers shall hold office during the pleasure of the Governor. Statement 3 is correct: As per Article 200 the Governor of a state can use his legislative power to reserve the bill for the consideration of the President. Statement 4 is incorrect: Making the rules to conduct the business of the State Government does not come under Governor’s discretionary power. In the Nabam Rebia judgement (2016), the Supreme Court held that the exercise of Governor’s discretion under Article 163 is limited and his choice of acti","PW-2119":" 1st ARC Recommendation (1966): The first ARC recommended the appointment of persons having long experience in public life and administration and non-partisan attitude as governors.  Rajamannar Committee (1969): The Rajamannar Committee recommended the provision that the state ministry holds office during the pleasure of the governor should be omitted.  Sarkaria Commission (1983): The “Sarkaria Commission” recommended that the Governor should be a distinguished outsider without intense political links, that he should not have recently participated in politics, and that he should not be a member of the ruling party.  National Commission to Review the Working of the Constitution (2000): The committee recommended that the president should appoint the governor of a state only after consultation with the chief minister of that state. 256","PW-2120":"Earlier sales tax was collected by the State Government, and the rate of sales tax varied from state to state. Toothpaste is a consumer good, and under the previous regime, it was subjected to Sales Tax or VAT (Value Added Tax), which was collected by the State Government. However, after the introduction of the Goods and Services Tax (GST) in 2017, sales tax was largely subsumed under GST, which is a dual taxation system involving both the Centre and the State Governments. 257","PW-2121":"","PW-2122":"Article 257 states that the executive power of every State must be exercised in a manner that does not impede or prejudice the exercise of the executive power of the Union. This provision ensures the supremacy of Union executive power in matters where coordination or cooperation is required between Union and State governments. 259","PW-2123":"The main idea behind the Panchayati Raj Institutions (PRIs) or Local Self-Government is to promote grass root democracy and development. The main aim is to evolve a system of democratic decentralisation and people’s participation with a view to ensure rapid socio-economic progress and provide adequate justice. The phrase to emphasise here is “Best”. Democratic decentralisation is the best description of Local self-government. Balwant Rai Mehta committee (on Community Development Program) in 1957 recommended the establishment of a scheme of Democratic decentralisation with 3-tiered structure of PRI. 261","PW-2124":"Statement 1 is incorrect: Part IX of the Constitution deals with the Panchayati Raj System in India. The Panchayati Raj was constitutionalized in India through the 73rd Constitutional Amendment Act of 1992. As per the act, no person shall be disqualified on the ground that he is less than 25 years of ageif he has attained the age of 21 years. Therefore the minimum age is 21. The minimum age that a person should have to contest an election is 21 years. Statement 2 is correct: Panchayat reconstituted after premature dissolution does not enjoy the full period of five years but remains in office only for the remaining period. 262","PW-2125":"Statement 1 is incorrect: The Gram Nyayalayas Act, 2008 was enacted to establish Gram Nyayalayas at the grassroots level, ensuring access to justice at citizens' doorsteps and preventing denial of justice due to social, economic, or other barriers. The Gram Nyayalaya shall be a mobile court and shall exercise the powers of both Criminal and Civil Courts. The Gram Nyayalaya shall follow summary procedure in criminal trial. Statement 2 is correct: The Court shall try to settle disputes via conciliation between the parties and the court can make use of the conciliators(social workers) to be appointed for this purpose. SUPER HINT For S1, Ask yourself: If the rural population is to get complete justice, should the court handle only civil cas- es? Aren’t criminal issues (like petty theft, assault, do- mestic disputes) also common in villages? So logically, limiting Gram Nyayalayas to civil cases defeats their very purpose. Hence likely false. S2 is positive, general, logical and can be corrected by common observation. 263","PW-2126":"Statements 1 and 3 are correct: The main idea behind the Panchayati Raj Institutions (PRIs) is to promote grass root democracy and development. The main aim is to evolve a system of democratic decentralisation and people’s participation with a view to ensure rapid socio-economic progress and provide adequate justice. Statement 2 is incorrect: Political accountability can be achieved in any system with democratic rule and thus not the fundamental objective of PRIs. Statement 4 is incorrect: Financial mobilisation was never the fundamental basis for the establishment of PRI. 264","PW-2127":"The Panchayat (Extension to Scheduled Areas) Act, 1996 (PESA Act) was enacted to extend the provisions of Part IX of the Constitution (related to Panchayati Raj) to the Scheduled Areas listed under Schedule V of the Constitution. Its primary objectives include: 1. To provide self-governance in tribal areas through Gram Sabhas. 2. To recognize traditional rights of tribal communities, particularly regarding community resources. 3. To free tribal people from exploitation by empowering Gram Sabhas to regulate and control resources, markets, and institutions in Scheduled Areas. The creation of autonomous regions is not an objective of the PESA Act. Autonomous regions are primarily a feature of Schedule VI of the Constitution, applicable to certain tribal areas in the northeastern states, not the Schedule V areas targeted by PESA. 265","PW-2128":"Under the Section 6(1) of Scheduled Tribes and Other Traditional Forest Dwellers (Recognition of Forest Rights) Act, 2006 (commonly known as the Forest Rights Act or FRA), the Gram Sabha is designated as the primary authority to initiate the process of determining the nature and extent of individual and community forest rights. Forest Rights Act, 2006:  The act recognizes and vests the forest rights and occupation in Forest land to forest Dwelling Scheduled Tribes (FDST) and Other Traditional Forest Dwellers (OTFD) who have been residing in for at least three generations prior to the 13th day of December, 2005. For the purpose of this clause, \"generation\" means a period comprising of twenty-five years  The act further enjoins upon the Gram Sabha and rights holders the responsibilities and authority for sustainable use, conservation of biodiversity and maintenance of ecological balance of FDST and OTFD.  While protecting the FDST and OTFD’s way of life and food security, it strengthens the conservation regime for the forests. 266","PW-2129":"PESA 1996. is a vital instrument in promoting participatory democracy and inclusive development in tribal areas. PESA Act, 1996: Key Features 1. Applies to Schedule V Areas: Extends Panchayati Raj provisions to tribal areas. 2. Empowers Gram Sabha (Section 4): Authority over resources, land, markets, and dispute resolution. 3. Recognizes Tribal Rights: Protects customs, traditions, and resource management. 4. Prevents Exploitation: Requires community consent for land acquisition and mining. 5. Promotes Self-Governance: Decentralizes power to tribal communities. Statement 1 is correct: Under Section 4(m)(iii) of PESA 1996. Gram Sabha has the power to prevent alienation of land and to restore any unlawfully alienated land of a scheduled tribe. Statement 2 is correct: The Gram Sabha, under the PESA Act, was granted wide-ranging powers, including consultation on land acquisition, ownership of minor forest produce, and the right to be consulted on leasing of minor minerals in Scheduled Areas. Statement 3 is incorrect: As per Section 4(k) and 4(l) of the PESA Act, the Gram Sabha must be co","PW-2130":"The 73rd Constitutional Amendment Act, 1992 added a new part IX to the Constitution of India. This part is entitled “The Panchayats” and contains articles 243 to 243 O. Statement 1 is incorrect: The 74th Constitutional Amendment Act provides for a District Planning Committee to consolidate the plans prepared by Panchayats and Municipalities (Article 243ZD) not 73rd Amendment. Statement 2 is correct: According to the 73rd Constitutional Amendment Act, the conduct of Panchayati Raj elections is vested in the state election commission(under Article 243-k) consisting of a state election commissioner appointed by the Governor of the state. Statement 3 is correct: Under article 243-I. 73rd Amendment Act also mandates for the establishment of State Finance Commissions. 268","PW-2131":"Statement 1 is correct: Article 243 ZE of Part IX A provides for establishment of the Metropolitan Planning Committee (MPC). Formation of Metropolitan Planning Committees (MPCs)is mandated in all metropolitan areas where population is above 10 Lakh. The elected officials of the municipalities and the heads of the panchayats in the metropolitan area elects 2/3rd of the MPC members from among themselves. 1/3rd are nominated. Elected members are proportionate to the rural: urban population ratio. Statement 2 is correct: Under Article 243-ZE, MPC prepares the draft development plans for the metropolitan area. Statement 3 is incorrect: MPC helps in draft planning and not in implementing the Govt sponsored schemes in the metropolitan area. 269","PW-2132":"According to Article 243E of the Constitution, if a Panchayat is dissolved before its term ends, elections must be held within six months. This ensures that the democratic process is restored promptly. However, if the remainder of the term is less than six months, elections may not be necessary. 270","PW-2133":"The first Municipal Corporation in India was established in Madras (now Chennai) in 1688 during British rule. It was created by the British East India Company to address administrative and civic issues in growing urban settlements. This was followed by the establishment of municipal corporations in Bombay (now Mumbai) and Calcutta (now Kolkata) in 1726. 271","PW-2134":"Statement (1) is correct: Part IX for Panchayats, Part IXA for Municipalities, and provisions under the 74th Amendment Act, 1992. Part IX of the Constitution, introduced by the 73rd Amendment Act, 1992, contains provisions for Panchayats, detailing their composition, powers, and functioning under Articles 243 to 243O. Statement (2) is incorrect: Part IXA of the Constitution, introduced by the 74th Amendment Act, 1992, governs Municipalities. However, Article 243Q does not envisage just two types of municipalities. It provides for three types:  Municipal Corporations for larger urban areas.  Municipal Councils for smaller urban areas.  Nagar Panchayats for areas transitioning from rural to urban. 272","PW-2135":"Local bodies are directly responsible for addressing citizens’ grievances related to municipal services, basic amenities, etc. However, the State Government can intervene in cases of inefficiency or corruption. Polity 217 274","PW-2136":"","PW-2137":"","PW-2138":"","PW-2139":"The Panchayati Raj System in India, as established by the 73rd Constitutional Amendment Act of 1992, follows a three-tier structure of local self-government. This system is designed to decentralize power and governance to the grassroots level, ensuring democratic participation and accountability in rural areas. The three-tier system ensures local governance at all levels: village, block, and district, allowing for effective planning, implementation, and oversight of developmental activities. 24. ANTI DEFECTION LAW 280","PW-2140":"Statement 1 is incorrect: A nominated member of a House becomes disqualified for being a member of the House if he joins any political party after the expiry of six months from the date on which he takes his seat in the House. This means that he may join any political party within six months of taking his seat in the House. Statement 2 is correct: The law does not specify any time period for the Presiding Officer to decide on a disqualification plea under the Tenth Schedule. 25. CONSTITUTIONAL BODIES 281","PW-2141":"Option 1 is correct: The National Commission for Backward Classes (NCBC) was initially constituted by the Central Govt through the National Commission for Backward Classes Act, 1993, which was repealed through the National Commission for Backward Classes (Repeal) Act, 2018. At present, the commission has been accorded Constitutional Status and constituted through the Constitution (One Hundred and Second Amendment) Act, 2018 whereby Article 338B has been inserted, forming a Commission for the socially and educationally backward classes to be known as National Commission for Backward Classes. Option 2 is incorrect: The National Human Rights Commission (NHRC) of India was established under the Protection of Human Rights Act (PHRA), 1993 and amended by the Protection of Human Rights (Amendment) Act, 2006. It is in conformity with the Paris Principles, for the promotion and protection of human rights. Section 2(1)(d) of the PHRA defines Human Rights as the rights relating to life, liberty, equality and dignity of the individual guaranteed by the Constitution or embodied in the Internation","PW-2142":"The Fifteenth Finance Commission (XVFC)’s Term of Reference was unique and wide-ranging in many ways. The Commission was asked to recommend performance incentives for States in many areas like the power sector, adoption of DBT, solid waste management, etc. The XV FC’s Report is organised in four volumes and deals with two kinds of devolution : Polity 219  Vertical Devolution: distribution of net proceeds of taxes between the Union and states.  Horizontal Devolution: distribution of net proceeds of taxes among the states. Options 1, 2 and 5 are correct: Horizontal Devolution based on principles of need, equity and performance, the overall devolution formula is as follows : Criteria Weight (%) Population 15 Area 15 Forest and Ecology 10 Income Distance 45 Tax and Fiscal Efforts 2.5 Demographic Performance 12.5  Demographic performance: States with better performance in controlling population growth were rewarded (12.5% weightage).  Forest and ecology: States with a larger share of dense forest area received weightage (10%).  Tax and fiscal efforts: States with higher tax collectio","PW-2143":"Statement 1 is incorrect: Attorney General has the right to speak and to take part in the proceedings of Parliament or their joint sitting and any committee of the Parliament of which he is a member, but without a right to vote. He enjoys all the privileges and immunities that are available to a Member of Parliament. While Solicitor General of India and Additional Solicitor General of India have no such rights or privilege. Statement 2 is incorrect: The term of office of the AG is not fixed by the Constitution and also, the Constitution does not contain the procedure and grounds for his removal. He holds office during the pleasure of the president and conventionally, he resigns when CoM resigns or is replaced, as he is appointed on its advice. SUPER HINT For S1, Watch for “only” trap, and why tag SG (non constitutional) along and on same footing as AG(constitutional)? Hence likely false. For S2, Resignation with government change Could be a political convention, not a legal mandate. Hence likely false. 284","PW-2144":"The Ministry of Tribal Affairs (MoTA) is the nodal agency for the implementation of the Scheduled Tribes and Other Traditional Forest Dwellers (Recognition of Forest Rights) Act, 2006. The ministry deals with forest and livelihood objectives at the national level. 285","PW-2145":"Statement 1 is incorrect: Strength of ECI is not specified in the Constitution, and it is determined by the President. Currently, there are 3 Members. Statement 2 is incorrect: The most important function of the commission is to decide the election schedules for the conduct of periodic and timely elections, whether general or bye-elections. Statement 3 is correct: It grants recognition to political parties & allot election symbols to them along with settling disputes related to splits/mergers of recognized political parties. 286","PW-2146":"Article 76 of the Constitution of India deals with the provisions of the Attorney General of India. The Attorney General of India is appointed by the President of India. Eligibility: He/She should be qualified to be Judge of Supreme Court (i.e. Citizen of India and must have been a judge of some high court for 5 years or an advocate of some high court for 10 years) or an eminent jurist, in the opinion of the president. Rights: He/She has the Right to speak and to take part in the proceedings of Parliament or their joint sitting and any committee of the Parliament of which he is a member, but without a right to vote. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 220 287","PW-2147":"Statement 1 is incorrect: The CAG does not exercise exchequer control during emergencies (whether national or financial). The Finance Ministry and the Department of Economic Affairs are responsible for the management of the exchequer during such emergencies. The CAG’s role remains to audit and report on the use of public funds, but it does not have direct control over financial matters during an emergency. Statement 2 is correct: PAC’s chief function is to examine the audit report of Comptroller and Auditor General (CAG) after it is laid in the Parliament. CAG acts as a guide, friend and philosopher of the Public Accounts Committee of the Parliament. Statement 3 is correct: Information from CAG reports can be used by investigating agencies to press charges against those who have violated the law while managing public finances. Statement 4 is incorrect: While dealing with the audit and accounting of government and PSUs, CAG does not have certain judicial powers for prosecuting those who violate the law. CAG is merely an advisory body and has some quasi-judicial powers. 288","PW-2148":"Statement 1 is correct: One of the notable recommendations made by the Thirteenth Finance Commission was related to the Goods and Services Tax (GST). The Commission recommended the introduction of a GST system as a comprehensive indirect tax reform. Additionally, it proposed a compensation mechanism for states that would face revenue losses during the implementation of the GST. The compensation package was meant to ensure that states did not suffer a revenue shortfall when transitioning from the existing system of sales tax and other taxes to the unified GST. The implementation of GST was linked to a timeline, and the Commission suggested setting up a GST compensation fund. Statement 2 is incorrect: While the Thirteenth Finance Commission did acknowledge the importance of utilizing India’s demographic dividend (the large working-age population), it did not specifically design a detailed job creation strategy or suggest a mechanism for creating lakhs of jobs in the next decade. The Commission focused more on fiscal and financial management, including issues related to devolution of fu","PW-2149":"","PW-2150":"The Finance Commission of India primarily deals with the distribution of financial resources between the Union and the States. Statement 1 is incorrect: The Finance Commission does not authorize withdrawals from the Consolidated Fund of India. This function falls under the purview of the Comptroller and Auditor General (CAG). Statement 2 is correct: One of the key roles of the Finance Commission is to determine the distribution of tax revenues between the Union and the States, ensuring an equitable allocation of resources. Statement 3 is correct: The Finance Commission considers applications for grants-in-aid from States. These grants help supplement the financial resources of states, particularly those in need. Statement 4 is incorrect: The Commission does not supervise or report on tax compliance by the Union or State governments. Its primary focus is on reviewing financial relations and making recommendations on revenue sharing and grants. 293","PW-2151":"Statement 1 is incorrect: The Chief Election Commissioner (CEC) and other Election Commissioners (ECs) have equal powers and responsibilities within the Election Commission of India. They receive equal salaries as well and there is no disparity in salaries between the Chief Election Commissioner and the other Election Commissioners. Statement 2 is correct: The Chief Election Commissioner is entitled to the same salary as is provided to a judge of the Supreme Court. Note: This fact was correct in accordance to the year in which it was asked. As per latest amendments in the Chief Election Commissioner and Other Election Commissioners (Appointment, Conditions of Service, and Term of Office) Act, 2023, the salary of the Chief Election Commissioner (CEC) and Election Commissioners (ECs) is now equivalent to that of the Cabinet Secretary. Statement 3 is correct: The removal process for the Chief Election Commissioner mirrors that of a Supreme Court judge. This safeguards the CEC’s independence and ensures impartiality in their role. While an EC can be removed on the CEC’s recommendation. S","PW-2152":"The Finance Commission plays a crucial role in India’s fiscal structure. It is a constitutional body constituted by the President of India every five years, or more frequently if deemed necessary.  Its primary responsibility is to recommend the distribution of financial resources between the central and state governments.  One key function of the Finance Commission is to propose principles and guidelines for distributing grants-in-aid to states from the Consolidated Fund of India.  These grants aim to support states in addressing fiscal needs, ensuring balanced regional development, and mitigating economic disparities among states. 295","PW-2153":"","PW-2154":"The Attorney General of India holds the highest legal office in the country, providing advice to the government on legal matters. Statement 1 is correct: According to Article 76(1) of the Indian Constitution, the President appoints the Attorney General. The appointment is based on the President’s discretion. Statement 2 is correct: As per Article 76(1), the qualifications for the Attorney General match those of a Supreme Court judge. This includes being an Indian citizen and having served as a High Court judge for at least five years, or an advocate in a High Court for at least ten years, or being an eminent jurist. Statement 3 is incorrect: There is no constitutional requirement for the Attorney General to be a member of either House of Parliament. Unlike ministers, the Attorney General does not need parliamentary membership to hold the office. Statement 4 is incorrect: The Attorney General serves at the pleasure of the President and can be dismissed at any time by the President. The process of impeachment, which applies to the President and judges, is not applicable to the Attorney","PW-2155":"The Finance Commission is a constitutional body established under Article 280 of the Indian Constitution. Its key role is to recommend how financial resources should be distributed between the Central Government and the State Governments. The Commission assesses several factors, including:  The financial conditions of the Centre and States  Revenue needs and expenditure patterns  The fiscal capacity of different states Based on this evaluation, it recommends the allocation of tax revenues, the distribution of revenue between the Centre and the States, as well as grants-in-aid and other financial resources. This helps ensure a balanced and equitable distribution of funds, promoting both fiscal autonomy and development across various states. Polity 223 26. NON-CONSTITUTIONAL BODIES 298","PW-2156":"The North Eastern Council (NEC) is not a constitutional body but a statutory organization established under the North Eastern Council Act, 1971, as amended in 2002. Initially, NEC was an Advisory Body for the North Eastern Region (NER). NEC’s composition was revised by the North Eastern Council (Amendment) Act, 2002. After the amendment: Option 1 is correct: The Governors of the eight North Eastern States are members of the NEC. Option 2 is correct: The Chief Ministers of the eight North Eastern States are also members of the NEC. Option 3 is correct: The President nominates three members to the NEC. Option 4 is incorrect: The Union Home Minister is the ex-officio Chairman of the NEC but is not considered a member under Section 3 of the Act. 299","PW-2157":"Statement 1 is correct: QCI was established jointly by the Government of India and Indian industry associations— ASSOCHAM, CII, and FICCI—to set up a national accreditation structure and drive the National Quality Campaign. Statement 2 is correct: The Chairman of QCI is appointed by the Prime Minister, based on recommendations from the industry to the government. The Council governing QCI consists of 38 members, equally representing the government, industry, and other stakeholders. The Department for Promotion of Industry and Internal Trade (DPIIT), under the Ministry of Commerce and Industry, serves as the nodal ministry for QCI. 300","PW-2158":"Statement 1 is incorrect: It is constituted by the President under Article 280 to give its recommendations on the distribution of tax revenues between the Union and the States. It defines the financial relations between the Centre and the States. Therefore, it is not directly associated with “Planning” in the traditional sense. Statement 2 is correct: Earlier, NDC served as “the highest decision-making authority” in the country on development matters. NDC used to advise the Planning Commission on planning. Statement 3 is incorrect: The Union Ministry of Rural Development is entrusted with the task of accelerating the socio- economic development of rural India. Statement 4 is incorrect: The Union Ministry of Urban Development is entrusted with the formulation and administration of the rules and regulations and laws relating to the housing and urban development in India. Statement 5 is correct: Parliament is the supreme legislative institution of the Republic of India. It is directly responsible to make laws and devise plans and strategies for the welfare of the society. Therefore, it ","PW-2159":"Statement 1 is incorrect: National Development Council (NDC) and Planning Commission (PC) have been abolished now. NDC was an advisory body and used to advise the Planning Commission on planning and included all CMs and union ministers etc. Statement 2 is correct: The Economic and Social Planning is kept in the Concurrent List in the Constitution of India. Statement 3 is correct: Preparation of plans and implementation of plans for economic development and social justice are one of the major powers and functions that comes under Panchayat Raj Institution. 302","PW-2160":"NDC comprises the Prime Minister, all the Union Cabinet Ministers, the Chief Ministers of all States and Union Territories and the Members of the Planning Commission. It does not include the chairman of the Finance Commission. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 224 303","PW-2161":"The National Development Council, the Planning Commission and the Zonal Councils do not find its mention in the Constitution. They are the Non-Constitutional Bodies. Few details about the same are as follows:  National Development Council (NDC) was set up on 6 August, 1952 by an executive order of the government. It served as “the highest decision-making authority” in the country on development matters. The National Development Council used to advise the Planning Commission on planning. Currently, there is no existence of NDC and Planning Commission, it has been replaced by NITI AAYOG.  The Planning Commission of India was set up by a Resolution of the Government of India in March 1950.  The Zonal Councils are the statutory (and not the constitutional) bodies. They are established by an Act of the Parliament, that is, the States Reorganisation Act of 1956. The act divided the country into five zones- Northern, Central, Eastern, Western and Southern and provided a zonal council for each zone. 27. GOVERNANCE 304","PW-2162":"Statement 1 is incorrect: In the report ‘Reorganisation of the Machinery of Central Government’ (1950) Sh. N. Gopalaswamy Ayyangar, suggested the grouping of ministries, improvement in the capabilities of the personnel, and also in the working of the Organisation and Method(O&M) Division. It nowhere mentions that a minister and a secretary be designated solely for pursuing the subject of administrative reform and promoting it. Moreover, it was the 1st ARC that suggested a minister and a secretary be designated solely for pursuing the subject of administrative reform and promoting it. Statement 2 is correct: In 1970, on the basis of the recommendations of the Administrative Reforms Commission, the Department of Personnel was set up. SUPER HINT For S1, \"Designated solely\" is an extreme phrase and thus highly improbable to be true. Designating someone of such a high post for such small specific task, is too im- practical to be suggested by a committee, hence likely false. 305","PW-2163":"The Government of India launched the National Child Labour Project (NCLP) in 1988 to rehabilitate children employed in hazardous industries and occupations. This central sector scheme involved identifying child laborers, removing them from hazardous work, enrolling them in Special Training Centres (STCs), providing necessary training, and mainstreaming them into formal education. Statement 1 is incorrect: It is run by the Ministry of Labour and Employment. Statement 2 is correct: The Gurupadaswamy Committee was formed by the Government of India in 1979 to study child labor and suggest ways to address it. 306","PW-2164":"","PW-2165":"Eighth Schedule contains languages recognised by the Constitution. Originally, it had 14 languages, but presently, there are 22. They are Assamese, Bengali, Bodo, Dogri (Dongri), Gujarati, Hindi, Kannada, Kashmiri, Konkani, Mathili (Maithili), Malayalam, Manipuri, Marathi, Nepali, Odia, Punjabi, Sanskrit, Santhali, Sindhi, Tamil, Telugu, and Urdu.  Sindhi was added by the 21st Amendment Act of 1967;  Konkani, Manipuri and Nepali were added by the 71st Amendment Act of 1992  Bodo, Dongri, Maithili and Santhali were added by the 92nd Amendment Act of 2003.  Oriya was renamed as ‘Odia’ by the 96th Amendment Act of 2011. 308","PW-2166":"","PW-2167":"","PW-2168":"The Ninth Schedule of the Indian Constitution contains laws initially intended to be exempt from judicial review, especially regarding their compatibility with fundamental rights. However, judicial review is permissible if such laws violate the basic structure of the Constitution. The Ninth Schedule was introduced to protect land reform laws and other social justice legislation from being challenged in courts. It was added through the First Amendment to the Constitution in 1951. 311","PW-2169":"","PW-2170":"The Constitution (One Hundred and Twenty-Eighth Amendment) Bill, 2023 was introduced in Lok Sabha on September 19, 2023. The Bill seeks to reserve one-third of the total number of seats in Lok Sabha and state legislative assemblies for women. Key features of the Bill :  Statement 1 is incorrect: The next delimitation exercise, or redrawing of constituency boundaries, is scheduled to be held in 2026. Effectively, this means that the earliest implementation of the women’s quota in the Lok Sabha can be in the 2029 general election (19th Lok Sabha), rather than in next year’s polls.  Statement 2 is correct: The reservation will be effective after the census conducted after the commencement of this Bill has been published. Based on the census, delimitation will be undertaken to reserve seats for women. The reservation will be provided for a period of 15 years. However, it shall continue till such date as determined by a law made by Parliament.  Statement 3 is correct: The Bill reserves, as nearly as may be, one-third of all seats for women in Lok Sabha, state legislative assemblies, an","PW-2171":"Statement 1 is incorrect: The authority to recognize and declare a community as a Scheduled Tribe is vested in the President of India under Article 342 of the Indian Constitution. The President issues a notification specifying the Scheduled Tribes in relation to a State or Union Territory, after consulting with the Governor of the concerned State. However, the Governor does not have independent authority to declare any community as a Scheduled Tribe. Statement 2 is correct: The status of a Scheduled Tribe is State/ Union Territory-specific. A community recognized as a Scheduled Tribe in one State may not necessarily enjoy the same status in another State unless it is explicitly notified as such for that State by the President. This reflects the differing socio-economic and cultural contexts across States, as well as variations in tribal populations. SUPER HINT S1 aligns with Function-person/organisation/ministry match trap as its easy to manipulate to make it false. Is it President or Governor? 317","PW-2172":"Statement 1 is correct: Part IXA of the Constitution was inserted by the Constitution (Seventy-fourth Amendment) Act, 1992. It contains provisions for local self-government at the urban level (including powers of the municipalities). Statement 2 is correct: Emergency provisions are outlined in Part XVIII of the Constitution, covering Articles 352 to 360, including National Emergency (Article 352), State Emergency (Article 356), and Financial Emergency (Article 360). These provisions empower the Central government to address any extraordinary situations effectively. Statement 3 is correct: Part XX deals with the provisions related to the amendment of the Constitution (Art 368). Parliament may, in the exercise of its constituent power, amend by way of addition, variation or repeal any provision of the Constitution in accordance with the procedure laid down in this part. 319","PW-2173":"Statement 1 is incorrect: Home Guards are raised under the Home Guards Act and Rules of the States/Union Territories. The Ministry of Home Affairs provides policy guidance, but the implementation is state-specific. Statement 2 is correct: The role of Home Guards is to serve as an auxiliary Force to the police in the maintenance of internal security situations, help the community in any kind of emergency such as an air raid, fire, cyclone, earthquake, epidemic etc., help in the maintenance of essential services, promote communal harmony and assist the administration in protecting weaker sections, participate in socio- economic and welfare activities and perform Civil Defence duties. Statement 3 is correct: Fifteen Border Wing Home Guards (BWHG) Battalions (Bns) have been raised in the border States viz. Punjab (6 Bns.), Rajasthan (4 Bns.), Gujarat (2 Bns.) and one each Battalion for Meghalaya, Tripura and West Bengal to serve as an auxiliary to Border Security Force for preventing infiltration on the international border/coastal areas, guarding of Vital Areas/ Vital Points and lines o","PW-2174":"Pair 1 is correctly matched : Section 6 of the Official Secrets Act,1923, deals with the unauthorised use of uniforms, falsification of reports, forgery, personation, and false documents. Pair 2 is incorrectly matched: Section 7 of the Official Secrets Act,1923 deals with the infraction of interfering with ‘Officers of the Police’ or ‘Members of the Armed Forces of the Union’ engaged in the discharge of their duties. Pair 3 is correctly matched: Arms (Amendment) Act, 2019 outlines that whoever uses a firearm in a ‘rash or negligent manner’ or in ‘celebratory gunfire’ so as to endanger human life or personal safety of others shall be punishable with imprisonment for a term which may extend to two years, or with fine which may extend to rupees one lakh, or with both. 321","PW-2175":"Statement 1 is correct: Under Article 355 of the Indian Constitution, it is the duty of the Union, i.e. the Central Government, to protect every State against external aggression and internal disturbance and to ensure that the government of every State is carried on in accordance with the provisions of this Constitution. Statement 2 is correct: Article 22(3)(b) of the Indian Constitution explicitly states that the rights under Article 22(1) and 22(2)—which include the right to legal counsel—do not apply to individuals detained under preventive detention laws. Statement 3 is incorrect: Section 32 of Prevention of Terrorism Act 2002, allows confessions made before a police officer (not below the rank of Superintendent of Police) to be admissible as evidence in court, provided they are recorded in accordance with prescribed safeguards. This provision departs from general criminal law, where confessions before police are inadmissible under Sections 25 and 26 of the Indian Evidence Act. Article 22 protects individuals who are arrested or detained, outlining two types of detention:  Punit","PW-2176":"Statement 1 is correct: According to Article 244(1) of the Fifth Schedule of the Constitution, “Scheduled Areas” refer to regions that the President can designate as such through an order following consultation with the Governor of the respective State. Statement 2 is correct: The largest administrative unit forming the scheduled areas has been the district, and the lowest is the cluster of villages in the block. This is consistent with how Scheduled Areas are designated based on administrative feasibility and compactness. Statement 3 is incorrect: The executive power of a state extends to the scheduled areas therein. But the Governor has a special responsibility regarding such areas. He has to submit a report to the President regarding the administration of these areas annually or whenever so required by the President as per Paragraph 3 of the Fifth Schedule. 325","PW-2177":"Statement 1 is incorrect: Parole is not a right but a privilege granted by prison authorities. Parole is a discretionary relief granted to prisoners under specific conditions. The decision to grant parole lies with the prison authorities or state authorities, and they may deny parole even if a prisoner makes out a sufficient case, depending on factors such as security risks or the nature of the crime committed. Statement 2 is correct: Each state has its own parole rules, governed by respective State Prison Manuals and the Prisons Act, 1894. These rules outline eligibility criteria, conditions, and the authority responsible for granting parole. SUPER HINT For S1, Trap phrase: “cannot be denied” → an absolute phrase implying parole becomes a right. But in India: Parole is not a Fundamental Right, nor is it automatical- ly granted. Even if a \"sufficient case\" is made, granting parole is at the discretion of the competent authority. Hence likely false. 327","PW-2178":"Statement 1 is incorrect: Judicial custody does not mean detention in a police station. Instead, the accused is sent to jail under the magistrate’s orders. Police custody, on the other hand, involves detention at a police station for investigation. Judicial custody ensures that the accused is under judicial supervision and not directly handled by the police. Statement 2 is correct: During judicial custody, the police cannot interrogate the accused without prior approval from the court. This provision protects the accused from undue pressure or custodial violence while ensuring due process. Judicial custody refers to a situation where an accused person is under the custody of the court and housed in a jail, whereas police custody means the accused is detained at a police station for investigation. These are governed by provisions under the Code of Criminal Procedure (CrPC), 1973. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 230 Aspect Judicial Custody Police Custody Authority Under the jurisdiction of the court. Under the jurisdiction of the police for investigation. Detention Location The accused is sent to","PW-2179":"Statement 1 is incorrect: EPF coverage is not universal for all casual workers. It applies to workers in establishments with 20 or more employees and only if they meet the eligibility criteria under the Employees' Provident Funds and Miscellaneous Provisions Act, 1952. Many temporary, seasonal, or casual workers may not qualify. Statement 2 is correct: Casual workers are entitled to regular working hours and overtime payment as per the Minimum Wages Act, 1948, and the Factories Act, 1948. These laws ensure that all workers, including casual labourers, have regulated working hours and are paid overtime wages at stipulated rates if they work beyond the prescribed hours. Statement 3 is correct: The government can mandate wage payments through banking channels under the Payment of Wages Act, 1936, which was amended by the Payment of Wages (Amendment) Act, 2017. This amendment allows the government to require industries and establishments to pay wages electronically or through bank transfers to enhance transparency and prevent exploitation. 330","PW-2180":"Statement 1 is incorrect: As per the Aadhaar Act, 2016, metadata cannot be stored beyond six months, not three months. Statement 2 is correct: The Supreme Court struck down Section 57 of the Aadhaar Act, which allowed private entities to use Aadhaar for authentication or to enter into contracts involving Aadhaar data. The Supreme Court ruling (2018) restricted Aadhaar data sharing with private entities, ensuring privacy and limiting government contracts with private corporations. Statement 3 is incorrect: Aadhaar is not mandatory for purchasing insurance products as per IRDAI guidelines. Statement 4 is correct: Aadhaar is required for availing benefits funded by the Consolidated Fund of India, as per Section 7 of the Aadhaar Act. Polity 231 331","PW-2181":"Statement 1 is incorrect: The Maternity Benefit (Amendment) Act, 2017, provides for 26 weeks of paid maternity leave for women employees for the first two children. Of this, a maximum of 8 weeks can be availed before delivery, and the remaining after childbirth. For women with more than two children, the entitlement is reduced to 12 weeks (6 weeks pre- delivery and 6 weeks post-delivery). Statement 2 is incorrect: Establishments with 50 or more employees must provide crèche facilities, but the law does not mandate six crèche visits per day, rather mothers are allowed to visit the crèche four times a day, including rest intervals. Statement 3 is correct: The Maternity Benefit (Amendment) Act, 2017, specifies that women who already have two or more surviving children are entitled to only 12 weeks of paid maternity leave, compared to 26 weeks for those with fewer than two children. 332","PW-2182":"Statement 1 is correct: According to the Ministry of Tribal Affairs, there are 75 PVTGs officially notified in India, residing across 18 States and one Union Territory (Andaman & Nicobar Islands). Statement 2 is correct: A declining or stagnant population is one of the key criteria for identifying a PVTG, along with dependence on subsistence-level economy and limited access to modern facilities. The criteria for identifying PVTGs include:  Pre-agricultural level of technology,  Low level of literacy,  Economic backwardness,  A stagnant or declining population. Statement 3 is incorrect: As of now, there are 75 officially notified PVTGs, not 95. Statement 4 is correct: Both Irular (Tamil Nadu) and Konda Reddi (Andhra Pradesh) tribes are included in the official list of PVTGs. 333","PW-2183":"Statement 1 is correct : The Food Safety and Standards Act, 2006, replaced the Prevention of Food Adulteration Act, 1954, and several other food-related laws to bring uniformity in food safety regulations. It aimed to establish a single authority (FSSAI) for regulating food safety and standards in India. Statement 2 is incorrect : FSSAI is an autonomous body under the Ministry of Health and Family Welfare, but it is not under the charge of the Director General of Health Services. Instead, it functions independently with its own Chairperson and Chief Executive Officer appointed by the Central Government. 334","PW-2184":"Statement 1 is incorrect: Under the Prohibition of Benami Property Transactions Act, 1988, a transaction can still be considered a benami transaction even if the owner of the property is unaware of or denies knowledge of the ownership. The Act defines a benami transaction as one where the property is held by one person but paid for by another, irrespective of whether the ostensible owner is aware or not. Statement 2 is correct: Benami properties are liable for confiscation by the government without compensation, as per Section 5 of the Act. Statement 3 is incorrect: The Act establishes three authorities for investigation—Initiating Officer, Approving Authority, and Adjudicating Authority—but also provides for an appellate tribunal to handle disputes and appeals related to benami transactions. SUPER HINT For S1, Law punishes the structure of concealment, not the mental awareness of the benamidar. Hence likely false. For S3, UPSC loves to trap with negative absolutes like: “does not provide…” , “only”, “never” Think prac- tically: Would any modern law not have an appellate mechanism? T","PW-2185":"Statement 1 is correct: Consumers have the right to take food samples for testing if they suspect adulteration, under the Food Safety and Standards Act, 2006. Statement 2 is incorrect: Filing a complaint in a consumer forum requires payment of a court fee, which varies depending on the value of the claim. For instance, no fee is charged for claims up to ₹5 lakh, but fees are applicable for higher claims as per the prescribed structure. Statement 3 is correct: Legal heirs can file or continue consumer complaints on behalf of a deceased consumer under the Consumer Protection Act, ensuring that grievances do not lapse upon the complainant's death. 336","PW-2186":"The Rights of Persons with Disabilities (RPWD) Act, 2016, and other policies provide multiple benefits to persons with disabilities to ensure their inclusion and accessibility in society. Statement 1 is correct: Children with disabilities are entitled to free education till the age of 18 in government schools, as per the RPWD Act, 2016. Statement 2 is correct: The government provides preferential allotment of land for businesses, housing, and special employment schemes for persons with disabilities. Statement 3 is correct: Public buildings are required to have ramps and other accessibility features under the Accessible India Campaign and the RPWD Act. 337","PW-2187":"Articles 371A to 371I were added through various amendments to preserve the cultural, social, and economic interests of specific regions, addressing their unique needs. Statement 1 is correct: Articles 371A to 371I were added to meet regional demands of states like Nagaland, Assam, Manipur, Andhra Pradesh, Sikkim, Mizoram, Arunachal Pradesh, and Goa. Statement 2 is incorrect: Although both constitutions allow a dual system of governance, the United States permits dual citizenship, while India adheres to single citizenship. Statement 3 is also incorrect: In India, a naturalized citizen can lose citizenship if acquired through fraud or disloyalty to the Constitution. 339","PW-2188":"The Food and Nutrition Board is primarily responsible for implementing various programs related to nutrition, food security, and the health of children and mothers. Currently. It works under the Ministry of Women and Child Development in the Government of India. However, in the year the question was asked, the body was under the purview of the Ministry of Health and Family Welfare. Polity 233 340","PW-2189":"","PW-2190":"The correct sequence in descending order is Judges of the Supreme Court-Deputy Chairman of Rajya Sabha- Attorney General of India-Members of Parliament. The correct sequence in the descending order of precedence in the warrant of precedence is: 1. President of India 2. Vice President of India 3. Prime Minister of India 4. Governors of States within their respective States 6. Speaker of Lok Sabha, and Chief Justice of India 7. Cabinet Ministers of the Union. 7A. Holders of Bharat Ratna decoration 8. Chief Ministers of States outside their respective States. Governors of States outside their respective States. 9. Judges of the Supreme Court 10. Deputy Chairman of RS 11. Attorney General of India 12. Member of Parliament 343","PW-2191":"Survey of India, the oldest scientific department under the Department of Science & Technology, was established in 1767. As the principal mapping agency, it ensures India’s domain is accurately mapped, providing base maps for development and resource utilization to support the country’s progress and security. The Department of Science & Technology which operates under the Ministry of Science and Technology, promotes science and technology in India, from high-end research and cutting-edge technology development to addressing the technological needs of the common man through skill development. 344","PW-2192":"The Ministry of Parliamentary Affairs ensures the smooth functioning of Parliament and communication with Members of Parliament (MPs). It establishes consultative committees, like the Consultative Committee for Railway Zones(Consultative Committee for the Ministry of Railways), where MPs from different constituencies discuss and provide input on railway-related issues. This committee helps MPs understand and address the functioning, development, and challenges of railway zones, allowing them to offer suggestions and raise concerns. The ministry coordinates these meetings to facilitate collaboration between MPs and the Ministry of Railways, enhancing railway services’ efficiency and responsiveness in specific zones. 347","PW-2193":"Statement 1 is correct: The Representation of the People Act, 1951, under Section 29A, provides for the registration of political parties with the Election Commission of India (ECI). Statement 2 is correct: The Election Commission of India is responsible for the registration of political parties in India as per the provisions of the Representation of the People Act, 1951. Statement 3 is correct: The criteria for recognizing a national party includes being recognized in at least four or more states as per the Election Commission’s guidelines. Hence, a party can be considered national if it fulfills certain criteria, which includes recognition in four or more states. Statement 4 is correct: During the 1999 general elections, there were indeed six national parties and 48 state-level parties recognized by the Election Commission. 349","PW-2194":"The Order of Precedence is a protocol list maintained by the Government of India that determines the ceremonial hierarchy for officials. The Chief Justice of India (CJI) ranks the highest among the given functionaries, occupying the 6th position in the Order of Precedence. Next is the Union Cabinet Minister, who ranks 7th, reflecting their high status as senior members of the executive. The Chief Election Commissioner comes next in rank, placed lower than a Union Cabinet Minister in ceremonial hierarchy. Finally, the Cabinet Secretary, though the highest-ranking civil servant in India, ranks lower than the other three functionaries, holding a position below the Chief Election Commissioner. Below is the Order of Precedence as per the latest guidelines: 1. President of India 2. Vice President of India 3. Prime Minister of India 4. Governors of States (within their respective states) 5. Former Presidents Chief Justice of India Speaker of the Lok Sabha 6. Union Cabinet Ministers Chief Ministers of States (within their respective states) Deputy Chairman of the NITI Aayog Former Prime Mini","PW-2195":"Statement 1 is correct: The Representation of the People (Amendment) Act, 1996, specifies that a person convicted of the offence of insulting the Indian National Flag or the Constitution of India is disqualified from contesting elections for six years from the date of conviction. Statement 2 is correct: The security deposit amount for candidates contesting elections was increased to discourage non-serious candidates. Statement 3 is incorrect: The law does not restrict a candidate from contesting elections from more than one Parliamentary constituency, but if a candidate wins both, they must vacate one. Statement 4 is correct: The amendment removed the provision requiring elections to be countermanded in the event of the death of a contesting candidate, ensuring that the electoral process is not delayed. The only exception would be if the candidate had already secured the maximum number of votes. 352","PW-2196":"The National Human Rights Commission (NHRC) is a statutory body established under the Protection of Human Rights Act, 1993. Statement 1 is Correct: The Chairman of the NHRC must be a retired Chief Justice of India, as per the original Act. However, the 2019 amendment provided that a person who has been a Judge of the Supreme Court is also made eligible to be appointed as Chairperson of the Commission in addition to the person who has been the Chief Justice of India. Statement 2 is incorrect: While State Human Rights Commissions exist, they are not present in every state; their establishment depends on state governments. Statement 3 is Correct: The powers of the NHRC are primarily recommendatory in nature. It can suggest measures for relief or improvement, but its recommendations are not legally binding. Statement 4 is Incorrect: There is no mandatory provision in the original Act requiring the appointment of a woman as a member of the NHRC. However The 2019 act amends this to allow at least one member to be a woman. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 236 353","PW-2197":" The Water (Cess) Act, 1977: This act is aimed at the conservation and sustainable use of water resources. It imposes a cess on water consumed by industries to promote efficient water usage, indirectly contributing to environmental protection.  The Forest (Conservation) Act, 1980: This act focuses on the preservation and protection of forests in India. It prevents the diversion of forest land for non-forest purposes, which helps in conserving biodiversity and mitigating climate change.  The Public Liability Insurance Act, 1991: This act ensures that industries that deal with hazardous substances have insurance to compensate victims of accidents, promoting environmental and public safety.  The Port Laws Amendment Act, 1997: This act deals with port management and administration but does not have a direct focus on environmental protection or conservation. 354","PW-2198":"A is matched with 3: The President of India takes an oath to “preserve, protect, and defend the Constitution” and uphold the Constitution of India, which corresponds to the oath of faith and allegiance to the Constitution. B is matched with 4: Judges of the Supreme Court swear to “discharge their duties without fear or favor” and uphold the Constitution and the law, aligning with the oath of upholding the Constitution and the law. C is matched with 2: Members of Parliament pledge to “bear true faith and allegiance to the Constitution of India,” which corresponds to the oath of faith and allegiance to the Constitution. D is matched with 1: According to Article 75(4), ministers take an oath to uphold secrecy and faithfully discharge their duties. 355","PW-2199":"The “Panchsheel” Agreement, also known as the Five Principles of Peaceful Coexistence, was a set of guidelines established in 1954 between India and China. The principles are: 1. Mutual respect for each other’s territorial integrity and sovereignty 2. Mutual non-interference in each other’s internal affairs 3. Equality and mutual benefit 4. Peaceful coexistence 5. Non-aggression Non-alignment is a separate concept, particularly associated with India’s foreign policy during the Cold War, where India refrained from aligning with any of the major power blocs. It is not one of the principles of Panchsheel. v v v","PW-2200":"Options 1, 2 and 4 are correct:  Italy has a low birth rate and ageing population. The country has one of the lowest fertility rates in the world at around 1.3 children per woman (well below the replacement rate of 2.1). This has led to a rapidly ageing population, with a significant proportion of the population over 65 years old.  Japan is often highlighted for its aging population and declining population. The country has one of the oldest populations in the world with over 28% of its population aged 65 or older. Japan’s birth rate is also very low, at around 1.4 children per woman leading to a shrinking population.  South Korea is frequently mentioned for its extremely low birth rate, which is the lowest in the world at around 0.7- 0.8 children per woman. This has led to concerns about a rapidly ageing population and a declining workforce. Options 3 and 5 are incorrect:  Nigeria has one of the highest fertility rates in the world at around 4.5-5.3 children per woman and a very young population. The median age in Nigeria is approximately 18 years which makes it one of the young","PW-2201":"Statement 1 is incorrect: Exercise Mitra Shakti-2023 was a joint military exercise between India and Sri Lanka, not Bangladesh. Statement 2 is correct : The ninth edition of the Joint Military exercise “Exercise MITRA SHAKTI-2023” was held at the For- eign Training Node in Aundh, Pune. Statement 3 is correct : The primary objective of the exercise was to rehearse sub-conventional operations under Chapter VII of the United Nations Charter focusing on joint responses during counter-terrorism operations. Activities included raids, search- and-destroy missions, and heliborne operations. The Scope of the exercise included synergising joint responses during count- er-terrorist operations. Statement 4 is correct : Indian Air Force was part of this as both sides practiced tactical actions such as raid, search and destroy missions, heliborne operations, etc. For the first time, Exercise Mitra Shakti-2023 included participation from the Indian Air Force (15 personnel) and the Sri Lankan Air Force (5 personnel) making it a bi-service exercise. 3","PW-2202":"Pair 1 is correctly matched : Argentina has been ex- periencing a severe economic crisis characterized by hyperin- flation, a depreciating peso, and fiscal instability. Persistent fiscal deficits and chronic inflation are longstanding issues in Argentina. The inflation rate averaged 190% between 1944 and 2023, and the government defaulted on its sovereign debt nine times (of which three occurred during the past two decades). Pair 2 is correctly matched : Since April 2023, Sudan has been embroiled in a violent conflict between the Sudanese Armed Forces (SAF) and the paramilitary Rapid Support Forces (RSF). This civil war has resulted in significant casualties and displacement of civilians. Pair 3 is incorrectly matched : As of February 2025, Turkey remains a member of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO). It plays a strategic role in the alliance particularly due to its geographic location bridging Europe and Asia. 10 International Relations and Current Affairs UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 642 4","PW-2203":"The International Grains Council (IGC) is an inter- governmental organization established in 1949 to promote cooperation and stability in the global grain trade. It oper- ates under the Grains Trade Convention (GTC), 1995, which aims to enhance market transparency and international pol- icy coordination. Headquartered in London, United Kingdom, the IGC has 30 member countries, including India, the USA, the EU, China, and Russia, working together to monitor grain supply, demand, and trade policies worldwide. Statement 1 is correct : The IGC is an intergovernmental organi- zation that promotes cooperation in the global grain trade. India, along with 29 other countries, is a member of the International Grains Council (IGC). Statement 2 is incorrect : A country does not need to be a member of the IGC to export or import rice and wheat. Mem- bership in the IGC is not a prerequisite for engaging in interna- tional trade of grains. Many countries actively participate in the global grains market without being members of the IGC. 6","PW-2204":"Statement 1 is incorrect: The World Toilet Organiza- tion (WTO) is an independent global non-profit organisation committed to improving toilet and sanitation conditions world- wide. It was founded in 2001. It is not an agency of the United Nations but it was granted consultative status with the United Nations Economic and Social Council in 2013. Statement 2 is correct: Through its initiatives, such as World Toilet Day, World Toilet Summit, World Toilet College and SaniShop, WTO continues to mobilise an international network of partners, supporters, donors, governments and international organisations to advocate for effective sanitation policies to en- sure health, dignity and well-being for everyone, everywhere. The World Toilet Summit and World Toilet Day were launched in 2001, and the World Toilet College was introduced in 2005 to address sanitation challenges through education and training. Statement 3 is incorrect: The main focus of the organisation is to continue to build the global sanitation movement through collaborative action. The WTO’s primary focus is on advocacy, educati","PW-2205":"The “100 Million Farmers” initiative, spearheaded by the World Economic Forum, aims to revolutionize global food systems by encouraging sustainable agricultural practices. Its key goals include achieving net-zero carbon emissions, im- proving biodiversity, and strengthening farmers’ resilience to the effects of climate change. The platform unites diverse stakeholders—such as businesses, governments, farmers, in- ternational organizations, and innovators—to collaboratively advance this transformation. By prioritizing regenerative agriculture and climate adapta- tion strategies, the initiative seeks to help farmers transition to sustainable practices through innovative financial models and partnerships. It also aims to position food systems and farmers at the forefront of global efforts to address climate and environ- mental challenges, aligning with broader sustainability objec- tives. 11","PW-2206":"Pair 1 is incorrectly matched: The Donbas region in eastern Ukraine includes Donetsk and Luhansk, which border Russia. These areas host the Russia-backed separatist entities, the Donetsk People’s Republic (DPR) and Luhansk People’s Re- public (LPR). Collectively, the entire region, including these terri- tories, is referred to as Donbas. Pair 2 is incorrectly matched: Kachin Region lies in the north- ern part of Myanmar. The Kachin Independence Army (KIA) has been fighting against Myanmar’s military for greater auton- omy. Pair 3 is incorrectly matched: Tigray is not located in North Yemen. It is a region in northern Ethiopia where a conflict erupted in November 2020 between the Ethiopian federal gov- ernment and the Tigray People’s Liberation Front (TPLF). UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 644 12","PW-2207":"Pair 1 is incorrectly matched : North Kivu and Ituri are located in the eastern region of the Democratic Republic of Congo. In these two provinces a “State of Siege” was declared in response to escalating violence. Pair 2 is incorrectly matched: Nagorno-Karabakh is a land- locked, mountainous region at the heart of a long-standing conflict between Azerbaijan and its predominantly Armenian population, which is backed by neighboring Armenia. Although internationally recognized as part of Azerbaijan, the region re- mains a source of ongoing dispute. Pair 3 is incorrectly matched: Russia has disclosed voting re- sults indicating significant backing from four Ukrainian provinc- es— Donetsk, Luhansk, Zaporizhzhia, and Kherson to unite with Russia. 13","PW-2208":"In recent years, several African nations have experi- enced military takeovers. In Chad, after President Idriss Dé- by’s death in 2021, his son led a military coup and established a Transitional Military Council. In Sudan, General Abdel Fattah al-Burhan led a 2021 coup, dissolving the civilian government and sparking protests. Mali saw two military coups in 2020 and 2021, with Colonel As- simi Goita overthrowing President Ibrahim Boubacar Keïta and later taking power himself. In Guinea, Colonel Mamady Doum- bouya led a 2021 coup, ousting President Alpha Conde after his controversial bid for a third term. 15","PW-2209":"Statement 1 is correct : The G-20 was established in 1999 in response to the financial crises of the late 1990s. It be- gan as a forum for Finance Ministers and Central Bank Gover- nors from major economies to discuss international economic and financial issues. The primary aim was to bring together both developed and emerging economies to promote interna- tional financial stability. Statement 2 is correct : During its G-20 presidency in 2023, India has prioritized digital public infrastructure (DPI) as a key agenda item. India has been a global leader in developing and implementing DPI such as the Aadhaar biometric identi- fication system, the Unified Payments Interface (UPI), and the DigiLocker platform. India aims to share its expertise and promote the adoption of DPI globally to foster inclusive growth and digital transformation. 16","PW-2210":"Statement 1 is correct : The Stability and Growth Pact (SGP) is an agreement among the member states of the European Union (EU) to facilitate and maintain the stability of the Economic and Monetary Union (EMU). It sets limits on the budgetary deficits and public debt of EU member states. It requires countries to keep their budget deficits below 3% of GDP and public debt below 60% of GDP or to be working to- wards these targets. Statements 2 and 3 are incorrect :  The Stability and Growth Pact does not mandate or involve sharing infrastructure facilities among EU member states. It is purely focused on fiscal discipline and economic stability.  The Stability and Growth Pact does not directly deal with technology sharing or cooperation in technological development. 18","PW-2211":"Statement 1 is incorrect: The Global Compact for Safe, Orderly and Regular Migration (GCM) was adopted by most UN member states in December 2018 but not all. Coun- tries like the US, Hungary, Poland, Israel, and the Czech Republic did not endorse it. It is the first global framework on interna- tional migration. Statement 2 is incorrect: The GCM is a non-binding agree- ment. It is a cooperative framework that provides guidelines and best practices for managing international migration but does not impose legally binding obligations on UN member states. It respects the sovereignty of states and is intended to foster inter- national cooperation. Statement 3 is incorrect: The GCM specifically focuses on international migration and does not address internal mi- gration or internally displaced people (IDPs). Internal dis- placement is covered by other frameworks such as the Guiding Principles on Internal Displacement. 19","PW-2212":"Somalia, the Eastern African nation has endured de- cades of civil strife and political instability since its central government collapsed in 1991, leading to widespread violence and displacement. Recurring droughts exacerbated by cli- mate change and conflict have caused severe food shortages and famine. In 2022 and 2023 Somalia faced one of its worst droughts resulting in a humanitarian crisis. Organizations like the United Nations and the World Food Programme have high- lighted the dire situation, calling for urgent aid. The combination of prolonged conflict, economic challenges, and environmental factors has made Somalia a focal point of global attention for its severe famine conditions. 20","PW-2213":"The United Nations Convention on the Law of the Sea (UNCLOS), 1982, defines maritime zones and rights of coastal and landlocked states. Statement 1 is correct: According to Article 3 of the United Nations Convention on the Law of the Sea (UNCLOS), every coastal state has the right to establish its territorial sea up to a maximum breadth of 12 nautical miles from baselines deter- mined under the convention. The state exercises full sovereign- ty over this zone, including its airspace and seabed. Statement 2 is correct: Article 17 of UNCLOS provides that all states, including landlocked ones, have the right of “innocent passage” through the territorial sea of a coastal state. Inno- cent passage means passing through the sea without harming the security, peace, or environment of the coastal state. Statement 3 is correct: Article 57 of UNCLOS specifies that an Exclusive Economic Zone (EEZ) extends up to 200 nautical miles from the baseline used to measure the territorial sea. In this zone, the coastal state has special rights over marine re- sources (fishing, oil exploration, etc.) but i","PW-2214":"Organization of Turkic States (OTS) formerly known as the Turkic Council was established in 2009 under the Nakh- chivan Agreement. Its primary objective is to promote compre- hensive cooperation among Turkic-speaking countries, fostering collaboration based on shared history, culture, and language. Full Members include Azerbaijan, Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan, Türkiye and Uzbekistan and Observer States are Hungary, Turkmeni- stan, and the Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus (TRNC). The OTS Secretariat is headquartered in Istanbul, Türkiye. Options (c) is correct:  Azerbaijan is a full member of OTS. It has strong ethnic, linguistic, and cultural ties with Turkey and other Turkic nations.  Uzbekistan is a full member of OTS, joining officially in 2019. It is a Turkic-speaking Central Asian country with historical connections to the Turkic world. Armenia is not a Turkic country and is not a member of OTS. It has historical conflicts with Azerbaijan, especially over Na- gorno-Karabakh. Croatia is not a Turkic-speaking country and not a member of OTS. It is part of the European Union (EU) an","PW-2215":"Statement 1 is incorrect: Bidibidi is not in Kenya. It is one of the largest refugee settlements in the world located in north-western Uganda, near the border with South Sudan. Statement 2 is correct: Bidibidi was established in 2016 to ac- commodate refugees fleeing the civil war in South Sudan. Bidibi- di refugee settlement in Uganda shelters people displaced by the South Sudan civil war (2013–2018). Uganda hosts over 1 million South Sudanese refugees with Bidibidi being the largest settlement. Statement 3 is correct: The Dadaab refugee complex, locat- ed in north-eastern Kenya, has been a major shelter for Somali refugees since the outbreak of civil war in Somalia in 1991. It remains one of the largest and longest-standing refugee camps globally. 23","PW-2216":"The United Nations General Assembly (UNGA) is one of the six principal organs of the United Nations (UN). It is responsible for granting observer status to non-member en- tities including states and intergovernmental organizations (IGOs). Statement 1 is correct: The UNGA can grant observer status to non-member states. Having observer status allows them to participate in its sessions and work without voting rights. For example, the Holy See (Vatican City) and Palestine have Permanent Observer status in the UN. Statement 2 is correct: Inter-governmental organizations (IGOs) can apply for observer status in the UNGA. Examples: European Union (EU), African Union (AU) and International Organization for Migration (IOM) have observer status at the UN. Statement 3 is correct: Permanent Observers at the UNGA can establish diplomatic missions at the UN Headquarters in New York. Example: The Holy See and Palestine maintain Permanent Observer Missions at the UN. 24","PW-2217":"The United Nations Credentials Committee is a sub- sidiary committee of the UN General Assembly (UNGA) and not the UN Security Council. It is responsible for reviewing the credentials of representatives of UN member states and re- porting its findings to the General Assembly. Statement 1 is incorrect: The Credentials Committee is estab- lished by the UN General Assembly (UNGA), not the UN Secu- rity Council (UNSC). It operates independently of the UNSC and reports directly to the General Assembly. Statement 2 is incorrect: There is no fixed schedule for the Credentials Committee. It usually meets before the annual Gen- eral Assembly session in September and whenever neces- sary. The statement that it meets three times a year (March, June, and September) is not correct. Statement 3 is correct: The committee reviews and validates the credentials of representatives of all UN member states. It then submits a report to the General Assembly which then votes on whether to accept or reject the credentials. This process ensures that only legitimate representatives of member states participate","PW-2218":"Option 1 is correct : Asian Infrastructure Investment Bank (AIIB) is a multilateral development bank headquar- tered in Beijing, China. It focuses on infrastructure financing in the Asia-Pacific region. India is a founding member (member since 2016) and the second-largest shareholder after China. Option 2 is correct : Missile Technology Control Regime (MTCR) is an informal political agreement among 35 mem- ber countries to prevent the proliferation of missile technolo- gy capable of carrying WMDs (weapons of mass destruction). India became a full member in 2016, helping strengthen its missile development programs. Option 3 is correct: Shanghai Cooperation Organisation (SCO) is a Eurasian political, economic, and security alliance originally led by China and Russia. India joined as a full member in 2017 alongside Pakistan. 26","PW-2219":"Statement 1 is correct: Vietnam has been one of the fastest-growing economies in recent years, with GDP growth averaging 6-7% annually. Strong manufacturing, exports, and foreign direct investment (FDI) have driven growth. Statement 2 is incorrect: Vietnam is a one-party communist state led by the Communist Party of Vietnam (CPV). There is no multi-party system in the country. Statement 3 is correct: Vietnam’s economic growth is highly linked to its role in global supply chains, particularly in elec- tronics, textiles, and manufacturing. It is a key exporter to the US, China, and the EU. Statement 4 is correct: Vietnam has long attracted global manufacturers due to low labour costs, a skilled workforce, and currency stability. Major companies like Samsung, Apple (via suppliers), and Nike have expanded production in Viet- nam. Statement 5 is incorrect: While Vietnam has a growing digital economy, it does not have the most productive e-service sec- tor in the Indo-Pacific. Countries like India and Singapore lead in e-services and digital innovation in the region. 27","PW-2220":"The Levant refers to the eastern Mediterranean region covering Syria, Lebanon, Jordan, Israel, Palestine and parts of Turkey and Egypt (Sinai Peninsula). It is derived from the French word lever (to rise) and signifies the eastward direction of the rising sun. This region has been historically significant for trade, ancient civilizations, and conflicts. The term is also asso- ciated with the Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant (ISIL), a designated terrorist organization. Option (b) is incorrect : Region along North African shores stretching from Egypt to Morocco is generally referred to as the Maghreb, not the Levant. The Maghreb includes Morocco, Algeria, Tunisia, Libya, and Mauritania with Egypt sometimes included in broader definitions. Option (c) is incorrect : Region along Persian Gulf and Horn of Africa includes countries such as Saudi Arabia, UAE, Oman, Yemen (Persian Gulf), and Somalia, Djibouti, Eritrea (Horn of Africa). Option (d) is incorrect : The Mediterranean coastline includes regions from Southern Europe, North Africa, and the Levant but the term “Levant” does not co","PW-2221":"The G20 Common Framework for Debt Treatments beyond the Debt Service Suspension Initiative (DSSI) was introduced in November 2020 to help low-income countries (LICs) manage unsustainable debt burdens caused by eco- nomic shocks like the COVID-19 pandemic. Statement 1 is correct: The G20 Common Framework was jointly developed by the G20 and the Paris Club, a group of ma- jor creditor nations that coordinate debt relief efforts. It aims to provide debt restructuring, relief, and sustainability mea- sures for eligible countries. Statement 2 is correct: The Common Framework focuses on low-income countries (LICs) with high debt burdens, par- ticularly those eligible for the International Development Association (IDA) assistance. It allows for case-by-case debt restructuring, ensuring that LICs can stabilize their economies and recover from financial crises. 29","PW-2222":"Pair 1 is correctly matched : Anatolia is a historical and geographical region covering most of modern-day Tur- kiye. It is often in the news due to geopolitical issues, earth- quakes, and archaeological discoveries. Pair 2 is correctly matched : Amhara is a region in Ethiopia that has been in the news due to conflicts involving the Ethi- opian government and Tigray forces. It is one of the major ethnic regions in Ethiopia. Pair 3 is incorrectly matched : Cabo Delgado is in Mozam- bique, not Spain. It has been in the news due to Islamist in- surgencies and attacks by terrorist groups in northern Mo- zambique. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 648 Pair 4 is incorrectly matched: Catalonia is in Spain, not Italy. It is a region in northeastern Spain that has been in the news due to independence movements and political conflicts with the Spanish government. 30","PW-2223":"Pair 1 is incorrectly matched : There is no confirmed report of China establishing a permanent military base in Chad. China has increased its influence in Africa through eco- nomic investments and Belt and Road Initiative (BRI) proj- ects but not through a military base in Chad. The only con- firmed Chinese overseas military base is in Djibouti. Pair 2 is correctly matched : In September 2021 Guinea’s mili- tary staged a coup by overthrowing President Alpha Condé and suspending the constitution and government. The coup was led by Colonel Mamady Doumbouya citing political instabil- ity, corruption, and economic issues. Pair 3 is correctly matched : Lebanon has been facing a deep economic crisis since 2019, marked by: Hyperinflation and currency collapse, mass unemployment, energy and food short- ages, Political instability. The World Bank described Lebanon’s crisis as one of the worst economic collapses since the 19th century. Pair 4 is correctly matched : In July 2021 Tunisia’s President Kais Saied suspended the Parliament and dismissed the Prime Minister citing emergency powers due ","PW-2224":"Statement 1 is incorrect: The Global Ocean Commis- sion (GOC) does not grant licenses for seabed mining. The Inter- national Seabed Authority (ISA) established under the United Nations Convention on the Law of the Sea (UNCLOS) is respon- sible for granting licenses for seabed exploration and mining in international waters. Statement 2 is correct: India has been granted licenses by the International Seabed Authority (ISA) for seabed mineral ex- ploration in international waters. India has received a contract to explore polymetallic sulfides in the Indian Ocean Ridge. The Indian Ministry of Earth Sciences and NIOT (National In- stitute of Ocean Technology) are leading the project. Statement 3 is correct: Rare earth elements (REEs) are found in deep-sea sediments, polymetallic nodules, and hydrothermal vents in international waters. These include elements like neo- dymium, yttrium, and dysprosium, which are essential for electronics, renewable energy, and defense industries. 33","PW-2225":"","PW-2226":"Statement 1 is incorrect: While India-Sri Lanka trade has grown over time but it has not shown consistent growth ev- ery year. Trade fluctuated due to factors such as economic slow- downs, policy changes, and the COVID-19 pandemic. Statement 2 is correct: Textiles and textile articles form a major component of India’s exports to Bangladesh. Bangla- desh is a leading global exporter of garments, and it imports raw materials (cotton, yarn, and fabric) from India for its textile and apparel industry. Textiles and made-ups account for 56% of Indi- an imports from Bangladesh. Statement 3 is incorrect: Bangladesh, not Nepal, has been In- dia’s largest trading partner in South Asia over the past five years. In the fiscal year 2022-23 India’s exports to Bangladesh were valued at US$ 13.84 billion which makes it one of India’s top export destinations. 35","PW-2227":"Pair 1 is correctly matched: The Alma-Ata Declara- tion (1978) was adopted at the International Conference on Primary Health Care (PHC) in Alma-Ata (now Almaty, Ka- zakhstan). It emphasized “Health for All” and the importance of primary healthcare. Pair 2 is incorrectly matched: The Hague Conventions of 1899 and 1907 primarily focus on the laws of war and the con- duct of hostilities including the prohibition of certain means of warfare. The control of biological and chemical weapons is cov- ered by the Biological Weapons Convention (BWC) and Chemical Weapons Convention (CWC), not the Hague Convention. Pair 3 is correctly matched: The Talanoa Dialogue was launched by Fiji during its presidency of the 23rd Confer- ence of the Parties (COP23) to the United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change (UNFCCC) in 2017. It is a facili- tative dialogue aimed at encouraging countries to enhance their climate action and ambition under the Paris Agreement. The term “Talanoa” refers to a traditional Pacific Island approach to inclusive and participatory dialogue. Pair 4 is incorrectly match","PW-2228":"Statement 1 is incorrect: The Protocol against the Smuggling of Migrants by Land, Sea and Air is not part of the United Nations Convention against Corruption (UNCAC). It is a supplementary protocol to the United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime (UNTOC) adopted in 2000. The UNCAC was adopted in 2003 and focuses specifically on combating corruption and does not include provisions re- lated to migrant smuggling. Statement 2 is correct: The UNCAC adopted in 2003 is the first legally binding global instrument to combat corruption. It provides a comprehensive framework for preventing and crim- inalizing corruption, promoting international cooperation, and recovering illicitly acquired assets. It has been ratified by nearly all UN member states. Statement 3 is incorrect: The UNTOC primarily focuses on combating transnational organized crime, including human traf- ficking, migrant smuggling, and illicit arms trafficking. It includes provisions for international cooperation and asset recovery but it does not have a specific chapter dedicated to returning assets to thei","PW-2229":"","PW-2230":"","PW-2231":"","PW-2232":"The International Labour Organization (ILO) has two key conventions focused on child labour :  ILO Convention 138 (Minimum Age Convention, 1973) focuses on the abolition of child labour by setting a minimum age for employment or work, which should not be less than the age of completion of compulsory schooling and, in any case, for most of the countries, not less than 15 years. It aims to ensure that children are not employed in work that jeopardizes their health, safety, or morals.  ILO Convention 182 (Worst Forms of Child Labour Convention, 1999) aims to eliminate the worst forms of child labour, including slavery, trafficking, debt bondage, forced labour, and hazardous work. It is recognized as one of the core ILO conventions, widely ratified by countries worldwide. 43","PW-2233":"","PW-2234":"The “Rule of Law Index” is an annual report published by the World Justice Project (WJP). It evaluates countries based on their adherence to the rule of law using factors such as:  Constraints on government powers  Absence of corruption  Open government  Fundamental rights  Order and security  Regulatory enforcement  Civil and criminal justice The index ranks countries based on data collected from experts and surveys to assess how well nations uphold legal principles. The index is widely used by governments, policymakers, and civil society organizations to identify strengths and weaknesses in the rule of law and to guide reforms. 45","PW-2235":"Statement 1 is correct : NSG members can engage in nuclear trade and obtain access to advanced nuclear technol- ogy and materials. This includes technologies for peaceful uses such as medicine, energy production, and research. India seeks NSG membership to improve its access to civilian nucle- ar technology and fuel for energy generation. Statement 2 is incorrect : NSG membership does not auto- matically grant NPT membership. Adherence to NPT princi- ples is often considered during NSG membership discussions but signing the NPT is not a mandatory requirement for joining the NSG. For instance, India seeks NSG membership without be- ing an NPT signatory. China has blocked India’s entry into NSG by citing India’s non-signatory status in NPT. 46","PW-2236":"Yemen and South Sudan have experienced severe hu- manitarian crises in recent years, with millions of people suffer- ing from famine, acute malnutrition, and starvation, primarily caused by ongoing wars and ethnic conflicts.  Yemen has been experiencing one of the world’s worst humanitarian crises due to a prolonged conflict since 2015. The war, combined with a blockade, has led to widespread famine-like conditions, with millions of people suffering from acute malnutrition and starvation. Over 80% of the population requires humanitarian aid, and millions are at risk of famine. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 652  Since its civil war began in 2013, South Sudan has faced severe food insecurity and famine conditions. Conflict has displaced millions, disrupted agricultural activities, and caused widespread hunger. In 2017, a famine was officially declared in parts of South Sudan, and even now, half the population faces extreme hunger. 47","PW-2237":"","PW-2238":"","PW-2239":"The Indian Ocean Naval Symposium (IONS) is a vol- untary initiative established by the Indian Navy in 2008 to enhance maritime cooperation among the littoral states of the Indian Ocean Region (IOR). It provides an open and inclusive platform for discussing regional maritime issues, fostering collaboration, and promoting security. IONS focuses on hu- manitarian assistance, disaster relief (HADR), and counter- ing regional challenges like piracy and terrorism. International Relations and Current Affairs 653 It includes 25 member nations grouped into four sub-regions (South Asia, West Asia, East Africa, and Southeast Asia & Australia) and 9 observer nations. The chairmanship rotates bi- ennially, with India set to chair from 2025-2027. Statement 1 is incorrect: The Indian Ocean Naval Symposium (IONS) was inaugurated in 2008, not 2015. The first meeting was held in New Delhi, India, in 2008, under the chairman- ship of the Indian Navy. Statement 2 is correct: IONS is a series of biennial meetings & voluntary initiative that promotes maritime cooperation among navies of the Indian Ocean l","PW-2240":"Statement 1 is correct : UN-Habitat (United Nations Human Settlements Programme) was established in 1978 and is mandated by the UN General Assembly. Its primary goal is to promote socially and environmentally sustainable human settlements and ensure adequate shelter for all. It works to- wards sustainable urban development, slum upgrading, and smart cities. Statement 2 is incorrect : UN-Habitat partners with a wide range of stakeholders, including NGOs, civil society organi- zations, academic institutions, private sector entities, and international development agencies, not just governments or local authorities. Statement 3 is correct : UN-Habitat contributes to reducing poverty by supporting inclusive urban planning, slum reha- bilitation, and sustainable housing solutions. It also promotes access to clean drinking water and basic sanitation, especial- ly in developing countries, through initiatives like the Water and Sanitation Trust Fund. 52","PW-2241":"The Global Infrastructure Facility (GIF) is a World Bank-led initiative that helps governments develop complex infrastructure projects through Public-Private Partnerships (PPPs) by attracting private sector and institutional investor capital. Launched in 2014, GIF offers comprehensive project support through the combined expertise of its technical and advisory partners. This group, which includes commercial banks and institutional investors, ensures that infrastructure projects are structured effectively and are financially viable, meeting the long-term needs of governments and users. Funding partners contribute financially to the GIF. Functions:  The Global Infrastructure Facility (GIF) mobilizes private sector investment by de-risking projects and promoting innovative financing mechanisms.  The GIF emphasizes sustainable infrastructure by integrating environmental, social, and governance (ESG) principles, with a focus on climate-smart projects.  It also builds capacity in partner countries through technical assistance and knowledge sharing.  Acting as a global collaboration pla","PW-2242":"The Asia Pacific Ministerial Conference on Housing and Urban Development (APMCHUD) is an intergovernmen- tal initiative established in 2006 under the auspices of UN-Hab- itat. It serves as a platform for collaboration among Asia-Pacific countries to address challenges in housing and urban develop- ment. APMCHUD is a biennial conference that convenes minis- ters and senior government officials from the Asia-Pacific region to discuss and exchange experiences on housing and urban de- velopment policies and strategies. Statement 1 is incorrect: The first APMCHUD was indeed held in India (New Delhi) in 2006, but the theme mentioned in the statement is incorrect. The actual theme was “A Vision for Sustainable Urbanization in the Asia-Pacific by 2020”, not “Emerging Urban Forms - Policy Responses and Governance Structure”. Statement 2 is incorrect: APMCHUD conferences are hosted by different countries in the Asia-Pacific region, not exclusive- ly by India. It is a UN-Habitat initiative, not a partnership with ADB (Asian Development Bank), APEC (Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation), or ASEAN (","PW-2243":"Statement 1 is incorrect : The Nuclear Security Sum- mit (NSS) was not organized by the United Nations (UN). It was a global initiative launched by the United States under President Barack Obama in 2010 to prevent nuclear terror- ism by securing nuclear materials.  The summits were held in 2010 (Washington, D.C.), 2012 (Seoul), 2014 (The Hague), and 2016 (Washington, D.C.).  These summits aimed at addressing nuclear terrorism and securing vulnerable nuclear materials but were independent of the UN framework. The UN, IAEA, and Interpol were involved in discussions. Statement 2 is incorrect : The International Panel on Fissile Materials (IPFM) is an independent group of experts focused on policy research related to nuclear disarmament and fis- sile material production. It works to reduce and secure global stocks of fissile materials like highly enriched uranium and plu- tonium but operates as a non-governmental organization. It is not an official organ of the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA). The IAEA deals with nuclear safeguards and monitoring, but IPFM operates separately","PW-2244":"Option (c) is correct: The Digital Single Market (DSM) Strategy is an initiative of the European Union (EU), created by EU in 2015. It is aimed at removing digital trade barriers among EU member states to create a unified and ef- ficient digital economy. The strategy aims to remove barriers to cross-border online activities, enhance digital connectivity, and promote fair competition. The DSM Strategy is a key part of the EU’s Digital Decade Policy for global digital leadership. It focuses on three key pillars:  Improving access to digital goods and services,  Creating an environment for digital networks and services to thrive, and  Maximizing the growth potential of the digital economy. 56","PW-2245":"It (GGGI) is published annually by the World Economic Forum (WEF). Global Gender Gap Index was introduced in 2006 by the World Economic Forum (WEF). The Index ranks countries based on gender parity (0 = complete inequality, 1 = complete equali- ty). It measures gender equality across four key areas:  Economic Participation and Opportunity  Educational Attainment  Health and Survival  Political Empowerment 57","PW-2246":"Statement 1 is correct: The International Solar Alliance (ISA) was launched on November 30, 2015, at the COP21 (Unit- ed Nations Climate Change Conference) in Paris, France. Statement 2 is incorrect: ISA does not include all UN member states. Initially, it was focused on solar-rich countries between the Tropics of Cancer and Capricorn. However, in 2018, its membership was expanded to include all member states of the United Nations. While all UN member states are eligible to join, not all have done so. 58","PW-2247":"GCC Member Countries are listed as under: 1. Saudi Arabia 2. United Arab Emirates (UAE) 3. Kuwait 4. Qatar 5. Bahrain 6. Oman Clearly, Iran is NOT a member of the GCC because it is a non-Arab country and has historical tensions with several GCC members. 59","PW-2248":"Statement 1 is incorrect: The OPCW is not an EU or- ganization. The Organisation for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons (OPCW) is an independent, autonomous international organization established in 1997 to implement the Chemical Weapons Convention (CWC). While OPCW collaborates with the UN, WHO, and other international agencies, it is not di- rectly linked to NATO or the EU. Statement 2 is correct: OPCW verifies and inspects chemical industries worldwide to ensure compliance with the Chem- ical Weapons Convention. It prevents the development and stockpiling of chemical weapons by monitoring the produc- tion and trade of dual-use chemicals. Statement 3 is correct: OPCW helps member states (States Parties) with protective measures against chemical weapon threats. It provides technical and logistical assistance in case of chemical attacks or threats. International Relations and Current Affairs 655 60","PW-2249":"Statement 1 is correct : The Third India-Africa Fo- rum Summit (IAFS) was held in 2015 in New Delhi, India. The first Summit was held in 2008 (New Delhi, India), and the sec- ond was in 2011 (Addis Ababa, Ethiopia). Statement 2 is incorrect : The India-Africa Forum Summit (IAFS) was first initiated in 2008, not in 1951. Jawaharlal Nehru did not start this summit; however, he played an im- portant role in strengthening India-Africa relations through the Non-Aligned Movement (NAM). The India-Africa Forum Sum- mit (IAFS) began in 2008 under the leadership of Prime Minister Dr. Manmohan Singh as a formal platform to strengthen relations between India and African nations. 61","PW-2250":"Statement 1 is incorrect: The Trans-Pacific Partner- ship (TPP) was a trade agreement, not a security alliance. Not all Pacific Rim countries were part of TPP. The TPP originally included 12 countries: United States, Canada, Mexico, Peru, Chile, Japan, Malaysia, Singapore, Vietnam, Brunei, Austra- lia, and New Zealand.  China and Russia were excluded, but many Pacific Rim countries like Indonesia, South Korea, and the Philippines were also not part of TPP.  In 2017, the U.S. withdrew from TPP, and the remaining 11 countries renegotiated it as the Comprehensive and Progressive Agreement for Trans-Pacific Partnership (CPTPP). In 2024, the United Kingdom became the first European country to join the CPTPP. Statement 2 is incorrect: The TPP was purely a trade and economic agreement, focusing on reducing tariffs, setting trade rules, and boosting investment. It was not related with maritime security or military alliances.  Maritime security issues in the Pacific are mainly handled by ASEAN, APEC, and military alliances like AUKUS and the Quad, not by TPP. 62","PW-2251":"The Global Hunger Index (GHI) is an annual report published by IFPRI (International Food Policy Research In- stitute) until 2018, and now by Concern Worldwide and Wel- thungerhilfe. It measures and tracks hunger at global, regional, and national levels using the following four key indicators :  Undernourishment  Child Wasting  Child Stunting  Child Mortality 63","PW-2252":"The European Stability Mechanism (ESM) is a per- manent crisis resolution mechanism for the eurozone. It was established in 2012 to provide financial assistance to euro- zone countries experiencing severe economic difficulties. The ESM offers loans, purchases bonds, and provides credit lines to stabilize member economies and prevent financial conta- gion within the euro area. The European Stability Mechanism (ESM), headquartered in Luxembourg, was established to re- place the European Financial Stability Facility (EFSF) and is funded by eurozone member states. It acts as a ‘lender of last resort’ for eurozone countries, offering loans and other types of support under strict conditions, such as implementing economic reforms. 64","PW-2253":"RCEP is a free trade agreement between ASEAN’s 10 member states and their five trade partners—Australia, Chi- na, Japan, New Zealand, and South Korea—aiming to boost trade, investment, and economic cooperation across Asia-Pa- cific. RCEP covers trade in goods and services, investment, e-com- merce, intellectual property, dispute settlement, and SMEs, fostering regional economic integration. The agreement grad- ually eliminates tariffs, enhances market access for goods and services, and simplifies rules of origin, benefiting global supply chains. RCEP promotes cross-border data flows, online consumer protection, and cybersecurity while improving investment protection and economic cooperation through capacity building and technology transfer. Ensuring equitable bene- fits, bridging economic disparities, and maintaining trans- parency remain key challenges. Despite this, RCEP represents a major milestone in global trade and economic collaboration. 65","PW-2254":"The Global Financial Stability Report (GFSR) is a bi- annual publication by the International Monetary Fund (IMF) that assesses global financial stability, systemic risks, and vulnerabilities in the international financial system. The report examines macroeconomic conditions, financial markets, reg- ulatory developments, and emerging risks. It provides pol- icy insights to help policymakers and financial institutions mitigate potential crises. The IMF conducts quantitative and qualitative analysis, including stress tests and scenario eval- uations, consulting with financial regulators and market ex- perts for a comprehensive risk assessment. 66","PW-2255":"The Belt and Road Initiative (BRI) is a China-led global infrastructure and investment project aimed at en- hancing trade and connectivity across Asia, Europe, and Af- rica. It consists of the Silk Road Economic Belt (land routes) and the Maritime Silk Road (sea routes), involving railways, roads, ports, power plants, and telecom infrastructure. BRI projects are financed by Chinese state-owned banks, the Asian Infrastructure Investment Bank (AIIB), and the Silk Road Fund. However, concerns about debt sustainability and financial transparency persist. Supporters highlight economic growth, trade facilitation, and regional integration, while critics warn of debt traps, environ- mental risks, and China’s geopolitical influence. 67","PW-2256":"Doctors Without Borders (Médecins Sans Frontières - MSF) MSF is a non-governmental, independent organization pro- viding emergency medical aid in conflict zones, epidemics, nat- ural disasters, and areas with limited healthcare access. Its teams include doctors, nurses, surgeons, logisticians, and admin- istrators, working in high-risk environments to deliver crit- ical healthcare services, including surgery, infectious disease treatment, maternal care, and mental health support. MSF relies primarily on private donations, ensuring neutrality and operational autonomy. It maintains strict financial trans- parency, publishing detailed reports on its funding and expen- ditures. Beyond medical aid, MSF raises awareness about humanitar- ian crises, neglected diseases, and human rights abuses. It advocates for improved healthcare access and humanitarian policies, using on-the-ground experience to influence public and policymaker decisions. 68","PW-2257":"The Treaty on the Non-Proliferation of Nuclear Weapons (NPT) classifies Nuclear-Weapon States (NWS) as those that tested nuclear weapons before January 1, 1967. These include China (Tested in 1964), France (Tested in 1960), Russia (formerly Soviet Union, 1949), United Kingdom (Tested in 1952) and United States (Tested in 1945). 69","PW-2258":"","PW-2259":"Statement 1 is incorrect : The Indian Ocean Rim As- sociation (IORA), formerly IOR-ARC, was established in 1997. It was not formed in response to piracy or oil spills but to promote regional economic cooperation, trade, and devel- opment among Indian Ocean nations. Piracy and maritime security became important issues later, but they were not the primary reason for formation of IOR-ARC. Statement 2 is incorrect : IORA is not just about maritime se- curity; it covers a broad range of areas, including: Trade and investment facilitation, Fisheries management, Disaster risk reduction, Academic and scientific cooperation, Tour- ism and cultural exchanges. International Relations and Current Affairs 657 71","PW-2260":"The Mekong-Ganga Cooperation (MGC) is a regional cooperation initiative launched in 2000 to strengthen ties between India and five Southeast Asian countries along the Mekong River and the Ganges River. MGC Member Countries include India, Thailand, Myanmar, Laos, Cambodia, Vietnam. Clearly, Bangladesh and China are not participants in MGC. : Objectives of MGC include :  Strengthening economic collaboration and trade between member nations,  Advancing cultural interactions and people-to-people connections, and  Encouraging dialogue and partnership on shared concerns. The MGC’s four core cooperation areas encompass tourism, culture, education, and transport & communication. Ad- ditionally, it has broadened its scope to cover emerging fields such as health and traditional medicine, agriculture and allied industries, small and medium enterprises, water resource management, science and technology, skill enhancement, and capacity development. 72","PW-2261":"Statement 1 is incorrect: APEC is a 21-member eco- nomic forum focused on promoting free trade and economic co- operation in the Asia-Pacific region. India has been seeking APEC membership, but it has not yet been admitted. Statement 2 is incorrect: ASEAN is a regional group of 10 Southeast Asian countries. However, India has strong ties with ASEAN and is a part of the ASEAN+6 framework but is not a full member. Statement 3 is correct: India is a member of the East Asia Summit (EAS). EAS includes 18 countries, including ASEAN members + India, China, Japan, South Korea, Australia, New Zealand, Russia, and the US. It focuses on political, security, and economic issues in the Indo-Pacific region. It promotes peace, stability, connectivity, and cooperation on global challenges such as climate change and health security. 73","PW-2262":"","PW-2263":"The World Bank is the publisher of the Global Eco- nomic Prospects report, a flagship publication that provides comprehensive analyses of the global economic landscape. This report is released twice a year, typically in January and June, and offers in-depth assessments of current economic conditions, emerging trends, and potential risks to the global economy. It serves as a key resource for policymakers. It focuses on the challenges faced by emerging markets and developing economies (EMDEs). The report highlights key is- sues such as trade restrictions, inflation, debt, and geopolit- ical tensions, while offering policy recommendations to foster sustainable growth. For 2025-26, global growth is projected to remain at 2.7%, with EMDEs contributing significantly to global GDP. The GEP emphasizes the need for investment, fiscal reforms, and international cooperation to address climate change, trade governance, and economic disparities. 77","PW-2264":"The 2014-2016 Ebola outbreak devastated West Af- rica, with Guinea, Sierra Leone, and Liberia at its epicenter. This was the largest Ebola epidemic ever recorded, exposing crit- ical weaknesses in regional healthcare systems and requiring a massive international response. The rapid spread and high mor- tality rate highlighted the global importance of infectious disease preparedness. 78. With reference to a grouping of countries known as BRICS, consider the following statements: 1. The First Summit of BRICS was held in Rio de Janeiro in 2009. 2","PW-2265":"The Arab Spring began in Tunisia on December 17, 2010. The catalyst for this wave of protests was the self-immo- lation of Mohamed Bouazizi, a street vendor in Sidi Bouzid, Tunisia, on December 17, 2010. Bouazizi’s desperate act, a re- sponse to the confiscation of his wares and the humiliation he suffered at the hands of local officials, ignited widespread public anger against the Ben Ali regime. This act of defiance resonated deeply with Tunisians who were already frustrated with high un- employment, corruption, and a lack of political freedom. The protests that followed Bouazizi’s death quickly escalated, spreading from Sidi Bouzid to other cities across Tunisia. Dem- onstrators demanded political reforms, economic opportuni- ties, and an end to the authoritarian rule of President Zine El Abidine Ben Ali. The Tunisian government’s attempts to quell the protests through force proved ineffective, and the movement gained momentum, fueled by social media and satellite televi- sion. After weeks of unrest, Ben Ali was forced to flee the country on January 14, 2011, marking the end of hi","PW-2266":"The Arctic Council is an intergovernmental forum that includes the following eight member states: 1. Canada 2. Denmark (including Greenland and the Faroe Islands) 3. Finland 4. Iceland 5. Norway 6. Russia (Russian Federation) 7. Sweden 8. United States (United States of America) Japan and the United Kingdom are not full member states. They hold observer status in the Council. The Arctic Council was established in 1996 through the Ottawa Declaration. Its primary mandate is to promote cooperation, coordination, and interaction among the Arctic States, par- ticularly on matters of sustainable development and environ- mental protection in the Arctic region. The Council serves as a platform for these eight member states to address the unique challenges and opportunities presented by the Arctic’s changing environment and the increasing interest in its resources. International Relations and Current Affairs 659 In addition to the core members and Indigenous Permanent Par- ticipants, other states, intergovernmental organizations, and non-governmental organizations can hold observer status, al","PW-2267":"Pair 1 is correctly matched : Chechnya is a federal subject of Russia, officially designated as the Chechen Republic. Located in the North Caucasus region, Chechnya has a complex history marked by periods of conflict and separatism. Following the collapse of the Soviet Union, Chechnya declared indepen- dence, leading to two devastating wars with Russia in the 1990s and early 2000s. Currently, Chechnya remains a part of the Russian Federation, though it enjoys a degree of autonomy. Pair 2 is incorrectly matched : Darfur is a region located in western Sudan, not in Mali. The Darfur region has been the site of a prolonged and complex conflict, marked by widespread vio- lence, displacement, and humanitarian crisis. The conflict, which began in 2003, involved various armed groups, including the Su- danese Armed Forces and the Janjaweed militia, and has result- ed in significant human rights abuses. Mali, on the other hand, is a country located in West Africa, distinct geographically and politically from the Darfur region. Pair 3 is incorrectly matched: The Swat Valley is situated in the K","PW-2268":"Statement 1 is correct: China has historically been the dominant global producer of rare earth elements, accounting for a significant share of the world’s supply. Concerns about supply disruptions have arisen due to China’s implementation of export restrictions, quotas, and other regulatory measures. These actions have included limiting export volumes, imposing ex- port tariffs, and consolidating its rare earth mining industry. These policies, while potentially aimed at domestic industrial development and resource conservation, have had significant impacts on global markets, creating price volatility and raising concerns about access to these crucial materials for other coun- tries. Statement 2 is incorrect: China, Australia, Canada, and Chile dominate the rare earth element market, but reserves are also found in Asia, Africa, Europe, and South America. Other coun- tries like the USA, India, Russia, Brazil, Vietnam, and Myan- mar also have significant rare earth deposits. While China re- mains the largest producer, global exploration and development efforts are underway to diversify ","PW-2269":"New START (Strategic Arms Reduction Treaty) is a bilateral nuclear arms control agreement between the United States and Russia, signed in 2010 and enforced from 2011. The treaty caps the number of deployed strategic nuclear warheads at 1,550 per country and imposes limits on intercontinental bal- listic missiles (ICBMs), submarine-launched ballistic missiles (SLBMs), and heavy bombers. Serving as a successor to the original START I treaty (1991), it continued the nuclear arms control initiatives established during the Cold War. In 2021, the treaty was extended for an additional five years, remaining in effect until Feb 4th, 2026. Option (b) is incorrect: The East Asia Summit deals with re- gional economic and security issues, but New START is unre- lated to energy security or multilateral agreements. Option (c) is incorrect: Russia and the EU have energy agree- ments, but New START is strictly a nuclear arms control treaty between Russia and the USA. Option (d) is incorrect: BRICS (Brazil, Russia, India, China, South Africa) focuses on economic cooperation, not nuclear arms reduction","PW-2270":"The most geostrategically significant factor about Southeast Asia is its location between the Pacific and Indian Oceans and its dominance in maritime trade routes, particu- larly through the Strait of Malacca, Sunda Strait, and Lombok Strait. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 660  The Strait of Malacca, one of the world’s most crucial maritime chokepoints, is vital for global shipping, making Southeast Asia central to global trade and security. Southeast Asia serves as a critical link between major global economies such as China, India, Japan, and the USA. It con- trols some of the world’s busiest sea lanes, with a significant portion of global trade and energy supplies passing through the region. 85","PW-2271":"Statement 1 is correct : One of the key goals of the Look East Policy was to strengthen India’s presence and influence in East and Southeast Asia, aligning with major economies like ASEAN, Japan, and South Korea. It aimed at enhancing trade, investment, defense cooperation, and connectivity in the re- gion. Statement 2 is incorrect : The end of the Cold War led to a shift in global power dynamics, but the Look East Policy was not specifically aimed at filling a power vacuum. Instead, it was driven by India’s need for economic liberalization, region- al integration, and diversification of foreign policy. Statement 3 is correct: India has deep-rooted cultural and historical links with Southeast and East Asian countries, par- ticularly through Buddhism, Hinduism, and trade routes. The policy is aimed at reviving these traditional ties to strengthen diplomatic and economic partnerships. 86","PW-2272":"Statement 1 is incorrect: The Australia Group (AG) is indeed an informal arrangement that aims to prevent the pro- liferation of chemical and biological weapons. However, the Wassenaar Arrangement (WA) is also an informal group, not a formal OECD body. The Wassenaar Arrangement focuses on the control of conventional arms and dual-use goods and technologies, not chemical or biological weapons. Statement 2 is incorrect: The Australia Group consists of 42 members (including the USA, European countries, Australia, and Japan). It does not primarily comprise Asian, African, or North American nations. The Wassenaar Arrangement con- sists of 42 members, mainly from Europe, North America, and some Asian countries (including India, Japan, and South Ko- rea). However, it is not exclusive to European and American continents. 87","PW-2273":"Statement 1 is correct : The CDS serves as the Perma- nent Chairman of the Chiefs of Staff Committee (CoSC), en- suring coordination and integration among the Army, Navy, and Air Force. This role is a key responsibility of the CDS. Statement 2 is incorrect : The CDS does not have direct mil- itary command over the three service chiefs (Chief of Army Staff, Chief of Naval Staff, and Chief of Air Staff). Each Service Chief retains operational command over their respective force. Instead, the CDS acts as a coordinator and advisor to en- sure jointness and integration across the services. Statement 3 is correct : The CDS acts as the principal military advisor to the Defence Minister, specifically on tri-service (joint military) matters, while individual Service Chiefs advise on ser- vice-specific issues. This is one of the primary roles of the CDS. International Relations and Current Affairs 661 89","PW-2274":"In 1998, the Northern Command of the Indian Army launched Operation Sadbhavana to address the challenges posed by terrorism and assist in rebuilding the socio-eco- nomic fabric of Jammu & Kashmir and Ladakh. The Army acts as a facilitator for development projects, identified collabora- tively with the state administration and local communities, fo- cusing on village-level initiatives. This operation aims to uplift remote populations by improving infrastructure, education, healthcare, and community development. Through these ef- forts, Operation Sadbhavana seeks to foster goodwill, empow- er local communities, and promote their integration into the national mainstream. 90","PW-2275":"Correctly matched equivalent rank in the three ser- vices of Indian Defence force are given below: Army Airforce Navy 1. Brigadier Air Commodore Commodore 2. Major General Air Vice Marshal Rear Admiral 3. Major Squadron Leader Lieutenant Com- mander 4. Lieutenant Colonel Commander Wing Commander 91","PW-2276":"Subrahmanyam Jaishankar, India’s External Affairs Minister, is the author of the books “The India Way: Strat- egies for an Uncertain World” and “Why Bharat Matters”. “The India Way” (2020) explores India’s foreign policy in a rapidly changing global order, emphasizing strategic autonomy and diplomacy. “Why Bharat Matters” (2024) discusses India’s evolving global role, economic progress, and strategic challeng- es. 92","PW-2277":"","PW-2278":"Statement 1 is incorrect : The Pradhan Mantri Surak- shit Matritva Abhiyan (PMSMA) guarantees a minimum package of antenatal care (ANC) services only during pregnancy (second and third trimesters). However, it does not provide health care services for six months post-delivery. Statement 2 is correct : Under PMSMA, private sector doc- tors (specialists like gynecologists, radiologists, and physicians) can volunteer to provide free maternal health services at gov- ernment health facilities on the 9th of every month. This pub- lic-private partnership aims to improve access to quality mater- nal health services. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 662 94","PW-2279":"Statement 1 is incorrect : The correct age group for enrollment is 18 to 40 years, not 21 to 40 years. Statement 2 is correct : The contribution varies based on the age of the beneficiary at the time of joining the scheme. For ex- ample, an 18-year-old contributes ₹55 per month, while a 40-year-old contributes ₹200 per month. Statement 3 is correct : After attaining 60 years of age, the sub- scriber is entitled to a monthly pension of `3,000. Statement 4 is incorrect : Family pension is applicable only to the spouse (50% of the pension amount, i.e., `1,500 per month after the subscriber’s death). Unmarried daughters are not included in the family pension provision. 95","PW-2280":"Option 1 is correct: Donyi Polo Airport, Itanagar is the first greenfield airport in Arunachal Pradesh. The airport is suitable for all weather day operations. Option 2 is correct: Since 2019, nearly 6 Greenfield airports namely, Kalaburagi, Orvakal (Kurnool), Sindhudurg, Itanagar, Kushinagar and Mopa have been operationalised, out of which Kushinagar and Mopa airports are International airports. Option 3 is incorrect: Airport Authority of India has undertaken development/ expansion of airports in Port Blair (Andaman & Nicobar Islands), Vijayawada and Tirupati (Andhra Pradesh), Ita- nagar and Tezu (Arunachal Pradesh). Thus, Vijayawada airport is not a greenfield project. 96","PW-2281":"Greenwashing is a deceptive marketing practice where a company misleads consumers into believing that its products, policies, or practices are environmentally friendly, when in reality they are not. It is used to improve a company’s public image without making real sustainability efforts. Companies often use misleading labels, vague terms (like “natural” or “eco-friendly”), or exaggerated claims to appear environmentally responsible. Examples of Greenwashing:  A company claims its plastic packaging is “biodegradable” but fails to mention that it takes decades to break down.  Fast fashion brands marketing “sustainable” clothing lines while continuing environmentally harmful practices.  Oil and gas companies promote carbon offset programs while still expanding fossil fuel extraction. :  Bluewashing – When companies or organizations exagg- erate their social responsibility or commitment to sustainable practices without substantial action, often by associating with the United Nations.  Greenhushing – When companies deliberately underre- port or downplay their sustainability initiati","PW-2282":"Statement 1 is incorrect : Instead, the ranking was based on the percentage of points (PCT) earned from matches played. Due to COVID-19 disruptions, the ICC modified the rank- ing system in 2020, and PCT (Points Percentage System) be- came the deciding factor rather than just the number of wins. Statement 2 is incorrect : England won more matches than New Zealand in the WTC cycle (England won 11, New Zealand won 7). However, New Zealand had a higher PCT (70%) com- pared to England (61.4%), securing their place in the final. 98","PW-2283":"Statement 1 is incorrect: 21st February is recog- nized as International Mother Language Day by UNESCO, not UNICEF. It was proclaimed by UNESCO in 1999 and observed worldwide since 2000. The day commemorates the 1952 Ben- gali Language Movement in East Pakistan (now Bangladesh), where protesters were killed for demanding Bangla as an official language. Statement 2 is correct: In 1948, Dhirendranath Datta, a mem- ber from East Pakistan (now Bangladesh), raised the demand for Bangla to be recognized as one of the national languag- es of Pakistan in the Constituent Assembly of Pakistan. The West Pakistani leadership rejected the demand, leading to protests and eventually the Bengali Language Movement (Bha- sha Andolon). This movement later contributed to the libera- tion of Bangladesh in 1971. : United Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural Orga- nization The United Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural Orga- nization (UNESCO), established on 16 November 1945, is a specialized UN agency headquartered in Paris, France. With 194 member states and nearly 11 associate members, ","PW-2284":"Statement 1 is correct : The Industrial Employment (Standing Orders) Central (Amendment) Rules, 2018 intro- duced fixed-term employment, allowing companies to hire workers for a specific period based on written contracts. Em- ployers are not required to provide retrenchment benefits or notice periods for non-renewal of contracts, making it easier to terminate employment. Once the contract ends, the employer is not obliged to provide further employment. This effectively makes it easier for companies to let go of workers without facing legal hurdles. Statement 2 is correct : As per the amendment rules, tempo- rary workers, including those on fixed-term contracts, do not require a notice of termination if their contract expires nat- urally. The employer is not obligated to provide a prior notice period or severance pay unless stated in the contract. 101","PW-2285":"Denisovans were an extinct hominin species closely related to Neanderthals and modern humans. Denisovans are an extinct species of archaic humans who lived around 50,000 to 300,000 years ago. They were first identified from DNA ex- tracted from fossils found in the Denisova Cave in Siberia, Russia in 2010. They are closely related to Neanderthals and also interbred with early modern humans (Homo sapiens). Genetic studies show that traces of Denisovan DNA can still be found in present-day humans, especially in Melanesians, Aus- tralian Aboriginals, and some East Asian populations. 102","PW-2286":"","PW-2287":"","PW-2288":"","PW-2289":"Option (1) is incorrect: The Digital India plan does not focus on forming India’s own internet companies like China did. Instead, it is more about enhancing infrastructure and acces- sibility to digital services across India. Option (2) is incorrect: While data sovereignty is a key issue, the Digital India initiative does not specifically aim to encourage multinational corporations to build large data centers within In- dia’s boundaries. However, it does encourage data protection and localization policies. Option (3) is correct: Connecting villages to the Internet and bringing Wi-Fi to schools, public places, and tourist centers is a major goal of the Digital India plan. This includes provid- ing broadband connectivity to rural areas and ensuring access to government services through digital platforms. Option (c) is incorrect: because while option 3 is correct, op- tions 1 and 2 are not part of the Digital India goals. 107","PW-2290":"Statement 1 is incorrect: NIIF is not an organ of NITI Aayog. It is an independent investment fund set up by the Indi- an government under the Ministry of Finance. While NITI Aayog plays a role in policy-making, it is not directly involved in man- aging the NIIF. Statement 2 is incorrect: NIIF does not have a corpus of `4,00,000 crore. The fund was initially set up with a corpus of `40,000 crore. The target corpus has been planned to increase over time, but it currently stands much lower than `4,00,000 crore. 108","PW-2291":"","PW-2292":"","PW-2293":"Statement 1 is correct: DigiLocker is a flagship ini- tiative under the Indian government’s Digital India Pro- gramme. Launched with the aim of creating a paperless gov- ernance system, DigiLocker provides a platform for citizens to store and access their important documents in a digital format. It is managed by the Ministry of Electronics and Informa- tion Technology (MeitY). The platform facilitates secure sharing of e-documents with authorized entities, thereby reducing the need for physical document submission. Statement 2 is correct: A core feature of DigiLocker is its acces- sibility. Users can access their stored e-documents from any- where, provided they have an internet connection and their login credentials. This eliminates the constraints of physical location and makes document access convenient and efficient. Whether a user is at home, traveling, or in a government office, their documents are readily available through the DigiLocker platform. 114","PW-2294":"Statement 1 is correct: The Atal Pension Yojana (APY) is a government-backed pension scheme specifically designed to provide a minimum guaranteed monthly pension to workers in the unorganized sector. This sector, which comprises a signifi- cant portion of the Indian workforce, often lacks access to formal retirement savings plans. The APY aims to address this gap by offering a simple and accessible pension product. The focus on unorganized sector workers is a core element of the APY’s design and purpose. Statement 2 is incorrect: The APY does not restrict participa- tion to only one member per family. Any individual who meets the eligibility criteria, primarily being an Indian citizen between the ages of 18 and 40 and not already a beneficiary of other statutory social security schemes, can subscribe to the APY, re- gardless of whether other family members have enrolled. Multi- ple family members can contribute to the scheme and receive separate pension benefits upon reaching the age of 60. Statement 3 is correct: A key feature of the Atal Pension Yojana is the provision for family p","PW-2295":"SWAYAM is a Government of India initiative offering free online courses to promote accessible and quality educa- tion for all. Courses & Accessibility: The platform provides MOOCs across disciplines like engineering, humanities, and management, featuring content from premier Indian institutions. It ensures inclusivity, catering to learners from diverse socioeconomic backgrounds and regions with limited internet access. Course Structure & Certification: Courses include video lec- tures, reading materials, assignments, and discussion fo- rums. SWAYAM follows a blended learning model and offers credit transfers and certificates to aid career and academic growth. National Coordination: Managed by the Ministry of Educa- tion, SWAYAM collaborates with universities and research in- stitutions to democratize education nationwide. 116","PW-2296":"The National Investment and Manufacturing Zone (NIMZ) in Prakasam district, Andhra Pradesh, holds the dis- tinction of being the first NIMZ in India to receive final ap- proval and progress towards implementation. This milestone marked a significant step in the Indian government’s efforts to promote manufacturing and attract investment. The NIMZ in Andhra Pradesh was granted final approval in October 2015, set- ting a precedent for other states pursuing similar zones. The primary objective of the Prakasam NIMZ is to attract both domestic and foreign investment in manufacturing industries. The zone aims to create a conducive ecosystem for businesses by providing them with access to essential resources, simplifying regulatory procedures, and offering fiscal incentives. The focus is on promoting sustainable and inclusive industrial development, generating employment opportunities, and boost- ing economic growth in the region. The NIMZ is expected to con- tribute significantly to the “Make in India” initiative and enhance the competitiveness of Indian manufacturing on a global scale. 117","PW-2297":"BEPS refers to tax strategies used by multinational en- terprises (MNEs) to shift profits from high-tax to low-tax ju- risdictions, exploiting gaps in international tax laws. This results in significant revenue losses for governments and an unfair competitive advantage for tax-avoiding corporations. Mechanisms: MNEs achieve BEPS through manipulating trans- fer pricing, shifting intangible assets, and using tax havens. For instance, a company may attribute profits to subsidiaries in tax havens despite economic activity occurring elsewhere. Impact: BEPS leads to government revenue loss, weakened public services, business inequality, and reduced trust in tax systems. International Efforts: The OECD and G20 launched the BEPS Project, introducing measures to close tax loopholes, prevent treaty abuse, and enhance transparency. BEPS Action Plan: The OECD/G20 15-Point Action Plan ad- dresses key issues like transfer pricing, tax treaty abuse, and digital economy taxation. Many nations are integrating these recommendations to ensure fair taxation of multinational cor- porations. 118","PW-2298":"Greased Lightning-10 (GL-10) is an experimental electric aircraft developed and tested by NASA. It’s notable for its unique design and capabilities. Its most distinctive feature is its unique design, which incorpo- rates ten electric motors distributed along its wings and tail. This distributed propulsion system enables the GL-10 to perform both vertical takeoff and landing (VTOL) and efficient hori- zontal flight. The aircraft’s ability to transition between these two modes of flight makes it highly versatile and potentially suit- able for a variety of applications. The GL-10’s unique combination of VTOL capabilities and efficient horizontal flight makes it potentially useful for a variety of applications. These could include cargo delivery, aerial surveillance, search and rescue operations, and even personal air transportation. The aircraft’s ability to operate without runways also opens up possibilities for its use in remote areas or disaster relief efforts. While the GL-10 is still an ex- perimental aircraft, it represents an important step in the de- velopment of electric VTOL t","PW-2299":"INS Astradharini, commissioned on October 6, 2015, is an in- digenously designed torpedo launch and recovery vessel of the Indian Navy. It supports underwater weapon research by conducting technical trials for torpedoes and underwater sys- tems.  Features a catamaran hull for stability and maneuverability in rough seas.  50m long, speeds up to 15 knots, with advanced navigation and communication systems.  Replaced INS Astravahini, serving under the Eastern Naval Command in Visakhapatnam.  Operated by 2 officers, 27 sailors, and can accommodate 13 DRDO scientists for trials. Its role is critical in testing, evaluating, and refining India’s na- val weaponry. 120","PW-2300":"Musa indandamanensis, a newly discovered banana species, was found in the tropical rainforests of Little Anda- man Island by the Botanical Survey of India (BSI).  Grows up to 11 meters, much taller than cultivated varieties.  Distinct orange color of pulp, suggesting unique pigments and possible nutritional differences.  Exceptionally long inflorescence over 4 meters.  Endemic to the Andaman Islands, making it vulnerable to habitat loss. The discovery highlights the need for conservation efforts to protect this unique species and the region’s biodiversity. 121","PW-2301":"Net metering allows consumers with renewable energy sys- tems (like rooftop solar) to connect to the utility grid, send excess electricity back, and receive credit to offset future con- sumption, reducing electricity bills.  Uses a net meter to track both electricity consumed and fed into the grid.  Consumers may receive bill credits or payments for surplus energy, depending on regulations.  Encourages renewable energy adoption, reduces reliance on centralized power, and promotes sustainability.  Challenges include metering infrastructure, fair billing mechanisms, and grid integration, requiring coordinated efforts for effective implementation. 122","PW-2302":"Project Loon, launched by Google in 2013 and later an Alphabet subsidiary, aimed to provide internet access to remote areas using high-altitude balloons. These helium-filled balloons operated at 20 km (12 mi) in the stratosphere, relaying signals via a solar-powered mesh network. Google used wind-da- ta algorithms to navigate them for consistent coverage. Despite successful deployments, including disaster relief in Puerto Rico (2017) and Kenya (2020), Alphabet shut down Project Loon in January 2021 due to high costs and scalability challenges. Its in- novations contributed to advancements in stratospheric balloon technology and wireless communication. 123","PW-2303":" Mission Indradhanush, launched by the Ministry of Health and Family Welfare, Government of India, on December 25, 2014, aims to increase full immunization coverage for children under two years and pregnant women. It targets vaccine-preventable diseases like diphtheria, pertussis, tetanus, polio, tuberculosis, measles, and hepatitis B. The program uses micro-planning to identify low-coverage areas and conducts special immunization drives.  Intensified Mission Indradhanush (IMI) was introduced in 2017 to accelerate coverage. The initiative has significantly improved immunization rates, contributing to reduced child mortality and better public health outcomes in India. 124","PW-2304":"Statement 1 is correct : Its purpose is to promote entrepreneurship among SC/ST and women entrepreneurs. A scheme by the Ministry of Finance launched on 5 April 2016 to support entrepreneurship among women and SC & ST com- munities by facilitating loans ranging from ₹10 lakh to ₹1 crore for at least one SC/ST borrower and one woman borrower per bank branch. For non-individual enterprises, a minimum 51% shareholding and controlling stake must be held by an SC/ST or woman entrepreneur. Statement 2 is correct : It provides for refinancing through SIDBI. The Stand-Up India scheme leverages the Small Industries De- velopment Bank of India (SIDBI) as a key mechanism for refi- nancing loans provided under the scheme. SIDBI plays a crucial role in providing refinance support to lending institutions, such as banks, that offer loans to eligible SC/ST and women entrepre- neurs. This refinancing arrangement helps to ensure that lending institutions have access to adequate funds to support entrepre- neurs under the Stand-Up India scheme. SIDBI’s involvement is essential for the scheme’s financial","PW-2305":"Statement 1 is incorrect: The Pradhan Mantri Fasal Bima Yojana (PMFBY) does not stipulate a uniform premium of two percent for all crops and seasons. The premium rates under the PMFBY are calculated based on the risk associated with each specific crop and region. Factors considered include the type of crop, the season in which it is grown, the historical yield data for the area, and the probability of various natural calamities. There- fore, farmers pay varying premium rates depending on these fac- tors, and the two percent figure is not a universal premium. The premium subsidy is shared between the Central and State gov- ernments. As per provisions of PMFBY guidelines, the premium share of the farmer is capped at 2% for Kharif crops, 1.5% for Rabi Crops and 5% for commercial/Horticultural crops Statement 2 is correct: The PMFBY provides comprehensive coverage against crop losses, including losses incurred during the post-harvest period. Specifically, it covers losses arising from specific perils such as cyclones, unseasonal rains, hailstorms, and other natural calamities. This cover","PW-2306":"Pair 1 is incorrect: The Kurdish people are a distinct ethnic group primarily inhabiting a region spanning parts of Turkey, Iran, Iraq, and Syria and not Bangladesh. They are the largest stateless nation in the world. While there are Kurdish diaspora communities in various countries, their historical and primary presence is not associated with Bangladesh. The Kurd- ish population has faced various challenges, including political persecution and struggles for autonomy, primarily within the aforementioned countries in the Middle East. Pair 2 is correct: Madhesi : Nepal The Madhesi people are an ethnic group residing predominantly in the southern plains of Nepal, also known as the Terai region. They have distinct cul- tural and linguistic identities, and their presence is a significant demographic factor in Nepal. The Madhesi community has of- ten played a crucial role in Nepali politics and has advocated for greater representation and rights. Their concerns have included issues related to citizenship, language, and representation in gov- ernment. International Relations and Current Aff","PW-2307":"The Rashtriya Garima Abhiyan launched in 2001 by the Ministry of Social Justice and Empowerment. It is a na- tional campaign to eradicate manual scavenging in India, a de- humanizing practice historically imposed on marginalized Dalit communities. Recognizing it as a human rights violation, the campaign mobilizes government agencies, NGOs, and civil so- ciety to raise awareness, enforce laws, and support affected indi- viduals in transitioning to alternative livelihoods. Through advo- cacy and grassroots action, it aims for a complete elimination of manual scavenging, ensuring dignity and social justice. 128","PW-2308":"Special Drawing Right (SDR) The SDR is an interna- tional reserve asset used by the IMF and other organizations as a unit of account. It is not a currency, but its value is based on a basket of five currencies—the US dollar, Euro, Chinese renminbi (added in 2016), Japanese yen, and British pound sterling. Key Features  SDR value is calculated daily based on market exchange rates.  The IMF reviews and adjusts the SDR basket every five years.  IMF quotas (member contributions) and voting power are denominated in SDRs.  SDR allocations to members are proportional to their IMF quotas.  India’s SDR Quota in IMF  2016 reforms increased India’s voting share from 2.3% to 2.6%, while China’s rose from 3.8% to 6%.  Currently, India holds 2.75% of the SDR quota and 2.63% of IMF votes.  India’s foreign exchange reserves include SDRs, gold reserves, foreign currency assets, and IMF’s Reserve Tranche. 129","PW-2309":"Statement 1 is correct: The International Finance Corporation (IFC) is a member of the World Bank Group, fo- cusing specifically on private sector development in developing countries. It acts as a sister organization to the International Bank for Reconstruction and Development (IBRD), but with a distinct mandate to promote private enterprise. Statement 2 is correct: “Masala bonds” are rupee-denomi- nated bonds issued by international entities, such as the IFC, in offshore markets. The proceeds from these bonds are typically used to finance projects in India, and the principal and interest payments are made in Indian rupees. This means that investors bear the currency risk, as the value of the rupee can fluc- tuate relative to other currencies. Masala bonds serve as a source of debt financing for both public and private sector entities in India, allowing them to raise capital for infrastructure projects, business expansion, and other development initiatives. The rupee denomination of these bonds makes them attractive to international investors seeking exposure to the Indian market whi","PW-2310":"IndARC is India’s underwater observatory in the Arctic, established for long-term climate and oceanograph- ic research. It monitors water temperature, salinity, ocean currents, and marine life, providing crucial data on climate change and Arctic ecosystems. Despite its geographic distance, India recognizes the Arctic’s global climate impact and its rele- vance to the Indian subcontinent. IndARC underscores India’s commitment to Arctic research, aiding climate predictions, policy decisions, and global scientific collaboration. 131","PW-2311":"Following approval by the Union Cabinet on February 20, 2014, the Odia (Odia) language became the country’s sixth classical language. Odia (Oriya) is an Indo-Aryan language primarily spoken in Odi- sha and one of six classical languages of India, recognized for its rich literary and cultural heritage. Its history dates back to the an- cient Kalinga kingdom, with inscriptions from the 10th century and a literary tradition spanning over a thousand years. Sarala Dasa, a medieval poet, is renowned for his Odia Mahabharata, a landmark literary work. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 670 : In 2024, Marathi, Assamese, Bengali, Pali and Prakrit were also given status of classical language by Cabinet on recom- mendation of the Language Expert Committee constituted by the Ministry of Culture and Sahitya Academy. Criteria for Classical Language Status in India  Recorded history of over 1,000 years.  Substantial body of ancient literature.  Independent literary tradition, not derived from any other language.  Distinct vocabulary, though it may have borrowings or influences from other languages. 132","PW-2312":"Statement 1 is correct : Brent crude is a major classifi- cation of oil and a key global benchmark for crude oil pricing, widely traded and followed for its significant market influence. Its importance comes from its quality, availability, and location, making it easily transportable to European refineries. Statement 2 is correct : Brent crude is primarily sourced from the North Sea, specifically the Brent oil field. This region is a major oil producer, and its origin influences the characteristics and market value of Brent crude. While the specific blend of crude oils that make up Brent crude may vary slightly over time, its North Sea origin remains a defining characteristic. Statement 3 is incorrect : While considered “sweet crude” for its relatively low sulfur content, Brent crude still contains some sulfur. “Sweet” indicates less sulfur compared to “sour” crudes, making it more desirable due to lower refining costs. Sulfur content is an important factor in crude oil pricing because higher sulfur content generally requires more complex and expensive refining processes to meet envi","PW-2313":"The Mahatma Gandhi National Rural Employment Guar- antee Act (MGNREGA) legally guarantees that adult members of all rural households can apply for work, ensuring inclusivi- ty without discrimination based on caste, creed, gender, or so- cio-economic status. Despite the broad eligibility, MGNREGA often prioritizes Below Poverty Line (BPL) households in practice, reflecting its primary goal of poverty alleviation and providing livelihood security to the most vulnerable rural communities. MGNREGA recognises the right to work as a fundamental en- titlement for all rural residents, aimed at improving livelihoods and empowering communities, even if implementation targets certain groups for effectiveness. 3. MISCELLANEOUS 135","PW-2314":"Statement 1 is correct: The 44th Chess Olympiad is being held in Chennai from July 28 to August 9, 2022. The presti- gious competition, organised since 1927, is being hosted in India for the first time and in Asia after 30 years. Statement 2 is correct: The 44th Chess Olympiad has unveiled the official logo and mascot for the event. The Mascot is a chess knight called Thambi. Statement 3 is incorrect:: Vera Menchik Cup is for 1st place in the Women’s section. Statement 4 is incorrect: Hamilton- Russell Cup is given to the winning team in the open section. :  The 45th edition of the Chess Olympiad will take place in Hungary from September 10 to 23.  This will be the first time since 1926 that the world’s biggest multi-national chess tournament returns to Budapest.  In the 45th edition, this was the first Chess Olympiad in which teams of refugees participated due to efforts made through FIDE’s initiative for refugees “Chess for Protection”.  India won Gold Medal in Open category, Women category, Open Individual (Gukesh Dommaraju).  Team India also won Gaprindashvili Trophy. 136","PW-2315":"The Janani Suraksha Yojana, a centrally sponsored scheme, was introduced in April 2005 by modifying the Nation- al Maternity Benefit Scheme (NMBS), which itself was estab- lished in August 1995 as a component within the National Social Assistance Programme (NSAP). Under the scheme, qualifying pregnant women are eligible to receive cash assistance regardless of the mother’s age or the number of children she has, as long as she gives birth in a gov- ernment or accredited private health facility. The scheme is currently being executed across all states and Union Territo- ries (UTs), with particular emphasis placed on Low Performing States (LPS). Statement 1 is incorrect : Janani Suraksha Yojana (JSY) is a safe motherhood intervention under the National Rural Health Mission (NRHM). It is not an initiative of State Health Depart- ments. Statement 2 is correct: The objective of the Janani Suraksha Yo- jana (JSY) is to reduce maternal and neonatal mortality among poor pregnant women. Statement 3 is correct: The Janani Suraksha Yojana (JSY) en- courages pregnant women, particularly those wit","PW-2316":"Statement 1 is correct: ‘Major Dhyan Chand Khel Ratna Award’ the highest sporting honour in India, is presented annually by the Ministry of Youth Affairs and Sports, Govern- ment of India. It is given for the spectacular and most outstand- ing performance in the field of sports by a sportsperson over a period of the previous four years. Statement 2 is incorrect: The Arjuna Awards holds the distinc- tion of being India’s second- highest sporting recognition. Recipi- ents are chosen by a committee appointed by the Ministry based on their commendable performance over a span of four years, coupled with demonstrated qualities of leadership, sportsman- ship, and discipline. Statement 3 is correct: The Dronacharya Award represents a prestigious coaching accolade within the Republic of India. Recipients are carefully chosen by a committee appointed by the Ministry of Youth and Sports Affairs, who have helped athletes achieve excellence over a period of four years. Statement 4 is incorrect: ‘Rashtriya Khel Protsahan Purus- kar’ is given to corporate entities (both in the private and pub- lic ","PW-2317":"Statement 1 is incorrect: Under the Anaemia Mukt Bharat Strategy, the key intervention is to provide prophylactic iron and folic acid supplementation for preschool children, ad- olescents and pregnant women. Statement 2 is correct: The Anaemia Mukt Bharat Strategy runs a campaign for delayed cord clamping (by at least 3 minutes or until cord pulsations cease) at the time of childbirth. Statement 3 is correct: The Anaemia Mukt Bharat Strategy provides a bi-annual mass deworming for children and ado- lescents in the age group between 1-19 years and of women of reproductive age and pregnant women as part of the National Deworming Day programme. Statement 4 is correct: The strategy attempts to intensify awareness and integrate screening and treatment for follow- ing non-nutritional causes of anaemia with a special focus on malaria, haemoglobinopathies and fluorosis. : The Anaemia Mukt Bharat - intensified Iron-plus Initiative aims to enhance current approaches and develop innovative strategies to address anaemia effectively. It targets six bene- ficiary groups, implements six interventio","PW-2318":"Statement 1 is incorrect: The largest solar park in India is Bhadla Solar Park, located in Rajasthan, not Gujarat. Spread over 14,000 acres, it has a capacity of 2,245 MW and is among the largest in the world. Statement 2 is correct: Cochin International Airport in Ker- ala is the world’s first fully solar-powered international airport. It was inaugurated as a completely solar-run airport in 2015 and won the UN Champions of the Earth award in 2018 for its sustainable model. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 672 Statement 3 is incorrect: Goa does not have the largest floating solar photovoltaic (PV) project. The largest floating solar PV project in India is located in Ramagundam, Telangana, with a 100 MW capacity, developed by NTPC. 140","PW-2319":"Statement 1 is correct: The Tea Board of India is a statutory body established under the Tea Act, 1953. It is re- sponsible for the promotion, research, regulation, and trade facilitation of the tea industry. Statement 2 is incorrect: The Tea Board functions under the Ministry of Commerce and Industry, not the Ministry of Agri- culture and Farmers Welfare. Statement 3 is incorrect: The headquarters of the Tea Board of India is in Kolkata, not Bengaluru. Kolkata has been the tradi- tional center of India’s tea trade. Statement 4 is correct: The Tea Board has overseas offices in Dubai and Moscow, which help facilitate tea exports, conduct quality inspections, and enhance international market reach. 141","PW-2320":"Statement 1 is incorrect: The India Sanitation Coali- tion (ISC) is an independent platform led by FICCI, aimed at promoting sanitation, but it is not funded directly by the Govern- ment of India or WHO. Statement 2 is correct: The National Institute of Urban Af- fairs (NIUA) is an autonomous research body under the Minis- try of Housing and Urban Affairs (MoHUA). It provides policy recommendations, urban research, and capacity building for cit- ies across India. 143","PW-2321":"Statement 1 is correct: The CCO is the primary source of coal statistics in India, collecting data on production, stock, and dispatch. Statement 2 is correct: It monitors captive coal and lignite blocks, ensuring efficient allocation and compliance. Statement 3 is correct: The CCO hears objections regarding coal-bearing land acquisition, as per the Coal Bearing Areas (Acquisition and Development) Act, 1957. Statement 4 is incorrect: The CCO does not oversee direct coal delivery; this function is handled by Coal India Limited (CIL) and private coal producers. Coal is India’s primary energy source, contributing to over 55% of electricity generation. The Coal Controller’s Organization (CCO) plays a pivotal role in coal regulation, monitoring, and pol- icy implementation. 144","PW-2322":"The Labour Bureau, part of the Ministry of Labour & Employment, is tasked with compiling and analyzing data on industrial disputes, closures, retrenchments, and layoffs in facto- ries with workers. It releases the Industrial Disputes Statistics Report and other labour market indicators, which are essen- tial for informing labour policy decisions in India. These data play a vital role in shaping policies, particularly in monitoring in- dustrial conflicts, workforce reductions, and factory shutdowns. Other options are incorrect: The Central Statistics Office (CSO) focuses on macroeconomic data, not industrial disputes. The Department for Promotion of Industry and Internal Trade (DPIIT) handles investment and trade policies, not labour issues. National Technical Information System Manpower does not compile labour statistics. International Relations and Current Affairs 673 145","PW-2323":"Statement 1 is correct: Polyethylene Terephthalate (PET) is a widely used thermoplastic polymer known for its strength, recyclability, and versatility in textiles and packag- ing. PET fibres can be blended with wool and cotton to enhance their durability, wrinkle resistance, and strength. It is commonly used in textile manufacturing for blended fabrics. Statement 2 is incorrect: PET containers are not suitable for all alcoholic beverages due to permeability issues and risk of chemical interaction with high-alcohol-content liquids. Statement 3 is correct: PET bottles are 100% recyclable and can be converted into fibres, packaging materials, and other plas- tic products. Statement 4 is incorrect: Incineration of PET releases carbon dioxide (CO₂) and other greenhouse gases, contributing to en- vironmental pollution. 146","PW-2324":"Open-source digital platforms enable transparen- cy, scalability, and accessibility in India’s e-governance ini- tiatives. Aarogya Setu (contact tracing for COVID-19) was later open-sourced to enhance security and transparency. CoWIN (COVID-19 vaccination platform) was built using an open-source framework to facilitate large-scale vaccination tracking. DigiLocker (cloud-based document storage) oper- ates on an open-source framework, allowing citizens to access digital documents securely. DIKSHA (Digital Infrastructure for Knowledge Sharing) is an open-source platform for education and teacher training. 147","PW-2325":"Statement 1 is incorrect: The Ayushman Bharat Dig- ital Mission (ABDM) is a flagship program for creating a uni- fied digital health infrastructure in India. While hospitals are encouraged to adopt it, there is no mandatory requirement for private hospitals to join ABDM. Statement 2 is incorrect: ABDM aims to improve accessibility to digital health services, but it is not mandatory for all citizens. Statement 3 is correct: ABDM offers seamless portability across India, enabling citizens to access health records digitally, irrespective of location. 148","PW-2326":"Statement 1 is incorrect: The 32nd Summer Olym- pics, originally scheduled for 2020 but held in 2021 due to the COVID-19 pandemic, was one of the most unprecedented edi- tions in Olympic history. The official motto for Tokyo 2020 was “United by Emotion,” a departure from the 2016 Rio Olympics’ motto, “A New World.” Statement 2 is correct: The Tokyo Olympics saw the addition of five new sports, Sport Climbing, Surfing, Skateboarding, Karate, and Baseball/Softball (which returned after being re- moved in 2008). These sports were included to enhance youth engagement and bring more diversity to the Games. 149","PW-2327":"Statement 1 is correct: The Laureus World Sports Award, also known as the ‘Oscar of Sports’, recognizes excep- tional performances in global sports annually. Tiger Woods was the first-ever winner of the Laureus World Sportsman of the Year Award in 2000, following his dominance in golf. Statement 2 is incorrect: Formula One drivers have received the award, but it has not been mostly won by them. Instead, tennis, golf, and athletics players have been frequent recipients. Statement 3 is correct: Roger Federer holds the record for the most wins (5 times: 2005, 2006, 2007, 2008, 2018) in the Laureus World Sportsman of the Year category. 150","PW-2328":"Statement 1 is incorrect: The Bharat Ratna and Padma Awards are among India’s highest civilian honors, conferred by the President of India. As per Article 18(1) of the Constitution, the State shall not confer titles except military and academic distinctions. However, Bharat Ratna and Padma Awards are not considered “titles” and have been upheld by the Supreme Court. Statement 2 is incorrect: The Padma Awards, instituted in 1954, were suspended twice, in 1977 and 1993 due to policy reviews. Statement 3 is incorrect: The maximum number of Bharat Rat- na awards per year is limited to three, not five. However, in 2024, this honour was bestowed upon five distinguished personalities namely, Karpoori Thakur, L. K. Advani, P. V. Nara- simha Rao, Charan Singh, and M. S. Swaminathan. 151","PW-2329":"Public Key Infrastructure (PKI) is a cryptographic framework that ensures secure electronic transactions, au- thentication, and digital signatures. It involves the use of pub- lic and private keys, digital certificates, and certificate authorities to enable safe communication online. PKI plays a crucial role in areas such as e-governance, online banking, Aadhaar authen- tication, and cybersecurity. In India, the Controller of Certi- fying Authorities (CCA) oversees digital signature certificates (DSCs) and encryption technologies under the Information Technology Act, 2000, making PKI integral to the country’s dig- ital security infrastructure. 152","PW-2330":"Statement 1 is incorrect: The Petroleum and Natu- ral Gas Regulatory Board (PNGRB) was established in 2006 to regulate natural gas and petroleum products. It is not the first regulatory body in India. The Telecom Regulatory Authority of India (TRAI) (1997) and Securities and Exchange Board of India (SEBI) (1992) were established earlier. Statement 2 is correct: PNGRB ensures competitive gas mar- kets, tariff regulation, and fair trade practices in natural gas distribution. Statement 3 is correct: Appeals against PNGRB’s decisions are heard by the Appellate Tribunal for Electricity (APTEL), which also deals with power sector disputes. 153","PW-2331":"India’s forest cover varies significantly across states, with east- ern and central states having higher coverage. According to the India State of Forest Report (ISFR), 2019, the correct ascend- ing order based on percentage of forest cover to the total area is: Maharashtra (16.47%) Madhya Pradesh (25.11%) Odisha (32.98%) Chhattisgarh (41.09%) Thus, the correct order is Maharashtra → Madhya Pradesh → Odisha → Chhattisgarh (3-2-4-1). 154","PW-2332":"Statement 1 is incorrect: NPOP is implemented under the Ministry of Commerce and Industry, not the Ministry of Rural Development. It sets standards for organic production and certification. Statement 2 is correct: APEDA (Agricultural and Processed Food Products Export Development Authority), under the Ministry of Commerce and Industry, serves as the Secretariat for NPOP, ensuring certification and export facilitation of organic products. Statement 3 is correct: Sikkim became India’s first fully or- ganic state in 2016, implementing strict policies to eliminate chemical fertilizers and pesticides, covering 75,000 hectares of farmland under organic farming. 155","PW-2333":"Air India was nationalized in 1953 under the Air Cor- porations Act, 1953. Imperial Bank of India was renamed as the State Bank of India (SBI) in 1955 as part of banking sector reforms. India’s first democratically elected communist government was formed in Kerala in 1957, with E.M.S. Namboodiripad as Chief Minister. Goa was annexed by India and became part of independent India in 1961 after “Operation Vijay”. Therefore, the correct chronological sequence is 3-2-1-4. Thus, the correct chronological order is 1953 (Air India Nation- alization) → 1955 (SBI Renaming) → 1957 (First Commu- nist Government) → 1961 (Goa’s Liberation). International Relations and Current Affairs 675 156","PW-2334":"Statement 1 is incorrect: The Pradhan Mantri Kaushal Vikas Yojana (PMKVY) is a flagship skill development pro- gram aimed at enhancing employability among youth. It is imple- mented by the Ministry of Skill Development and Entrepre- neurship (MSDE), not the Ministry of Labour and Employment. Statement 2 is correct: The scheme imparts training in soft skills, entrepreneurship, financial and digital literacy, im- proving employment readiness. Statement 3 is correct: It aligns competencies of informal sector workers with the National Skills Qualification Framework (NSQF) to standardize skill assessment. 157","PW-2335":"Statement 1 is incorrect: India does not rank third in silicon wafer manufacturing. The top three manufacturers are China, Taiwan, and South Korea. India still imports most of its solar photovoltaic (PV) wafers. Statement 2 is incorrect: Solar tariffs in India are not deter- mined by the Solar Energy Corporation of India (SECI), but by the Central Electricity Regulatory Commission (CERC) and state electricity regulatory commissions (SERCs) through compet- itive bidding. 158","PW-2336":"Statement 1 is incorrect:The National Food Security Act (NFSA), 2013 aims to provide food and nutritional secu- rity to the population through subsidized food grains. The NFSA covers up to 75% of the rural population and 50% of the urban population, not just BPL families. It includes Priority House- holds and Antyodaya Anna Yojana (AAY) beneficiaries. Statement 2 is correct: As per Section 13 of the NFSA, the el- dest woman (18 years or above) is mandated to be the head of the household for the purpose of ration card issuance. Statement 3 is incorrect: Pregnant women and lactating mothers receive free meals under the Integrated Child Devel- opment Services (ICDS) scheme, but no fixed calorie intake of 1600 kcal per day is prescribed in the NFSA. 159","PW-2337":"Statement 1 is correct: Aadhaar APIs can be integrat- ed into multiple electronic devices such as biometric scanners, mobile phones, and ATMs to enable identity verification and dig- ital transactions. Statement 2 is correct: Aadhaar authentication supports iris- based verification, which is more secure and accurate than fin- gerprint-based authentication, especially for elderly individuals and those engaged in manual labor. The Aadhaar identity platform enables seamless authentica- tion and integration with various applications through open Ap- plication Programming Interfaces (APIs), facilitating secure digital identity verification. 160","PW-2338":"Statement 1 is incorrect: Aadhaar is a 12-digit unique identification number issued by UIDAI to Indian residents based on biometric and demographic data. However, it does not serve as proof of citizenship or domicile, as it is issued to all residents, including foreign nationals residing in India. Statement 2 is incorrect: Aadhaar numbers can be deactivated or omitted by UIDAI in cases of fraud, duplication, or non-use for an extended period, as per Section 23 of the Aadhaar Act, 2016. 161","PW-2339":"The NSSO 70th Round (2012-13) “Situation Assess- ment Survey of Agricultural Households” provides crucial data on the socio-economic conditions of Indian farmers. Statement 1 is correct: Rajasthan had the highest percent- age of agricultural households (78.4 percent) among its rural households followed by Uttar Pradesh (74.8 percent) and Mad- hya Pradesh (70.8 percent). UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 676 Statement 2 is incorrect: As per the survey, about 45 percent out of the total agricultural households in the country belonged to Other Backward Classes (OBC). About 16% of agricultural households were from Scheduled Castes (SC) and 13 percent were from Scheduled Tribes (ST). Statement 3 is correct: In Kerala, over 60% of agricultural households derive their main income from non-agricultur- al sources such as services, remittances, and trade due to the state’s economic structure. 162","PW-2340":"Unnat Bharat Abhiyan (UBA) is a flagship initiative launched by the Ministry of Education (MoE) to bridge the gap between higher educational institutions and rural India by addressing developmental challenges through technolo- gy-driven solutions. It aims to leverage knowledge from pre- mier educational institutions like IITs, NITs, and universities to enhance rural development and focuses on sustainable devel- opment, water management, energy, and organic farming. The Indian Institute of Technology (IIT) Delhi is the nodal agency for implementing the program. 163","PW-2341":"The Vidyanjali Yojana was launched by the Ministry of Education (formerly MHRD) in 2016 as an initiative to enhance the quality of education in government schools through com- munity and private-sector participation. Statement 1 is incorrect: The scheme does not allow foreign universities to set up campuses in India. It is focused on im- proving public education at the school level through volunteer participation rather than international collaborations. Statement 2 is correct: The scheme seeks to give quality ed- ucation in government schools by engaging volunteers from various fields, including retired professionals, working profes- sionals, and college students, to contribute their knowledge and skills to students through non-teaching activities such as reading, mentoring, and extracurricular programs. Statement 3 is incorrect: While Vidyanjali 2.0, launched in 2021, allows for voluntary donation of resources, the origi- nal Vidyanjali Yojana did not focus on monetary contributions or infrastructure development. The primary goal was community engagement rather than financial donat","PW-2342":"The Soil Health Card (SHC) Scheme, launched in 2015 by the Ministry of Agriculture & Farmers Welfare, aims to provide farmers with soil health assessments to ensure opti- mal fertilizer usage and sustainable farming practices. Statement 1 is incorrect: The scheme does not focus on expand- ing the cultivable area under irrigation. Instead, it aims to en- hance soil fertility and productivity through soil analysis. Statement 2 is incorrect: The scheme does not facilitate bank loan assessments for farmers. It primarily provides information on soil health to guide proper fertilizer use. Statement 3 is correct: A key objective of the scheme is to check the overuse of fertilizers and promote balanced nutrient man- agement to improve crop productivity and reduce soil degra- dation. 165","PW-2343":"Statement 1 is incorrect: NSQF allows certification through multiple pathways, including formal, non-formal, and informal learning, ensuring recognition of prior learning (RPL) for workers who acquire skills outside formal institutions. Statement 2 is correct: One of the key goals of NSQF is to ensure mobility between vocational and general education, allowing students and workers to shift between academic and skill-based careers seamlessly. : The National Skills Qualification Framework (NSQF) is a competency-based framework introduced in 2013 by the Min- istry of Skill Development & Entrepreneurship (MSDE) to standardize skill development, vocational education, and aca- demic learning in India. 166","PW-2344":"Statement 1 is correct: The Bureau of Indian Stan- dards (BIS) mandates certification for automotive tyres and tubes to ensure road safety and product quality. The BIS Stan- dard Mark indicates compliance with ISI standards. Statement 2 is incorrect: AGMARK is a certification issued by the Directorate of Marketing & Inspection (DMI), Ministry of Agriculture & Farmers Welfare, Government of India, and not by FAO. It ensures the quality of agricultural products like grains, pulses, and edible oils. 167","PW-2345":"Statement 1 is correct: A key goal is raising aware- ness about malnutrition, particularly for vulnerable groups like pregnant women and lactating mothers. Statement 2 is correct: The mission aims to reduce anemia prevalence among children, adolescent girls, and women through dietary diversification and micronutrient supplementa- tion. Statement 3 is correct: The program promotes nutrient-rich foods, including millets and unpolished rice, to enhance di- etary diversity. Statement 4 is incorrect: While eggs are recommended as a pro- tein source, the mission does not specifically promote poultry eggs. 168","PW-2346":"‘The Man Who Knew Infinity’ (2015) is a biograph- ical film on Srinivasa Ramanujan, an Indian mathematical genius known for his extraordinary contributions to number theory, infinite series, and mathematical analysis. Ramanujan, largely self-taught, made groundbreaking contributions and col- laborated with British mathematician G. H. Hardy at Cambridge University. His work laid the foundation for modern research in mathe- matical physics, cryptography, and computer science. His fa- mous “Ramanujan Prime” and “Ramanujan Theta Function” remain fundamental in mathematical studies today. 169","PW-2347":"The Bureau of Energy Efficiency (BEE) Star Labeling Program is a government initiative that promotes energy effi- ciency by rating appliances based on their power consumption. Ceiling fans, electric geysers, and tubular fluorescent lamps all come under the BEE Star Labeling scheme as they are com- mon energy-consuming appliances. The labeling program helps consumers make informed choices by indicating the energy ef- ficiency of electrical appliances. The program has been extended to refrigerators, air condition- ers, televisions, and many other household electrical prod- ucts. 170","PW-2348":"Introduced by the Government of India in 2015, the Neem-coated Urea policy aims to improve nitrogen use ef- ficiency and curb the diversion of urea for non-agricultural purposes. The neem coating slows the dissolution rate of urea in the soil, ensuring a gradual release of nitrogen that minimiz- es nutrient loss and boosts crop productivity. Additionally, it helps prevent soil degradation caused by overuse of urea and discourages illegal diversion for industrial applications, as neem-coated urea is unsuitable for non-agricultural uses. 171","PW-2349":"Statement 1 is correct : The initiative promotes adv- anced production, post-harvest technologies, and value addi- tion techniques to enhance millet productivity and processing. Statement 2 is correct : The scheme benefits poor, marginal, and tribal farmers as millets are drought-resistant and thrive in low-input farming conditions. Statement 3 is incorrect : While the initiative promotes millet cultivation, it does not mandate shifting from commercial crops or provide free kits for inputs and micro-irrigation equipment. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 678 172","PW-2350":"Statement 1 is correct : The entire Ganga River Basin is used as a planning and management unit, ensuring com- prehensive conservation efforts. Statement 2 is correct : NGRBA is responsible for national-lev- el policy and implementation strategies for river cleaning and pollution control. Statement 3 is incorrect: The Prime Minister of India is the Chairperson of NGRBA, not a rotating Chief Minister. 173","PW-2351":"A Geographical Indication (GI) tag is granted to prod- ucts that have a specific geographical origin and possess qual- ities or a reputation linked to that location. Banaras Brocades and Sarees (GI Tag - 2009): Famous for in- tricate Zari and silk weaving, these sarees are handwoven in Varanasi, Uttar Pradesh. Tirupati Laddu (GI Tag - 2009): This prasadam from the Tirumala Venkateswara Temple in Andhra Pradesh is known for its unique recipe and religious significance. Rajasthani Daal-Bati-Churma is incorrect: It is a traditional Rajasthani dish but has not been granted a GI tag. 174","PW-2352":"Statement 1 is incorrect: The decomposition process is initiated by anaerobic bacteria developed by DRDO, not by a fungal inoculum. These bacteria break down human waste into simpler compounds. Statement 2 is incorrect: The end products of decomposition in bio-toilets include methane (CH₄), carbon dioxide (CO₂), and water, with trace amounts of ammonia, but not only ammo- nia and water vapour. 175","PW-2353":"In 2014, the award was conferred upon ISRO for its re- markable achievements in space technology and its role in scien- tific advancement and national development. The Indira Gandhi Prize for Peace, Disarmament, and Development is awarded annually for exemplary contributions to peace, sustainable de- velopment, and scientific progress. ISRO continues to make strides in space technology, with projects like Chandrayaan-3, Gaganyaan, and Aditya-L1. The Mars Orbiter Mission (Mang- alyaan) was a key factor in ISRO receiving this award, making India the first country to reach Mars in its maiden attempt and at a low cost. 176","PW-2354":"The Planning Commission, which followed a central- ized economic planning model, was replaced by NITI Aayog (National Institution for Transforming India) on January 1, 2015. NITI Aayog is leading initiatives like Aspirational Dis- tricts Programme, Atal Innovation Mission, and National Data and Analytics Platform. NITI Aayog emphasizes ‘cooperative federalism’, where states are given more autonomy in poli- cy-making. Unlike the Planning Commission, which imposed five-year plans, NITI Aayog focuses on long-term policy strat- egies, innovation, and sustainable development goals (SDGs). It functions as India’s premier policy think tank and promotes digital governance, social sector reforms, and economic competitiveness. 177","PW-2355":"The Demographic Transition Model (DTM) describes the shift in population growth patterns as an economy devel- ops. India is currently in Stage 3, moving towards a stabilized population with lower fertility rates.  Stage 1 (High Birth Rate & High Death Rate): This occurs in pre-industrial societies, where disease, famine, and poor healthcare keep both birth and death rates high.  Stage 2 (High Birth Rate & Low Death Rate): With better healthcare and sanitation, mortality declines while fertility remains high, leading to rapid population growth.  Stage 3 (Low Birth Rate & Low Death Rate): As urbanization, education, and family planning improve, birth rates decline, stabilizing population growth. International Relations and Current Affairs 679 178","PW-2356":"Statement 1 is correct : Bio-asphalt is not derived from fossil fuels but from renewable biomass sources like plant-based oils, algae, and bio-waste. This makes it a sus- tainable alternative to conventional petroleum-based asphalt. Statement 2 is incorrect : The claim that bio-asphalt is made from non-renewable resources is wrong because its raw ma- terials come from renewable sources such as biomass and or- ganic waste. Unlike conventional asphalt, which relies on finite petroleum reserves, bio-asphalt can be continuously replen- ished. Statement 3 is correct: Bio-asphalt can be produced from or- ganic waste materials, such as agricultural residues, used cooking oil, and forestry waste. This reduces waste accumu- lation and promotes circular economy practices by repurpos- ing waste into construction materials. Statement 4 is correct: Using bio-asphalt lowers greenhouse gas emissions as it reduces dependency on fossil fuels and uti- lizes carbon-sequestering biomass. It contributes to sustain- able road infrastructure, aligning with global efforts to reduce carbon footprints in cons","PW-2357":"“Unto This Last” & Gandhi  Written by John Ruskin (1860), the book deeply influenced Mahatma Gandhi.  The message that transformed Mahatma Gandhi was “The good of individual is contained in the good of all”  Gandhi translated it into Gujarati as “Sarvodaya” (The Welfare of All).  Core message: Individual well-being is tied to societal welfare, promoting ethical economics, self-sufficiency, and equitable wealth distribution.  Inspired Gandhi’s Phoenix Settlement in South Africa and self-reliant village development in India. v v v","PW-2358":"Between the 8th and 12th centuries AD, medieval India saw the rise of regional dynasties like the Chandelas, Paramaras, Gurjara-Pratiharas, and Rashtrakutas, which shaped the political, cultural, and architectural landscape after the decline of centralized powers like the Guptas and Harsha’s empire. Pair 1 is correctly matched: The Chandela dynasty was founded around the 9th century, and Nannuka is traditionally regarded as the founder. Chandela dominion extended from the Yamuna (Jumna) River in the north to the region of Saguar (now Sagar) and from the Dhasan River in the west to the Vindhya Hills. It was during Chandela rule that Khajuraho turned into a cultural and architectural hub. The Kandariya Mahadeva Temple stands as the pinnacle of Chandela architectural achievement. The Chandela dynasty is famous for constructing the Khajuraho temples, a UNESCO World Heritage Site. Nannuka established the dynasty in the early 9th century CE. Pair 2 is incorrectly matched: Vakpati’s sons Jayashakti (Jeja) and Vijayashakti (Vija) consolidated the Chandella power. Vakapati succeeded his fathe","PW-2359":"Hundis are used as a form of remittance instrument to transfer money from place to place. It was used as a form of credit instrument or IOU to borrow money and as a bill of exchange in trade transactions. The Hundis was a letter of credit payable after a period of time. The word \"hundi\" is often linked to the Sanskrit root \"hundika,\" meaning a type of bill or note. The Lekhapaddhati (12th century, in post-Harsha period) refer to the use of hundika by kings and nobles to make payments but it may have been used by merchants as well. Hundis were widely used during the post-Harsha period (7th century onwards) and played a significant role in the growth of trade and urbanization in India. 3","PW-2360":"In the context of the economic history of medieval India, the term 'Araghatta' refers to a waterwheel, an important piece of technology used for irrigation. The term ‘Araghatta’ derives from the words “ara” which means “spoke” and “ghatta” means “pot”. The waterwheels were used to lift water from wells or rivers to irrigate crops. This technology played a significant role in agricultural productivity, particularly in regions with an agrarian economy by providing a reliable and efficient method of irrigation. Baburnama provides a comprehensive explanation and a picture of the Persian Wheel which was in use in the Punjab province. 2 Medieval History UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 54 4","PW-2361":"In the medieval era, feudalism was the predominant socio-economic structure. Statement 1 is incorrect: As a political principle of organization that divided the power of lords, feudalism laid the foundations for a decentralization of political power, wherein the nobility owned land from the Crown in return for military service, and vassals were tenants of the nobles. The peasants were required to reside on their lord’s land and to offer him homage, labor, and a share of the production in exchange for military protection. Statement 2 is correct: In a feudal system, land is the main economic resource, and it is the key to political power and authority. The feudal system is built around the concept of land ownership, where lords or landholders control vast estates and manage them with the help of vassals, peasants, or serfs. Land is granted in exchange for military service, loyalty, or other obligations, forming the basis for the entire administrative and economic structure. Statement 3 is correct: One of the key features of the feudal system is the lord-vassal relationship, which forms","PW-2362":"Buddhism emerged in India around the 6th century BCE, and reached its zenith during the reign of Emperor Ashoka embraced Buddhism and instituted dharma as the state ideology. (3rd century BCE). Later, it began to decline in the 4th–6th century CE due to increasing influence of Brahmanism and was mostly replaced by Hinduism by the 12th century. Statement 1 is correct: Buddhism declined during the entire phase of Bhakti movement absorbing various aspects of Hinduism such as Buddha's inclusion as 9th incarnation of Vishnu thus becoming a part of Vaishnavism. This assimilation made Buddhist practices and beliefs blend into mainstream Hinduism. Statement 2 is incorrect: The Kushans, the Sakas, the Greeks, and the Parthians were some of the Central Asian tribes that invaded India. Though some tribes like the Huns adopted Hinduism during the period 200 B.C. to 300 A.D. Buddhism gained a strong foothold in the north western India. Many of the foreigners like the Indo-Greeks and the Kushanas, who invaded India during this time accepted Buddhism Statement 3 is incorrect: The Gupta rulers gave ","PW-2363":"The Mongol invasions of India, particularly during the Delhi Sultanate, began in the early 13th century under Genghis Khan and continued through the 14th century. The invasions targeted northern India, with significant assaults during the reigns of Iltutmish, Ala-ud-din Khalji, and Muhammad-bin- Tughlaq. Despite several incursions, the Mongols did not establish permanent control over Indian territories. Statement 1 is incorrect: The first Mongol invasion of India took place in the reign of Sultan Shams-ud-din Iltutmish. Who was a ruler of Slave dynasty and was also able to preserve his kingdom. Statement 2 is correct: During the reign of Ala-ud-din Khalji, Mongols attacked and pillaged not only the surrounding areas, but Delhi itself. Alauddin formed a large standing army for conquest and defense, but the Mongols attacked during his Chittor siege. Statement 3 is incorrect: Muhammad-bin-Tughlaq faced several Mongol invasions during his reign but he successfully defended his kingdom against them and did not lose any territory to the Mongols. In some cases, he even launched counterattac","PW-2364":"The 'Kulah-Daran' are a group of Persian immigrants who lived in India in the eleventh century. \"Kulah-Daran\" literally translates to \"hat-wearers\" and was used to describe people who wore a specific kind of Persian cap called a \"kulah.\" The Sayyids (1414 to 1451 AD) were known as ‘Kulah Daran’ during the Delhi sultanate. They were the fourth ruling family of the Delhi Sultanate established by Khizr khan. Other dynasties of the Dehi Sultanate are:  Mamluks (AD 1206–AD 1290)  The Khaljis (AD 1290–AD 1320)  The Tughlaqs (AD 1320–AD 1412)  The Lodis (AD 1451– AD 1526). 8","PW-2365":"Statement 1 is correct: In the pursuit of the fugitive Khwarezm prince, Changez Khan arrived in India during the reign of Iltutmish. By denying shelter to Prince Jalaluddhin of Central Asia, Iltutmish protected India from Changez Khan’s fury. Statement 2 is incorrect: The period of Muhammad bin Tughlaq was from 1325 to 1351. Taimur invaded India during the reign of Nasir-ud-Din Mahmud Shah Tughluq (1394-1412), the last Tughlaq ruler. Statement 3 is incorrect: Vasco da Gama reached the coast of Kerala in 1498, but Deva Raya II ruled the Vijayanagara Empire earlier, from 1424 to 1446. At the time of his arrival, the ruler of the Vijayanagara Empire was Krishnadevaraya (reigned 1509– 1529). 9","PW-2366":"The Delhi Sultanate (1206–1526) was a series of Muslim dynasties that ruled over large parts of the Indian subcontinent. It marked the introduction of Islamic governance and administration in India. Statement 1 is correct: In the land revenue system of the Delhi Sultanate, the central government appointed amil to collect revenues in each subdivision called Amil. Statement 2 is incorrect: The Iqta system of land control was first introduced in the Delhi Sultanate by Iltutmish. The institution known by its Arabic name, iqta, had existed in the early Islamic world as a means of rewarding services to the state. In the administration of the Caliphate, it served as a means of funding operations and compensating civil and military leaders. It was not an ancient indigenous institution. Statement 3 is incorrect: The office of Mir Bakshi was established under the Mughal empire, who was head of the military department, nobility, information and intelligence agencies. SUPER HINT For S2, The term “Iqta” sounds Persian/Arabic — not Sanskritic or Dravidian. So claiming it's both “ancient” and “indi","PW-2367":"Muhammad bin Tughlaq (reigned 1325–1351) was a controversial Sultan of Delhi known for his ambitious yet often failed policies, including the introduction of token currency and the shifting of the capital to Daulatabad. While his reforms aimed at modernizing administration, they led to economic instability and widespread discontent. Assertion (A) is correct: Muhammad bin Tughlaq introduced a variety of coins during his reign, including a gold coin referred to as the Dinar by Ibn Batutah. His interest in monetary innovations is well-documented. Reason (R) is incorrect: Muhammad bin Tughlaq’s plan to introduce token currency was implemented using copper and brass coins, not gold. The intention behind issuing token currency was to address a shortage of precious metals and not to promote trade with West Asian and North African countries.​ 11","PW-2368":"The Lodi Dynasty (1451–1526) was the last Afghan ruling dynasty of the Delhi Sultanate. It was founded by Bahlol Lodi, Which marked the beginning of Afghan rule in Delhi, and ended with the defeat of Ibrahim Lodi at the First Battle of Panipat, which led to the establishment of the Mughal Empire. Option (c) is correct UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 56 The correct chronological order of the rulers of the Lodi dynasty are as follows:  Bahlol Khan Lodi (1451–1489) established Afghan rule in Delhi after overthrowing the Sayyid Dynasty.  Sikandar Shah Lodi (1489–1517)was son of Bahlol Lodi. He is known for administrative efficiency and establishing the city of Agra in 1504.  Ibrahim Lodi (1517–1526) was son of Sikandar Lodi.His defeat by Babur at the First Battle of Panipat (1526) marked the end of the Delhi Sultanate and the beginning of the Mughal Empire. 12","PW-2369":"Tughlaq dynasty (1320-1413) which was the third ruling dynasty of the Delhi Sultanate was founded by the Ghiyasuddin Tughlaq who was commonly referred to as Ghazi Malik. Nasir-ud- Din Mahmud Shah, another name for Mahmud Shah Tughluq was the final sultan of the Tughlaq dynasty to govern the Islamic Delhi Sultanate. The list of rulers who ruled the Tughlaq dynasty are:  Ghiyasuddin Tughlaq - 1320-25  Muhammed Bin Tuglaq - 1325-51  Feroz Shah Tughlaq - 1351-88  Ghiyas-uddin Tughlaq shah II 1388-1390  Nasiruddin Mahmud Shah 1390-1394  Mahmud Shah Tughlaq 1394-1412 13","PW-2370":"Qutb-ud-Din Aibak (1206-1210 AD) was the first Sultan of Delhi and the founder of the Mamluk dynasty. Aibak’s notable achievements include the construction of the Qutb Minar in Delhi, which is a symbol of Islamic architecture, and his efforts to consolidate control over northern India by defeating Rajput kingdoms and expanding his empire. Option (d) is correct: Qutb-ud-din Aibak died in 1210 CE from a fatal accident while playing Chaugan (a Persian-origin game similar to polo). He fell from his horse during the match in Lahore and succumbed to his injuries. His death was accidental and occurred during a leisure activity, not due to treachery or battle. Other important rulers of the Mamluk dynasty are:  Shamsuddin Iltutmish 1210 - 1236 AD  Raziyya Sultan - 1236 - 1240 AD  Ghiyasuddin Balban - 1266 - 1287 AD 14","PW-2371":"Zia-ud-Din Barani (1285–1357) was a prominent historian and political thinker during the period of Tughlaq Dynasty. His most famous work, “Tarikh-i-Firoz Shahi”, chronicles the history of the Delhi Sultanate and provides valuable insights into the political and social conditions of the time. He advocated a theocratic system of governance, where Islamic law would guide the state’s policies. Option (c) is correct: ​The Sultans of Delhi, frequently made decisions based on political and administrative pragmatism rather than strictly following Islamic laws. He argued that the state was not “truly Islamic” because the Sultans often supplemented or modified Sharia (Islamic law) with their own administrative and secular regulations (Zawabit). 16","PW-2372":"","PW-2373":"Chengiz Khan (1162–1227) was a Mongol ruler who established one of the largest empires in history by uniting the Mongol tribes and launching successful military campaigns across Central Asia, China, the Middle East, and Eastern Europe. Iltutmish (reigned 1211–1236 AD) was the third Sultan of the Delhi Sultanate, and during his reign, the Mongols, under the leadership of Chengiz Khan, attempted several incursions into the Indian subcontinent. In 1221, after the Khwarezmian prince fled into northern India, Chengiz Khan's forces reached the Indus River and attacked the northwestern frontier of India. He successfully repelled the Mongol invasions, though the Mongols continued to raid the northwestern regions sporadically for some years. 20","PW-2374":"Abdul Qadir Badayuni was an Indian historian, writer, and translator who lived during the Mughal Empire. He is notable for translating key Hindu texts, including the Ramayana and the Mahabharata (Razmnama), into Persian. Option (c) is correct: Muhammad-bin-Tughlaq (1325–1351) was known for his controversial and ambitious policies. It includes the: UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 58  Introduction of token currency  Shifting the capital from Delhi to Daulatabad, and aggressive expansionist campaigns.  The quote \"The king was freed from his people and they from their king\" was made by Badauni on the death of Muhammad-bin-Tughlaq. 21","PW-2375":"The Lodi dynasty was an Afghan royal family that ruled the Sultanate of Delhi from 1451 to 1526. It was the fifth and last dynasty of the Delhi Sultanate. Bahlol Lodi defeated Hussain Shah Sharqi (1458 to 1505 CE) of Jaunpur in 1479. Bahlul Khan Lodi was the chief of the Pashtun Lodi tribe and was the founder of the Lodi dynasty from the Delhi Sultanate upon the abdication of the last claimant from the previous Sayyid rule. 22","PW-2376":"Fawazil was the surplus or excess revenue collected by the Iqtadars beyond their prescribed share and remitted to the central treasury, ensuring financial accountability and contributing to the Sultanate's centralized economy. Sikandar Lodhi (1489 to 1517) of the Lodi dynasty abolished the practice of sending \"fawazil\" to the central treasury. This move by Sikandar Lodi was part of his efforts to consolidate his power and reduce the financial control of the central government over the military officials, allowing them greater autonomy. 23","PW-2377":"Firoz Shah Tughlaq (reigned 1351–1388 AD) was one of the most prominent rulers of the Tughlaq dynasty of the Delhi Sultanate. His reign is remembered for a number of reforms and infrastructural developments. He is credited with building the largest and most significant canal network during this period, aimed at boosting agriculture and ensuring water availability. The Britisher used to call him the Father of the Irrigation Department because of the many gardens and canals he built like the canal connecting the Yamuna to Hissar city; Satluj to the Ghaggar, etc. 24","PW-2378":"Assertion is correct: The early Turkish rulers in India relied heavily on their military to establish and maintain control over the region. The Delhi Sultanate was founded on military conquest, and the rulers relied on military commanders for administrative control. During this time, the sultanate's governance was largely militarized, and military leaders had significant power and influence over the territory. Reason is true: The concept of Iqta was introduced in India during the rule of Shams-ud-Din Iltutmish (r. 1211–1236). An Iqta was a land grant that was given to military leaders in return for their service. These military leaders, often called Iqtadars, were in charge of the administration of the land within their assigned Iqta and were responsible for maintaining law and order, collecting revenue, and providing military support to the Sultan. The system of Iqta created a decentralized form of administration, where military leaders had significant autonomy within their assigned territories. Thus, Reason (R) correctly explains the Assertion (A). 25","PW-2379":"Abul Fazl, a historian and one of Navratnas in Akbar’s court, mentioned the discovery of America by Europeans in his monumental work ‘Ain-i-Akbari’. His writings provide insights into Akbar’s court, administration, and cultural milieu, showing the reach of Mughal intellectual pursuits. Other important writings of the Abul Fazl are:  Akbarnama  The History of Akbar  Inshā-i-Abu'l Fazl  Persian translation of the Bible 26","PW-2380":"Balban (reigned 1266–1287) was one of the most prominent rulers of the Delhi Sultanate, particularly known for his strong and centralized rule. He was part of the Slave dynasty which began with Qutb-ud-Din Aibak. After consolidating his power, Balban assumed the grand title of \"Zil-i-Ilahi\", which means \"The Shadow of God\" or \"The Shadow of the Divine.\" This title was a reflection of his absolute authority and divine right to rule. By adopting this title, Balban sought to emphasize the sacred nature of his rule and his unquestionable authority, essentially equating his position with the will of God. 3. REGIONAL KINGDOMS 27","PW-2381":"","PW-2382":"Hoysala Dynasty: Originating from the Indian subcontinent, the Hoysala Empire held sway over a significant portion of present-day Karnataka from the 11th to the 14th centuries. While the Hoysalas initially established their capital at Belur, it was later relocated to Halebidu. Gahadavala Dynasty: Following the dissolution of the Pratihara empire, several Rajput states emerged in northern India. Among these, the Gahadavalas of Kanauj (12th to 13th century), the Paramaras of Malwa, and the Chauhans of Ajmer were the most prominent. Kakatiya Dynasty: The Kakatiya dynasty ruled the region comprising present day Telangana and Andhra Pradesh during the 12th and 14th centuries. Their capital was Warangal in Telangana. The distinct style of Kakatiya-era architecture is seen in the Thousand Pillar Temple and Ramappa Temple near Warangal. Yadava Dynasty: The Yadava dynasty ruled in the 12th–14th- century and comprised the Hindu kingdom of central India in what is now the Indian state of Maharashtra. Originally a feudatory of the Eastern Chalukyas of Kalyani, the dynasty became paramount in the","PW-2383":"Statement 1 is incorrect: The Nizamat of Arcot was a Muslim princely state in South India during the 18th century. It was founded by the Nawabs of Arcot, who initially served as vassals under the Nizam, the ruler of the Hyderabad State. After the weakening of the Nizam’s power, they gained greater control over the region. The Nizamat of Arcot included areas such as Arcot, Carnatic, and parts of modern-day Tamil Nadu. Statement 2 is correct: Under the Vijayanagar Empire, there was a small feudal kingdom called Mysore. The Kingdom of Mysore was founded by the Wodeyar dynasty in 1399. The Wodeyar dynasty declared their independence following the fall of Vijayanagar in 1565, and Raja Wodeyar ascended the throne in 1578. The capital moved from Mysore to Srirangapatna in 1610. Statement 3 is incorrect: Afghan Chiefs under the leadership of Daud Khan established Rohilakhand, from erstwhile Mughal territory in Awadh region, by taking advantage of the breakdown of authority in North India following Nadir Shah’s invasion. 30","PW-2384":"Correct chronology is as follows: 2-4-1-3  The Pallavas were a powerful dynasty that ruled a large part of southern India between the 6th and 9th centuries AD, with Kanchipuram (now in Tamil Nadu) as their capital. The Pallavas achieved their pinnacle with Mahendravarman I’s rule (c. 600–630), who reigned alongside Harsha and Pulakeshin II.  The Pala Empire, which started in the Bengal region and ruled throughout the post-classical period (8th and 9th century AD), was an imperial power. The empire was officially established when Gopala was chosen to rule as Gauda’s emperor in 750 AD.  Nagabhatta I founded the Gurjara Pratihara Dynasty (8th to 11th Century AD) in the Malwa region around the 8th century AD. Mihir Bhoja (836–885 AD) was the greatest ruler of the Pratihara dynasty.  The Cholas rose to prominence in the 9th century and formed an empire that included most of South India; Tanjore/ Tanjavur served as their capital. The reign of the Chola king Parantaka, who succeeded his father Aditya I as king, lasted from 907-953 AD. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 60 31","PW-2385":"","PW-2386":"The 9th century saw the rise of a number of hill states, some of which maintained their identity until recent years, despite their wars with each other and frequent raids from the plain areas. Medieval Indian State Present Region Champaka Chamba (Himachal Pradesh) Durgara Jammu Kuluta Kullu (Himachal Pradesh) Malwa Central India Kamarupa Assam Trigarta Jalandhar Utkala Odisha Twipra Tripura 33","PW-2387":"The Nizam Shahi dynasty (1490 to 1633 AD) ended when the Mughals annexed Ahmadnagar in 1633. Hussain Shah, the last ruler, was captured and imprisoned for life by the Mughal forces, marking the dynasty’s end and strengthening Mughal control over the Deccan. Option (b) is incorrect: Nizam-ul-Mulk, a key figure of the Nizam Shahi dynasty of Ahmadnagar, did not die as a result of battle with the Mughals. Instead, he passed away from natural causes. Option (c) is incorrect: The son of Malik Amber, Fateh Khan surrendered to the Mughals in the siege of Daulatabad in 1633 and handed over the young Nizam Shahi ruler Hussain Shah to the Mughals who was sent as a prisoner to the fort of Gwalior. Option (d) is incorrect: Malik Ambar was a prominent general and regent in the Ahmadnagar Sultanate, but he died in 1626, and the Nizam Shahi dynasty’s formal end came in 1636. Furthermore, the entire royal family was not killed by Mughal troops. 34","PW-2388":"Marathas were a prominent warrior group from the western region of India who rose to power in the 17th century under the leadership of Shivaji Maharaj. They formed the Maratha Empire, which became the strongest native power in India following the decline of the Mughal Empire. Assertion (A) is correct: The Marathas emerged as a dominant force after the decline of the Mughal Empire due to their military strength, administrative capabilities, and extensive networks of alliances. Reason (R) is incorrect: Marathas did have a vision of a strong and unified empire under their control, but the idea of a “united Indian nation” as a political and cultural entity was not articulated in the way we understand the modern concept of a nation-state today. The Maratha Empire was driven more by regional, dynastic, and military ambitions rather than a unifying national ideology. 35","PW-2389":"Ibrahim Adil Shah II (1580-1627 AD) of Bijapur sultanate was known for promoting religious harmony and blending Hindu-Muslim traditions in music, art, and literature. His secular outlook earned him the title 'Jagadguru' (World Teacher) among his subjects. He also wrote a book called 'Kitab- i-Nauras', which discussed religious tolerance and philosophical ideas. Gulshan- i- Ishq was one of his portraits made after his death. 36","PW-2390":"Balaji Vishwanath (1713-1720 AD) became the Peshwa (Prime Minister) of the Maratha Empire in 1714 during the reign of Chhatrapati Shahu Maharaj, the grandson of Shivaji Maharaj. He is credited with playing a pivotal role Medieval History 61 in strengthening the administration of the Maratha Empire and ensuring the centralization of power under the Peshwa system. His leadership set the stage for the Maratha Empire's expansion in the 18th century. 37","PW-2391":"The Jama Masjid in Kashmir, completed under the patronage of Zain-ul-Abidin (1420 – 1470 AD), is renowned for its unique blend of architectural features, including Persian influences, turrets, and a resemblance to Buddhist pagodas. This architectural synthesis reflects Kashmir’s historical interaction with Persian culture and Buddhist heritage. 38","PW-2392":"","PW-2393":"Shivaji (1627-1680) opposed the Mughal dynasty and founded the Maratha kingdom in 17th-century India. His kingdom’s security was based on religious toleration and on the functional integration of Brahmans, Marathas, and Prabhus. He was assisted by a council of Eight members (Ashtapradhan) in his administration. The members of the council are: 1. Peshwa - Head of the administration, overseeing governance. 2. Sumant - In charge of foreign affairs and diplomacy. 3. Sachiv - Managed records and communications. 4. Amatya - Responsible for finances and revenue. 5. Dabir - Handled correspondence. 6. Senapati - Military commander-in-chief. 7. Nyayadhish - Chief justice, overseeing law and order. 8. Pandit Rao - Managed religious affairs and advised on spiritual matters. 4. VIJAYANAGARA EMPIRE 40","PW-2394":"King Krishnadevaraya (1509 to 1529) of Tuluva dynasty allowed the Portuguese to build a fort Bhatkal in 1510. The town was named Bhatakala after the Jain grammarian Bhattakalanka Deva, who hailed from Haduvalli, 16 km away, capital of the Saluvas of Gerusoppa. The Vitthal temples and the Hazara Rama temple were constructed during his reign. 41","PW-2395":"Vijayanagar was founded in 1336 by Harihara and Bukka of the Sangama dynasty. Four dynasties – Sangama, Saluva, Tuluva and Aravidu – ruled Vijayanagar from A.D. 1336 to 1672. Deva Raya I (c.1406–1422 CE) of the Sangama dynasty was a very capable ruler noted for his military exploits and his support to irrigation works in his kingdom. He constructed a dam across the river Tungabhadra to bring canals into the city to relieve the shortage of water. He also built a dam on the river Haridra for irrigation purposes. Many foreign travelers also visited the Vijayanagar Empire and their accounts are also valuable.  Portuguese writer Duarte Barbosa - Krishna Deva Raya.  Venetian traveller Nicolo de Conti - Dev Raya II.  Persian traveller Abdur Razzak - Dev Raya II.  Portuguese traveller Domingo Paes - Krishna Dev Raya. 42","PW-2396":"Abdur Razzak, was a the Iranian ambassador who visited the Indian subcontinent during the reign of Deva Raya II, noted that in Vijayanagar, three types of coins were prominently used: Varaha, Dinara, and Fanam. Among these, the Fanam was the most widely used.  The chief gold coin of the Vijayanagar Empire was the varaha or pagoda.  Tar was a silver coin  Jittal was a copper coin. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 62 43","PW-2397":"The accounts of foreign travelers such as Abdur Razzak from Persia, Nicolo de Conte from Italy, Fernao Nuniz, Domingo Paes and Duarte Barbosa from Portugal, provide us with a valuable historical lens of the Vijayanagara Kingdom. Fernao Nuniz, a Portuguese traveler who visited the Vijayanagara Empire during the reign of Achyuta Deva Raya, noted that women in the empire held prominent roles. He observed that they were trained in various skills, including wrestling, swordsmanship, soothsaying, astrology, and accounting. These women were actively involved in the kingdom’s political, social, and cultural life. In addition to fine arts like music, some also received education in literature​. SUPER HINT You can try, The \"NOT\" approach for all statements, this tests the improbability of negating a statement—if de- nying its impact seems highly unlikely, the statement is plausibly true. Nuniz would’ve recorded exceptions, so probability of all being true is very high. 44","PW-2398":"Statement 1 is correct: Under the rule of Krishna Deva Raya (ruler of Vijayanagar empire), the taxation system was quite well-organized and efficient. The tax rate was fixed between one-third and one-sixth depending on the quality of the land. This method ensured that the tax burden was more equitable, as fertile land produced higher yields and therefore could bear a higher tax rate. Statement 2 is correct: Commercial taxes consisting of levies, duties and customs on manufactured articles of trade were also levied. Private owners of workshops also paid an industry tax. In addition to the land tax, there were taxes levied on shopkeepers, farm workers, farm servants, laborers, posters, shoemakers, musicians, etc. Grazing and house taxes were also imposed. 45","PW-2399":"Harihara I, along with his brother Bukka Raya I, laid the foundation for the city of Vijayanagara in 1336 on the south bank of the river Tungabhadra, a tributary to the river Krishna. Harihara I believed that the land south of the river Krishna belonged to the deity Virupaksha (a form of Lord Shiva). He undertook the responsibility of ruling the kingdom on behalf of this deity, considering himself as an agent of the deity. This reflects the deep religious and cultural connection to the land and the empire’s association with divine authority. The rulers of Vijayanagara were often referred to as the \"servants of Virupaksha\", showcasing their role as divine agents. 46","PW-2400":"The Angkor Vat Temple, located in modern-day Cambodia, was built under the reign of King Suryavarman II (reigned 1113–c. 1150) of the Khmer empire. Originally dedicated to Lord Vishnu, it later became a major Buddhist center. The temple complex is a prime example of Khmer architecture and is one of the largest religious monuments in the world. Fig: Angkor Vat Temple 47","PW-2401":"Raja Wodeyar established the Wodeyar dynasty in Mysore, around the late 14th century. During this period, Venkata II (1586 to 1614) was one of the rulers of the Vijayanagar Empire (1336 A.D to 1646 A.D.), which, despite being in decline, continued to wield influence over southern India. 48","PW-2402":"The Vijayanagara Empire experienced notable dynastic transitions, beginning with the founding Sangama dynasty, which was replaced by the Saluva dynasty due to internal instability. This was followed by the rise of the Tuluva dynasty. All the Statements 1, 2, 3 and 4 are correct:  The Vijayanagar Empire witnessed significant dynastic changes, beginning with Narasimha Saluva, who ended the Sangama dynasty and established the Saluva dynasty.  Subsequently, Vira Narasimha seized throne by deposing the last Saluva ruler, and his younger brother, Krishnadeva Raya succeeded him and became one of the greatest rulers of the empire.  Following his death, Krishnadeva Raya was succeeded by his half-brother, Achyuta Raya. 49","PW-2403":"The Saluva Dynasty is credited with stabilizing the Vijayanagara Empire after the decline of the Sangama Dynasty, restoring order and expanding its territories. Under Saluva Narasimha, the empire strengthened its military and administrative structures, ensuring its resilience. The dynasty also laid the groundwork for the prosperity that flourished under the subsequent Tuluva Dynasty. Assertion (A) is correct: Saluva Narasimha, a Vijayanagara Empire ruler in the late 15th century, is credited with ending the declining Sangama dynasty and founding the Saluva dynasty in 1485 CE. Reason (R) is correct: This shift was necessitated by internal rebellion and external threats from the Bahmani Sultanate and the Gajapati rulers of Odisha. His primary motive was to restore stability and prevent further disintegration of the empire. The assertion about his actions and the reason attributing these to his concern for the kingdom’s survival are both accurate, and R explains A effectively. Hence, R is the correct explanation of A. 5. BHAKTI AND SUFI MOVEMENT 50","PW-2404":"Statement 1 is incorrect: Saint Nimbarka (1130- 1200) is thought to have lived in the 11th and 12th centuries CE. His theology revolves around Krishna and Radha, with a focus on bhakti. The Mughal emperor Akbar lived from 1542 -1605. Nimbarkacharya also known as Nimbarka, Nimbaditya or Niyamananda, was a Hindu philosopher, theologian and the chief proponent of the theology of Dvaitadvaita (dvaita–advaita) or dualistic–non-dualistic. He wrote Dashashlokee. Statement 2 is incorrect: Saint Kabir (1440–1518) was a famous mystic poet and saint considered to have been influenced by Sant Tukaram, Vishnu-based bhakti traditions, and Sufism, but Shaikh Ahmad Sirhindi (1564–1624), a later figure, was not a contemporary of Kabir. In fact, Shaikh Ahmad Sirhindi was a reformist figure in the Naqshbandi Sufi order and his thoughts were centered around orthodox Islam. 52","PW-2405":"Statement 1 is correct: In the sixteenth and seventeenth centuries, a monotheistic movement, mystical in nature, developed within Shaivism in the Tamil region. This was known as the Sittars or Siddhas. The term siddha literally means one who has attained perfection as distinct from a bhakta who is attempting to perceive god. Statement 2 is correct: The Lingayats of kannada region challenged the idea of caste-heirarchy and the “pollution” attributed to certain groups by Brahmanas. They also questioned the theory of rebirth. The Lingayats are devotees of Basaveshwara, a poet and social reformer who lived in the 12th century. The term “Linga” refers to universal consciousness as defined by the universal energy, not to Lingas seen in temples (Shakti). Lingayats are Shaivites and have been categorized as a Hindu subcaste known as “Veerashaiva Lingayats.” 53","PW-2406":"Sufism is a mystic branch of Islam that puts emphasis on the search for God on a spiritual level and rejects materialism. Statement 1 and 2 are correct: Sufism focuses on love and devotion to God. Devotees used music and dance for expression of their devotion. They also practiced breath-control techniques and meditation. They also used to perform severe ascetic exercises in solitude. Statement 3 is correct: The practice of Sama is a musical performance that aims to elicit a mystical feeling of ecstasy. Murid, or disciple, must pass through countless phases while engaging in spiritual activities in a lonely setting. SUPER HINT You can try, The \"NOT\" approach for all statements, this tests the improbability of negating a statement—if de- nying its impact seems highly unlikely, the statement is plausibly true. For example: Sufi's DON'T do meditation or recitation of holy songs or they were NOT ascetics. Doesn't it sound absurd? Yes, hence all are likely true. 56","PW-2407":"Nagarjuna (2nd century A.D.), a key figure in Mahayana Buddhism, founded the Madhyamaka school, emphasizing philosophical concepts like emptiness (shunyata). He was not associated with the Bhakti cult, which focused on devotional worship of a personal deity. In contrast, Tukaram (a Marathi saint), Tyagaraja (a Carnatic music composer), and Vallabhacharya (proponent of Pushtimarg) were central figures in the Bhakti movement, emphasizing love and devotion to God. Medieval History 65 57","PW-2408":"Tukaram, a renowned Bhakti saint from Maharashtra, lived in the early 17th century, making him a contemporary of Jahangir (reign:1605–1627 AD). He is remembered for his devotional poetry (Abhangas) dedicated to Lord Vitthal, promoting equality, devotion, and moral values. His life and works contributed significantly to the Warkari tradition, which emphasized collective worship and a simple, ethical life. 58","PW-2409":" Shankaracharya (8th century AD) established Advaita Vedanta, emphasizing the non-duality of Brahman. He also established 4 mathas at Jyotirmath,Dwarka,Puri and Sringeri.  Ramanuja (11th–12th century AD) later founded Vishishtadvaita Vedanta (qualified non dualism), advo- cating devotion to a personal god. He played a pivotal role in the Bhakti movement, promoting inclusive spirituality and reforming temple rituals.  Chaitanya Mahaprabhu (15th–16th century AD) was a key figure in the Bhakti movement in Bengal, popularizing devotional worship of Lord Krishna. Their sequence reflects the historical progression of these philosophical and devotional traditions. 59","PW-2410":"Statement 1 is Incorrect: Sheikh Ahmad Sirhindi, known as Mujaddid Alf Sani, lived during the Mughal period and was a contemporary of Akbar and Jahangir long after Ibrahim Lodi (who ruled from 1517 to 1526). Statement 2 is Correct: Sheikh Nasiruddin Chirag-i-Dehlavi was a prominent disciple of Sheikh Nizamuddin Auliya, carrying forward the Chishti Sufi order in Delhi. Statement 3 is Incorrect: Sheikh Salim Chisti, a revered Sufi saint of the Chishti order, was associated with Akbar’s reign and was not contemporary to Aurangzeb. He is known for his spiritual influence at Emperor Akbar’s court and for blessing him with the birth of his son, Salim (later Emperor Jahangir). Statement 4 is Correct: The Qadiri Sufi order was one of the oldest in India and was introduced by saints like Sheikh Niamutullah and Makhdum Muhammad Jilani in the Deccant. These saints and orders significantly influenced Indian society by promoting spiritualism, tolerance, and equality. 60","PW-2411":"Ramananda, a 14th-century Bhakti saint, was the first to use Hindi and its dialects to spread devotional teachings, making Bhakti accessible to the common people. He focused on devotion to Lord Rama, rejected caste hierarchies, and advocated equality in worship. His followers, including Kabir, Ravidas, Tulsidas, and Dadu, further popularized Hindi, solidifying Ramananda’s role in using the vernacular for religious reform. 61","PW-2412":"Sufism is the mystical branch of Islam that emphasizes inner spiritual development, seeking a direct connection with God through meditation, poetry, and devotion. Sufis are often part of “orders” called tariqa, which are congregations centered around a grand master wali. These orders trace their teachings through a lineage of successive teachers, ultimately connecting back to the Islamic prophet Muhammad. Khwaja Muin-ud-din Chisti, founder of the Chishti Sufi order in India, emphasized the use of sama (devotional music) as a means of spiritual connection with God. He believed that music, when performed with pure devotion, could elevate the soul and foster closeness to the divine. This practice became central to Chishti gatherings, inspiring spiritual ecstasy. While Baba Farid and Sayyid Muhammad Gesudaraz focused more on spiritual teachings and community service, the tradition of sama continues today at Muin-ud-din Chisti’s dargah in Ajmer. 6. MUGHAL PERIOD 65","PW-2413":"","PW-2414":"Statement 1 is incorrect: Jagirdars were granted land assignments (known as jagir) in return for military, administrative, or service-related duties. Zamindars, on the other hand have the primary role of revenue collection. But in many cases, especially during the Mughal period, Zamindars were also responsible for maintaining law and order in their regions, depending on the specific region and the emperor's policies. Statement 2 is incorrect: Jagirdars did not necessarily hold hereditary land assignments. The jagir was often granted for services rendered. The emperor could change or revoke these assignments as needed, which means the jagir was not hereditary in the strict sense. Zamindars, however, typically held hereditary rights over the lands they controlled. The right to collect revenue from their land passed down through generations, making their position mostly hereditary in nature. SUPER HINT For S1, The phrase \"without obligation to perform any duty other than revenue collection\" is absolute and ex- treme. In any functional empire, someone collecting revenue would naturally h","PW-2415":"The Mughal school of painting achieved increased charm, elegance, and grandeur during Jahangir’s rule. Mughal Emperor Jahangir shifted emphasis from illustrated manuscripts to albums and individual portraits. The portrait of Jahangir, who is pictured holding a picture of the Virgin Mary in his right hand, is the best representation of this time period. Ayar-i-Danish and Anwar-i-sunavli are two further animal fable books with illustrations that date to Jahangir’s reign. 69","PW-2416":"Babur successfully conquered Bhira (1519–1520), Sialkot (1520), and Lahore (1524) in Punjab. The decisive encounter between Babur and Ibrahim Lodi took place at the Battle of Panipat in 1526. Despite having fewer soldiers, Babur’s army was better organized and strategically superior. Babur’s battlefield tactics were distinctive, he strategically flanked Ibrahim’s army on both sides while his cavalry launched a central assault using arrows and gunfire from skilled Ottoman gunners. Statement 1 is incorrect: Gunpowder was first used in the Indian subcontinent during the 14th century earlier than Babur’s arrival . However it gained prominence during Babur’s campaign for control of Bhera in India in 1519. Statement 2 is incorrect: The introduction of Islamic architectural details, such as true domes and arches, and the fusion of Indian and Islamic architectural forms were the Delhi Sultanate’s biggest contributions to Indian fine arts. This was much before the arrival of Babur. Statement 3 is correct: The Timurids, an islamic Sunni dynasty, had two notable empires in history.  The Timuri","PW-2417":"The English East India Company set up its first factory in Surat in 1613 with the permission of Mughal Emperor Jahangir. Jahangir, who ruled from 1605 to 1627, granted the English the permission to establish a trading post, and this marked the beginning of English trading activities in India. This significant development was achieved through the diplomatic efforts of Sir Thomas Roe, who was sent as an ambassador by King James I of England to Jahangir’s court. 71","PW-2418":"The English East India Company established its first factory in India in 1613 during the reign of Mughal Emperor Jahangir (1605-1627). This historic milestone was achieved when Jahangir granted the Company permission to set up a trading post in Surat, following diplomatic efforts by Sir Thomas Roe. The factory in Surat marked the beginning of a sustained British commercial presence in India and was crucial for accessing the lucrative Indian spice and textile markets. Surat, being a major port city, was central to maritime trade in the Arabian Sea, attracting not only the British but also the Portuguese, Dutch, and other European powers. 72","PW-2419":"Abdul Hamid Lahori was a distinguished historian during the reign of Shahjahan (1628-1658), the Mughal emperor renowned for his architectural achievements like the Taj Mahal and Red Fort. Lahori is best remembered for his monumental work, the Padshahnama, a detailed chronicle of Shahjahan’s reign. This official record documents the emperor’s military campaigns, administrative reforms, cultural contributions, and architectural endeavors, offering valuable insights into the Mughal Empire’s zenith. Lahori’s work is regarded as a continuation of Akbar’s historian Abul Fazl’s style, blending meticulous historical recording with a grand narrative of the emperor’s glory. 73","PW-2420":"The English East India Company was granted permission to establish its first factory in Surat in 1613 by Mughal Emperor Jahangir. This decision was the result of Sir Thomas Roe’s successful diplomatic negotiations with the Mughal court, as he represented King James I of England. Surat, a thriving port city on the western coast of India, was a hub for international trade and was strategically chosen for its access to trade routes connecting India with the Middle East and Europe. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 68 74","PW-2421":"","PW-2422":"Mughal Emperor Shahjahan’s failing health set off the war of succession among his four sons Shuja, Murad, Dara Shikoh and Aurangzeb in 1657. Option (c) is correct: The Battle of Dharmat was fought between Aurangzeb and Dara Shikoh on April 30, 1658, who were both vying for the Mughal throne. Aurangzeb emerged victorious in the battle. 77","PW-2423":"Jahandar Shah (1661-1713) was the 9th Mughal Emperor who reigned from 1712 to 1713 and he was the son of Bahadur Shah. After the death of Bahadur Shah, a new element entered Mughals’ political arena, in which nobles were ‘king makers,’ and rulers were only ‘puppets’ in their hands. Jahandar Shah was considered as the first Mughal India puppet ruler as he won the seat of throne with the support of Zulfiqar Khan, the most powerful noble of the time. Jahandar Shah’s reign came to an early end in January 1713. He was defeated in the battle at Samugarh (a city near Agra) by his nephew Farrukhsiyar on 10th January 1713 with the help of Sayyid Brothers. Farrukshiyar proclaimed himself the Mughal emperor after the battle. 78","PW-2424":"Mughal Emperor Akbar (1556-1605) used diplomacy and military campaigns to expand the Mughal Empire. Assertion (A) is correct: In 1580s , Akbar led his army to Kabul and defeated Hakim Mirza, the king of Kabul. When Hakim Mirza died, the territory of Kabul was annexed to the Mughal Empire. Reason (R) is incorrect: Akbar marched towards Afghanistan in 1580s to create a safety valve to this empire but not to reclaim his ancestral country of Ferghana in Central Asia. 79","PW-2425":"","PW-2426":"The Mughal empire under Shah Jahan (1628-1658) is typically shown with vast territories, including most of northern and central India and parts of southern India, which matches the shaded area. In the year 1635, Shah Jahan marched to deccan kingdoms in person and conquered Nizamshahi of Ahmednagar and Bijapur kingdoms. Aurangzeb, the third son of Shah Jahan was given the viceroyalty of Deccan in 1655. In his capital Agra he was responsible for the construction of the two mosques Moti Masjid and Jami' Masjid (Great Mosque) and the famous mausoleum Taj Mahal. 82","PW-2427":"The Babul Makka (Gate of Makka) was a symbolic and ceremonial term often associated with structures built or designated during the Mughal period that signified spiritual or geographical connections to Mecca, the holiest city in Islam. Option (d) is correct: During the Mughal period, the port of Surat was referred to as Babul Makka due to its importance as a major trading port and its role in facilitating the pilgrimage to Makka. 83","PW-2428":"","PW-2429":"The Mughal Empire began in 1526 and lasted for over 200 years. At its peak it covered modern day India, Pakistan and Afghanistan. The empire was founded by Babur, a Muslim warrior prince from Central Asia, who descended from the Mongols. Several European travelers, including Ralph Fitch, William Hakins, Sir Thomas Roe, Francois Bernier, and Jean- Baptiste Tavernier, documented the Mughal Empire's wealth, administration, society, and culture. Pair 1 is correctly matched: William Hawkins visited Jahangir’s court as a representative of the East India Company. He gained favor with Jahangir and was granted trading privileges. Pair 2 is incorrectly matched: Sir Thomas Roe (1615–1619), an English ambassador sent by King James I to Jahangir’s court to negotiate trade rights for the East India Company. Pair 3 is correctly matched: Jean-Baptiste Tavernier was a French gem (particularly diamond) trader and traveler in the 17th century Tavernier visited India six times between 1630 and 1668 and provided invaluable accounts of trade, society, and the Mughal court, particularly during the reign of","PW-2430":"Assertion is true: During Akbar's reign, the Mansabdari system was an essential part of his military and administrative structure. The Mansabdar was a title given to officials who held military or civil offices. The Mansabdars were required to maintain a specific number of cavalrymen, and the ratio was set at 10 cavalrymen for every 20 horses. Reason is true: Horses needed rest during long marches, especially in difficult terrain or extended campaigns. Additionally, during war, horses might get injured or exhausted, and replacements were essential to ensure that the cavalry remained effective. Having extra horses provided the necessary logistical support for the Mansabdars to keep their cavalry functional during both long marches and active combat situations. 86","PW-2431":"","PW-2432":"As direct descendants of Tamerlane, the Mughals of India considered Central Asia their true home and ancestral domain and thus desired to recover their ancestral lands. Also, the areas of Kandahar, Balkh, and Badakhshan were strategically important for the Mughal Empire due to their proximity to the borders of the Safavid Empire. Assertion (A) is correct: Dara Sikoh, the son of Shah Jahan, was sent on a military expedition to Balkh, Badakhshan, and Kandahar. These missions aimed to consolidate Mughal influence in these strategically important regions. Reason (R) is incorrect: Dara Shikoh's expedition to the Middle east failed despite the use of a large army and advanced Mughal artillery. The campaign did not achieve its goals, and the Mughals suffered significant setbacks during Shah Jahan's reign, including the permanent loss of Kandahar to the Safavids, weakening their influence in the region. 88","PW-2433":"The loss of Kandahar was a significant setback for the Mughal Empire due to its strategic importance. It was located in present-day Afghanistan and served as a vital buffer zone between the Mughals and the Safavid Empire, protecting the western frontier. Kandahar was also a key strategic stronghold, controlling trade and military routes with Central Asia and the Middle East. Its fortifications were crucial for projecting Mughal power into regions like Balkh, Badakhshan, and Herat. Losing Kandahar weakened the Mughal position in the northwest. 89","PW-2434":"The Mir Bakshi was a pivotal figure in the military administration under Akbar’s reign. They managed the recruitment, organization, and payment of the army. Additionally, they supervised military campaigns and oversaw overall military affairs. Diwan was the head of the revenue department in the provinces and oversaw revenue and finance. Mir Saman was in charge of the imperial household. He was responsible for managing the purchase and procurement of goods and supplies for the royal household, including furniture, clothing, and other necessities. Bakshi was head of the military department at provincial level. 90","PW-2435":"Mughal paintings blended indigenous Indian, Persian, and Islamic styles, creating a unique and distinct art form. Option (c) is correct: Mughal painting reached its zenith during the reign of Emperor Jahangir (1605-1627). His reign is regarded as a period of flourishing artistic achievements, particularly in miniature painting. Under his patronage, Mughal painting became more sophisticated, with detailed depictions of portraits, court scenes, hunting scenes, religious themes, and landscapes. He employed Ustad Mansur to achieve unparalleled sophistication in Mughal art and showcased a great fascination for nature and portraiture. 91","PW-2436":"The Mansabdari system was a significant administrative framework introduced by Emperor Akbar in the 16th century. The system was a hierarchical structure that catered to both military and civil administration. Option (d) is correct: The Mansabdari system provided a centralized structure with clear ranks and responsibilities, ensuring smooth administration. This system ensured the recruitment of competent and loyal soldiers, with each Mansabdar responsible for a specific number of soldiers, fostering discipline and efficiency. Mansabdars managed tax collection and land revenue, contributing to the imperial treasury, reducing corruption, and ensuring fair resource distribution. 7. MISCELLANEOUS 92","PW-2437":"Jean-Baptiste Tavernier was a French traveler and gem merchant who traveled extensively in India during the 17th century. He was an independent traveller and trader who, between the years of 1630 and 1668, made travels to Persia and India in the courts of Shah Jahan and Aurangzeb. He is well- known for his detailed accounts of the diamonds and diamond mines of India, particularly the famous Golconda mines. Tavernier provided extensive information on the diamond trade, the mines in places like Golconda, and the prized diamonds, such as the Koh-i-Noor. 93","PW-2438":"During the Indian, banjaras were generally merchants. They referred to their caravans as tanda. Option (d) is correct: During the reign of Alauddin Khalji, banjaras had a significant impact. For the purpose of transporting grain to the markets in the cities, Alauddin Khalji used the Banjaras. They were responsible for moving goods from one location to another. According to the Emperor Jahangir’s chronicles, the Banjaras transported grain from various regions on their bullocks and sold it in towns. 94","PW-2439":"In Medieval India, particularly during the Delhi Sultanate and the early Mughal period, the terms Mahattara and pattakila were the village headmen. Pattalika is generally identified with the modern Patel, believed to be the king’s representative in the village. Mahattara was a non-official and possibly a representative of the people. The Mahattara had significant authority within the village and was often tasked with overseeing the community's activities and ensuring that taxes were collected and local disputes were settled. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 72 95","PW-2440":"The Virupaksha Temple in Hampi, dedicated to Lord Shiva, has been operational since the 7th century AD. It is a prime example of Vijayanagara architecture built by Lakkan Dandesha, a chieftain under King Deva Raya II and features intricate carvings, sculptures, and towering Gopuras adorned with Hindu mythological scenes. The temple's central shrine houses Lord Virupaksha, an incarnation of Shiva. Surrounding the temple are smaller shrines, mandapas (pillared halls), and a spacious courtyard. Over the centuries, various dynasties have contributed to its expansion and preservation. Beyond its religious significance, the temple is part of the UNESCO World Heritage Site of Hampi, which showcases the ruins of the Vijayanagara Empire. 96","PW-2441":"The Vijaya Vittala Temple in Hampi, a UNESCO World Heritage site, was built during King Devaraya II’s reign in the 15th century. Dedicated to Lord Vittala, an incarnation of Lord Vishnu, the temple is famous for its 56 musical pillars that produce melodic sounds when struck. Its most notable feature is the stone chariot in front of the Ranga Mantapa, dedicated to Garuda, with two elephants pulling it. The temple showcases the exceptional craftsmanship of the artisans of the Vijayanagara Empire. 98","PW-2442":"Statement 1 is correct: Kitab-I-Nauras (The Book of 9 Rasas), a collection of songs praising both Hindu deities and Muslim saints, was composed by Sultan Ibrahim Adil Shah II of Adil Shahi dynasty in the 16th century. The fifty-nine songs and seventeen couplets of the book are written in Dakhni Urdu. It also indicates the ragas in which they were to be sung. He was a dhrupad singer and the player of an instrument called tambour. Statement 2 is correct: Amir Khusrau, a renowned Sufi poet, musician, and scholar, is credited with the foundation of Qawwali music in India. Qawali is a devotional form of Islamic music deeply embedded in the mystical traditions of Sufism, and Amir Khusrau is often regarded as its spiritual and musical architect in the Indian subcontinent. 99","PW-2443":"The Lingaraj Temple, located in Bhubaneswar, Odisha, is one of the most important and revered temples in eastern India, dedicated to Lord Shiva. The temple is believed to be built in the 11th century during the rule of King Jajati Keshari of Somavamshi dynasty (9th century C.E. to 11th century C.E.). It is an excellent example of Kalinga architecture, showcasing intricate carvings and an impressive structure. Medieval History 73 100","PW-2444":" The Qutub Minar was built by Qutb-ud-Din Aibak, the first ruler of the Delhi Sultanate, in 1193. It was later completed by his successor Iltutmish in the early 13th century. It is a victory tower or minaret that was constructed to mark the beginning of Muslim rule in India and to celebrate Qutb-ud-Din Aibak's victory over the Rajputs. Sultan Firoz Shah Tughlaq is credited with having repaired the tower in the 14th century after it was damaged by lightning. The Qutub Minar was designated as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1993, recognizing its architectural and historical significance.  Firoz Shah Tughlaq, a Delhi Sultan known for administrative reforms, died in 1388 A.D. Firoz Shah introduced the Faujdar system and created the post of Shiqdar (District head).  Vasco da Gama’s arrival at Calicut in 1498 marked the beginning of Portuguese maritime influence in India.  Krishna Deva Raya of Vijayanagara (1509–1529 A.D) was the greatest ruler of the Vijayanagara Empire, contributing to military, administrative, and cultural advancements. 102","PW-2445":" In the Jagirdari System, land was assigned to feudal landlords or nobles (Jagirdars) in exchange for administrative or military service. The land granted to Jagirdars was not permanently owned by them. They were assigned the revenue rights of the land for a fixed term.  Under the Zamindari System, intermediaries (Zamindars) collected revenue from peasants and passed it to the government. They did not own the land but had the right to collect taxes from the peasants in exchange for keeping a portion of the collected revenue.  In the Ryotwari System, individual peasants (Ryots) owned the land directly and had the right to sublet, mortgage, or sell it. It was mainly implemented in areas like Madras, Bombay, and parts of Assam.  The Mahalwari System involved revenue collection based on the collective responsibility of an entire village (Mahal). The head of the village, often a local leader or a prominent landowner, would be responsible for paying the land tax for the entire group of villages. 103","PW-2446":"Amir Khusrau (1253–1325) was a prolific poet, musician, and scholar during the Delhi Sultanate. He is credited with being one of the earliest to use a proto-Urdu form in his works, mixing Persian, Khari Boli, and Hindavi dialects, laying the foundation for Urdu poetry. He is regarded as the “father of Urdu literature” and played a crucial role in the development of this language.  Mirza Ghalib (1797–1869) is renowned for his contributions to classical Urdu poetry, but he came centuries after Khusrau.  Bahadur Shah Zafar (1775–1862) was a Mughal emperor and a poet, but not the first to use Urdu.  Faiz Ahmed Faiz (1911–1984) was a modern Urdu poet known for poetry focused on social justice, resistance, and human rights. UPSC GS Paper-I PYQs 74 104","PW-2447":"The term Ahadis was used in the context of Mughal military service, specifically during the reigns of emperors like Akbar and his successors. Ahadis were soldiers who served in the imperial army. Statement (1) is correct: Ahadis offered their services individually and were not part of a larger contingent. They were distinct in their roles and reporting structure. Statement (2) is correct: They did not align themselves with any noble or chief but served independently. Statement (3) is correct: Ahadis reported directly to the emperor and were considered elite troopers. Their services were provided to the central authority, bypassing local chiefs. Statement (4) is incorrect: They did not attach themselves to Mirzas (a title for nobles or princes). 105","PW-2448":"The construction sequence is Qutub Minar (1193) > Tughlaqabad Fort (1321)>Lodi Garden (1451-1526)> Fatehpur Sikri (1571).  Qutub Minar (1193-1220) construction was initiated by Qutb-ud-din Aibak and completed by Iltutmish during the early Delhi Sultanate era.  Tughlaqabad Fort was built by Ghiyas-ud-din Tughlaq as a fortified city during the Tughlaq dynasty. It was designed with robust defense mechanisms, including thick walls, towers, and a deep moat.  Lodi Garden was made during the Lodi dynasty. The park is home to several notable tombs from the Lodi dynasty, including the tomb of Sikandar Lodi, the founder of the Lodi dynasty, and the tomb of Muhammad Shah Lodi, the last Sultan of the Lodi dynasty.  Fatehpur Sikri was constructed by Emperor Akbar in the late 16th century. It served as the capital of the Mughal Empire for a brief period before it was abandoned. 106","PW-2449":"The word \"Apabhramsa\" literally means \"corruption\" or \"degeneration.\" In a linguistic context, it was used to describe a deviation or transformation from classical Sanskrit that led to the emergence of regional languages, which later evolved into modern Indian languages. Apabhramsa emerged during the medieval period (from the 6th to 13th centuries). It was a transitionary stage between Prakrits (the vernacular languages of ancient India) and the modern Indo-Aryan languages such as Hindi, Gujarati, Marathi, Bengali, and others. It was a mixture of regional dialects influenced by the local vernaculars, and its forms were quite diverse across different regions. Medieval History 75 109","PW-2450":"Raskhan’s Prem Vatika stands out as an exquisite devotional work on Krishna, blending intense love (prem) with devotion (bhakti). Raskhan, originally a Muslim by birth, became a devoted follower of Krishna and is known for his devotional poetry. Some of his important works are: Sujana Raskhana, Danalila, Astayama, and a collection of Padas.  Bihari, a 17th Century poet, authored the Satsai, being a brilliant poet of classical Hindi literature, his works do not specifically focus on Krishna’s life.  Surdas was a prominent saint of the Krishna Bhakti tradition. He is known for his work Sur Sagar, a collection of poems celebrating Krishna’s childhood (bal leela) and divine play (raas leela). However, Prem Vatika is not attributed to him.  Kabir, a Nirguna Bhakti professed worshiping a formless divine (nirakar). His works like Sakhi and Bijak focus on spiritual truths and unity, not Krishna-centric themes. v v v","PW-2451":"The Old World refers to the continents of Europe, Asia, and Africa, known to Europeans before the discovery of the Americas. The New World refers to the Americas, including North and South America, which were “discovered” by Europeans after Christopher Columbus’s voyages in the late 15th century. Tobacco, cocoa, and rubber were domesticated in the ‘New World’ and introduced into the ‘Old World’ through the European explorers in the late medieval or early modern era. The Columbian exchange was the widespread transfer of plants, animals, culture, human populations, technology, diseases, and ideas between the Americas, West Africa, and the Old World in the 15th and 16th centuries.","PW-2452":"Ans: A Exp: Option (a) is correct: In the Western Coast, the English India Company established their factories at Agra, Ahmadabad, Baroda and Broach by 1619, under the control of the president and council of the Surat factory which was established in the year 1612. In the South-eastern Coast the East India Company established their factories at Masulipatam in 1611 and Armagaon near Pulicat in 1626. In Eastern India, East India Company established their factories at Hariharpur and Balasore (now Odisha) in 1633, at Hugli in 1651, followed by setting up factories at Patna, Dacca, Kasimbazar in Bengal and Bihar respectively.","PW-2453":"1 and 3 only Pair 1 is correctly matched: The image of Mahaparinirvana of Buddha is in cave 26 of Ajanta caves in the Sahyadri range on the Waghora river in Aurangabad, Maharashtra. They were built under the patronage of Vakataka rulers. Pair 2 is not correctly matched: A huge image of the Varaha Avatar of Lord Vishnu, rescuing Goddess Earth from the deep and chaotic waters is in Udayagiri caves near Vidisha, Madhya Pradesh. They were built under the patronage of Gupta rulers around the 5th century AD. Pair 3 is correctly matched: Arjuna’s Penance/ Descent of Ganga is the monolithic sculpture built under the reign of Pallava King Mahendravarman and is located in Mamallapuram (Mahabalipuram), Tamil Nadu. This site was also included in UNESCO World Heritage Sites.","PW-2454":"Pair 1 is correctly matched : Tabo Monastery situated in the Spiti Valley of Himachal Pradesh, India is a historically and culturally significant Buddhist monastery. It was founded in 996 CE and is one of the oldest continuously functioning Buddhist monasteries in India and is renowned for its exquisite murals, sculptures, and architecture reflecting a blend of Tibetan and Indian artistic influences. Pair 2 is incorrectly matched : Lhotsava Lhakhang is located in Nako village which is part of Kinnaur district of Himachal Pradesh. Pair 3 is correctly matched : Alchi Temple Complex located in the village of Alchi in Ladakh, India and was built in the 12th century is another important Buddhist site. It is particularly famous for its unique and well- preserved wall paintings which showcase a fusion of Indian and Kashmiri artistic styles.","PW-2455":"3 only Statement 1 is not correct: Ajanta Caves are the most famous cave site in Ajanta. It is located in the Aurangabad District of Maharashtra State. Ajanta has twenty-nine caves. It has four chaitya caves datable to the earlier phase, i.e., the second and the first century BCE (Cave Nos. 10 and 9) and the later phase, i.e., the fifth century CE (Cave Nos. 19 and 26). It has large chaitya viharas and is decorated with sculptures and paintings. Ajanta is the only surviving example of painting of the first century BCE and the fifth century CE. The caves at Ajanta as well as in western Deccan in general have no precise chronology because of the lack of known dated inscriptions. The shore temple at Mahabalipuram was built later, probably in the reign of Narasimhavarman II, also known as Rajasimha who reigned from 700 to 728 CE. Statement 2 is not correct: Ajanta caves are mostly dedicated to Buddhist denominations. While the shore temple at Mahabalipuram was built later, probably in the reign of Narasimhavarman II, also known as Rajasimha who reigned from 700 to 728 CE. It is oriented to the east facing the ocean, it actually houses three shrines, two to Shiva, one facing east and the other west, and a middle one to Vishnu who is shown as Anantashayana. Statement 3 is correct: Both Mahabalipuram and Ajanta are some of the finest examples of rock-cut monuments.","PW-2456":"Pair 1 is incorrectly matched: Besnagar (located in Madhya Pradesh) is not known for being a Shaivite Cave Shrine. It is known for Garuda Pillar dedicated to lord Vasudeva by Heliodorus,an envoy of an Indo- Greek ruler Antialkidas in the court of Bhagabhadra. Heliodorus followed Vaishnava Sect. Pair 2 is correctly matched: Bhaja (located in Maharashtra) is renowned for its Buddhist cave complex dating back to the 2nd century BCE. The 22 cave complex is part of the early phase of Buddhist rock-cut architecture and include a chaitya (prayer hall) and viharas (monastic cells). Pair 3 is correctly matched: Sittanavasal (located in Tamil Nadu) is famous for its Jain cave complex which dates back to the 2nd century BCE. The site includes a rock-cut cave temple with beautiful frescoes depicting Jain themes such as the Samavasarana (divine preaching hall).","PW-2457":"Statement 1 is incorrect : The distinction between Mitakshara and Dayabhaga is not based on caste i.e. upper or lower castes but on regional variations of Hindu law. Mitakshara was prevalent in most parts of India, whereas Dayabhaga was primarily followed in Bengal and parts of Assam. Statement 2 is correct : Both were Hindu law books and governed property rights and inheritance. The Mitakshara was written by Vijnanesvara, a scholar in the Kalyani Chalukya court in the late 11th century. The Dayabhaga was authored by Jimutavahana, a 12th-century scholar from Bengal. In the Mitakshara system, sons acquire a right to ancestral property by birth, meaning they have a share in the joint family property during the father’s lifetime. In the Dayabhaga system, sons do not have a right to the property until the father’s death. Statement 3 is incorrect : The Mitakshara system historically favored male descendants, with females becoming coparceners only after the Hindu Succession Act, 2005. In contrast, the Dayabhaga system provides relatively better property rights to women, allowing both male and female heirs to inherit property. However it is wrong to say that Mitakshara deals with matters of property rights of only males as the wife is allowed to have share when husband and son partition the property. Additional Information: Additional Information: Main differences between the Mitakshara and Dayabhaga systems Mitakshara System Dayabhaga System Writ er Vijnanesvara in the late 11th century Jimutavahana in the 12th- century Geo grap hical Prev alen ce Most parts of India, except Bengal and Assam Bengal and parts of Assam Inhe ritan ce Righ ts Sons acquire rights to ancestral property by birth Sons acquire rights to property only after the father's death Pro pert y Divis ion Joint family property is divided among male members Does not recognize the joint family structure and instead focuses on individual property rights and inheritance. Cop arce nary Pro pert y Only male members were traditionally considered coparceners until the Hindu Succession Act, 2005, allowed females to become coparceners Coparcenary concept does not exist; property is inherited individually","PW-2458":"Shantiniketan located in West Bengal is the home of Rabindranath Tagore’s Visva- Bharati University. It was inscribed on the UNESCO World Heritage List in September 2023 for its cultural and educational significance. Santiniketan which means ‘abode of peace’ started taking shape in 1901, and it was this place Tagore later put up the foundations of Visva Bharati University. Sacred Ensembles of the Hoysalas: The Sacred Ensembles of the Hoysalas located in Karnataka, include the Hoysala temples at Belur, Halebid, and Somnathapura. These temples were inscribed on the UNESCO World Heritage List in September 2023 for their exceptional architecture and artistry. The shrines are characterized by hyper-real sculptures and stone carvings that cover the entire architectural surface, a circumambulatory platform, a large-scale sculptural gallery, a multi- tiered frieze, and sculptures of the Sala legend. Other sites: Rani-ki-Vav located in Gujarat is an 11th-century stepwell known for its intricate architecture and sculptures. These stepwells are a distinctive form of subterranean water resource and storage systems on the Indian subcontinent, and have been constructed since the 3rd millennium BC. It was included in UNESCO WHS list in 2014. Mahabodhi Temple Complex at Bodhgaya is one of the four holy sites related to the life of the Lord Buddha, and particularly to the attainment of Enlightenment. The first temple was built by Emperor Asoka in the 3rd century B.C., and the present temple dates from the 5th or 6th centuries. It was included in the UNESCO WHS list in 2002.","PW-2459":"Ans: C Exp: Statement 1 is correct: In the sixteenth and seventeenth centuries, a monotheistic movement, mystical in nature, developed within Shaivism in the Tamil region. This was known as the Sittars or Siddhas. The term siddha literally means one who has attained perfection, as distinct from a bhakta who is attempting to perceive god. Statement 2 is correct: The Lingayats of the Kannada region challenged the idea of caste hierarchy and the “pollution” attributed to certain groups by Brahmanas. They also questioned the theory of rebirth. The Lingayats are devotees of Basaveshwara, a poet and social reformer who lived in the 12th century. The term “Linga” refers to universal consciousness as defined by the universal energy, not to Lingas seen in temples (Shakti). Lingayats are Shaivites and have been categorized as a Hindu subcaste known as “Veerashaiva Lingayats.”","PW-2460":"Ans: D Exp: Statement 1 is incorrect: Saint Nimbarka is believed to be the contemporary of Ramanuja (11th century) and lived much earlier than Akbar. He believed in total devotion to Krishna and Rama. The Mughal emperor Akbar lived from 1542 -1605. Nimbarkacharya also known as Nimbarka, Nimbaditya, or Niyamananda, was a Hindu philosopher, theologian, and the chief proponent of the theology of Dvaitadvaita (dvaita–Advaita) or dualistic– non-dualistic. He wrote Dashasloki and Vedanta. He was also a prominent astronomer Statement 2 is incorrect: Saint Kabir, a medieval Indian mystic poet and saint, lived in the 15th century, was a follower of Nirguna bhakti. While, Shaikh Ahmad Sirhindi was Islami Hanif, a scholar of Naqshbandi Silsilah lived in the seventeenth century, whose ideology is often contrasted with the liberal and non-sectarian views of Akbar, are amongst those most frequently discussed by scholars.","PW-2461":"Ans: A Exp: Shri Ramanujacharya firmly believed that intense devotion to Vishnu was the best means to attain salvation. Sri Ramanujacharya was born in 1017 CE in Tamil Nadu. He is the most respected Acharya in the philosophy of Sri Vaishnavism. Ramanuja was deeply influenced by the Alvars. He firmly believed that intense devotion to Vishnu was the best means to attain salvation. He is famous as the chief proponent of Vishishtadvaita subschool of Vedānta. He was also referred to as Ilaya Perumal,which means the radiant one. He wrote nine works that came to be known as the Navratnas including three major commentaries, the Vedartha-Sangraha, the Sribhasya and the Bhagava Gita-bhashya aimed at providing a philosophical foundation for devotional worship. Vishishtadvaita is a non-dualistic school of Vedanta philosophy in which Brahman alone exists, but is characterized by multiplicity.","PW-2462":"Option (c) is correct: Permane nt Settleme nt Started by Lord Cornwallis in 1793. Prevalent in Bengal, Bihar, Orissa, Varanasi (United Provinces), and Northern Karnataka. Covered 19% of British India. A new section of Zamindars was appointed who would provide 10/11th part of the revenue collected to the British while keeping the remaining. Ryotwari System Started by Thomas Munro and Alexander Reed in 1820. Started in the Baramahal district of Tamil Nadu and later spread to Madras, parts of Bombay, East Bengal, Assam and Coorg (Karnataka). Covered 51% of British India. Ryots (farmers) were given ownership and other rights over the land and were required to pay the revenue directly to the government. Involved high taxes and strict collection. Mahalwar i System The Mahalwari system was introduced by Holt Mackenzie in 1822. Prevalent in United Provinces, Central Provinces and Punjab. Covered 30% of British India. The village or mahal served as the unit for collecting revenue. Village land belonged to the community and it was the responsibility of the entire community to pay the land revenue.","PW-2463":"The Butler Committee, chaired by Sir Harcourt Butler in 1927, investigated the relationship between British India and the princely states. Its 1929 report reaffirmed the doctrine of paramountcy, clarifying that the British Raj’s control over the princely states was not just contractual but a dynamic, evolving relationship shaped by history and policy. The committee recommended that the financial relationship between the Raj and the states should be fair.","PW-2464":"Ans: C Exp: Option (c) is correct: Under British rule,Indian agriculture became increasingly commercialized. The traditional subsistence farming was replaced by large-scale cultivation of crops such as cotton, indigo, and jute for export purposes, often to meet the needs of British industries. Options (a), (b) and (d) are incorrect: Indian handicrafts suffered during British rule due to the influx of cheap machine-made British goods, which displaced local handicrafts in domestic and international markets. The number of Indian-owned factories was very limited during the 19th century. Most of the industries, including textile mills, were controlled by the British. The urban population did not see a rapid increase during British While some cities grew due to British administrative and military needs, the overall urbanization rate was low compared to European countries. Moreover, much of India’s population remained rural, engaged in agriculture.","PW-2465":"Pair 1 is incorrectly matched: Aurang is a Persian term referring to a warehouse where goods are collected before being sold. Pair 2 is correctly matched: The term Banian (or Banyan) was used during the colonial period to refer to Indian agents or intermediaries who acted as local representatives or agents for European trading companies, including the East India Company. They helped the company in business dealings, acted as middlemen, and facilitated trade. Pair 3 is correctly matched: A Mirasidar was a landowner or hereditary holder of land in South India under the Ryotwari settlement system. The East India Company recognized mirasdars as the only proprietors of land, dismissing tenants’ rights completely. They acted as a designated revenue payer of the state.","PW-2466":"Option (d) is correct : Fort William College was established in 1800 by Lord Wellesley, the Governor-General of India in Calcutta (now Kolkata). The primary purpose of the college was to train British civil servants in Indian languages, customs, and laws to improve the efficiency of the East India Company's administration in India. Lord Wellesley recognized that British officials often lacked knowledge of Indian languages, culture, and traditions which hindered effective governance. The college was designed to train newly recruited British civilians in Indian languages (such as Persian, Sanskrit, Arabic, and regional languages) and familiarize them with local customs and laws. He believed that a well-trained administrative cadre would help the East India Company govern India more effectively and reduce reliance on Indian intermediaries.","PW-2467":"Statement 1 is correct : St. Francis Xavier, along with St. Ignatius of Loyola and others, co-founded the Society of Jesus (Jesuit Order) in 1534. The Jesuits were established to promote education, missionary work, and counter the Protestant Reformation. Statement 2 is incorrect : He died on December 3, 1552, on Shangchuan Island (Sancian Island), off the coast of China, while waiting for a ship to take him to mainland China for missionary work. His body was later brought to Goa, where it is enshrined in the Basilica of Bom Jesus, a church dedicated to him. Statement 3 is correct : The Feast of St. Francis Xavier is celebrated annually on December 3 in Goa. Additional Information : Francis Xavier, a Spanish missionary and one of the founding members of the Jesuit Order, is renowned for his extensive missionary work in Asia during the 16th century. He played a pivotal role in spreading Christianity in India, Japan, and the Malay He arrived in Goa in 1542 and worked to spread Christianity.","PW-2468":"Ans: B Exp: Statement 1 is incorrect: In Ryotwari system the government revenue was a fixed amount, irrespective of crop output, and was to be paid in cash. Thus during periods of bad crops or low prices the peasants were forced to pay the land revenue, even if it required borrowing from moneylenders . Statement 2 is correct: In the Zamindari system the revenue was invariable, regardless | | UPSC of the harvest, and had to be paid punctually. According to the Sunset Law, if payment did not come in by sunset of the specified date, the zamindari was liable to be auctioned. Additional Information : The Ryotwari system : Introduced by Thomas Munro in the Madras and Bombay Presidencies, aimed to collect land revenue directly from individual cultivators (ryots). Unlike the zamindari system, peasants were recognized as landowners and were personally responsible for paying taxes to the British government. However, the revenue demand was high and periodically revised, often placing a heavy financial burden on farmers. The Permanent Settlement : Introduced by Lord Cornwallis (1793) in Bengal, Bihar, and Odisha, was a zamindari-based land revenue system where zamindars were made hereditary landowners responsible for paying a fixed land tax to the British. This system provided stability in revenue collection for the British, but it led to severe peasant exploitation, as zamindars, who were only interested in maximizing rent, extracted high dues from cultivators.","PW-2469":"Option (a) is correct: Amaravati in Andhra Pradesh holds historical significance as the site of ancient Dhanyakataka, a prominent town in the Deccan region of the later Satavahanas, as recorded in numerous inscriptions. This area also housed a significant Buddhist settlement. According to some Tibetan scriptures Dhanyakataka is the place where early Kalachakra tradition took off. Kalachakra is a Buddhist tantric practice. It was a significant hub of Mahayana Buddhism and was associated with the Mahasanghika sect. The famous Amaravati Stupa, one of the largest Buddhist stupas in India, is located near this site. Options (b), (c) and (d) are incorrect : Gandhara (Pakistan-Afghanistan region) was a center of Gandhara art and Mahayana Buddhism. Kalinga (Odisha) was significant for Ashoka’s Buddhist transformation but not specifically for the Mahasanghikas. Magadha (Bihar) was the heartland of early Buddhism but not linked to Dhanyakataka. Additional Information: Major ancient Buddhist Sites :","PW-2470":"Ans: A Exp: Statement 1 is correct: The Constitution of India only provides for single citizenship. Indian citizens are loyal only to the Indian Union. Moreover, the citizenship of an Indian citizen will expire immediately if they voluntarily acquire the citizenship of any other country. In India, only one domicile is permitted. A single State or UT may only issue a Domicile Certificate. Statement 2 is incorrect: In India, the Head of the State is the President, and as per the Indian Constitution both a citizen by birth as well as a naturalised citizen are eligible for the office of President. Thus, a naturalized citizen can also become the Head of the State in India. Statement 3 is incorrect: A foreigner who has previously received Indian citizenship can be deprived of his citizenship. Indian citizenship can be terminated by the Central government if obtained the citizenship by fraud; shown disloyalty to the Constitution of India; unlawfully exchanged goods or information with the enemy while at war; two years of imprisonment in any country within five years of registration or naturalisation; he or she has been ordinarily resident out of India for seven years continuously.","PW-2471":"Ans: A Exp: Statement 1 is correct: The Indian Constitution has the provision for single citizenship only, i.e., Indian citizenship. India's citizens only owe allegiance to the Indian Union. Additionally, the citizenship of an Indian citizen immediately expires when he or she voluntarily obtains the citizenship of another nation. In India, only one domicile is permitted. A single State or UT may only issue a Domicile Certificate. Statement 2 is incorrect: In India, the Head of the State is the President, and as per the Indian constitution both a citizen by birth as well as a naturalized citizen are eligible for the office of President. Thus, a naturalized citizen can also become the Head of the State in India. Statement 3 is incorrect: A foreigner who has previously received Indian citizenship can be deprived of his citizenship. Indian citizenship can be terminated by the Central government, if: Obtained the citizenship by fraud. Shown disloyalty to the Constitution of India Unlawfully exchanged goods or information with the enemy while at war. Two years of imprisonment in any country within five years of registration or naturalization.","PW-2472":"The Gandhi Salt Satyagraha (1930) was a non- violent protest against the British monopoly on salt production and its heavy taxation. Led by Mahatma Gandhi, it involved the famous Salt March to Dandi, symbolizing defiance against British colonial rule and mobilizing mass support for India’s independence movement. Such symbolic marches were organised throughout India. C Rajagopalachari organised a march from Tiruchirapalli to Vedaranniyam on Tanjore coast. Additional information : Annie Besant (1847–1933) – A British socialist and theosophist who championed India's self-rule, she founded the Home Rule League (1916) and became the first woman president of the Indian National Congress (1917). She actively promoted education, theosophy, and Indian nationalism. V.O. Chidambaram Pillai (1872– 1936) – A freedom fighter and nationalist from Tamil Nadu, he founded the Swadeshi Steam Navigation Company (1906) to challenge British shipping dominance. He was imprisoned for his involvement in the Swadeshi Movement and is often called \"Kappalottiya Tamizhan\" (The Tamil Helmsman).","PW-2473":"The Gandhi-Irwin Pact was primarily caused by the escalating Civil Disobedience Movement, which included widespread protests against British laws like the salt tax, leading to a need for political negotiation. Statement 1 is correct: The Gandhi–Irwin Pact was a political agreement signed by Mahatma Gandhi and Lord Irwin, Viceroy of India in March 1931 before the Second Round Table Conference in London, where the Indian National Congress was invited to participate. Statement 2 is correct: Withdrawal of all ordinances imposing curbs on the activities of the Indian National Congress was agreed by the Viceroy. Statement 3 is incorrect: The demand for a public inquiry of excesses committed by police during the civil disobedience movement was rejected by the Viceroy. Statement 4 is correct: Release of all political prisoners, except those guilty of violence was agreed.","PW-2474":"Ans: B Exp: The Earth's atmosphere is continuously stirred over the globe by winds. As a result, ozone- depleting gases get mixed throughout the atmosphere, including Antarctica, regardless of where they are emitted. The special meteorological conditions in Antarctica cause these gases to be more effective there in depleting ozone compared to anywhere else. Human emissions of chlorofluorocarbons (CFCs) and halons (bromine-containing gases) have occurred mainly in the Northern Hemisphere. About 90% have been released in the latitudes corresponding to Europe, Russia, Japan, and North America. Gases such as CFCs and halons, which are insoluble in water and relatively unreactive, are mixed within a year or two throughout the lower atmosphere. The CFCs and halons in this well-mixed air rise from the lower atmosphere into the stratosphere mainly in tropical latitudes. Winds then move this air polewardboth north and south from the tropics, so that air throughout the global stratosphere contains nearly equal amounts of chlorine and bromine. In the Southern Hemisphere, the South Pole is part of avery large land mass (Antarctica) that is completely surrounded by ocean. This symmetry is reflected in the meteorological conditions that allow the formation in winter of a very cold region in the stratosphere over the Antarctic continent, isolated by a band of strong winds circulating around the edge of that region. The very low stratospheric temperatures lead to the formation of clouds (polar stratospheric clouds) that are responsible for chemical changes that promote production of chemically active chlorine and bromine. This chlorine and bromine activation then leads to rapid ozone loss when sunlight returns to Antarctica in September and October of each year, which then results in the Antarctic ozone hole. The magnitude of the ozone loss has generally grown through the 1980s as the amount of human-produced ozone-depleting compounds has grown in the atmosphere. Similar conditions do not exist over the Arctic. The wintertime temperatures in the Arctic stratosphere are not persistently low for as many weeks as over Antarctica, which results in correspondingly less ozone depletion in the Arctic","PW-2475":"Ans: A Exp: Among the cities listed, Bengaluru lies closest to Delhi in terms of longitude. Bengaluru is situated at approximately 77.59 degrees East, while Delhi is located at around 77.23 degrees East. The difference in longitude between Bengaluru and Delhi is relatively small compared to the other options. Hyderabad is farther east with a longitude of approximately 78.47 degrees East, followed by Nagpur at around 79.09 degrees East. Pune lies significantly to the west of Delhi, with a longitude of roughly 73.85 degrees East. Therefore, Bengaluru's longitude is the closest match to Delhi among the given cities.","PW-2476":"Second half of the month of June Summer Solstice (21st June): The Northern Hemisphere is tilted towards the sun and the rays of the sun falling directly on the Tropic of Cancer areas receive more heat. The longest day and the shortest night at these places occur on 21st June. Thus, the second half of the month of June in the northern hemisphere has the longest day of the year. Areas near the poles receive less heat as the rays of the sun are slanting.The North Pole is inclined towards the sun and the places beyond the Arctic Circle experience continuous daylight for about six months. Since a large portion of the Northern Hemisphere is getting light from the sun, it is summer in the regions north of the equator. However in Southern Hemisphere all these conditions are reversed (winter season- longer nights).","PW-2477":"Queen Victoria’s Proclamation (1858) ended East India Company rule, bringing India directly under British Crown control. Lord Canning became the first Viceroy and Governor- General. Statement 1 is correct: The proclamation was read out by Lord Canning at a durbar held on November 1, 1858 at Allahabad. The proclamation put an end to the era of further expansion of the British Empire in India. Statement 2 is correct: Queen Victoria’s proclamation of 1858 aimed at ending the rule of the company and transferring all the powers to the British crown after the 1857 revolt. It also promised non- interference in the religious affairs of the people, grant of equal protection of law and respect for ancient rights and customs of the people. Statement 3 is incorrect: Queen Victoria’s Proclamation (1858) is aimed at improving the administrative machinery of supervision and control over the Indian government.","PW-2478":"Ans: B Exp: The Montagu-Chelmsford Reforms which became the Government of India Act in 1919, defined the jurisdiction of the central and provincial governments. It introduced dyarchy in eight provinces, where executive powers were shared between the Governor and elected ministers. Subjects were divided into ‘reserved’ (e.g., law, finance) managed by the Governor and his council, and ‘transferred’ (e.g., education, health) handled by ministers from the legislative council, increasing provincial authority.","PW-2479":"Montague-Chelmsford Proposals had the scheme of constitutional reforms, known as the Montagu-Chelmsford (or Mont-Ford) Reforms, which led to the enactment of the Government of India Act of 1919. It introduced diarchy (rule of two individuals/parties) at the provincial government level. The diarchy was implemented in eight provinces: Assam, Bengal, Bihar and Orissa, Central Provinces, United Provinces, Bombay, Madras and Punjab.","PW-2480":"The Government of India Act, 1919 introduced dyarchy at the provincial level, dividing executive powers between the Governor and elected ministers. The system increased provincial authority, with the Governor as the chief executive. Subjects were divided into two lists: reserved and transferred. The reserved list (e.g., law and order, finance) was managed by the Governor and his executive council. The transferred list (e.g., education, health) was administered by ministers from the elected legislative council. This dual scheme of governance was known as ‘dyarchy’.","PW-2481":"The Government of India Act, 1935 divided powers between the Centre and provinces into three lists: Federal (59 items), Provincial (54 items), and Concurrent (36 items). It granted residuary powers to the Governor-General, who could authorize either legislature to legislate on such matters.","PW-2482":"The Charter Act of 1813 renewed the East India Company’s charter for another 20 years, ending its monopoly on trade with India (except for trade in tea and opium with China). It also allocated funds for promoting education in India and acknowledged the need for social and economic reforms. It gave missionaries permission to travel to India was one of the key components of this law. Statement 1 is correct: The Charter Act 1813 ended the trade monopoly of the East India Company except for the trade in tea, opium, and with China. Statement 2 is correct: company’s territories in India came under the sovereignty of the British Government through this Act. Statement 3 is incorrect: The revenue of India was controlled by the British parliament through Pitt’s India Act 1784.","PW-2483":"Statement (1) is incorrect: The Montagu- Chelmsford Reforms of 1919 introduced a diarchy system in provincial governments, where key areas like finance and law & order remained under British control, while other departments were transferred to Indian ministers. It also paved the way for the creation of a bicameral legislature at the centre. It recommended the voting rights to women in limited numbers to be extended on the basis of property, tax or education. Statement (2) is correct: Government of India Act, 1935 divided the powers between the Centre and provinces. It abolished dyarchy in the provinces and introduced ‘provincial autonomy’ in its place, while adopting the dyarchy at the Centre.It further extended the principle of communal representation to the depressed classes (Scheduled Castes), women and labour (workers).","PW-2484":"With reference to Indian History, Alexander Rea, A. H. Longhurst, Robert Sewell, James Burgess and Walter Elliot were all associated with archaeological excavations. Alexander Rea (1858-1924) was an archaeologist who worked mainly in South British India and is known for unearthing a sarcophagus from the hillocks of Pallavaram in Tamil Nadu. He arrived in India in 1882 and became assistant of Burgess in the Archaeological Survey of India (A.S.I.), Madras Division. He went on to become Superintendent of the Archaeological Survey of Southern India (1902). Albert Henry Longhurst (1876-1955) was an archaeologist and art historian who worked in India and Ceylon. He was in charge of the systematic digging of Nagarjunakonda (1927- 1931). Robert Sewell (1845-1925) was a civil servant in the Madras Presidency in colonial He undertook archaeological work at the Amaravati stupa. The site had previously been surveyed by Colin Mackenzie and Walter Elliot (1803-1887). James Burgess (1832-1916) was the founder of the Indian Antiquary in 1872 and an important archaeologist of British India in the 19th century. From 1886-89 he was Director General of the Archaeological Survey of India.","PW-2485":"Ans: C Exp: Araghatta/Persian Wheel: The ‘Persian Wheel’ has been referred to as Araghatta in ancient Sanskrit writings. The term \"ara-ghatta\" derives from the words \"ara,\" which means \"spoke,\" and \"ghatta,\" which means \"pot.\" There is evidence to support the theory that India was the origin of this method of drawing water from open wells. It is referred to as the \"cakka-vattakka\" or the \"ghati yantra\" in the Panchatantra (3rd century BCE) and the Rajatarangini (12th century CE). In the twelfth century, this term, also known as the \"Araghattikka\" or \"arahattiyanara,\" was frequently used to refer to a person or animal working the Araghatta. The Persian wheel is a water-lifting device used usually by draft animals, like bulls, buffaloes, or camels. Baburnama provides a comprehensive explanation and a picture of the Persian Wheel which was in use in the Punjab province.","PW-2486":"‭Ans: A Exp: Statement 1 is correct: In the land revenue system of the Delhi Sultanate, the central government appointed “Amil” to collect revenues in each subdivision called shiq. ‭Statement 2 is incorrect: The Iqta system of land control was first introduced in the Delhi Sultanate by Iltutmish. The institution known by its Arabic name, Iqta, had existed in the early Islamic world to reward services to the state. In the administration of the Caliphate, it served as a means of funding operations and compensating civil and military leaders. It was not an ancient indigenous institution. Statement 3 is incorrect: The office of Mir Bakshi was established under the Mughal empire, he was head of the military department, nobility, information, and intelligence agencies.","PW-2487":"1 only Statement 1 is correct: In his pursuit of the fugitive Khwarezm prince, Changez Khan arrived in India during the reign of Iltutmish. By denying shelter to Prince Jalaluddhin of Central Asia, Iltutmish protected India from Changez Khan's fury. Statement 2 is not correct: The period of Muhammad bin Tughlaq was from 1325 to 1351. Taimur invaded India during the reign of Nasurud-din Muhammad Shah(1394-1412), the last Tughlaq ruler. Statement 3 is not correct. The reign of Devaraya II lasted from 1422 to 1426 and he died in 1446. Vasco da Gama came to India in 1498.","PW-2488":"Statement 1 is correct: In the pursuit of the fugitive Khwarezm prince, Changez Khan arrived in India during the reign of Iltutmish. By denying shelter to Prince Jalaluddhin of Central Asia, Iltutmish protected India from Changez Khan’s fury. Statement 2 is incorrect: The period of Muhammad bin Tughlaq was from 1325 to 1351. Taimur invaded India during the reign of Nasir-ud-Din Mahmud Shah Tughluq (1394- 1412), the last Tughlaq ruler. Statement 3 is incorrect: Vasco da Gama reached the coast of Kerala in 1498, but Deva Raya II ruled the Vijayanagara Empire earlier, from 1424 to 1446. At the time of his arrival, the ruler of the Vijayanagara Empire was Krishnadevaraya (reigned 1509–1529).","PW-2489":"2 only Statement 1 is not correct: The first Mongol invasion of India took place in the reign of Sultan Shams-ud-din lltutmish. Statement 2 is correct: During the reign of Alauddin Khalji, one of the Mongol invasions reached till the outskirts of Delhi city and besieged it. Alauddin established a huge permanent, standing army to satisfy his ambition of conquest and to protect the country from Mongol invasion. The Mongols attacked at the worst time possible for Alauddin Khilji – when he was busy laying siege to Chittor. Statement 3 is not correct: Muhammad-bin-Tughlaq defeated the Mongols and he had not lost any of the portions of his kingdom to them. In 1327 the Chagatai Mongols under Tarmashirin, who had sent envoys to Delhi to negotiate peace the previous year, sacked the frontier towns of Lamghan and Multan and besieged Delhi. Tarmashirin was a Buddhist who later converted to Islam. Religious tensions in the Chagatai Khanate were a divisive factor among the Mongols.","PW-2490":"The 'Kulah-Daran' are a group of Persian immigrants who lived in India in the eleventh century. \"Kulah-Daran\" literally translates to \"hat-wearers\" and was used to describe people who wore a specific kind of Persian cap called a \"kulah.\" The Sayyids (1414 to 1451 AD) were known as ‘Kulah Daran’ during the Delhi sultanate. They were the fourth ruling family of the Delhi Sultanate established by Khizr khan. Other dynasties of the Dehi Sultanate are: Mamluks (AD 1206–AD 1290) The Khaljis (AD 1290–AD 1320) The Tughlaqs (AD 1320–AD 1412) The Lodis (AD 1451– AD 1526).","PW-2491":"The Mongol invasions of India, particularly during the Delhi Sultanate, began in the early 13th century under Genghis Khan and continued through the 14th century. The invasions targeted northern India, with significant assaults during the reigns of Iltutmish, Ala-ud-din Khalji, and Muhammad- bin- Tughlaq. Despite several incursions, the Mongols did not establish permanent control over Indian territories. Statement 1 is incorrect: The first Mongol invasion of India took place in the reign of Sultan Shams-ud-din Iltutmish. Who was a ruler of Slave dynasty and was also able to preserve his kingdom. Statement 2 is correct: During the reign of Ala-ud-din Khalji, Mongols attacked and pillaged not only the surrounding areas, but Delhi itself. Alauddin formed a large standing army for conquest and defense, but the Mongols attacked during his Chittor siege. Statement 3 is incorrect: Muhammad-bin- Tughlaq faced several Mongol invasions during his reign but he successfully defended his kingdom against them and did not lose any territory to the Mongols. In some cases, he even launched counterattacks and drove the Mongols out of the region.","PW-2492":"Statement 1 is correct: The idea of supporting educated Indians and promoting knowledge of contemporary sciences in the country was enshrined into the Charter Act of 1813. The Charter Act of 1813 permitted Christian missionaries to propagate English and preach their religion. It mandated the company to allocate one lakh rupees annually for the revival and improvement of literature and the promotion of science among the inhabitants of British India. The Act emphasized the need to educate Indians in Western sciences and literature which indirectly laid the foundation for English education. Statement 2 is correct: A “General Committee of Public Instruction” was established by the Governor-General-in- Council in 1823 with the task of allocating one lakh rupees for educational purposes under the Presidentship of Lord Macaulay. Lord Macaulay’s Minute resolved the debate in favor of the Anglicists, directing the limited government resources toward the teaching of Western sciences and literature through the medium of the English language. Statement 3 is correct: The Orientalist-Anglicist Controversy in the early 19th century centered on the medium and content of education in India. Orientalists led by scholars like H.T. Prinsep advocated for preserving traditional Indian knowledge through Sanskrit, Persian, and Arabic. Anglicists led by Thomas Babington Macaulay, pushed for English education to create a class of Indians who were culturally English but Indian by birth. The debate culminated in Macaulay's Minute of 1835 which favored English education. Governor-General Lord William Bentinck endorsed this view thereby officially making English the medium of instruction in higher education.","PW-2493":"Ans: C Exp: Mahendravarman I (590-630 CE) became the ruler after his father’s demise. Under him, the Pallavas became a major political power. He was a king with many accomplishments. He is known for his literary works and temple- building activities and he was also a skilled veena player. He promoted many artistic activities like drama, painting, and music. Gopala went on to become the founder of the Pala dynasty in Bengal, consolidated his rule over Bengal, and brought much-needed stability and prosperity to the region. The date of his accession is not known in definite terms but is generally believed to be in the second half of the 8th century A.D. He died in about 780 A.D. and was succeeded by his son Dharmpala The real founder and the greatest ruler of the Pratihara dynasty was Bhoja (835-85 CE) because he rebuilt the empire after it had almost disintegrated with the defeat of the Pratihara king Nagabhatta II, by the Rashtrakuta king Govinda III. By 836 CE Bhoja had regained Kanauj which remained the Capital of the Pratihara dynasty till the very end. He also re- established his sway over the Gurjaratra (central and eastern Rajasthan). But he was checked in the east by the Palas, and so turned his attention towards central India and Deccan. His attempts to conquer Gujarat and Malwa led to the revival of the conflict with the Rashtrakutas. Parantaka Chola I ruled the Chola kingdom in southern India from 907 CE–955 CE.","PW-2494":"A bill of exchange Hundis: The Hundis was a letter of credit payable after a period of time at a discount. The word \"hundi\" is derived from the Sanskrit word \"hundika,\" which was first used in 914 AD.. The Lekhapaddhati and Kalhan’s Rajatrangini (12th century) refer to the use of hundika by kings and nobles to make payments but it may have been used by merchants as well. Hundis are used as a form of remittance instrument to transfer money from place to place, as a form of credit instrument or IOU to borrow money and as a bill of exchange in trade transactions. The Reserve Bank of India describes the Hundi as \"an unconditional order in writing made by a person directing another to pay a certain sum of money to a person named in the order.\" The hundi was a piece of paper, usually written in Hindi or any other Indian language, promising the payment of a sum of money to the bearer at a particular place either immediately or afterwards. The darshani hundi was paid at sight whereas the miyadi hundi was redeemed after a stipulated period of time. It was called a bill of exchange because the device was originally associated in Europe with the exchange of foreign currencies given at one place and taken at another. | | UPSC Two types of hundis were popular in medieval India: one which was an instrument of money transfer and the other which was an instrument of credit. It was the first type that was used by the bankers to accumulate capital. If a businessman decided to send money from one place to another, he could deposit the cash with a Sarraf in exchange for a hundi and avoid risks of transportation.","PW-2495":"Ans: D Exp: By the late 17th century and early 18th century, Bengal had begun to emerge as an essential source of supply that the East India Company could purchase for sale in Europe. Goods purchased from Bengal included cotton, cloth, opium, saltpetre, sugar, and silk. The English East India Company had vital commercial interests in trading in Bengal, as nearly 60 percent of the British imports from Asia consisted of goods from Bengal. From the mid-17th century, the British established trading factories at Balasore, Hooghly (1651), Kasimbazar, Patna, and Dacca, marking the expansion of their regular contact with Bengal.","PW-2496":"Statement 1 is correct: During the early 1900s, Mahatma Gandhi was instrumental in getting the indentured labour system abolished in the British Empire. He also supported Manilal Doctor’s campaign to get a resolution passed in the INC meeting condemning the indentured labour system in all British territories. Statement 2 is incorrect: Lord Chelmsford invited Gandhi to Delhi at a War Conference. Gandhi agreed to move people to enlist in the army for WW-I hoping such support would lead to political reforms and greater self-rule for India. Statement 3 is correct: Indian National Congress was declared illegal upon breaking of salt law. The British government arrested thousands of Congress leaders and activists, and Gandhi was imprisoned for leading the movement.","PW-2497":"Ans: A Exp: Option (a) is correct: The Ghadar Party was a revolutionary organization based in San Francisco. Initially, it was centered on the weekly newspaper \"The Ghadr,\" which had branches in the Far East and along the US coast in addition to its San Francisco headquarters. Most of these revolutionaries were ex-soldiers and farmers who migrated from Punjab to the United States and Canada in search of better employment opportunities. Arriving in 1911, Ramdas Puri, G.D. Kumar, Taraknath Das, Sohan Singh Bhakna, and Lala Hardayal were involved in pre-Ghadr revolutionary activities.","PW-2498":"Ans: D Exp: Statement 1 is incorrect: Barindra Kumar Ghosh was associated with a revolutionary group called Anushilan Samiti. In the Alipore Bomb Case, he and Ulaskar Dutta were sentenced to death, and due to the intervention of C.R. Das, the sentence was commuted to life imprisonment and deported to a Cellular Jail, in Andaman. Statement 2 is incorrect: Jogesh Chatterjee served in the Hindustan Republican Association/Army (HRA), later joined the Revolutionary Socialist Party (RSP) after independence, and became a member of the Rajya Sabha from the Congress Party in 1956. Statement 3 is correct: The prominent leaders associated with the Ghadar Party were Lala Hardayal, Bhagwan Singh, Ramchandra, Kartar Singh Saraba, Barkatullah, Bhai Parmanand, Raghubar Dayal Gupta, Rash Behari Bose, and Sachin Sanyal were involved in the movement.","PW-2499":"Ans:A Exp: About Article 14: Right to Equality It says that the State shall not deny any individual the right to equality before the law and the right to equal protection of laws. Equality Before Law denotes that there is a lack of any special privileges for any individual; the equal subjection of all persons to the ordinary law of the land administered by ordinary law courts, and No one is above the law, regardless of their status (rich or poor, high or low, official or not). Equal Protection of Law states that the equality of treatment under equal circumstances, both in the privileges conferred and liabilities imposed by the laws; the similar application of the same laws to all persons who are similarly situated, and the like should be treated alike without any discrimination.","PW-2500":"Ans: C Exp: Option (c) is correct: Right to Privacy - Article 21 of the Indian Constitution deals with the protection of life and personal liberty. In the KS Puttaswamy Case (2017), the Supreme Court held that privacy is a natural right that inheres in all natural persons and that the right may be restricted only by state action that passes each of the three tests: Such state action must have a legislative mandate. It must be pursuing a legitimate state purpose It must be proportionate.","PW-2501":"Ans: D Exp: Statement 1 is correct: Sedimentary rocks are primarily formed at the Earth's surface through the process of sedimentation, which involves the deposition and subsequent compaction of mineral and organic particles. This process is closely tied to the hydrological system, which includes the movement of water in various forms such as rivers, lakes, oceans, and even wind-driven processes. Statement 2 is correct: The parent rocks that undergo weathering can be igneous, metamorphic, or even other sedimentary rocks. Weathering processes break down these rocks into smaller particles, including minerals and organic material. Statement 3 is correct: Sedimentary rocks are associated with fossils, which are the preserved remains or traces of once-living organisms. Fossils are critical for understanding past life forms, environments, and the Earth's history. The process of fossilization typically involves the rapid burial of organic material in sediment, preventing decay and promoting preservation. Statement 4 is correct: One characteristic feature of sedimentary rocks is their tendency to occur in distinct layers, known as strata. Each layer represents a different episode of deposition and can provide valuable information about the geological history of an area. These layers may vary in composition, grain size, and color, reflecting changes in environmental conditions over time.","PW-2502":"Ans: A Exp: Statement 1 is correct: Barren Island Volcano is a part of Indian Union Territory of Andaman and Nicobar Islands is an active volcano in South Asia (along a chain of volcanoes from Sumatra to Myanmar). Statement 2 is incorrect: Barren Island is located at about 140 km from Port Blair, in Andaman Sea. The distance between Barren Island to Great Nicobar is more than the given distance and Great Nicobar is the southernmost and largest of the Nicobar Islands of India. Indira Point (6°45’10″N and 93°49’36″E) is the southernmost point of the Great Nicobar Island and India itself. Indira Point subsided 4.25 m in the 26 December 2004 tsunami and the lighthouse there was damaged. Statement 3 is incorrect: Barren Island is the only confirmed active volcano in the Indian subcontinent, and the only active volcano along a chain of volcanoes from Sumatra to Myanmar. The first recorded eruption of the volcano dates back to 1787. The last eruption on Barren Island was recorded in 2018; however there have been instances where smoke and ash has billowed from the mouth of the volcano, covering the sky as recently as 2022.","PW-2503":"Ans: A Exp: Option (a) is correct: In India, trade with foreign empires dates to Harappan culture. Important among them were Lothal, Lakhabawal, Kindarkhera, Kuntasi, Megham, Prabhasa, Todio, and Amra. This tradition continued through the Mauryan and Gupta empires. India had commercial and cultural ties with nearly all of the Southeast Asian nations, as well as Egypt, Rome, the Greeks, the Arabs, and China. Chaul was one of the ports in Western India, with Kalyan, Broach, and Cambay. In the south were Kadura, Ghantsala, and Puhar (Kaveripattinam).","PW-2504":"Ans: B Statement 1 is incorrect: No building has been discovered in the Indus valley which can resemble a temple. Although “Great Bath” may have been used for ritual purposes by the Indus valley people. Statement 2 is correct: Figurines resembling female deities and male gods have been found in the Indus Valley. These included terracotta figurines of women, heavily jewelled, some with elaborate head-dresses. These were regarded as mother goddesses. Rare stone statuary of men in an almost standardised posture, seated with one hand on the knee – such as the “priest-king” – was also similarly classified. Statement 3 is incorrect: The Indus Valley people were not aware of the use of horses and did not show the same regard for the cow or bull. Whilst, the Vedic people attached great importance to cows and horses amongst various animals.","PW-2505":"1 and 3 only Statement 1 is correct: For offensive weapons, the Vedic-Aryans have the bow and arrow, spear, dagger, and axe, and for defensive armour the helmet and coat of mail. The Indus people also have the bow and arrow, spear, dagger, and axe, but defensive armour is quite unknown to Indus Valley people. Statement 2 is not correct: The metals which the Indo-Aryans used in the time of the Rigveda are gold and copper or bronze, but a little later, these metals are supplemented by silver and iron. Among the Indus people, silver is more common than gold, and utensils and vessels are sometimes made of stone- a relic of the Neolithic Age-as well as of copper and bronze. Statement 3 is correct: The horse seems to have been unknown to the inhabitants of Mohenjo-Daro and Harappa. But Many references have been made regarding the Surkotada site containing horse remains dated to 2000 BCE, which is considered a significant observation with respect to Indus Valley Civilisation. After evaluating the Surkotada bone fragments, Sándor Bökönyi (1997) concluded that at least six of the samples most likely belonged to the real horse. However, this is not definitive proof, and it does not imply that people in the Indus Valley knew about horses.","PW-2506":"Option (c) is correct: Sohgaura is located in Gorakhpur, Uttar Pradesh on the banks of the Rapti River. The Sohgaura copper plate inscription, dating to the Mauryan period (possibly pre-Ashokan), was found here. The Sohgaura inscription belongs to the Mauryan era (not the Harappan civilization) and refers to famine relief measures, food grain storage, and granary management. It was written in Prakrit in the Brahmi script. Options (a), (b) and (d) are incorrect : Kot Diji, Desalpur and Chanhudaro are Harappan sites. Kotdiji means “Fort of the Daughter'' and is located in Khairpur province, Pakistan. Here copper-bronze objects, bangles and arrowheads; etched carnelian and other beads and numerous terracotta human, bull, and bird effigy figurines were found. Desalpur, located in Gujarat, is a key Harappan site known for its well-planned settlement, including fire altars and beads, highlighting its role in trade and craft production. Chanhudaro is located on the bank of the Indus River in Sindh, Pakistan. Bead makers' shops have been found here.","PW-2507":"Ans. (a) Exp: Indus Valley Civilization featured advanced town planning with well-laid-out streets, drainage systems, and standardized brick construction. Notable examples include the cities of Mohenjo-Daro, with its grid-like streets and Great Bath, and Harappa, known for its drainage systems and carefully planned residential areas. Option (a) is correct: Discovered in 1968 by Jagat Pati Joshi, Dholavira is one of the best-preserved Indus Valley sites, with a unique water management system using reservoirs and dams. Located between the Manhar and Mandsar streams, it was likely accessible by boat when the Rann’s water levels were higher. Options (b), (c) and (d) are incorrect: Kalibangan is located on the bank of the Ghaggar river in Rajasthan. A fire altar and wooden plough have been found here. Rakhigarhi is the largest Harappan site in the Indian subcontinent. Planned townships having mud-brick as well as burnt-brick were found here. At the Ropar site, a building made of stone, a dog buried with humans and an oval pit burial have been found. Additional Information : Indus Valley Site Dhol avira Known for an advanced water management system with reservoirs and dams; features a unique three-part city layout. Lotha l Important dockyard and maritime trade center; evidence of early shipbuilding and bead-making industries. Mohe n-jo- Daro Features the Great Bath, well- planned streets, and advanced drainage system; one of the largest IVC cities. Hara ppa Major urban center with granaries, distinct town planning, and evidence of early writing. Rakhi garhi Largest known Indus Valley Civilization site, with extensive evidence of urban settlement and burial practices. | | UPSC Chan huda ro Famous for craft production, including bead-making, shellwork, and metalwork; lacks fortifications. Kalib anga n Known for fire altars, suggesting ritualistic practices, and evidence of the earliest plowed fields. Bana wali Oval-shaped settlement with both Harappan and pre-Harappan features; evidence of barley cultivation.","PW-2508":"Statement 1 is incorrect: The first woman President of the Indian National Congress was Annie Besant in the 1917 Calcutta Session. Sarojini Naidu became the first Indian woman President of INC in 1925 Kanpur Session. Statement 2 is correct: Badruddin Tyabji (1844–1906) was the first Muslim President of the Indian National Congress. He presided over the third session of the INC in 1887 (Madras Session). He was a progressive leader, reformist, and the first Indian to practice law in the Bombay High Court.","PW-2509":"The Radcliffe Committee was appointed by the British government in 1947 tasked with demarcating the borders between the newly independent nations of India and Pakistan. The division primarily focused on the regions of Punjab and Bengal, where large Hindu and Muslim populations coexisted. The resulting Radcliffe Line was announced on August 17, 1947, two days after India’s independence. The border division led to massive population displacement, causing widespread violence and communal riots, with millions of people migrating across the new borders, resulting in significant loss of life and property.","PW-2510":"Sattriya is a classical dance form from Assam which was developed in the 15th–16th century by Srimanta Sankardev as part of the Vaishnavite movement. The dance follows a codified sequence, beginning with Ramdani (pure dance), followed by Gayan Bayan (percussive music and dance), and includes Krishna Nritya and Gopi Nritya, depicting Krishna’s tales. It is accompanied by Borgeet (devotional songs) composed by Sankardev and Madhavdev and often features Ankia Naat (one-act plays). Statement 1 is correct: Sattriya was traditionally performed in sattras (Vaishnavite monasteries) and combined dance, music, and drama. Sattriya dance tradition is governed by strictly laid down principles in respect of hasta mudras, footwork, aharyas, music etc. Statement 2 is correct: The Sattriya dance form was introduced in the 15th century A.D by the great Vaishnava saint and reformer of Assam, Mahapurusha Sankaradeva as a powerful medium for the propagation of the Vaishnava faith. Statement 3 is incorrect: It is based on the songs composed by Sankaradeva and Madhvadeva not Tulsidas, Kabir and Mirabai.","PW-2511":"Ans: B Exp: Mega Food Park Scheme 2008-09: It was introduced in 2008–09 with the goal of significantly boosting the food processing industry by increasing value and lowering food waste at every point in the supply chain, with a focus on perishables. The Mega Food Park Scheme is being carried out in the nation by the Ministry of Food Processing Industries. (Hence, statement 2 is correct.) Through a cluster-based approach, mega food parks build cutting-edge infrastructure facilities for food processing along the value chain from farm to market with strong forward and backward connections. Aim: To provide a method for connecting agricultural production to the market by bringing together producers, processors, and retailers in order to maximise value addition, reduce wastage, boost farmers' incomes, and create jobs, particularly in the rural sector. (Hence, statement 1 is correct) Approach: The \"Cluster\" approach-based Scheme plans to build state-of-the-art support infrastructure in a clearly defined agri/horticultural zone to facilitate the establishment of contemporary food processing units on the industrial plots offered in the park with a well-established supply chain. There are no provisions for providing emerging and eco-friendly food processing technologies to entrepreneurs. (Hence, statement 3 is incorrect)","PW-2512":"Sangam literature, composed between 300 BCE and 300 CE, is a collection of Tamil poems reflecting ancient South Indian society, culture, and politics. It was composed by poets at the Sangam councils held in Madurai and include contributions from poets like Agastya, Kapilar, and Nakkirar. The literature is divided into Eighteen Greater and Ten Lesser Anthologies, covering themes of love (akam), valor (puram), and ethics. Key texts include Tolkappiyam (grammar), Purananuru (heroic poetry), and Akananuru (love poetry), offering insights into the region’s political, social, and religious life. The two major Tamil epics, Silappathikaram and Manimekalai, are cornerstones of Tamil literature and reflect the cultural and spiritual life of ancient Tamil society Option (b) is correct: Sangam literature does make references to the social classification of Varna, which was a system of social classification in ancient India based on occupation and birth. Sangam Literature provides valuable details about the Sangam society and polity.Social classification of varna was known to Sangam poets.There is mention of social classes like the Arashar (kings), Vaishiyar (traders), and Velalar (farmers). Option (a), (c) and (d) are incorrect: Sangam literature is rich in descriptions of material culture, including trade, agriculture, wealth, and urban life. Sangam literature contains numerous references to warrior ethics, valor, and the heroic code, especially in the context of battles and chieftains. Sangam literature often depicts magical forces and divine interventions as part of its worldview, consistent with the religious and cultural beliefs of the time.","PW-2513":"Option (b) is correct: Parishishta Parvan also called the Sthaviravali Charita. It was written by Hemachandra (12th century CE). It is a Jain historical text that provides biographies of Jain monks and rulers who supported Jainism. It contains details about Chandragupta Maurya's conversion to Jainism under the guidance of Bhadrabahu. Trishashtilakshana Mahapurana is a Jain Purana written by Hemachandra in the 12th century CE. It details the lives of 63 great Jain figures (Shalaka Purushas), including the 24 Tirthankaras, 12 Chakravartins, 9 Vasudevas, 9 Balabhadras, and 9 Prati-Vasudevas. Additional Information : Nettipakarana (The Guidebook) is an ancient Pali Buddhist It is part of the Khuddaka Nikaya of the Pali Canon and serves as a guide for interpreting Buddhist teachings. Avadanasataka(Century of Noble Deeds) is a Buddhist text written in It is a collection of Buddhist legends and moral stories, emphasizing karmic consequences and rebirth.","PW-2514":"Vatakkiruttal, also known as Vadakiruthal or Vadakiruttal, was particularly prevalent during the Sangam period (3rd century BCE to 2nd Century CE). Tamil Kings, in a bid to uphold their honor and prestige, were willing to face death by fasting, a practice known as “Vatakkiruttal.”","PW-2515":"Pair 1 is incorrectly matched: Devichandragupta is a Sanskrit play attributed to Vishakhadatta, not Bilhana. The play is based on the historical events surrounding the Gupta king Chandragupta II and his queen Dhruvadevi. Vishakhadatta also authored Mudrarakshasa. Bilhana was an 11th-century Kashmiri poet known for his works like Vikramankadevacharita (a biography of the Chalukya king Vikramaditya VI) and Chaurapanchasika (a collection of love poems). Pair 2 is correctly matched: Hammira- Mahakavya is a Sanskrit epic poem written by Nayachandra Suri, a Jain scholar. The text narrates the life and exploits of Hammira, a 13th-century Chauhan king of Ranthambor and his resistance against the Delhi Sultanate. Pair 3 is incorrectly matched: Milinda- panha (Questions of King Milinda) is a Buddhist text that records a dialogue between the Indo-Greek king Menander I (Milinda) and the Buddhist monk Nagasena. The text is attributed to Nagasena, not Nagarjuna. Nagarjuna was a 2nd-century CE philosopher and founder of the Madhyamaka school of Mahayana Buddhism and is known for works like Mulamadhyamakakarika. Pair 4 is correctly matched: Nitivakyamrita is a treatise on ethics and polity written by Somadeva Suri, a 10th-century Jain scholar. The text provides guidance on governance, morality, and statecraft, reflecting the Jain emphasis on non-violence and ethical conduct.","PW-2516":"Musical tradition in North-West India. Manganiyars: The community of people called Manganiyars is well-known for their musical tradition in North-West India. They are a Muslim community of hereditary musicians who live in the desert regions of Rajasthan and parts of Pakistan. They, along with the Langa community, are known for their folk music. They have been professional musicians for generations supported by wealthy landlords of the area. Extra Edge: Pietra Dura is the art of carving the stone from a general point of view. This is an Inlay technique. The words “Pietra dura” come from Italian, it means “hard stone”, but also “semi-precious stone”. Nur Jahan built the tomb of Itimaddaulah at Agra. It was constructed wholly of white marble with floral designs made of semi-precious stones on the walls. This type of decoration was called pietra dura. This method became more popular during the reign of Shah Jahan. The pietra dura method was used on a large scale in the Taj Mahal by Shah Jahan.","PW-2517":"Sankirtana is a Meitei cultural performance art which includes a wide range of artistic expressions carried out to commemorate special religious occasions and different phases in the lives of the Vaishnava people of the Manipur plains. Sankirtana rituals are centered around temples and domestic spaces, where dancers and singers narrate stories of Lord Krishna’s life and actions through dance and song. In 2013, UNESCO added Manipur’s distinctive cultural legacy to its Representative List of Intangible Cultural Heritage of Humanity. Statement 1 is correct: Manipuri Sankirtana is a vibrant combination of song and dance. It is a form of devotional performance that involves singing, drumming, and dancing, often performed in a circular formation. The performers sing hymns and devotional songs, accompanied by rhythmic movements and drumming. Statement 2 is incorrect: While cymbals (kartal) are an essential part of Manipuri Sankirtana but they are not the only instruments used. The primary instrument in Sankirtana is the Pung, a traditional Manipuri drum. Other instruments such as the | | UPSC harmonium and flute may also be used in some performances. Statement 3 is correct: Manipuri Sankirtana is deeply connected to the Vaishnavite tradition and its themes often revolve around the life and deeds of Lord Krishna. The lyrics of the songs are usually devotional praising Krishna and recounting episodes from his life such as his childhood exploits (Bal Leela) and his divine love for Radha.","PW-2518":"Carnatic music is a classical music tradition of South India, characterized by its intricate ragas (melodies) and talas (rhythms), with a strong emphasis on vocal performance and improvisation. Prominent early singers include Muthuswami Dikshitar, Syama Sastri, and Tyagaraja, who significantly contributed to its development through their compositions and performances. Statement 1 is incorrect: Tyagaraja is known for his devotional songs (Kritis) to Lord Rama and not Lord Krishna. Statement 2 is correct: He innovated the technique of structural variations of musical lines and created new Ragas. Statement 3 is incorrect: Annamacharya belonged to the 15th century whereas Tyagaraja belonged to the 18th century and so they are non-contemporary. Statement 4 is correct: Annamacharya is renowned for his keertanas (devotional songs), most of which are dedicated to Lord Venkateshwara, the deity of the Tirumala Venkateswara Temple in Tirupati.","PW-2519":"Ans: A Exp: Indian folk paintings are traditional art forms rooted in local culture, depicting daily life, nature, and religious themes using vibrant colors and symbolic motifs. Examples include Madhubani from Bihar, known for its intricate patterns and mythological themes, Warli art from Maharashtra, which features tribal life and nature, and Pattachitra from Odisha. Option (a) is correct: Kalamkari cotton textile is made in Andhra Pradesh and Telangana and is either hand-painted or block- printed. The kalam (pen) is used for freehand drawing of the subject and filling in the colors is entirely done by hand. Kalamkari was first used to depict scenes from sacred texts such as the Mahabharata, Ramayana and Bhagavatam. It is practiced in two distinct styles: Srikalahasti (freehand drawing) and Machilipatnam (block-printing). The Srikalahasti style is more intricate and involves hand-painting while the Machilipatnam style uses wooden blocks for printing. Artists use natural dyes derived from plants, minerals, and other organic sources. The process involves multiple steps including dyeing, washing, and painting.","PW-2520":"Ans: A Exp: Bodhisattva Padmapani The painting of Bodhisattva Padmapani is in Ajanta cave no.1, which dates back to the 5th century AD. Other paintings of Bodhisattvas include Vajrapani (protector and guide, a symbol of Buddha’s power) and Manjusri (manifestation of Buddha’s wisdom). In this painting, Bodhisattva is holding a lotus in his hand in a tribhanga pose.","PW-2521":"Ans: A Exp: About the Somnath Temple: Somnath Temple is one of the most sacred pilgrimage sites for the Hindus, they believe it to be the first among the twelve Jyotirlinga shrines of Shiva. (Statement 1 is correct) Somnath is a magnificent temple situated in Sagar Kant of Saurashtra in Gujarat state. A description of the temple by Al-Biruni, an Arab traveler, was so glowing that it prompted a visit in 1024 by Mahmud of Ghazni. (Statement 2 is correct) During the reign of Bhima I (the Solanki Rajput King), Mahmud of Ghazni overran Gujarat and plundered Somnath in 1025 CE. The contemporary Somnath temple's reconstruction was started under the orders of the first Home Minister of India Vallabhbhai Patel and completed in May 1951 after his death. Then President of India, Dr. Rajendra Prasad, did the Pran-Pratistha at the existing temple on 11 May 1951. (Statement 3 is incorrect)","PW-2522":"Ans: C Exp: Statement 1 is correct: Vijayalaya, founded the Imperial Chola dynasty. He took advantage of a war between the Pandya and Pallava dynasties in c. 850 to seize Thanjavur from Muttarayar and create the imperial line of the medieval Chola Dynasty. Rajendra Chola I succeeded his father Rajaraja Chola I to the throne in 1014 CE. He is considered as one of the greatest emperors of India and he defeated the Chera and Pandya dynasty and established his domination in Southern India. Statement 2 is correct: Rajaraja I, one of the greatest Chola rulers, led a naval expedition against the Shailendra Empire (Malaya Peninsula). In 1025 CE, Rajendra led Chola forces across the Indian Ocean and invaded Srivijaya, attacking several places in Malaysia and Indonesia. The Chola forces captured the last ruler of the Sailendra Dynasty Sangrama Vijayatunggavarman. The Chola invasion was the end of Srivijaya.","PW-2523":"Ans: C Exp: Effects of Decreased Interest Rates on Money Supply and Investment Expenditure: A decrease in interest rates within an economy tends to prompt individuals to deposit less money in banks due to lower returns, while also encouraging increased borrowing at more favorable rates. Consequently, this dynamic leads to a rise in the overall money supply. This influx of available funds facilitates greater investment expenditure. Lower interest rates provide banks with increased flexibility to extend loans to both businesses and consumers, enabling the purchase of household goods and investment in productive ventures. (Hence, Option C is correct)","PW-2524":"Ans: A Exp: Statement 1 is correct: When a company funds are used to acquire, upgrade, and maintain physical assets such as property, plants, buildings, technology, or equipment are known as Capital Expenditure (CapEx) of a Company. When a company borrows money to be paid back at a future date with interest it is known as debt financing. Example: Repayment of a loan is an example of capital expenditure. Statement 2 is incorrect: Equity financing is the process of raising capital through the sale of shares. It is an example of non-debt capital receipts. Capital receipts are receipts that create liabilities or reduce financial assets. They also refer to incoming cash flows. Examples: Recovery of loans and advances, disinvestment, issue of bonus shares, etc.","PW-2525":"Ans: D Exp: Kalaripayattu is an ancient martial art form which originated in Kerala, a state in the southern part of India. Its name derives from the Malayalam words \"Kalari,\" meaning training ground or battlefield and \"Payattu,\" meaning practice or fight. This martial art is renowned for its comprehensive training regimen which includes strikes, kicks, grappling, weaponry, healing methods, and meditation. Practitioners begin their training with an oil massage to enhance body agility and suppleness. The art also emphasizes knowledge of \"Marmas\" or vital points by integrating traditional healing practices into its system. Mar tial Art Ori gin Key Features Weapons/ Technique s Kala ripa yatt u Ker ala Comprehensive system of strikes, kicks, grappling, and weaponry; includes healing practices. Sticks, swords, daggers, flexible swords, barehande d techniques; marma points. Sila mba m Ta mil Nad u Weapon-based art focused on the use of the bamboo staff (Silambam stick); emphasizes fluid movements and footwork. Bamboo staff, swords, daggers, various other weapons. Gat ka Pun jab Sikh martial art centered on armed combat, especially with swords and sticks; strong spiritual component. Swords, sticks (lathi), shields. Tha ng- Ta Ma nip ur Combines armed and unarmed combat; features sword and spear techniques and hand-to-hand fighting Swords, spears, daggers, shields. Mar dani Khel Ma har asht ra Primarily a weapon-based art, with a focus on sword skills; historically used by Maratha warriors. Swords, shields, spears, daggers. Mall akh amb Ma dhy a Gymnastic sport and martial art; Vertical pole, rope. | | UPSC Pra des h involves performing aerial yoga postures and holds on a vertical pole or rope.","PW-2526":"Ans: A Exp: \"Ranyo Ashoka\" refers to a relief sculpture at the Kanaganahalli Buddhist site near Sannati, Karnataka, that features a portrait of Emperor Ashoka along with the inscribed title \"Rāya Asoko\" in Brahmi script. This discovery is significant as it provides the first- ever stone portrait of Ashoka, identifying him as the subject of the relief, which also depicts him with his queens and attendants.","PW-2527":"Ans: A Exp: Option (a) is correct: Ashoka through his Policy of Dhamma insisted that all religions should co-exist and the ascetics of all religions were honoured. The principles of Dhamma were so formulated as to be acceptable to people belonging to different communities and following any religious sect. Dhamma was not given any formal definition or structure. It emphasised on toleration and general behaviour. Dhamma stressed on dual toleration-it emphasised on toleration of people themselves and also an toleration of their various beliefs and ideas. As per the Major Rock Edict VII and XII, Ashoka insisted that all religions should co-exist and the ascetics of all religions were honoured. His Major Rock Edict VII is a plea for toleration amongst all the sects. It appears from the edict that tensions among the sects were expressed intensely, perhaps in open antagonism. The plea is part of the overall strategy to maintain unity. Ashoka’s Major Rock Edict XII is again an appeal towards toleration among sects. This edict reflects the anxiety the king felt due to the conflict between sects and carries his plea for harmony.","PW-2528":"Ans: B Exp: The Arthashastra, attributed to Kautilya (Chanakya), is an ancient Indian treatise on statecraft, economic policy, and military strategy. It offers detailed guidance on governance, law, diplomacy, and administration, making it one of the earliest works of political science. Statement 1 is incorrect: While Arthashastra mentions slavery in the context of debt and war, it does not explicitly mention enslavement purely as a judicial punishment. Slavery could result from non-payment of debt, voluntary enslavement, or war, but not directly as a punishment for a crime. Statement 2 is correct: The Arthashastra states that if a female slave gave birth to a son by her master, she would be granted her freedom. This was a provision that allowed the slave woman to be liberated from servitude upon giving birth to the master’s child, likely due to the importance of lineage and inheritance. Statement 3 is correct: The Arthashastra states that if a master fathered a child with a slave woman, the child would inherit the legal status of the master’s son, rights, and property, recognising their connection as legitimate.","PW-2529":"Ans: C Exp: Jahandar Shah was the ninth Mughal Emperor who ruled for a brief period from 1712–1713. With the help of Zulfikar Khan, he became the emperor, and therefore, Zulfikar Khan was appointed prime minister; Jahandar Shah introduced izara system to improve the financial condition of the empire. He also abolished Jaziya. However, Jahandar Shah’s inglorious reign came to an early end in January 1713 when he was defeated at Agra by Farrukh Siyar, his nephew.","PW-2530":"In the medieval era, feudalism was the predominant socio-economic structure. Statement 1 is incorrect: As a political principle of organization that divided the power of lords, feudalism laid the foundations for a decentralization of political power, wherein the nobility owned land from the Crown in return for military service, and vassals were tenants of the nobles. The peasants were required to reside on their lord’s land and to offer him homage, labor, and a share of the production in exchange for military protection. Statement 2 is correct: In a feudal system, land is the main economic resource, and it is the key to political power and authority. The feudal system is built around the concept of land ownership, where lords or landholders control vast estates and manage them with | | UPSC the help of vassals, peasants, or serfs. Land is granted in exchange for military service, loyalty, or other obligations, forming the basis for the entire administrative and economic structure. Statement 3 is correct: One of the key features of the feudal system is the lord-vassal relationship, which forms the backbone of feudal society. A vassal is granted land (a fief) by a lord in return for military service, loyalty, and other obligations. This relationship is often hierarchical, with the vassal owing loyalty and service to a superior lord, who in turn may be a vassal to a higher lord or the king. The lord-vassal relationship is not just a social contract but a legal one, with specific duties and rights that define the relationship between the two parties.","PW-2531":"Statement 1 is incorrect: Jagirdars were granted land assignments (known as jagir) in return for military, administrative, or service- related duties. Zamindars, on the other hand have the primary role of revenue collection. But in many cases, especially during the Mughal period, Zamindars were also responsible for maintaining law and order in their regions, depending on the specific region and the emperor's policies. Statement 2 is incorrect: Jagirdars did not necessarily hold hereditary land assignments. The jagir was often granted for services rendered. The emperor could change or revoke these assignments as needed, which means the jagir was not hereditary in the strict sense. Zamindars, however, typically held hereditary rights over the lands they controlled. The right to collect revenue from their land passed down through generations, making their position mostly hereditary in nature.","PW-2532":"Raja Ram Chandra of Bandavagarh employed Tansen as a court musician at his darbar (Rewa). After learning of Tansen’s extraordinary talent, Akbar wrote the king of Rewa a \"Farman\" requesting Tansen and appointed him as one of the Navaratnas in his court. He bestowed upon him the name “Mian.” Option (a) is correct: Tansen was the title given to him by Raja Vikramjit of Gwalior. Tansen composed various dhrupads on Rama, Parvati, Shiva, and Ganesha. A compilation of 300 of his dhrupad that were in Gauhar Bani is called Kalpadruma. Tansen composed his favorite ragas- Multani, Bhairavi and Todi. He created the ragas Darbari Kanhra for the night, Mian Ki Todi for the morning, Mian ki Sarang for the midday, and Mian ki Malhar for the season. He composed numerous songs for his patrons.","PW-2533":"Ans: D Exp: The holder of the land was termed Zamindar. They have hereditary rights over the land. The primary responsibility of zamindars was to collect revenue and deposit it in the royal treasury. Law and order were another duty imposed on zamindars in their jurisdictions. The local zamindars handled the police and judicial duties. The Jagirdari system, the system of assignment of revenue of a particular territory to the nobles for their services to the state was an integral part of the Mansabdari system. A jagir did not confer any hereditary rights on the holder, or disturb any of the existing rights in the area. It only meant that the land revenue due to the state was to be paid to the jagirdar. Hence, both the statements I and II are incorrect.","PW-2534":"Hundis are used as a form of remittance instrument to transfer money from place to place. It was used as a form of credit instrument or IOU to borrow money and as a bill of exchange in trade transactions. The Hundis was a letter of credit payable after a period of time. The word \"hundi\" is often linked to the Sanskrit root \"hundika,\" meaning a type of bill or note. The Lekhapaddhati (12th century, in post-Hrasha period) refer to the use of hundika by kings and nobles to make payments but it may have been used by merchants as well. Hundis were widely used during the post-Harsha period (7th century onwards) and played a significant role in the growth of trade and urbanization in India.","PW-2535":"In order to organise his kingdom for better administration and taxation, Akbar adopted Sher Shah’s methods and principles. The Mughal administration was organized into “Subas,” which were further subdivided into “Gram,” “Pargana,” and “Sarkar.” Under Akbar’s reign, there were approximately 15 Subas, while the number increased to nearly 20 during Aurangzeb’s rule. Option (a) is correct: The correct order according to the size is: Pargana -Sarkar- Suba. The entire Suba was split into Sarkars (districts), with a military commander known as the chief Shiqdar in charge of each one. Each Sarkar was divided into smaller units called Parganas. Each Pargana had two Karkuns (clerks or writers), one Fotahdar (treasurer), one Shiqdar (military officer), one Amin or Munsif (civilian judge).","PW-2536":"Ans. (c) Exp: The Santhal Rebellion (1855-56) in the Rajmahal Hills was sparked by the oppression of revenue officials, police, moneylenders, and landlords (referred to as “dikus” by the Santhals). Led by Sido and Kanhu, the Santhals revolted, declaring independence from the British. The rebellion was suppressed by 1856 after extensive military action. Statement (1) is correct: After the Santhal Uprising (1855– 56), the British created the Santhal Parganas in 1855 by carving out areas from Bhagalpur and Birbhum districts to provide the Santhals with a separate administrative region. Statement (2) is correct: The British introduced legal restrictions on land transfers, making it illegal for a Santhal to transfer land to a non-Santhal. This was done to prevent exploitation by moneylenders (Mahajans) and landlords (Zamindars), which had been a major cause of the rebellion.","PW-2537":"Ans: B Exp: Statement 1 is incorrect: Buddhism professed a middle path, and avoidance of extremities of penance and enjoyment whereas Jainism advocated extreme penance and asceticism. Statements 2 and 3 are correct: Buddhism and Jainism rejected the idea of grand rituals along with the authority of Vedas and Priests. They both believe in the concept of reincarnation. Extra Edge: Similarities between Buddhism and Jainism: Both were influenced by the Upanishads’ ideology as well as that of other Hindu religious groups. For instance, salvation is the ultimate aim of life. Both groups welcomed members from various social classes while also catering to the socially outcast. Both believed that Nirvana, or salvation, frees one from the cycle of perpetual birth and death. Both placed more emphasis on moral principles than on engaging in ritualistic behaviour or paying homage to and worshiping God.","PW-2538":"Ans: B Exp: Statement 1 is incorrect. Samkhya philosophy believes in the theory of rebirth. Samkhya is an Orthodox Indian philosophical system. Orthodox Indian philosophical system believes in soul and karma theory. For Karma theory to hold, the soul has to undergo rebirth or transmigration. Therefore, without liberation, no soul can be free from the cycle of rebirth or transmigration. Statement 2 is correct: Samkhya Philosophy is dualistic and not monistic because it has two entities, Purush (spirit) and Prakriti (nature). Samkhya emphasizes the attainment of knowledge of the self by means of concentration and meditation. It believes that after you have ‘died’ in this life you will go through a process of rebirth where depending on your actions in your former life your status will be decided.","PW-2539":"1, 2 and 3 Jainism advocates the practice of penance as the surest way of annihilating Karma. According to Jainism, every object, including the smallest particle, has a soul. Karma is considered the bane of the soul and must be ended to achieve liberation. As per Jain doctrine, the surest way of annihilating Karma is to practice penance. Everything has a soul, even the smallest particle. (Hence, Option 1 and 2 are correct) Karma is the bane of the soul and must be ended. (Option 3 is correct) Three Jewels of Jainism are Right Faith, Right knowledge Right Action. Five doctrines of Jainism are - 1. Ahimsa: Non-injury to all living beings; 2. Satya: Do not speak a lie; 3. Asteya: Do not steal; 4. Aparigraha: Do not acquire property; 5. Brahmacharya: Observe continence.","PW-2540":"Ans: A Exp: Buddhism defines Nirvana as being free from desire, pain, pleasure etc. It is like the extinction of flame. In Buddhist traditions, nirvana is often described as the extinction of three fires- greed (raga), aversion (dwesha) and ignorance (moksha). When these flames are extinguished, the cycle of rebirth is skipped.","PW-2541":"Ans: C Lokayata and Kapalika are not part of these six systems. Lokayata refers to the materialist school of thought that originated in ancient India, while Kapalika is a tantric sect that emerged in the medieval period.","PW-2542":"2 only Statement 1 is not correct. Sautrantika and Sammitiya were the sects of Buddhism. Statement 2 is correct. Sarvastivadin considers everything empirical to be impermanent, they maintain that the dharma factors are eternally existing realities. Sarvastivad in ➢ Believes in the eternal existence of dharma factors. ➢ Considers empirical phenomena as illusory but exist beyond the empirical world. ➢ Affirms the presence of past, present, and future. ➢ Criticized by Sautrantikas for violating the Buddhist idea of impermanence. Sautrantika ➢ Descended from the Sarvastivadins | | UPSC ➢ Relies on sutras rather than Abhidharma commentaries. ➢ Adheres to extreme momentariness, believing only the current moment exists. ➢ Criticizes Sarvastivadin’s belief in the existence of past, present, and future phenomena. Sammitiya and other sub-schools ➢ Branches off from Vatsiputriya, a parent school. ➢ Well-known in Gujarat and Sindh during the Maitraka dynasty. ➢ Speaks Apabhraṃśa as their primary language. ➢ Replaced Sarvastivadins as Sarnath’s most illustrious institution by the 4th century CE. ➢ Split into two sub- schools: Avantakas and Kurukulas.","PW-2543":"Jainism The “Sthanakvasi” sect belongs to Jainism. It is a branch of Svetambara Jainism that was started in 1653 AD by a merchant named Lavaji. It holds that the path to soul purification and achieving Nirvana/Moksha does not include idol worship.","PW-2544":"Ans: C Exp: Maitreya, in Buddhist tradition, is the future Buddha, presently a bodhisattva residing in the Tushita heaven. He will descend to earth to preach dharma (“law”) when the teachings of Gautama Buddha have completely decayed. Since Maitreya is currently waiting to enter the world, he is usually depicted sitting and waiting.","PW-2545":"Maitreya Maitreya is a future Buddha, yet to come to save the world. According to Buddhist tradition, Maitreya is a Bodhisattva who will appear on earth in future, attain enlightenment and teach pure dharma. He will be the future Buddha. He is also known as Ajit Bodhisattva (Amitabha sutra and Lotus sutra).Whereas, Avalokiteshvara (“The Lord Who Looks Down”), also called Padmapani (“The Lotus-Bearer”) also called Lokesvara in Sanskrit (The Lord of the World).","PW-2546":"Option (c) is correct: Paramitas are qualities to be perfected in order to attain a state of self enlightened Universal Buddha (a samma sambuddha) a term prevalent in Eastern and Northern Buddhist traditions. Paramitas These are qualities to be perfected in order to transcend into a self enlightened Universal Buddha . Here, The Fourth Noble Truth outlines the Eightfold Path, which is a practical guideline for attaining the cessation of suffering (nirvana), while the Ten Paramitas focus more on the qualities required of a Bodhisattva, both paths lead toward enlightenment. Following are the Ten Paramitas: Generosity, Morality, Patience, Energy, Meditation, Wisdom, Skillful means, Resolution, Power, Knowledge.","PW-2547":"Buddhism has evolved into various sects and subsects over time due to doctrinal disagreements, geographical spread,and cultural influences. 1. Early Schisms (3rd Century BC): After the Buddha’s death, disagreements arose over the interpretation of his teachings. The first major split occurred at the Council of Rajagriha (circa 5th century BCE), dividing followers into two groups: the Sthaviravada (Elder’s teaching) and the Mahasanghika (Great Assembly). The Sthaviravada later became associated with what was called Hinayana (the “Lesser Vehicle”), while the Mahasanghika became the precursor to the later Mahayana 2. Hinayana vs. Mahayana: The term Hinayana was used by Mahayana Buddhists to describe the earlier schools that focused on | | UPSC personal enlightenment (through arhatship) and adhered to the teachings of the Pali Canon. These schools, such as the Sthaviravada and others, were seen by Mahayana as “lesser” because they were perceived as focusing more narrowly on individual salvation, as opposed to the Bodhisattva path of universal liberation central to Mahayana However, the use of the term Hinayana is now considered derogatory, and modern practitioners of these traditions prefer to call them Theravada or other specific sect names. 3. Mahayana Emergence (1st Century BC- 1st Century AD): Over the centuries, the Mahasanghika sect developed the belief that the Buddha was a transcendent and divine This belief in the supernatural Buddha was a key idea that led to the rise of Mahayana Buddhism, which emphasized the Bodhisattva ideal — the aspiration to become a Buddha for the benefit of all sentient beings. Mahayana also expanded the notion of the Buddha beyond a historical figure, viewing him as a cosmic, eternal presence. 4. Development of Sub-sects: Within both Hinayana (Theravada) and Mahayana, multiple sub-sects arose over time: In Hinayana (or Theravada) Buddhism, the main focus was on monastic discipline and individual The tradition spread primarily to Sri Lanka, Thailand, Burma, and Cambodia. In Mahayana, further divisions occurred, such as the Lokottaravadins, who viewed the Buddha as supernatural, and later schools like Zen, Pure Land, and Tibetan Buddhism emerged, each with distinct practices and philosophies. 5. Vajrayana and Tibetan Buddhism (6th Century AD onward): The Vajrayana school, also known as Tantric Buddhism, emerged in India and later flourished in Tibet, incorporating esoteric practices and rituals aimed at attaining enlightenment more swiftly. Statement 1 is incorrect: The Sthaviravadins were an early Buddhist sect that later became associated with Theravada Buddhism, not Mahayana. Statement 2 is correct: Mahasanghika was further subdivided into several sects including Lokottarvadin, Kavya Variks, Kaukkitikas in coming years. Lokottarvadin was based on the philosophy of Lokottar Buddha or Supernatural Buddha. Statement 3 is correct: The deification of Buddha by Mahasanghika fostered Mahayana Buddhism. They attributed divinity to Buddha and worship of Buddha in Statue form started which is still prevalent in modern days.","PW-2548":"Answer: B Pair 1 is correctly matched: The Sanskrit word Parivrajaka means renunciant & wanderer in English. Ajita Keshkambalin, Makhkhali Goshala, Gauthama Buddha, and Vardhamana Mahavira are a few well-known examples for Parivrajaka. Pair 2 is not correctly matched: Brahmins were privileged as intermediaries between God and its followers, making them socially dominant groups of the society. There have been many movements that tried to distance themselves from this practice and belief. Shramanas were one such group. Famous among them were Buddhists, Jains, lokayats, and Ajivikas. The Shramanas included a variety of ascetics, monks, and lay followers of various sects. They renounced worldly life to search for the truth about life and the universe. The main feature of Shramana was their equal treatment. They lived as an equal member of the order, without any caste distinctions. Pair 3 is correctly matched: Lay followers of Buddhism were known as Upsakas or Upasikas. This title is used for the followers of Buddhism who were not monks, or nuns and took certain vows.","PW-2549":"In ancient Indian Non-Vedic religious traditions like Buddhism and Jainism, distinct roles and terminologies were used to describe various types of spiritual practitioners and followers such as Parivrajaka, Shramana and Upasaka. Pair 1 is correctly matched: The Sanskrit word Parivrajaka means renunciant & wanderer in English. Ajita Keshkambalin, Makhkhali Goshala, Gauthama Buddha, and Vardhamana Mahavira are a few well-known examples for Parivrajaka. Pair 2 is incorrectly matched: Brahmins were privileged as intermediaries between God and its followers, making them socially dominant groups of the society. There have been many movements that tried to distance themselves from this practice and belief. Shramanas were one such group. Famous among them were Buddhists, Jains, lokayats, and The Shramanas included a variety of ascetics, monks and lay followers of various sects. They renounced worldly life to search for the truth about life and the The main feature of Shramana was their equal treatment. They lived as an equal member of the order, without any caste distinctions. Pair 3 is correct: Lay followers of Buddhism were known as Upsakas or Upasikas. This title is used for the followers of Buddhism who were not monks, nuns and took certain vows.","PW-2550":"Option (c) is correct: Āryadeva was a Mahayana Buddhist monk, a disciple of Nagarjuna and a Madhyamaka His key work \"Catuḥśataka\" (Four Hundred Verses) elaborates on Madhyamaka philosophy. His writings are important sources of Madhyamaka in both East Asian Buddhism and Tibetan Buddhism. Dignaga, a Buddhist logician and author of the Pramāṇasamuccaya (Compendium of the Means of Valid Knowledge) laid the foundations of Buddhist logic. Additional Information : Nathamuni (9th–10th century CE) was a Vaishnavite scholar and theologian. He is credited with compiling the Nalayira Divya Prabandham, a collection of hymns by Tamil Alvars, which became a foundational text in Sri Vaishnavism. He was also the guru of Yamunacharya and predecessor of Ramanuja in the Vishishtadvaita tradition.","PW-2551":"Sri Ramanujacharya was born in 1017 AD in Tamil Nadu. He is the most respected Acharya in the philosophy of Sri Vaishnavism. Ramanuja was deeply influenced by the Alvars. Option (a) is correct: Shri Ramanujacharya firmly believed that intense devotion to Vishnu was the best means to attain salvation. He is famous as the chief proponent of Vishishtadvaita subschool of Vedānta. Vishishtadvaita is a non-dualistic school of Vedanta philosophy in which Brahman alone exists, but is characterized by multiplicity. He was also referred to as Ilaya Perumal, which means the radiant one. His works such as Vedartha-Sangraha, the Sribhasya and the Bhagavad Gita-bhashya aimed at providing a philosophical foundation for devotional worship.","PW-2552":"Only two pairs Pair 1 is not correctly matched: Āryadeva was a Mahayana Buddhist monk, a disciple of Nagarjuna and a Madhyamaka philosopher. After Nagarjuna, he is considered to be the next most important figure of the Indian Madhyamaka school. His writings are important sources of Madhyamaka in both East Asian Buddhism and in Tibetan Buddhism. Āryadeva is also known as Kanadeva, recognized as the 15th patriarch in Chan Buddhism and some Sinhalese sources also mention an elder (thera) called Deva which may also be the same person. He is known for his association with the Nalanda monastery in modern-day Bihar, India. Pair 2 is correctly matched: Dignāga, Buddhist logician and author of the Pramāṇasamuccaya (“Compendium of the Means of True Knowledge”), a work that laid the foundations of Buddhist logic. Dignāga gave a new definition of “perception”: knowledge that is free from all conceptual constructions, including name and class concepts. Dignāga’s tradition was further developed in the 7th century by Dharmakīrti. Pair 3 correctly matched: Sri Ranganathamuni, popularly known as Sriman Nathamuni (823 CE–951 CE), was a Vaishnava theologian who collected and compiled the Nalayira Divya Prabandham. Considered the first of Sri Vaishnava āchāryās, Nathamuni is also the author of Yogarahasya and Nyāyatattva.","PW-2553":"Option (b) is correct : The core principle of Jainism revolves around non-violence, with no other religion placing as great an emphasis on this value. Jains hold the belief that souls inhabit plants, animals, and even certain non- living entities such as air and water, similar to humans. The doctrine of non-violence encompasses refraining from causing harm to humans, plants, animals, and the natural world.","PW-2554":"Option (b) is correct : Shakyamuni epithet is widely used in Buddhist texts such as the Lalitavistara Sutra and Mahayana scriptures for Gautama Buddha \"Shakyamuni\" means \"Sage of the Shakya Clan.\" Gautama Buddha was born as Prince Siddhartha in the Shakya clan which ruled the region of Kapilavastu (modern Nepal-India border). Tathagata means \"The One Who Has Thus Gone (Tatha- gata) or Thus Come (Tatha-agata),\" referring to Buddha's enlightened state and transcendence over worldly existence. It is one of the most common epithets used by Gautama Buddha himself in Pali Canon texts like the Digha Nikaya and Majjhima Nikaya. Additional Information : Nayaputta(Son of the Naya Clan) was a title used for Mahavira, the 24th Tirthankara of Jainism. The term Nayaputta is derived from \"Jnanaputra\", meaning \"Son of the Jnana Clan (Nyagrodha or Naya clan). He was born into the Naya clan of the Kshatriya community in Vaishali.","PW-2555":"Ans: C Exp: Option (c) is correct: Sanghabhuti was an Indian Buddhist monk from Kashmir who traveled to China towards the end of the 4th century AD. Sanghabhuti is primarily associated with the Sarvastivada Vinaya, a text that outlines the monastic rules and discipline for Buddhist monks and nuns. He traveled to China and collaborated with Chinese scholars to translate and comment on this text, which was crucial for the establishment of Buddhist monastic practices in China. Additional Information : Several Indian monks played pivotal roles in transmitting Buddhism to China, profoundly influencing Chinese religious and cultural landscapes. Here are some notable figures: Mon k Peri od Contributio ns Journey and Legacy Bodh idhar ma 5th– 6th Cent ury CE Founder of Chan (Zen) Buddhism in China. Associa ted with the Shaolin Monast ery. Credite d with introdu cing martial arts to Shaolin monks (as per legends ). Travele d from India to China. Meditat ed at the Shaolin Monast ery. Influen ced Zen practic es and martial arts. Kum ārajī va 344– 413 CE Renow ned translat or of Buddhi st texts from Born in Kucha (moder n day Xinjiang , China) to an | | UPSC Sanskri t to Chines e. Improv ed clarity and eleganc e in Buddhi st scriptur es. Indian father and Kuchea n mother . His translat ions signific antly shaped Chines e Buddhi sm. Dhar makṣ 385– 433 Mission ary, Reside d in ema CE scholar & translat or of key Buddhi st scriptur es into Chines e. Helped spread Buddhi st teachin gs in China. Dunhu ang, later moved to Northe rn Liang for translat ion work. Active during the 5th century in China.","PW-2556":"Between the 8th and 12th centuries AD, medieval India saw the rise of regional dynasties like the Chandelas, Paramaras, Gurjara-Pratiharas, and Rashtrakutas, which shaped the political, cultural, and architectural landscape after the decline of centralized powers like the Guptas and Harsha’s empire. Pair 1 is correctly matched: The Chandela dynasty was founded around the 9th century, and Nannuka is traditionally regarded as the founder. Chandela dominion extended from the Yamuna (Jumna) River in the north to the region of Saguar (now Sagar) and from the Dhasan River in the west to the Vindhya Hills. It was during Chandela rule that Khajuraho turned into a cultural and architectural hub. The Kandariya Mahadeva Temple stands as the pinnacle of Chandela architectural achievement. The Chandela dynasty is famous for constructing the Khajuraho temples, a UNESCO World Heritage Site. Nannuka established the dynasty in the early 9th century CE. Pair 2 is incorrectly matched: Vakpati’s sons Jayashakti (Jeja) and Vijayashakti (Vija) consolidated the Chandella power. Vakapati succeeded his father Nannuka of the Chandela dynasty and he was succeeded by Vijayshakti and Jayshakti. The Paramara dynasty was a prominent Rajput dynasty that ruled Malwa, with kings like Bhoja and Munja being its most famous rulers. Pair 3 is correctly matched: Vatsaraja was a Pratihara ruler who came to the throne in about 778 AD controlled eastern Rajasthan and Malava. Nagabhata II (reigned c. 793– 833) was his successor. He was defeated by the Rashtrakuta king Govinda III (reigned 793– 814). He ruled in the early 9th century CE and is known for his military campaigns against the Palas and Rashtrakutas. Pair 4 is incorrectly matched: Bhoja I / Mihir Bhoja (c.836−885 AD) was the successor of Nagabhatta II, who had a long reign of over 44-46 years and proved to be the most successful and popular ruler of Pratiharas. An Arab visitor to western India, the merchant Sulaymān, referred to the kingdom of Juzr (which is generally identified as Gurjara) and its strong and able ruler, who may have been Bhoja. The Rashtrakuta dynasty was a prominent power in the Deccan, with kings like Amoghavarsha and Krishna I.","PW-2557":"Ans: D Exp: Pair 1 is incorrectly matched: Burzahom had a well-developed bone tool industry. Other finds at Burzahom include pits and coarse pottery. Rock- cut shrines were not a feature of the Burzahom site. Pair 2 is correctly matched: Chandraketugarh is located in the Ganges delta in West Bengal. It was famous for terracotta art. It is connected to Ganga by the Vidyadhari River which makes it ideal for a flourishing trade centre. Pair 3 is correctly matched: Ganeshwar is located in the northeastern part of Rajasthan. Hundreds of copper artefacts have been found at this site which suggests it must have been a copper working centre.","PW-2558":"India’s historical sites highlight diverse peculiarities as Bhimbetka’s prehistoric rock art, Nalanda’s ancient university, Sanchi’s stupas, Dholavira’s urban planning, Pattadakal’s Chalukyan temples, and Khajuraho’s erotic sculptures, reflecting the subcontinent’s rich contributions to art, architecture, and education across areas. Pair 1 is incorrectly matched: Burzahom (Kashmir) had a well-developed bone tool industry. Other finds at Burzahom include pits and coarse pottery. Rock-cut shrines were not a feature of the Burzahom site. Pair 2 is correctly matched: Chandraketugarh is located in the Ganges delta in West Bengal. It is known for its rich collection of terracotta plaques and figurines that date back to the pre-Mauryan and Gupta periods. Pair 3 is correctly matched: Ganeshwar is located in the northeastern part of Rajasthan. Hundreds of copper artifacts have been found at this site which suggests it must have been a copper working center.","PW-2559":"Second Round Table Conference was held in London, between September 7, 1931 to December 1, 1931. The Indian National Congress nominated Gandhi as its sole representative. The Quit India Movement, launched by Mahatma Gandhi in August 1942, called for an immediate end to British rule in India. It was a mass civil disobedience movement, marked by protests, strikes, and widespread arrests. The Royal Navy Mutiny of 1946, also known as the Naval Uprising, involved Indian sailors protesting against harsh conditions, low wages, and discrimination in the British Royal Navy. The mutiny spread across several naval bases, becoming a significant part of the larger Indian independence movement.","PW-2560":"Ans: D Exp: About Indian federalism: The Indian Constitution adopts the federal system of Government but with more tilt towards a unitary system of government. So, every state government does not have power of its own. The term ‘Federation’ has nowhere been used in the Constitution. Article 1, on the other hand, describes India as a ‘Union of States’ which implies two things: one, Indian Federation is not the result of an agreement by the states; and two, no state has the right to secede from the federation. Thus, it is considered as a quasi-federal system. It contains all the usual features of a federation, viz., two governments, division of powers, written Constitution, the supremacy of Constitution, the rigidity of Constitution, independent judiciary and bicameralism.","PW-2561":"Pair 1 is correctly matched: Eripatti was a special kind of land donated by individuals. The revenue from it was set aside for the maintenance of tanks in the village. Pair 2 is incorrectly matched: During the Chola administration, occasionally a very large village would be administered as a single unit and this was called Taniyur. These villages were not necessarily just large administrative units but could also be village settlements that were either wholly or largely populated by Brahmins or associated with religious functions. Pair 3 is correctly matched: Ghatikas were educational institutions, often associated with temples, where learning took place. These colleges were centers for higher education, particularly in subjects like philosophy, logic, and religious studies. Additional Information: Here is a list of similar historical terms related to land revenue, administration, and education in ancient India: Term Description Brahm adeya Land grants given to Brahmins, often leading to the formation of Agrahara villages. Devad ana Land donated to temples for religious and charitable purposes. Vellanv agai Land held by non-Brahmin, peasant communities in the Chola administration. Pallich chanda Land grants given to Buddhist monasteries and Jaina m institutions. Salabh oga Land or revenue assigned for the maintenance of educational institutions. Agraha ra A village or settlement granted to Brahmins, often exempt from taxes. Ghatik a Educational institutions, often attached to temples, known for higher learning. Matha Hindu monasteries that functioned as centers of religious and educational activities. Vasti Residential settlements. Nagara m Towns or trade centers that played a significant role in urbanization.","PW-2562":"Option (c) is correct: Ishwar Chandra Vidyasagar (1820-1891) was appointed as the secretary of the governing body of Bethune School/College. The Bethune Female School, established in 1849 in Kolkata (then Calcutta) was one of the first schools in India dedicated to the education of girls. It was founded by John Elliot Drinkwater Bethune, a prominent social reformer and advocate for women's education in India. Vidyasagar was a strong advocate for women's rights and education, and his involvement with the Bethune School was part of his broader efforts to reform Indian society, including his campaigns for widow remarriage and the abolition of child marriage. It was mainly due to his efforts that the Hindu Widows’ Remarriage Act, 1856 was passed.","PW-2563":"Ans: A Exp: Pair 1 is correctly matched: Bhabar refers to a zone along the foothills of the Himalayas, primarily in northern India and parts of Pakistan. It is characterized by the deposition of a large number of pebbles and rock debris. The area may have a porous and stony surface due to the presence of these large fragments. Water from the rivers in this region often disappears underground due to the porous nature of the substrate. Pair 2 is incorrectly matched: Bhangar refers to the older alluvium found along the river beds, forming terraces that are higher than the floodplain. Over time, as rivers continue to deposit sediment, older layers of alluvium build up along the river banks, creating elevated terraces known as Bhangar. These terraces are remnants of previously active floodplains. Pair 3 is incorrectly matched: Khadar refers to the newer alluvium that forms the floodplains along the river banks. The deposition of fine particles, such as silt and clay, occurs during periodic flooding events. These events bring nutrient-rich sediment onto the floodplain, making Khadar soil highly fertile.","PW-2564":"Ans: D Exp: Statement 1 is incorrect: India has joined the exclusive club of nations with its own space observatory with the successful launch of ASTROSAT, joining the US, Japan, Russia, and Europe. Along with six other foreign satellites, ASTROSAT, India's first dedicated multi-wavelength space observatory, will aid in the knowledge of the cosmos. Statement 2 is incorrect: AstroSat is the first dedicated Indian astronomy mission aimed to study celestial sources in X-ray, optical and UV spectral bands. The payloads cover the energy bands of Ultraviolet (Near and Far), limited optical and X-ray regime (0.3 keV to 100keV). AstroSat with a liftoff mass of 1515 kg was launched on September 28, 2015 into a 650 km orbit inclined at an angle of 6 deg to the equator by PSLV-C30 from Satish Dhawan Space Centre, Sriharikota.","PW-2565":"The Congress Socialist Party (CSP) was a socialist faction within the Indian National Congress, established in 1934 by Congress members such as Acharya Narendra Dev, Jayaprakash Narayan and others. Statement 1 is incorrect: The CSP advocated decentralised socialism in which co-operatives, trade unions, independent farmers, and local authorities would hold a substantial share of the economic power. They did not promote the boycott of British goods or the evasion of taxes as a policy demand. Statement 2 is incorrect: Their focus was to attain independence and believed in socialism through nationalism and did not aim to establish the dictatorship of the proletariat. Statement 3 is incorrect: They were secularists and hoped to transcend communal divisions through class solidarity. Many people, like Narendra Deva and Basawon Singh (Sinha), favoured a democratic socialism that was separate from both reformist social democracy and Marxism. They did not support a separate electorate for minorities and oppressed classes.","PW-2566":"Statement 1 is incorrect: The Factory Act of 1881, passed during Lord Ripon’s tenure, aimed to improve working conditions in factories using mechanical power and employing at least 100 workers. It prohibited the employment of children under 7, limited children aged 7-12 to 9-hour workdays, and required dangerous machinery to be properly fenced. However, it did not address the formation of trade unions. Statement 2 is correct: Narayan Meghaji Lokhande (1848– 1897) is regarded as the father of the trade union movement in India. He worked to improve the conditions of textile mill workers and took courageous stands on caste and communal issues. He played a key role in reducing daily working hours from 16 to 10 hours in mills.","PW-2567":"Option (a) is correct: The Industrial Revolution in Britain led to the mass production of textiles and other goods in Britain, which flooded the Indian market. This caused a decline in demand for Indian handicrafts which could not compete with the cheaper, machine-made British goods. This led to the ruin of traditional handicraft industries and artisans. Machine-based production in Indian textiles became more prominent after the 1850s, with the establishment of British-wned factories like the Bombay Spinning and Weaving Mill (1854). The first railway line in India was opened in 1853 between Bombay and Thane. By the latter half of the 19th century, the railway network expanded rapidly to facilitate the movement of goods (especially raw materials for British industries). British goods were often imported into India without heavy duties. British colonial policy was designed to ensure that India served as a market for British manufactured goods.","PW-2568":"The Indus Valley Civilization was highly materialistic, with advanced urban infrastructure, standardized weights, and extensive trade networks. In contrast, the Rig Vedic Civilization had a more pastoral economy, focusing on cattle wealth and ritualistic offerings rather than large-scale material production or urban development. Statement 1 is correct: The Rigvedic Aryans are described in the Rigveda as using advanced weapons and armor, including coats of mail and helmets. In contrast, the Indus Valley Civilization shows no evidence of such organized military gear, suggesting a less militaristic society. Statement 2 is incorrect: The Rigvedic Aryans knew gold, silver, and copper, while the Indus Valley Civilization used copper and bronze, lacking iron. Iron technology emerged after the decline of the Indus Valley, during the later Vedic period. Statement 3 is correct: The horse seems to have been unknown to the inhabitants of Mohenjo-Daro and Harappa. Horse remains found at Surkotada, dating to around 2000 BCE, suggest the possibility of horses in the Indus Valley. However, Sándor Bökönyi’s analysis of bone fragments is inconclusive and does not definitively prove that the Indus people knew horses.","PW-2569":"Ans: C Exp: Vijayanagara Kingdom Vijayanagara or the “city of victory” empire was founded in the fourteenth century by Harihara and Bukka (1336). It encompassed the entire Krishna- Tungabhadra Doab peninsula, extending from the river Krishna in the north to its furthest southern point. In the memories of people living in the Hampi district of the Krishna Tungabhadra doab, they remembered it as Pampadevi, a name derived from that of the local mother goddess.","PW-2570":"Harihara I, along with his brother Bukka Raya I, laid the foundation for the city of Vijayanagara in 1336 on the south bank of the river Tungabhadra, a tributary to the river Krishna. Harihara I believed that the land south of the river Krishna belonged to the deity Virupaksha (a form of Lord Shiva). He undertook the responsibility of ruling the kingdom on behalf of this deity, considering himself as an agent of the deity. This reflects the deep religious and cultural connection to the land and the empire’s association with divine authority. The rulers of Vijayanagara were often referred to as the \"servants of Virupaksha\", showcasing their role as divine agents.","PW-2571":"Statement 1 is correct: Under the rule of Krishna Deva Raya (ruler of Vijayanagar empire), the taxation system was quite well- organized and efficient. The tax rate was fixed between one-third and one-sixth depending on the quality of the land. This method ensured that the tax burden was more equitable, as fertile land produced higher yields and therefore could bear a higher tax rate. Statement 2 is correct: Commercial taxes consisting of levies, duties and customs on manufactured articles of trade were also levied. Private owners of workshops also paid an industry tax. In addition to the land tax, there were taxes levied on shopkeepers, farm workers, farm servants, laborers, posters, shoemakers, musicians, etc. Grazing and house taxes were also imposed.","PW-2572":"2 only Statement 1 is not correct: The kingdom of Arcot, also known as the kingdom of Carnatic, was the monarchy that ruled over the majority of the eastern part of the present-day Tamil Nadu region throughout the eighteenth century. Statement 2 is correct: Under the Vijayanagar Empire, there was a small feudal kingdom called Mysore. The ruling Wodeyar dynasty declared their independence following the fall of Vijayanagar in 1565, and Raja Wodeyar ascended the throne in 1578. The capital moved from Mysore to Srirangapatna in 1610. Statement 3 is not correct: Ali Muhammad Khan established Rohilakhand, a small kingdom, by taking advantage of the breakdown of authority in North India following Nadir Shah's invasion.","PW-2573":"The accounts of foreign travelers such as Abdur Razzak from Persia, Nicolo de Conte from Italy, Fernao Nuniz, Domingo Paes and Duarte Barbosa from Portugal, provide us with a valuable historical lens of the Vijayanagara Kingdom. Option (d) is correct: Fernao Nuniz, a Portuguese traveler who visited the Vijayanagara Empire during the reign of Achyuta Deva Raya, noted that women in the empire held prominent roles. He observed that they were trained in various skills, including wrestling, swordsmanship, soothsaying, astrology, and accounting. These women were actively involved in the kingdom’s political, social, and cultural life. In addition to fine arts like music, some also received education in literature.","PW-2574":"Ans: C Exp: Sir Stafford Cripps was assigned the duty of winning India's cooperation and pacifying the Indian leaders during the outbreak of World War II. The pressure exerted by the U.S., particularly after Japan attacked the U.S. Naval base at Pearl Harbour, also had been responsible for this Cripps Mission. Jawaharlal Nehru and Maulana Azad were the official negotiators for the Congress. Cripps worked to keep India loyal to the British war effort in exchange for a promise of elections and Dominion status once the war was over. The Congress rejected his proposals.","PW-2575":"A high-powered mission of three British Cabinet members- Lord Pethick-Lawrence (the Secretary of State for India), Sir Stafford Cripps (President of the Board of Trade) and A. V. Alexander (the First Lord of the Admiralty) reached Delhi on 24th March 1946. Statement 1 is correct: The Cabinet Mission proposed a Threetier executive and legislature at provincial, section and union levels which essentially means a federal government. All subjects other than Union subjects and residuary power would vest in the provinces of British India. Statements 2 and 3 are incorrect: The plan did not include the enlargement of the powers of the Indian Court nor provided for more Indians in the ICS.","PW-2576":"Cripps Mission (1942) headed by Stafford Cripps was sent to India with constitutional proposals to seek Indian support for World War II. Key proposals were: Indian union with a Dominion status would be set up which would be free to decide its relation with the Commonwealth. After the war, the Constituent Assembly would be formed with members from Provinces (elected through proportional representation) and Princely states (nominated). Any Province not willing to join the Union can have a separate Constitution and form a separate union. The new Constitution-making Body and the Government would negotiate a treaty for transfer of power."};